<SLUG> BC-MRSCLINTON-GIULIANI-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MRS. CLINTON GETS CRASH COURSE IN NEW YORK POLITICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to insert location of Mrs. Clinton's remarks in 4th graf.)  
(ART ADV: Photo NYT 30 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a crash course in New York racial politics,
Hillary Rodham Clinton observed Martin Luther King's birthday in a
flurry of celebrations from Brooklyn to Harlem on Monday, tying
King's legacy to her own political ambitions while denouncing what
she and some ministers asserted was a racial divide marking Rudolph
Giuliani's years as mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, the Republican mayor and Mrs. Clinton's probable
opponent in this year's race for U.S. Senate, kept a more limited
schedule, skipping annual celebrations that he had attended in the
past in favor of smaller events organized by black supporters.
Giuliani's aides said he declined invitations to the larger events
after learning that Mrs. Clinton would be there and concluding that
they would be politically charged.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton took advantage of Giuliani's absences, giving three
audiences a prepared speech in which she talked about hearing the
Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. speak when she was a child in a white,
middle-class suburb of Chicago and implicitly denounced Giuliani's
leadership style.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton, speaking in soft and measured tones at the Harlem
headquarters of the Rev. Al Sharpton, said: ``If I am given the
privilege of representing the people of New York, I would want to
be defined as someone who unites, not divides. I want to be defined
by who I lift up, not by who I push down.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a hectic and tense day that often verged on chaos,
providing Mrs. Clinton with a vivid glance of what it is going to
be like for her to be a candidate for public office in New York. A
huge press entourage accompanied her, intent on observing the
spectacle of her first public appearance with Sharpton.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the celebration of King's birthday also served to
highlight the delicate situations facing Mrs. Clinton and Giuliani
in a prominent election. Giuliani's decision to avoid the kind of
appearances where he has been booed in the past reflects that his
standing among black voters is at a particularly low point, coming
after a succession of demonstrations organized by Sharpton that
protested police tactics.
</P>
<P>
   For Mrs. Clinton, visiting Sharpton carried definite political
risks, and had been resisted by some of her advisers. For all
Sharpton's influence among black voters _ as evidenced by the
procession of senior Democratic elected officials who stopped by to
pay tribute to him Monday _ he remains a highly unpopular figure
among many white voters, and is frequently a target of Giuliani's
attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said through aides that he had chosen to miss the two
other events Mrs. Clinton attended _ at the Convent Avenue Baptist
Church in Harlem and the Brooklyn Academy of Music _ because the
organizers had also invited Mrs. Clinton. In the past, Giuliani has
been booed at those events, including when he was running for
re-election against Ruth W. Messinger in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani attended a dinner organized by the Congress of Racial
Equality Monday night, and he presided over a muted prayer
breakfast at Gracie Mansion with black clerics, black Republican
leaders and administration officials, where he spoke briefly, and
reverentially, about King.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the two best ways to reflect him, so we don't begin to
interpret him in a way in which he really didn't intend,'' Giuliani
said, ``is to, No. 1, to read what he said rather than what other
people have to say about it, and No. 2, to pray, because I think
that's the thing that he would tell us to do. He would tell us to
pray, in order to get guidance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
