u a BC-NY-SPIDERMAN-FUGITIVE     01-18 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SPIDERMAN-FUGITIVE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGILE SUSPECT CAUGHT AT CUSTOMS CHECKPOINT 
</HEADLINE>
   (Subs for updating throughout) 
 (sw) 
 By C.J. CHIVERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A fugitive who is believed to have eluded the police
in midtown Manhattan last Tuesday by leaping from a 19th-story
window to the ledge of an adjacent building was returned to New
York City on Monday and charged with murder after being stopped on
a bus crossing into Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement officials said that the suspect, Jaquan
Muhammad, was carrying a hand-written journal and three weapons
that linked him to a string of knifepoint robberies in Manhattan
and the stabbing death of a Hunter College custodian in Brooklyn
last month.
</P>
<P>
   The journal ``was very descriptive,'' said Dennis Murphy, a
spokesman for the U.S. Customs Service.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy said Muhammad, 21, of Brooklyn, was detained at 6:15 a.m.
Sunday at a border checkpoint on the Peace Bridge, which spans the
Niagara River from Buffalo to Ontario. Muhammad arrived there on a
Greyhound bus, Murphy said, but was refused entry into Canada after
he was asked for identification during a routine immigration check.
</P>
<P>
   He showed a passport in the name of Naftali Triplett, who is
wanted for an assault unrelated to the other crimes. Canadian
border agents who searched his luggage then found a sword and two
knives, Murphy said.
</P>
<P>
   Muhammad, whose sprint through the streets and his leap from an
East 53rd Street office tower led some newspapers to refer to him
as Spider-Man, is suspected in 13 knifepoint robberies of Manhattan
pedestrians, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   Customs Service officials said Muhammad continued his efforts to
dodge the authorities even after he was detained on Sunday. After
being briefly left alone by the border agents who were questioning
him in Buffalo, the officials said, Muhammad shinnied into the
crawl space of the ceiling in a Customs holding room. He was
recaptured after officers poked the ceiling panels with a
broomstick, causing him to fall to the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Muhammad has been secured in leg irons and officers
were ``watching him like a hawk,'' a law enforcement official said
and he arrived on a flight to New York on Monday under police
guard. ``He will remain in police custody as the investigation
continues, and will participate in police line-ups in front of the
victims,'' said Sgt. Andrew McInnis, a police spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   New York police detectives had been sent to Buffalo to bring
Muhammad back after the Customs agents examined the diary found in
his luggage, Murphy said.
</P>
<P>
   Based on a comparison of the diary notes with unsolved crimes,
Muhammad was charged on Monday night with second-degree murder in
the death of Paul Farrell, 47, a custodian and father of three who
was stabbed and slashed numerous times in Lincoln Terrace Park in
Brooklyn the day after Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   A police spokesman, Detective Robert Samuel, said that Muhammad
had stabbed Farrell to settle ``a dispute,'' but offered no more
details.
</P>
<P>
   Customs officials said the sword Muhammad was trying to spirit
into Canada appeared to be the weapon used to kill Farrell, and
that it and the two knives had been turned over to the New York
police, who later charged Muhammad with criminal weapons
possession.
</P>
<P>
   The police said they were investigating whether to charge
Muhammad with any of the robberies.
</P>
<P>
   The police also confiscated notes and reading material that
included threats against Israel and the United States. But they
said Muhammad was not believed to be a terrorist and that his notes
were ``just rantings,'' in the words of a Customs official.
</P>
<P>
   Customs officials said they believed the name Naftali Triplett
was an alias, along with another name, Umar Ahmed, which appears on
a Pennsylvania driver's license Muhammad was also carrying.
</P>
<P>
   Raymond W. Kelly, commissioner of the Customs Service, said the
border agents' searches led to a solid case against Muhammad. ``The
thoroughness of the Customs inspectors in going through the
suspect's materials was critical to his apprehension,'' he said in
an interview.
</P>
<P>
   On the day after the robber made his leap from the building, New
York City's police commissioner, Howard Safir, was asked about the
investigation after a breakfast sponsored by the Citizens Crime
Commission. The early details were dramatic: the robber had landed
on the 18th floor air-conditioning unit of an adjacent building,
climbed through a window into a law office and sprinted for an
elevator.
</P>
<P>
   During the car ride down, he robbed a sandwich deliveryman of an
apron, shirt and cap, and, so dressed, slipped into the crowd when
the elevator reached the ground floor.
</P>
<P>
   Safir cautioned reporters not to glamorize such an escape,
saying the robber was merely someone who jumped from a window when
cornered. The so-called Spider-Man, he said, is ``a common criminal
who happened to do something pretty stupid.''
</P>
</TEXT>
