<HEADER>
A8776 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-TITANS-JAGUARS-HN     01-18 0819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-TITANS-JAGUARS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN McCLAIN  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
After pulling a 19-16 upset at Indianapolis in an AFC divisional
playoff, the Tennessee Titans are the biggest thing in Nashville
since country music.
<TEXT>
<P>
   When they returned home after the victory over the Colts, which
propelled them into Sunday's AFC Championship Game at Jacksonville,
the Titans were met by a crowd estimated at 9,000 that halted
traffic for miles and threatened to shut down the airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was incredible,'' said running back Eddie George, who set a
franchise playoff record with 162 yards rushing against the Colts.
``It was like we were the Beatles or something.''
</P>
<P>
   Or as free safety Marcus Robertson put it, there seemed to be
more fans at the airport Sunday night than watched the team play at
the Liberty Bowl in Memphis in 1997 after it left Houston to play
its first season in Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   The Titans survived the mob at the airport. If they can survive
the Jaguars for the third time this season, they will play in their
first Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Jacksonville is coming off a 62-7 victory over Miami that
improved its record to 15-2. The Titans dealt the Jaguars both
losses, 20-19 and 41-14, but still couldn't overtake Jacksonville
and win the AFC Central title.
</P>
<P>
   ``The seed of doubt's been planted in their minds, but we know
it's not going to be easy,'' Titans guard Bruce Matthews said.
``Because we know them and they know us, there shouldn't be any
surprises.''
</P>
<P>
   Beating a team three times in one season isn't rare. Since the
NFL/AFL merger in 1970, seven teams have defeated an opponent three
times in one season, including five in the 1990s. But never in
history has one team accomplished the three-peat on the road, which
the Titans would have to do against Jacksonville.
</P>
<P>
   Jaguars running back Fred Taylor, who rushed for 135 yards and
scored two touchdowns against the Dolphins, is fired up about the
opportunity to face the Titans again.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're on a mission,'' Taylor said. ``Any guy on this team who
lets that 62 points stay in his head is crazy. It's not going to be
easy at all.''
</P>
<P>
   After experiencing so much bad luck during their history as the
Oilers, the Titans believe they have been reborn and that divine
intervention has played a part in their reaching their first AFC
Championship Game since Bum Phillips' 1979 team lost at Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like the hand of God is on us,'' Robertson said.
</P>
<P>
   Added middle linebacker Barron Wortham, ``Only God knows if
we're a team of destiny. We're just a team of puppets.''
</P>
<P>
   To outside linebacker Joe Bowden, there's no question the Titans
are getting help from outside the team, and he doesn't mean from
the officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like we're a team of destiny,'' Bowden said. ``So many
crazy things have happened in our favor. In the past, things like
that went against us. This season, a lot of things have been going
our way.''
</P>
<P>
   The Titans have won back-to-back playoff games by playing
old-fashioned football. Coach Jeff Fisher relies heavily on the
running of Eddie George and solid defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no secret,'' Fisher said. ``Our philosophy is to run the
ball. You run the ball when you're not supposed to be able to run
it.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Indianapolis game, the players were surprised when
Fisher awarded the game ball to Matthews rather than George, who
scored the only touchdown on a 68-yard run.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has to do with what Bruce has done the last 17 years,''
Fisher said. ``Bruce has been on this team forever, and he's never
been to a championship game.''
</P>
<P>
   Matthews, left tackle Brad Hopkins and right tackle Jon Runyan
are three of the starting linemen who are playing throwback
football. They are punishing drive blockers who help George control
the clock.
</P>
<P>
   In the playoffs, George has accounted for 57 percent of the
Titans' offense with 106- and 162-yard performances.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pride myself on being able to do that,'' George said. ``To
have the opportunity to do it is great. It's a challenge, and we
want to meet that challenge head on.''
</P>
<P>
   The strategy won't change just because the Titans are playing
the Jaguars again. Fisher will continue to do the same things on
both sides of the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're confident that we know Jacksonville,'' said Titans
strong safety Blaine Bishop, who led the team in tackles against
the Colts. ``When you've got a chance to beat a team three times,
you must be pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   The Titans are good, but so are the Jaguars. Their confidence is
sky-high after the way they manhandled the Dolphins.
</P>
<P>
   Miami guard Kevin Donnalley, who played for the Oilers and
Titans, has a warning for his former teammates and the rest of the
league.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'd better take notice,'' Donnalley said. ``Fred Taylor is
back, and their defense is outstanding. Other teams better look
out.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
