<HEADLINE>
AL GORE, BILL BRADLEY DEBATE IN IOWA ON MINORITY CONCERNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT CANON  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star   DES MOINES, Iowa _ Working to top each
other's concern for minorities, Vice President Al Gore and former
U.S. Sen. Bill Bradley dueled Monday with promises of including
African-Americans and Hispanics in their presidencies.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Democrats used the Martin Luther King Jr. holiday to repeat
their support for affirmative action, their promises to end racial
profiling by police agencies and their desire to choose a Hispanic
as the next Supreme Court justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will make sure,'' said Bradley, ``the administration that I
lead reflects the diversity of the country for one reason _ because
that will make for a better administration.''
</P>
<P>
   The vice president, in turn, boasted that the Clinton-Gore
administration had put more women and people of color in top
government jobs than any of its predecessors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have...brought about one of the strongest economies in
history not in spite of diversity, but because of diversity,'' Gore
said. ``It is past time for us to remove the old barriers, move
past the old prejudices, and truly become one America.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday's debate, the ``Iowa Brown-Black Presidential Forum,''
was designed for Iowa's black and Hispanic voters to question the
candidates on issues of race. And although Bradley has made race
relations a centerpiece of his campaign _ he regularly refers to
lessons on race gleaned from his career in the National Basketball
Association _ he and Gore differed little on issues Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, each challenged the other's commitment to overcome the
country's struggles with race. The sharpest of their exchanges came
over racial profiling, the practice by law enforcement of
identifying criminal suspects primarily by the color of their skin.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the first day of the Gore presidency, I would issue an
executive order to ban racial profiling,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   But, Bradley chided the vice president: ``We have a president
now. You serve with him. I want you to walk down that hallway, walk
into his office, say, `sign this executive order today.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The crowd hooted in delight at the challenge. Gore fired back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think President Bill Clinton needs a lecture from Sen.
Bill Bradley on how to stand up and fight for African-Americans,''
Gore said, and the audience at North High School in Des Moines
cheered with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one thing to talk the talk; it's another thing to walk
the walk,'' Gore continued, and the spectators responded with
derisive groans.
</P>
<P>
   Race has been a controversial subject in the 2000 campaign. It
has distinguished Gore and Bradley from the Republicans and from
each other.
</P>
<P>
   One questioner, saying issues of interest to minorities were
being overlooked in the campaign, asked whether the candidates
supported keeping the nation's first presidential caucuses in Iowa,
which is 97 percent white, and the first primary in predominantly
white New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   Both men, their fortunes about to be tested in the states that
treasure their special status, said they saw no need for changing
the order of states that pick the parties' presidential nominees.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
