<SLUG> BC-GAMING-COMMISSION-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BILLS WOULD MAKE LYING TO GAMING COMMISSION A FELONY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK ALM  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Lying under oath to
the Missouri Gaming Commission would be a felony under bills
separately introduced by two Democratic state lawmakers.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sen. Ronnie DePasco of Kansas City and Rep. Brian May of St.
Louis each drafted legislation to plug a loophole in the 7-year-old
statute that established the commission.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently because of an oversight, there is no prohibition or
penalty for perjury when testifying before the Gaming Commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an expectation that people who are testifying are
going to be truthful,'' May said. ``The law needs to provide that
they shall be truthful.''
</P>
<P>
   Conviction under each proposal carries a maximum sentence of
five years and a $5,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
   The problem went unnoticed until December 1998, when
then-Jackson County Prosecutor Claire McCaskill used Missouri's
horse-racing statutes to file perjury charges against a former
casino executive.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, however, Jackson County Circuit Judge Justine Del
Muro dismissed all charges against former Hilton Hotels Corp.
Senior Vice President Markland Rousseau. The judge ruled that the
state's horse-racing law couldn't be applied in riverboat gambling
cases.
</P>
<P>
   McCaskill, now Missouri's auditor, said she turned to the
horse-racing statute because it was the only law that could apply
in the Rousseau case.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson County Prosecutor Robert Beaird said he would appeal the
dismissal, hoping to reinstate a three-count indictment that
alleges Rousseau lied to the Missouri Gaming Commission at a 1996
pre-licensing hearing for Flamingo Hilton Casino.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like every year there's some quirk in the gaming laws
that needs to be fixed,'' DePasco said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Last year DePasco and May successfully co-sponsored legislation
that rewrote the state's public bribery law.
</P>
<P>
   The same criminal investigation involving the Flamingo casino
also exposed a legal flaw that made it impossible to charge unpaid
public officials with accepting a bribe, including citizens
appointed to public boards and commissions.
</P>
<P>
   The Hilton investigation focused on the casino company's
relationship with a member of the Kansas City Port Authority.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
