 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For TUESDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Tuesday, Jan. 18.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CHILE-PRESIDENT (Santiago) _ A profile of Ricardo Lagos, the
newly elected president, whose personal history mirrors the
evolution of Chilean politics since the 1973 coup. By Clifford
Krauss.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE-MEDICINE (Undated) _ Until recently, doctors who
specialized in so-called lifestyle medicine _ elective and largely
cosmetic procedures _ were limited to rarefied corners of the
medical profession. But facing declining revenues because of
reimbursement cuts by managed care companies, thousands of doctors
in New York and across the country are turning to cosmetic medicine
to keep their practices lucrative. By Jennifer Steinhauer.
</P>
<P>
   CLASSIC-BOOKS-EDUC (Chicago) _ A new program at Wilbur Wright
College, a community college on this city's North Side that caters
primarily to high school graduates considered not ready for
four-year institutions, allows students to earn a special minor or
certificate by taking a concentration of courses on the so-called
great books of the Western canon. What is different is that at
Wright and other institutions, most of them ranked in the middle to
lower end of the national academic pack, are taking steps to
underline such classes and to emphasize that they are critical to a
liberal arts education. By Jacques Steinberg.
</P>
<P>
   GASOLINE-PIPELINE (Sunset Valley, Texas) _ A plan to convert an
existing pipeline from crude oil to gasoline has stirred an unusual
controversy in Texas, a state where oil once was king.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMPAIGN _ (Moved in ``p'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN-JOKES (Manchester, N.H.) _ A look at Sen. John McCain's
skills as a stand-up comic. By Jodi Wilgoren.
</P>
<P>
   FORBES-CAMPAIGN (Des Moines) _ Even though Steve Forbes has been
written off as a realistic presidential contender by most political
pundits, the Forbes campaign continues its seemingly never-ending
swing through Iowa , filled with the enthusiastic belief that one
day, if the breaks just fall their way, Forbes might actually
occupy the Oval Office. By Leslie Wayne.
</P>
<P>
   VOTING-RATES (Des Moines) _ The $1,000 limit on presidential
campaign contributions, enacted in 1974 in reaction to the
corruption of Watergate, now serves chiefly to clear the field
before anyone gets to vote, according to two prominent Republican
dropouts. Lamar Alexander and Dan Quayle, while praising
front-running Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, contended in separate
interviews that the narrowed field, combined with the scramble of
states to hold early primaries, is a major factor in the declining
voting rates: just 49 percent of adults voted in 1996. By Adam
Clymer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AIRPORT-SECURITY _ The Transportation Department is re-thinking
plans to test if airport security measures discriminate against
minorities after the Arab American Institute said the test would be
worse than the problem it is meant to detect. By Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MOTOROLA-MARKETPLACE (Chicago) _ Motorola Inc. showed more
evidence Monday that it is in the midst of a remarkable turnaround
by reporting a big jump in fourth-quarter profits on growing demand
for its cellular telephones and semiconductors. By David Barboza.
</P>
<P>
   DOLLAR-ZONE (Quito, Ecuador) _ Even in the rest of Latin
America, this country of 12 million has never been regarded as much
of an economic leader. But by deciding to replace Ecuador's
currency with the American dollar, President Jamil Mahuad has
thrust his nation onto center stage of a heated, continent-wide
debate about monetary policy and economic relations with the United
States. By Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-MUSIC (Los Angeles) _ For the music industry, the
merger of America Online and Time Warner promises to hasten the
coming of the day when music is distributed digitally through the
Internet rather than through record stores. But that does not sound
the death knell of record stores just yet. Many obstacles must be
overcome before consumers routinely download music rather than buy
compact discs. By Andrew Pollack.
</P>
<P>
   GLAXCO-SMITHKLINE (London) _ Until this weekend, only one
obstacle had blocked a merger of drug makers SmithKline and Glaxo
Wellcome: the egos of the companies' top brass. Glaxo's chairman,
Sir Richard Sykes, and SmithKline's chief executive, Jan Leschly,
refused to merge because neither executive wanted to give up
control. On Monday, as Glaxo announced it would acquire SmithKline
for about $76 billion in stock, both executives gave up the control
they so coveted to a third man, Jean-Pierre Garnier, SmithKline's
chief operating officer. By Andrew Ross Sorkin.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CULTURE (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NORTON-ART-DONATE (Undated) _ Peter Norton, the California
software entrepreneur and his wife, Eileen, who are art collectors,
have announced that they are donating nearly 1,000 works by more
than 450 artists to 29 institutions. Most of the works are from the
1990s. In sheer numbers, this is one of the largest gifts of
contemporary art by a private donor. By Michael Kimmelman.
</P>
<P>
   SEX-MUSEUM (Undated) _ On the list of 29 institutions receiving
art from Peter and Eileen Norton is the nascent Museum of Sex in
Manhattan. Its president and chief executive describes the intent
of the museum, which does not yet have a home, as a center for the
study of ``the history and evolution of human sexuality.'' It is to
be the first of its kind in this country. By Michael Kimmelman.
</P>
<P>
   CREATIVE-HISTORY (Undated) _ Not only have all artists
manipulated history to forge theater and cinema, the greatest of
them all, William Shakespeare, did it too. And if Shakespeare
allowed himself to invent scenes that never happened and to put
words into the mouths of historical figures who never said them,
then isn't it more or less the same thing when filmmakers do those
things today? A Critics Notebook. By Richard Bernstein.
</P>
<P>
   KIDS-BOOKS-AWARDS (San Antonio, Texas) _ As the nation observed
the birthday of the Rev. Dr. Martin Luther King Jr., the American
Library Association announced Monday that two of the most
prestigious prizes for children's literature, the Newbery Medal and
the Coretta Scott King Author Award for excellence by
African-American writers, were both going to ``Bud, Not Buddy,'' by
Christopher Paul Curtis. By Eden Ross Lipson.
</P>
<P>
   MOZART-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ In ``Mozart: A Cultural
Biography,'' the scholar Robert W. Gutman tries to give the reader
a down-to-earth portrait of Mozart as a highly professional
musician who used his genius to assimilate and transform the
artistic currents of the day. By Michiko Kakutani.
</P>
<P>
   TV-EVEREST-REVIEW (Undated) _ Tuesday night's installment of
``Nova'' on PBS tugs you into two real-life dramas that unfolded,
75 years apart, on the frozen slopes of Mount Everest. By Ron
Wertheimer.
</P>
