Hill of the Pistons. By Mike Wise.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-PLAYOFFS-CONTENDERS (Indianapolis) _ On Pro Football column
discussing the four teams still in the hunt. By Mike Freeman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE TIMES (Moved in ``a'' category) &QL; 
 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CANCER-PREVENT (Undated) _ Over the years, researchers have
found hundreds of drugs to slow the growth of cancer. But they have
found virtually nothing that can prevent cancers from forming. Now,
however, scientists at the National Cancer Institute say they have
a promising candidate, an aspirinlike drug that is commonly used to
treat arthritis pain. By accident, scientists found that such drugs
might also prevent cancer. By Gina Kolata.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-INCOMPETENT-PEOPLE (Undated) _ A Cornell researcher has
found that most incompetent people do not know that they are
incompetent. People who do things badly, researchers found, are
usually supremely confident of their abilities _ more confident
than people who do things well. By Erica Goode.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ANTARCTICA-ROBOT (Undated) _ Humans have long ventured to
Antarctica to study and make discoveries on the icy continent. Now,
a new breed of explorer _ a metallic robot crammed with wires and
electronics _ is poised to add its name to the annals of polar
history: Nomad, the meteorite hunter, a four-wheeled machine built
by Carnegie Mellon University's Robotics Institute in Pittsburgh.
By Warren E. Leary.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ANTARCTICA-BIKE (Undated) _ Two bicycles designed and built
specifically for the harsh conditions of Antarctica are to undergo
formal testing at the South Pole this week, part of a program to
make life a little easier _ and perhaps a bit more fun _ for those
who spend long, dark winters at the remote outpost. By Warren E.
Leary.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-NEW-SEA-CREATURES (Undated) _ Creepy things from beneath the
sea are cliches of modern exploration, but the abyss has now
produced a surprise so bizarre as to have touched off hot
international debate: tiny, mysterious, apparently living creatures
far smaller than any known bacterium _ so small as to strain the
limits on what is needed for independent life. By William J. Broad.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-TROPICAL-RAINS (Undated) _ Scientists at the National
Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration are refining new methods to
chart how much rain is falling in a major tropical storm. By Robert
Saar.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-EDGERTON-PHOTOS (Undated) _ Dr. Harold E. Edgerton was a
wizard of invention who changed the way people see things. The
flash of his camera opened up hidden worlds of motion as his
photographs revealed the drama hidden in the commonplace. This
month, MIT Press released a multimedia CD-ROM, ``Exploring the Art
and Science of Stopping Time: The Life and Work of Harold E.
Edgerton.'' By William J. Broad.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MASS-HYSTERIA (Undated) _ Stampedes of anxiety can spread
rapidly among healthy people. Outbreaks have occurred around the
world since at least the 14th century. In past eras, some were
triggered by thoughts of demons, possessed states and religious
events. Nowadays, the triggers are usually fears of exposure to
hazardous substances and pollution. By Lawrence K. Altman.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-FAT-DIETERS (Undated) _ As everyone around me goes on
high-protein diets, I ask a question: If these diets, waxing and
waning in popularity for nearly 140 years, are so great, why are so
many people fat? An essay by Gina Kolata.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SPEEDSKATING (Undated) _ A novice learns to speedskate. By
Julie Walsh.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BRODY-HEALTH (Undated) _ Americans are now living about
three decades longer than they did at the start of the last
century. But for far too many older Americans, the so-called Golden
Years are tarnished by diseases that seriously undermine the
quality of those extra decades _ diseases that with tools now at
hand are usually preventable, postponable or detectable at a
curable stage. By Jane E. Brody.
</P>
