<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-18 01:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8789 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-ROCKETS-MAVS-HNS &LR;      01-18 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROCKETS-MAVS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
DALLAS _ The Mavericks were doing their mad-scientist nonsense,
putting together wholly illogical combinations so crazy they just
might work. And for long enough to entertain the locals, they did.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Rockets fell into Dallas' half-court traps, rushed
3-pointers, threw the ball away, fought with officials and allowed
Cedric Ceballos and a bunch of backup guards to cruise down the
lane. They tempted fate until they looked up to find their 20-point
lead down to a 3-pointer.
</P>
<P>
   Then Steve Francis got so fed up he decided to dunk on 7-6 Shawn
Bradley and nearly pulled it off. Cuttino Mobley, pounded by
Bradley so hard that Bradley later apologized, attacked the human
swizzle stick at the rim. Kenny Thomas drove the lane en route to
the best game of his career.
</P>
<P>
   And just like that Tuesday night, the Rockets had a 121-111 win
to end a four-game road trip with a three-game winning streak,
matching their longest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winning at home is great, but there is nothing like winning on
the road,'' Rockets coach Rudy Tomjanovich said. ``You get a big
one out here, and you get on the plane, and you're all together.
You stay together. You start to bond. You form something.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what happened to us during our championship year. All
the really big things, the coming together, happened on the road.
I'm not comparing this to that, but I like the way we're handling
ourselves. This winning on the road, man, it's just great.''
</P>
<P>
   So great that it hardly mattered that the Rockets nearly blew a
huge lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets got Hakeem Olajuwon back from more than seven weeks
of inactivity. They scored more points than they had in regulation
time all season (they had 122 in a double-overtime game in
Phoenix). Their rookies had their most prolific scoring games of
the season, Francis pairing 31 points with Thomas' 20. Francis had
his third consecutive game with at least 10 assists, getting 11.
Thomas matched his season high with 12 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a weird, wild game,'' Tomjanovich said happily,
unconcerned for the time being with his team's role in making it so
bizarre. ``Our rookies were great.''
</P>
<P>
   Their elder statesman was rusty. Olajuwon played just 14
minutes, going scoreless for the first time in his career, but he
grabbed seven rebounds and blocked three shots.
</P>
<P>
   However, when the Mavericks, trailing by 19, went with either
Ceballos or Michael Finley and four guards, Olajuwon was not ready
to burn them for their lunacy. The Rockets instead matched up
small, and the Mavericks' all-gunner lineup forged a rec-center
comeback.
</P>
<P>
   Determined to take the ball to the basket when the Rockets left
the lane undefended, Ceballos scored all of his season-high 39
points in the 34 minutes Olajuwon was out of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Leading by 16 with two minutes left in the third quarter, the
Rockets were outscored 12-4 to end the period, all on layups or
free throws. The Mavericks scored 40 points in the quarter, the
most against the Rockets this season or last. And when the
Mavericks started the fourth quarter with a Finley 3, they were
within 90-85.
</P>
<P>
   But with eight minutes left, Mobley and Francis ignored all
logic and took their games at Bradley with angry abandon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The refs were cheating us,'' said an obviously perturbed
Mobley, who had an ice bag to his head to numb the result of a
Bradley elbow. ``They were giving them ticky-tack calls. We were
getting beat going to the hole and not getting anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Francis, meanwhile, was infuriated by the Rockets' inability to
beat the traps.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hyper, angry,'' he said. ``We were turning the ball over
a lot. You can't turn it over against a rinky-dink scramble like
that. They put on a little press, and we got careless with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Mobley slipped a shot around Bradley on his drive, and Francis
nearly got over Bradley on his, drawing a foul. His two free throws
gave the Rockets a 98-89 lead. But the Rockets did not regain
control until Matt Bullard nailed a 3-pointer off an inbounds pass
to put them up 105-99 with 2:14 left.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just worried about getting the ball inbounds,''
Tomjanovich said. ``I told him, `Break the play.' I'm yelling,
`Back out! Back out!' and it ends up being the key basket of the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   It held up as the key basket because Francis and Thomas made 11
of 12 free throws in the last two minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was fun,'' Rockets guard Walt Williams said. ``What have we
got? Thirteen wins? We'll take them any way we can get them.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
