   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NA844917-TNS-WIR BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-NYT 722 1/17,19:35 U K
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY: POLITICS OF REAL PORK
</P>
<P>
   NA843417-TNS-WIR BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT 759 1/17,19:21 U K
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY: THELANDGRAB.COM
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-18-00 0151EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000118.0012 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-18 01:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8791 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     01-18 0781
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
DALLAS _ They had a Dream.
</P>
<P>
   Well, actually, it was more like one of those
sitting-at-your-desk-on-a-long-day-at-the-office reveries.
</P>
<P>
   Hakeem Olajuwon returned to the Rockets' lineup after an absence
of nearly two months carrying as much rust as the hull of the
Titanic. And for the first time in his 16-year NBA career, he did
not score a point.
</P>
<P>
   He attempted four shots in 14 minutes that were split between
the second and fourth quarters.
</P>
<P>
   In the first half, a 15-foot fadeaway on the left baseline came
up short, and a try for a layup down on the low block was stripped
by Hubert Davis.
</P>
<P>
   In the second half, there was another missed attempt on a
turnaround and then a jump hook that didn't quite have the legs to
get over both the outstretched arms of Shawn Bradley and the front
of the rim.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there were seven rebounds, three blocked shots and a few
other times when he made himself a defensive presence on the
inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will come,'' said Olajuwon. ``My strength felt great. My
whole body felt so good. Now it is just a matter of timing, rhythm,
getting comfortable again.''
</P>
<P>
   When he was told that his previous NBA low _ one single point _
came at Reunion Arena in November 1984, his rookie season, Olajuwon
smiled like the Cheshire cat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really?'' he said giggling. ``How could that be? I must have
been thrown out of the game. You know, I got thrown out of a lot of
games in those days. It is all about growth and maturity.''
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to Steve Francis, who is starting to look like
one of those egghead kids who graduate from an Ivy League
university when they're barely old enough to cross the street
without holding their mother's hand.
</P>
<P>
   The rookie point guard is to prodigies what a laser-guided
missile would have been when the troops stormed the castle gate in
the Middle Ages, that far ahead of his time.
</P>
<P>
   It is not just the scoring of a season-high 31 points, the
dealing of 11 assists or the snagging of six rebounds. It is the
way he is going about it, with the assurance and ease of a man
relaxing in a custom-made silk robe.
</P>
<P>
   Francis does it all for a simple reason. Because he can.
</P>
<P>
   However, it is the way he is learning to do it all while playing
within the structure of the Rockets' system that has transformed
him lately from just a bundle of raw talent into someone who must
be feared. And respected.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think about being a rookie anymore,'' Francis said.
``I've played enough games now, and that stuff is behind me. Now
this is just basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   It is the glimpse of basketball the way the Rockets want to play
it in the 21st century while they make the transition from a team
built around the most athletic big man of his time to a point guard
with no boundaries on his skills and no limit on his confidence.
</P>
<P>
   See him take the ball to the hoop on a crossover dribble that
practically breaks the ankles of Dallas' Erick Strickland. See him
weave through traffic and set up Pig Miller or Cuttino Mobley or
Shandon Anderson for a hoop. See him take over the fourth quarter
when Dallas makes things tight and even drive in to dunk the ball
on the 7-6 Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had him,'' Francis said. ``Until he grabbed my wrist.''
</P>
<P>
   To see a more obvious changing of the guard, you'd have to look
outside Buckingham Palace.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is so talented, so full of ability,'' Olajuwon said.
``There is nothing he cannot do on the court, and I tell him that
all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Francis nods in agreement and does a brief impersonation of
Olajuwon, complete with the English boarding school accent. ``Shoot
the ball, Steve,'' says Francis the mimic. ``Be aggressive, Steve.
Don't back down, Steve.''
</P>
<P>
   The real Hakeem expects as much from Francis as he always has
from himself. While Olajuwon figures there is still an important
place for himself in the picture over the next 1{ seasons, he
acknowledges this is the rookie's team now.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is the coach on the floor,'' Hakeem said. ``He is in
control.''
</P>
<P>
   Francis' words say no, but his eyes say something different. He
knows it is his deal now.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a funny word, deal,'' said Francis. ``The first time
coach (Rudy Tomjanovich) told me it was my `deal,' I said, `What
are you talking about? A trade? A deal? Cards?' I learned it's a
Texas thing.''
</P>
<P>
   His thing. Rudy knows it. Hakeem knows it.
</P>
<P>
   What would it have been like to team Olajuwon with Francis 10 or
12 years ago?
</P>
<P>
   ``Wow!'' said Hakeem. ``But I'm just glad I have him now.''
</P>
<P>
   A Dream and a Future. Fit for the occasion.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
