<HEADER>
A8836 &Cx1f; kan-z
r e BC-`INTERRUPTED'-CASTING     01-18 1066
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-`INTERRUPTED'-CASTING-COMMENTARY-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITHOUT RIGHT PERSON FOR RIGHT ROLE, `INTERRUPTED' WOULD GO WRONG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT W. BUTLER  
 c. 2000 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When talking movies it's not uncommon to mention photography,
art direction, music and, of course, acting.
</P>
<P>
   But nobody ever talks about casting.
</P>
<P>
   Which is ironic, because any director will quickly confirm that
the success of a dramatic venture rises or falls on the actors at
his or her disposal. With the dramatic arts, casting is 90 percent
of everything.
</P>
<P>
   We're referring here not just to individual performances, but
rather to the unique dynamic that results when certain actors work
with one another.
</P>
<P>
   What, for example, would ``Casablanca'' have been like if the
producers had not cast Humphrey Bogart as the cynical Rick, but
instead had gone with an earlier recommendation that Ronald Reagan
be given the role? How would Reagan have interacted with Ingrid
Bergman? It certainly wouldn't be the ``Casablanca'' we know and
love.
</P>
<P>
   About the only time casting gets mentioned is when it goes
wrong, when two performers clearly are operating on different
wavelengths. This circumstance is most commonly recognized when
actors are supposed to be playing lovers but exude absolutely no
on-screen chemistry.
</P>
<P>
   Something like that happens in the current film ``Anna and the
King,'' in which Hong Kong actor Chow Yun-Fat gives a remarkably
nuanced interpretation of the King of Siam while co-star Jodie
Foster turns in a brittle, even affected performance as the royal
family's English governess. The two actors seem to be working in
different movies.
</P>
<P>
   Good, competent casting seems so natural and effortless that it
rarely draws attention to itself. A rare exception to this rule _
casting so good you can't ignore it _ can be found in the current
``Girl, Interrupted,'' director James Mangold's adaptation of
Susanna Kaysen's memoir about the year she spent in a private
mental hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Actress Winona Ryder fell in love with the book and bought the
film rights several years ago. So it was a given that Ryder would
play the role of Susanna, a recent high school graduate whose
depression (and an affair with a teacher) leads her to check
herself into a mental ward.
</P>
<P>
   Put yourself in the shoes of the film's casting director _ in
this case Lisa Beach. You've inherited Ryder for the role of
Susanna ... not at all a bad thing.
</P>
<P>
   Susanna is a young woman who is not so much angry as sad and
bewildered. She knows something is terribly wrong in her life but
can't quite pin it down.
</P>
<P>
   Ryder's forte as an actress lends itself very comfortably to
this persona. Physically, she's a waif, with delicate features, a
fragile physique and huge eyes that suggest the character's
vulnerability and introspective nature. Audiences naturally
empathize with Ryder and want to protect her.
</P>
<P>
   Her most endearing characters tend to be unsure, conflicted and
indecisive. (However, every now and then a canny director inverts
that quality to good effect. In ``The Age of Innocence'' Martin
Scorsese cast her as a prim, unassertive society wife, only to
reveal in the last reel that beneath that shrinking exterior hides
an iron will and a steel trap mind.)
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Ryder's a natural to play Susanna.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge, then, is to find the right actress to tackle the
pivotal role of Lisa, who is in many ways Susanna's polar opposite.
</P>
<P>
   A headstrong, charismatic young woman who has spent half her
life in the mental ward, Lisa is a born agitator and manipulator.
She periodically runs away from the institution; invariably, after
a few days or weeks she's returned in handcuffs, spitting and
clawing until the tranquilizers kick in.
</P>
<P>
   When Lisa does stick around, she specializes in breaking rules.
A favorite trick is to lead the other patients on nocturnal raids
of the administrative offices so they can read their own medical
files.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa is all attitude _ and not pleasant attitude at that. At one
point in ``Girl, Interrupted'' Lisa so mercilessly picks apart a
fellow patient that the unfortunate woman commits suicide. Instead
of expressing remorse, Lisa contends that some people just can't
handle the truth.
</P>
<P>
   The relationship between Susanna and Lisa is the key to ``Girl,
Interrupted.'' At first Susanna fears the in-your-face Lisa;
gradually she comes to admire and emulate Lisa's rebelliousness.
And, finally, she recognizes that beneath the charisma Lisa is
toxic _ a desperately sick and miserable person capable of
infecting others. Only then does Susanna turn away and begin
concentrating on using therapy to heal herself.
</P>
<P>
   There's plenty of potential for scenery chewing in the role of
Lisa. The trick was to find an actress with her own brand of
natural charisma, one who could sweep us up into Lisa's mad world
while gradually revealing the soul-crushing misery beneath the
anger and attitude. An actress we can hate and pity and desire all
at once.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Angelina Jolie, who seems destined to win an Oscar
nomination for her work here. In just a couple of years this
actress (the daughter of actor Jon Voight) has established herself
as a performer who commands the screen. It doesn't matter who else
is in the shot. Jolie's the one we look at.
</P>
<P>
   Typically there's nothing pliant or laid back in a Jolie
performance. She specializes in defiant characters, young women
totally unashamed of their sexual appetites and casually disdainful
of convention and propriety. (Check out her award-winning work in
the made-for-cable movie ``Gia.'')
</P>
<P>
   And she puts all this to good work in ``Girl, Interrupted.'' But
she adds something more _ a gradual revelation of the constant
terror that is Lisa's lot and which can be masked only by a show of
cockiness and cruelty and indifference.
</P>
<P>
   The wonder of ``Girl, Interrupted'' lies in the way these two
performances dovetail. Ryder's Susanna and Jolie's Lisa become a
sort of yin and yang of the feminine psyche. Where one is bawdy,
the other prefers sexual privacy. Where one is withdrawn and
cautious, the other is an aggressive daredevil.
</P>
<P>
   In complementing each other so perfectly, Ryder and Jolie
provide an eerie balance that centers the entire film.
</P>
<P>
   And as is usually the case with perfect casting, we end up
unable to imagine anyone else in these roles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-18-00 1013EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
