<DOCNO> NYT20000118.0015 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-18 10:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8837 &Cx1f; kan-z
r e BC-WATSON-2ROLES-KANSAS-     01-18 0892
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WATSON-2ROLES-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ASHES,'`CRADLE' GIVE WATSON TWO VERY DIFFERENT ROLES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT W. BUTLER  
 c. 2000 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Emily Watson, who's starring in two new movies this Friday,
never planned on being a movie star. It just sort of crept up on
her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always was ambitious to do well in the theater,'' the
two-time Oscar nominee said in a recent telephone interview from
New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``But for British actors, movie stardom doesn't happen often.
There are so many wonderful actors who have full careers just on
the stage and in the occasional television role. So for me becoming
a star was never a forged ambition. More like pie in the sky.''
</P>
<P>
   Until, of course, she was cast in 1995's ``Breaking the Waves''
as a religion-obsessed young wife who believes she can save her
paralyzed husband by debasing herself sexually. That led to her
first Oscar nomination and _ whether she was ready for it or not _
movie stardom.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suddenly there I was in a movie, being called a star. At first
it was rather alarming. Now I must admit I rather enjoy myself. The
goal of every actor, after all, is to get good roles, and I'm now
in the position of having good roles sent to me. The worst part of
it is that I don't get to spend enough time at home, which I could
when I was just working in the theater.''
</P>
<P>
   Moviegoers have a chance this weekend to see the 33-year-old
actress in a couple of guises. In Alan Parker's ``Angela's Ashes''
she plays a young Irish mother attempting to keep her family
together in the face of crushing poverty and an alcoholic husband;
in actor//director Tim Robbins' ``Cradle Will Rock'' she portrays
an impoverished American actress who lands a job with the
Depression-era Federal Theater Project and gets involved in the
legendary New York debut of America's first ``serious'' musical,
``The Cradle Will Rock.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Angela's Ashes,'' of course, is based on Frank McCourt's
Pulitzer-winning memoir of growing up deprived in Limerick,
Ireland. The book became an international phenomenon and developed
a fiercely loyal following. And that put special pressures on the
moviemakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The book is one of those things that so grips you can't put it
down,'' Watson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``One moment you're weeping, the next you're laughing madly. You
feel a real sense of responsibility when working with material like
this. Millions of people love this book and you don't want to
offend them by getting it wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   The movie's biggest fan, in fact, may be McCourt himself, who
has gone on record claiming director Parker's is the best film
adaptation he could have imagined.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had several conversations with Frank,'' Watson said,
``but oddly enough we never talked directly about his mother. I
once asked him, `Is there anything about your mum you want to say?'
And he said, `No, not especially.' His position was that the book
said it all.''
</P>
<P>
   The challenge of playing Angela, Watson said, is that she
doesn't have any big actorish moments. She tends to suffer quietly,
and that fact left the actress with little opportunity to vent in
front of the camera.
</P>
<P>
   ``As an actor you take the story and inhabit in a way that comes
naturally to you. For me, the key to the role was dwelling in the
details, the way she cared for her children, the way she threw away
her pride to beg for food. Physically I'm not like the real Angela
at all. She was quite a big woman. But the mothering instinct is
something most of us identify with.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she really suffered a nervous breakdown by the end of
the story. Frank waited until she died to finish the book because
he thought it would be quite humiliating for her.''
</P>
<P>
   As downbeat as much of ``Angela's Ashes'' is, wasn't it
difficult to keep a positive attitude?
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually the set was a great atmosphere because of the kids.
They were all over, and you can't get pretentious and maudlin with
kids around. They wanted attention all the time, and since I was
playing the role of their mother, they usually turned to me. I was
too busy to become too moody.''
</P>
<P>
   Although she and her husband have no children, Watson said that
``I have a lot of nephews and nieces so I'm used to being around
wee ones.''
</P>
<P>
   She admitted, however, that the physical circumstances of the
filming were fairly harrowing. The film crew built an exact replica
of ``the lanes,'' the low-low-income Limerick neighborhood in which
the McCourt family hit bottom. Immediately behind their rented
house was a privy used by dozens of area residents. Even worse, the
house sat in a low area and during Ireland's long rainy season as
much as a foot of water collected in the downstairs rooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those lanes no longer exist, thank heaven,'' Watson said. ``It
was pretty grim just being on the set _ grisly, dank and dark. You
couldn't sleep at night because your feet wouldn't warm up. So we
got a real sense, if only a slight one, of how miserable that life
must have been. At least as actors we could always look forward to
food at end of the day, which is more than the McCourts could
claim.''
</P>
<P>
   Watson's next film is a major change of pace. Her first comedy
role will be in Alan Rudolph's ``Trixie'' in which she plays a
wannabe private eye. Co-starring are Nick Nolte, Will Patton and
Dermot Mulroney.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-18-00 1014EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
