<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-18 10:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8840 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN19-CO     01-18 0513
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: Wisdom from a tooth
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUFKIN, Texas _ My mother has to go to the dentist. She's broken
a tooth. It's something that can't wait.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, my wife would step in and take care of everything, but
my wife is out of town.
</P>
<P>
   So, I make the appointment, I pick up my mother, we go to the
dentist's office.
</P>
<P>
   He's the same dentist she took me to when I was a little boy.
Now, I was taking her. Such is life.
</P>
<P>
   These days he has a limited practice, coming in only three times
a week. He's in a little building behind where he used to have his
office ... just a block over from where I went to grammar school
... a couple of blocks from where my grandmother lived ... a
lifetime away from my earliest memories.
</P>
<P>
   This in particular I remember:
</P>
<P>
   I must have been about 3 years old. It was late evening,
summertime. We were all sitting on the porch of my grandmother's
house _ Mother and Daddy, aunts and uncles.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody _ maybe my Uncle Bubba _ had taken a piece of string,
tied a bait of bacon to it and was showing me how to fish for
crawdads.
</P>
<P>
   He dropped the bacon and string down a crawdad mound. He told me
I had to be still, quiet, patient.
</P>
<P>
   I don't remember that any other kids were there. The grownups, I
guess, were trying to keep me occupied while they visited. The men
were taking turns at cranking an ice cream freezer. I remember
there was a lot of laughter.
</P>
<P>
   After a while lightning bugs caught my fancy and I wandered away
from the crawdad mound.
</P>
<P>
   Later, maybe a few minutes, maybe half an hour, I remembered to
check the string _ and it was gone! I couldn't believe it. There it
was, and now it wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   I went running toward the porch, yelling that the string was
gone, the string was gone. I may have been on the verge of tears.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody _ maybe my Uncle Bubba _ took it all in with a glance,
told me to stand back and then _ to my amazement _ gave the crawdad
mound a kick that destroyed it in an instant.
</P>
<P>
   He reached down, found the end of the string where it had been
pulled into the mound by the crawdad and yanked it up. Nothing was
on the line, not even the bacon.
</P>
<P>
   I couldn't get over it, how my uncle had dealt with that mound.
It was a shocking revelation for a 3-year-old, that there is no
permanency in this life. Things change, disappear. There it was,
and then it wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   The grammar school is gone. My grandmother's house is gone. Dad,
uncles and aunts ...
</P>
<P>
   Now one less tooth for Mother.
</P>
<P>
   But it'll be just fine. The dentist is fixing her up with a
partial plate. He's the same dentist she took me to when I was a
little boy, and now I take her. Such is life. Such is the circle of
life.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
jmurray(at)lcc.net; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-18-00 1021EST &QL; 
