<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-18 10:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8841 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN19-CO     01-18 0684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Choking in illegal aliens
 &HT;    (For release Wednesday, Jan. 19, 2000.)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The flood of illegal aliens entering the U.S. continues, and
apparently has not yet reached its crest. Just last week, U.S.
Border Patrol agents intercepted _ in one night! _ 1,400
undocumented immigrants trying to cross the border in Arizona.
Authorities say they have detained 14,664 illegals there this month
alone. It is astonishing.
</P>
<P>
   Add to that the hundreds of Haitians who were blocked at sea
near Miami and repatriated; add to it the tragedy of 16 Dominican
Republic refugees trying to make it by sea to Puerto Rico and,
therefore, the United States; add to it the equally tragic
discovery in Seattle of dead and alive Chinese immigrants stuffed
into container boxes on ships that traversed the Pacific from Hong
Kong; add to it the fortunate stopping of bomb-minded suspects at
the Canadian border.
</P>
<P>
   While much of the country sits mesmerized or bored by the
extended saga of Elian Gonzalez, the Cuban youngster who is the
pawn in a distasteful war of ideology, everyone else seems to be
slipping into the U.S. without much fanfare.
</P>
<P>
   If Border Patrol agents nabbed 1,400 in one night, just think of
how many got in unnoticed. The border with Mexico runs from
Brownsville, Texas, to San Diego. Some decades ago _ I believe it
was during the Lyndon Johnson administration _ the U.S. began
building a fence at its most vulnerable border spots but backed
away after a spate of complaints from the Mexican government, which
considered it an insult.
</P>
<P>
   It was projected at the beginning of this month that the
population of the U.S. will double in the next 100 years; buoyed by
a continuing flow of illegal aliens, the fully authorized
immigration quotas and aliens' traditionally high birth rates.
</P>
<P>
   That's a lot of people, particularly if they remain in the
status of low wage earners who require some sort of help, be it
with food stamps, welfare checks, housing and schooling.
</P>
<P>
   All but Native Americans come from immigrant families, so we all
should be sympathetic toward immigrants. I am. But only to those
who come in the right way. It is against our laws to enter the
country illegally.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the assault is so huge along the Mexico-U.S. border and in
the seas around Florida that one tends to surmise that for every
one who is intercepted, five or more get in unnoticed. They find
jobs here, driving many earlier immigrants out of their livelihoods
because they will work for less.
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of the Cuban Adjustment Act of 1966, which
enabled any Cuban floating into U.S. waters to be claimed by
relatives here and be eligible for citizenship in just one year,
authorities have tried to bottle up illegal immigration.
</P>
<P>
   Even the Cuban Adjustment Act was qualified by later White
Houses to extend only to those who touched dry land here; a
half-mile from shore and you were going back to Cuba. A limit of
20,000 a year was set for Cubans to legally immigrate.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, there are political considerations in the deluge of
illegal aliens coming to the U.S. But a predominant number of these
people are coming here for economic reasons _ a job. They don't
seek the refuge that Emma Lazarus's words on the Statue of Liberty
talk about. They seek a buck. And I don't blame them. I blame the
U.S., however, for having no workable border security.
</P>
<P>
   While we dash off around the world, protecting countries from
other countries, telling others how to live, we leave our doors
open to a horde of people who enter illegally and will be much a
part of the doubling of our population by 2100.
</P>
<P>
   We ought to be paying more attention _ and money _ to the
breakdown that has developed along our borders and in our waters.
It's becoming a struggle that we are losing.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
