<TRAILER>
NYT-01-18-00 1042EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000118.0024 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-18 10:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8863 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-WAR-CRIMINALS19-COX     01-18 2226
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WAR-CRIMINALS19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New law would send modern war criminals packing
 &HT;    By Jenny Staletovich
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Five years ago Nazi hunter Eli Rosenbaum
sat in the Fort Myers, Fla., airport amid a clutch of spring-break
tourists. By sheer coincidence, the day also marked the 50th
anniversary of Germany's surrender to the Allies and everywhere in
the airport televisions broadcast solemn observances from around
the world.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting beside him was a grey-haired grandfather returning to
Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Once a prominent homebuilder, the grandfather had fled his
adopted country and retired to Marco Island after Canadian
officials discovered he once belonged to a Nazi death squad under
the notorious Einsatzgruppen, which killed an estimated 1.5 million
Jews during World War II. Now Rosenbaum, having obtained
deportation orders, was escorting Helmut Oberlander out of the
country.
</P>
<P>
   As the pair silently watched Germany's surrender on the TVs,
suddenly a crew from the Canadian Broadcasting Company appeared and
trained a camera on the 70-year-old Oberlander.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was beyond bizarre,'' Rosenbaum said.
</P>
<P>
   But not totally beyond belief. Not in Florida. Like other
snowbirds, Nazis have flocked to this sunny land of leisure over
the years. So, too, have modern-day oppressors: Salvadoran generals
accused of orchestrating the murder of three nuns and a social
worker, members of Haiti's bloody paramilitary unit FRAPH, which
killed up to 6,000 in the early 1990s, and one of Chilean dictator
Augusto Pinochet's elite secret police, a squad responsible for at
least 72 deaths.
</P>
<P>
   Florida is second only to Illinois in the number of Nazis
located by Rosenbaum's Office of Special Investigations at the U.S.
Department of Justice.
</P>
<P>
   Many suspect the number of modern war criminals is even higher,
but because immigration officials rarely investigate them _ and
Rosenbaum's office deals only with Nazis _ they are less easy to
track. One human rights group says it has identified 66, but
estimates run as high as 7,000 to 10,000 nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Many have been allowed into the U.S. because weak immigration
laws require that war crimes rise to the level of genocide _ not
mere atrocities like the torture of a few innocent people.
</P>
<P>
   But that could soon change.
</P>
<P>
   In November, the Senate passed a bill to close loopholes in the
law and expand Rosenbaum's authority to include anyone who commits
atrocities. A companion bill has been proposed in the House by
Reps. Mark Foley (R-West Palm Beach, Fla.) and Gary Ackerman
(D-N.Y.). Hearings are expected to be held later this month or
February.
</P>
<P>
   ``While the OSI was dealing with the Nazis, the INS should have
been dealing with this. They ignored it,'' said Richard Krieger,
president of International Educational Missions, Inc., based in
Boynton Beach. Krieger, a former State Department administrator and
director of the U.S. Holocaust Memorial Council, threw the
considerable clout of his 19-year-old foundation _ board members
include former ambassadors _ behind the search for war criminals
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Krieger and others suspect the government has been less than
enthusiastic about taking a blanket approach because some members
of repressive regimes, like a Haitian FRAPH leader openly living in
Queens, N.Y., can be used to gather intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the original legislation that permitted the U.S.
government to go after Nazis was passed in 1978 . . . the bill was
aimed at all war criminals in this country,'' Krieger said. ``But
people from the intelligence community came up and lobbied against
it because they needed these people for information and that bill
was killed. But they didn't lobby against the Nazis.''
</P>
<P>
   That has left nonprofit groups _ primarily the Center for
Justice and Accountability in San Francisco _ to pursue civil
lawsuits. The group has so far sued the Salvadoran and Chilean
military leaders living in Florida with the help of the American
Civil Liberties Union. It has also sued a Bosnian Serb, Nikola
Vuckovic, living in Atlanta, on behalf of three Bosnian Muslims who
claim he tortured them.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenbaum and others say it comes as no surprise that Florida,
long a hideout for bootleggers, drug smugglers and scammers, is a
refuge for torturers, rapists and assassins from foreign lands.
</P>
<P>
   What the state offers is obscurity in its transiency: a large
retirement population where an aging German or Lithuanian slips
into the crowd, growing Spanish communities that camouflage a
Salvadoran or Chilean general, and Haitian enclaves that justify
the presence of a Creole accent. Surprisingly, the alleged
criminals now being pursued were not living so obscurely.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Guillermo Garcia, a former Salvadoran defense minister,
lives in Plantation and Carlos Eugenio Vides Casanova,
director-general of the country's National Guard, in Palm Coast.
Both were sued in May for their alleged roles in the murders of the
four American church women. A second suit claims they oversaw the
torture of a Salvadoran doctor, professor and two other
unidentified church workers.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Dorelien, a former leader in FRAPH, the paramilitary unit
of 7,000 under Gen. Raul Cedras, lives in Port St. Lucie in a brick
house on a winding cul-de-sac with potted plants by the front door
and a screened garage. In 1997, he won a $3.2 million lottery
jackpot. Although he once talked openly of his past, he now refuses
to answer questions.
</P>
<P>
   But until recently, public attention focused largely on the
suspected 60,000 surviving Nazis. Operating with a staff of 11
historians and 12 attorneys on a $6 million budget, the OSI has
filed charges against 108 over the years. Sixteen of its cases _ 10
percent _ have been in Florida. Altogether the agency has stripped
American citizenship from 64 Nazis and deported 53.
</P>
<P>
   ``My colleagues and I have spent an awful lot of time traversing
the roads of Florida, interviewing suspects and having doors
slammed in our faces,'' Rosenbaum said.
</P>
<P>
   The movie Marathon Man, frequently invoked when Rosenbaum's work
comes up (in the last scene the Nazi character who fled to the U.S.
after the war is recognized by one of his victims), is far from
reality, Rosenbaum said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality is much more mundane. But for those of us on the
cases it's much more exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   Historians serve as investigators, pouring over old Nazi
records, translating them from Lithuanian, German and other
languages. A watch list with the 60,000 names has been created.
Once someone is identified, legal proceedings can begin. Sometimes,
a case is as easy as a passport check. Alexander Schweidler,
formerly of Inverness, was snared by U.S. Customs at an Orlando
airport, Rosenbaum said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happens with some frequency is we stop them (at an
airport) and they say, 'No, No. I don't know what you're talking
about.' And at our direction, Customs will ask them to remove their
shirt and look under their arm and there's a tatoo or scar in just
the right place,'' Rosenbaum said. Nearly every member of the SS
had his blood type tattooed under his arm.
</P>
<P>
   Time has proved to be the agency's biggest enemy: Nazis are
dying off faster than the office can find them. Most of those
located in Florida lived on the west coast, around St. Petersburg.
And not all very secretly. As with Oberlander's case, some have
unfolded strangely.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, the mayor of Miami Beach unwittingly honored Franz
Hausberger with a gold city medallion when he visited to promote
his Austrian ski town. A day later he fled under cover of night,
just before demonstrations broke out when Justice Department
officials learned he had been a sergeant in the infamous First SS
Infantry Brigade which mopped up behind German lines in the Soviet
Union.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, a Tampa federal judge revoked the citizenship of Adolph
Milius, an 81-year-old obstetrician who retired to St. Pete Beach
in 1979 and had served in the Lithuanian Security Police. In 1992,
Antanas Mineikis, living in Gulfport, was deported after he
admitted taking Jews to Lithuanian concentration camps as a member
of the Lithuanian Schutzmannschaft that killed tens of thousands of
Jews. In 1996, Juozas Budreika, also a former member of the
Schutzmannschaft living in Gulfport, left rather than fight
deportation orders and died later that year. Jurgis Juodis, another
member of the Lithuanian police unit, was denaturalized in 1981 and
died in Tampa in 1986. In May, a federal judge in Pensacola jailed
Vytautas Gecas, 77, of Sunny Hills, after he refused to answer
questions. Gecas served in Belarus during the war in a unit that
killed thousands of Jews and remains jailed.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 16 Nazis located by the OSI in Florida, all, with the
exception of Gecas, have either died or been deported.
</P>
<P>
   What has not been so easy is finding modern war criminals,
largely because no agency has been responsible for them. The
Anti-Atrocity Act, if it passes, should solve that, Krieger and
other human rights activists say.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the century we've seen blood letting on a
horrific scale, yet there's no institutional response,'' said Rob
Weiner, of the Lawyers Committee for Human Rights. ``We've finally
said 'enough' to the continued violence without response.''
</P>
<P>
   The Center for Justice and Accountability was established after
psychotherapist Gerald Grey, working with Amnesty International,
began encountering more and more victims of torture seeking help
over the last decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are 18 centers (to treat torture victims) in the U.S.
alone and they're trusted by the immigrant communities who will in
the course of treatment talk about problems, including the presence
of torturers, and that's how I find out,'' Grey said.
</P>
<P>
   The law protecting victims of torture dates back 200 years to
the Alien Tort Claims Act which allows victims of international
human rights violations to sue in U.S. court. But no one was
successfully prosecuted under the law until 1976, when the family
of Joelito Filartiga sued his Paraguayan torturer and won. In 1992,
Congress reinforced the law by enacting the Torture Victim
Protection Act. The newer law defines specific causes of action and
extends the right to sue to aliens as well as U.S. citizens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Generally, there is a first wave of refugees from areas of
upheaval and often in the next wave of refugees are the
perpetrators,'' explained attorney Beth Van Schaak, who has worked
with the center to prosecute the cases. ``So the perpetrators are
often resettled in the same places as their victims, and they run
into them on the streets, or see them on TV, and until we were
created, there was no place to turn. So what we're responding to is
the failure of the U.S.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, the U.S. signed the U.N. Convention Against Torture,
which includes laws to criminally prosecute war criminals. But so
far it has been reluctant to try them out, Grey said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The entire refugee community is held hostage by weak U.S.
prosecution, which means the whole country is held hostage by the
criminals,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While the Anti-Atrocity Act is a step in the right direction,
Grey says it falls short because it calls for deportation only and
not prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   ``The communities don't want deportation because that puts (the
criminals) among their families and they don't want that,'' he
said. ``That's the weakness of the bill.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he concedes, it will significantly improve the effort to
investigate former leaders and officials of repressive regimes.
</P>
<P>
   Uncovered so far: Emmanuel Toto Constant, one of the leader's of
Haiti's FRAPH. After the U.S. invaded Haiti, Constant moved in with
an aunt in Queens. When an immigration judge tried to deport him,
the State Department reportedly interceded and argued sending him
back would destabilize the country. One of his deputies, Gwo Fan
Fan, was a neighbor in Queens. Last year, the Boston Globe located
Dorelian living in Port St. Lucie. He told the Globe that another
FRAPH colleague, Jean-Claude Duperval, is also living in the U.S.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the two Salvadoran generals being sued in federal
court in West Palm Beach, Armando Fernandez-Larios, of Miami, is
being sued by a family claiming he tortured their relative as a
lieutenant in the Chilean army under Pinochet.
</P>
<P>
   In Atlanta, Ethiopian Kelbessa Negewa, alleged to be a leader in
the ``Red Terror'' that executed thousands in the mid 1970s, was
successfully sued for $1.5 million in 1993 by three of his victims.
And a Rwandan, Elizaphan Ntakirutimana, a Hutu believed to have
orchestrated the killings of thousands of Tutsis in Rwanda in the
spring of 1994, is awaiting word on whether the U.S. Supreme Court
will consider his appeal of an order to surrender to the
International Tribunal in Arusha, Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are more and more examples of ethnic cleansing occurring
in parts of the world,'' said Jonathan Lamy, a spokesman for Sen.
Patrick Leahy, D-Vermont, who introduced the Anti-Atrocity Act.
``And the perpetrators of the acts . . . are seeking the U.S. as a
safe haven more and more.''
</P>
<P>
   Jenny Staletovich writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla. Lynne Palombo and Dorothy Shea contributed to this
report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
