<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-18 10:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8867 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-LUNAR-ECLIPSE19-COX     01-18 0347
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LUNAR-ECLIPSE19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Midnight lunar eclipse to show moon in different light
 &HT;    By Tim O'Meilia
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Schoolkids across the country have the
perfect excuse to stay up past midnight Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Their science teachers will tell them to.
</P>
<P>
   The entire western hemisphere will see a total lunar eclipse,
when the Earth passes between the sun and the moon, blocking the
sun's rays from reaching the moon.
</P>
<P>
   At 9:03 p.m., the moon begins to enter a light shadow of the
earth _ called the penumbra _ but it is difficult to detect at
first. The moon will gradually turn from bright yellow to dingy
gray.
</P>
<P>
   At 10:01 p.m., the moon will begin to slide into the earth's
darker shadow _ the umbra. ``You can actually see the umbra moving
across the face of the moon,'' said Erich Landstrom, astronomy
director at the South Florida Science Museum in West Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   The eclipse reaches totality at 11:05 p.m. and stays that way
for an hour and 17 minutes. The moon begins to emerge from the
umbra at 12:22 a.m. Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of looking like a flat disc in the sky, it will
actually look three-dimensional, like a round ball suspended in the
heavens,'' said Jack Horkheimer, director of the Miami Space
Transit Planetarium.
</P>
<P>
   The moon won't black out. It will burn gold to copper red. Why?
Ask your seventh grader.
</P>
<P>
   He or she should say it's because indirect sunlight still
manages to reach the moon but not before it passes through the
Earth's atmosphere, which filters out most of the blue light,
leaving yellow and red.
</P>
<P>
   The best way to see the three-dimensional effect is to use
binoculars, Landstrom said.
</P>
<P>
   So, class, what else does a lunar eclipse prove?
</P>
<P>
   That the Earth is round, as the Greeks deduced more than 2,000
years ago as they watched the Earth's shadow crawl across the moon.
</P>
<P>
   Tim O'Meilia writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla. E-mail: timomeilia(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
