<DOCNO> NYT20000118.0027 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-18 10:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8870 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-MONEYTALK-COLUMN19-CO     01-18 0996
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYTALK-COLUMN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    10 steps to a debt-free life
 &HT;    By Hank Ezell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Two years ago, with fear in her heart, Mary Ann Walls
cut up all eight of her credit cards.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was probably the saddest moment in my life,'' she recalls
of her first visit at the Consumer Credit Counseling Service of
Greater Atlanta. ``I thought my life was gone.''
</P>
<P>
   But she had to do it. She and her husband, Gary, owed nearly
$20,000 on their maxed-out cards. They were missing payments, and
they were oppressed by what they had done. ``I was truly, truly
ashamed,'' Mary Ann Walls said.
</P>
<P>
   She's not alone. Americans spent an average of $1,067 for
holiday gifts just weeks ago. That doesn't count spending on
travel, entertainment, decorations and cards, and all the other
stuff that makes the December holidays a commercial success.
</P>
<P>
   Now their credit card bills have started arriving in the mail.
For many, it is a time of remorse and financial distress.
</P>
<P>
   But it can be relieved. Getting out of debt requires a personal
and family commitment, some careful planning and the discipline to
follow through.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't just wish improvement to happen, any more than you
can wish away weight,'' said Suzanne Boas, president of CCCS in
Atlanta. ``You've got to lay out a plan that is really specific.
And you've got to keep at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Here are 10 tips on how to make your way down a long road to
recovery:
</P>
<P>
   1. Stop using credit cards. It sounds terribly obvious, but it
removes a temptation from your everyday life.
</P>
<P>
   If you're worried about emergencies, carry a few traveler's
checks in your wallet _ not a credit card. You can use a debit card
for things like mail-order purchases.
</P>
<P>
   2. Find out how bad the problem is. Put all your bills in one
place and add up how much you owe. Also, write down what interest
rate you are paying on each account. ``You need to get a really
clear picture of where you are and where you want to be,'' Boas
said.
</P>
<P>
   3. Evaluate your spending. Some people go through their
checkbook to make a list of how much they spend and where. But that
may not be enough, especially if you make frequent trips to the
ATMs.
</P>
<P>
   A better method is to keep a daily notebook, writing down
everything you spend for two weeks or even a month. That should
give you an idea of how much you spend on necessities and how much
on feel-good items.
</P>
<P>
   This is the time to make sure the whole family is involved.
Keeping to a budget is like quitting smoking: It's a lot easier if
you and your spouse decide you owe it to each other.
</P>
<P>
   4. Cut your spending. Most people believe they could save $20 a
week without feeling any pain, according to one recent survey. Some
easy ways are taking your lunch to work, cutting back on restaurant
visits, controlling long-distance phone calling, putting off
spending for new clothes and trimming any expensive vacation plans.
</P>
<P>
   Keep a toll of how much you've cut back, and make sure you add
that much to your bill-paying.
</P>
<P>
   5. Beware of easy answers. ``Credit doctors'' and ``credit
repair clinics'' often charge high fees and don't do much for you.
</P>
<P>
   If you are in deep trouble or just need the structure of an
outside agency, check out Debt Counselors of America,
www.getoutofdebt.com or 1-800-680-3328.
</P>
<P>
   Boas advises against borrowing more money through consolidation
loans or home equity loans to pay off debts. ``If you don't change
underlying behavior, people invariably go out and spend again,''
she said. ``That is the most common mistake people make.''
</P>
<P>
   6. Pay off the most expensive card first. High interest rates
are a penalty in themselves. The quicker you pay off those
accounts, the less you will have to pay in interest. It's cheaper,
and you'll climb out of the hole faster.
</P>
<P>
   7. Try to lower the cost of credit. If you have been paying on
time, you may be able to negotiate a lower rate with the creditor.
Your pitch: If you don't get a better deal, you'll move to a
lower-interest card.
</P>
<P>
   If you do decide to switch, check carefully on the terms of the
new credit card. Look for annual fees, punishing late-payment
penalties and introductory offers that quickly move up to a higher
rate.
</P>
<P>
   8. Boost your payments. Most credit card companies will let you
get away with paying only a fraction of your bill each month. But
if you do, it takes much longer to pay off the bill, and the
interest charges keep on sapping your income.
</P>
<P>
   The Walls family began their credit repayment plan with a
commitment of $355 a month. With the help of CCCS branch manager
Susan Cantrell, they figured they could pay their bills in four
years. By nearly doubling their payment to $655 a month, the family
finished in two years.
</P>
<P>
   9. Use automatic payment plans. You can direct your bank or
credit union to make a regular payment to a creditor each month.
You don't have to write a check, and you can't put it off. For many
people, this is the easiest way.
</P>
<P>
   10. Celebrate. ``If you make a commitment to lose weight, you
get a little help along the way because your friends see the
results and give you compliments,'' Boas said. ``You get to talk
about it, and you're proud.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if you're silently working off debt, there's nobody to
help you celebrate. It's important, particularly for families, to
take time to celebrate your achievements.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't forget the rewards when you finally finish. Walls recalls
that she sneaked into the CCCS office in Carrollton two years ago,
afraid that co-workers in her nearby office might see her.
</P>
<P>
   Now she has regained a spritely outlook. ``There's a sense of
freedom now,'' she exulted. ``We don't have all the phone calls
(from bill collectors). And it's done a lot for my self-esteem _
we're responsible adults now.''
</P>
<P>
   Hank Ezell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
