<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-18 10:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8872 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN19-COX     01-18 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Taking loss from a Biddy's point of view
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ This morning over tea and toast, and well
before daybreak, Biddy and I had a serious chat. Actually, I seemed
to be doing most of the talking while Biddy wigwagged agreement
with a series of flicks of her most expressive tail. Biddy is
Siamese...if you please.
</P>
<P>
   Over the 10 years we've been together, Biddy and I have learned
the art of cat-to-person communication as in: Mee-oww!
(Translation: My basket is no longer in the sun; would you please
move it?) This is a fairly easy one but if I'm a little slow and
she loses patience: Wee-yoww! (Translation: In this lifetime,
Dummy!)
</P>
<P>
   Our person-to-cat talk, on the other hand, needs work. For
example: ``Biddy, it would make me very happy if you would get off
my desk so I can work.'' Naturally, she ignores me and goes on
hooking rubber bands from a partially-open drawer just to remind me
who's really in charge here. If that doesn't work, she'll slide
over to the file baskets and shove all five of them onto the floor,
hopelessly jumbling the In, Out, and To Do papers.
</P>
<P>
   One look over the edge convinces her she's accomplished all she
can there, so she'll turn around twice and splay herself across a
stack of notes I may have just finished sorting according to topic.
Stretching to the very limits of her two-toned Ricky Ricardo
kittysuit, she'll then initiate a painstaking investigation of the
pages under her and begin shredding the corners of those she finds
the tastiest. This would be a normal morning, but today is
different. The desktop doesn't seem to interest her at the moment
and she doesn't even slow down to check out the inside of the shade
on my desk lamp. She's headed for my lap.
</P>
<P>
   Gingerly, she taps a paw first on my arm, and then over to my
stomach, kind of like the way a winter fisherman tests the ice
before heading onto the pond. Once she's sure the chair and I
aren't going to move out from under her, she carefully steps across
to my chest, flattens herself and rests her nose on my chin. I ask
what's wrong.
</P>
<P>
   A staccato mew is her only answer. I stroke the top of her head,
pausing to rub a silky ear between thumb and forefinger. She bumps
my chin and stretches a paw up to each shoulder. I ask her if she's
lonely. An affirmative mew. I tell her I understand and she purrs.
</P>
<P>
   The week before Christmas, we lost Stella, her 15-year-old
sister, and even though the girls weren't very close, Biddy misses
the dainty white ladycat she'd known all 10 years of her life. Nap
time certainly isn't the fun it used to be when there was
competition for the sunniest spot, nor is a treat nearly as sweet
when there's no one to pummel for it. And it was fun to have a
buddy to get goofy with when Mom broke out the catnip.
</P>
<P>
   Biddy probably still remembers the clout on the nose that was
Stella's initial response to the tiny newcomer's invasion of her
basket beside the radiator.
</P>
<P>
   That's what we're talking about this morning _ the good times.
The days when Stella was still strong enough to jump onto the
cistern and spend an evening raccoon watching through the basement
window. When she felt up to their twice-daily, fur-flying,
screeching race through the house until one or the other was
seduced by the siren call of a spot of sunlight on the carpet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you want a little brother or sister?'' I ask the warm body
glued to my chest. Biddy looks at me, but doesn't respond so I try
again. ``Wouldn't it be fun to have a furry little thing to climb
all over you and bite your ears? Someone to help you roll balls
into the sump-pump hole and maybe stuff a few catnip mice under the
stove?'' No answer.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe she's thinking it over. Or maybe it's just too soon.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, Ohio 43431 or email: eschuett (AT)nwonline.net
</P>
