<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-18 10:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8873 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-YOUNG-COLUMN19-COX     01-18 0681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gratuitous pitch shifts mounting debt onto future taxpayers
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ George W. Bush isn't just talking billions. He's
talking $1 trillion.
</P>
<P>
   Over a decade, that's Bush's tax-cut proposal. And some of it
can be yours.
</P>
<P>
   What's your answer, New Hampshire?
</P>
<P>
   ``Uh, we'd like to call Sen. McCain.''
</P>
<P>
   In one of the most anti-tax states in the union, with some of
the hardest hardliners on federal spending, the man with one of the
most sweeping tax-cut plans in history and the biggest war chest to
sell it risks losing the first primary to McCain, a veritable
prude.
</P>
<P>
   This even though McCain has yet to call Bush's big tax-cut plan
what it is: a big tax _ a tax on future taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   If he doesn't, McCain is not as smart as he appears. And if Al
Gore or Bill Bradley, should either face Bush in the fall, doesn't
point out the same, the Democrats miss a mighty lick that should
resonate with everyone who knows what debt does.
</P>
<P>
   Here are the facts ignored. The United States over the last 25
years bought more government than it had cash to pay for. This
included the largest peacetime military buildup ever, to where the
Pentagon at one point commanded nearly a third of the federal
budget. Meanwhile, Ronald Reagan and blue-sky disciples cut tax
rates.
</P>
<P>
   The national debt now is $5.7 trillion. It grows $436 million
every day. Interest amounts to about $1,000 per man, woman and
child. And it grows. That's a tax someone must pay. Not us, under
G.W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Bush talks about equal-opportunity tax cuts. (Actually, 60
percent of the $1.1 trillion would go to the wealthiest 10 percent
by rolling back Bill Clinton's tax hike on the wealthiest 20
percent of Americans.) To get there, Bush would bypass a monstrous
opportunity: to reduce the federal debt that today's children and
their children must resolve.
</P>
<P>
   McCain proposes a tax cut about half that size. He has said a
portion of each surplus should be held to bolster Social Security
and reduce the national debt.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's plan would take every penny of projected annual surplus
and plow it into tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   That might make sense for a state with a budget balanced by law.
It makes no sense for a federal government trillions in the hole.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, built into Bush's plan _ to cut marginal rates for
every American and to reduce tax brackets from five to four _ are
two unrealistic expectations: First, that today's prosperity will
continue unabated; second, that Congress can hold fast to 1994
balanced-budget caps that require drastic reductions in domestic
spending.
</P>
<P>
   We've already seen this Congress weaseling around the caps by
trying every accounting deceit in the book.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, one of Bush's proudest moments as a candidate was when
he took on Republican leaders for callously proposing to cook the
year-end books by paying the Earned Income Tax Credit for the
working poor in monthly installments rather than one lump sum in
April.
</P>
<P>
   These 11th-hour contortions were needed to stay under the
self-imposed budget caps.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's tax plan relies on adhering to the same spending
restrictions, though a GOP-dominated Congress was at wit's end
figuring out how to do that.
</P>
<P>
   With all the revenue and the supposed savings aimed at balancing
the budget, you'd think we could be storing away dollars to resolve
the debt question hanging over future generations. McCain seems to
be interested in that. So, too, Gore and Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   Someone please explain to us why anti-tax Republicans in New
Hampshire haven't fully embraced Bush, the man with a more
gratuitously Reagan-ific tax-cut proposal. Instead, the more
cautious McCain leads in some polls.
</P>
<P>
   Where's the enthusiasm, New Hampshire tax haters? Could it be
that even those who hate taxes hate lingering debt worse? Today's
pre-schoolers sure ought to.
</P>
<P>
   John Young writes for The Waco Tribune-Herald, Waco, Texas.
E-mail: jyoung(at)wacotrib.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
