<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Simpsons' success unexpected for woman behind Bart's voice
 &HT;    By Laura A. Bischoff
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ When she started as the voice of Bart Simpson 12
years ago, Nancy Cartwright never thought the 10-year-old smart
aleck would become a cultural icon.
</P>
<P>
   Or that the animated family would get a star on the Hollywood
Walk of Fame, which happened Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being added to the Walk of Fame is a major feather in our
caps! I always thought it would be tremendous honor, but I never
thought that I would be included! How fun,'' Cartwright wrote in an
e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   The Simpsons will join Bugs Bunny and Mickey Mouse as animated
characters honored with stars on the walk. The Simpsons' star will
be outside the Galaxy Theater on Hollywood Boulevard. ``Mel Blanc
and Bugs Bunny are our neighbors! Sounds appropriate,'' she wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The Simpsons premiered in 60-second snippets on the ``Tracey
Ullman Show'' in 1987 and joined Fox as a series 10 years ago
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The show's endurance and popularity has surprised Cartwright.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of us knew that the show would be the major,
international hit that it is. Into the first season we had the idea
that the show was a success, but no one had the prediction of how
great a success it would be. Ninety-four countries and Bart is one
of the top entertainers of the 20th century (according to Time)
along with Picasso, Frank Sinatra, Lucille Ball . . . that doesn't
suck at all!''
</P>
<P>
   Cartwright, who lives in California with her husband and their
two children, said the show's future hinges on the writers' ability
to do it justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because it is animation, there is a lot more leeway than your
average sitcom. But they are already beginning to feel the crunch,
and we have at least season 12 to do. Rumor has it that they are
wanting to negotiate for another three years. We'll see . . . I'd
love that!''
</P>
<P>
   Laura A. Bischoff writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton,
Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
