he became of his theory. But he was trained as a biochemist and
pathologist, not as a clinician. Although he could decipher
homocysteine's mechanism of action, he wasn't equipped to undertake
the human trials that might have validated his suspicions.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the establishment,'' he adds, ``felt that until it was
proven in patients, (the theory) probably was wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Wrong'' wasn't the half of it. When McCully first made his key
observations, the cholesterol model of heart disease was wowing
cardiologists. There was no need for an alternative theory. And for
a decade or so, McCully was one of only a handful of scientists who
appreciated the complicated biochemistry of homocysteine
metabolism.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1970s, he couldn't find funding for his medical
research and wound up working as a pathologist at a Veterans
Affairs hospital in Providence, R.I. (where he has remained). But
he persisted in publishing modest studies funded by a
better-established colleague's grant.
</P>
<P>
   Then about a decade ago, results from some of the first major
long-term studies of heart disease began to trickle in. To
McCully's surprise, many included data on homocysteine. To everyone
else's surprise, the data revealed significant correlations between
homocysteine and heart disease.
</P>
<P>
   In a study of almost 15,000 physicians, for example, those whose
homocysteine levels were highest had more than three times the risk
of heart attack as those whose levels were lowest.
</P>
<P>
   In an ongoing 50-year study of the population of Framingham,
Mass., an examination of more than 1,000 seniors found that
homocysteine levels corresponded to clogging of the arteries in the
neck. About 80 trials have suggested that elevated homocysteine is
associated with hardening or blockage of blood vessels.
</P>
<P>
   The homocysteine hypothesis suddenly became respectable.
McCully's colleagues cite several reasons for the theory's belated
acceptance. In addition to the cholesterol prejudice, there's the
fact that, until recently, measuring homocysteine levels was
costly, difficult and time-consuming. But the latest homocysteine
blood tests are fast and affordable.
</P>
<P>
   Most experts agree that there's a desperate need for a long-term
study to evaluate whether lowering homocysteine levels will in fact
help to prevent heart disease. But they say that even if the
connection holds up, homocysteine won't entirely eclipse the other,
more familiar, risk factors such as age, weight, smoking, blood
pressure and cholesterol levels.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't say, `Well, I'll take folic acid and eat whatever I
want and I'll be protected,''' says Craig Scott, a cardiologist at
the University of Pennsylvania. High homocysteine levels don't
guarantee a heart attack, he says, and low levels won't rule one
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I do recommend folic acid for all my patients,'' Scott
says. ``It's something that everybody who's at risk for coronary
disease should consider doing as an adjunct.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately such recommendations may scuttle efforts to prove
once and for all the merits of the homocysteine hypothesis. Federal
guidelines introduced in 1998 increased the amount of folic acid
that must be added to enriched grain products; that increase,
together with the growing popularity of B vitamins in cardiology
clinics, might eliminate any heart conditions caused by vitamin
deficiency and homocysteine surplus.
</P>
<P>
   The latest results from the Framingham study, for example, show
that the new fortification program has added an average of 100
micrograms of folic acid to subjects' daily diets, resulting in a
sizable lowering of homocysteine levels, Krauss says. ``That's
going to make it difficult to do the studies that need to be
done.''
</P>
<P>
   For McCully, it's perhaps the final irony in a bittersweet
career.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (Karen Wright is a contributing editor to Discover magazine.)
</P>
</TEXT>
