<P>
   The Hearst News Service will file these stories for Wednesday.
If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at 202-298-6320.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (``HNS'' appears in all sluglines.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   READING-CAMPAIGN (San Francisco) _ There's a funny, clever edge
to the advertising campaign under way in California that encourages
children to read and reminds their parents what a difference
reading makes. By GEORGE RAINE.
</P>
<P>
   PRIEST-TRIAL (San Francisco) _ Two years after a Roman Catholic
parish in Burlingame, Calif., was stunned by disclosures of a
nocturnal wrestling match between the church's pastor and a teenage
male rectory worker, the case is quietly heading to trial in San
Francisco. By ELIZABETH FERNANDEZ.
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR-JAIL (San Francisco) _ The editor and publisher of a
Glenn County weekly newspaper is braced to spend five days in jail
rather than reveal the names of two confidential sources five years
after they tipped him off about the theft of a pistol by a lawman.
By ERIC BRAZIL.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE-PUBLISHING (Undated) _ A fledgling Internet company
provides budding writers the chance to get their words into print.
Authors who say they could not get any attention from large
publishing houses praise the company for giving them an outlet for
their work. By VANESSA HUA.
</P>
<P>
   FEATURES/LIFESTYLE (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BREEDING-ZOO (San Antonio) _ San Antonio undeniably is a
romantic city. Strolls on the River Walk. Moonlit rides in
horse-drawn carriages. Leisurely drinks and meals at quaint patio
cafes. And most romantic of all _ an intimate tryst in a dusty
exhibit at the zoo. That's right. A lot of the city's romance does
not involve humans at all. At least, not directly. By JACQUE
CROUSE.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GLF-STEWART (Palo Alto, Calif.) _ One week ago, Paul Azinger sat
alone in a room, his head in his hands, his heart in his stomach.
He had just seen the practice green at the Sony Open in Honolulu,
filled with professional golfers laughing, chatting, chipping and
putting. Full of life. Which was the problem. ``It looked like
everybody had forgotten,'' Azinger said. ``Life was going on.''
Yes, life was going on without Payne Stewart. By BRIAN MURPHY.
</P>
<P>
   WRESTLER-SURGERY (San Antonio) _ Stone Cold Steve Austin _ the
scowling, foulmouthed, bad boy of pro wrestling _ is recovering at
a local hospital after undergoing surgery to correct years of
head-butting, body-beating behavior. By NICOLE FOY.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ These must be good times because
the nation is torn apart over a piece of fabric, the firing of a
coach, do-good messages on TV shows and a lost 6-year-old boy. At
the beginning of a new century, these are the issues proclaimed as
important, so let's go with them. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   LYNCH-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ There's an area for write-in
candidates on the ballot in New York. If you're a Democrat and you
want to write in a candidate, go for it. But Republicans don't vote
directly for the candidates, they vote for delegates pledged to
those candidates. So writing in the name of a Republican candidate
who isn't on the ballot _ like Alan Keyes or Gary Bauer _ will mean
nothing. By DAN LYNCH.
</P>
