<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-18 12:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8947 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-DEBORAH-KARA-UNGER-IN     01-18 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEBORAH-KARA-UNGER-INTERVIEW-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNGER FIRE  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from Women's Wear
Daily, contact New York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!----------------------
 &HT;    ONE COLOR SLIDE showing Deborah Kara Unger is available FREE OF
CHARGE to purchasers of this article. The art can be sent
ELECTRONICALLY by e-mail. Please specify that you want the art when
you order the article.
 &HT;    ----------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``e'' entertainment news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By LOUISE FARR  
 c.2000 Fairchild Publications   
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Deborah Kara Unger, sipping tea in the garden at
Hollywood's Chateau Marmont Hotel, might think she's well
disguised. She's wearing a bulky suede jacket and her blond hair is
pulled back in a ponytail.
</P>
<P>
   For a while, all is fine. A bird flaps through the bushes.
Butterflies flutter about the bougainvillea. Everyone ignores her.
</P>
<P>
   Then an eager producer lands tableside, reminding her that they
met once in Toronto. Unger is polite, yet looks blank. The man
protests: He seems to think it was a memorable meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whoopsie,'' says Unger as he walks away.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Unger doesn't enjoy being approached by strange men.
Although the actress, 33, has the image of an icy femme fatale _
mainly from her roles in ``Crash'' and ``The Game'' _ and although
she has appeared in a handful of nude scenes, she points out that
she is actually rather shy. So shy, she says, that she was a virgin
until she was 20.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people are disappointed when they meet me,'' she
says, snapping out the words. ``Those people are usually silly and
they're usually male, and they can go back to the silly Web sites
they create about me. It feels like such a violation.''
</P>
<P>
   True, Unger is about to appear in two more films in which she's
not completely virtuous: In ``Sunshine,'' set during the 1959
Hungarian revolution, she plays Ralph Fiennes's married love
interest, and in ``Signs and Wonders,'' she's the mistress who
breaks up Stellan Skarsgaard's marriage.
</P>
<P>
   But in ``The Hurricane,'' which recently opened, she plays a
Canadian activist fighting to free American prizefighter Rubin
``Hurricane'' Carter from jail, where he languishes after being
framed for three murders.
</P>
<P>
   Director Norman Jewison was impressed when Unger, who was drawn
to the story intellectually and emotionally, flew in from Hungary
to meet him.
</P>
<P>
   ``She showed up at my apartment in New York on a day when I was
reading two other actresses,'' Jewison remembers. ``She said,
`Please excuse the bags under my eyes.' And she really touched me.
As I got to know her, I realized she has an edginess to her, but
she also has a sensuous side.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was nice to go to work every day and not have to be some
sort of depraved vixen,'' says Unger, who was also elated by
watching Denzel Washington play Carter. ``He was exercising muscles
metaphorically that he hasn't exercised for a very long time. It's
inspiring to spend time around somebody who's that great an
emotional athlete.''
</P>
<P>
   In general, though, Unger, who grew up in Canada, the daughter
of a doctor and a political activist, has not found herself
particularly inspired since she first landed in Hollywood eight
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no resonance to fame,'' she says. ``It's so valueless.
So there's a lot of sadness in this town. God bless the loneliness
of those people. It's hard to address what's ontologically valuable
when you're running from your shadow.''
</P>
<P>
   Unger, who attended the Australian National Institute of
Dramatic Arts _ the alma mater of Cate Blanchett, Judy Davis and
Mel Gibson _ claims she's not running from anything; for her, she
says, acting is a means of discovery.
</P>
<P>
   But as a child of divorce, she admits, she's had trouble
figuring out where her real home is. And psychotherapy wouldn't be
much help.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody can tell me that going to a shrink brings any
retribution for your past _ so just get on with it,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   That was her attitude even as a teen-ager, when she finished
school a year and a half ahead of her peers. She was also
precocious in other ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had very large mammary glands,'' she says of herself at 12.
``I looked like the teacher's mistress. But I ended up being
valedictorian, which was my retribution.''
</P>
<P>
   Unger is not now _ and never has been_ anyone's mistress. But
after just ending a 3 1/2-year relationship with a producer, she's
hungry for love. And no, she doesn't mean wild sex.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing wrong with dim lighting and a very intimate
missionary position,'' Unger says. ``The missionary position and
candles. Nouveau sex. The journey back to blushing, I think, is a
fabulous one.''
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Louise Farr is a reporter for Fairchild Publications.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
</TEXT>
