<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-18 12:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8982 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-ONLINE-PUBLISHING-HNS     01-18 1112
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-PUBLISHING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ON-LINE COMPANY TAKES NOVEL APPROACH TO BOOK PUBLISHING 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By VANESSA HUA  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Three years of publishers' rejections proved to David Loye that
he was right.
</P>
<P>
   His book, which challenges prevailing notions of Charles
Darwin's theory of evolution, found no takers. Loye remained
confident despite the rejections, reasoning that groundbreaking
works often meet resistance.
</P>
<P>
   Then the former Princeton University psychology professor found
an outlet through iUniverse, an upstart publisher in Campbell,
Calif., that wants to change the book world.
</P>
<P>
   Due out later this month, ``Darwin's Lost Theory of Love''
argues that the evolutionist did not mean for his landmark thesis
to lead to cutthroat competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``The book was so revolutionary, it was turned down by academic
and trade presses,'' said Loye, 74, an award-winning author who now
lives on the Monterey Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   For as little as $99, iUniverse will publish any new title in
paperback. If an existing book is out of print, the company will
publish it for free.
</P>
<P>
   In return, authors receive royalties ranging from 20 to 50
percent of sales, depending on whether the book is new or
out-of-print, or in paperback or electronic form.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other vanity houses, iUniverse does not charge authors
for the print run. Instead, it makes money from book sales.
</P>
<P>
   The privately-held company, which is not yet profitable, joins a
growing number of on-line publishing houses, including Santa
Clara-based Fatbrain.com and 1stBooks.com of Bloomington, Ind.
Although it is too soon to tell whether such companies will be
profitable, their development has been a page-turner for the book
industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The traditional publisher perpetuates the myth that the book
is rejected because it has no quality. That's elitist. A lot of
good books don't get published,'' said Richard Tam, the president
and chief executive of iUniverse.
</P>
<P>
   With iUniverse, anyone with a version of the great American
novel can see the book in print within a month _ thanks to new
digital, low-cost printing technology and a total free-for-all in
editorial standards.
</P>
<P>
   The company is heir to toExcel, which began publishing
out-of-print titles in late 1998 through its printing business
partner, Lighting Press in Lightning Print is located in La Vergne,
Tenn. A year later, the service's popularity led executives to
expand into publishing new titles, which now account for half its
business, and to launch the company as iUniverse in October 1999.
The name ``toExcel'' remains as iUniverse's line of out-of-print
books.
</P>
<P>
   Old-line publishers in the $80 billion-a-year book market tend
to wager on blockbusters from established authors, rather than take
a risk on new writers with smaller followings, industry watchers
said. Typically, traditional publishers spend $25,000 to $50,000 on
editing and printing for a 10,000- paperback run and must fork over
thousands and even millions of dollars in author advances, upfront
costs they must try to recoup through sales. Other overhead
includes warehousing books and tracking inventory.
</P>
<P>
   iUniverse, with 300 employees, targets the opening left by
traditional houses with fatter budgets. It prints a book only after
receiving a customer order, and can then ship it within 48 hours.
</P>
<P>
   iUniverse's print-on-demand system eliminates inventory costs,
enabling the company to make money on print runs of less than 100
books.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are all about changing the economics of the industry,''
said Tam, who criticized publishers as inefficient and out of touch
with readers. He said the industry's high rate of unsold books
returned to publishers _ up to 30 percent _ signals the need for a
better way to predict and manage inventory.
</P>
<P>
   Conventional publishers defended their process, and also
questioned whether crowding the competitive market with more titles
would help authors.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a consumer point of view, it's better if we can show them
the specials rather than present them with a six-page dinner
menu,'' said Leslie Pockell, an associate publisher at Time Warner
in New York.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS. &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   iUniverse's ambition is to publish 80,000 titles annually by
next year. Last year the company published about 1,300 titles, with
thousands more in the production pipeline.
</P>
<P>
   Its publishing approach won the support of New York-based Barnes
&AMP; Noble, the national bookseller, which acquired a 49 percent stake
in the on-demand publisher in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see this as a tremendous opportunity for people with a
voice to reach an audience,'' said Ken Brooks, Barnes &AMP; Noble's
vice president of digital content.
</P>
<P>
   By February, all 528 Barnes &AMP; Noble retailers will carry
iUniverse displays with publishing information and works from 12 to
15 authors _ an important boost for writers who want to entice
browsing shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   However, iUniverse makes no guarantee of shelf space for its
budding authors. Buyers from Barnes &AMP; Noble will select from titles
recommended by iUniverse staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our buyers need to make sure they exercise control over what
goes into stores,'' Brooks said.
</P>
<P>
   The retail sales channel, coupled with distribution through the
Internet, greatly appealed to Loye. After shoppers browse the text
of iUniverse works on the Internet, they can order through retail
and cyber booksellers.
</P>
<P>
   ``People all over the world can access the book on the first day
it comes out,'' Loye said. Conventional publishers may take years
before reprinting books for overseas markets.
</P>
<P>
   Loye has had other titles published by traditional academic and
trade presses. ``The Healing of a Nation'' received the
Anisfield-Wolfe Award for the best scholarly book on race relations
in 1971. His other books include ``The Leadership Passion: A
Psychology of Ideology,'' ``The Knowable Future: A Psychology of
Forecasting and Prophecy,'' and ``The Sphinx and the Rainbow:
Brain, Mind, and Future Vision.''
</P>
<P>
   Other authors viewed iUniverse as a publisher on the forefront
of technology. Cultural historian Riane Eisler, a Monterey
Peninsula writer, picked iUniverse to publish her latest book,
``The Gate,'' a fictionalized memoir about her experiences growing
up as a European refugee in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to be adventurous. This is the direction that
publishing will be going in many ways. Warehousing costs are
infinitely less, and more and more people are shopping on the
Web,'' said Eisler, 68, whose nonfiction book ``The Chalice and
Blade,'' has sold 500,000 copies worldwide.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-18-00 1251EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
