<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-18 13:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9003 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      01-18 0685
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NEW YORKER VOTERS ARE PRISONERS OF POLITICAL BOSSES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAN LYNCH  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Like most New Yorkers, I'm thrilled that we'll
have a presidential primary election in this state on March 7. Were
I enrolled in a party, I would be enthralled at the prospect of
playing my role in selecting the next leader of the world's oldest
democracy.
</P>
<P>
   OK, George Bernard Shaw had a point when he described democracy
as the substitution of judgment by the incompetent many for that of
the corrupt few. And we've certainly seen ample evidence that
majorities are not always right. But democracy at least provides
us, the people, the opportunity to choose somebody else to blame
for everything that annoys us.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that democracy is hard to come by in this
presidential primary. Most primary states make it fairly easy for
wannabe presidents to get on the ballot. California, for example,
holds its primary on March 7, the same day New York does. The
Golden State ballot will carry about 20 names. Even Libertarian
candidate Lyndon LaRouche will be on there. The California
political bosses put everybody on the ballot except flat-out,
baying-at-the-moon, around-the-bend head cases.
</P>
<P>
   Empire State bosses are vastly less charitable. To get on the
Democratic Party's primary ballot, a candidate has to gather 5,000
signatures on nominating petitions statewide and additional
signatures in each congressional district. On the Republican side,
candidates need 40,000 signatures statewide. The GOP system is less
restrictive than four years ago when Bob Dole was virtually
anointed by New York's Republican bosses, but the principle remains
the same.
</P>
<P>
   That is why the bosses' choice, Texas Gov. George W. Bush, is on
the ballot in all 31 congressional districts. The party
organization carried his petitions for him. Steve Forbes is on in
every district because he had a spare $750,000 clinking around in
his pocket to use in hiring workers to carry petitions. And Arizona
Sen. John McCain won't be on the ballot in several districts. New
York's GOP establishment opposes him, and McCain's daddy didn't
leave him as much money as Forbes' daddy left him.
</P>
<P>
   When I pointed out in a recent column that New York's
presidential primary system is fundamentally undemocratic, my phone
rang off the hook with angry members of both parties incensed over
the situation. Republicans who wanted a chance to vote for Alan
Keyes or Gary Bauer were especially furious.
</P>
<P>
   A woman named Nancy from the Poughkeepsie area asked if she
could write in the candidate of her choice. I checked. The answer
is yes, if she's a Democrat, and it's no if she's a Republican.
</P>
<P>
   There's a write-in area on the voting machine. Close the curtain
and look for it. If you're a Democrat and you want to write in,
say, Jesse Jackson or Warren Beatty, go for it. But on the
Republican side, you don't vote directly for the candidates.
Instead, you vote for delegates pledged to those candidates. Since
neither Keyes nor Bauer could gather enough signatures to get their
delegates' names on the ballot, writing in the name of either
candidate will mean nothing. Election officials won't count your
vote.
</P>
<P>
   Don't think, though, that the Republicans are alone in their
contempt for real democracy in this process. Under Democratic party
rules, party bigwigs are automatically delegates without anybody's
vote. Those so-called super delegates and delegates-at-large make
up roughly 20 percent of the total. And virtually all those people
are solidly in Al Gore's pocket at the moment, whether you and Bill
Bradley like it or not.
</P>
<P>
   What we are looking at on March 7 is a deck cunningly stacked by
the bosses to benefit the bosses' choices. Which means,
essentially, that we New Yorkers have failed to communicate a
crucial message to our political bosses.
</P>
<P>
   Namely, that we insist on governing ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
