<DOCNO> NYT20000118.0059 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-18 13:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9014 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-EVIL-EMPIRE-WARGAMES-     01-18 1437
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EVIL-EMPIRE-WARGAMES-ONE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO US, THE UNITED STATES WAS THE EVIL EMPIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This is Part I of a three-part series by Sergei Khrushchev
about the Cold War from the Soviet perspective. To publish it as a
``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times Syndicate sales
representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.) 
 &HT;    
 By SERGEI KHRUSHCHEV  
 c.2000 American Heritage  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   When the Cold War began, Russians my age were in school, and
when it ended, we were already thinking about retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Our lives were spent amid the fear that America _ our great
national enemy _ would strike a fatal blow if we made the slightest
false step or showed the least weakness. For Americans, of course,
the Soviet Union was the Evil Empire. But for Russians, the United
States was the Evil Empire.
</P>
<P>
   Most of my life was spent in Russia. When, as a mature adult, I
came to the United States, I was amazed at all the parallels
between our respective fears and determination to defend our ideals
and our countries.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, each Cold War power came very close to seizing the
other by the throat in a fit of righteous indignation. In defense
of national ideals, each side verged on using force to make the
other admit it was wrong (always a hopeless approach).
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the statesmanlike and human wisdom of the leaders of
both countries _ and luck _ we succeeded in avoiding a violent
``resolution'' to the ideological quarrel. On its own, the Cold War
expired and, having survived, we can look back now and even joke
about our recent past.
</P>
<P>
   Today we know how close we came to World War III. Now many
secrets are secrets no longer: We know that at the time of Joseph
Stalin's death in 1953, everything seemed to be heading toward a
real war, a nuclear war. The Soviet dictator had ordered an
accelerated buildup of the armed forces not only of the Soviet
Union but also the Warsaw Pact allies, in order to be fully ready
for an armed clash by 1954 or 1955.
</P>
<P>
   Motivated by fear, Stalin ordered that 10,000 tactical IL-28
Soviet bombers, with a range of about 1,500 miles, be produced and
stationed at airfields built on the Arctic Ocean icecaps, closer
than the Soviet empire was to U.S. territory.
</P>
<P>
   The number of Soviet military personnel had reached 5,394,038,
an insupportable burden for a peacetime economy. And yet Stalin
could have done little in case of conflict because the U.S.
strategic Air Force, whose bases surrounded the Soviet Union, could
have destroyed whatever it chose.
</P>
<P>
   Stalin did not possess a weapon capable of responding with a
comparable retaliatory strike on American territory. He knew this
and was deathly afraid of war, but at the same time he considered
it inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   In September 1952 I finished school and began studying at the
Electric Power Institute in Moscow. I wanted to become an engineer
in the field of automated control. At the time, we students were
inclined to be militant, even aggressive: ``Just let them (whomever
you like) poke their noses in here and we'll show them a thing or
two.''
</P>
<P>
   At our desks in school we, like our leaders in the Kremlin, felt
sure that war was not far off.
</P>
<P>
   When America elected Gen. Dwight D. Eisenhower, a hero of World
War II, as president in November 1952, we had no doubt of what it
meant: ``The USA has decided to fight. Otherwise why do they need a
general as president?''
</P>
<P>
   Not that, after living through the horrors of the German
bombings in World War II, we were frightened by the atomic bomb. We
flaunted our courage.
</P>
<P>
   During civil defense classes we were told to cover ourselves
with something white, preferably a sheet, in the event of a nuclear
blast. Supposedly this would reduce the impact of radiation. And
so, a joke immediately went the rounds:
</P>
<P>
   ``If an atomic bomb explodes, cover yourself with a sheet and
crawl to the cemetery _ but without hurrying.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why without hurrying?''
</P>
<P>
   ``So as not to cause a panic.''
</P>
<P>
   However, on March 5, 1953, Providence intervened: Stalin died.
And my father, Nikita Khrushchev, who soon became the head of the
new Soviet leadership, knew from personal experience what war was
like. He had traveled the country's roads for four years during
World War II, retreating from our western borders to Stalingrad and
advancing from Stalingrad to Kiev.
</P>
<P>
   From his first months in power he tried to discern whether the
Americans were irrevocably bent on war or whether it was possible
to reach agreement with them. Interestingly, the White House was
thinking more or less along the same lines.
</P>
<P>
   The first time my father and President Eisenhower met (aside
from a fleeting encounter in June 1945 atop the Lenin Mausoleum,
during a Victory Day Parade in Moscow) was in Geneva in 1955, at
the Four-Power Summit Conference.
</P>
<P>
   In preparing for the trip to Geneva, Father had tried to
anticipate every minor detail; he wanted to prevent any sign of
U.S. disrespect or discrimination against our country.
</P>
<P>
   Still, right away, our national pride was wounded, but not
because of any malicious scheme by the West. The Soviet delegation
arrived in Switzerland on a small two-engine IL-14, while President
Eisenhower landed in a giant four-engine Constellation. That did
not escape Father's attention.
</P>
<P>
   The next year he took his revenge during a visit to England. A
TU-104 passenger jet, which had not yet completed all its test
flights, brought his mail from Moscow to London every day. Even the
Americans did not yet have such a plane. The British queen, hearing
an unusual roar coming from the sky (as she told Father later when
they met), went out on the balcony of her palace to gape at the
marvel.
</P>
<P>
   For sure, the process of getting acquainted was not without its
bizarre moments. During one of the breaks between sessions,
Eisenhower introduced Father to his assistant _ then it was Nelson
Rockefeller. Father inquired, ``Is he THAT Rockefeller?''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it was.
</P>
<P>
   A multimillionaire, but looking no different from anyone else,
as Father later would tell me, not in top hat and tails but
modestly dressed and, moreover, serving in a subordinate position.
</P>
<P>
   Right away, Father was dying to touch a real multimillionaire,
but he didn't know how such a gesture would be interpreted. He
didn't hesitate for long, though, but spread his arms and embraced
Rockefeller somewhere around the waist _ ``Rocky'' was a head and a
half taller than Father.
</P>
<P>
   At first Rockefeller was taken aback, but after a moment he
responded in kind, bearhugging my father.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard for us now, in America or in Russia, to imagine that
era and how distant we were and how little we understood each
other. Such personal episodes were more valuable then than any
round of official negotiations, which were as yet essentially
unproductive.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Father would conclude that he could do business with
Eisenhower, who of course had also experienced the recent war
firsthand and was not about to seek a new one. But a long and
difficult path lay ahead.
</P>
<P>
   At the Four Power Summit, Eisenhower presented his Open Skies
plan, which would have allowed each side to fly over the other's
territory in order to prevent a surprise attack. Father rejected it
outright.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Eisenhower feared a Soviet attack. But Father was afraid
of something quite different. In the process of flying over our
country, America might discover how much weaker we were than they.
This was our most important secret _ the truth of our inadequate
power. Its discovery might prompt the United States to believe it
could carry out a preventive strike against us.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEXT: Part II _ `We Will Bury You' &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c.2000 American Heritage &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Sergei Khrushchev is a senior fellow at the Thomas J. Watson
Jr. Center for International Studies at Brown University. His book,
``The Creation of a Superpower,'' will be published by Penn State
University Press in the fall of 2000. Sergei Khrushchev and his
wife, Valentina Golenko, reside in Rhode Island. They became
citizens of the United States in 1999.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   -------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-18-00 1318EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000118.0060 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-18 13:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9015 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-EVIL-EMPIRE-WARGAMES-     01-18 1437
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EVIL-EMPIRE-WARGAMES-ONE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO US, THE UNITED STATES WAS THE EVIL EMPIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This is Part I of a three-part series by Sergei Khrushchev
about the Cold War from the Soviet perspective. To publish it as a
``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times Syndicate sales
representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.) 
