<DOCNO> NYT20000118.0066 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-18 13:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9018 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-EVIL-EMPIRE-CUBA-THRE     01-18 1464
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EVIL-EMPIRE-CUBA-THREE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 FATHER, CASTRO, KENNEDY and THE CUBAN MISSILE CRISIS  
 &HT;     (This is Part III of a three-part series by Sergei Khrushchev
about the Cold War from the Soviet perspective. To publish it as a
``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times Syndicate sales
representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.)  By SERGEI KHRUSHCHEV  
 c.2000 American Heritage  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   My father, Nikita Khrushchev, always favored direct dialogue,
without intermediaries, and in Vienna, in June 1961 he and
President John F. Kennedy _ at what would turn out to be their only
face-to-face meeting _ agreed to establish a direct White
House-to-Kremlin link by means of special couriers. Kennedy
proposed exchanging confidential letters outside of official State
Department channels; my father readily agreed.
</P>
<P>
   It was a pact that would serve the parties well during the Cuban
missile crisis, which broke out soon afterward, in October 1962.
For the first time in Cold War history, a secret personal
correspondence between two leaders, rather than mutual threats and
propaganda escapades, was the main instrument for resolving a dire
international crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Both the U.S. president and the Soviet leader understood that
although they may have been determined to defend their own national
principles and values, which were incompatible, it was only through
dialogue that they could achieve their common goal of preserving
life on earth.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, when Castro and his companions-in-arms entered
Havana, on Jan. 1, 1959, no one in Moscow took the slightest
interest. The Soviet embassy in Cuba was considered unnecessary and
had closed in 1952. Diplomatic relations continued, but neither an
embassy nor a single Soviet representative remained in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   After reading Western news agency reports about Castro's
triumph, however, Father became curious.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to gather more information, he received the following
reply from the intelligence service and the Party Central
Committee's International Department: ``Castro is the usual Central
American dictator, probably closely connected to the CIA, and will
dance to the American tune, just like Batista.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, when Castro went to Washington expecting to meet with
President Eisenhower, a high-level international specialist from
the Party Central Committee told Father in my presence: ``You see,
Nikita Sergeyevich, we were right. Castro is hurrying to bow to his
master.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Castro intended to conduct a totally independent
policy was evident only later, and Father was the first to
recognize it.
</P>
<P>
   He decided that the only way to defend Cuba from the United
States' inevitable aggression was by deploying missiles with
nuclear warheads on the island. In so doing, he was warning
Washington that military action in that region would automatically
lead to World War III.
</P>
<P>
   In 1963 President Kennedy behaved like Father by declaring that
he was a West Berliner and would defend the city from possible
future Soviet seizure with all the power America possessed. In
economic and other terms, West Berlin was even more useless to
Kennedy than Cuba was to Father.
</P>
<P>
   But the status of a superpower leaves its special mark on the
conduct of world leaders. They have to defend their allies with all
the means available to them. If they retreat an inch, it is
tantamount to bidding farewell to superpower status forever. No one
will believe them any more; such are the implacable rules of the
game in power politics.
</P>
<P>
   It has become customary to argue that Father gave in because of
America's firm stance, that Nikita Khrushchev yielded and blinked
first. In fact, both leaders realized that they would remain in
control of the situation only until the first shot was fired, until
the first bomb was dropped on Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   After that, other rules would take over, the rules of war, of a
third world war. And Father loved to say, ``Any fool can start a
war, but then where are we going to find the wise men to stop it?''
</P>
<P>
   Both he and Kennedy tried to prevent that first shot by every
possible means.
</P>
<P>
   However, Kennedy was under tremendous pressure. Father knew
this, and he took it into account when he decided to withdraw the
missiles from Cuba in exchange for Kennedy's promise not to invade
the island _ a promise he trusted.
</P>
<P>
   This would have been inconceivable in 1952: Trust an American
president! When Father argued at a meeting of the Soviet leadership
in favor of withdrawing the missiles, he made this unprecedented
statement: ``We have to help Kennedy withstand pressure from the
hawks. They are demanding an immediate military invasion.''
</P>
<P>
   A little later, after the withdrawal of the Soviet missiles from
Cuba had begun, Kennedy too asked journalists to help Khrushchev by
not crowing about the American victory. Could anyone have imagined
hearing such words in the White House five years earlier?
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to view the Cuban missile crisis superficially as
Kennedy's victory; he forced the Soviet Union to withdraw. And
Father also thought he had won by protecting Cuba from possible
aggression and by averting a great war. In the political game of
brinkmanship, Father stuck to his opinion: He who decides to blink
first doesn't have weaker nerves, but possesses greater wisdom.
</P>
<P>
   The real main consequence of the Cuban missile crisis was the
American society's irrevocable perception of parity, of equality
between the USSR and the United States in shared nuclear
destructive force.
</P>
<P>
   The American media, not Father, were responsible for that. They
so frightened their countrymen into believing that the Soviets
could blast them to eternity that soon it made no sense at all to
talk about nuclear superiority in terms of plain numbers. The
nation's subconscious simply would not absorb them.
</P>
<P>
   And yet the Cuban drama ended the cycle of crises and
missile-bluff diplomacy. Both sides recognized that they could now
inflict a mortal blow capable not only of mutual annihilation but
also of destroying an entire civilization, of ending life on earth.
</P>
<P>
   In November 1963 John F. Kennedy was assassinated; a year later,
in October 1964, my father was removed from power. The leaders who
replaced Father hurried to ``correct his mistakes'' by giving a new
impetus to the arms race and producing tens of thousands of
tactical nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   By 1989 the Soviet army had 7,000 nuclear cannons. The Cold War
was prolonged by 20 years, on through the start of the 1990s when
the Soviet Union dissolved. Was the failure to end the Cold War in
the 1960s a wasted opportunity? Was the world ready for it to end
then? We can only guess, and regret that it did not happen. Could
the Cold War have been avoided? Was it a product of the ill will of
politicians or was it historically inevitable?
</P>
<P>
   For thousands of years peoples have resolved their conflicts by
armed clashes. With the invention of nuclear weapons, however,
diplomats and politicians suddenly realized that war would no
longer lead to victory, that both sides would lose. Yet they didn't
know how to behave differently so they behaved the same way,
belligerently and aggressively, but without going to war.
</P>
<P>
   War without war was called ``cold war.'' A very accurate
definition. And at the start of this process, at the dawn of the
Cold War, when a great deal was still unsettled and all the
destructive consequences of the use of nuclear weapons were not yet
apparent, it would have been very easy to yield to temptation and
drift into a real war.
</P>
<P>
   I consider it a great achievement, a heroic deed of the world
leaders of those years _ primarily Dwight D. Eisenhower, John F.
Kennedy and my father, Nikita Khrushchev _ that they showed the
wisdom to pass safely over the reefs of a hot war and preserve the
life of humankind.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c.2000 American Heritage &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Sergei Khrushchev is a senior fellow at the Thomas J. Watson
Jr. Center for International Studies at Brown University. His book,
``The Creation of a Superpower,'' will be published by Penn State
University Press in the fall of 2000. Sergei Khrushchev and his
wife, Valentina Golenko, reside in Rhode Island. They became
citizens of the United States in 1999.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   -------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
