<HEADER>
A9024 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-FILM-CAINE-FEATURE-LA     01-18 1135
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-CAINE-FEATURE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITIZEN CAINE _ MICHAEL, THAT IS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's tough to maintain a rebel stance when your life has gone as
well as Michael Caine's.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was the archetypal British angry young man,'' the
66-year-old actor says in what has long been the most sophisticated
Cockney accent on the planet. ``I was always angry at the system
... until we beat the system and there was nothing to be angry
about.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially for Caine, whose journey up from the lower rungs of
England's working class has made him something of an icon for a new
generation of barrier-busting Brits. Long one of the most respected
and hardest-working movie stars on both sides of the Atlantic,
Caine proudly exemplified both his caste (``Alfie,'' ``Get
Carter,'' ``The Man Who Would Be King,'' ``Little Voice'') and a
more general, high standard of English intelligence (``The Ipcress
File,'' ``Sleuth,'' ``Dressed to Kill,'' ``Educating Rita,'' his
Oscar-winning supporting part in ``Hannah and her Sisters'')
throughout a career that has included some 80 feature films.
</P>
<P>
   Add to that 28 years of a happy marriage that's produced two
daughters he adores. And success in other fields (a string of
restaurants, his best-selling autobiography). Not much to complain
about, especially now that the character-based movies he prefers
are back in style.
</P>
<P>
   But there is something about ``The Cider House Rules,'' Caine's
latest picture, that brought out the old maverick impulse.
</P>
<P>
   ``The title refers to the rules posted on the wall of this house
where itinerant apple-pickers stay,'' Caine says of the acclaimed
adaptation of John Irving's popular, 1940s-set novel. ``Delroy
Lindo delivers the most important line in the picture when he says,
`Whoever wrote those rules never lived here.' That's what worries
me about all those things. I came from a very class-conscious
country and from the lowest possible class, and there always seemed
to be somebody making rules for me who not only did not know me but
didn't want to know me. So I became an absolute rebel about rules,
and I think the abortion theme, in John Irving's mind, is a
metaphor for that: You cannot blanket anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Caine plays Dr. Larch, the kindly, ether-addicted master of a
rural Maine orphanage who performs safe but illegal abortions on
the side. He longs to convince his favorite charge, Homer Wells
(Tobey Maguire), to follow in his footsteps. But even though the
young man displays great doctoring talent despite his lack of
medical schooling, he's understandably hesitant to perform an
operation that, but for chance, could easily have prevented his own
existence.
</P>
<P>
   Though Irving released pre-emptive defenses against potential
criticism of the film's pro-choice stance and Larch's character in
particular, such protests have so far failed to materialize. Part
of that may be due to the way that Caine makes Larch, whatever his
shortcomings, such a sweet guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is the nicest man, the kindest man, the most compassionate
man that I have ever played ... and I've played a lot of
sleazebags,'' Caine acknowledges. ``I mean, Dr. Larch could be a
sleaze as well, depending on your point of view. A guy who performs
illegal abortions, does ether and forges medical documents isn't
exactly St. Francis of Assisi. But it was the compassion in the
character that meant so much to me.''
</P>
<P>
   So much, in fact, that Caine did something he'd never done
before: essay a typical American accent. While he's occasionally
gone for regional U.S. dialects, such as in the Georgia-set ``Hurry
Sundown,'' Caine has overwhelmingly stuck to his own voice for the
past 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   Again, not the typical habit of the well-trained English actor,
most of whom make a big deal out of showing off their expertise
with every variation of the language the world has to offer.
Caine's approach ran characteristically counter to all of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happens to me is, I'll watch a performance like that and
say, `My God, there's a British actor doing a wonderful American
accent,''' Caine explains. ``I didn't do that. I just tried to be
American, that's it, not do any accent. When you see the movie, you
shouldn't be aware that I'm British, it's so subtle. If I'm doing
it right, you can't see the performance.''
</P>
<P>
   Caine did employ a dialogue coach for the job, insisting that he
frankly tell the actor, after two weeks of practice, whether he was
at all convincing or not. That and ``American friends whose
barbarity I rely on.''
</P>
<P>
   Reviews have been mixed, with some saying Caine nailed the
accent perfectly and others left unconvinced. But it was good
enough for the Hollywood Foreign Press Association, which has
nominated Caine for a Golden Globe Award. He won the group's
supporting actor trophy last year for his sublime portrayal of a
two-bit talent manager in ``Little Voice.'' But there was no
subsequent Oscar nomination, which didn't necessarily surprise the
actor. After all, he considers his Academy Award for Woody Allen's
``Hannah'' a fluke.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who were voting were very perceptive that year,''
Caine says, not sounding too egotistical. ``Very often, you'll see
Academy Awards go to actors who are patently and obviously acting.
Everybody says, `What a wonderful performance that is!' But you're
supposed to be sitting there feeling sorry, happy, sad or hilarious
for this wonderful human being you're seeing. It has nothing to do
with actors.''
</P>
<P>
   By Caine's estimation, movies in general had little to do with
acting by the mid-1990s. Never exactly a snob about work _ he would
rather infamously knock out three to five films a year, often
regardless of quality, in his heyday _ the actor had essentially
lost interest in the field between 1993 and '97.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a couple of years, a person who was an actor rather than
an action star or something like that thought that they were never
going to make plot- or character-led movies again because they
don't make any money,'' he recalls. ``I worried about that because
I was too old to play the action stuff and I couldn't find anything
that was worth doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``But now, there is a load,'' adds Caine, who has ``Quills,'' a
film about the Marquis De Sade, and an update of ``King Lear'' set
in a contemporary underworld milieu on the horizon. ``Now, I
continue to work because I like to work, and I'm doing work that I
want to do. Professionally and in all other ways, I am an extremely
fulfilled and happy man.''
</P>
<P>
   But the young man hasn't completely gone away.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some reason, I still have some leftover anger,'' Caine
reveals, not entirely convincingly. ``So what I do is, I'm now
angry for others; I'm liable to espouse some causes.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
