</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIAN-PUBLIC-SPEAKS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT THE RUSSIAN PEOPLE ARE SAYING ABOUT NUKES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased
_ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.) 
 &HT;    
 By VLADIMIR ORLOV and IVAN A. SAFRANCHUK  
 c.2000 The Bulletin of the Atomic Scientists  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   For the first time, an opinion poll reveals what the Russian
public thinks about a wide range of nuclear security issues, from
the Strategic Arms Control Treaty to nuclear smuggling.
</P>
<P>
   The poll, ``Examining Attitudes of Russians Towards Nuclear
Weapons and Nuclear Threats,'' was jointly sponsored by Moscow's
Center for Policy Studies in Russia and the Center for
Nonproliferation Studies of the Monterey Institute in California.
</P>
<P>
   It was based on interviews with 1,500 people in 56 localities
throughout the Russian Federation, and was released Nov. 16. The
research was conducted by Fond Obshestvennoye Mneniye _ a well
respected, politically independent Russian polling company.
</P>
<P>
   The survey helps to clarify how Russians think about nuclear
weapons _ including the role they play in world politics, how much
Russia needs them for its own security and how they could be
diverted for use by international terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   The results also demonstrate that, as elsewhere, the public on
this issue does not always agree with the official government and
military positions.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the end of the Cold War and a halt to the U.S.-Soviet
superpower arms race, the survey showed that a significant number
of Russians find comfort in their country's nuclear weapons; 77
percent supported the Russian National Security Concept provision
that says: ``Nuclear weapons play a decisive role in providing
national security.''
</P>
<P>
   Of those polled, 24 percent acknowledged that it is costly for
Russia to maintain its nuclear arsenal, but 32 percent said Russia
ought to have as many nukes as the United States _ while 26 percent
supported the idea of a Russia with more nuclear weapons than
America.
</P>
<P>
   As for totally deactivating their nuclear weapons, it wasn't a
popular idea: 82 percent thought Russia's nuclear arsenal must be
on active duty and ready for use; a mere 12 percent said that the
nukes should be kept in storage. Only 18 percent of those polled
thought Russia didn't need any nukes at all.
</P>
<P>
   That such weapons could fall into the hands of the wrong people
weighed heavily on respondents, with fear voiced about possible
sabotage of Russian nuclear facilities, including power plants and
nuclear munitions storage sites _ 90 percent of those polled
expressed such a fear.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, the survey was taken after a devastating series of
terrorist bombs in Moscow and other Russian cities killed more than
300 people _ attacks blamed by the Kremlin on Chechen warlords and
bandits, although solid evidence of guilt remains absent. This
continues to be used as rationale for the bloody Russian military
campaign in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the fact that nine out of every 10 of Russian
adults polled said that nuclear sabotage is possible demonstrates
how great the fear is. It also shows how little the Russian people
trust the official statements which claim that ``all strategic
facilities are under control.''
</P>
<P>
   While only 52 percent of those polled expressed concern about a
nuclear attack by foreign states, 86 percent expressed fear that
international terrorists might use nuclear weapons against Russia.
Only 10 percent considered such terrorism to be improbable; only 4
percent had difficulty answering this question, which suggests that
the majority are indeed living with concern about nuclear
terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   Ordinary Russians, the poll revealed, simply don't buy the
assurances of their senior government officials that there is no
way for nuclear thieves to steal weapons-grade fissile materials
from domestic nuclear facilities. The majority, 83 percent of
respondents, believed it possible to smuggle such lethal materials
out of the country.
</P>
<P>
   Russians generally valued the concept of curbing the spread of
nukes, with 76 percent saying the world would be far less stable if
more countries had nuclear weapons. Education played a role in
this: 81 percent of those with a higher education said nuclear
proliferation would diminish global stability; so did 74 percent of
those with a secondary education and 64 percent with a primary
education.
</P>
<P>
   Even those respondents who believed that world stability could
be improved by the proliferation of nuclear weapons opposed the
idea of selling Russian nuclear arms and technologies abroad.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, Russians don't balk at the idea of total world
nuclear disarmament. Of those polled, 57 percent believed the world
would be a more stable place if all nuclear weapons were abolished.
Russians 60 years of age or older were the biggest supporters _ 67
percent of the elderly Russians believed that eliminating all
nuclear arms would add to international stability.
</P>
<P>
   As for cutbacks, 55 percent of those polled supported
ratification of the START II treaty, which has languished in the
Russian Duma, or parliament, since 1993, and only 25 percent were
opposed. Interestingly, 72 percent of those polled said America
would implement only those treaty provisions of benefit to itself.
</P>
<P>
   Being a nuclear power is linked to global influence, many
Russians believed. Of those polled, 40 percent said Russia will
have a say in world politics if it kept its nuclear weapons; 37
percent thought other nations wouldn't dare attack a nuclear-armed
Russia. Only 23 percent said nuclear weapons were necessary because
developing nuclear technology promotes technical progress.
</P>
<P>
   Almost half of respondents, 47 percent, also thought that Russia
should retain the right to launch a first strike _ which is the
official position of their government. However, a large minority,
38 percent, held the opposite view, and the rest found the question
difficult to answer.
</P>
<P>
   As to politics, people's political preferences generally had
very little impact on the opinions reflected in their answers. But
among the more illuminating data:
</P>
<P>
   __ Seventy-nine percent of those polled who were followers of
Yevgeny M. Primakov, former prime minister and leader of
Fatherland-All Russia, a centrist electoral alliance, said the
United States could not be trusted to act fairly in fulfilling its
international arms-control treaty obligations. Primakov is
currently the most likely competitor to Acting President Vladimir
V. Putin in the March 26 presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   __ Twenty-three percent of those polled who were supporters of
Gennadi A. Zyuganov, leader of the Communist Party, maintained that
Russia should have the same number of nuclear weapons as the United
States; 31 percent were sure that Russia needed more. Moreover, his
supporters accounted for the largest number of those opposed to the
six-year-old START II treaty, which calls for the reduction of
nuclear stockpiles.
</P>
<P>
   __ Fifty-four percent of those polled who were followers of
Vladimir V. Zhirinovsky, the ultranationalist leader, believed that
Russian nukes should be permanently targeted at certain states.
</P>
<P>
   __ Eighty-seven percent of supporters of Sergei Kiriyenko,
another former prime minister and leader of the Union of Right
Forces, a pro-capitalist group, were sure the world would be less
stable if more countries possessed nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c.2000 The Bulletin of the Atomic Scientists &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Vladimir Orlov is the director of Moscow's Center for Policy
Studies in Russia. Ivan A. Safranchuk is a research associate at
the center. This article appeared originally in the Jan.-Feb. 2000
issue of The Bulletin of the Atomic Scientists
(www.thebulletin.org).) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ------------------ &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
