<HEADLINE>
CHANGES MAY NOT SUIT HARKES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Revolution coach Fernando Clavijo has some
major decisions to make before preseason training begins next week,
and among the first will involve his former World Cup teammate,
John Harkes.
</P>
<P>
   Harkes has been rehabilitated to US national team status, which
is justice for the unceremonious way he was dismissed before France
'98. Harkes was on the bench for the US's 1-1 tie with Iran at the
Rose Bowl Sunday, but his status has not been defined for either
the US or the Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   The question Clavijo must answer is: Can Harkes's status as a
top-salaried player be justified without him being the focal point
of the team? Harkes could play a role as elder statesman with the
national team, but the Revolution have several others qualified for
those responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Harkes, then, must decide whether he can take on a lower profile
and accept a lower salary, at least on paper. This will not be easy
for someone who has performed in 168 English League games, the FA
Cup final, and two World Cup finals, and won two MLS Cup titles
with D.C. United.
</P>
<P>
   ``John is a big part of the team,'' Clavijo said. ``I know how
he feels because I've been there myself.
</P>
<P>
   ``He thinks we have a playoff team without making any changes.
But we are bringing in guys, and some guys are going to have to
make sacrifices, and he is one of them. The salary issue is an
unfortunate situation because every player who renegotiates expects
a 5 percent increase. Something has to give. No individual can win
or lose games by himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am trying to build a team and we are going to have to go
through the process, and that includes some suffering. I've told
John he has a big part to play. He is a great competitor, a winner,
and he can help the team tremendously.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the small group of US fans at the Rose Bowl was one with a
sign that read: ``Harkesy Rules.'' But even though Harkes performed
well in pregame training sessions, he was not used by coach Bruce
Arena. Clearly, Arena plans to go with younger players, but he also
wants to mix in some veterans to provide guidance.
</P>
<P>
   At age 32, Harkes is at a crossroads in his career. He said he
is negotiating with MLS and hopes to return to the Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a contract that potentially allows me to stay in New
England for three or four years,'' Harkes said. ``I love playing in
New England and for the fans. I enjoy the people up there. The only
problem is my family is in Northern Virginia and we are expecting
our third child in March.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fernando wants me on the team and I am an important part of
the team and I'm excited about that. It was frustrating last year
because we had good players and we had the potential but we just
didn't come around.''
</P>
<P>
   Harkes might be overvaluing the Revolution, who won just seven
games in regulation time last season. Certainly, the starting
lineup was capable of success, especially with Walter Zenga in
goal. But no team can be expected to perform at maximum ability
every game, and the Revolution simply lacked the depth to
compensate for injuries and national team absences.
</P>
<P>
   Nor should the Revolution delude themselves. They could not
challenge D.C. United last year and they will not be able to do so
this season. They should attempt to simply improve to the point
where they have a coherent, consistent style of play. If they can
remained poised for 90 minutes for the majority of games _ whether
losing, tying, or winning _ then they can make progress.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Iranian inroads
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Iranian players such as Andranik Eskandarian performed well in
the North American Soccer League, which recruited them after the
Argentina '78 World Cup. And Los Angeles Galaxy coach Sigi Schmid
expressed interest in Khodadad Azizi, who set up Iran's goal
against the US Sunday. The purchase price of Azizi, 30, would be
$700,000 from FC Cologne in Germany, an amount the MLS could
quickly recoup by promoting Azizi in Southern California, home of
hundreds of thousands of Iranian immigrants. But the Galaxy also
hope to add a Mexican player to replace Carlos Hermosillo, who has
returned to Mexico to play for America. ``An Iranian player with
the Galaxy would look good for the MLS,'' said Hassan Alesafar, a
commentator for Radio Sedaye, a Santa Monica-based Iranian
broadcaster. ``This tour should be a positive for the Iranian
players, especially the ones who are not playing much in Germany.''
Azizi, at 5 feet 6 inches, is an excellent foil for 6-3 Ali Daei in
Iran's forward line. But while Daei is an important part of the
Hertha Berlin team, Azizi seldom plays for Cologne . . . The
US-Iran game was played exactly 21 years after Shah Mohammed Reza
Pahlavi abdicated. And it provided a chance for the exorcising of
demons: The US compensated somewhat for its poor performance at
France '98, when it was defeated by Iran (2-1), and for Iranians
who have been contending with identity and image problems since
militants seized 52 American hostages at the US embassy in Teheran
in 1979 . . . Iran supporters were in the majority of the
approximately 35,000 spectators who attended the Iran-Ecuador match
Wednesday. The attendance for the US-Iran game was announced as
50,181, but the 100,000-seat Rose Bowl appeared to be two-thirds
full.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A losing trend
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Four MLS teams have lost their leading scorers from 1999. The
latest to depart was Musa Shannon, a Liberia native with a US
passport, who went from Tampa Bay to Maritimo in Portugal. Shannon
was offered $50,000 by MLS after scoring 11 goals last season. But
based on a two-day visit to the Madeira Islands, Maritimo sealed a
deal worth more than $125,000 annually, plus bonuses, for 3 1/2
years, according to his agent, Patrick McCabe. Maritimo officials
believe Shannon could be worth as much as $1 million if he has a
successful season. Shannon appears to be an example of either a
double standard or misplaced emphasis by MLS. He had the
uninhibited personality that captures the imagination of fans,
setting him apart from the generic US player. Yet he was offered
the same salary as D.C. United striker A.J. Wood, who has scored
fewer goals and had no leverage in negotiations. ``It's a question
of economics,'' McCabe said. ``Certain players, for whatever
reason, are valued more than others, for reasons other than talent
and how they perform. There doesn't seem to be any logic in it. The
MLS says they want to keep their best players, especially the young
ones, but there were only three young players among the leading
scorers in the league, and they lost two of them.'' MLS signed San
Jose striker Ronald Cerritos, 25, for $330,000 annually but lost
Stern John, 23, and Shannon, 24. The league profited from John, who
earned a total of about $85,000 while producing 44 goals in two
seasons for the Columbus Crew, then went to Nottingham Forest in a
deal worth at least $2 million. But MLS lost Shannon, Joe-Max Moore
(Revolution/Everton), and Hermosillo (Los Angeles/America) without
compensation. Moore scored his first goal of the season for Everton
in a 2-2 tie with Tottenham Hotspur Saturday . . . The hiring of
April Heinrichs as head coach of the US women's national team is
expected to accelerate negotiations to end a player strike before
the next game, against Norway Feb. 6. A meeting with the players
and US Soccer Federation officials is planned in New York Jan. 24.
Heinrichs was captain of the team, then retired after the 1991
World Cup . . . Debbie Belkin, formerly of Needham, also a member
of the '91 World Cup team, was named to the all-time collegiate
women's all-star team by Soccer America magazine. Belkin, who
played at the University of Massachusetts, is coaching at the
University of Michigan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
