<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE END OF MANAGED CARE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I have opined that Manuel Ferris was the single most blameworthy
manager in the debacle at Harvard Pilgrim Health Care, now in state
receivership after losing an estimated $177 million or so last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine my surprise when I discovered that Ferris is still
serving as chairman of the board at Boston Medical Center, the
Boston University-affiliated reincarnation of Boston City Hospital,
now run by a semi-independent authority.
</P>
<P>
   A Boston resident, as reported at the time of his appointment?
Are you kidding?
</P>
<P>
   Ferris was the out-of-work hotel industry exec who took over the
helm at Harvard Community Health Plan in 1991, merged it with
Pilgrim Health Care in 1994, all the while living in Tucson and
commuting for three or four days at a time to a pied-a-terre at the
Four Seasons.
</P>
<P>
   When in 1996 the 63-year-old Ferris gave up his $880,000 job
``for personal reasons'' and retired to Arizona for the second
time, Mayor Thomas Menino persuaded him to stick around enough to
head the Boston Medical Center board _ Ferris having kindly brought
the troubled city hospital into the HCHP network. He is chief among
30 trustees _ 10 of them named by Menino, 10 by Boston University,
and 10 ex-officio members representing various constituencies.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine my delight when Ferris's Arizona phone number, which is
unlisted, came in over the transom from a reader. Imagine my
disappointment when I called Monday to learn he had just gone out.
</P>
<P>
   It is important to explore the history of the Harvard HMO, to
identify the missteps and missteppers and hold them up to public
view. We can expect Massachusetts Attorney General Thomas F. Reilly
to provide a thorough accounting of the case. For openers, Reilly
last week canceled generous severance packages for two executives
on whose watch the problem escalated out of control. He's preparing
to hire an investment banker to survey the range of options _ many
of them quite complicated _ that might return the health plan to
solvency.
</P>
<P>
   It is important to remember, however, that the health care
system has been in turmoil nationally for more than a decade. The
Massachusetts system with its local problems is embedded in the
far-more-extensive controversy over the appropriate form for a
national health insurance system. How to tell which way is up?
</P>
<P>
   The current issue of the Journal of Health Politics, Policy and
Law, edited by Mark Peterson of the University of California at Los
Angeles, is a big help in finding the horizon. Called the ``The
Managed Care Backlash,'' it contains 36 articles by many of the
biggest names in health care economics examining the problem from
every conceivable angle.
</P>
<P>
   Among the most persuasive of its essays is ``The Death of
Managed Care as We Know It,'' a critique of the logic of managed
care by a liberal health care economist, Katherine Swartz, of the
Harvard School of Public Health.
</P>
<P>
   HMO medicine grew to prominence on the strength of two basic
promises, Swartz writes; to deliver better care at lower cost
through good management and better information systems; and to
foster competition among health plans that would render all
organizations more efficient. Today, she says, the public believes
that neither of these promises has been fulfilled. For at least two
reasons, she says, the backlash against managed care will be hard
to reverse. First, she writes, ``managed care's financial
incentives for providers to skimp on care make it difficult for
patients to trust that an advised course of action is in a
patient's true best interests.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Second, consumers want to be able to choose providers . . . in
large part so that they can find providers that they feel are
responsive to their needs and who will act as their agents,'' she
adds. Physicians now recognize that they risk losing patients'
trust if they don't distance themselves from managed care plans.
</P>
<P>
   Any remedy for the Harvard Pilgrim receivership is going to
require an informed bet on where the national system is headed next
_ starting with the next election.
</P>
<P>
   Is it possible that George W. Bush, though he says little about
health care on the stump, is a better bet to come up with an
equitable and efficient solution than either of the Democrats, each
of them full of bold talk?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Warsh is a Boston Globe columnist. His e-mail address is
warsh(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
