<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROFILE-BETTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHE' FASHIONING A BRAND-NEW BAZAAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUZANNE C. RYAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With the turn of the century, the fashion world is
witnessing cultural change at the speed of light. Hip hop clothing
is as relevant to style as Paris runways, Internet ``e-tailing'' is
thriving, design houses are trading on Wall Street, khakis are
eclipsing business suits, and senior citizens are garbed in Old
Navy.
</P>
<P>
   It's not an era for an out-of-touch, lady-who-lunches species of
fashion editor. Enter Katherine Betts, 35, the new editor in chief
of Harper's Bazaar.
</P>
<P>
   Betts resigned as a top editor at Vogue last June to take the
helm of its longtime rival. Her mission is simple _ to turn the
oldest US fashion magazine (Bazaar, founded in 1867, currently
ranks No. 3 in circulation behind Vogue and Elle) into a ``more
practical, journalistic'' entity with a focus on lifestyles,
off-runway fashion news, society, culture, and arts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the days of fashion magazines being created in one
person's image are over,'' Betts said recently in her 37th-floor
executive suite in Manhattan. ``You have to show lots of different
options and points of view. You can't just say there's only one way
to look.'' Betts, dressed smartly in black Prada jacket, tweed
Celine skirt, and Christian Louboutin high-heeled black suede
boots, said she wants to make Bazaar ``younger in spirit, energy,
and inclusiveness.''
</P>
<P>
   This week, Bazaar readers, whose median age is 38, can judge for
themselves with the newsstand release of Betts's third issue. The
February edition, with Gwyneth Paltrow on the cover, features a
complete redesign, with new writers, photographers, typefaces, and
sections such as Tremor (on industry trends), Style Safari
(off-runway fashion news), and Reality Check (a look at how women
are adapting to fashion in their lives).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Stories include a feature on the post-PC generation; a profile
on a group of young female photographers who are hot just now in
the art world; and a look inside the homes of sisters Aerin and
Jane Lauder, granddaughters of the founder of the Estee Lauder
cosmetics company.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt strongly that one of the great traditions of Bazaar was
its quirky, offbeat content,'' said Betts. ``I wanted to maintain
that feeling of surprise but combine it with more journalistic news
and design. Often, those are considered to be mutually exclusive.''
</P>
<P>
   Betts was approached for the top job last June after her
predecessor, Liz Tilberis, 51, died of ovarian cancer in April.
Tilberis had served as editor since 1992. ``I knew Liz
professionally. Those were big shoes to fill,'' said Betts.
</P>
<P>
   Cathleen Black, president of Hearst Magazines (a division of
Bazaar's publisher, Hearst Communications), challenged Betts to
create a prototype ``as if she was doing the July, August, and
September issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``She put together a wonderful book with a fabulous cover and
three tables of content,'' Black said. ``We loved it.''
</P>
<P>
   A job offer soon followed. ``This was an opportunity I couldn't
turn down. This is a dream job,'' Betts said. But the timing on the
appointment couldn't have been worse; she was nine months pregnant
with her first child, Oliver. ``I resigned (from Vogue) on my due
date. I was very pregnant. Oliver was 10 pounds, 6 ounces!''
</P>
<P>
   Betts took a two-month maternity leave during which she worked
from her Manhattan home, recovered from a caesarean section, and
opened gifts from designers all over the world. ``Oliver got a lot
of baby clothes,'' she said, smiling. ``People were very
generous.''
</P>
<P>
   In September, the 5-foot-9 dynamo hit the ground running,
working 10-hour days building her staff and creating the magazine
redesign. Oliver stayed at home with a nanny.
</P>
<P>
   In October _ just one month into the job _ Betts prepared to
bring her infant to Milan while she covered the fashion shows. Her
intent was to have her nanny and her husband, Chip Brown (a
freelance magazine writer and author of an alternative medicine
book), keep her son at the hotel. ``I would never bring a baby to a
show,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Betts was assured by her travel agency that Oliver
didn't need a passport to travel, only a birth certificate, the
Delta Airlines agent wasn't budging when the time came to board the
plane. ``He said, `Where's the baby's passport?' '' recalled Betts,
who was standing there with eight suitcases full of formula,
diapers, bottles, wipes, and clothing. ``I tried to beg them and
plead. But they said even if they let me go, Italy wouldn't allow
us in when we arrived.''
</P>
<P>
   Duty called, so Betts flew forlornly to Milan by herself while
Oliver went back home with his father, who secured a passport in
three days. Husband, son, and nanny then joined Betts in Europe.
``Most of the way across the Atlantic,'' Betts said in her December
editor's letter, ``I wondered how millions of modern American women
manage the difficult balance of motherhood and work.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Betts's role model was her own mother, Glynne Robinson
Betts, a photographer and former publisher of two Connecticut
newspapers, the Lakeville Journal and the Millerton News. Not only
did Glynne work when Katherine was growing up, she was also a style
maven, said her daughter. (Katherine's father, Hobart Betts, is an
architect). To be sure, it wasn't hard to be fashion-conscious
growing up in Manhattan four blocks from Bloomingdale's and across
the street from the famed designer Halston.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``He had all these huge, blow-out parties and I was always
really fascinated, looking out the window. I remember drag queens
lounging on Jaguars outside. My brother and I would always try to
sneak in,'' she said. ``My brother got in a lot, but I didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   During her years at Princeton University as a European history
major, Betts immersed herself in fashion by summering in Paris
twice. ``I love France, the language, the people. I always knew I
wanted to live there.'' After graduation in 1986, Betts, fluent in
French, landed a job as an editorial assistant at the International
Herald Tribune newspaper in Paris. Meanwhile, she freelanced for
various magazines, writing profiles and traveling across Europe.
``I always wanted to be a reporter.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, a magazine piece she wrote on wild-boar hunting caught
the eye of John Fairchild, editor at large of Fairchild
Publications (which publishes W magazine and the industry newspaper
Women's Wear Daily, or WWD). ``WWD was looking for a feature writer
in Paris,'' she said. ``I didn't have any experience in the
industry.'' But Betts got the job anyway. And in 18 months, the
go-getter was bureau chief. ``It's amazing the training you get at
WWD. It's sort of a graduate school for fashion journalism.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, Betts met Anna Wintour, Vogue's editor in chief,
through a friend. The two hit it off and in May 1991, Wintour
persuaded Betts to leave Paris, move back to New York, and work for
Vogue as a writer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very lucky at Vogue,'' Betts said. ``Anna gave me a lot
of freedom. I was very independent.'' And fruitful. Betts produced
runway reports, designer profiles, popular culture stories, and
Vogue's themed issues. The editor also created two popular
sections, Vogue's View (feature stories) and Vogue's Index (hot
items and where to find them). Betts was promoted to fashion news
director in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was at Vogue a long time and I loved it,'' she said. Her
December editor's letter in Harper's Bazaar credits Wintour as her
mentor. ``She taught me how to connect trends in fashion to the
culture at large, gave me the freedom to develop my own ideas, and
when, after eight years at Vogue, I had the chance to take the
reins of the competition, she gave me her blessing.''
</P>
<P>
   Wintour, in her September editor's letter, said, ``Weeks after
Kate joined Vogue. . . I knew that one day she would edit her own
magazine. . . She is highly intelligent, has a great journalistic
sense, and has never been duped by even the most passionate fashion
enthusiast. I feel sad that we will now be rivals and will miss
sitting next to her at fashion shows.''
</P>
<P>
   Although she was rumored to be the heir apparent at Vogue, Betts
maintains that wasn't true. ``I didn't feel I was going to be
editor,'' she said emphatically. ``I always wanted to be the editor
of a magazine.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now Betts has her hands full motivating 55 staffers to cover an
industry where, as she puts it, ``the only constant is change.''
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times recently said that Betts is, essentially,
remaking Bazaar in the image of Vogue with similar headlines,
feature stories, and even the same January cover model. Amazingly,
the model, Gisele, is dressed for both covers in Gucci python
outfits. Said Betts, ``It's a fashion moment. No, I am not remaking
Bazaar in the image of Vogue. Let Bazaar speak for itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly Betts's publisher is confident in her abilities. Said
Black, ``I joined the company about four years ago and people right
away said there's a big young talent at Vogue that you ought to
keep your eye on. Kate stood out because of the work she was doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she has a very young, contemporary, modern vision of
fashion. . . beyond the runway. My sense is that she is an editor
for a new generation. I think she'll take the best of what Bazaar
stands for and will infuse it with a new and younger perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   Bazaar's paid circulation, currently about 750,000, has
fluctuated since 1994 but never approached Vogue's, which currently
has a paid circulation of about 1.1 million, according to the Audit
Bureau of Circulations. Elle's paid circulation is about 913,000.
Then there is the newcomer competition, such as InStyle magazine
and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   All these rivals are vying for the attention of busier-than-ever
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, naysayers in the industry contend the average woman
no longer cares about fashion because runways are irrelevant to her
life.
</P>
<P>
   ``People love to say that fashion is dead,'' said Betts with a
smirk and dismissive wave of her hand. ``Yes, the business has
changed dramatically. There are (initial public offerings),
mergers, and this whole idea that the consumer is more aware of the
stock price and the shoe price.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still think women will always be interested in designer
fashion. That's what's new. I think every brand now needs a certain
profile on the Net (Bazaar's site is coming in April). But I'm not
convinced people are reading full pieces on the Net. People still
want to read magazines.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
