<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-COLLINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIT PLAYER SRICHAPHAN SHOWS A FLAIR FOR THE DRAMATIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MELBOURNE _ Although ``Anna and the King'' is banned in Thailand
as politically incoherent _ a tough break for the country's Jodie
Foster fans _ a local version in sneakers opened here to fine
reviews Monday at an amphitheater beside the muddy but sun-speckled
Yara River.
</P>
<P>
   Anna and the King of the former Siam _ a.k.a. Anna Kournikova
and Paradorn Srichaphan _ played their parts brilliantly as the
Australian Open cranked into being, the traditional springboard for
another long-running tennis campaign.
</P>
<P>
   This Russian Anna, who commands innumerable male subjects across
the world, must be the most glorified athlete never to win
anything. But even though she's getting on, aged to 18, there's
still a chance she'll cop a title somewhere one of these days.
Nevertheless, that shortcoming doesn't seem to matter to her
worshippers.
</P>
<P>
   But Paradorn Srichaphan? A king? You bet. The king of Thailand
tennis. The greatest in his homeland's history. However, can
anybody name another?
</P>
<P>
   ``Our real king, King Pumipol, does play tennis,'' said
Srichaphan, smiling after stunning 14th-seeded Karol Kucera of
Slovak Republic, 6-2, 6-4, 3-6, 6-3. ``But I guess I'm better.''
</P>
<P>
   US Open finalist Todd Martin thought he was better than
Zimbabwean Byron Black, but had to spend all afternoon proving it
while making the escape of the day, 5-7, 6-7 (4-7), 6-4, 6-2, 8-6.
After working his way back to 5-4, 30-0 in the fifth, Martin
(moaning inwardly, ``what happened?'') found himself staring at
three match points, 5-6, 0-40, before serving his way to safety.
</P>
<P>
   Kournikova can emote. Not in a league with Jodie Foster. Or
Deborah Kerr, who was Anna opposite Yul Brynner's monarch in the
earlier film, a musical, ``The King and I.'' But there was no drama
to this Anna's 2000 debut at Melbourne Park, not enough of her on
the asphalt stage, a mere stadium cameo leaving an audience of
13,000 wanting more.
</P>
<P>
   Silencing Austrian Patricia Wartusch in 34 minutes, Kournikova
rolled a merciless double bagel. Still, from the loser's
standpoint, it was a genuine tear-jerker. Wartusch wept as she
departed the 6-0, 6-0, scene _ ``my first (major) match, and all
those people watching. I wanted to do better.'' She collected all
of 24 points, but $7,200, which should cover a lot of Kleenex.
</P>
<P>
   It was different out on Court 6. There, a few hundred customers,
largely Slovak immigrants plus a couple dozen Thais living in
Melbourne and the otherwise curious, gathered to witness an
expected victory for Kucera. Two years ago Kucera beat Pete Sampras
to make the semis here, and Andre Agassi to enter the quarters at
the US Open while rising to No. 8. He was a quarterfinalist here a
year ago, a name.
</P>
<P>
   Across the net, Srichaphan was just a 20-year-old extra from a
tennis desert, ranked No. 106. But the curious wanted to know what
a Thai guy with racket could do. They were aware of Siamese cats
and Siamese twins, Thai cuisine and Thai silk after the country
changed its name. But a Thai tennis player?
</P>
<P>
   ``There aren't many of us, only two of us on the tour,'' said
Srichaphan, his eyes sparkling after ``my greatest day. Me and
Tamarine (Tanasugarn).'' She ranks No. 72 on the female tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``My brother, Narathorn, and I are the Thai Davis Cup team, but
he isn't good enough for the ATP Tour. But we're proud to have
moved up to Division 1, and play New Zealand next month.''
</P>
<P>
   Srichaphan has picked up English quickly and well, and hopes to
inspire ``more Thai, more Asians to play.'' A quick-stepping 6 feet
1 inches (``big for a Thai''), he was as hot as the spicy tom yum
soup he adores, as smooth as Thai silk all over the court, banging
flat, topped, and sliced groundies and nailing crucial volleys.
</P>
<P>
   No Thai male had ever won a major match until he qualified at
the last Wimbledon, then stopped France's Guillaume Raoux in the
first round before losing to Yevgeny Kafelnikov in four sets.
</P>
<P>
   How did this swift and eager beaver develop in the land of the
elephant?
</P>
<P>
   ``My father just fell in love with tennis,'' said Srichaphan.
``He read some instruction books, saw some videos, and taught me
and my two older brothers to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Extraordinary. As the stage king, Brynner, crooned, ``It's a
puzzlement!''
</P>
<P>
   ``My father's been my only coach,'' he added. ``My mother
supported us as a schoolteacher. She's happy that her four men are
happy in tennis. My brother, Thanakorn, is a professional coach
now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's a funny thing. The first professional match I ever saw,
I was 10, and my father took me to the tournament at Pattaya. Slava
Dosedel won, and I had my picture taken with him. The picture is
still in my room. In the second round I play Dosedel. He won't
remember me.
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' Srichaphan said with a laugh, ``I hope to give him
something to remember.''
</P>
<P>
   The young man from Bangkok, the home of kick-boxing, gets his
kicks with fast hands. A Thai TV crew is now following him, a
growing, glowing presence among his people. Who knows how long the
sneakered Anna and the King will run in Melbourne? But don't you
imagine that when it's over King Pumipol will invite King Paradorn
over to the palace to hit a few?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-18-00 1346EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
