<HEADLINE>
IT'S RECRUITING SEASON FOR THE MASSCAP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Believe it or not, it's time to take a look at the $600,000
Massachusetts Handicap. New England's richest race won't be run
until June 3 at Suffolk Downs, but the field will actually begin to
take shape in less than two weeks, when vice president Lou Raffetto
makes his annual recruiting trip to Florida. Now there's a warm
thought on a cold day.
</P>
<P>
   Raffetto will leave Feb. 1 and point his pitch toward trainers
gearing up horses for the Donn Handicap Feb. 5, the first major
test in the East. Raffetto then will travel to California for the
Santa Anita Handicap March 4. His two big outings in the past have
been so successful that he has been able to lure standouts such as
Cigar (twice), Skip Away (twice), and Behrens to Suffolk.
</P>
<P>
   This year, there is great interest in Horse Chestnut, the Triple
Crown winner in South Africa, who came to America and looked strong
winning the Broward Handicap at Gulfstream Park Jan. 8. Horse
Chestnut will race next in the Donn, and Raffetto is planning a
meeting with his trainer, Michael De Kock.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to be looking at the South African horse, he was
very impressive,'' said Raffetto. ``If the Dubai World Cup (March
25) is on his schedule, maybe we can work something out, as we did
with Cigar's people. The MassCap could be his first race after he
rests from Dubai.''
</P>
<P>
   Raffetto will concentrate much of his efforts on Payson Park, a
training center 90 miles from Gulfstream. Trainers Elliot Walden,
Bill Mott, and Jim Bond all stable there over the winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Walden has Ecton Park and Menifee, Mott has Unbridled Jet and
Vision And Verse, and Bond has Behrens and Pleasant Breeze,'' said
Raffetto. ``Other trainers I hope to talk to are Mark Henig, who
has taken over the training of Almutawakel, and Randy Schulhoefer,
who is training Lemon Drop Kid for his father.''
</P>
<P>
   On Raffetto's list for the California trip are Bob Baffert, who
has General Challenge and Real Quiet (third in last year's
MassCap), Richard Mandella, who has Puerto Madero, and D. Wayne
Lukas, who has Breeders' Cup Classic winner Cat Thief.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who could have imagined that we would attract such big names
when we started out?'' said Raffetto. ``It's taken a lot of work
and a lot of luck to go with it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A warm return
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jockey Rudy Baez visited frigid Suffolk Saturday, the first time
he has been at a racetrack since he suffered a paralyzing injury at
Rockingham Park Aug. 4. Baez was surrounded by family and friends
as he watched the races from the Terrace dining room.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good to be back,'' said Baez. ``I am just having a good
time and enjoying myself. I was lucky that the jockeys decided to
ride today. Those guys are tough.''
</P>
<P>
   While at the track, Baez received a call from top California
rider Kent Desormeaux.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was real nice of him,'' said Baez. ``He told me to hang in
there, and that he wished me luck. It's nice to talk to guys like
that and see that they care.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `Thief' was caught
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cat Thief, who seldom wins but is often in the money, finished
second in Saturday's $300,000 San Fernando Breeders' Cup at Santa
Anita. It was the second time he has lost since winning the $4
million Classic (third in the Mailbu Dec. 26). Cat Thief's record
in 1999 was 13-2-3-5, and while it was no surprise that he was
beaten, it was startling that the winner turned out to be 24-1 shot
($50.60 to win) Saint's Honor. Basically an allowance horse,
Saint's Honor stormed through the lane under Desormeaux to prevail
by 1 1/2 lengths. The time for the mile and one-16th was 1:41 4/5.
Cat Thief, the 3-2 choice with Pat Day, was caught in traffic
turning for home, but got up in time to nip 38-1 shot Mr. Broad
Blade and Pat Valenzuela by a head . . . Greenwood Lake, winner of
the Champagne and Remsen last season, also went down to defeat
Saturday, finishing sixth in the $100,000 Holy Bull Stakes at
Gulfstream. Greenwood Lake is a lagger, and Gulfstream favors
front-runners, but the 3-year-old son of Meadowlake was far back at
all times under Jean-Luc Samyn. The winner was Hal's Hope, a 40-1
shot ($82.40), who went wire to wire with Roger Valez, tallying by
better than 5 lengths. The time for the mile and one-16th was 1:44
2/5. ``Greenwood Lake just didn't grab the track,'' said Samyn.
``He warmed up well, but he just couldn't get a hold of the
surface.'' . . . The Godolphin Stable of Dubai took its first shot
at the Kentucky Derby last year and failed when Worldly Manner
tired turning for home. Last week, Godolphin proved it was even
more serious this year by purchasing Chief Seattle, the No. 1 Derby
contender on many lists. Godolphin bought the son of Seattle Slew
from William Bets and Philip Needham for an undisclosed sum. Chief
Seattle will be shipped to Dubai, but you can bet that, barring
injury, he'll be back for the Derby. ``We'll see how he settles in
when he reaches Dubai before deciding on a program for this year,''
said Godolphin racing manager Simon Crisford.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Material from publicity departments at various racetracks was used
to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
