<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLLINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KIWI: A FINE NAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OTOROHANGA, New Zealand _ It isn't every day in New Zealand that
you can walk into the living room of the national symbol. Are we
dressed for the occasion? Is this an acceptable time? Will it
disdainfully give us the cold-feathered shoulder?
</P>
<P>
   Don't be nervous, says the guard. Shorts, T-shirt, and sneakers
are perfectly presentable guest attire. But no photographs, please.
</P>
<P>
   After all, New Zealand is a pretty relaxed, informal place. The
most celebrated citizen, explorer Sir Edmund Hillary _ he who made
Mount Everest seem like a walk in a chilly park in 1953 _ is listed
in the Auckland phone book. Of course, he isn't the national
symbol. If he were, the natives would call themselves Hillarys.
Maybe Eds.
</P>
<P>
   Instead they are known as Kiwis. Their nom de plumage is the way
the populace happily pays respect to a rare, cherished bird, the
kiwi, flightless figurehead of a nation. A bird unable to imagine
getting as high as Hillary, or even a foot or two in the air. Other
countries have winged symbols, but do Americans refer to themselves
as Eagles, or Chinese as Peking Ducks?
</P>
<P>
   Found only in this country (and seldom found at all), kiwis are
carefully protected and cared for. Security is tight. No armed
guards, you understand, or metal detectors when you enter the Kiwi
House in this small North Island town, Otorohanga. But, crossing
the threshold, you can feel the presence of a respected presence. I
haven't been so awed since meeting a songbird named Grace Slick of
the since-extinct Jefferson Airplane, a symbol of the '60s. One of
her tunes, ``Somebody to Love,'' would have described Kiwis'
feeling for kiwis.
</P>
<P>
   But it's mostly spiritual, and at a distance. Kiwis, secretive,
nocturnally Garboesque groundlings, treasure their privacy. They
hide out during the daytime in wilderness abodes. Lucky is the
infrequent person who sights one on its own turf. Once, about 2
a.m., I think I heard one wail like Slick, but briefly on Great
Barrier Island, a sparsely inhabited chunk of forests and mountains
about 50 miles off Auckland. At least it was identified as
kiwi-croon by a resident, Nicole Wineland-Thomson.
</P>
<P>
   Another Kiwi, friend Steve McIvor, said that a number of
contrived kiwi habitats, such as this, are located throughout the
country, ``but Otorohanga is the best to see, with the most birds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Besides, it's close to Te Awamutu, known as the `Rose Town of
New Zealand.' Also revered as the hometown of the Finn brothers,
Neil and Tim, of our most famous rock bands. Split Enz, then
Crowded House. Surely you remember their hit, `Can I Have Another
Piece of Chocolate Cake?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Uh . . . sounds devilishly tasty.
</P>
<P>
   ``The roses are fabulous,'' McIvor underlined, ``and, unlike the
kiwis, you can get close enough to smell 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   If Gertrude Stein had visited Te Awamutu, the rock-and-rose
town, she mightn't have asserted, ``A rose is a rose is a rose.''
Those of the town's aromatic public garden, about 2,000 of them,
bloom tall and distinctively, each raising an intricately
expressive, gorgeous face. The startlingly lusty hues _ scarlets,
tangerines, cerise, lemon, purple, lavender, on and on _ defy a
color chart.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aphrodisiacal!'' proclaimed a fellow sniffer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pretty, too,'' said another.
</P>
<P>
   When they're not in bloom, a striking mural of the garden on the
public toilet building across the street preserves their best
appearance. A hundred yards away is one of New Zealand's first
churches, shingle-steepled, white frame St. John's, opened in 1854.
Curious-looking footprints on the ceiling are said to be those of
angels who inspired the carpenters. Logical, since angels have been
partial to carpenters for a couple of millenniums.
</P>
<P>
   Otorohanga's kiwis probably wouldn't like rock, roses, or
Anglican hymns. They prefer a quiet, somber, even gloomy atmosphere
such as has been created for them in their living room behind
glass. Ushering us in at noon, Susan Hancock, a keeper, says,
``You've come at the right time. Feeding time. They're up and awake
only about four hours, and sleep the other 20.''
</P>
<P>
   The darkened, temperature-controlled environment is gradually
illuminated by simulated moonlight, revealing a drab setting of
trees, brush, and dirt floor that 28 kiwis share with other
domestic birds called keas and kakas. The kiwis are moonies,
attracted to the silvery rays. Rise and shine. Sort of like
moonstruck vampires, they emerge from casket beds, stretch their
legs, shake hungry bellies.
</P>
<P>
   They are built like footballs, waddling in grayish brown coats
and the style of Groucho Marx on short, bent legs. Their long,
hooked beaks, seeming out of place on such small bodies, are
designed for digging up worms. Through a door into the living room
goes another keeper, hip-booted Louise Brady, spreading joy and
sustenance with a meal of worms and a vitamin concoction that is
good for the hearts of the housebound.
</P>
<P>
   Chow time. They peck away wholeheartedly, females
indistinguishable from males except vocally. The females utter a
throat-clearing rasp; the males cry out piercingly in a voice that
I'd heard on Great Barrier Island.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, the guys are loud-mouthed showoffs. ``Typical,'' says
a woman squiring three children. ``They probably drink a lot of
beer, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The kiwis, responsible little patriots, have spawned a cottage
industry to help pay for their upkeep. The gift shop is filled with
kiwi kitsch, such as replicas of the birds in a variety of
substances including chocolate.
</P>
<P>
   Visiting time doesn't last long. Of course, we don't want to
keep them up past bedtime. The moon goes off, and so do we, pleased
to have had an audience, if impersonal, with the national symbol
that has done so much for its country. Someday, maybe, the country
can do something progressive for the kiwis _ like teaching them to
fly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-18-00 1348EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
