<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-NOTES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STAYING HEALTHY IN THE AIR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Especially on a long flight, airplane air can be tough to take.
Germs may well be flying through the dry, recirculated air, and you
could begin your vacation with a cold or otherwise feel ill.
PassengerRights.com, a Web-based consumer organization, offers
these tips for staying healthy far above the ground:
</P>
<P>
   --Wash your hands with soap and hot water several times before,
during, and after your flight. Exta-careful passengers use a cloth
or paper towel to open the bathroom door because germs can be
passed on from the handle.
</P>
<P>
   --Douse a hanky or other cloth with water from a source you know
is good and cover your nose and mouth. Few may want to do this, but
it can add humidity to your lungs and prevent the spread of germs.
</P>
<P>
   --Dry cabin air can enlarge the teeny-tiny cracks in your
nostrils, making it easier for germs to creep in. Try coating the
inside of those nostrils with almond oil, olive oil, baroleum, or
other ointments.
</P>
<P>
   --Here's your chance to look like a doctor _ or perhaps Michael
Jackson: Wear a disposable surgeon's mask, available from
drugstores. Says PassengerRights.com: ``Maybe airlines will
eventually manufacture these masks with their logos.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
And speaking of airlines: If you have had a problem with airline
ticket pricing or an experience involving overbooking, the US
Department of Transportation wants to hear about it, via
www.oig.dot.gov/bookjump.htm. That site also has a a link to a page
where you can share other airline experiences. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Travel Trivia: What is the southernmost capital in the contiguous
48 states? (Answer at end of column.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
In a name: Badminton was first known as ``poona'' in India. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Quotable: ``A luxury resort is a place with tropical plants outside
and outstretched palms inside'' _ Anonymous. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Today's loopy law: If you live in Maine and your Christmas
decorations are still up, you could be fined. Jan. 14 was the
removal deadline. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Well, you see, boss: St. Valentine's Day falls on a Monday this
year, so the White Barn Inn in Kennebunkport, Maine, has created an
appropriate two-night package for Feb. 13-14. Champagne and
chocolate-dipped berries will greet the couple upon arrival, a
long-stemmed rose will be placed on the pillow at turndown, and
dinner will be a romantic, four-course affair at the AAA Five
Diamond White Barn Inn Restaurant. And upon departure, guests will
receive a note on White Barn Inn stationery, explaining the guest's
absence and thanking the boss for his or her kind understanding.
(The inn does note, however, that the note is unlikely to be
accepted as a legitimate excuse ``unless one works for Cupid.'')
The package begins at $541 per couple. For more information, call
207-967-2321, visit www.whitebarninn.com, or e-mail
innkeepar(at)whitebarninn.com. &QL; 
 &QL; 
And speaking of romance: You and your spouse-to-be could be chosen
as one of 55 couples to be married on New York City's Top of the
World Trade Center Observatories in an individual, free ceremony.
To enter the enticingly named Make Love on Top of the World
Contest, send a letter telling why being married on top of the
world is the perfect ending to your courtship and the beginning of
the rest of your lives. You must be over 18 and have a New York
State marriage license. Send entries to Make Love on Top of the
World Contest, c/o Top of the World Trade Center Observatories,
2WTC, Suite 150, New York, NY 10048, or fax them to 212-323-2352,
attention of Make Love on Top of the World Contest. Entries must be
received by Feb. 12. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Advice to go: When visiting another country, check to see if
tipping is customary. Here's tip number 75 from the newest edition
of ``Going Abroad: 101 Tips (Plus) for Mature Travelers'': ``In
many countries, such as Singapore, China, and Tahiti, tipping is
frowned upon. In Japan and New Zealand, most tips are included in
the bill.'' The ``101 Tips'' guide is free from Grand Circle
Travel. For a copy, call 800-248-3737. &QL; 
 &QL; 
The naked truth: Donald Duck comics were once banned in Finland
because he doesn't wear pants. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mush! It's not too late to bid on a chance to ride along in
Alaska's famed Iditarod Trail Sled Dog Race. More than 80 mushers
are expected to sign up, race, and each will carry a winning bidder
for the first 11 miles of the 1,100- mile race. For more
information, call 907-566-7533 or visit www.iditarod.com. To bid,
check on the status of bids, or ask a specific question, call
800-566-SLED. The auction closes Jan. 28, and the race begins March
4. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Did you guess it? Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Send comments and questions to Travel Tidbits, Boston Globe,
Boston, MA 02107. Send e-mail to carpen(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
