<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GOOD TIMES, 2000 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROB MORSE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ These must be good times because the nation is
torn apart over a piece of fabric, the firing of a coach, do-good
messages on television shows and a lost 6-year-old boy.
</P>
<P>
   At the beginning of a new century, these are the issues
proclaimed as important, so let's go with them.
</P>
<P>
   The piece of fabric is the Confederate battle flag that flies
over the South Carolina state Capitol, a flag the NAACP and many
African-American citizens of that state find offensive and would
like lowered.
</P>
<P>
   Why not? The flag was raised over the Capitol of South Carolina
for the first time in 1962 as a sign of resistance to the civil
rights movement and a symbol of ``states' rights,'' which then
meant whites' right to dominate blacks.
</P>
<P>
   Now look what happens. Arizona Sen. John McCain, who is wrong
about one divisive war (the one he fought in and thinks was a good
war that could have been won) now is wrong about an even more
divisive war. He called the Confederate battle flag a ``symbol of
heritage.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the heritage of defending slavery by rebelling against
the government McCain wishes to lead as president and a member of
the party of Lincoln.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are always saying ``the party of Lincoln.'' It
should mean something.
</P>
<P>
   McCain is an honorable man, and he should go back to what he
originally said, that the flag is ``offensive.''
</P>
<P>
   But no, now he's pandering to grown men who put on gray soldier
suits and march around with muzzle-loading rifles trying to
recapture their ``heritage.'' He forgets those who marched 100
years later against that flag to recapture their dignity and human
rights.
</P>
<P>
   The latter just don't happen to vote in great numbers in
Republican primaries in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said the issue of that most symbolically loaded flag
``should be settled without interference from presidential
candidates.''
</P>
<P>
   But when it comes to the custody of a lost and symbolically
loaded 6-year-old, McCain and every Republican presidential
candidate is a social worker who knows what's best for the child.
</P>
<P>
   The party of family values and fathers' rights would take Elian
Gonzalez from his father because of his dad's address and his
politics.
</P>
<P>
   No, that's not it. The fanatical anti-Castro Cuban American vote
is important, so therefore it's best for the child not to go back
to dad in Havana but to stay with the cousins in Miami who shower
presents on the kid and teach him how to wave to the cameras.
</P>
<P>
   Some members of Congress are trying to get in on the act by
granting Elian citizenship. Never have so many conservatives been
so hospitable to one boat person. And never have they cared so much
about child welfare.
</P>
<P>
   Give me your tired, your hungry and your pathetic little
political footballs. They're going to Disney World.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know what the Rev. Jesse Jackson's position on Elian is.
It's the kind of situation that calls for his hostage negotiation
skills, but those wacky right-wingers in Miami probably won't deal
with Jackson. Besides, they need Elian, because they don't have
much else anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson is pursuing the issue of the Confederate battle flag in
South Carolina, which makes sense. But he also has grabbed hold of
two issues that don't offer much in the way of high ground _ the
rioting kids in Decatur, Ill., who were expelled from school, and
Ray Rhodes, who was fired as coach by the Green Bay Packers.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the Decatur kids who beat people up in the football stands
were punished too severely. But they're not modern-day freedom
fighters like Rosa Parks, as Jackson has proclaimed.
</P>
<P>
   Neither is Rhodes a martyred black leader.
</P>
<P>
   He's a coach who was hired, then fired, as justly or unjustly as
any other high-paid scapegoat with headphones.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson should do what he does so well, move on to another
issue, and quickly. Sometimes the constant effort to be in the
spotlight can be blinding.
</P>
<P>
   It's bad enough that the nation is mired in a racial war of
capture the flag and an international child-custody battle.
</P>
<P>
   When we flip away from the evening news to light sitcoms, we
enter a drug war zone.
</P>
<P>
   The White House Office of National Drug Policy has been
reviewing TV scripts and rewarding networks that insert anti-drug
messages.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know where they put those anti-drug messages, what with
all the messages to use guns to settle disputes, maintain absolute
faith in doctors and cops and _ if you're a young woman _ aspire to
be a sex-crazed lawyer who is as dumb and skinny as a stick.
</P>
<P>
   Still, federal narcovision is an outrageous violation of the
spirit of the First Amendment, and my right as a beer-swilling,
prescription-drugged couch potato to enjoy the worst drug of all,
television.
</P>
<P>
   What does television tell us? We have grave political problems
like idiots flying an offensive flag, coaches who get fired and a
little boy seemingly doomed to grow up as a very scuffed political
football.
</P>
<P>
   Television also tells us we have politicians who aren't up to
dealing with those issues. But already we knew that, just as we
already knew that drugs are bad for us.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
