<HEADLINE>
HOTEL, DINING RATINGS GET TOUGHER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mobil is shaking up the hotel and restaurant world with a fresh
look at who gets its coveted five-star ratings.
</P>
<P>
   One winner is the Four Seasons Hotel, Boston, which just
received its first five-star rating, making it the first Boston
hotel in years to hold the distinction. Mobil annually reviews
22,000 properties in the country, and this year only 42 made the
five-star list. Another 425 received four-star ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Jacobson, who heads Mobil's rating system, said winners of
the five- and four-star ratings are all excellent, but the
five-star winners are ``the best of the best.'' At a five-star
hotel, Jacobson said, ``guests receive attention that is
unparalleled'' and leave with the ``most memorable experience of a
lifetime.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mobil Guides, which have become a traveler's bible for
accommodations and dining, are taking a fresh look at the food and
lodging industry, with many longstanding five-star properties being
downgraded to four-star status.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobson said his job is to make the guides the preeminent
rating system in the country, and last year he embarked on ways to
improve the rating committee. He recruited travel writers,
restaurant critics, hotel school professors, and people in the
industry to upgrade the committee. Mobil does all its inspections
anonymously.
</P>
<P>
   In New England, other properties holding five stars are the
Mayflower Inn in Connecticut (five years with five stars) and Twin
Farms in Vermont (five years). The Point in Saranac Lake, N.Y.,
also continues its five-point rating (three years).
</P>
<P>
   Winning four stars for lodging in Massachusetts are the Boston
Harbor Hotel, The Eliot, and Ritz-Carlton Hotel, all in Boston;
Blantyre, Lenox; Charlotte Inn, Edgartown; the Wauwinet, Nantucket;
and the Wequassett Inn, Chatham. In Maine, four-star properties are
Bar Harbor Hotel-Bluenose Inn, Bar Harbor; Captain Lord Mansion,
Inn at Harbor Head, and The White Barn Inn, all in Kennebunkport;
and the Lodge at Moosehead Lake, Greenville. In New Hampshire, the
Balsams Grand Resort Hotel, Colebrook. In Vermont, Governor's,
Ludlow; Inn at Sawmill Farms, West Dover; Rabbit Hill Inn, Lower
Waterford; Topnotch at Stowe Resort &AMP; Spa; and Woodstock Inn &AMP;
Resort. In Connecticut, the Inn at National Hall in Westport.
</P>
<P>
   No restaurants in New England received the five-star rating.
</P>
<P>
   Winning four stars for dining in Massachusetts were Four
Seasons' Aujourd'Hui, Biba, Clio, Grill 23, Hamersley's Bistro,
L'Espalier, Radius, and Rowes Wharf, all in Boston; Chillingsworth
in Brewster; and Wheatleigh in Lenox.
</P>
<P>
   Reduced to four-star ratings were The Greenbrier in West
Virginia (38 years with five stars); The Carlyle in New York City
(a 31-year winner); Marriott's Camelback Inn in Arizona (30 years);
and the C Lazy U Ranch in Colorado (22 years).
</P>
<P>
   Longtime hotels and resorts still holding five stars are Four
Seasons Hotel, New York City (five years); Little Nell, Aspen,
Colo. (five years); Mansion on Turtle Creek, Dallas (11 years); St.
Regis, New York (5 years); The Peninsula, Beverly Hills, Calif.
(seven years); the Breakers, Palm Beach, Fla. (18 years); the
Phoenician in Arizona (seven years); and The Ritz-Carlton, Naples,
Fla. (12 years).
</P>
<P>
   The 2000 Mobil Guides are available in seven regional volumes,
each $16.95. For those wishing to read about just the best of the
best, there's the ``Mobil Travel Guide: America's Best Hotels and
Restaurants: The Four- and Five-Star Winners of 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Safety first
</P>
<P>
   Jiminey Peak in Hancock, Mass. is going all out to reduce
accidents and provide a more enjoyable environment for skiers. The
most visible safety effort is the creation of Non-Speed Zones where
skiers and snowboarders are required to keep at the averge speed of
the users of that particular slope. On the seven trails marked,
Mountain Safety Patrol members will be giving tickets to those who
violate the rules. Consistent violators will lose their lift ticket
but get an opportunity to redeem it by watching a mountain safety
video. The safety patrol is a volunteer organization with 40
members (very visible in their bright yellow jackets) that started
five years ago. For more information, check out www.jiminypeak.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Hands on Asheville
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Each weekend in February and March, Asheville, N.C., artisans
will hold workshops in a variety of mediums, including pottery,
glass blowing, fiber arts, nature crafts, jewelry design, and
culinary and musical arts. Visitors can join in making an object in
the field of their choice. Workshops cost $30 to $80 and include
materials and the finished object. Many workshops are geared toward
children. During ``Hands on Asheville,'' Biltmore Estate will offer
guided tours as part of its complementary event, ``Winter Pastimes:
The Arts in America's Largest Home.'' Theater and musical
performances will be offered in Asheville. For more information on
workshops and hotels, call the Asheville Convention and Visitors
Bureau at 800-280-0005 or, on the Web, go to
www.ashevillechamber.org/crafts.htm. To book a Hands On package,
call 888-874-7799.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Be paid to travel
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you've ever thought of being a tour leader and getting paid
to travel, a Jan. 22 seminar may be for you. The International Tour
Management Institute will hold its 14th annual tour director
training program in Boston in April. On Jan. 22 the free seminar
will describe the program, job opportunities, pay, what makes a
successful tour director, and more. To attend the morning or
afternoon session at the Boston Park Plaza Hotel, call 800-442-4864
or 617-742-9780 between 2 and 9 p.m. or, on the Web, tour
www.ITMItourtraining.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Winter carnival
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, N.H., will hold its annual Winter Carnival Jan. 21-24.
The four-day event begins Friday with a champagne brunch, a
quarter-pipe snowboard competition, a moonlight cross-country ski
tour, and a spectacular torchlight parade. Other weekend events
include the First Annual Jackson Magical Mystery Stroll, ice
skating, a mini historical display marking the Jackson Bicentennial
Inauguration, a gala party, bonfire, sleigh rides, a Ski Meister
Competition, ski races, a progressive inn-to-inn lunch via
cross-country skis, a jazz breakfast, snowshoe challenge, and more.
For more information, call the Jackson Area Chamber of Commerce at
603-383-9356 or visit www.jacksonnh.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Eagle viewing
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Eagles are soaring in the Connecticut River Valley and travelers
can view them by cruising on the Connecticut River or joining a
walk. On Saturdays through Feb. 26, the Deep River Navigation Co.
will offer cruises (call 860-526-4954 for prices and information),
and on Sundays, Feb. 6-27, Capt. John's Bald Eagle Cruises will
take place (860-443-7259). On Saturdays, Sundays, and holidays
through Feb. 26, the Audubon Shop of Madison will offer walking
tours that include information on how to spot and identify the
eagles and the flora and fauna of the river ($16 including lunch;
call 860-443-7259). For information on the area, call the
Connecticut River Valley &AMP; Shoreline Visitors Council at
800-486-3346 or, on the Web, visit www.cttourism.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Boston walk
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Boston is known as the walking city, because it is easy to get
around on foot. One can follow the Freedom Trail and wander through
300-plus years of history in three miles or less, without strain.
Now there's a new way to discover old Boston, the Shawmut Peninsula
Walk, which traces Boston's original shoreline. The walk captures a
time when the fledgling city was a rough Colonial settlement on a
hilly promontory in Boston Harbor. The Shawmut Peninsula Walk opens
a new window onto Boston's Colonial and genealogical past, said Ann
Hershfang, president of WalkBoston, the pedestrian advocacy
organization, which produced the map. Using the self-guided map,
walkers can trace the original shoreline along present-day streets.
The map also contains lively historical notes, neighborhood
information, and transit stops. The map is $5 and can be found in
bookstores or from Bryant Altman Map and Book Distributors,
Endicott Street, Building 26, Norwood, MA 02062; telephone
781-762-3339.
</P>
