<HEADLINE>
EXTRA SAVINGS _ EXTRA FUN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Looking for a different cruise, one that offers extra value in
pricing, ports of call, and itinerary?
</P>
<P>
   Then this year consider a ``repositioning'' cruise.
</P>
<P>
   Every year in spring and fall most cruise lines begin to move
their ships to the waters where they will spend the season _ in
spring they sail to Europe and Alaska; in the fall, the ships
return from those ports and head to the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   What makes these cruises particularly attractive is the pricing.
Most lines offer two-for-one fares, air-inclusive offers, and a
variety of off-season pricing, according to the Cruise Lines
International Association.
</P>
<P>
   Other reasons for considering a repositioning cruise are:
</P>
<P>
   One-of-a-kind itineraries. Because ships are moving from one
geographic area to another, the combination of ports visited is
interesting and unusual.
</P>
<P>
   Trans-Atlantic crossings. Ships of all sizes and styles will be
crossing the Atlantic from the sunny waters of the Caribbean this
spring for European ports of call.
</P>
<P>
   Panama Canal transits. To begin or end their Alaskan cruise
seasons, most ships travel through the Panama Canal, visiting
Mexico and Central America along the way.
</P>
<P>
   Special themes and entertainment. Cruise lines often enhance
repositioning cruises with fun themes and out-of-the-ordinary
entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   And, ``Repositioning cruises are among the most relaxing cruises
available,'' said James G. Godsman, president of CLIA. ``It's the
ideal cruise for vacationers who want to unwind, be pampered, enjoy
days at sea and interesting activities before visiting ports of
call that are truly off the beaten path.''
</P>
<P>
   Travel agents have details.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
New canal boat
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Canal boating, long a favorite way to travel in France and
England among other European countries, is coming to New England.
The Blackstone Valley Tourism Council's 40-foot canal boat, the
Samuel Slater, has arrived in Central Falls, R.I. The boat, built
in England to ensure authenticity, will be used for sightseeing and
overnight stays on the Blackstone River, which runs through the
Blackstone Valley region of Rhode Island and Massachusetts. Plans
are to use the boat for overnight stays at a cost of $125. The boat
is named for Samuel Slater, who began America's Industrial
Revolution at a mill in Pawtucket, R.I., that is now a museum to
that period.
</P>
<P>
   One of the country's earliest canals was along the Blackstone,
providing transportation of goods from the many mills that lined
its banks. The boat will not be sailing along the rivers of nearby
Providence because, according to a story in the Providence Journal,
those waters are considered navigable waterways, which under law
allow only US-built boats to carry cargo and passengers between US
destinations. The Blackstone is not considered a navigable
waterway.
</P>
<P>
   The council is seeking period furnishings for the boat, and
plans to put the vessel into service sometime this spring.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Disney goes 7 days
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Disney Cruise Line will be expanding its horizons this year.
In August, the line plans on offering a seven-day Caribbean cruise
to its schedule, which now consists of three- and four-day cruises.
</P>
<P>
   The Disney Magic will sail Saturdays from Port Canaveral to St.
Maarten, St. Thomas, and St. John in the US Virgin Islands, and, of
course, to Disney's private island in the Bahamas, Castaway Cay.
New entertainment and shore excursions will also be introduced for
this cruise.
</P>
<P>
   This is the second change for the line, which began by offering
only a one-week package that included a three- or four-day cruise
with a stay at Disney World. Last year the line began offering
cruise-only packages.
</P>
<P>
   The line's newest ship, the Disney Wonder, will continue to
offer the three- and four-day cruises.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
World cruise
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Crystal Cruises has just announced plans for its 2001 world
cruise. The Jan. 21 to April 27 sailing will boast more countries
visited than any previous Crystal cruise. The sixth world cruise of
the Crystal Symphony will visit 38 exotic ports of call in 31
countries, including rarely visited destinations in Southeast Asia,
India, the Middle East, Africa, and the Canary Islands.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Skipper your boat
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Travelers looking for a different way to see Europe might want
to consider a Crown Blue Line cruise that allows them to be captain
of their own boat as they travel the waterways of Germany, France,
Ireland, Holland, and the line's newest destinations, Italy and
Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   The line offers more than 500 self-skippered vessels, allowing
travelers to experience the character and charm of some of Europe's
most picturesque regions.
</P>
<P>
   Weekly prices begin at about $500 a person. For example, in
France, the four-person Tamarisi starts at $1,960 a week in low
season, and the luxurious 10-person Grand Classique is $4,980 per
week during July and August. Prices include fuel, a damage waiver,
VA,T and canal tolls.
</P>
<P>
   For information, call Crown Blue Line at 888-355-9491 or visit
www.crown-blueline.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Coastal sailings
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Norwegian Coastal Voyage is offering senior savings of $90
to $220 to passengers 67 and older on the 1,250-mile trip along
Norway's spectacular west coast. The 11-ship fleet sails daily
year-round between Bergen in the south and Kirkenes in the north,
above the Arctic Circle. More than half the ships have been built
since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Senior savings are available except from June 1 to July 15.
Fares, with the savings, begin at $1,075 a person.
</P>
<P>
   The Norwegian Coastal Voyage has been operating since 1893, its
ships doubling as cargo vessels and local transportation for
Norwegians. The ships call at 34 fishing villages, towns, and
cities, pausing only briefly at some places to pick up and unload
goods, and at others long enough for sightseeing and shopping.
Ports visited at night on the northbound voyage are called on in
the daytime during the southbound trip.
</P>
<P>
   For a brochure, call 800-666-2374.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Low ratings from gays
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Out &AMP; About, the travel newsletter for gay men and lesbians, is
giving cruise lines a low rating in its January issue.
</P>
<P>
   The newsletter gave Carnival a C, Princess an F, Crystal Cruises
a D, and Disney Cruise Line, Norwegian, and Royal Caribbean, D+.
</P>
<P>
   ``These low ratings are disappointing, but not unexpected,''
said Billy Kolber-Stuart, editor of Out &AMP; About. ``Despite enormous
growth over the past 10 years, and big profits from all-gay charter
cruises, the cruise industry has been shockingly slow in addressing
the needs and issue of its gay customers and employees.''
</P>
<P>
   The newsletter looked at cruise line policies, programs, and
procedures, ranging from hiring and benefits to marketing. Issues
of general quality, customer satisfaction, and reputation were not
considered.
</P>
<P>
   Out &AMP; About is $49 a year. For information, call 800-929-2268.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Veterans' reunion
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A reunion of veterans who served in the Pacific Islands is
planned for September. The 28-day voyage departs San Francisco
Sept. 24. The cruise begins at $4,795 a person and is not limited
to veterans. For information, write to Joan Irvine Travel, 1600
West Coast Highway, Newport Beach, CA 92663; or telephone
949-640-7402.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Loyalty discounts
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A new and innovative guest loyalty program for travelers who
sail on the six lines belonging to World's Leading Cruise Lines _
Carnival, Holland America, Windstar, Seabourn, Cunard, and Costa _
is now available.
</P>
<P>
   The program, called Vacation Interchange Privileges, provides
the same discount benefits accorded to members of each line's past
program.
</P>
<P>
   For example, guests who sail on Seabourn, Windstar, or Cunard
will not only have access to discounts offered through past-guest
programs of the Seabourn Club, Windstar Foremast Club, and Cunard
World Club, but also savings available through any of the six WLCL
member lines' repeat-passenger programs. All the cruise line
members of the WLCL are owned by Carnival.
</P>
<P>
   Savings of up to 50 percent are offered on select sailings of
Carnival, Costa, and Windstar. The discounts on Holland America are
up to 35 percent and those on Cunard, up to 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   To obtain the discount, a traveler simply books a cruise through
any travel agent, who then informs the cruise line reservations
agent of the past-guest status at the time of bookings and, with
the initial deposit, supplies proof of the prior WLCL cruise. Other
restrictions may apply.
</P>
<P>
   The World's Leading Cruise Lines has a Web site that provides
information and a gateway to the Web sites of the participating
lines: www.leaderships.com.
</P>
