<SLUG> BC-SOCCER-MOMS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOCCER MOMS STAGE A REVOLUTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOANNA WEISS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EPPING, N.H. _ There are moms in shinguards everywhere you look.
Moms body-checking each other into plexiglass walls, shouting at
referees, knocking soccer balls off knees and heads.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent evening at the Crossroads Sports and Entertainment
Center, an indoor arena in small-town New Hampshire, mothers are
part of the indoor soccer frenzy. They play, often aggressively,
late into the night, while their children are busy with homework or
crawling into bed. Or playing games of their own. Or doing nothing
at all.
</P>
<P>
   News flash, children: One night a week, for one hour, some
mothers have their own things to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get my kids rides if there's a conflict,'' said Cecelia
Carroll, 48, a Derry teacher whose team of mostly moms won its
game, 8-2. ``I missed my daughter's winter chorus. I missed my
staff dinner for the playoffs. I guess this has been a priority.''
</P>
<P>
   Consider it a revolt of the soccer mom, the car-pool-driving,
child-toting, husband-cheering, one-woman family support system. In
the presidential campaign four years ago, she was the bedraggled
symbol of selfless motherhood _ enabler of the affluent modern
childhood, where weeknights bring a stream of sports games, band
practices, and lessons of all kinds.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as some of the mothers step back from that role, they are
admitting it feels like defiance: a shift in the family dynamic, a
modest rebellion from the idea that your children are your world.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my one night,'' said one mother, who has missed a child's
basketball games for her once-a-week soccer fix. ``The kids have
their nights.''
</P>
<P>
   Some children are watching that change with bemusement. Alyssa
Park, 9, admitted she was surprised when her 35-year-old mother,
Deb, took up the sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know they had older ladies' soccer,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But many children are encouraging, even begging their mothers to
play, and increasingly families are viewing a once youth-centered
sport as an all-encompassing affair. As indoor arenas rise across
the country, more households find themselves focused on the same
field three or four nights a week, attending games for brothers,
sisters, fathers, and mothers.
</P>
<P>
   It's happening in earnest in places like Crossroads, the newest
indoor soccer site in a state where six arenas have sprung up in
the past six years, and at least two more are under construction.
</P>
<P>
   Like many arenas, this one looks, from the outside, like a
warehouse: a modest, no-frills metal building beside a busy
highway. Inside, it is cavernous, with two oval-shaped playing
surfaces surrounded by plexiglass walls. In the afternoons and
evenings, the fields fill and empty with mechanical precision, as
teams stream on and off for hourlong games.
</P>
<P>
   Children still make up the bulk of Crossroads' 140 soccer teams,
owner T.J. Shaughnessy said. But in numbers surprising to many,
more and more women are taking part. Two or three women's teams
quickly grew to 12 teams of women over age 30. Two years ago, he
said, many of them had never kicked a soccer ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``They would say, `I'm so sick of my kids playing, and my
husband playing, and I want to play,' '' Shaughnessy said.
``They're having more fun than any other group, the moms.''
</P>
<P>
   Indoor soccer is a perfect way to start the revolution,
aficionados say. It's a faster-paced version of the outdoor game.
Teams are smaller, and balls can't go out of bounds; they just
bounce off the walls and back onto the field. To participate, the
player doesn't have to be a great athlete, a fierce competitor, or
highly trained. And little time is devoted.
</P>
<P>
   At Crossroads, the teams do not practice, and they play for only
an hour a week. At the Seacoast United Soccer Club arena in
Hampton, teams of mothers take turns baby-sitting toddlers on an
Astroturf field strewn with coloring books, while other teams play
a few yards away.
</P>
<P>
   During night games at Crossroads, husbands watch, calling out
advice or keeping vigil for old injuries that could spring up
again. Children shout encouragement and explain complex rules that,
to them, are second nature.
</P>
<P>
   Courtney Nelson, 13, acts as unofficial coach of the Oyster
River Hurricanes, shouting pointers to her mother, Anne, in the
goalkeeper's box.
</P>
<P>
   One of Anne Nelson's teammates recently asked Courtney if she
worried about balls flying at her mother's head. Courtney was
unmoved.
</P>
<P>
   ``If she can handle birth,'' she said, ``she can handle getting
the ball in her face.''
</P>
<P>
   There are a lot of balls in faces on indoor soccer fields, and
fingers slammed into walls, ankles swollen by errant kicks, and
women quietly cursing their opponents as they stumble off the
field. Some women say they've had to adjust to the aggression,
though they still take pride in being a different sort of player
than men.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we knock somebody down, we say, `Are you OK?' '' Deb Park
said. The men? ``They just keep going.''
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't mean the women take it easy. When the Bloomers
recently played the New England Crew at Crossroads, the game came
to a halt as the women argued with referee Michelle Weaver, 17,
over whether a kick was legal. They wouldn't continue playing until
they got a second opinion. Women tend to argue more than children,
Weaver said.
</P>
<P>
   The pressures on women are different, many say, as they shed
their insecurities in favor of sneakers and shorts. Julie Spuria,
33, a newspaper columnist from Auburn, admits that she puts makeup
on her carpet-burned knees when she wears dresses.
</P>
<P>
   And image worries left the name of Deb Park's team in flux. The
players considered Blue Thunder, but worried that people would call
them Thunder Thighs. They switched to Blue Lightning, but nobody
could remember it. Finally, they settled on the Hornets.
Baggage-free.
</P>
<P>
   Generations of women, who grew up playing hopscotch while the
boys took to the sports field, have had to drop old ideas as
they've now turned to sports, said Sharlene Hess-Biber, a Boston
College sociology professor.
</P>
<P>
   In large part, she said, they've taken ideas and encouragement
from their daughters.
</P>
<P>
   The leagues are open to all women over 30, and they do not have
to be moms to qualify. But the majority of players are mothers who
have spent years watching their children and husbands play.
</P>
<P>
   Soccer-playing moms are learning a new feeling of pride; they
urge newcomers onto the field and cheer even when their teammates
fail. Spuria, a seasoned player, passed the ball repeatedly to
rookies, hoping they would have a chance to score.
</P>
<P>
   She loves to watch mothers play, she said, and hear their
children scream out support. When they yell, ``Go, Mom,'' she said,
``My heart flips.''
</P>
<P>
   But many women find that support from their teammates is enough
for now. Celeste Dietterle, 43, a Newmarket secretary, said she
tells her husband not to come to her games.
</P>
<P>
   ``They criticize you too much,'' she said. ``This is what I do,
and I don't want him. This is my thing. Go away.''
</P>
<P>
   Lynn Allen, 43, a Durham teacher, said her four daughters, all
soccer players, wanted to see her first-ever game with the
Hurricanes. She borrowed their soccer shoes and shinguards, but she
wouldn't let them come. She wanted to do it alone.
</P>
<P>
   So, for the first time, she pulled on a pink team shirt and
matching pink ponytail holder, and bounded onto the field. She
crunched her face with concentration and stabbed at the ball.
</P>
<P>
   And she made a discovery: After years of watching her children's
games, scrutinizing their teams, and tracking their successes, she
knew what she was doing. Enough to do it well, scoring one of the
team's two goals that night.
</P>
<P>
   As teammates congratulated her, Allen gave the credit to her
children. ``I've been watching for a really long time,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Then she thought for a second and added: ``Well, it's hard to
believe they got it all from my husband.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
