<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-18 13:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9117 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-COLUMN-POP-BOS &LR;      01-18 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLUMN-POP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV RESURRECTIONS SHOW LITTLE LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lady Macbeth would have made a lousy television executive.
</P>
<P>
   Oh sure, William Shakespeare's famous dragon lady was an
immoral, lethally ambitious schemer chock-full of the sorts of
character deficiencies that have served many a Hollywood suit well.
And her tendency toward the cutthroat bottom line would have come
in handy in making those tough personnel decisions: ``Out, damned
programmer! Out, I say!''
</P>
<P>
   But she is also the woman who uttered the famous line, ``What's
done is done,'' and as everyone should now understand, nothing in
TV land is ever truly done.
</P>
<P>
   These days, TV's theme song should be, ``Everything Old Is New
Again.'' If the four major networks are interested in doing
anything nowadays, it's repackaging and regurgitating the past. You
want innovative and original _ watch HBO. You want TV as dusty and
faded as an old photograph _ look no further than network
television. The most obvious and recent example is the sudden
infestation of prime-time game shows _ FOX's ``Greed,'' NBC's
``Twenty One,'' CBS's ``Winning Lines,'' and the show that began
the madness, ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire,'' ABC's favorite
warhorse.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, it is not, unfortunately, the only example. Every few years
or so, someone gets the bright idea to resurrect some long-gone TV
show in the form of a two-hour movie. The latest comes Feb. 7 with
``Mary and Rhoda.'' Yes, that's Mary as in Mary Richards, and Rhoda
as in Rhoda Morgenstern, characters made famous by Mary Tyler Moore
and Valerie Harper, respectively, in the great 1970s comedy ``The
Mary Tyler Moore Show.'' When last we saw Rhoda she was living in
New York on her eponymous sitcom, while Mary and the gang _
co-workers Lou (Ed Asner), Murray (Gavin McLeod), Ted (Ted Knight),
Sue Ann (Betty White), and Georgette (Georgia Engel) were hugging,
crying, and singing ``It's a Long Way to Tipperary,'' as they left
their WJM-TV studio for the final time in 1977. It was a perfect
ending for an often-perfect show. But for reasons someone needs to
explain, well enough could not be left alone.
</P>
<P>
   Hence, in a few weeks there will be the sight of a recently
widowed Mary living in a tony Upper West Side apartment, and a
twice-divorced Rhoda trying to settle into her hometown after
living in Paris. Both have daughters, and the old friends find
themselves trying to navigate new lives on the shady side of middle
age. To be sure, the emotional tug of seeing again Mary's too-wide
nervous smile, and hearing Rhoda's ever-present Noo Yawk accent is
inevitable. We spent seven years with these people, and came to
know them as well as members of our own families. Yet, whatever
warm feelings are generated quickly evaporate once that cheap
nostalgia high wears off.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, television isn't the only peddler of such things. The
music industry has been doing this mess for years. Numerous bands _
from the Eagles to Fleetwood Mac to Blondie to the Sex Pistols (who
were at least cheeky and upfront enough to call their reunion the
``Filthy Lucre'' tour) _ have traded on our memories to squeeze a
few more millions from their once-glorious careers. Though all
claimed they would never, ever get together again, suddenly we were
inundated with concert tours,
take-the-money-and-run-with-our-memories CDs, and TV specials, also
available with never-before-seen footage on DVD for $24.95.
</P>
<P>
   Even death isn't a deterrent as surviving Beatles Paul
McCartney, George Harrison, and Ringo Starr proved a few years ago
when they warmed up John Lennon's leftovers and released two
``new'' tracks, ``Free as a Bird'' and ``Real Love.'' The Rutles
were right _ all you need is cash.
</P>
<P>
   But there is something even more unseemly when our favorite TV
shows and characters are raised from the dead. At least with
musicians, the songs, give or take a high note here and there,
essentially remain the same. But revived TV shows try to write new
chapters for books long finished and closed. From ``Cagney and
Lacey'' to ``The Rockford Files'' to ``Mary and Rhoda,'' they
arrive in our TV sets with the conceit that if we loved them once,
we'll certainly love them again. But the stars are older and
thicker, and more often that not, the shows lack much of what made
them special the first time around.
</P>
<P>
   Television is a business, but the intimacy of the medium makes
it so much more. Yet TV execs and creators are so cynical they can
see only big ratings and ad revenue, never appreciating that TV's
greatest shows _ and our favorite characters _ are best served not
by creaky reunions but by the tender indulgence of our memories.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-18-00 1355EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
