<HEADLINE>
SURVIVALIST GRITZ IN COURTROOM FIGHT TO STAY FREE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MITCHELL ZUCKOFF  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ENFIELD, Conn. _ Bo Gritz is, as usual, on a mission.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike the former Green Beret's high-profile exploits _
searching for POWs in Laos, talking Randy Weaver down off Ruby
Ridge, scouring the North Carolina woods for accused bomber Eric
Rudolph _ he's being uncharacteristically quiet about it.
</P>
<P>
   The reason is, this time the 60-year-old celebrity freedom
fighter is fighting for his own freedom. This mission is to save
himself.
</P>
<P>
   Gritz, a Vietnam War hero who is now a leader of the
ultraconservative Patriot Movement, is on trial here for attempted
kidnapping, conspiracy to commit kidnapping, and three other
charges that could land him in prison for up to 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   The charges stem from a September 1996 incident in which Gritz
(rhymes with ``fights'') and his son were arrested in a car
registered to an alias of a Connecticut woman named Linda Wiegand.
In the months leading up to the arrests, Wiegand had become the
darling of Gritz's followers by alleging that custody of her two
sons was given to her sexually abusive, satanic former husband as
part of a government conspiracy. Her allegations, strenuously
denied by her former husband, have never been independently
verified.
</P>
<P>
   Gritz had aggressively promoted Wiegand's claims, railing about
her case on his shortwave radio show and bringing her to
survivalist conventions. He would sign up students for his
military-inspired training courses and burn the United Nations
flag, while she collected money for her legal battle.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut prosecutors allege that Gritz and his son, James R.
Gritz, 41, crossed the line from support to criminality by plotting
unsuccessfully to snatch the boys, then 10 and 7, as they left
school.
</P>
<P>
   The alleged scheme was foiled, authorities said, when a police
officer investigating an unrelated report of a suspicious vehicle
stopped the car containing Gritz and his son in the parking lot of
a middle school attended by one of Wiegand's sons. A third man,
Sheldon Robinson of Texas, a friend of Bo Gritz, was arrested in
1998 as an alleged coconspirator.
</P>
<P>
   The case is largely circumstantial; there is no evidence the
Gritzes ever came near the boys. But in the car with Gritz and his
son were two-way radios, a lock-picking device, a large knife, a
photo of the two boys, a school schedule, and other items
prosecutors said would have aided a kidnap attempt.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with his future at stake, combined with a gag order from
the judge and a legal strategy of downplaying his swashbuckling
tendencies, Gritz has at least temporarily abandoned the
self-promotion that has been his calling card for two decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm doing fine,'' he said during a break in the trial last
week. ``But 3 1/2 years of this is a very high price to be paid to
be proven innocent.'' At that point, his lawyer, David Kritzman,
cut him off, making it possibly the briefest interview Gritz has
ever given.
</P>
<P>
   Gritz's trial is the latest chapter in a uniquely American life
that has veered from the straight lines of Army formations to a
string of freelance adventures that at times have bordered on the
absurd. Most recently, they have been embarrassing failures,
including a purported suicide attempt in late 1998.
</P>
<P>
   James Gordon Gritz _ known as ``Jimbo,'' then just ``Bo'' _
joined the Army in 1957 and became one of the earliest members of
the newly formed Special Forces. ``I needed to be tested,'' he
wrote in a 1991 book, ``Called to Serve.''
</P>
<P>
   He proved his mettle during the Vietnam War, accumulating most
of his 62 career decorations, including five Silver Stars, 10
Bronze Stars, the Distinguished Flying Cross, two Purple Hearts,
and two Legion of Merit awards.
</P>
<P>
   Having risen to the rank of lieutenant colonel, Gritz retired
from the Army in 1979 and quickly embarked on a headline-grabbing
effort to find Vietnam-era American soldiers he said were still
being held prisoner in Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Several early efforts were aborted or shelved, but in November
1982 he led a group of guerrillas into Laos, a misadventure that
ended when they were ambushed. The effort, called Operation
Lazarus, was later revealed to have been financed in part by actor
Clint Eastwood.
</P>
<P>
   Riding a wave of celebrity, Gritz was nominated in 1988 to run
for vice president under the Populist Party banner. He withdrew
from the race after learning that his running mate would be former
Ku Klux Klansman David Duke, but stayed with the party and ran for
president in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, in 1989 he founded the Center for Action,
through which Gritz provides SPIKE Delta Force training, which is
popular among men and women who anticipate having to repel a coming
New World Order. Among other offerings, Gritz teaches a class on
``clandestine agent handling operations and government mind
control,'' according to the center's on-line catalog.
</P>
<P>
   Arguably his biggest postwar success came in 1992, when Gritz
persuaded white separatist Randy Weaver to leave his cabin in Ruby
Ridge, Idaho, ending an 11-day siege that resulted in the deaths of
a US marshal and Weaver's wife and infant son.
</P>
<P>
   But since then, Gritz has proved far less effective. He failed
in a similar effort to end the 1996 standoff between the Montana
Freemen and federal agents. Then, in 1998, he promised to bring
accused antiabortion bomber Eric Rudolph out of the North Carolina
woods, only to leave bee-stung and empty-handed.
</P>
<P>
   While Gritz was in North Carolina, his third wife filed for
divorce. When he returned to his home in Idaho and learned of her
decision, Gritz put on his uniform, loaded his Colt .45 service
pistol and shot himself in the chest, blowing several medals off
his uniform in the process. A police report said the injury
appeared to have been designed not to kill Gritz, but ``to raise
sympathy from his wife.''
</P>
<P>
   Gritz spent much of last year promoting his Y2K preparedness
courses. When chaos failed to arrive as he predicted on Jan. 1, his
detractors pounced.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gritz is fundamentally an opportunist, a parasite who has been
living off people's fears concerning the `End Times,' '' said Mark
Potok, editor of Intelligence Report, a magazine on the radical
right published by the Southern Poverty Law Center in Montgomery,
Ala.
</P>
<P>
   Of all Gritz's ups and downs, the Connecticut trial could prove
the most difficult. After months of jury selection and pretrial
hearings, the trial began Jan. 6 with testimony from Suffield,
Conn., police Officer David Reese, who made the arrests. Gritz is
being tried with Robinson, while Gritz's son is to be tried
separately.
</P>
<P>
   Gritz cuts the most imposing figure in the small courtroom, a
gray-haired, broad-shouldered man with a gold POW bracelet on his
wrist and two medals _ a combat infantry badge and one of his
Legion of Merit medals _ pinned to his lapel.
</P>
<P>
   Among a half-dozen or so spectators is his fourth wife, Judy,
whom he married four months ago in a ceremony officiated by a
pastor from the explicitly anti-Semitic Church of Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Gritz's lawyer, Kritzman, has sparred repeatedly with the state
prosecutor, John Malone, over Malone's attempts to show the jury of
six women and three men evidence of Gritz's training and political
views, which Kritzman calls irrelevant.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, in trying to introduce Gritz's martial-arts
background, Malone told Judge Nicola Rubinow he wanted to show that
Gritz ``would be the type of person who would be selected by Linda
Wiegand to undertake this kind of mission.''
</P>
<P>
   But Kritzman mocked Malone's effort as an attempt to suggest
that Gritz would have used martial arts to overpower a sixth-grade
student who tried to intervene with the alleged plot.
</P>
<P>
   Rubinow has ruled largely in Gritz's favor, finding last week
that the state ``hasn't shown a relationship between military or
paramilitary training in committing the crimes.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not clear whether Gritz will testify at the trial; by some
accounts he wants to but his lawyer is against it.
</P>
<P>
   Among the spectators in court last week was Bob Noll of
Colorado, a white-bearded Gritz supporter who said he is a World
War II Navy veteran. ``I think Bo is an A-number-one man, and I see
no justification for these charges,'' Noll said.
</P>
<P>
   While Gritz remains a hero to some, his involvement with Wiegand
has caused a rift between him and other leaders of the Patriot
Movement who regard Wiegand as untrustworthy. She spent two years
on the run with her sons before linking up with Gritz.
</P>
<P>
   ``He refused to believe Linda was anything but the injured
party,'' said Clayton Douglas, publisher of ``The Free American''
magazine. ``At best, I'd like to believe he was duped.''
</P>
<P>
   As Gritz fights for his freedom, he will have to do so without
Wiegand. She has disappeared again, allegedly with thousands of
dollars of Patriot Movement contributions, rather than face a
related charge of custodial interference.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
