<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRADITION HAS BEEN ELIMINATED FROM NFL PLAYOFFS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Super Bowl Tournament has been pared to a final four . . .
the Tennessee Titans, Jacksonville Jaguars, St. Louis Rams, and
Tampa Bay Buccaneers.
</P>
<P>
   Where have all the Cowboys gone?
</P>
<P>
   Yeesh. Tampa Bay, St. Louis, Nashville, and Jacksonville. How
did Hooterville, Dogpatch, and Bugtussle miss the cut?
</P>
<P>
   I don't know about you, but when the playoffs get to this stage,
I find myself looking for the Green Bay Packers, Chicago Bears,
Pittsburgh Steelers, and Dallas Cowboys. Where are Al Davis, Mike
Ditka, Don Shula, and Tom Landry? Where's the frozen tundra and the
Dawg Pound? Where are the Cowboy cheerleaders?
</P>
<P>
   The NFL's new world order is tough to digest for those who grew
up listening to Chris Schenkel describe the exploits of Y.A.
Tittle, Sam Huff, and Jimmy Brown. Starting with the Lions in Tiger
Stadium on Thanksgiving, late-season football was played outdoors
in cold climates by an assortment of Lions, Packers, and Bears.
</P>
<P>
   Now we have the NFC championship being played indoors, and the
AFC title game in the tropical wasteland of Jacksonville, Fla. None
of the four cities left in the bakeoff has ever been represented in
a Super Bowl. Only Tampa has ever played host to a conference
championship game.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Any Given Sunday,'' Oliver Stone wasn't allowed to use NFL
names or logos. Stone gave us the Miami Sharks and Minnesota
Americans vying for a spot in the Pantheon Cup. That's what Titans
vs. Jags at Alltel Stadium looks and sounds like.
</P>
<P>
   This is the baseball equivalent of the Tampa Bay Devil Rays vs.
the Seattle Mariners in the ALCS, and the Florida Marlins vs. the
Milwaukee Brewers in the NLCS.
</P>
<P>
   The Jaguars didn't exist until 1995. The Titans were the Houston
Oilers until '97 and played as the Tennessee Oilers until this
year. The Rams were in Los Angeles until 1995. St. Louis, which
originally had the football Cardinals (now in Phoenix), never
hosted an NFL playoff game until last weekend. So of the remaining
four teams in the Super Bowl hunt, the Tampa Bay Buccaneers are
most steeped in tradition. And what a tradition. The Bucs finished
in last place 11 times in their first quarter-century of existence
and didn't win their second game in January until last weekend.
Tampa would have to duplicate this year's 11-5 record for 18
consecutive seasons in order to get to .500 lifetime. Did anyone
say ``Los Angeles Clippers''?
</P>
<P>
   None of this should count against the worthy Rams, Jags, Titans,
and Bucs. It's just tough to think of an NFL playoff with so few
old-school representatives.
</P>
<P>
   As a sports town, St. Louis has the most history of the NFL's
Final Four. St. Louis had a nice century with the baseball
Cardinals, whose home baseball uniforms rival Detroit's for the
best in the game. St. Louis had Stan the Man, Bob Gibson, Dizzy
Dean, and most recently, Mark McGwire. It might be the best
baseball town in the States and had hoop and hockey success with
the Hawks and Blues. St. Louis gave Boston the draft rights to Bill
Russell and it was against the Blues that Bobby Orr won the Cup
with his flying-through-the-air goal in 1970. Let's not forgot that
the Patriots came close to moving to St. Louis before Bob Kraft
saved the day in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay has big league baseball and NHL hockey, but no
basketball and absolutely no winning tradition. It's home to Wade
Boggs, Dwight Gooden, and George Steinbrenner. It has strip malls,
strip clubs, and old people who left Northern neighborhoods to be
warm. And it has the Bucs _ who set the standard for NFL ineptitude
when they went 0-14 in their inaugural season in 1976. Tampa leads
the league in media members wearing team garb. Do you Yahoo?
</P>
<P>
   Jacksonville is Worcester on the St. John River. It's what
Hartford would have been if Homer Simpson hadn't contaminated the
proposed Patriot site at Yo Adriaen's Landing. It isn't big league
in any other sport and has Tom Coughlin to thank for its premier
status in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Nashville is Jacksonville without the sophistication. The
Titans, who were the Oilers, have played home games at Jeppensen
Stadium, Rice Stadium, and the Astrodome, all in Houston. In 1997
they were walking in Memphis at the Liberty Bowl, in '98 they
played at Vanderbilt Stadium in Nashville, and this year they moved
into Adelphia Coliseum, where they performed the miracle kickoff
lateral against Buffalo. Nashville has NHL hockey. If you know the
name of the team, you are a true Hockey Krishna.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams and Jags are this weekend's favorites, and the winners
will take their show to Atlanta. It matters little to those of us
who covet tradition. With Nashville, St. Louis, Jacksonville, and
Tampa Bay left in the mix, Super Bowl XXXIV is guaranteed to be
Yahoo Bowl I.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-18-00 1401EST &QL; 
