<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR WEDNESDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Wednesday, Jan. 19:
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded i)
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-INSPECTIONS (United Nations) _ France announces that it
rejects Rolf Ekeus, the Swedish arms control expert, before the
Security Council meets at 3 p.m. ET in a showdown over
Secretary-General Kofi Annan's choice to head a new arms inspection
commission for Iraq. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-ANGOLA (United Nations) _ The Security Council takes up the
unending civil war in Angola. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-ASSESS (Jerusalem) _ News Analysis: When Prime Minister
Ehud Barak first declared his ambitious intentions to juggle two
peace efforts simultaneously, he said he could keep both balls in
the air and prevent them from touching each other. But that turns
out to be a contortionist's trick. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   SYRIA-PEACE (Damascus) _ Syrians on the street welcome the
prospect of peace, in large part because the economy is in terrible
shape. By Susan Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHECHNYA (Mozdok, Russia) _ Developments: Russians have
reportedly reached the center of Grozny. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-SCANDAL (Berlin) _ Under pressure from Christian
Democrats to clear up a campaign financing scandal, former
Chancellor Helmut Kohl resigns as honorary party chairman.
Developing; summary from wires. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   SERBIA-ARKAN (Belgrade) _ Authorities say the wounded attacker
of the notorious Serbian paramilitary leader known as Arkan is part
of the Montenegro mafia (i.e., they say the police are trying to
solve it and the Serbian authorities are not involved). By Steven
Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-CULT (Tokyo) _ The Japanese cult that killed 12 people
with a nerve-gas attack on the Tokyo subway in 1995 said it had
deposed its jailed former guru, Shoko Asahara, and would carry out
far-reaching reforms. By Calvin Sims.
</P>
<P>
   POPE-PROTESTANTS (Rome) _ Pope pleads for unity but some
Protestant leaders boycott a special ceremony at the Vatican. By
Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded a)
</P>
<P>
   GUN-MAKERS (Las Vegas) _ National Shooting Sports Foundation, a
manufacturers group, has joined the NRA as a major player in the
gun wars, fighting gun control laws and forming a PAC to influence
the presidential race. It expects to raise $10 million a year. By
Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   GUN-LAWS (Boston) _ The proposal to step up enforcement of gun
laws gets warm reception from NRA, plus new details. By Marc Lacey.
</P>
<P>
   FLA-CITRUS-CANKER (Florida dateline to come) _ Citrus canker is
playing havoc with Florida agriculture, particularly the lime crop.
By Peter T. Kilborn.
</P>
<P>
   RABBIS-JERUSALEM (Undated) _ Breaking with longheld views, 300
rabbis sign a call for a shared Jerusalem. By Neil MacFarquhar.
</P>
<P>
   EDUC-SCHOOLS-MOBILITY (Undated) _ Attacking excessive mobility:
the problem of students who switch schools repeatedly. By Richard
Rothstein.
</P>
