<SLUG> BC-FBN-RAMS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE PLACE RAMS CAN'T BE BEAT IS IN THE HELMET DEPARTMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ A great example of the difference in sports between
the slick America of 2000 and the more basic world of half a
century ago will be apparent next Sunday when the Rams _ once of
Cleveland, then of Los Angeles and Anaheim, and now of St. Louis _
meet the Tampa Bay Buccaneers.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, the uniforms. And, precisely, the helmets.
</P>
<P>
   It is not apocryphal that Eric Dickerson, when asked in 1983
what team he wanted to be drafted by out of SMU, said the Rams, for
a basic reason: ``I've always liked their helmets.''
</P>
<P>
   Who hasn't?
</P>
<P>
   At Rams headquarters in Earth City, Mo., there are pictures of
Rams of the distant past and Rams of the recent past, and all are
wearing the helmet with the horns on it. Bob Waterfield, Norm Van
Brocklin, Crazy Legs Hirsch, Jack Snow, Roman Gabriel, Pat Haden,
and, yes, Eric Dickerson.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay will need a blizzard, a tornado, and perhaps an
earthquake or two to beat these Rams, one of the most explosive
teams in recent NFL history. As much of a handicap, though, might
be the ghastly uniforms, ghastly logo, and ghastly helmets that the
Buccaneers wear, all the creation of anonymous, modern, high-tech
graphics artists.
</P>
<P>
   In this area, for sure, the world has not improved in the last
half-century.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams' horns, by contrast, were the creation of a decidedly
low-tech world, back when an individual's vision counted for so
much more than a computer's creation. The individual in question
was Clarence ``Fred'' Gerhke, a running back from Utah who played
with the Cleveland Rams in 1940 and then after World War II, from
1945-49, with the Los Angeles Rams. Gerhke was also a graphic
designer.
</P>
<P>
   Football teams back then did not have designs on their helmets,
which had just made the transition from leather to more protective
substances. But Los Angeles being Los Angeles, even in 1947, Gerhke
decided to add a touch of Hollywood style to the plain helmets the
Rams wore. That year, the Rams became the first team in pro
football to have anything on their helmets other than scratches.
</P>
<P>
   Gerhke designed a very basic, minimalist set of horns, a design
that most likely wouldn't pass muster with the high-tech artists of
today. Too simple. Too basic. Too plain.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, but so perfect.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend, as Rams Mania swept over St. Louis, the art critic
of the St. Louis Post-Dispatch, Jeff Daniel, jumped into the
spirit. He not only defended the Ram horns as a true artistic
creation, but claimed that minimalism, op art, and pop art, all of
which followed Gerhke's creation by a decade or two, were
influenced by it.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel even cited artist Jasper Johns. ``It's long been a
rumor,'' wrote Daniel, ``but Johns supposedly said that `there are
three recognizable symbols in our culture, the American flag, the
circular target and . . . the Rams' helmet.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The National Football League lately has called on anonymous
high-tech artists to design or redesign team logos. The Patriots'
Elvis-as-patriotic-Superman is as forgettable as Seattle's seahawk,
but what defies description is Tampa Bay's depiction of a
buccaneer.
</P>
<P>
   The Bucs may show that they deserve to be on the same AstroTurf
as the Rams _ not likely, but possible _ but in one area the Rams
are already _ and long have been _ in a class by themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Their helmets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
