<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-18 14:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9145 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-BREEDING-ZOO-HNS &LR;      01-18 0610
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BREEDING-ZOO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SAN ANTONIO ZOO OFFERS A WARM LOVE NEST FOR THE ANIMAL
KINGDOM 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JACQUE CROUSE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ San Antonio is a romantic city. Strolls on the
River Walk. Moonlit rides in horse-drawn carriages. Leisurely
drinks and meals at patio cafes.
</P>
<P>
   Or an intimate tryst in a dusty exhibit at the zoo.
</P>
<P>
   It seems the San Antonio Zoo is a productive honeymoon spot for
the animal kingdom. It was the first zoo to successfully breed
white rhinos in the 1960s, and has since proved one of the most
prolific breeding grounds for the endangered snow leopard.
</P>
<P>
   The zoo helped breed golden lion tamarins, which have been
released to restart wild populations in Brazil, and was a factor in
the resurgence of the Arabian oryx.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably because of the climate, we do well as a breeding
zoo,'' said Terry Fisher, a zoologist who keeps records of all
movements of animals to and from the San Antonio Zoo. ``Zoos all
across the country do this. We all help breed many types of
animals. The American Zoological and Aquarium Association has
committees of experts which decide who needs to be bred, when and
where, in order to keep populations alive.''
</P>
<P>
   Not even the experts can predict chemistry, and sometimes this
zoological match-making does not work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just like people who date, sometimes the animals just take one
look at each other and are not interested,'' Fisher said.
``Luckily, it doesn't happen that often.''
</P>
<P>
   While a handful of animals may need a cooler climate to breed,
those are few and far between, Fisher said. Even snow leopards, it
seems, prefer this balmy habitat to their cold native soil.
</P>
<P>
   ``It must be like a honeymoon vacation to Bermuda for them to
come here, because they breed like crazy,'' Fisher said. ``Since
1970, 58 cubs have been born here. They have been shipped to places
like Japan, Finland and Australia.''
</P>
<P>
   The zoo's young Sumatran tiger cubs, Maluka Khan and Melu Khan,
are the progeny of the San Antonio meeting of father Manfred from
the Rotterdam Zoo and mother Malaya from the San Diego Zoo.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher explained that the experts on tiger populations decided
Manfred and Malaya should breed, and they picked San Antonio as the
place.
</P>
<P>
   Now, mother and cubs remain together while Manfred is in a
separate area. Big cats are much the same as their household
counterparts in that males may kill their young offspring.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are only 50 Sumatran tigers left in the wild, and 250 in
captivity,'' Fisher said. ``After the cubs are older, we will move
them and mate the parents again, probably in March. It's a good
step in assuring the survival of the subspecies.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past, animals were bred in captivity with the aim of
releasing them into the wild, but Fisher said that is becoming less
likely in many cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in Brazil a couple of years ago working with the man who
was releasing the golden lion tamarins,'' he said. ``They were
trying to find real estate to buy to be able to release more. But
there was no land to be had. The wild areas, which are the
tamarins' natural habitat, are pretty much gone.''
</P>
<P>
   The other obstacle to endangered species being released in the
wild is poachers. Fisher said poachers are the primary reason for
the demise of various rhino species.
</P>
<P>
   ``The herds of Arabian oryx that were released on the Arabian
Peninsula are guarded, 24 hours a day, by soldiers carrying
automatic weapons,'' Fisher said. ``Before, the goal was always to
release back into the wild. Now, we realize that may not always be
the best idea.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
