<HEADLINE>
&HT;     EDITOR FACES JAIL TIME FOR PROTECTING SOURCES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ERIC BRAZIL  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The editor and publisher of a small-town
newspaper in Northern California is prepared to spend five days in
jail rather than reveal the names of two confidential sources five
years after they told him that a lawman was suspected of stealing a
pistol.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm being held in contempt of court for refusing to name
sources on a story I didn't run until four years later,'' said an
unrepentant Tim Crews, 57. ``Is that not bizarre?''
</P>
<P>
   Retired Tehama County Superior Court Judge Noel Watkins found
Crews in contempt last week. Sentencing was delayed until Friday,
when Crews re-takes the witness stand in the preliminary hearing
for Highway Patrol officer Dewey Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson is accused of grand theft of a .38-caliber pistol,
receiving stolen property and possessing a weapon with an
obliterated serial number. He has pleaded not guilty.
</P>
<P>
   The weapon was seized as evidence by the Tehama County
Interagency Drug Enforcement Unit. Anderson, who was then the
county's undersheriff, said it accidentally became mixed in with
his personal equipment, and he forgot to return it when he left the
unit in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The pistol popped up last year in the possession of the
boyfriend of Anderson's daughter at a Shasta County high school,
and it was traced to Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   Crews recently wrote an article in his twice-weekly Sacramento
Valley Mirror mentioning that he had been tipped off in 1995 by two
law enforcement officers who said that Anderson had stolen the
pistol, but that he did not report the tip at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't feel like I had enough information to say the
undersheriff is a thief,'' Crews said Monday. One of the officers
actually read him a report written on the loss of the weapon that
had been sent to then-Glenn County Sheriff Kevin Donnelly, he said.
``But I never saw a copy of the report.''
</P>
<P>
   Crews' disclosure that he had received a tip about the theft was
seized upon by Anderson's lawyer, William Malloy of Redding, who
contends that it proves that officials knew about the theft more
than four years ago and that the statute of limitations on the
felony grand theft charge has expired.
</P>
<P>
   Watkins ordered Crews to disclose the names of his informants,
adding: ``I make a finding that revealing your sources will not
impair your news gathering ability.''
</P>
<P>
   When Crews refused, the judge found him in contempt of court and
sentenced him to five days in jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our part of the world _ Glenn County has only 27,000 people
_ we have to have confidential sources. If we don't use them, we'd
have to go back to just printing pablum, but we're expected to
report the news and raise hell. ... I'm not giving up these
sources.''
</P>
<P>
   Crews, who has edited and published the Valley Mirror in the
little Glenn County town of Artois since 1991, is a former editor
for newspapers in Aberdeen and Olympia, Wash. In 1997, he was a
winner of the First Amendment Coalition's Beacon Award for
courageous reporting.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Crews has not been represented by a lawyer. He said he
would have to address that problem fast. ``I won't be going there
(court) naked on Friday,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
