<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   IOWA _ Second installment of Dispatches from Iowa. In the
offing: snow flurries, campaigning with dark horse candidate Mark
Kennis and scenes from the Gore-Bradley debate. (Beach, Austin
American-Statesman). 40.
</P>
<P>
   ISSUEADS _ Amidst the commercials from the major presidential
candidates, independent lobbying groups are also filling the
airwaves in New Hampshire with unregulated political
advertisements. The Sierra Club is running a ``voter education'' ad
attacking the environmental record of Gov. George W. Bush, and a
conservative tax group is attacking Sen. John McCain (R-Ariz.) on
campaign finance reform. So far, however, independent groups appear
to be playing only a minor role in the New Hampshire primary.
(Foskett, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 20.
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush may have coined a new term to
describe his brand of ideology _ compassionate conservatism _ but
John McCain is exploiting a new brand of conservatism as well:
Anti-establishment populism unfettered by the rigid social
conservatism that usually accompanies it. It seems to have found an
audience. (Sherman, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 25.
</P>
<P>
   FORBES _ With poor poll numbers in New Hampshire, Steve Forbes
is looking to Iowa to build some early momentum. Will he turn to
negative ads like four years ago? We file a campaign update from
Iowa. (Baxter, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 25.
</P>
