<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-18 14:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9167 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k BC-ROBB-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      01-18 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBB-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN'S TAX-CUT PROPOSAL LACKS COURAGE, INSIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT ROBB  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - In his tax-cut speech, John McCain invoked the legacy
of Ronald Reagan while repudiating one of its central planks:
expanding economic growth by reducing marginal tax rates.
</P>
<P>
   And he called for courage on Social Security while demonstrating
none.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's tax-cut plan abandons Republican claims to be the party
of economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the repeated canard that we are in the midst of an
``unprecedented'' economic expansion, this is an underperforming
economy. The Congressional Budget Office projects economic growth
of 2.5 percent a year. During the 50s and 60s, the economy grew at
a rate of 4 to 5 percent a year, and it grew nearly 4 percent a
year during the Reagan tax-cut era.
</P>
<P>
   While George W. Bush accepted the CBO estimate as a constraint
in fashioning his tax-cut plan, he made it clear in an interview
last month with ``''``The Arizona Republic'' editorial board that
his plan is designed, in part, to grow the economy more than that
through across-the-board reductions in marginal personal income tax
rates, returning them to near the Reagan levels.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's tax-cut plan is more of a social program than an
economic growth strategy. He expands the current 15 percent tax
bracket and includes a hodgepodge of other tax credits and breaks.
But he does nothing to reduce punitive and economically
unproductive high marginal tax rates, or percentage of tax paid on
the next dollar earned. Under current law, that can be as high as
39.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he cites the relatively minuscule tax relief his plan
offers high-income Americans compared to Bush's as one of its
virtues, and resorts to the language of economic envy by
dismissively referring, in one comparison, to a ``lucky
millionaire.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps to someone whose only private sector experience consists
of a short stint in a makeshift job provided by his father-in-law,
it seems that people become millionaires in America through luck.
In reality, most millionaires in America get there through hard
work, by creating a product or service people want, and by
providing employment and economic opportunity to others.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's populist cant betrays an ignorance of the stake low-
and middle-income Americans have in economic expansion fueled by
reductions in high marginal tax rates. Real incomes for both groups
increased more during the Reagan tax-cut era than they have during
the current expansion.
</P>
<P>
   McCain asserts that Bush's tax cut is fiscally irresponsible
because it largely consumes the projected non-Social Security
surplus over the next decade. McCain says he would use 62 percent
of that surplus to pay Social Security benefits when Social
Security taxes will no long cover the bill, currently projected to
occur sometime after 2014.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain doesn't say exactly how he proposes to save today's
surplus to pay tomorrow's Social Security benefits, undercutting
his claim to be responsible and courageous on the subject.
</P>
<P>
   Unless something is done with surplus monies, 100 percent of
them will go to reducing the federal debt, not just the 5 percent
McCain says he intends to be used for that purpose.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton also proposes using non-Social Security
surpluses to pay future Social Security benefits, but he has
identified a mechanism by which to do it: Put the surpluses in the
Social Security Trust Fund and invest them in the economy.
</P>
<P>
   That would give the federal government a large position in the
equity and debt of American companies, a dangerous federal presence
in the economy.
</P>
<P>
   This would be hugely unpopular with Republican primary voters,
but it is difficult to see how McCain can use near-term non-Social
Security surpluses to pay long-term Social Security benefits
without doing something similar.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said his tax-cut plan was also crafted to help young
people ``threatened by a potential future of crushing debt of $5.6
trillion.'' Yet his plan would reduce the cumulative national debt
only by about 1 percent over the next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   So, instead of saddling young people with a $5.6 trillion debt,
McCain would saddle them with a $5.54 trillion debt. Why? So McCain
can pander to the senior vote, promising no reduction in Social
Security benefits ever, regardless of how small the reduction, or
how wealthy the senior.
</P>
<P>
   In this speech, McCain proved that when it comes to tax cuts,
he's no Ronald Reagan. And when it comes to Social Security reform,
he's no profile in courage. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reach Robb at Bob.Robb(at)ArizonaRepublic.com. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-18-00 1445EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
