<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-18 15:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9192 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX     01-18 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COOKIES ARE A RECIPE FOR KITCHEN SKIRMISHES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MONICA FRAZIER ANDERSON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They were not the sounds that I usually associate with baking. I
was expecting whirring and stirring with perhaps the occasional
sound of a cabinet door opening and closing. You know, the
customary Mom's-in-the-kitchen type sounds that precede the
delicious aroma of fresh-baked cookies.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, there was a lot of banging, clanging and sawing going
on in the kitchen. Even for two boys, it seemed like a lot of noise
just to make a few dozen sugar cookies.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, I'm not an expert on these things. For me, it's just
too easy to swing by the bakery and pick up a cake. However,
because my mother inspects my kitchen periodically, I try to keep
the basic ingredients for baking in the cupboards. I even use them
sometimes _ just not often.
</P>
<P>
   So, when my two sons asked me to help them bake some sugar
cookies one evening, I was flattered. Unfortunately, because of a
looming deadline on an important project, I had to decline with
regrets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can do it tomorrow,'' I offered.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's all right, Mom,'' Junior said. ``It's a simple recipe.
I think we can do it, if it's OK with you. I'll read the directions
and my brother can mix it all up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, go ahead,'' I said, reminding myself how good they'd
gotten at microwave bacon and French toast. ``Remember to turn the
oven on first, and clean up the kitchen when you're done. I'm
sorry, but I really need to finish this work so don't disturb me
unless it's really important.''
</P>
<P>
   I should have defined ``really important.''
</P>
<P>
   First, there was the banging. I think they opened and closed
every cabinet in the kitchen. Then, there was this long, loud
argument about who was in charge. I couldn't hear all of it, but I
heard enough of it. After about 10 minutes of bickering, I yelled,
``I'm in charge tonight. Junior, read the directions. Kevin, mix
everything together and then you can both take turns with the
blender. Now, keep it down! You're baking cookies, it's a quiet
sport.''
</P>
<P>
   After that, they whispered their argument.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes later, there was a knock on my bedroom door. It
was Junior. ``Mom, do we have any vanilla?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, it's in the cabinet near the salt, far left, small
red-and-white box.''
</P>
<P>
   Five minutes later, Junior returned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mom, do we have any almond extract or tartar sauce?''
</P>
<P>
   I had to smile at that question.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, we don't have almond extract or cream of tartar. The
cookies will taste fine without it.''
</P>
<P>
   He looked skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   ``Son, just because I don't bake often doesn't mean that I don't
know how to bake. In fact, I'm also quite good with a sewing
machine, but don't tell your father. Listen, all you need for sugar
cookies is: sugar, butter, vanilla, an egg, flour, and baking soda.
And before you ask, the baking soda is in a red can near the
vanilla. Do not use that baking soda in the yellow box in the
refrigerator. It's a deodorizer, and it's been in there a couple of
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Impressed by my culinary expertise, he turned to leave the room.
Imagine my joy.
</P>
<P>
   I returned to my project with total concentration. I had a good
20 minutes of peace before I heard the electric chain saw. We own
so few power tools that I immediately recognized the sound. I ran
into the kitchen. Kevin had my best cookie sheet perched on the
sink and he was preparing to amputate a big section of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stop!'' I screamed. ``What are you doing?''
</P>
<P>
   ``It won't fit in the oven,'' he said. ``I have to cut some of
it off.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you try turning it sideways?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh.''
</P>
<P>
   I looked around. There was flour and sugar everywhere. The oven
was on 375 degrees and ``broil.'' The hand blender had only one of
the two metal stirrey things in it. And there seemed to be a lot of
egg shells for a recipe that required only one egg.
</P>
<P>
   I turned the oven dial to ``bake'' and washed my hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``What about your project?'' Kevin asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll do it later. This project looks like a lot more fun,'' I
said, smiling.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, I was trying to save my cookie sheet and avoid a visit to
the ER. Yes, I was up well into the AM trying to beat that
deadline.
</P>
<P>
   And yes, those were the best sugar cookies I've ever had.
</P>
<P>
   (Monica Frazier Anderson is a wife, mother and dentist in
Arlinton, Texas. You can call her at (817) 548-5564, or write in
care of the Arlington Star-Telegram at 1111 W. Abram St.,
Arlington, TX 76013. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on
the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
