<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-18 15:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9225 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-PRIEST-TRIAL-HNS &LR;      01-18 0966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRIEST-TRIAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PRIEST FACES TRIAL FOR WRESTLING WITH RECTORY WORKER 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (Eds: Note optional trim.)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ELIZABETH FERNANDEZ  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Two years after a Roman Catholic parish in
Burlingame was stunned by disclosures of a nocturnal wrestling
match between the church's pastor and a teen-age male rectory
worker, the case is heading to trial in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Mediation late last year failed to settle differences in a
personal injury lawsuit lodged by the teen _ who is now an adult _
against the Archdiocese of San Francisco and the priest, the Rev.
James Aylward.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit contends that the teen was ``physically and mentally
abused'' by the priest for more than a year while working in the
rectory of St. Catherine of Siena Church, and that the archdiocese
sanctioned the misconduct by failing to discipline the priest.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit claims damages of more than $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   Archdiocesan officials and Aylward, who have maintained that the
improper conduct consisted of a single incident of ``horseplay and
wrestling,'' vehemently deny the allegations.
</P>
<P>
   And law enforcement officials who investigated the accusations
said they lacked enough evidence to file charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing happened,'' said Paul Gaspari, the lawyer who is
representing the archdiocese and Archbishop William Levada, who as
head of the Catholic Church in San Mateo, San Francisco and Marin
counties, also is a defendant.
</P>
<P>
   The case achieved notoriety in part because of the way the
incident was discovered and because of the odd circumstances that
transpired afterward.
</P>
<P>
   A parish priest, who had worked as a federal prosecutor prior to
his ordination, stumbled upon the encounter in a darkened rectory
room and reported it to both church and civil authorities. Soon
afterward, that priest, the Rev. John Conley, was placed on
administrative leave. The archdiocese said Conley was disciplined
for previous transgressions and for insubordinate and disrespectful
behavior toward his bishop.
</P>
<P>
   In a highly unusual move, Conley then sued his own religious
superiors, maintaining that he was defamed and penalized for
reporting suspected child abuse. That lawsuit was dismissed in San
Francisco last year and is on appeal. Conley remains on
administrative leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``He won't do what they are asking him to do, which is to submit
to psychological counseling,'' said Michael Guta, the lawyer
representing Conley.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is our contention that what happened to Father Conley was
an attempt to neutralize the witness to a boy being molested. They
figured the best way to do that is to say that Father Conley is
crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Aylward, now 61, publicly apologized for his ``foolishness and
imprudence'' for engaging in conduct that is forbidden by
archdiocesan policy, and said he was seeking counseling. About
seven months after the incident was exposed, Aylward _ who was
ordained in 1964 and appointed to St. Catherine's in 1996 _
resigned from the parish, attributing his departure to ``personal
and administrative pressures'' and to health reasons. He has since
served at Our Lady of Mount Carmel Church in Mill Valley as
associate pastor.
</P>
<P>
   Last spring, the teen, a former altar boy, filed suit. Because
he was a minor at the time, his identity is being protected by the
court.
</P>
<P>
   The trial is scheduled for April in San Francisco Superior
Court.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS. &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiff, called John Doe in the suit, was hired by Aylward
in August 1996 when he was 15 to work three evenings a week
answering phones at the parish rectory. According to the lawsuit,
young women and young men were hired for clerical work at the
rectory before Aylward became pastor, but that employment was
limited to young males during Aylward's tenure.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after his hiring, Aylward began making inappropriate
advances to the teen, the lawsuit alleges.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aylward would hold Doe hostage by massaging his neck, rubbing
his back, placing him in head lock, clasping him to his chest in
tight hugs, and rubbing his penis and/or buttocks against Doe's arm
and other body areas,'' the lawsuit alleges. ``Aylward committed
these acts to gratify his sexual desires.''
</P>
<P>
   As time passed, Aylward's alleged advances became more
aggressive, the lawsuit contends.
</P>
<P>
   Maintaining that the archdiocese was responsible for providing
its young employees with a ``safe place to work,'' the lawsuit
contends that Aylward should have been immediately removed from
contact with the youth. Yet the lawsuit says Aylward continued to
engage in improper conduct, even after discovery, for two
additional weeks until the teen quit his job on Nov. 19, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of his encounters with the priest, the young man has
suffered ``extreme emotional distress,'' said Justine Durrell, a
San Francisco lawyer representing the former altar boy.
</P>
<P>
   After Conley reported the incident, the archdiocese has said it
conducted its own investigation and concluded that Aylward's
conduct was inappropriate but not sexual. The archdiocese said it
strongly disapproved of a priest wrestling with a youth, but termed
Aylward's conduct a lapse in judgment.
</P>
<P>
   The San Mateo district attorney's office declined to file
charges in the case.
</P>
<P>
   District Attorney James Fox said in an interview last week that
the young man told both his investigator and the police that his
physical encounter with the priest was limited to a single
incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``We concluded we would not be able to meet the burden of proof
beyond a reasonable doubt,'' Fox said. ``We did not believe it
appropriate to file criminal charges based on our evaluation of the
available evidence.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
