<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-18 15:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9246 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-TEXASATLARGE-CHAPMAN-     01-18 0641
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXASATLARGE-CHAPMAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABILENE LOSES BIT OF HISTORY, AND TOWN'S BEST DINING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Abilene is not Abilene anymore. Not the real West Texas city
where oilmen swap lies and belly laughs with cattle ranchers, and
then go with bankers to the Petroleum Club for lunch.
</P>
<P>
   The Petroleum Club in Abilene has closed.
</P>
<P>
   It was two days before Christmas when the doors slammed shut for
the last time on the Abilene Petroleum Club, and some people here
on the West Texas plains have yet to adjust. Abilene and oil have
always mixed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel lost,'' said Flossie Osborn, a longtime oil patch
character. ``I feel like a man without a country. It's where I went
for TLC, for fellowship. I met a lot of people there.''
</P>
<P>
   Osborn won't give her age, said she never does: ``I'm an old
lady, but I don't admit it. I try to stay as young as I can.'' But
she will admit to eating at the club twice a day for the past 20
years. ``I was the unofficial mother of the club,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Petroleum Club existed for a half-century in Abilene. It was
in three locations over its lifetime, but the final resting place
was high atop the Bank of America Tower.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to have our own place down on North First,'' Osborn
said. ``Then the bankers talked them into moving to the new bank
and paying rent and utilities. That didn't make any sense to me,
but times were good, and they thought it would never end.''
</P>
<P>
   It did.
</P>
<P>
   Osborn was a part of the oil boom in Abilene. She managed a
company called Grand Mud for 13 years. She was the lone woman boss
over 53 oilfield workers who carted chemicals to more than 70 oil
rigs throughout the area.
</P>
<P>
   ``People ask me how I could manage those men,'' Osborn
remembered. ``I always answer: `We had an understanding.'''
</P>
<P>
   She said she wasn't a lady while running Grand Mud. There wasn't
time or a need for it. ``If you're raised in the country and work
like the devil all your life, you learn how to handle yourself,''
she said. ``Sometimes the guys liked me, and sometimes they didn't.
But they always worked hard for me.''
</P>
<P>
   The oil business crashed in Abilene several years ago, just like
it did everywhere else. Business at the club fell off.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a beautiful pla flowers on the tables _ the
prettiest place in town,'' Osborn said. ``That's no lie.''
</P>
<P>
   And the food? ``Honey, I ate it all, I'm not fat but I should
be,'' she said. There was one item she never got around to, though.
The club was known for its ``chicken-fried lobster,'' but Osborn
never got a taste. Never wanted one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm an honest steak woman,'' she said defiantly. ``I'm from
dry land. I'm not a fish person.''
</P>
<P>
   Osborn tthe club would survive the hard times, hoped it
would. And when the oil business began its recent recovery, she
looked for a return to the Petroleum Club's glory.
</P>
<P>
   But it didn't happen. City clubs and private clubs faced a tough
battle against upscale restaurants and burgeoning country clubs.
</P>
<P>
   The clients moved away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought they could pull it out,'' she said. ``I thought that
if you cared enough about something, you could save it. I guess I
was wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   It's over now, she admits, and there'll never be another one
like it. It is a part of her life she'll never be able to replace,
though she is still looking hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been trying every place,'' she said. ``I guess I'll join
the country club. I've never been a member out there, but who
knows, maybe I'll join and I'll be able to get my groove back. I
kind of need some culture.''
</P>
<P>
   (Art Chapman writes a weekly column on things Texan. You can
call him at (817) 390-7422, or e-mail: artc(at)star-telegram.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-18-00 1544EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
