<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBISON'S DECISION PROVIDES A COMFORTING THOUGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There was good news and bad news on the criminal justice front
last week.
</P>
<P>
   Good: Multiple murderer Larry Keith Robison instructed his
lawyers and his family to stop appealing his death sentence and
allow him to keep his appointment with the Texas executioner this
Friday. Robison slaughtered five people near Lake Worth more than
17 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Bad: A judge in Michigan sentenced 13-year-old killer Nathaniel
Abraham to while away his youth in a juvenile detention center,
which is to say that the kid will be unleashed on society when he
reaches the age of 21. The judge could have imposed a sentence that
would have made Abraham's release contingent upon his
rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
   This way, the people of Michigan must hope that the revolting
little sociopath will mend his ways and will resist any future
urges to practice his shooting skills on human targets.
</P>
<P>
   The kid's lawyer _ revolting-in-his-own-right Geoffrey Fieger _
has been saying in media interviews that his client was just
``playing with a gun'' in 1997 when he fatally shot 18-year-old
Ronnie Greene Jr. outside a convenience store in Pontiac, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   Just playing? That puts a new twist on the phrase ``Boys will be
boys,'' doesn't it?
</P>
<P>
   If the judge had gone the other way _ if he had chosen the
``blended sentence'' recommended by prosecutors _ the state of
Michigan could have kept Abraham under wraps in juvenile detention
until he was 21 and then decided whether he should be released or
ordered to serve some time in an adult prison.
</P>
<P>
   A member of the Michigan Legislature opined on one of the
morning TV gabfests that the judge was more concerned about the
welfare of the convict than the welfare of Michigan's law-abiding
citizens. Imagine that: a legislator who knows what he's talking
about.
</P>
<P>
   So much for the downside of the justice system. That mess-up in
Michigan is clearly outweighed by the welcome news that Larry Keith
Robison has decided to stop stalling and accept the punishment that
he has so long deserved.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, Robison was willing to take that last walk _ he
said he was, anyway _ way back in August. But the brain-dead Texas
Court of Criminal Appeals blocked the execution and ordered a
hearing to determine whether Robison was mentally competent enough
to understand that ``lethal injection'' is a synonym for ``dead.''
</P>
<P>
   He was. And he is.
</P>
<P>
   ``The competency hearing wasn't my idea,'' Robison said during
testimony at the November hearing. ``There are people out there who
love me ... and they want me to live.''
</P>
<P>
   Robison's mother loves him, and she said so in no uncertain
terms during a segment of the TV show ``48 Hours'' on Thursday
night. Because her son was a lovable little boy _ and because she
adores him, no matter how brutally he murdered those folks in 1982
_ Lois Robison is of the opinion that the state of Texas should
show him some mercy.
</P>
<P>
   She was hoping for mercy when she walked into the courthouse for
her son's competency hearing, but she wasn't counting on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have much faith left in the criminal justice system,''
she told ``48 Hours.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironic, isn't it? That's exactly what the loved ones of Larry
Robison's victims have been saying about a system that allowed a
vicious killer to dodge the executioner all these years, appeal
after appeal and delay after delay.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to understand a mother's anguish over the impending
death of her son. It's also easy to understand the anguish of those
who have waited so long for justice to be done.
</P>
<P>
   Give Robison credit for wanting to get it over with.
</P>
<P>
   His mother would keep fighting, if he would give her the
go-ahead. The Fort Worth Star-Telegram quoted her:
</P>
<P>
   ``There are still some things we could have done in the courts
to try to stop this, but Larry has made it clear that he does not
want us to continue. We felt like we have to honor his wishes.''
</P>
<P>
   By all means. If Larry Keith Robison wishes, at last, to get
what's coming to him, we should definitely honor his wishes.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can reach him at (817) 390-7787 or
billthompson(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
