</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-GIGANTE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VINCENT `THE CHIN' GIGANTE LOSES FINAL APPEAL 
</HEADLINE>
 (nk) 
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ He once wandered the streets of Greenwich Village
in pajamas and bathrobe in what his pursuers said was an attempt to
show that he was mentally incompetent to stand trial for
mob-related crimes. In behaving that way, Vincent Gigante sparked a
lot of conversation.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, he lost his final appeal when the U.S. Supreme Court
refused to hear his case. The justices turned him down without
saying a word.
</P>
<P>
   So Gigante, now in his early 70s and by all accounts a shell of
the frightening man he once was, will continue to serve a 12-year
prison sentence for racketeering and murder-conspiracy charges.
</P>
<P>
   The appeal that the High Court turned away contended that
Gigante was denied a fair trial before his 1997 federal court
conviction because a key government witness testified from a remote
location via two-way closed-circuit television.
</P>
<P>
   Gigante's lawyers had contended that the closed-circuit
arrangement violated his constitutional right to face his accusers.
No, a federal appeals court declared; the televised testimony was
close enough to a live courtroom appearance.
</P>
<P>
   The defendant's lawyers had also contended that their client
suffered because the jurors improperly discussed the case among
themselves throughout the trial. That contention also was rejected
last year by the trial judge, Jack B. Weinstein.
</P>
<P>
   Gigante's pajamas-and-bathrobe routine was ridiculed by the
authorities, but it worked _ and for quite a while. He was able to
stave off a trial for seven years while lawyers argued over whether
he was truly incompetent to stand trial or simply pretending.
</P>
<P>
   He was simply pretending, the courts finally ruled. Forced to
stand trial at last, Gigante was portrayed as a cold-blooded
gangster.
</P>
<P>
   In July 1997 the jurors found that, among other things, he had
plotted unsuccessfully to kill John Gotti, the head of the rival
Gambino crime family, in the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   And they found Gigante guilty of plotting to kill other gangland
figures and of running lucrative rackets as one of the leaders of
the notorious Genovese crime family. The jurors acquitted him of
having ordered three slayings and could not agree on four other
murder charges.
</P>
<P>
   When the verdict was read, Gigante's eyes widened briefly,
though he managed to keep the same blank expression he had worn
through the trial, and for that matter while he was wandering the
streets like a sleepwalker in his nightclothes.
</P>
<P>
   ``His criminal charade is over,'' a jubilant prosecutor said.
</P>
<P>
   So, in a way, was an era, or at least part of one. Vincent
Gigante in his prime could have played a role in ``The Godfather''
without acting. He had a good gangster nickname _ The Chin, because
he had a prominent one _ and he had a brother who was a priest.
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, the last word on Vincent Gigante came not from the
Supreme Court on Tuesday but from Weinstein, when he sentenced
Gigante late in 1997. ``This defendant must be sentenced both for
what he was and for what he is,'' the judge said.
</P>
<P>
   Age was indeed catching up with the old mobster, manifesting
itself in heart disease, weight loss and other ailments. ``He is a
shadow of his former self,'' the judge said. ``An old man finally
brought to bay in his declining years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
