<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-TASTING-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GERMAN WINE IN AN ALSATIAN TOUCH MADE IN AUSTRALIA WITH LABELS IN
ENGLISH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Australia, Germany)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(Eds: A list, in order of preference, appears at end of review.)
(DW) 
 By ERIC ASIMOV   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Unexpected pleasure is one of the joys of tasting wine. That is
why I was so happy to discover Australian rieslings, whose finesse
and crisp, refreshing flavors took me by surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Riesling is a great white grape (many say the greatest) but it
has never had the popularity of chardonnay or even sauvignon blanc
in the United States. This is mostly because rieslings soar to
their greatest heights in Germany and Alsace, wine regions that
many Americans regard as alien and intimidating. The United States
produces some decent rieslings (Bonny Doon's come to mind), but
never good enough or in sufficient quantity to make a dent in the
American market.
</P>
<P>
   Australia has long had its own market for rieslings, but they
have generally been the kind of dismal wines sold in cartons and
poured through a spigot. Over the last few years, though,
Australian wineries have changed their approach, tearing out vines
from hot, irrigated areas and replanting in cooler regions, where
riesling is more likely to flourish. Areas to look for on labels
include the Clare Valley in South Australia and the Margaret River
in Western Australia.
</P>
<P>
   The results speak for themselves: wines made more in the
Alsatian style than the German, meaning dry and beautifully
scented, steely rather than luscious, and with more alcohol and
less sugar than is typical in Germany. Perhaps most comforting for
Americans, the labels are in English.
</P>
<P>
   The six wines here are listed in order of preference. A
suggestion: While the tendency is to serve white wines cold, these
wines almost always taste better slightly warmer, say, 20 to 30
minutes out of the refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   Leeuwin Estate, Margaret River, 1997 $22 &QL; 
Floral aromas, complex well-balanced peach and pear flavors. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Sevenhill Stringy Brae, Clare Valley, 1998 $22 &QL; 
Racy, honeyed aroma, slate flavors with a touch of sweetness.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
Pikes, Clare Valley, 1998 $15 &QL; 
Tart and brisk with a delicious mineral tang.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
Grosset, Polish Hill, Clare Valley, 1998 $22 &QL; 
Mineral aromas, dry and powerful. with a long, complex finish.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
Tim Adams, Clare Valley, 1998 $14 &QL; 
Tart and acidic with citrus and apricot flavors.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
Crabtree, Watervale, 1998 $17 &QL; 
Tart, dry, clean and refreshing. Slightly skunky, funky aroma, dry,
tart and clean in the mouth. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
