<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-18 16:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9271 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-WAITERWEAR-ART-NYT &LR;      01-18 1252
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WAITERWEAR-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT BECOMES A WAITER MOST? 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos are being sent. Non-subscribers can purchase by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By RICK MARIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ God is in the details, the architects say. And if
you're a restaurateur opening a hot, cool-looking new place, He may
be in the waiters' cobalt-blue utility belts.
</P>
<P>
   That was Diane Ghioto's thinking when she designed the
Ultrasuede belts to match the two-tone tile in Isla, her new
Cuban-themed restaurant on Downing Street in Manhattan. As a former
accessories editor for Elle, Ms. Ghioto thought long and hard about
The Look of the '50s-modern decor and the 2000-modern staff.
</P>
<P>
   She tried guayabera shirts for the first couple of nights, then
decided they looked like a Cuban cliche. Now, as long as her
servers wear saturated black, they pass muster. ``I have a really
big problem with faded black things,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   And they must wear the blue utility belt.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the one thing that sets apart the servers,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Setting them apart isn't as easy as it once was. The old
modified penguin has been extinct at cutting-edge establishments at
least since the '60s, when waiters started wearing love beads.
Later came the khakis and button-downs. But in this era of
self-conscious stylishness, waiterwear is expected to make as much
of a design statement as the matchbooks and bar stools. It is now
possible for New York diners to confuse their server with a
Buddhist priest, a Benedictine monk, a garage mechanic, a chef, a
dishwasher or a perfume ad. Anything but a waiter.
</P>
<P>
   Take Local. There's nothing Asian about this newish haute diner
in the theater district. But the waiters wear black
mandarin-collared jackets that evoke an Eastern devotional
aesthetic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really didn't want to do a tie and a traditional shirt,''
said David Napolitan, the managing partner of Local. He said he
didn't think of the jackets as devotional, but as a futuristic
``Star Trek'' thing, though he does think they emphasize ``the
sanctity of the food.''
</P>
<P>
   They were designed with the aid of a Broadway costume designer,
Stev Taylor, for $60 to $70 each, Napolitan said _ a midrange price
for high-end waiterwear. Local also recently costumed the servers
working the long chef's counter in tie-dyed blue and green chef's
uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   Kitchenwear as waiter attire is another mini-movement away from
the traditional tie-and-vest uniform. At Beacon, the waiters wear
chef's coats. Buttons on the side. Everything but a toque on top.
The subliminal message seems to be, This place is so good, our
waiters could drop their note pads and grill a quail on the spot.
</P>
<P>
   Waldy Malouf, the actual chef at Beacon, explained his concept.
``I wanted the uniforms to be unique,'' he said, an extension of
the open kitchen that would make the customer feel ``part of what
was going on.''
</P>
<P>
   This gimmick, Malouf said, ``has been thought of as brilliant,
and it's also been thought of as ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   For the record, the chefs at Beacon do not wear waiter uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   Lupa, Mario Batali's new Greenwich Village osteria, takes this
look a little further down the culinary food chain. The servers
sport loose-fitting white smocks that are either ``butchers'
jackets,'' as one of the owners, Jason Denton, said, or
dishwashers' shirts, which they also strongly resemble.
</P>
<P>
   All black, the New Yorker's staple uniform, is still alive and
well from the Village (EQ, Coup) to the Upper East Side (the black
pants and long-sleeve polo shirts worn at Nicole's are conveniently
for sale in the Nicole Farhi store upstairs: $100 for the polo
shirts, $170 for the pants).
</P>
<P>
   For Icon, in the new W Court hotel at 39th Street and Lexington
Avenue, Michael Trenk, the general manager, considered the mandarin
collar. ``I almost went that way,'' he said. ``But they didn't look
that good on our wait staff. They looked sloppy, like a bunch of
ninjas running around.'' He switched to black miniskirts with a
slit up the side and black scoop-necked stretch tops. ``Sexy but
not too revealing,'' Trenk said. ``Right on the edge.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it goes without saying that 95 percent of Trenk's servers
are women. The men wear black pants, and black DKNY shirts with
gray Calvin Klein T-shirts underneath.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of gray, wasn't it supposed to be the new black? It is
at two very designy new places: Quantum 56 and the Brasserie. Axel
Rudolph, the general manager at Quantum 56, in the Drake hotel,
described his wide-collared gray shirts as ``shimmery gray.''
</P>
<P>
   Together with black pants or skirts and long black vests, they
are intended to match the gray leather chairs in the restaurant's
neo-Bauhaus design. ``It's not a monkey costume,'' Rudolph said.
White, he added with a note of disdain, ``would have been too crass
in the room.''
</P>
<P>
   The Brasserie, which reopened last week in the Seagram Building,
was designed by the architecture firm of Diller &AMP; Scofidio. To
complement the curvy wood walls and video monitors that show
pictures of patrons coming through the front door, Liz Diller, a
partner in the firm, chose charcoal-gray shirts (mandarin-collared)
and aprons with a gray plastic pouch for pads, pens and such,
attached with Velcro.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea was to keep it very simple but to have some elements
to make it distinctive,'' said Ms. Diller, who was especially happy
with the plastic pouch.
</P>
<P>
   Are all these vagaries of wardrobe overthink merely harmless
affectations? Or could taking liberties with the monkey suit
further undermine the ever-eroding distinction between server and
servee?
</P>
<P>
   Anne Hollander, the art historian who wrote ``Sex and Suits''
(Alfred A. Knopf, 1994), is a believer in the traditional garb
favored at the bistro around the corner from her apartment in
Paris: black jackets and bow ties, waistcoats, apron. ``It shows
they are willing to work, not just posing and looking decorative,''
she said. ``One of the things waiters do badly is casual _ telling
jokes and being too friendly. They must always be impersonal, so a
costume that shows they can be impersonal is preferable.''
</P>
<P>
   It's an expectations game. You might think waiters clad in a
monastic shirt or jacket will bring you sanctified food or you
might think you've entered the dining hall of a California cult.
</P>
<P>
   Adam Tihany, the architect and restaurateur, has overseen his
share of uniform designs. Also a shirt-and-tie traditionalist, he
said, ``My first and foremost direction is, Make sure the staff
looks like the staff and doesn't look like the customer.'' He
added, ``There's got to be a very strong element of practicality,
not so much because of use and abuse, but because the staff changes
so fast.'' A designer outfit, he said, ``looks good on good-looking
people, but it's not just like anyone can wear a Prada suit and
look fantastic.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, the servers at Pop on Lafatette Street all appear
to be biding their time between fashion shoots. Sackcloth would
look good on them. (Better than it does on the frites-bearing monks
at Belgo, down the street.)
</P>
<P>
   Roy Liebenthal, Pop's owner, decided garage mechanic coveralls
were the way to go for his retro-mod dining room. What he called
``the whole `Dr. No' vibe'' is accentuated by the telephone
headsets worn by the waiters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was a nice way to have uniformity and equality
for male and female,'' Liebenthal said of his grease-monkey suits.
</P>
<P>
   They only cost $30. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
