<P>
   POLITICS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   McCAIN-2000 (Nashua, N.H.) _ When John McCain talks about taxes
or education on the campaign trail these days he frequently tosses
in the observation that ``there is a growing inequity between the
haves and have nots.'' While such remarks would not be
extraordinary coming from a Democratic politician, it is jarring
coming from a leading Republican presidential contender, whose
party has repeatedly accused their liberal opponents of waging
class warfare. By BENNETT ROTH.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-IOWA (Indianola, Iowa) _ Vice President Al Gore plunges
into a day of campaigning in Iowa, telling college students and
senior citizens here that he will ``fight my heart out for you'' if
elected. Gore holds a commanding lead in most Iowa polls. By DAN
FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   GOP-2000 (Nashua, N.H.) _ Republican presidential hopefuls
George W. Bush and John McCain continue their quarrel over taxes.
McCain says Bush should pledge to keep the Internet tax-free
forever; Bush says he favors a temporary moratorium on Internet
taxes until a commission concludes a study on electronic commerce.
By BENNETT ROTH and R.G. RATCLIFFE.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE-CHAPLAIN (Washington) _ When the House began seeking a new
chaplain, the search committee compiled a list of qualifications
stating that it would be ``extremely beneficial'' if the successful
candidate were a ``dedicated spouse and parent,'' a provision which
would effectively rule out Catholic priests from the job. By JUDY
HOLLAND.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-VOTE (Washington) _ Hispanic voters in Texas lose a
Supreme Court challenge to their local school boards' method of
electing members, which Hispanics claimed was discriminatory. The
justices, without comment, let stand lower court decisions that
validated the controversial at-large election systems in the
Pasadena and Alamo Heights school districts. Hispanic voters had
argued that the systems were illegally designed to prevent Latinos
from getting elected. By STEVE LASH.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PRISONS-TEXAS (Austin, Texas) _ The director of training for the
Texas prison system tells Gov. George W. Bush that prison guards
are in danger because of understaffing and poor training. He
estimates at least 30 corrections officers have been injured in the
past year; a month ago, a guard was stabbed to death in the first
staff fatality at a prison in 17 years. By KATHY WALT.
</P>
<P>
   NASA-SHUTTLE (Houston) _ NASA managers set a launch date for the
first shuttle mission of 2000, an 11-day flight to map most of the
Earth's surface with radar. By MARK CARREAU.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-BUCS (Tampa, Fla.) _ A look at Tampa Bay's outstanding
defense, led by defensive lineman Warren Sapp. The Buccaneers
travel to St. Louis to play the favored St. Louis Rams in the NFC
Championship this weekend. By JOHN McCLAIN.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ Jesse Jackson refuses to give up his
fight against the school policy of zero tolerance of violence. The
goal of that policy is to keep classrooms free of guns, drugs and
brawling. This isn't about racism _ it's about violence. Martin
Luther King, whose birthday we celebrated Monday, would surely
disapprove of Jackson's crusade. Demonstrating against the
confederate flag in South Carolina is a more appropriate way to
uphold King's legacy. By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
