<HEADLINE>
&HT;     WRESTLING STAR RECOVERING AFTER SURGERY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By NICOLE FOY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Stone Cold Steve Austin, the bad boy of
professional wrestling, is recovering at a San Antonio hospital
after undergoing surgery to correct years of head-butting,
body-beating behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Austin, aka the Texas Rattlesnake, had surgery Monday at
Methodist Hospital to relieve chronic pain in his neck, arms and
legs. During the nearly three-hour procedure, surgeons removed bone
spurs, or abnormal growths, from vertebrae in his neck.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Lloyd Youngblood, chief of neurosurgery at the hospital,
said Austin's bruising lifestyle in the ring contributed to the
condition. He speculated that the macho muscled machine could be
sidelines for up to a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he were an office worker, he'd be back at work in two to
three weeks,'' he said, ``but strenuous physical activity takes
longer. What we're looking for is solid healing of the bone, and
that takes a matter of several months.''
</P>
<P>
   Once the bone heals, Austin should be able to enter the ring
with the vengeance that's made him famous, Youngblood said.
</P>
<P>
   There were no complications during surgery, he said. Still, it
took a little longer than usual.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's built a little more strongly and solidly than most
patients we operate on,'' Youngblood said of the 6-foot-2-inch,
252-pound Austin.
</P>
<P>
   After the procedure, Austin stood up on his own and attempted to
walk a few steps, Youngblood said. He should be able to leave the
hospital within the next few days, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looks like the champ that he is,'' Youngblood said. ``He's
doing super.''
</P>
<P>
   During the procedure, Youngblood made an incision in the front
side of Austin's neck. The cervical disks were taken out so the
team of surgeons could access and remove the bone spurs irritating
nerves along the spinal canal.
</P>
<P>
   The wrestling star, who has inspired everything from T-shirts to
action figures to video games, continued living the rough life in
the ring until he couldn't ignore the pain and slight weakening the
bone spurs caused, Youngblood said. Without the surgery, he would
have weakened further and had numbness throughout his body, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he minimizes pain. He just tunes it out,'' Youngblood
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
