<SLUG> BC-FRENCH-CHEESES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CREAMY ANSWER TO FLAVORED YOGURT 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By AMANDA HESSER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Flavored yogurts have never done it for me. They fill
the void and are easy to eat, but they always seem pretty limp.
I've preferred to buy plain whole-milk yogurt and mix in some fruit
myself.
</P>
<P>
   Then I came across Petit Montebourg fresh cheese with fruits.
The cheese, whipped smooth, is what I've always thought yogurt
should be: incredibly creamy, tangy and round in flavor with none
of the sour, chalky taste of other yogurts.
</P>
<P>
   And the cheeses actually taste like the flavors printed on the
tiny yogurtlike packages (about one-third the size of an individual
yogurt pot). The six-cheese packages have two portions each of
berry, peach-pear and banana-strawberry, or strawberry, ap2icot and
pineapple-vanilla.
</P>
<P>
   Peach-pear is the best. It's pure tasting and not too sweet,
though I wouldn't refuse the others.
</P>
<P>
   The big difference between these and real yogurt is the fat
content. These contain cream, unlike most virtuous and dull yogurts
made with low-fat milk. Another surprise: they're not made in
America. They come from a place where people understand the virtues
of cream: France.
</P>
<P>
   Petit Montebourg fresh cheese wat( fruit is $3.59 for a package
of six at Fairway, 2127 Broadway, in Manhattan; (212) 595-1888.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
