<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BATHROOM-SINKS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORGET WHITE PORCELAIN: SINKS GO SNAZZY 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can purchase by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 (DW) 
 By FLORENCE FABRICANT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ No one can accuse restaurant designers of throwing in
everything but the bathroom sink. The one detail some diners never
see has suddenly become a statement.
</P>
<P>
   At the redesigned and reopened Brasserie in the Seagram
Building, a troughlike sink, fabricated of red resin, runs in one
long unit through the wall between the men's and women's restrooms.
</P>
<P>
   The users are separated but can pass the soap back and forth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to flirt a little and create some tension,'' said
Liz Diller of Diller and Scofidio, the architects who designed the
restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Other new sinks around the city are made of anything but white
porcelain. Metrazur in Grand Central Terminal has just opened with
handmade brass sinks with perforated covers, modeled on the compact
ones once used on trains. The sinks were commissioned by Tsao &AMP;
McKown.
</P>
<P>
   Thalia, in the theater district, has a series of colored basins
that are meant to ``continue the theme of colorful flavors'' from
the dining room, said Martin Jerry, who designed the restaurant
with Toby Haines.
</P>
<P>
   The old-fashioned stone basins at Mercer Kitchen and the
eight-foot shallow marble sink at Daniel are examples that were
ahead of the trend.
</P>
<P>
   More are on the way. The new Rosa Mexicano near Lincoln Center
will have sinks with rose petals embedded in clear acrylic bowls,
designed by David Rockwell. A stone basin that will look something
like a fountain in a village is being installed at the new Greek
restaurant Avra, in Manhattan's East 50s. At the new Sea Grill in
Rockefeller Center, Adam Tihany has designed a big Corian trough
like a communal sink.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bathrooms are no longer utilitarian,'' he said. ``They are an
extension of the design.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
