<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-18 16:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9293 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-NYT &LR;      01-18 0485
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BUSY MAN'S INDULGENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MARK BITTMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Back in the old days, when I thought no steps were
too many in a recipe, I made a wonderful roasted monkfish with meat
sauce. It was an understated dish, but absurdly tiresome to cook.
</P>
<P>
   The sauce alone was a reduction that began with meat bones,
continued with roasted vegetables and required a total of four or
five steps over two days. The result was delicious, but so ordinary
looking that only the best-trained palates ever picked up on how
ridiculously complex it was.
</P>
<P>
   When my children were born, this kind of dish fell out of my
repertory as quickly as sleeping through the night. But the concept
is a solid one. Monkfish, sometimes called ``poor man's lobster''
but better described as ``veal of the sea,'' has a meaty texture
and mild flavor that makes it the perfect foil for a deep, rich
sauce.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge was how to update the dish and make it possible to
prepare in 40 minutes rather than 40 hours.
</P>
<P>
   The obvious shortcut was canned stock. But when I reduced beef
stock to a glossy sauce, it was too salty and one-dimensional. I
could taste beef (a mild but pleasant surprise), but the flavor
lacked depth.
</P>
<P>
   I thought back to the original process and remembered that the
complexity of roasted meat stocks, or of any stock for that matter,
comes not only from the long, slow cooking of meat and bones, but
also from the vegetables added to them.
</P>
<P>
   So I started by pan-roasting vegetables, just darkly browning
onion, carrot and celery in a little bit of butter, a process that
took less than 10 minutes. Next, I added a spoonful of tomato
paste, for smoothness, body and color (you don't really need it),
and finally a can of beef stock.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty minutes later I had my glaze, and although it did not
have the richness of my original work of art, no one I served both
to could tell the difference with any certainty. Water would not
work in place of beef broth _ you need the gelatin that only meat
can give _ but chicken broth would. In fact, when I made this with
homemade chicken broth, the sauce was paler but more flavorful.
</P>
<P>
   The monkfish itself is roasted with salt, pepper and a tiny bit
of olive oil, and its juices are added to the simmering sauce about
five minutes before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Large pieces of monkfish _ those weighing more than a pound _
should be split down the middle lengthwise to make two fillets
before cooking. And remove the thin membrane clinging to them
before cooking so it doesn't seize up and toughen. Just pull and
tug on it while cutting through it with a paring knife; you don't
have to be too compulsive, but try to get most of it off.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most whitefish, monkfish is not better when slightly
undercooked. It requires thorough cooking, to the point where it is
opaque and tender throughout.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
