<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEASE-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: HEY, STEVE CASE, GIVE ME A CALL: YOU'VE GOT MY MONEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DARYL LEASE   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   I wasn't quite sure what to make of the America Online merger
with Time Warner Inc. _ the thought of $165 billion changing hands
mostly made me woozy _ until I heard that Ted Turner, one of the
biggest shareholders in the transaction, had said the deal was as
exciting as the first time he had sex.
</P>
<P>
   I think we all have to agree that the shy, retiring Turner has
once again managed to put everything in perspective. This is indeed
as exciting to the rest of us as, yawn, the first time Ted Turner
had sex.
</P>
<P>
   Really now, what's all the commotion about? So what if this sale
creates another incomprehensibly huge media conglomerate that will
determine a large share of what will appear on our TVs, our
computers, our movie screens, our CD players and our coffee tables?
</P>
<P>
   So what if the deal is so big the existing incomprehensibly huge
media conglomerates can't figure out whether the sales price is
$165 billion (New York Times), $156.14 billion (Wall Street
Journal) or $183 billion (Washington Post)?
</P>
<P>
   So what if the new AOL Time Warner will be worth an estimated
$350 billion, which, I'm guessing, is more than the value of some
small continents? So what if this vast wealth will be controlled by
AOL founder Steve Case, whose greatest gift to modern American
culture thus far is the chat room?
</P>
<P>
   So what if this creates the possibility of an annual Christmas
special, simulcast on cable and online, featuring Fred Flintstone,
Wolf Blitzer, the Atlanta Braves, whoever's on the cover of People
magazine that month, and colorized, bootleg film of the first time
Ted Turner ever had sex (hey, this is the Internet)?
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, I'm underwhelmed. I'm much more worked up about a
merger now under way in Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   A little town called Halfway, it seems, has cut a deal with a
little Internet company called Half.com. This deal, I think, also
will have great big repercussions across this great, big, greedy
land of ours.
</P>
<P>
   According to Wired magazine, which _ who the devil can keep
track? _ may well be owned by AOL Time Warner, the Halfway town
council has voted to change the town's name to Half.com.
</P>
<P>
   To seal the deal, Half.com, a small e-commerce company in
Philadelphia, offered an array of goodies, including stock options
and (woo wee!) six months of subsidized Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   Halfway Mayor Dick Crow told Wired that the town, population
360, hopes the name-change will boost tourism. ``Being the first
`dot-com' city in America will ... introduce our rustic beauty to
the country,'' Crow crowed.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which chose Halfway after searching the Internet
for towns with ``half'' in their name, is hoping for big things,
too. ``It's a great opportunity for both sides,'' Joshua Kopelman,
the CEO of Half.com, said. ``We want to boost their tourism (and)
we get a level of attention and publicity and recognition as
`out-of-the-box' thinkers.''
</P>
<P>
   Kopelman points out the town's location is perfect. ``They're
within four miles of the 45th parallel, which makes it halfway
between the equator and the North Pole,'' he told Wired
``excitedly.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, some folks might quibble with whether it's appropriate for
a town to surrender its identity, its history, to a company in
exchange for cash and a little publicity.
</P>
<P>
   But that's in-the-box thinking. This is, as Steve Case says,
``the Internet Century.'' We've got to toss out our old,
fuddy-duddy, 20th century way of doing things and ask ourselves,
``Hey, how can I make a buck off this?''
</P>
<P>
   In that spirit, I've decided to join the mad dash for cash.
Herewith, I put all incomprehensibly huge conglomerates on notice
that I'd be happy to change my name to whatever they wish. I'll go
by Halfbaked.com, ``You've Got My Money,'' or _ oh, why not? _ Jane
Fonda.
</P>
<P>
   Admittedly, there's not much in this for the conglomerates,
except that I do write a lot of checks to pay my bills, so my name
_ their name _ would be widely circulated among other
incomprehensibly huge conglomerates.
</P>
<P>
   But it's a bargain. I'm not asking for $165 billion, or anything
ridiculous like that. We can flip the ``b'' to an ``m.'' Heck, at
this point, I'd be willing to settle for something much simpler
from the conglomerates: How about lower prices?
</P>
<P>
   (Daryl Lease is an editorial writer at the Herald-Tribune in
Sarasota, Fla., a member of The New York Times Regional Newspaper
Group. This article was distributed by The New York Times News
Service. Lease can be contacted at daryl.lease(AT)herald-trib.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-18-00 1649EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000118.0166 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-18 16:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9303 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      01-18 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     THE CONFEDERATE FLAG VS. SCHOOL VIOLENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARIANNE MEANS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Martin Luther King's birthday was celebrated Monday
in a variety of appropriate ways honoring his nonviolent crusade
for civil rights, from the massive rally in South Carolina
protesting the Confederate battle flag to special community service
projects in cities across the country.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton and the Rev. Jesse Jackson used the occasion
to jointly promote a new administration program that would give
additional tax credits to businesses that invest in the nation's
poorest areas, which are often black ghettos. Jackson, a fringe
figure in the National Association for the Advancement of Colored
People's boycott of South Carolina for flying the Confederate flag
over its statehouse, also spoke at the rally and vowed to spread
the boycott to Georgia, which incorporates the confederate symbol
into its state flag.
</P>
<P>
   But Jackson, a former presidential candidate who is arguably the
best-known African-American in public life, has spent more energy
hyping a cause that King would undoubtedly have disapproved.
Jackson led a rally marking King's birthday in Decatur, Ill., last
weekend on behalf of six black students who were expelled from high
school there for a brawl in the bleachers that terrified hundreds
of fans at a school football game.
</P>
<P>
   As rallies go, this was peanuts, attracting only a few hundred
supporters. The cause isn't worth it and Jackson ought to drop it.
</P>
<P>
   But he is trying to turn the incident into a racial issue,
claiming that such punishment is unfairly meted out more often to
blacks than to whites. He points to statistics that indicate a
higher percentage of African-American students were penalized last
year by several big city schools than were white students.
</P>
<P>
   Such statistics, however, do not prove racism. All they prove is
that schools are getting tougher on students who disrupt classrooms
and student activities, take guns to school, peddle drugs and
terrify their peers. This is not about racial discrimination. This
is about controlling and trying to end violence in schools.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson should be preaching individual accountability for
actions that hurt others, not defending thugs on the basis of their
skin color. King was willing to go to jail for his beliefs but
Jackson doesn't want the brawling students to be disciplined for
their violence. In this instance, he makes a mockery of his
mentor's message of peace and dignity.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Michael McCuskey ruled last week that the
Decatur school board had the right to expel the students involved
in the fight that sent terrified football fans fleeing and that
left eight people wounded. The judge said the melee stemmed from a
confrontation between members of two rival gangs; this was no
innocent fistfight but one gang seeking revenge by attacking a
student from the rival group.
</P>
<P>
   The frightening scene was taped by a parent and repeatedly
replayed for the nation on television. This was clearly not
acceptable, normal teen-age behavior that could be ignored. Noting
that the school board had never discussed the students' race, the
judge said he was ruling on the case at hand and not upon
``statistical speculation.''
</P>
<P>
   School boards nationwide have been cracking down on miscreants
to reassure parents and students that it is safe to get an
education. The Decatur board and others have adopted zero-tolerance
policies toward violence of any kind. Sometimes this has led to
overzealous enforcement, such as punishing a student for bringing a
nail-clipper to class, but it sends a strong message to students
that they will be held accountable for wild behavior that scares or
harms others.
</P>
<P>
   It is baffling that Jackson doesn't get this. He called
McCuskey's ruling a ``disgrace'' and threatened to appeal the court
decision.
</P>
<P>
   This is nuts. It's a ``disgrace'' to be concerned for the safety
and security of the peaceful majority of students who deserve a
right to attend school events without fear?
</P>
<P>
   During Jackson's first protests against the expulsions, he said
the issue was not about race but fairness, portraying the students
as victims of ``a national intolerance of our kids'' rather than as
the chronic truants and bullies they really were. At last weekend's
rally, however, he tried to transcend the unattractive individual
trees by dragging in the whole forest, claiming zero-tolerance
school policies were discriminatory because they supposedly affect
black students disproportionately.
</P>
<P>
   This will not fly. And speaking of flying, Jackson ought to
concentrate on something that does have public resonance, that
offensive Confederate flag in South Carolina. It was hoisted in
1962 to protest the civil rights movement and waves over the state
Capitol, implying official approval of the slavery policy that
provoked the civil war.
</P>
<P>
   But the NAACP seized the leadership on this one, and Jackson is
left with a marginal role, trying to expand the protests to
Georgia. His problem is that he'd rather star in a bad cause than
be a bit player in a meaningful one.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address
means(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-18-00 1654EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000118.0167 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-18 17:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9307 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-WINTER-STEWS-ART-2TAK     01-18 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINTER-STEWS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VEGETABLE STEWS HEARTY ENOUGH FOR MEAT LOVERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By MELISSA CLARK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Almost by definition, stew means meat. Beef, veal and
lamb are the usual foundation of stews, the heartiest food of
winter. But lately, chefs around New York have been creating
intensely flavored stews made with vegetables only. And not just
vegetarians are ordering them.
</P>
<P>
   At Prune in the East Village, Gabrielle Hamilton says she
includes vegetable and bean ragouts on her menu because they are
what she likes to eat. ``I'm a serious meat lover, but I also love
to make a meal out of nothing but vegetables,'' Ms. Hamilton said.
Stews are an obvious one-dish solution.
</P>
<P>
   The trick with vegetable stews is to add as much flavor as
possible to seasonal ingredients, making them heartier and more
satisfying, though based on vegetable broths, rather than beef or
chicken stock. Spices, and plenty of them, are the key. Roasting
also intensifies the vegetable flavor and adds an illusion of
meatiness.
</P>
<P>
   Prune's menu changes every few weeks, but it now includes an
oniony stew of flageolets and chanterelles, enhanced with leeks and
thyme, and a fragrant chickpea stew with North African spices.
</P>
<P>
   At Five Points, Marc Meyer serves a stew of roasted carrots,
onions and turnips with chickpea vegetable puree and risotto
fritters spiced with cardamom. At 21, Eric Blauberg uses
traditional saffron in a bouillabaisse of vegetables like fennel,
artichokes, celeriac, broccoli rab, tomatoes and zucchini, instead
of shellfish, and serves it with classic rouille on toasts.
</P>
<P>
   At Heartbeat, Michel Nishan makes a squash-based winter stew
seasoned with raz al hanout, a North African mixture usually made
with cumin, coriander, ginger, turmeric, cardamom, nutmeg,
cinnamon, cayenne and rosebuds. The stew itself is served inside a
large roasted Hubbard squash. As portions are ladled out, slices of
the squash are cut from the rim and sprinkled with raz el hanout
and fresh herbs like chives and mint. The spices set off the
natural sweetness of the squash, while adding depth of flavor and a
touch of heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a terrific banquet dish, but takes a little finesse to
serve,'' Nishan said.
</P>
<P>
   Both he and Meyer roast some of the vegetables in their stews
(375 degrees until they are tender). Winter root vegetables, like
parsnips, celeriac, turnips, rutabagas and carrots, as well as
winter squash and onions, caramelize in high heat, adding still
another layer of flavor.
</P>
<P>
   At Quantum, Joseph Fortunato roasts tomatoes at this time of
year to concentrate their less-than-summery flavor. He then simmers
them with chickpeas and garlic in vegetable broth to make a robust
stew.
</P>
<P>
   In general, vegetable stews are made like the meat versions. A
base of chopped vegetables is sauteed, then liquid is added, and
the mixture is simmered until soft. This part can take as little as
20 minutes, compared with hours for beef. Starchy ingredients like
rice or dried beans take longer to cook, but they will help thicken
the broth to make what is essentially a rich sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Chefs choose either harmonious vegetables _ all from the cabbage
family, for instance _ or mix-and-match flavors, as with peppery
mustard greens and sweet onions. While many stew-making chefs limit
themselves to seasonal produce, Odette Fada of San Domenico
combines fava beans, peas, artichokes and asparagus with wine and
olive oil in a mellow stew garnished with sharp, salty pecorino
Romano. Called scafata, it is traditionally a spring dish served
when the first new vegetables appear in the markets, but with
high-quality frozen fava beans and imported vegetables it also
works out of season.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Telepan of Judson Grill prefers the seasonal approach,
because he thinks sturdy vegetables are better suited to cold
weather. His vegetable stew reflects the Greenmarkets: turnips,
cabbage, carrots, potatoes, parsnips, celeriac and leeks.
</P>
<P>
   Diane Forley of Verbena takes a different approach with the
stews on her vegetable tasting menu. She often focuses on one
assertive vegetable and builds the flavors around it. In her wild
mushroom stew, for instance, she starts with earthy portobellos,
hen of the wood, shiitakes and other wild mushrooms and accentuates
their flavors with fresh greens and herbs like spinach, chickweed
and parsley. Amaranth adds body and absorbs the dark, rich broth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get a lot of vegetable eaters in here, but they are not
necessarily vegetarians,'' she said. ``It's mostly people who want
to have a vegetable option, even if they do end up ordering the
meat.''
</P>
<P>
   (STORY ENDS HERE. RECIPES FOLLOW IN 2ND TAKE)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   WINTER VEGETABLE STEW
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Michel Nishan, Heartbeat
</P>
<P>
   Time: about 3 hours  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup raz al hanout spice mixture (available at specialty
markets)
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons raw cane sugar
</P>
<P>
   { tablespoon kosher or coarse sea salt
</P>
<P>
   } teaspoon freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 6 to 8 pound Hubbard squash
</P>
<P>
   10 cipolini
</P>
<P>
   10 red pearl onions
</P>
<P>
   { peeled butternut squash, cut into bite-size pieces (about 4
cups)
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   { peeled rutabaga, cut into bite-size pieces (about a cup)
</P>
<P>
   1 medium peeled turnip, cut into bite-size pieces (about a cup)
</P>
<P>
   2 large Peruvian potatoes, peeled and cut into 1-inch chunks
</P>
<P>
   3 to 4 large Yukon Gold potatoes, peeled and cut into 1-inch
chunks
</P>
<P>
   { leek, thinly sliced (white part and one inch of green)
</P>
<P>
   3 toasted cinnamon sticks
</P>
<P>
   { jalapeno pepper, seeded and minced
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon freshly grated nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   Squash sauce (see recipe)
</P>
<P>
   \ cup coarsely chopped fresh herbs
</P>
<P>
   4 to 6 slices Russian black bread or walnut raisin bread.
</P>
<P>
   1. Heat oven to 350 degrees. In a bowl, combine raz al hanout,
sugar, coarse salt and pepper. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   2. Cut top off Hubbard squash as a lid. Seed and scrape inside
of squash clean. Wash, and reserve seeds. Rub lid and inside of
squash with half of spice mixture. Place lid and squash, cut side
down, on baking sheet. Cover with foil. Bake for 45 minutes. Remove
lid. Return squash to oven, and bake for 45 minutes more, until
tender.
</P>
<P>
   3. Meanwhile, place cipolini and pearl onions on a baking sheet,
and roast for 15 minutes. Spread butternut squash cubes on a
separate baking sheet, sprinkle lightly with 1 tablespoon olive oil
and roast for 20 minutes. On another baking sheet, arrange rutabaga
and turnip cubes in two separate piles. Sprinkle each lightly with
{ tablespoon olive oil, and roast, taking turnips out after 15
minutes and leaving rutabaga to continue for 10 minutes more. Peel
roasted pearl onions, and cut cipolini onions in half.
</P>
<P>
   4. Put potatoes in a steamer basket over simmering water, and
steam for 10 minutes, until slightly softened.
</P>
<P>
   5. In a large pot over medium heat, warm remaining olive oil.
Add onions, leeks, cinnamon sticks, jalapeno and nutmeg, and saute
until leeks start to soften. Add squash, rutabaga and turnip, and
heat through. Add all of the squash sauce and potatoes, and bring
to a simmer. Cook for 20 minutes, until all vegetables are tender.
</P>
<P>
   6. Meanwhile, spread Hubbard squash on a baking sheet, sprinkle
with olive oil and salt, and toast in oven until they start to pop,
about 10 minutes. Set aside to cool.
</P>
<P>
   7. When vegetables are done, turn off heat, and add fresh herbs.
To serve, ladle stew into cavity of Hubbard squash. Toast bread,
and place a slice in each warmed bowl. Ladle stew into bowl.
Sprinkle spice mix on rim of squash. With carving knife, cut a thin
slice of squash horizontally across rim. Place slice on stew in
bowl. Sprinkle rim with more spice mix, and the stew with more
fresh herbs. Repeat with remaining bowls. Garnish with seeds.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 to 6 servings.
</P>
<P>
   SQUASH SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   Time: 45 minutes  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons grapeseed or extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1{ cups peeled and cubed butternut squash
</P>
<P>
   \ cup diced onion
</P>
<P>
   4 cups vegetable stock
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Raw cane sugar to taste
</P>
<P>
   Raz al hanout to taste.
</P>
<P>
   In a saucepan, warm oil over medium heat. Add squash and onion,
and saute until onion is soft, 2 to 3 minutes. Add stock, bring to
a simmer and cook until squash is soft, about 15 minutes. Season to
taste with salt, pepper, sugar and raz al hanout.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: about a quart.
</P>
<P>
   SCAFATA
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Odette Fada, San Domenico
</P>
<P>
   Time: 40 minutes  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   { cup extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   { dry white wine
</P>
<P>
   4 baby artichokes, trimmed and cut into eighths
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped onion
</P>
<P>
   6 stalks asparagus, trimmed and cut in }-inch lengths
</P>
<P>
   2 scallions, sliced
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup peeled fava beans (see note)
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup fresh shelled peas
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Thinly sliced pecorino Romano cheese.
</P>
<P>
   1. Combine oil and wine in a pan at medium heat. Add artichokes
and onions. Bring to boil. Cook, partly covered, 5 minutes. Add
asparagus and scallions. Cook 3 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   2. Lower heat, and stir in fava beans, peas and salt and pepper
to taste. Let mixture simmer, partly covered, for about 10 minutes,
or until artichokes are tender. Serve topped with pecorino Romano
cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 2 servings.
</P>
<P>
   Note: Fresh fava beans are not in season, but frozen peeled
beans are sold at Kalustyan's, 123 Lexington Ave. (28th Street),
$2.99 for 14 ounces; (212) 685-3451. They are also at Sahadi's, 187
Atlantic Ave., Brooklyn, $1.35 for 14 ounces; (718) 624-4550.
</P>
