<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PAYNE-STEWART-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     AZINGER REMEMBERS PAYNE STEWART AT PEBBLE BEACH 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service subscribers)  
 &HT;     By BRIAN MURPHY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALO ALTO, Calif. _ One week ago, Paul Azinger sat alone in a
room, his head in his hands, his heart in his stomach.
</P>
<P>
   He had just seen the practice green at the Sony Open in
Honolulu, filled with professional golfers laughing, chatting,
chipping and putting. Full of life. Which was the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looked like everybody had forgotten,'' Azinger said. ``Life
was going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, life was going on without Payne Stewart. Life was going on
without one of the PGA Tour's most popular players. Life was going
on without one of Azinger's closest buddies, who died last year in
a plane crash that brought a premature end to a 42-year-old life
filled with joy.
</P>
<P>
   All of which led Azinger to leave the practice green. He stared
at the floor in a room off the pro shop, wondering if he, too,
could go on. It was Azinger, remember, who gave the most memorable
eulogy at Stewart's emotional funeral last year. It was Azinger who
put on a cap and argyle socks at the service, in tribute to the
outrageous fashion sense of his departed friend. It was Azinger who
wondered why no one was still mourning.
</P>
<P>
   Then he went and did the best possible thing to bring back the
memory of Stewart: He won his first PGA Tour event in seven years,
and dedicated the win to, among others, the Stewart family and
Payne's widow, Tracey.
</P>
<P>
   And in a gesture rich with personal meaning, he boarded a
red-eye flight to California to show up at a press conference
advancing next month's AT&AMP;T Pebble Beach National Pro-Am. The press
conference, held at Stanford Golf Course on Monday, always features
the defending champion.
</P>
<P>
   The defending champion is Payne Stewart, who had committed to
attend the media day just before his death. Sitting in Stewart's
chair Monday was Paul Azinger, keeping alive the memory.
</P>
<P>
   That Azinger overcame cancer in his back and chemotherapy from a
1993 diagnosis was secondary, the golfer said. More important to
him was the remembrance of things past, and of Stewart'spassing.
It was Azinger who called the promoters of the popular tournament
formerly known as the Crosby and volunteered to make the long
journey. Azinger arrived _ at 5 a.m. on the mainland after his
emotional win in Hawaii _ to stand in Stewart's place.
</P>
<P>
   ``That accident changed the way I look at life,'' Azinger said.
``I always saw the world through rose-colored glasses, even through
cancer. I was confident I'd survive cancer. I was very emotional in
January of 1994 when I saw the tour go on without me. But I knew
I'd get better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought about Tracey Stewart (on Sunday), at the realization
that the tour is going on. They're similar events, but in a much
worse way. The tour is going on without Payne Stewart.''
</P>
<P>
   Memories stay alive in the eeriest of ways. Stewart so loved
Pebble Beach that Tracey Stewart told Azinger in a Monday morning
phone chat that Stewart would have played his last round ever at
Pebble if he had had a choice. Now, not only will Stewart's name be
remembered during the Pro-Am from Feb. 3-6, but also during the
U.S. Open in June, also to be held at Pebble Beach. Stewart, after
all, would have been the defending champion at that event, too.
</P>
<P>
   Azinger began the healing process last week when he vanished
from the practice green in Honolulu. A friend came in and asked if
Azinger were all right.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I'm not all right,'' Azinger said. ``It's like everybody's
forgotten. They just went on.''
</P>
<P>
   The friend told Azinger that his fellow pros hadn't forgotten,
and would always remember Stewart on the inside.
</P>
<P>
   Strengthened by the thought, Azinger went back outside and was
greeted by well-wishers. Azinger was buoyed by the moment, and went
on to play the best post-cancer golf of his career.
</P>
<P>
   Then he came to the Bay Area on Monday and stood in his buddy's
place, stronger and sadder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will never look at the world through rose-colored glasses
again,'' Azinger said. ``I know that now, really, there is the
potential for a lot of sadness in life. Yes, there's potential for
happiness, too, but I thought of Tracey Stewart (on Sunday), and
that life is going on without her husband.''
</P>
</TEXT>
