<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-18 17:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9318 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-COOKING-DUCK-ART-3TAK     01-18 0962
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COOKING-DUCK-ART-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUCK, DEMYSTIFIED: MASTERING THE WHOLE BIRD 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Four photos (NYT8, -11, -12, -13) were sent on Jan. 18 to
NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(Editors: recipes and optional sidebar at end of article)  
 (bl)  
 By AMANDA HESSER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   I laid two halves of a duck skin side down in a cold pan with a
few unpeeled cloves of garlic and some thyme, covered the pan,
placed it over low heat and went into another room to read.
</P>
<P>
   An hour later, I turned the pieces.
</P>
<P>
   And an hour after that, I lifted out four of the most heavenly
pieces of duck I have ever tasted. The slow, enclosed heat had
steamed the meat and softened it like confit. The fat had rendered
and, along with the generous amount of salt I had seasoned the duck
with, had turned the skin chestnut brown with delicious,
caramelized edges.
</P>
<P>
   I crisped the skin in some hot oil, and tasted it right on my
cutting board. It was better than many restaurant dishes, and I had
actually gotten past a table of contents while making it. My only
regret was that I hadn't learned to cook duck this way sooner.
</P>
<P>
   Duck is long beyond its days as the stuffy fare of French
restaurants, and has taken on life in all forms on restaurant
menus. In fact, there are few menus without duck. Slivers of confit
are cradled in spring rolls; wild duck is roasted rare and paired
with things like berries and root vegetables; duck breasts are
turned into a salty, satiny ``prosciutto''; there's even duck
sausage.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, it's hardly a mainstream household food. I've never
been served duck at someone's house, and I rarely cook it at home
myself. Home cooks seem to regard it in the same way they do a
souffle: an appealing idea but a hassle to make.
</P>
<P>
   Truth be told, duck at home is often a disappointment. Most
cooks roast a duck like a chicken. Its skin browns. It cooks
through. But it is as tough as leather next to a roasted chicken.
</P>
<P>
   Duck needs to be treated differently in order to get the meat
tender and moist, and the skin thin and crisp like a tuile. And as
I discovered recently by cooking ducks _ many, many ducks _ there
are a number of ways to achieve this, and none are the daunting,
messy tasks they threaten to be. As Julia Child, who taught many
Americans which way is up on a duck, said by telephone last week,
it's more interesting and much more forgiving than chicken.
</P>
<P>
   I couldn't agree more. But I would also add that the two are
barely comparable. The price difference alone could tell you that:
a roasting chicken is about $1.39 a pound; duck is $2.99 a pound.
But duck is not just fattier; it is actually a red meat. It has a
deep, richly flavored flesh that can be served rare or well done.
And its skin, lined with a healthy layer of fat, crisps in a way
that lean chicken never can.
</P>
<P>
   Restaurant chefs tend not to roast it, instead sauteeing the
breasts rare and often roasting or braising the legs until they are
tender. If they do roast it, they usually roast it for just a short
while, and then remove the breasts while they are still rare and
return the legs to the oven to finish cooking.
</P>
<P>
   At home, this method is simply ridiculous. No one is going to
take a 400-degree duck from the oven, grab hold of it and carve off
the breast meat. Besides, I don't agree that this is the best way
to eat this bird. When duck is cooked slowly, its fat renders out
entirely. As it does, it runs over and through the meat, cooking it
and achieving the kind of succulence lamb shanks have when braised
for a long time. As the fat melts from below the skin, the skin
toasts and crisps, for a great skin without having to sear it in a
pan or blast it under a hot broiler.
</P>
<P>
   Which is how I came to the version braised over the stove.
Spencer Hugh Levy, the chef at Spencer, in New York near Irving
Place, prefers to begin duck breasts and legs on the stove over low
heat. He renders the fat, and then finishes the breasts in the
oven, serving them medium rare, and braises the legs.
</P>
<P>
   Jacques Pepin demonstrates a similar method in his book ``The
Art of Cooking'' (Alfred A. Knopf, 1988). He first cooks the duck
pieces over medium heat to render the fat, and then covers them and
braises them over low heat until they are cooked through, letting
the heat from the fat steam the meat.
</P>
<P>
   I cooked mine longer and more slowly, until the meat was very
tender. And I left it covered the entire time, eliminating the
typical grease-fest of open cooking.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, though, it was not the only way to achieve the
results I wanted.
</P>
<P>
   In New York City, Union Square Cafe, one of the few restaurants
to roast its ducks whole, without interruption, has served the same
roasted duck dish for more than 11 years. I figured the method was
worth a try. Michael Romano, the chef, roasts the duck until it is
nearly done, and then lets it cool and quarters it. These steps can
be done up to a day ahead of time. To serve, he heats a saute pan,
puts the pieces in, skin side down, to begin crisping them, and
then covers them and transfers them to a hot oven to heat through.
</P>
<P>
   It's foolproof. When I did it at home, the meat was tender, not
meltingly soft. But the skin was as dark as a hazelnut and crunched
like a potato chip. And there was no worry of having to wrestle the
carcass while carving it as people were waiting at the table.
</P>
<P>
   A friend mentioned the slow-roasting method. I liked the image
of putting the duck in the oven and letting it do its thing. I
modeled my method after one by Greg Sonnier, the chef at both
Gabrielle and Gamay Bistro, in New Orleans, who keeps slow-roasted
duck on the menus.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
