<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-18 17:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9321 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-COOKING-DUCK-ART-2NDT     01-18 0997
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COOKING-DUCK-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: the menus.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   His recipe, with a sauce of orange juice, sherry and soy sauce,
was a little more complex than what I was looking for. I just
stuffed the duck with root vegetables _ carrots, turnips, garlic,
shallots, beets _ and placed it in a roasting pan, surrounded by
more vegetables. Those inside helped keep the breast moist; those
outside roasted slowly in the fat.
</P>
<P>
   After covering the duck with foil, I began roasting it in a very
hot oven _ 500 degrees _ for 10 minutes, and then dropped the heat
to a temperature even lower than what I use to toast nuts, to 300
degrees. Then I roasted it for four and a half hours, the last hour
without the foil, to crisp the skin.
</P>
<P>
   What came out of the oven was a revelation. The duck had nearly
collapsed under its own weight. Its skin had given up most of its
fat and had reduced to a thin, chewy layer, the color of caramel.
The meat, moist and slippery like buttery rillettes, fell from the
bone. The vegetables had cooked tender in the duck fat, shrinking a
little. I had hardly done a thing, and my oven did not look as if a
fat bomb had exploded in it.
</P>
<P>
   But divine as it was, it had a rival.
</P>
<P>
   I had called Nina Simonds, the author of several books on
Chinese cooking, including ``Asian Wraps'' (William Morrow, $23),
to ask her how to make Peking duck, prepared with the skin
separated from the flesh and the entire duck coated in maltose
syrup and then hung to roast. It's difficult to do at home, she
told me, and instead she suggested a Sichuan dish called ``crispy
skin duck.'' The name was all I needed to hear.
</P>
<P>
   The duck is marinated in rice wine, scallions, ginger, star
anise and Sichuan peppercorns. Then it is steamed whole in a
covered wok for nearly two hours. As it steams, its fat melts,
falling into the water, and the meat relaxes until it weeps.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, the challenge is to refrain from eating it as is
(it could, in fact, be served like this without the skin). Steaming
forces the aroma of scallions, ginger and peppercorns to permeate
the bird like a vanilla bean infusing warm cream.
</P>
<P>
   I forged on. Ms. Simonds' recipe next instructs you to coat the
entire duck in soy sauce and cornstarch, and then to fry it whole
in peanut oil. ``Traditionally, it's deep-fried twice, and it gets
so crisp,'' she said. ``But who wants to bother with that?''
</P>
<P>
   Who wants to bother with that once? This seemed not only
dubious, but also frighteningly messy. I did just half the bird.
</P>
<P>
   It was delicious, indeed, and incredibly crunchy. But the mess
was as awful as I had imagined. My sofa across the room still
smells of duck a week and a half later.
</P>
<P>
   For the remaining half, I went back to the Union Square Cafe
method of pan-roasting it at the last minute. As the pieces touched
down on the pan, they sizzled and immediately began crisping and
browning. And by the time they emerged from the oven, they looked
as if they'd been lacquered.
</P>
<P>
   The duck was perfect: the skin was crisp and deliciously salty,
the meat was moist, and its rich flavor had melded completely with
the scallion, ginger and peppercorns.
</P>
<P>
   And I was speechless. What  &UR; was &LR;  I doing all those years
roasting duck like chicken?
</P>
<P>
   (STORY ENDS HERE. RECIPES AND OPTIONAL SIDEBAR FOLLOW)
</P>
<P>
   SLOW-ROASTED DUCK
</P>
<P>
   Technique adapted from Greg Sonnier, Gabrielle, New Orleans
</P>
<P>
   Time: about 5 hours
</P>
<P>
   1 5-pound duck, rinsed and dried
</P>
<P>
   Salt
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   10 sprigs thyme
</P>
<P>
   10 cloves garlic, skin on
</P>
<P>
   } pound (about 6) thin carrots, trimmed
</P>
<P>
   } pound turnips, peeled and cut into wedges
</P>
<P>
   } pound golden beets, peeled and cut into wedges
</P>
<P>
   4 shallots, skin on and halved
</P>
<P>
   1. Preheat oven to 500 degrees. Season duck generously inside
and out with salt and pepper. Put 1 or 2 pieces each of thyme,
garlic, carrots, turnips, beets and shallots, in cavity. Truss
duck; set in large casserole dish or medium roasting pan. Scatter
rest of ingredients and neck around duck; season with salt and
pepper. Cover loosely with foil. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2. Roast duck for 10 minutes, lower temperature to 300 degrees
and roast for 3{ hours, basting vegetables and duck with pan juices
and skimming off fat occasionally. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   3. Remove foil. Take out vegetables and neck, and set aside;
roast duck for 1 more hour (if vegetables are not tender, continue
roasting until they are). Skin should be well browned and crisp;
the meat, extremely tender. Transfer duck to cutting board. Skim
fat off pan juices; add water to pan, if necessary, to make { cup.
Bring juices to boil, adjust seasoning, and transfer to serving
bowl. Reheat vegetables and neck in baking dish in oven. Carefully
carve duck (meat may fall off bone), adding vegetables from cavity
to those in pan. Serve with pan juices and vegetables. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 3 servings. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BRAISED DUCK
</P>
<P>
   Time: 2{ hours
</P>
<P>
   Salt
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 4{-to-5-pound duck, rinsed, dried and cut in half (neck and
backbone reserved for broth)
</P>
<P>
   4 sprigs thyme
</P>
<P>
   3 cloves garlic, skin left on and lightly crushed. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Salt and pepper duck generously on both sides. Place halves,
skin side down, in large saute pan (preferably seasoned cast-iron
or nonstick) or 2 medium saute pans. Wedge thyme and garlic under
skin. Cover pan with lid or foil; place over low heat. Braise for 1
hour (duck should crackle and sizzle gently; skin should be golden
and crisp; most fat should be rendered). Turn duck; cover pan.
Braise for 1 more hour, until duck bottom is well browned and meat
very tender. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2. Remove duck to cutting board; cut halves in half. Reserve fat
from pan. In clean saute pan, heat 2 tablespoons fat (if there is
not enough, use canola oil) over medium-high heat. Place duck
pieces skin side down, and saute for 3 to 5 minutes, just until
skin is crisp and dark. Transfer to dish, and serve. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 2 to 3 servings. &QL;
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
