<SLUG> BC-AOL-TIME-NEWSHOUR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITIC'S NOTEBOOK: WHEN CORPORATE SYNERGY BECOMES MANIFEST
DESTINY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was a scoop for Jim Lehrer. Within hours of the announcement
of America Online's agreement to purchase Time Warner, the two
chief mergees showed up for an interview. (In an image reversal,
America Online's Steven Case was the one with the necktie, Time
Warner's Gerald Levin the one without, inviting speculation that
the $165 billion purchase price had included his tie.)
</P>
<P>
   Instead of further torturing the technological ramifications of
this marriage of the Internet to an entertainment and information
empire and its implications for the stock market, which had been
occupying the cable business channels since the announcement,
Lehrer, in his customary common-sense way, wanted to know what the
merger meant for the mere television viewer.
</P>
<P>
   What difference would it make, for instance, to the PBS
``NewsHour'' fan who has found that an hour a day of discussion of
serious events was worth more than the hours and hours of
repetitious CNN reporting, commentary and Larry King, or to people,
if there are any, who can't get excited at the prospect of buying
twice as much stuff in half the time with a click or two?
</P>
<P>
   Well, what he learned was that the merger had nothing to do with
money and power. No, it was a public service, a liberation for
consumers that promised to enrich all our lives. ``This is not
trying to have control for some self-serving reason,'' said Case.
Levin was reading from the same inspirational script. ``In
business,'' he explained, ``you can have a social commitment.'' He
went on, ``This company is going to operate in the public
interest.'' He went further, ``We want to make a better world.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a revivalist sing-along, lacking only the tribute to a
higher power. Case said he was committed to creating ``the most
respected company in the world.'' Levin was carried away by a
strange image of gobbling up all the information and entertainment
that he foresees flooding America, digitally or otherwise: ``I want
to ingest it'' and ``embrace it'' and ``consume it.'' He sounded
like a commercial for Pepcid AC. He did his own diagnosis and
discovered that his genetic makeup assured ``first-quality
journalism.''
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to be a cynic to have trouble swallowing such
image-embellishing claims. These advertisements for themselves,
after all, come from men running institutions with a record. Time
Warner's record these days ranges from respectable but rarely
outstanding news coverage that plays hard on diversions like Monica
Lewinsky. As for entertainment, it swings between the best of HBO
and plenty of pop clutter. (With all appreciation for ``The
Sopranos,'' only in the dim world of television could that show
have created quite such a sensation.)
</P>
<P>
   As for the Internet, with its grand vision as a fount of
information, for America Online subscribers it turns out to be
mainly an engine of marketing. The special appeal of Time Warner to
Case is, he confessed, ``the power of established media brands and
the customer relationships that those brands represent.'' Will the
Internet's much hailed role as an idea exchange be more stimulating
than a typical cable call-in show? What can the vaunted promise
that consumers will now be able to make their own choices really
mean as long as the menus are cooked up by Time Warner and America
Online?
</P>
<P>
   In trying to imagine the secret, tough, complex, high-powered
negotiations that must have gone into their deal, it is difficult
to see Levin and Case, not to mention their advisers from Salomon
Smith Barney, Morgan Stanley Dean Witter and other bottom-line
professionals, pausing to worry about pledges of service to the
world. It was complicated enough to figure out how the assets and
the control should be shared without taking time out for mutual
flattery.
</P>
<P>
   The quotations from lesser corporate players prove more to the
point. Executives regaled reporters with the prospect of CNN's
cashing in on America Online's 22 million subscribers and America
Online cashing in on CNN's ``global brand,'' with Time Warner's
enhanced ability to deliver saleable music online and America
Online's ability to carry movies and other features concocted by
Time Warner. Such are the calculations of a culture in which
everything is merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   It is also easy to appreciate the enthusiasm of Ted Turner, Time
Warner's vice chairman and its biggest shareholder, who said,
``When I cast my vote for 100 million shares, I did it with as much
excitement as I felt the first time I made love some 42 years
ago.'' The rise in Time Warner stock immediately after the merger
announcement brought him a paper profit of $2.53 billion.
</P>
<P>
   But what will all this do for Lehrer's viewers? Will the visions
being floated by Case and Levin include the enrichment and
upgrading of the nation's sorry array of television offerings? Will
the new megacompany find it economically inviting to compete with
``NewsHour'' in an upscale interview program? Will it find room for
unprofitable documentaries? Will it take more chances on innovative
entertainments?
</P>
<P>
   Worries have been voiced by the merger's critics that the
movement toward ever larger conglomerates will result in more
uniformity instead of the diversity that the Internet is supposed
to exemplify. But even if that does not happen, the Case-Levin duet
does not inspire confidence. In at least one respect the changes
they envision in the way information and entertainment are
delivered will probably come to pass: There will be more brand
names like Warner and Time, more readily available for Case to
promote. But nothing about this merger offers the likelihood of
higher-quality, pardon the expression, merchandise.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
