<BODY>
 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
the Page 1 of Wednesday, Jan. 19. The N.Y. Times News Service night
supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-INSPECTIONS (United Nations) _ The Security Council holds
showdown meeting over Kofi Annan's choice of Rolf Ekeus to head new
Iraq inspection team. Besides Russian and Chinese opposition,
France announces that it rejects the choice. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-ASSESS (Jerusalem) _ When Prime Minister Ehud Barak
first declared his ambitious intentions to juggle the Palestinian
and Syrian peace efforts simultaneously, he said he could keep both
balls in the air and prevent them from colliding. But that turns
out to be a contortionist's trick. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-SCANDAL (Berlin) _ Helmut Kohl, the former German
chancellor, on Tuesday resigned his post as honorary chairman of
the Christian Democrats after the party's leadership turned on him
with extraordinary vehemence and accused him of ``violating his
duties'' by refusing to name people who secretly gave him money. By
Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-CAMEL-FIGHTING (Selcuk, Turkey) _ The sporting season is
under way in western Turkey, and Hamza Akmese, 61, who has been in
the game for most of his life, furtively surveyed the competition
and decided he had nothing to worry about. ``My camel is strong,''
he said. ``He has a good body, good technique, and he knows how to
use his front legs for tripping. He's going to do fine today.'' By
Stephen Kinzer.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   DEBATES-RDP (Des Moines, Iowa) _ Not since 1998 have so many
candidates taken part in so many debates before the voting begins
in the Iowa caucuses. Now that the first round of encounters is
over -- the major Republican contenders participated in seven
debates; the Democrats held six -- politicians, academics and civic
groups all praised the process for elevating the discourse and
giving the public a genuine opportunity to observe the people
competing to be the next president. By Richard L. Berke and Robin
Toner.
</P>
<P>
   GIULIANI-MCCAIN (Undated) _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani rebuked the
New York Republican State Committee on Tuesday for trying to knock
Sen. John McCain off the presidential primary ballot in half of the
state, creating a new rift with party leaders he had otherwise been
courting in his bid for Senate. By Clifford J. Levy.
</P>
