<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Wednesday, Jan. 19, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(bl) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Heavy rain will once again batter western Oregon and portions of
northern California on Wednesday as a powerful jet stream
disturbance spirals into the Northwest Coast. Rainfall will locally
exceed an inch from north of San Francisco to south of Portland,
Ore. As the plume of moist air ascends the higher terrain of the
interior, the stage will be set for heavy snow in the southern
Cascades, Klamath and Sierra mountains, where totals could exceed 2
feet by Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   A tandem of jet stream disturbances will reach the Middle West
on Wednesday, causing a swath of inclement weather from the upper
Mississippi Valley to the northern Tennessee Valley. Several inches
of snow could whiten the ground across Minnesota, Wisconsin, Iowa
and Illinois on Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Farther south, a wedge of milder air riding up and over chillier
air near the ground will cause the snow to change to freezing rain
near the Ohio River. In the warmer air to the south, light rain is
likely near the Tennessee Valley. Wednesday night, the jet stream
disturbances will merge near Ohio, bringing snow to the central
Appalachians and Middle Atlantic states. Indeed, several inches of
snow could fall by morning in Washington, D.C., Philadelphia and
New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Abundant sun will cover New England on Wednesday as the gusty
breezes from the northwest relinquish their assault on the region.
Elsewhere, unseasonably warm conditions will persist in Texas and
the western Gulf Coast. Amid plentiful sun, afternoon readings will
surpass 80 degrees in many locations.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Icy Mixture  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Icy precipitation fell in the Carolinas on Tuesday morning as a
mound of cold air moved slowly to the south. In winter, almost all
precipitation begins as snow 10,000 to 20,000 feet aloft. In the
rainy areas of coastal South Carolina, a layer of mild air more
than 5,000 feet thick melted the falling flakes before they reached
the ground. Farther northwest, in some valleys where a shallow
layer of sub-freezing air clung to the ground, raindrops froze on
cold objects, causing an icy glaze. Elsewhere, a thin warm layer
aloft melted the flakes, but the drops refroze into pellets of ice
called sleet.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
