<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-18 17:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9335 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-WINE-TALK-ART-1STLD-W     01-18 1085
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-TALK-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINE TOO GOOD TO LET SLIP BY UNHERALDED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: France, Italy, Spain, Calif., Ore.) (Eds: CORRECTS price in last graf to $22, sted $15.) 
(ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can make purchase
by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By FRANK J. PRIAL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Over the course of time and columns, good wines come along that
seem to defy pigeonholing. Some don't fit into any category I'm
writing about at the moment; some don't fit into any category at
all. So they slip by unreported. Here are a few wines that deserved
a better fate.
</P>
<P>
   A HANDMADE FRENCH SYRAH
</P>
<P>
   The first is from the Languedoc, the ancient French region that
extends along the Mediterranean coast from the Rhone to Narbonne
and beyond. Historically the source of much of France's vin
ordinaire, it became, in the 1970s and 1980s, the scene of a major
agricultural revolution, as thousands of vineyard acres were
replanted with the so-called noble varieties _ cabernet, merlot and
chardonnay among them.
</P>
<P>
   The resulting wines were far better than what had come before,
but they were commercial wines, for the most part, produced on a
huge scale. More recently, small estates have begun to flourish in
the region, much as they do in Burgundy and the Rhone Valley. Many
of the winemakers have come from the Rhone, bringing their grape
varieties with them. Syrah is the favorite grape among the
newcomers.
</P>
<P>
   The Clos des Truffiers is an estate in the hill town of
St.-Pargoire, overlooking the city of Beziers and the
Mediterranean. The wine from the Clos is made from syrah vines
planted in the 1960s, long before the current vogue for the grape
in the Languedoc. In a region where big yields are expected from
vines, the 1997 Clos des Truffiers was made from an incredibly
small harvest of one ton an acre. The grapes were picked, sorted
and destemmed by hand and crushed by foot, still one of the
gentlest ways to extract the juice but not the bitterness of the
grapes.
</P>
<P>
   After 17 months in new oak, the wine was bottled unfiltered. It
is a rich, concentrated, altogether remarkable wine with layers of
flavor. Only 3,200 bottles were produced; if you can find one, it
will cost about $100.
</P>
<P>
   AN OUTSTANDING PINOT NOIR
</P>
<P>
   Argyle is one of those wine names without a modifier. It isn't
Argyle Cellars or Argyle Vineyards _ it's just Argyle. Actually,
it's the principal label of the Dundee Wine Co. in Dundee, Oregon,
and it has every right to stand on its own. A succession of
outstanding pinot noirs have appeared in recent years under the
Argyle label. Outstanding for quality and for price.
</P>
<P>
   I have been enjoying the 1996, a lighter-bodied and less intense
wine compared with the fine 1994 Oregon pinots. But great
Burgundies are often surprisingly light-bodied; one doesn't look
for zinfandel thickness in a good pinot noir. Not a wine for the
ages, this 1996 should probably be drunk over the next two or three
years. But at around $15, it offers the enjoyment of many a
Burgundy at twice the price.
</P>
<P>
   AN EXCEPTIONAL CABERNET
</P>
<P>
   Giorgio Grai is one of the legendary winemakers of Italy but is
almost unknown in this country. The late Sheldon Wassermann, who
wrote extensively about Grai in ``Italy's Noble Red Wines''
(Macmillan, 1991), once said: ``Giorgio is only interested in
making the wine. Selling it interests him not at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather like an appellate court judge, Giorgio Grai is rarely
involved in the early stages of winemaking. He has never owned
vineyards, but he does make wine, for many different cantine, or
wineries. For his own label he prefers to buy finished wines and
blend them. He is from the Alto Adige in the far north of Italy,
but he makes wine in Tuscany, the Piedmont and as far south as
Apulia.
</P>
<P>
   His cabernet sauvignon is considered by many Italians to be the
best produced in that country. It is full-bodied with classic
black-currant flavors, but its elegance and long finish are neither
Bordeaux-like nor Italian. It is an exceptional wine, and most
unusual. It, too, is difficult to find; around $30.
</P>
<P>
   A cabernet Grai makes for Marina Danieli, a winery in Friuli, is
in the Grai style but less intense and slightly easier to find. It
is the classic Bordeaux blend of cabernet sauvignon with cabernet
franc and petit verdot. The 1997 sells for about $10.
</P>
<P>
   A FULL-BODIED SPANISH MERLOT
</P>
<P>
   Vega Sindoa wines from Spain are almost unknown in this country,
but they won't be for long. Produced by Bodegas Nekeas in the
province of Navarre, they represent some of the best values in the
wine market, not just from Spain but from any wine-producing
region. With all the junky merlot around these days, this $10
bottle (as low as $8 in some shops) is a revelation. Full-bodied
with just enough oak, it puts more than a few American merlots to
shame.
</P>
<P>
   A tip: Navarre is noted for its rose. If you like the merlot,
try Vega Sindoa's rose. It's about $7.
</P>
<P>
   AN IMPRESSIVE BORDEAUX
</P>
<P>
   It's what's in the bottle that counts, right? Well, there are
times when the bottle itself can be pretty impressive. I'm thinking
of a double magnum of Chateau Malmaison I shared with some friends
recently. Malmaison is in Moulis, a town near Margaux in Bordeaux.
That big bottle _ the equivalent of four regular bottles _ was as
much fun as the wine.
</P>
<P>
   Moulis wines will never equal the best Margaux, but they can be
attractive when well made. Along with Chateau Clarke, which it
adjoins, Malmaison was owned by the late Baron Edmond de
Rothschild. Before his death in 1997, he turned Malmaison over to
his wife, Nadine, who has continued his tradition of impeccable
winemaking. Malmaison will never be another Lafite (nor will
Clarke), but it will always be a better than average Bordeaux, at a
reasonable price. A double magnum of the 1995 sells for about $80.
</P>
<P>
   A GREAT CALIFORNIA ZINFANDEL
</P>
<P>
   Finally, a winery returns _ excuse the expression _ to its
roots. Sutter Home Winery in the Napa Valley was once known for a
zinfandel it made from grapes from the Deaver Ranch in Amador
County. This was a big, rustic zinfandel that set a pattern for
other zinfandel producers.
</P>
<P>
   Sutter Home bought Montevina in Amador some years ago and more
recently added a zinfandel made from Deaver grapes to the Montevina
line. There are plenty of great zinfandels coming out of California
these days; one produced from Deaver vineyard old vines deserves
its place among them. It's about $22. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-18-00 1730EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000118.0186 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-18 17:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9339 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-HILLERMAN-BOOKS-TEX     01-18 0702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HILLERMAN-BOOKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HILLERMAN'S NAVAJO HEROES LIVE ON _ FOR NOW, AT LEAST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tony Hillerman doesn't have specific plans to stop writing
mysteries featuring Navajo policemen Joe Leaphorn and Jim Chee _
not yet, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   But he says he's continually evaluating his work for signs of
burnout, and, after a dozen bestsellers based on the same main
characters, the 74-year-old Hillerman doesn't plan to disappoint
his audience by letting the series go on too long.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a way, every book is harder,'' Hillerman says on the phone
from his New Mexico home. ``You don't want to repeat yourself. I
think I'll reach the time the quality is diminished. I'm concerned
about that.''
</P>
<P>
   As far as Hillerman's fans are concerned, at least, there's no
reason he should worry. ``Hunting Badger'' (HarperCollins, $25),
released in December, continues to hold a high place on every
national bestseller list. It moves at a brisk pace and is
characterized, as always, by the author's insights into tribal
culture. It bespeaks the care Hillerman took to make it at least a
little different from previous Leaphorn/Chee adventures.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to keep moving (the main characters) all around the
reservation,'' he says. ``This one takes place in the north area.
When I write these books, I write them with maps of the reservation
spread all around me. Readers do pay close attention. I get letters
from ones who just read to find errors. They'll say I have
characters going in the wrong direction to get to a place. And
they're probably right _ I have a habit of meaning left and saying
right.''
</P>
<P>
   But, Hillerman notes, he writes about New Mexico and its Navajo
reservation because it's geography he knows.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love this land, I really do,'' Hillerman says. ``I first
came here on furlough after World War II. I became a reporter for
the United Press International bureau in Santa Fe, and then became
bureau manager in 1952. I also taught for 20 years. My first book
was published in 1970. But writing, whether news stories or, later,
books, is the thing I do naturally. That's my work and hobby. I
can't imagine playing golf.''
</P>
<P>
   Hillerman spends a lot of his time studying writing technique.
</P>
<P>
   ``I go back and read the guys and gals who make magic with
words,'' he says. ``Joan Didion, for the way she establishes mood.
Tom Wolfe, just for the way he uses words. I want to be conscious
of when I fail.''
</P>
<P>
   Hillerman tries to be his own toughest critic.
</P>
<P>
   ``For each book, I always start out with a grandiose notion, and
I read it when I'm done and try to grade how far it falls short,''
he says, chuckling. ``I haven't written anything I think is perfect
yet.''
</P>
<P>
   His plot inspirations, Hillerman says, come from reading and
from simply looking around as he goes about normal life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Take the next Navajo book I'm going to write,'' he says. ``I
was sitting in church one day at Mass, and we were rereading from
the Old Testament, a passage where a prophet is waiting for word
from God, not an earthquake but a tiny whisper. I love that
passage. So in the next book Leaphorn, feeling bored after
retirement, hears the tag end of a conversation, a whisper, and it
somehow reminds him of an old case where he wasn't sure the guy who
got convicted was really guilty.''
</P>
<P>
   Hillerman says he'll tie that opening scene into another
involving a fingerprinting technique he has read about: ``That on
rough surfaces, fingerprints last for years. See, I'm always
collecting ideas like that. At some point, you can usually use what
you've picked up on.''
</P>
<P>
   With another Leaphorn/Chee adventure in the works, Hillerman
says he'll simply work from book to book until he decides he no
longer is delivering the quality his readers deserve.
</P>
<P>
   ``And when that happens, I'll stop the series,'' he says firmly.
``I don't want readers to ever say, `These aren't as good as they
used to be.'''
</P>
<P>
   (Jeff Guinn is books editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7720, or e-mail:
jguinn(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
