<HEADLINE>
WB TRIES FOR A LAUGH WITH RETOOLED `NORMAL' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Everyone likes a good laugh. The folks at The
WB will pay serious money for one.
</P>
<P>
   Susanne Daniels, president of entertainment at the network
currently known for smart dramas about young adults, goes so far as
to say: ``Our future programming plans are largely dedicated to
creating a breakthrough half-hour series.'' Translation: We need a
comedy.
</P>
<P>
   Trouble is, ``comedy'' has become a dirty word because the
traditional sitcom format featuring joke/punchline/laughter hasn't
been hugely successful the past few seasons. So producers and
executives are careful to distance themselves from the genre,
preferring to focus on shows that might be funny but also poignant,
pithy and provocative.
</P>
<P>
   One such series, The WB hopes, is ``Brutally Normal,''
premiering next Monday night. Shot with a single camera, like a
movie, rather than several cameras in front of an audience, like
most sitcoms, ``Brutally Normal'' follows the lives of _ surprise!
_ four teenage friends as they negotiate the confusing pathways to
young adulthood.
</P>
<P>
   The show's own gestation has been a confusing one. Originally
conceived as a single-camera half hour in the fall of 1998, it was
transformed into a one-hour dramedy because, in the words of one of
the producers, the marketplace was ``inhospitable'' to
single-camera half hours at the time. ABC bought the hourlong
concept but chose to pass after the pilot was filmed. Enter The WB,
which liked the show but wanted it as a half-hour series.
</P>
<P>
   Executive producer Greer Shephard is happy to be back with the
original concept, which is a lightly shaded treatment of the events
in a teenager's life. ``They may be fairly minuscule,'' she said,
``but in their minds they sort of expand to hyperbolic, operatic
proportions.''
</P>
<P>
   _The WB and its rival netlet, UPN, are celebrating their fifth
anniversaries this month, and that's pretty much where the
similarity ends. While UPN has finally found direction in catering
to young males, The WB continues with a schedule that still skews
decidedly female. Besides ``Brutally Normal,'' new for the
midseason and summer at The WB are ``D.C.,'' an ensemble drama from
producer Dick Wolf (``Law &AMP; Order'') about five twentysomethings
trying to make it in the nation's capital; ``Baby Blues,'' an
animated comedy based on the popular comic strip about new parents,
and ``Young Americans,'' a semi-steamy drama series set at a New
England boarding school, and specifically earmarked for a summer
launch. Also returning are three shows The WB took off the air for
retooling/repositioning: the Harry Hamlin comedy ``Movie Stars,''
the animated comedy ``Mission Hill,'' and the kids-in-the-hallway
comedy ``Zoe,'' which used to be ``Zoe, Duncan, Jack &AMP; Jane'' but
now has a shorter name and a more mature story line (the kids are
in college instead of high school).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
