<SLUG> BC-SPAIN-FED-PAINTINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FED GRANTS A LOAN TO SPAIN. HOW MUCH CASH? NONE. 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By AL GOODMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MADRID, Spain _ The Federal Reserve Board in Washington is known
for setting monetary policy, not for its modest art collection. But
for the first time the Fed has allowed part of that collection,
which is dominated by American paintings, to be shown beyond its
own headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Even in Washington, the public rarely sees the Fed's art because
it hangs in offices and private reception areas. But 34 of the
Fed's 270 artworks are on view in a show through Jan. 30 at the
Banco de Espana, Spain's central bank. The exhibition,
``Architecture and Paintings From the Federal Reserve Board,''
includes a 19th-century landscape of New York state by Alexander
Lawrie that normally adorns the office of Alan Greenspan, the Fed
chairman, and other works by William de Leftwich Dodge and William
Trost Richards.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's never been done before,'' said Mary Anne Goley, the Fed's
fine arts director, of the overseas show. Although the Fed
exhibited 55 recent acquisitions at its Washington headquarters in
1996, this is the first time that any part of the collection has
traveled anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   The Madrid show is a double payback to Spain's central bank,
which inspired the Fed to build its own collection and lent 13 old
masters, including three Goyas, for an exhibition at the Fed last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Such exchanges are still rare, although several European central
banks _ those in Britain and France, for instance _ have
collections that dwarf the Fed's. The Bank of Spain owns 3,500
works, including eight oils by Goya, who was commissioned in 1783
to paint portraits of the bank's senior officials.
</P>
<P>
   In 1971 Arthur Burns, then chairman of the Fed and an avid
amateur painter, saw the Spanish bank's art treasures during a
visit to Madrid and returned to Washington determined to expand the
Fed's collection, which then consisted of four paintings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're the central bank of a great democracy, and he wanted to
have something that spoke about our culture,'' Ms. Goley said. With
Burns' influence, the bank soon borrowed five paintings, three from
the Metropolitan Museum of Art in New York and two from a friend.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed acquired its own art slowly after Ms. Goley was hired in
1975 as its first fine arts director. Most of the collection, she
said, has come from tax-deductible donations, although the Fed does
not accept gifts from those it regulates.
</P>
<P>
   She also made numerous purchases over the years, especially from
Manhattan dealers, and these works include some of the standouts at
the Madrid show, like the Richards gouache on paper ``Entrance to
West Cove, Conanicut Island, R.I.,'' from 1882.
</P>
<P>
   It depicts a rocky green terrain with grazing sheep in the
foreground and sailboats in the distance. Ms. Goley said that she
purchased it in 1979 from the Manhattan dealer Gil Einstein for
$5,000 and that it was insured for $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   She also bought a Dodge oil on canvas, ``Midocean.'' Painted in
1896, it shows the deep-blue sea meeting a sky filled with purplish
clouds, a scene inspired by Dodge's crossings between New York and
Paris, where he studied art.
</P>
<P>
   Half of the Madrid exhibition features 19th-century American art
because it is little known in Spain, said Jose Maria Vinuela, the
Spanish bank's curator, who organized the show. ``I wanted a
representation of the 19th-century landscape, which is really the
century of creation of American painting,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For the other half of the show, he chose such works as the
richly drawn renderings by the architect Paul Cret for the
construction of the Fed's current headquarters in Washington in the
mid-1930s.
</P>
<P>
   ``These architectural drawings are a cut above,'' Ms. Goley
said, ``and of a certain date that really fell into the category of
art, because of the shading and the projection of shadow.''
</P>
<P>
   Several of the renderings show intricate details, including the
wall decorations in the Fed's boardroom, a plaster ceiling ornament
and the elevations for doors and a fireplace.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Goley said she would like the Madrid show, which is open
daily at the central bank at 50 Alcala St., to be the start of
other tours for the Fed's collection, with certain conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's logical to assume that someone else would ask us, and our
first question would be about the facility and can they guarantee
the safety of the art objects,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She complained that the frames of a few works suffered nicks
during transportation to Spain. The Fed's collection is still not
large enough to allow for a big loan of works without the risk of
bare walls in Washington, she added.
</P>
<P>
   There is no such problem in Greenspan's office, which sent the
Lawrie oil on canvas, ``Pleasant Valley,'' painted in 1867. The Fed
chairman replaced it with a 19th-century John Tullidge landscape,
``The Great Salt Lake.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
