<SLUG> BC-MASTER-CHEF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EATING WELL: LENTILS FOR THE UNLEISURELY  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARIAN BURROS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Lentils have been around for thousands of years, but
in this country, lentil soup excepted, they are considered an
exotic component of ethnic cuisine, much too difficult and
time-consuming to make at home. The most popular lentils here,
which are light brown with a greenish cast, take about 40 minutes
to cook, longer than most people have for a weeknight dinner.
</P>
<P>
   And ``popular'' is probably too strong a word. Americans eat,
per capita, a little more than a sixth of a pound of lentils a
year, a fraction of what is eaten elsewhere. In Spain, for example,
the figure is four pounds a year.
</P>
<P>
   But lentils are actually an easy alternative to rice and pasta,
and should be high on everyone's must-eat list. There are, in fact,
quick-cooking lentils.
</P>
<P>
   And these legumes have many other attributes, like a slightly
earthy but mostly neutral flavor, which combines well with almost
anything. They are also an excellent source of protein and come in
a variety of colors _ yellow, red, dark green, light green, brown,
black and white _ which makes them an intriguing addition to meals.
</P>
<P>
   For people in a hurry, lentils that are sold without the skin _
red, yellow and white ones _ are of particular interest, because
they cook in a fraction of the time of other lentils. I use red
lentils in recipes, like the one below, that I make after work.
These lentils cook so quickly, about 10 minutes, that they must be
watched carefully because they turn to mush in the blink of an eye,
which is great in soup or a sauce.
</P>
<P>
   In experimenting with lentils I tried a trick I often use with
brown rice to make it cook quickly: I soaked whole lentils that
still had their skins for eight hours and then cooked them in the
soaking water. The soaked French green lentils, also called du
Puys, cooked in 10 minutes; a type of black lentil called Urad
cooked in 12 minutes and needed a little additional water, as did
large green lentils, which took 22 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Once cooked, lentils make a delicious salad with goat cheese and
tomatoes, or can be combined, as they are in India, with potatoes,
peas and tomato sauce. There is even a baba gannouj in which
lentils replace the usual chickpeas.
</P>
<P>
   Lentils have lots of nutritional goodies: half a cup cooked
contains 8 grams of protein, 2 milligrams of sodium, 20 grams of
carbohydrates, 115 calories and no fat. Skinless lentils have only
about 2 grams of fiber per half-cup serving; with the skin, they
have about 7 grams.
</P>
<P>
   Lentils also contain iron, potassium and a B vitamin that is not
so easy to come by, folic acid or folate. An adequate intake of
folate by women of childbearing age is important to prevent neural
tube defects in infants, and it is also important for older people
because it greatly reduces the risk of heart attacks. The
recommended daily consumption of folate is 180 micrograms for
adults (400 micrograms for women of childbearing age). Half a cup
of cooked lentils contains 180 micrograms.
</P>
<P>
   Lentils provide complete protein when any of the following foods
are eaten on the same day (not necessarily in the same meal):
grains, seeds, nuts, meat, eggs or dairy products.
</P>
<P>
   Brown lentils are sold everywhere, and specialty markets carry
some others. A wide variety is available at Kalustyan's, 123
Lexington Avenue (28th Street), (212) 685-3451, and from Legumes
Plus, (800) 845-1349, www.legumesplus.com.
</P>
<P>
   LINGUINE WITH LENTILS AND PROSCIUTTO
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``Cucina Simpatica'' by Johanne Killeen and George
Germon (HarperCollins, 1991)
</P>
<P>
   Time: 35 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1 stalk celery, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 carrot, chopped
</P>
<P>
   4 or 5 ounces onion, diced
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   1 jalapeno, chopped
</P>
<P>
   \ teaspoon hot red pepper flakes
</P>
<P>
   3 ounces prosciutto, diced
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 heaping cup red lentils
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   1{ pounds linguine
</P>
<P>
   1 red onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1. Saute celery, carrot, onion, garlic, jalapeno, pepper flakes
and prosciutto in the oil in a large, deep skillet for about 10
minutes, until very soft and fragrant.
</P>
<P>
   2. Add lentils and 5 cups water, and bring to a boil. Reduce
heat, and boil gently until lentils are soft but not mushy, about
10 minutes. Season with salt.
</P>
<P>
   3. Cook the pasta according to the package directions. Drain,
and add to the lentil mixture; toss well. Serve topped with chopped
red onion.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
