<SLUG> BC-TV-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`LATE SHOW' TAKES A BREAK  
 THE ULTIMATE ANSWER 
`MALCOLM' IN THE CHIPS 
BOB DOLE, COMIC
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla.)  (rk) 
 By BILL CARTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite rampant speculation _ and apparently numerous volunteers
_ there are no plans at the moment for anyone to serve as a
substitute host for David Letterman during his convalescence from
heart bypass surgery last week.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, CBS will keep offering reruns of ``Late Show'' while
Letterman continues his recovery, which, by a number of accounts
from people close to him, is going well.
</P>
<P>
   But because he has never before missed a scheduled appearance,
his emergency leave has raised a number of questions centering
mainly on how long the show might be able to go before it became
necessary to call on one of those many volunteers. (Among those who
have publicly raised their hands as being ready to step in for
Letterman are Rosie O'Donnell and Regis Philbin.)
</P>
<P>
   CBS released a statement indicating that its main concern was
Letterman's health and saying that the only current plan was to
broadcast reruns. Some of those may be specially packaged, with
some guests doing newly recorded introductions to memorable shows.
``Late Show'' may, for example, repeat Letterman's prime-time
specials.
</P>
<P>
   The thinking seems be that should Letterman progress rapidly, as
he seems to be doing, it will not be necessary to go to any
substitute hosts. If his time away from the show extends to several
months, that position might be reconsidered. But the reconsidering
would have to be done by Letterman, who owns his show through his
company, Worldwide Pants. He will be the one to decide the issue of
substitute hosts.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, another question concerns what will happen to
the show's staff and crew. The staff _ writers, producers, guest
bookers, clerical staff, Paul Shaffer and his band _ all work for
Worldwide Pants. One staff member said Letterman had passed word to
them that nobody would miss a paycheck. This week the staff has
been shooting comedy pieces that can work around Letterman's
absence.
</P>
<P>
   The technical crew is a different matter because its members
work for CBS. Depending again on the length of Letterman's absence,
the network might try to reassign some of them to other shows
temporarily.
</P>
<P>
   The Ultimate Answer
</P>
<P>
   ``Millionaire'' magic struck again Monday night for ABC as a
second contestant in the brief history of ``Who Wants to Be a
Millionaire'' hit the jackpot, winning $1 million for knowing that
the sun is 93 million miles from Earth.
</P>
<P>
   In a show that was actually taped on Saturday, Dan Blonsky, a
34-year-old lawyer from Miami, sailed through the list of questions
unscathed, though he was compelled to seek help from a law partner
on the $500,000 question: Who appeared on the cover of the first
issue of People magazine? Answer: Mia Farrow.
</P>
<P>
   The ABC quiz show is shattering every recent rating standard,
and another million-dollar winner surely will not hurt. Behind the
strength of ``Millionaire,'' ABC is moving closer to first place
among the networks in the seasonlong ratings, its first such
victory in six years. But ABC's top entertainment executives, Lloyd
Braun and Stu Bloomberg, said at a news conference last week that
they were not predicting any seasonal victory yet.
</P>
<P>
   As happened the first time the show had a million-dollar winner,
the timing was all but ideal. The first time, the winner came
toward the end of the show's 18-night run in the November sweep
month. The new top-dollar success took place on the first night of
the show's new three-times-a-week format.
</P>
<P>
   In Britain, where the show originated in 1998, nobody has ever
won 1 million pounds.
</P>
<P>
   `Malcolm' in the Chips
</P>
<P>
   As big a hit as ``Millionaire'' is, it may have a rival for hit
show of the season. ``Malcolm in the Middle,'' a new series on Fox,
posted spectacular ratings numbers for a second week on Sunday
night. The show already has the look of the first true runaway
comedy hit of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Malcolm'' has already done some things Fox has rarely, if
ever, seen before, like improving on a lead-in from ``The
Simpsons'' two weeks in a row and pulling in even more people in
its second week on the air than it did for its heavily promoted
premiere.
</P>
<P>
   ``Malcolm'' was so big last week that only the mighty ``E.R.''
beat it in the ratings among 18-to-49-year-old viewers, the
measurement that Fox, NBC, and ABC all live and die by.
</P>
<P>
   In that category, ``Malcolm'' was the top-rated comedy last
week, beating ``Friends,'' ``Frasier'' and all the rest. It also
beat every edition of ``Millionaire'' last week among those
viewers. With those between 18 and 34, ``Malcolm'' was totally
supreme, beating every other show, including ``E.R.''
</P>
<P>
   The other hit show whose ratings were much anticipated this
weekend was ``The Sopranos,'' but because of Monday's holiday, HBO
does not yet have any national rating results for the show. They
are expected to be available later this week.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Dole, Comic
</P>
<P>
   Comedy Central, which has gained a reputation for skewering
election coverage on presidential election-year specials titled
``Indecision,'' named a new comic Tuesday to its roster for
``Indecision 2000'': Bob Dole.
</P>
<P>
   Dole, the former Senate majority leader and presidential
candidate, who has been droll in a number of talk show appearances
since his failed run for the presidency in 1996, will join the cast
of the comedy channel's nightly satire on the news, ``The Daily
Show,'' with Jon Stewart as host.
</P>
<P>
   Dole is expected to serve as a political commentator for the
coverage, providing analysis from the Republican National
Convention in Philadelphia as well as during other events in the
political year, ending with the Election Night edition of ``The
Daily Show.''
</P>
<P>
   In a news release the channel quoted Dole as saying, ``After all
the campaigns I've been through, it'll be nice to be on the other
side for this one.''
</P>
<P>
   No one at Comedy Central could say what the channel might do if
Dole's wife, Elizabeth, winds up on the Republican ticket as the
vice presidential candidate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
