<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-18 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9372 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-MOSELEY1STTAKE20-COX     01-18 1502
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOSELEY1STTAKE20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    83-year-old gardener Margaret Moseley's recipe for beating the
winter blahs
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Thursday, Jan 20.
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Margaret Moseley lies awake at night, pondering
whether to transplant a sasanqua closer to her gingko so that in
fall the shrub's yellow-centered flowers will accent the tree's
yellow leaves.
</P>
<P>
   By 5 a.m., this 83-year-old dynamo hits the floor running to get
her housework out the way so that by daybreak she can be where she
really wants to be _ in her South DeKalb County, Ga., garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't wait to get up every morning!'' says the
great-grandmother of nine. ``At my age, I have friends who don't
know they're in the world. Or are in nursing homes. Or have died.
But I feel great. When I think of all my friends who have no
interests in life, I just don't understand.''
</P>
<P>
   What's clear is that gardening keeps her young.
</P>
<P>
   And, at a time of year when many folks battle the blahs, this
gardener couldn't be more hyped if it were spring. That's because
she's filled her three-quarter acre garden with plants sure to
bring a smile in the dead of winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's the only person I know who will call me at 8 a.m. on a
bleak, cold and miserable day in January and say, `You ought to see
my garden this morning. It's the most beautiful I've ever seen
it,''' says Martha Tate, a longtime friend and garden writer.
``Here I am looking outside at gray, maybe a few evergreens, and
her garden is full of color.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not that Margaret planned it that way; the seasonal color,
she admits, is by accident. She simply plants what she likes. And
for more than 30 years, her shopping list has included trees,
shrubs and perennials that put on a show in late fall, winter and
early spring _ especially camellias, sasanquas and viburnums.
</P>
<P>
   A self-taught gardener, Margaret has built a reputation for
having the vision to introduce Atlantans to both old-fashioned and
new plants. Knowing nothing about design, she's managed to mix
those plants in pleasing color combinations, a feat even some
artists find a challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``For someone who claims she didn't know what she was doing,
she's done a masterful job,'' says Sandra Jonas, an Atlanta
landscape designer. ``It makes me think, why did I spend five years
in school for this?''
</P>
<P>
   Jonas is among the army of friends Margaret has made through
gardening _ ones with whom she readily shares her arsenal of
treasured plants upon visits to her garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have twin daughters who are both interested in gardening,''
Margaret says with pride. ``When I find plants I like or that I
think they or my friends might not come across, I buy two _ one for
me and one for them. I love that, because then they get so excited
just like I do.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what I enjoy about gardening.''
</P>
<P>
   A middle-age discovery: Margaret's backyard garden was nothing
more than the ubiquitous pines, azaleas and honeysuckle when she
and her husband, Lamar, built their home 35 years ago. At the time,
she was too busy making clothes for their four daughters to fret
over yardwork.
</P>
<P>
   But once the last of the girls had left for college, Margaret,
then 52, was hungry for a hobby, so she took up gardening. She
joined a garden club and took a class in flower arranging. ``That
was for the birds,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Margaret just wanted to dig.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started with 25 feet of old-fashioned zinnias and marigolds,
and it just grew and grew from there,'' she recalls, waving her
perfectly manicured hands above her red head.
</P>
<P>
   The site, once a cotton field, proved ideal, with rich soil,
proper drainage and exposure to both full sun and partial shade.
</P>
<P>
   Margaret began by removing many of the pines and encircling the
rest with stones she hauled in from vacant lots to create island
beds. ``There was no plan to it,'' she recalls. ``Every plant here
has been moved at least five times _ too much sun, too much shade.
But, you know, I don't know of many plants I've lost.''
</P>
<P>
   She discovered most of her plants by getting to know employees
at nurseries, such as Hall's Flower Shop. ``She came in every
Friday, and we would fight over who got to wait on her because we
all just learned so much by walking around with her, with that
eagle eye of hers for plants,'' says Atlanta garden designer Tara
Dillard, who once worked at Hall's. ``Margaret started gardening
before most of her plants could be bought in this area.''
</P>
<P>
   By asking a nursery to order a plant she'd read about, Margaret
introduced many varieties to Atlantans. ``I'd get so excited about
a plant, I'd just have to have it,'' she says. ``Then I'd have to
go to bed to think about where to plant it!''
</P>
<P>
   Her addiction to gardening became rivaled only by her passion
for shopping. To support her habits, she sold impatiens and poppy
seeds for 15 years through the Farmers &AMP; Consumers Market Bulletin,
which became an outlet for meeting more gardeners.
</P>
<P>
   Through Dillard, Margaret met Penny McHenry, a.k.a. Atlanta's
Hydrangea Lady and founder of the American Hydrangea Society.
</P>
<P>
   ``The woman is much older than I,'' joked McHenry, who turns 75
in March, ``but what an incredible mind she has and such vision.
She's certainly become an expert on viburnum and camellias.''
</P>
<P>
   Wintertime extravaganza: What Margaret loves about those plants
is they provide color in winter when most of the garden is dormant.
</P>
<P>
   In October, her garden becomes a dazzling stage, with Camellia
sasanquas such as `Cotton Candy', `Pink Snow' and `Sparkling
Burgundy'. Even after blooming, the shrubs _ some reaching 25 feet
_ continue to provide color by shedding carpets of pink or white
petals at their feet. ``People who don't plant sasanquas don't know
what they're missing,'' Margaret says.
</P>
<P>
   In November, the sasanquas share the spotlight with their
cousins, the camellias, though some varieties, such as her red
Camellia japonica `Daikagura', bloom as early as October.
</P>
<P>
   In December, a late-blooming sasanqua, `Yuletide' _ the one with
red flowers and yellow centers she planted near her ginkgo tree _
makes a special appearance, and in January, Margaret's favorite
camellia, `Fragrant Pink', bursts onto stage with the fresh scent
of springtime.
</P>
<P>
   By then, the patches of pink, lavender and purple pansies she
planted in fall for instant color are complemented by the pink
blossoms of daphne and hellebores, followed by those show-stopping
harbingers of spring, the daffodils.
</P>
<P>
   In March and April, Margaret's garden gleams in white with
Chinese Snowball viburnum and 20 other varieties, white flowering
quince and the `Kwanzan' Japanese cherry tree's canopy of popcorn.
</P>
<P>
   Despite her passion for color, Margaret is painfully reminded
each time she adds a new plant that she risks overdoing it. Her
best gardening advice, she says, came from her favorite author and
biggest inspiration, garden writer Elizabeth Lawrence: ``Once I had
a lovely garden, and I ruined it with plants.''
</P>
<P>
   Her second best advice comes from experience: ``If you don't
like to weed, don't garden,'' says Margaret, who for the past six
years has employed a helper to mow the grass and move large plants
when she gets the notion.
</P>
<P>
   And the notion strikes often. Tate recalls that on one visit to
the garden a 10-foot-tall viburnum she once photographed was
missing. Surely Margaret didn't lose one of her oldest shrubs, she
thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I just moved it,'' she told Tate. ``I didn't like it
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Woman's prerogative?
</P>
<P>
   That and just trial and error, Margaret's secret to a
half-century of success.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT OTHER GARDENERS SAY
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Margaret once had this pink camellia I was crazy about, and
she wanted to give me one for my birthday but couldn't find one in
bloom. So she bought me one anyhow and picked and Scotch-taped
blooms from her camellia onto mine!'' _ Penny McHenry, Atlanta
gardener and founder of the American Hydrangea Society
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Margaret has too much to do in her garden to grow old. She's
constantly refining it and passes along garden knowledge with a
story attached. When the conversation strays from gardening, she
will pull you by the arm and say, `Come on, I want to show you
something.''' _ Tara Dillard, Atlanta garden designer
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``If she reads about a new plant, she's making calls to
nurseries before she's through with the sentence. But she's also
got her grandmother's pink rose and other plants that have stood
the test of time, things that are native to the South and to this
region.'' _ Martha Tate, Atlanta gardener and producer of HGTV's
``A Gardener's Diary''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``She's just the kindest, most generous person; Penny McHenry
calls her `The Original Pass-
</P>
<P>
   along Lady.' I don't think I've ever been to her garden when
I've left empty-handed. I'm now building my own garden with her
plants.'' _ Sandra Jonas, Atlanta landscape designer
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
