<P>
   CAMELLIAS
</P>
<P>
   HOW TO GROW THE 'ROSE OF WINTER'
</P>
<P>
   One of Margaret Moseley's favorite plants is a shrub that gives
her garden the most color in winter _ the camellia.
</P>
<P>
   The Camellia japonica, which blooms from October to March, also
provides glossy evergreen foliage at a time when most of the
landscape is brown. Although they are coastal flowers that thrive
in termperatures from 40 to 60 degrees, camellias do well in
Atlanta area gardens, given the right conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what the American Camellia Society, headquartered at
Massee Lane Gardens south of Fort Valley, Ga., recommends:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Where to plant: Partial shade and well-drained soil
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  When to plant: Late fall through early spring
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  How to plant: Dig a hole 1 to 2 feet wider than the root ball.
Place the ball so that its top is slighlty higher than soil level.
Fill the hole with a mixture of top soil, coarse sand and organic
matter (peat moss, leaf mold, sawdust or cow manure mixed with
soil). Build a berm of soil around the plant 3 feet in diameter to
prevent runoff when watering. Mulch with pine straw or other
organic matter and water well after planting, then about once a
week during dry spells.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  How to feed: With good soil, one application of 10-10-10
fertilizer in spring should be adequate.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Which to plant: A few include Camellia japonica 'Professor
Charles S. Sargent,' an old-fashioned red; C. japonica 'Debutante,
pink; C. japonica 'Pink Perfection'; and C. japonica 'White
Empress.'
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  More information: American Camellia Society, One Massee Lane,
Fort Valley, Ga., 31030, call 912-967-2358 ; North Georgia Camellia
Society's annual Camellia Show, 9.a.m.-5 p.m. Feb. 19 and 1-5 p.m.
Feb. 20, Atlanta Botanical Garden, free with garden admission,
404-876-5859.
</P>
<P>
   MARGARET'S PICKS FOR FALL, WINTER
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hellebores. A perennial with dark green foliage that bears
large clusters of pale green, pink and burgundy flowers.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Arum. A foliage plant, Arum italicum 'Pictum' dies back in
summer but in late fall begins yielding lush green arrow-shaped
leaves with creamy white veins that last until spring.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Sasanquas. An evergreen shrub, Camellia sasanqua offers pink,
white or red flowers from late September through December.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Confederate rose. An old Southern favorite that's actually a
hibiscus, Hibiscus mutabilis is a large shrubby perennial that in
early fall produces creamy white flowers that turn pink and finally
deep red.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Flowering apricot. One of the few winter-blooming trees is
Prunus mume, the Japanese flowering apricot, which has pink or
white flowers in January and February.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Daphne. Daphne odora, a low-growing evergreen shrub with
coarse green leaves outlined in cream, offers fragrant clusters of
white or pink flowers, typically beginning in mid-February.
</P>
<P>
   _ Danny C. Flanders writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
