<SLUG> BC-FASHION-SHOES-SIDE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEP INTO THE TRENDS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: With FASHION-SHOES-MAIN) 
 
 
By BARBARA DE WITT 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shopping for new shoes? These are some of the latest trends,
designed to freshen up your fringed jeans, floral sun dresses and
basic black ensembles.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sequins: These little sparklers are showing up in solid colors
and floral designs in dainty evening shoes with sling backs and
small heels.
</P>
<P>
   _ Animal prints: Leopard is still looking hot, but newer prints
are pony, cow and zebra, seen on a variety of fabrics from faux fur
to velveteen.
</P>
<P>
   _ Florals: Think of Carmen Miranda and the tropics, and look for
large blooms in hot-house colors.
</P>
<P>
   _ Far East themes: Mystical dragons, Asian-inspired cat prints,
Indian sari fabrics and wooden beads with Chinese writing are what
you'll find on casual footwear.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sculpted heels: Shoes with a profile are back, often carved
out of wood with a see-through center like free-form sculptures or
resembling wooden clogs. Other heel novelties include balls, cubes
and cylinders, as well as stilettos and their shorter variation
called a ``Sabrina'' heel after the shoes worn by Audrey Hepburn in
the film ``Sabrina.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Decorative shoe beds: In a season of barely there shoes
(thongs, slides and mules) the area that your foot rests on is
covered in bright contrasting colors, as well as painted with
flowers or dragons.
</P>
<P>
   _ Loud colors: Hot pink, orange, turquoise and red are now
standard equipment in the shoe biz. Some are solid tones, but the
newest designs feature contrasting colors in whip-stitching on shoe
beds or heels.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-18-00 1811EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000118.0200 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-18 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9374 &Cx1f; tad-z
r w BC-TECH-AGENDA-$ADV23-CO     01-18 0903
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-AGENDA-$ADV23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TECH INDUSTRY HAS A LONG WISH LIST FOR CONGRESS THIS YEAR
 &HT;    With TECH-CONGRESS. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial
categories for release Sunday, Jan. 23.
 &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Last year, Congress got beyond its partisan rancor
long enough to pass a number of laws sought by the nation's booming
high-tech companies. This year, the tech titans expect even more
out of Washington.
</P>
<P>
   On trade, taxes, visas, digital signatures and many other
issues, the owners of technology-driven companies will be pushing
for far-reaching bills when the 106th Congress reconvenes Monday.
With lawmakers planning to recess in late July to attend political
party conventions and launch re-election campaigns, the pressure to
get bills passed early in the year will be intense.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't just say, 'OK, this is a short year, so let's just
put these bills in a drawer,' `` said Rep. Bob Goodlatte, R-Va.,
co-chair of the Congressional Internet Caucus. Rather than dismiss
2000 as a do-nothing election year, tech supporters will ``be
pushing every step of the way,'' he said. ``You have to build
momentum.''
</P>
<P>
   Until 1998, technology-related issues were not particularly hot
topics in Washington, both because most lawmakers were unfamiliar
with the Internet and because many tech entrepreneurs were too busy
making money to care about politics.
</P>
<P>
   But as the Web has woven itself into the workplaces and homes of
tens of millions of Americans, tech legislative issues have shot to
the top of the agenda on the Hill. And in places like Austin, Palo
Alto, Boston, Seattle, Atlanta and Northern Virginia, entrepreneurs
now realize their fortunes may be determined in large part by
Congress's action or lack of it.
</P>
<P>
   With tech companies hiring lobbyists at a frantic pace and
lawmakers eagerly listening to them, bills have been moving along
in a surprisingly bipartisan fashion. In less than two years, the
Republican-led Congress and Democratic White House have agreed to
impose a three-year moratorium on taxes on electronic commerce,
increase the number of visas issued to highly skilled immigrants,
limit lawsuits against companies involved with Y2K-related software
flaws, and extend copyright protections to material published on
the Web.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the tech agenda is even more aggressive. Of course,
electronic-commerce companies, chip makers and other sectors of the
diverse high-tech business community have different priorities, but
companies propelled by new technologies generally want lawmakers to
help them by:
</P>
<P>
   _ Expanding global trade.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1992, high-tech products have been the leading U.S.
exports. To increase growth, computer makers, chip manufacturers,
software developers and others want greater access to foreign
markets, especially China.
</P>
<P>
   Tech companies want Congress to grant permanent normal trade
relations status to China. That's not a simple matter in an
election year because labor unions, a core Democrat constituency,
oppose expanded trade. So do some conservatives who believe China
never lives up to its agreements.
</P>
<P>
   Tech companies also are demanding that government further loosen
controls on the export of high-performance computers. Again, this
is a touchy issue because many legislators fear that equipment
vital to our national security will end up illegally in the hands
of Chinese military officials.
</P>
<P>
   _ Increasing the pool of highly skilled workers.
</P>
<P>
   Employers are desperate for more engineers and programmers. They
want Congress to increase the number of H-1B temporary work visas
used by companies and universities to hire foreign workers with
specialized skills. Industry was successful in boosting the visa
level two years ago, but opposition from labor unions will be stiff
in this election year. Anti-immigration Republicans may oppose the
visa increase as well.
</P>
<P>
   Tech employers also want the government to bolster U.S. schools
by providing development grants for teachers who want more computer
training and scholarships for students pursuing technology-related
degrees.
</P>
<P>
   _ Spurring research and development.
</P>
<P>
   Tech-driven entrepreneurs want a permanent extension of the
research and development tax credit.
</P>
<P>
   _ Encouraging the growth of electronic commerce.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest issue is whether to allow state and local
governments to collect sales taxes from online purchases.
Currently, most shoppers pay no sales taxes on Internet purchases
because of a temporary tax moratorium imposed by Congress. But as
e-commerce grows, more mayors and governors are clamoring for the
right to collect sales taxes.
</P>
<P>
   This may be too hot of a potato for Congress to hold in an
election year, so the moratorium may be extended to bump the issue
into 2001. But Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., a vocal opponent of
Internet taxes, could push for a permanent ban to attract attention
to his presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Tech companies also want Congress to move on a number of other
issues, such as approving the use of electronic signatures to allow
more business dealings over the Internet, and settling a number of
thorny privacy issues involving transfers of financial data and
medical records.
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Geewax's e-mail address is marilyng(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
