<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-18 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9375 &Cx1f; tad-z
r w BC-TECH-CONGRESS-$ADV23-     01-18 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-CONGRESS-$ADV23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HIGH-TECH ECONOMY BENEATH THE NOTICE OF MANY IN CONGRESS
 &HT;    With TECH-AGENDA and TECH-LIST. Moving in (w) Washington and (f)
financial categories for release Sunday, Jan. 23.
 &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The stock market may be racing along on ``Internet
time,'' but many members of Congress still seem to set their pace
by an old-fashioned pocket watch attached to a long chain of
traditions.
</P>
<P>
   While new technologies are transforming the U.S. economy, many
lawmakers continue to focus on decades-old issues such as
protecting agricultural subsidies, imposing steel quotas and
preserving banking regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 535 members of Congress, only a few dozen have carved out
a reputation for understanding legislation important to
technology-driven companies. And those few who have become
technology-savvy are not widely dispersed geographically.
</P>
<P>
   Most lawmakers recognized by industry as tech leaders come from
just two states: California, home of Silicon Valley, and Virginia,
birthplace of America Online and many other Internet-driven
companies.
</P>
<P>
   But tech leadership may begin growing as Congress reconvenes
this year. Now courted by hordes of high-paid tech lobbyists and
eager to win the support of entrepreneurs making money and creating
jobs, more members of Congress are educating themselves on
tech-related issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people in Congress, regardless of party, are starting to
recognize how important technology is to the country,'' said Marc
Brailov, a spokesman for the American Electronics Association, a
trade group. ``They know it has been driving the economy.''
</P>
<P>
   And even more legislators will be paying attention once the
results of the 2000 census are revealed, predicted Rep. James
Moran, D-Va., who has witnessed the phenomenal growth in tech jobs
in Northern Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians ``are going to see that not a lot of people are
doing manual labor any more,'' Moran said. ``The census will help
us identify the sources of employment, ale (in Congress) are
going to realize they have more tech workers than they ever
imagined.''
</P>
<P>
   Until very recently, technology-driven changes in the economy
have not been widely recognized by lawmakers, who often appear more
comfortable with 20th-century industries _ or even 19th-century
ones _ than with the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   For example, about 104 members of Congress continue to keep
alive the Steel Caucus, which tries to block foreign competition.
That's about the size of the informal Congressional Internet
Caucus, which tries to help legislators learn more about the online
world.
</P>
<P>
   But the steel industry has nearly evaporated from the U.S.
economy. The combined market value of the nation's top steel
companies _ USX Steel Group Inc., Bethlehem Steel Corp. and LTV
Corp. _ amounts to about $4 billion, while Yahoo!, just one
Internet-focused company, has a market value exceeding $90 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for devotion to venerable causes such as steel or
peanut subsidies is that lawmakers ``still envision their districts
as industrial or agricultural centers,'' Moran said. Even states
that have gained the most from the technology boom, such as Texas,
Massachusetts and Washington, do not have congressional delegations
that are recognized as tech leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The most frequently cited reasons for the lack of enthusiasm
among lawmakers for tech issues are age and professional
background. Legislators tend to be older and have educations in
law, not engineering.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we started the Internet Caucus about four years ago,
(lawmakers) didn't have e-mail addresses or Web sites,'' said Rep.
Bob Goodlatte, R-Va. That has changed, with virtually all
legislators having some online presence, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Goodlatte, widely recognized as one of the most knowledgeable
lawmakers on technology issues, said Congress is now moving beyond
the basics of sending e-mail and getting down to the difficult work
of shaping laws for the new economy.
</P>
<P>
   He predicted that Congress will do so not by creating any new
structures, such as a Senate Technology Committee on a par with the
Senate Banking Committee, because the influence of new technologies
is too diffuse and widespread.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every committee is going to have to deal with these issues''
of how powerful technologies are transforming commerce, medicine,
communications and more, Goodlatte said. ``I don't think you could
devise a single committee that could handle all of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Geewax can be reached by e-mail at
marilyng(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
