A9377 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-TV-MILLIONAIRE19-COX     01-18 0384
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-MILLIONAIRE19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    More `Millionaire' makes ABC merry
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ ABC executives like to joke that they're
thinking of changing the name of their network to MBC, the
``Millionaire'' Broadcasting Co., and why shouldn't they?
</P>
<P>
   ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' continues to rack up ratings
at a truly amazing clip; last week's run averaged more than 27
million viewers a night and placed several shows in the Nielsen Top
10 for the week (see ratings below). It's singlehandedly made ABC
competitive again, even though most of its new fall shows were
Nielsen flops. Now the game show phenomenon has moved to three
nights a week _ Tuesdays, Thursdays and Sundays _ and executive
producer Michael Davies is looking for ways to make sure the public
doesn't tire of it.
</P>
<P>
   First up are special themed shows. The Jan. 29 show will focus
on the Super Bowl and feature pro football questions. The second
themed show will air in March before the Academy Awards and deal
with movie questions.
</P>
<P>
   Davies says he's also toying with special ``Millionaires'' in
which celebrities would play for charity, and a
tournament-of-champions competition that would bring back winners.
</P>
<P>
   But Davies knows that one of the show's attractions is the
possibility of contestants losing most of their money, and that's a
problem for the charity shows he's mulling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just worry that if you do a celebrity `Millionaire,'''' he
says, ``it's very difficult to tell someone who is playing for
charity, `Well, I'm sorry, you just lost $468,000. And now you're
just going home with $32,000.'
</P>
<P>
   ``So we have to figure a way to make the show work for that
format. But we've got an idea up our sleeve,'' which, of course, he
wouldn't divulge at this early stage.
</P>
<P>
   Davies also has another idea that he's already sold to ABC _ an
American version of another British game show _ ``Mastermind.''
It's been a hit in England for years, and is noted for its
extremely hard questions, much like the U.S. game shows of the late
'50s. He says he's developing it slowly, and hopes to have it on
sometime this year.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Kloer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
