<DOCNO> NYT20000118.0209 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-18 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9390 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-COKE-ANALYST-COX     01-18 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-ANALYST-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Analyst predicts Coke in for big changes
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A well-respected Wall Street analyst predicted
Coca-Cola will be undergoing ``the greatest sea change in its
business in 20 years,'' including cutting as many as 2,000 jobs
from its global workforce.
</P>
<P>
   Sanford Bernstein analyst Bill Pecoriello estimated that about
600 jobs would be eliminated in Atlanta alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's my own analysis, not the company's,'' Pecoriello said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola spokesman Robert Baskin said ``management is taking a
look at every aspect of operations. We have no further comment on
rumor and speculation.''
</P>
<P>
   And Coke director Jimmy Williams said the board discussed ``all
aspects of the company's business'' at its meeting Tuesday in
Atlanta. He said a clearer picture of the financial strategy will
emerge when earnings are released Jan. 26.
</P>
<P>
   Pecoriello said he intentionally did not wait for the company to
announce its new strategy before issuing his report.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is risk in waiting,'' he said, because the new
management team is not pursuing the status quo.
</P>
<P>
   Pecoriello upgraded the stock Tuesday to ``outperform'' from
``neutral.'' He predicted the stock will rise to $71 during the
next 12 months, with an upside chance of reaching $77.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't sit on the sidelines and wait for Doug Daft and Jack
Stahl to communicate this message to investors because it will be
too late,'' Pecoriello wrote, referring to the two executives who
will run the company. ``We believe Coca-Cola's new strategy will
become apparent to the market over the coming hours/days/weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   He said reducing the number of jobs globally to about 27,000
from 29,000 is more than just a move to cut labor costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes it's about trimming the fat from an organization that
hasn't gone on a diet in quite some time, but it's also about
changing the way Coke does business around the world and allocates
its resources,'' Pecoriello wrote.
</P>
<P>
   By closing and moving office locations, as well as undergoing a
``significant house cleaning'' among mid-level managers, the
company would have a clean start regarding its new strategic
directives, he predicted.
</P>
<P>
   Pecoriello said those new strategies include:
</P>
<P>
   _ More realistic growth goals. ``We believe Coke will shift from
chasing volume and (market) share at any cost to realistic volume
goals the system can support,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, the company has told Wall Street it can produce an
average annual increase in case sales of 7 percent to 8 percent. It
also has said that would generate earnings per share growth of 15
percent to 20 percent annually.
</P>
<P>
   But the company has not been able to hit those targets recently,
and several Wall Street analysts have questioned whether those are
realistic goals over the long-term.
</P>
<P>
   Pecoriello believes the goals will be revised downward to 6
percent average annual volume growth and 13 percent annual
earnings-per-share growth over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   More realistic goals would help both Coca-Cola and its global
network of bottlers financially because less money would be
invested in new plant and equipment going forward, which would
improve the return on capital, he said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Better resource allocation. He believes the company will more
wisely spend its marketing dollars where it will be getting the
most bang for its bucks. ``On the margin, the incremental capital
and marketing dollars spent in certain markets in recent years ...
reduced shareholder value,'' Pecoriello wrote.
</P>
<P>
   _ More local decision-making. He said the new management team
will move more decisions from Atlanta to local operations around
the world, where executives have more firsthand knowledge of
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   _ Taking write-downs on troubled overseas assets, such as the
company's Russian bottling operations. ``By cleaning house on the
balance sheet ... Coke positions itself to deliver more consistent
profit growth,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Pecoriello said the main risk to the company comes in
implementing the new strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably the biggest risk is execution, with new management in
every senior position that has inherited operating plans from their
predecessors,'' he wrote. ``Turning a ship the size of Coke isn't
an easy task.''
</P>
<P>
   Henry Unger writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
