<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Wednesday, Jan. 19. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The N.Y. Times News Service
Night Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-INSPECTIONS (United Nations) _ The Security Council holds
showdown meeting over Kofi Annan's choice of Rolf Ekeus to head new
Iraq inspection team. Besides Russian and Chinese opposition,
France announces that it rejects the choice. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-SCANDAL (Berlin) _ Helmut Kohl, the former German
chancellor, on Tuesday resigned his post as honorary chairman of
the Christian Democrats after the party's leadership turned on him
with extraordinary vehemence and accused him of ``violating his
duties'' by refusing to name people who secretly gave him money. By
Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   (MOVED)
</P>
<P>
   DEBATES-RDP (Des Moines, Iowa) _ Not since 1998 have so many
candidates taken part in so many debates before the voting begins
in the Iowa caucuses. Now that the first round of encounters is
over _ the major Republican contenders participated in seven
debates; the Democrats held six _ politicians, academics and civic
groups all praised the process for elevating the discourse and
giving the public a genuine opportunity to observe the people
competing to be the next president. By Richard L. Berke and Robin
Toner.
</P>
<P>
   GUN-MAKERS (Las Vegas) _ Feeling the pressure from lawsuits and
state legislatures, the trade organization for gun manufacturers is
collecting millions of dollars from its members and this week
announced plans to support candidates, lobby legislatures and
defend the industry in a growing number of court cases. By Michael
Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   CONSUMER-WEALTH (Washington) _ The booming stock market showered
benefits onto both middle- and upper-income households during the
latter part of the last decade, but incomes generally crept up only
modestly despite the strong economy, the Federal Reserve said
Tuesday in the most detailed look so far at consumer finances
during the period. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   With a graphic.
</P>
<P>
   YANKEES-JETER (New York) _ The Yankees are on the verge of
signing their standout shortstop, Derek Jeter, to a seven-year
$118-million contract that would be the largest ever in
professional baseball and the second largest ever in professional
sports. The long-term deal for Jeter would represent a shift in
strategy by the Yankees, who until now have been content to sign
their young stars to successive one-year contracts or simply battle
it out with them in salary arbitration. By Buster Olney.
</P>
<P>
   With photo NYT22.
</P>
