<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-SPANKING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITAIN MOVES TO PROTECT CHILDREN FROM PARENTAL HITTING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The British government said Tuesday it wanted to make
it illegal for parents to hit their children on the head, &UR;  &LR; but will
uphold the right of parents to smack kids elsewhere using only
their bare hands.
</P>
<P>
   The government said its proposals, called ``Protecting Children,
Supporting Parents,'' were a compromise made necessary after the
European Court of Human Rights ruled the Victorian-era law
governing child discipline in England was outdated and inhumane.
</P>
<P>
   While the government said it would consult child welfare
advocates before submitting the proposals to Parliament, officials
said the 1860 law governing the discipline of children would be
amended to enshrine the right of parents to hit their children, but
would ban the use of any implements and make it illegal to strike a
child anywhere on the face or head.
</P>
<P>
   Child welfare advocates criticized the proposals, saying they
did not go far enough to protect children, while others dismissed
the plans as the latest example of a meddlesome ``nanny state''
that tries to police every facet of life.
</P>
<P>
   The government's proposals, and the reaction to them, underscore
how sensitive the punishment of children is in Europe in general
and Britain in particular. The hitting of children by adults as a
form of discipline or punishment is outlawed in eight European
countries, Austria, Croatia, Cyprus, Denmark, Finland, Latvia,
Norway and Sweden, and bans are under consideration elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   But British Health Minister John Hutton, who unveiled the
government's plans Tuesday, rejected the idea of a ban, saying that
extensive polling shows there is little public support for a ban
that would be unpopular and unenforceable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must recognize both the rights of parents to exercise their
parental responsibility and to bring up children safely, and as
they think best, without undue interference from the state, while
the rights of children remain protected,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The proposals, almost certain to become law because the ruling
Labor Party has an overwhelming majority in Parliament, will outlaw
caning, a practice in which children are beaten with sticks.
Outlawed in public schools a decade ago, caning has a long
tradition here and remained legal in private British schools up
until two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   It was a caning administered by a man to his 9-year-old stepson
that forced the government to step into an area it would rather
avoid. The man, who used a three-foot pole to beat the boy, was
acquitted by an English jury after he cited the ``reasonable
chastisement'' law of 1860 that gives parents the right to punish
their children physically.
</P>
<P>
   But lawyers for the boy took their case to the European Court of
Human Rights in Strasbourg, which ruled that the English law did
not protect the rights of children and had to be changed.
</P>
<P>
   Claiming that at least one child dies every week in Britain
after being beaten by an adult, child welfare advocates here have
called for a ban on all forms of physical punishment of children.
In Sweden, child advocates argue, only four children have died at
the hands of abusive adults since corporal punishment was outlawed
there some 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Gerry Tissier, a spokesman for the National Society for the
Prevention of Cruelty to Children, said his group wants the
government to bring English law in to line with progressive
European thinking. He said the proposals leave children vulnerable
and adults unclear on what they can and cannot do.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a recipe for confusion,'' said Tissier. ``We are hugely
disappointed at the government's refusal to scrap this Victorian
defense. At the beginning of the 21st century, children should have
the same legal protection against assault as adults.''
</P>
<P>
   But Liam Fox, a physician who is the health spokesman for the
opposition Conservative Party, said the proposals were unnecessary
and evidence of the government's ``obsessive nannying.'' Fox said
``smacking'' was often ``a necessary if painful'' task for parents.
</P>
<P>
   The proposals unveiled Tuesday apply only to England. A
spokesman for Hutton said local assemblies for Scotland, Wales and
Northern Ireland are obliged to make similar proposals as a result
of the Strasbourg court ruling handed down 16 months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's recommendation by the government to change the law
governing child discipline is just the latest in a series of
societal changes being wrought in Britain and other European
countries because of the Strasbourg court's interpretation of the
European Convention of Human Rights. Earlier this month, the
British government dropped its ban against gay people serving in
the military after the Strasbourg court ruled the ban violated the
convention's provisions on privacy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
