<P>
   STORM _A quick-hitting storm dumped up to half a foot of snow on
North Carolina, shutting down schools, local governments and
businesses from the mountains to the shore Tuesday. Bad weather
struck much of the nation as well. (Taylor, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   w/STORM-TRAFFIC _ GREENVILLE, N.C. _ Snow and freezing rain
cause dozens of accidents on area roads. (Fain, Daily Reflector)
ETA 7:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   STORM-SCHOOLS _ GREENVILLE, N.C. _ School officials are already
dealing with a shortage of make-up days as a result of last year's
flooding. Today's storm and school closings will add to this
probelm. (Batchelor, Daily Reflector).
</P>
<P>
   DAVIDIANS _ WACO, Texas _ Tuesday is the day the evidence is due
in the Davidian case. Checking on how much information government
turns over to plaintiffs. Will weave into story motion by
plaintiffs' attorney Mike Caddell questioning whether the Justice
Department is turning over original evidence or copies. Also,
Caddell filed a motion asking the court to make government agencies
state for the record whether any of their employees fired shots at
Mount Carmel. Only the FBI has said its agents didn't fire a shot
on April 19, 1993. (England, Waco Tribune-Herald)
</P>
<P>
   TRUCKSTOP-FIRE _WACO, TEXAS _ Look at cause and investigation
into fire at Elm Mott truck stop on I-35 north of Waco early
Tuesday morning. Two bodies have been located, presumably employees
who slept at the truck stop. Fire started about 2 a.m. A trucker
smelled smoke in a restroom. A waitress was sent to warn the two
employees. But the lounge area was hot and full of smoke. There was
no answer when the employees' names were called out.(England/GaaR,
Waco Tribune-Herald).
</P>
<P>
   WAR-CRIMINALS _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Five years ago Nazi
hunter Eli Rosenbaum sat in the Fort Myers, Fla., airport amid a
clutch of spring-break tourists. Sitting beside him was a
grey-haired grandfather returning to Canada. Once a prominent
homebuilder, the grandfather had fled his adopted country and
retired to Marco Island after Canadian officials discovered he once
belonged to a Nazi death squad under the notorious Einsatzgruppen.
Now Rosenbaum, having obtained deportation orders, was escorting
Helmut Oberlander out of the country. Like other snowbirds, Nazis
have flocked to this sunny land of leisure over the years. So, too,
have modern-day oppressors: Salvadoran generals accused of
orchestrating the murder of three nuns and a social worker, members
of Haiti's bloody paramilitary unit- FRAPH, which killed up to
6,000 in the early 1990s, and one of Chilean dictator Augusto
Pinochet's elite secret police, a squad responsible for at least 72
deaths. Many have been allowed into the U.S. because weak
immigration laws require that war crimes rise to the level of
genocide _ not mere atrocities like the torture of a few innocent
people. But that could soon change. (Staletovich, Palm Beach Post)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LUNAR-ECLIPSE _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Schoolkids across the
country have the perfect excuse to stay up past midnight Thursday.
Their science teachers will tell them to. The entire western
hemisphere will see a total lunar eclipse, when the Earth passes
between the sun and the moon, blocking the sun's rays from reaching
the moon. (O'Meilia, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
