<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-18 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9426 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT19-COX     01-18 0637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MICROSOFT CLAIMS NO ANTITRUST FAULT
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Microsoft Corp. told a federal judge Tuesday that
the federal government has failed to prove a breach of the
antitrust laws, even though the judge has branded Microsoft a
predatory monopolist.
</P>
<P>
   In a 70-page filing rebutting the government's claims,
Microsoft's lawyers said the Justice Department and 19 states had
``failed to establish the requisite causal connection between the
allegedly anti-competitive acts and the maintenance of the alleged
monopoly.''
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 5, U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson issued a
far-reaching set of ``findings of fact'' _ the first part of what
is to be a two-part ruling.
</P>
<P>
   In that finding, Jackson declared Microsoft held a monopoly in
personal-computer operating systems and that it had leveraged its
power illegally to harm consumers, thwart competition and halt
innovation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft respectfully disagrees with many of the court's
findings of fact and believes they are unsupported by the record,''
the company said.
</P>
<P>
   The main purpose of Microsoft's filing Tuesday was to respond to
proposed ``conclusions of law'' _ the second part of Jackson's
ruling _ that the government submitted last month, arguing that
Microsoft had violated antitrust laws in at least four ways. The
government will respond to Microsoft's own submission this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having an extremely popular product does not make a company a
monopolist,'' Microsoft said of its Windows operating system, which
powers 95 percent of the world's personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   The company's bottom line: even if the facts as presented by the
court are accepted for the sake of argument, the ``plaintiffs still
have not satisfied their burden under the governing law on any of
their claims.''
</P>
<P>
   The brief also cites Jackson's view that Microsoft's integration
of Web browsing software into its Windows operating system
benefited millions of consumers. That was one of the few nuggets in
his long ruling that gave the company any relief.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, Microsoft attorneys went to Chicago to meet with a
court-appointed federal mediator in a bid to settle the antitrust
lawsuit before Jackson issues his final ruling and, presumably,
begins to review proposed remedies.
</P>
<P>
   Those talks remain embittered even though the government has
denied several press accounts that will it seek to break up
Microsoft, either into separate operating divisions or into
similar-sized competitive chunks.
</P>
<P>
   While top Justice Department officials know these accounts of
its position on proposed remedies to be incomplete and
ill-informed, they say that they cannot discuss their true position
without violating a mutual secrecy pact.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the current posture of the case it would be
inappropriate for us to debate the merits of any particular
remedy,'' said Gina Talamona, a Justice Department spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Ballmer, speaking at a press conference last week called
to announce his succession as Microsoft's new chief executive
officer, said it ``would be absolutely reckless and irresponsible
for anyone to try and break up this company.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, in a teleconference with Wall Street analysts, Ballmer
said he believed the talk of a breakup was purposely leaked by
Justice Department officials in hopes of pressuring Microsoft to
settle quickly. ``I believe the leaks are deliberate. I don't think
there's any doubt about that,'' Ballmer said.
</P>
<P>
   If no settlement is reached, Jackson is set to hear oral
arguments Feb. 22.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass's e-mail address is andyg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
