<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-LADN </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following general
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs of
Jan. 19 and thereafter. For questions about stories, contact the
Daily News, (818) 713-3705.
</P>
<P>
   LAPD-CRASH (Los Angeles) -- The Los Angeles Police Department's
anti-gang unit CRASH would be renamed and its officers rotated
through with more frequency to save them from the lure of
criminality, under a recommendation stemming from the Rampart
Division corruption scandal. ``We don't want officers to stay too
long to become overly familiar with a particular criminal
element,'' said Los Angeles police Cmdr. Dave Kalish. The
recommendation comes from the Los Angeles police Board of Inquiry,
which proposes merging and renaming CRASH and the career criminal,
special problems and the narcotics enforcement units as the Special
Enforcement Unit. By Lisa Van Proyen. (Will move on the ``n''
California news wire.)
</P>
<P>
   GUNSHOW-TAXES (Los Angeles) -- L.A. County will give the L.A.
Fairplex up to $2.7 million in the next 6 years to cover revenue
shortfalls resulting from the supervisors' recent decision to ban
gun shows, a bill that has taxpayer groups and others firing mad.
``What is suggests to me is that the ordinance was pursued for
blatantly political reasons without regard for the financial
consequences to the county,'' said Jon Coupal, president of the
Howard Jarvis Taxpayers Association. ``This is what we get when the
county engages in social engineering. By Troy Anderson. (Will move
on the ``n'' California news wire.)
</P>
<P>
   CORTINES-LAUSD (Los Angeles) -- Keeping his promise of
downsizing LAUSD's bloated bureacracy, Superintendent Ramon C.
Cortines is closing three administrative departments, including
that of Francis K. Nakano, deputy superintendent of operations and
support services, and reassigning those administrators. By David
Baker. (Will move on the ``n'' California news wire.)
</P>
<P>
   GALPIN-CARS (Los Angeles) -- Galpin Motors, the nation's top
selling Ford Store, is undergoing a rennovation that will add the
Mazda nameplate to the company's broad collection of brands.
Galpin's Lincoln Mercury dealerships will be moved across the
street to make room for the new Mazda line. Owner Bert Boeckmann is
picking up the brand, formerly sold at Keyes Motors in Van Nuys. By
Suzie St. John. (Will move on the ``f'' financial news wire.)
</P>
