<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-18 18:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9432 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-GORE-IOWA-HNS &LR;      01-18 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-IOWA-HNS </SLUG>
  
 &HT;     BRADLEY CONCEDES HE'S A LONGSHOT TO DEFEAT GORE IN IOWA   (Eds:
Refiling to clean up coding, spacing problems)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAN FREEDMAN   c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  INDIANOLA, Iowa _
<TEXT>
Bill Bradley, seeking to lower expectations on his chances for
victory in Iowa, conceded Tuesday that he was unlikely to beat Vice
President Al Gore in the all-important Iowa caucuses next week.
<P>
   Bradley said he would be content to exceed 31 percent of the
vote in Monday's Democratic caucuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a difficult state when you're up against an entrenched
power,'' said Bradley, a former senator from New Jersey. ``We are
reaching out to as many people as possible. We don't have the
apparatus, the apparatus is with the vice president. But we do have
a lot of enthusiasm.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., won 31 percent of the party vote
in Iowa in his short-lived effort to challenge President Jimmy
Carter in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to do better than expected in Iowa. I look at the
historical performance of insurgents in Iowa, which is Ted Kennedy
in 1980,'' Bradley told reporters in Iowa City.
</P>
<P>
   With the strong backing of organized labor, Gore consistently
has led Bradley in most polls in Iowa, a pivotal state because a
victory there can boost the national standing of the winner.
</P>
<P>
   Gore spokesman Chris LeHane dismissed Bradley's concession as an
effort to soften an inevitable defeat. Several weeks ago ``they
thought they could win Iowa,'' he said, adding that Kennedy's
performance in 1980 ``was not thought of as a particularly strong
showing.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore kicked off a day of campaigning in southern Iowa with a
rally in Indianola, a town of 11,300 southeast of Des Moines. As
part of his strategy to abandon at least some of the trappings of
high office, Gore doffed his suit coat as he took the microphone in
the Simpson College gymnasium.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must recognize our obligation to extend the power of the
American dream to all Americans, because that's what we're all
about in this country,'' Gore told the crowd evenly divided between
college students in sweatshirts and baseball caps, and senior
citizens, including a contingent of war veterans.
</P>
<P>
   Elementary-age children ringed the running-track balcony of the
gymnasium holding Gore campaign signs.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president entered to the music of Tina Turner wailing
``simply the best, better than all the rest,'' and Paul Simon's
``Call me Al.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The presidency is a day-by-day fight for real people with real
problems,'' Gore said. ``Elect me president of the United States
and I'll fight my heart out for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore broke no new ground in the speech. Indeed, LeHane said it
followed a standard script of speeches he would give in nearby
Knoxville, Ottumwa and Burlington, which is on the Mississippi
River in southeast Iowa. In Knoxville, the American Federation of
Government Employees endorsed the vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has worked hard to turn back the popular image of him as a
stiff, wooden speaker immersed in the technicalities of government.
He grew up primarily in Washington, D.C., as a senator's son and
served in Congress 16 years before becoming vice president in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   But as part of his image-softening offensive, he was part
inspirational speaker and part talk-show host as he called out for
veterans of World War II, Korea and Vietnam to raise their hands in
sequence.
</P>
<P>
   After mentioning that he and his wife Tipper became grandparents
last year, he asked grandparents to raise their hands.
</P>
<P>
   Then he asked for the hands of those with 10 grandchildren, with
11 grandchildren, with 12 children and so on. He got to 21 before
one particular grandmother put her hand down. ``Twenty
grandchildren!'' Gore said as the crowd clapped.
``Congratulations!''
</P>
<P>
   Gore got in only one mild jibe against Bradley when he said the
40 million Americans who receive Medicaid should not lose it to a
``highly inadequate substitute.'' That was a reference to Bradley's
health plan, which would replace Medicaid with a income-based
subsidy aimed at bringing the poor into the mainstream of health
care.
</P>
<P>
   The two candidates sparred over the same issue Monday night
during their final face-to-face debate before the Iowa caucuses.
</P>
<P>
   In that debate, Bradley defended his plan, saying that ``only
politicians in Washington think Medicaid is a great system.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Gore talked about his family's roots in Tennessee,
his own bitterness over politics in the wake of his Vietnam War
service and the Watergate scandal in the early 1970s. And he talked
about his reawakening to politics as a young reporter covering
local and state government in Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president also found time for the local issues.
``Keeping our prosperity going and using it as a foundation for
these sweeping changes means also making changes to bring everybody
into the prosperity,'' Gore said. ``And the number one group left
out is farmers. We need to have profitability restored on the
farm.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS. &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Many of the college students appeared to be Gore supporters. But
Jay Shearer, a 21-year-old junior from Farragut, described himself
as a Republican leaning toward Texas Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   He attended the rally because ``I want to have an open
opinion.'' Would he ever consider supporting Gore? ``Yeah, there's
a good chance if he's that impressive.''
</P>
<P>
   Bart Elliott, a 20-year-old junior from Melcher-Dallas, said he
was leaning toward Gore because of what the vice president had to
say about rebuilding schools, connecting them to the Internet, and
providing smaller classes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said a lot of good things,'' said Elliott, who is thinking
about a teaching career and whose parents are teachers. ``I guess
it depends on whether he can come through with it.''
</P>
<P>
   With the polls showing Gore comfortably ahead of Bradley, ``It's
basically non-stop for here on out,'' LeHane said. ``You enter the
last six days with the basic goal of mobilizing your forces,
energizing them. We're going to fight for every single vote we
can.''
</P>
<P>
   As the crowd cheered for Gore's entrance, LeHane pointed and
said: ``Look! Energy!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
