<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-18 18:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9434 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-U.N.-ANGOLA-NYT     01-18 0708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.N.-ANGOLA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAVIMBI APPROVED DOWNING U.N. PLANES, FORMER ANGOLAN REBELS SAY
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ The Security Council on Tuesday saw videotaped
testimony from former rebels in Angola who said their leader
approved the shooting down of two U.N. planes a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had instructions to bring down any type of aircraft that
came within range of our anti-aircraft weapons,'' a former rebel
from the UNITA rebel army said in the videotape. Referring to the
rebel leader, Jonas Savimbi, the former rebel said, ``Savimbi said
that U.N. aircraft were in the service of the Angolan government.''
</P>
<P>
   The tapes were made by Robert Fowler, Canada's U.N.
representative. Fowler, who also heads the council's sanctions
committee on Angola, has just returned from a week in Angola, where
he made the tapes.
</P>
<P>
   There has never been conclusive evidence on what happened to the
two aircraft, which were apparently brought down by missiles on
Dec. 26, 1998, and Jan. 2, 1999. Twenty-two people are presumed to
have died, but their bodies have not been found.
</P>
<P>
   The former rebels later defected and joined the Angolan army.
</P>
<P>
   The information emerged as Fowler talked with former rebels
about UNITA's ability to arm itself despite international sanctions
against the movement. He was gathering evidence to be used by a
commission he formed last year to study how sanctions are being
evaded and by whom. In a report expected to be published in March,
the commission intends to name people, countries and companies,
Fowler told the council Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   All information being collected will be cross-checked against
other sources, he later told reporters, who asked about the
reliability of defectors now wearing Angolan army uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   The commission includes experts in arms, petroleum and diamonds.
Savimbi uses diamonds to pay for his weapons purchases, the
defectors said, contending that he saves some of the best stones
for himself. ``He doesn't use banks,'' a former rebel said.
</P>
<P>
   To stop the fighting, now in its third decade, U.N. sanctions
have been imposed on the rebels. They are supposed to stop the
rebels from buying arms and petroleum, and to prevent their leaders
from traveling abroad and having diplomatic contacts.
</P>
<P>
   In forming the commission, Canada, which holds a rotating
Security Council seat, has tried to broaden the action of the
sanctions committee. Diplomats see this as an experiment in getting
the committee work out of meeting rooms and into the field.
</P>
<P>
   Although the rebel forces have suffered serious defeats
recently, including the loss of airstrips in the southern highlands
vital to their foreign supply lines, UNITA continues to resist the
Angolan government and look for new ways to circumvent sanctions,
Fowler told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   His aim is to publicize the commission's findings in order to
expose sanctions-breakers and make it more difficult for UNITA to
resupply.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the outside world ceases and desists from providing
military assistance to Savimbi, he will not be able to maintain
this war,'' Fowler said. ``Responsibility for this war has been
squarely and unequivocally laid at the feet of Jonas Savimbi.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a huge volume of information out there indicating _
crystal clear _ that UNITA's arsenal is essentially east
European,'' he said. The same is true of the government army, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   In the Security Council gallery Tuesday were a group of Angolans
who wanted to deliver another message to the members discussing the
Angolan war. Daniel Ntoni-Nzinga, a Baptist minister who works with
the American Friends Service Committee in southern Africa, said in
an interview after the meeting that the world was still too much
focused on the two protagonists of the Angolan civil war.
</P>
<P>
   He leads a growing citizens' movement _ including labor
organizations, women's groups and religious leaders _ trying to
persuade ordinary Angolans to take an active part in building a
nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``War is not Angola's crisis, Angola's tragedy, but the symptom
of those,'' Ntoni-Nzinga said. The country needs a new identity and
an economy that works for all, not only for the warring factions,
he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
