<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-18 19:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9444 &Cx1f; tad-z
r p BC-IOWA-COX     01-18 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IOWA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dispatches from Iowa: if Kennis were president, things would be
a lot different
 &HT;    EDS. Second in an occasional series.
 &HT;    By Patrick Beach
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRIMES, Iowa _ What, you probably aren't wondering, motivates
the political fringe? Why, to pick three names, are Alan Keyes,
Gary Bauer and Orrin Hatch stomping around here, quixotically
stumping before voters who next week will head to the Iowa caucuses
and in all likelihood send some of these candidates packing?
</P>
<P>
   Keyes: mission from God. Bauer: mission from God. Hatch: Iowa
around caucus time more fun than Utah or wherever he's from. But
even these guys make it into the news here occasionally, and
they're allowed to debate their opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Mark Kennis, the most underexposed candidate in the
2000 presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   His organization is small; his campaign funds cover ``Kennis 4
President'' bumper stickers and little else. But Kennis is most
severely hobbled by his inability to travel: He has to check with
his probation officer every time he wants to leave Polk County, and
his driver's license has been revoked. Kennis, who hosts a local
cable-access TV show called ``Big People News,'' on which he
rambles about discrimination against persons of girth, is a
convicted felon, having been busted along with his 25-year old son
for possession of marijuana with intent to deliver. Under the
strictest reading of the law, this prohibits Kennis from voting,
let alone leading the free world into a new century. So Kennis, who
long pledged to fight laws prohibiting felons convicted on drug
charges from running from office, cannot run for office because
he's a convicted felon. And that's just one of dozens of things
Kennis, 52, finds wrong with the system.
</P>
<P>
   It'd be easy to paint Mark Kennis as a wackball, a student of
unrealpolitik, someone with only a passing acquaintance with hard
reality. It'd be easy to do that if, all mockery aside, he didn't
exude a palpable longing to help the little guy. I drove to Kennis'
home here just west of Des Moines the other day, sat in his
basement (which doubles as a production facility for ``Big People
News'') and listened. Go ahead and laugh, but if Mark Kennis were
president, things would be a lot different.
</P>
<P>
   Guns would be outlawed and pot would be legal. Everybody would
get to go to college, and college would include more vocational
training. A worldwide disarmament agreement would be negotiated.The
U.S. would end the embargo against Cuba. Voters would have real
choices between candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Democratic Party, all it is is the left wing of the
Republican Party,'' said Kennis, who claims to vote for the
candidate, not the party. (In the '96 election, he says he voted
for himself.)
</P>
<P>
   Well, who can argue with that? Not the New York Times' R.W.
Apple, who years back so devastatingly labeled the two-party system
as the culprit in limiting voters' choices between ``tweedle-dumb''
and ``tweedle-dumber.'' The mass scramble for the middle leaves
non-mainstream voters to seek and support candidates who,
unburdened by so much as a snowball's chance of getting elected,
are free to say what they really believe.
</P>
<P>
   And in intraparty squabbling the stakes are smaller still, a
point that was made numbingly clear at the most recent exercise in
redundancy and media overkill _ Monday's Black &AMP; Brown Forum
between Al Gore and Bill Bradley at North High School in Des
Moines. These two agree on almost everything except which one
should get the Democratic nomination. The questions _ pointed,
substantive questions dealing mostly with minority issues _ led to
interchangeable answers and so much consensus that I feared Gore
and his opponent might hug when it was over.
</P>
<P>
   Racial profiling? Bad. Confederate flag? Bad. Minority
representation in the Cabinet? Good.
</P>
<P>
   As is usually the case, most of the political media watched the
debate not in the school auditorium but in a nearby gym that had
been converted into a filing center. (Yet another instance of
collective insanity: Media outlets spend tens of thousands of
dollars a week to keep their people on the trail so that they can
watch debates on TV, in this case courtesy of MSNBC.) The only
significant dustup between Gore and Bradley came when Bradley asked
why Gore didn't march into Bill Clinton's office and demand he sign
an executive order banning racial profiling.
</P>
<P>
   The answer, of course, is because Clinton's president and Gore
isn't, and what effect would such an order have, anyway? But Gore
didn't say that. He told Bradley that ``President Bill Clinton
doesn't need a lecture from Bill Bradley about how to stand up and
fight for African-Americans and Latinos.''
</P>
<P>
   The crowd loved it. The reporters reported it.
</P>
<P>
   Then, as the thing wound down, Gore and Bradley took a question
about whether those convicted of drug possession should have their
voting rights stripped for life.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Kennis' name didn't come up.
</P>
<P>
   You may contact Patrick Beach at pbeach(at)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
