<DOCNO> NYT20000118.0237 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-18 19:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9446 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-SERBIA-ARKAN-NYT &LR;      01-18 1022
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SERBIA-ARKAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELGRADE ATTRIBUTES KILLING OF SERBIAN LEADER TO MONTENEGRIN
MAFIA  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ The government of Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic had no role in the killing on Saturday of Zeljko
Raznatovic, the notorious Serbian paramilitary leader known as
Arkan, a senior Yugoslav government official said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arkan was simply a criminal, and he was killed by the
Montenegrin mafia that wants to take over Belgrade,'' said the
Yugoslav information minister, Goran Matic, in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   He confirmed a report in Tuesday's government newspaper,
Politika, that one of the gunmen was seriously wounded and is in a
hospital after an operation, adding that the hospital is in the
southern Serbian city of Leskovac.
</P>
<P>
   While the gunman has so far not regained consciousness, Matic
said, the police expect to be able to interrogate him about the
murder. ``I'm very glad we'll have an answer as to who killed
Arkan,'' he said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   He also promised new developments soon on a long-standing police
investigation of the November 1997 gangland-style shooting of a
politician close to Milosevic, Zoran Todorovic, known as Kunda.
</P>
<P>
   Todorovic was a close associate of Milosevic's wife, Mirjana
Markovic, and a senior official of her Yugoslav United Left party,
or JUL, and his death has also been widely laid at the door of the
Milosevic regime.
</P>
<P>
   Matic's comments were the first explicit denial of widespread
accusations by Serbian analysts and the political opposition that
the Milosevic government and its security forces had murdered
Raznatovic, the 47-year-old businessman, gangster and indicted war
criminal in a professionally organized hit on Saturday at
Belgrade's Intercontinental Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Together with the exclusive Politika report, which clearly came
from official sources, Matic's comments were an effort to stop
rampant speculation here that the murder was politically motivated
and had any relationship to Raznatovic's activities in the Croatian
and Bosnian wars. There, he fought with his own Serbian Volunteer
Guard and was indicted for his actions by the international
tribunal for war crimes in the Hague.
</P>
<P>
   Many in Belgrade believe that Raznatovic's hints that he might
provide the tribunal information about the role of Milosevic and
other Serbian officials in those wars was one of the reasons he
might have been murdered.
</P>
<P>
   But Raznatovic, clearly disaffected from the regime and allied
with former police officials opposed to Mrs. Markovic's party, was
also making overtures to the political opposition in recent months.
He was a supporter of Montenegrin President Milo Djukanovic, who
broke with Milosevic and has moved closer to the West.
</P>
<P>
   Raznatovic also had wide business interests, both open and
criminal, funded from the profits of his earlier work with the
secret police and the wars in Bosnia and Croatia, that ranged from
soccer clubs and bakeries to banking and gasoline smuggling. He is
thought to have had no end of possible enemies. But his reputation
and his extensive security made anything but a highly professional
hit unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   Killed with Raznatovic were a business associate in a casino,
Milenko Mandic, known as Manda, and a senior police official with
the Interior Ministry, Dragan Garic, believed to have been a
colonel.
</P>
<P>
   According to Politika, Garic and Mandic were killed so they
could not identify the two assassins, one of whom came up to them
in a cordoned off part of the lobby, greeted Raznatovic and then
fired at the three from close range, escaping unharmed, while his
associate was seriously wounded by a bodyguard before escaping.
</P>
<P>
   Matic, similarly, explained the presence of the police official
with Raznatovic as in the nature of his job, which was to deal with
foreigners for the Interior Ministry.
</P>
<P>
   ``His job meant dealing with foreigners, which meant that he was
often in the Intercontinental Hotel,'' Matic said.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that one of the assassins was injured, in police
custody in the hospital and that a serious police investigation was
under way, Politika asserted, should stop speculation about a
political hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``In any case, all the versions about a prepared liquidation,
`an act of professionals' carried out because of Arkan's
involvement in the war and due to activities of the Hague Tribunal
no longer hold water,'' Politika said, calling ``allegations of
state terrorism malicious.''
</P>
<P>
   The chief prosecutor of the tribunal, Carla del Ponte, has
denied that there were any direct contacts between Raznatovic and
the tribunal, though his 1997 indictment would not be unsealed
despite his death.
</P>
<P>
   The police found the wounded gunmen by checking hospitals
throughout Serbia, Matic said. ``The gunman had the option of dying
or going to a hospital,'' Matic said. Matic confirmed that the
police had not yet been able to talk to the man, and that he is
``in serious condition.''
</P>
<P>
   Many opposition figures and independent observers have said the
murder would probably not be solved, and some suggested the state
was behind the killing of Arkan, either because he had become too
powerful and independent or because he knew too much.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbian Renewal Movement of Vuk Draksovic, who says the
secret police tried to murder him in a car crash last October, said
the killing was ``confirmation that we live in a country of state
terrorism.'' In a statement on the Belgrade television channel it
controls, Studio B, the party said: ``Such brutal executions aim to
spread fear and general insecurity among citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   Politika said Raznatovic had known his killers, that he had
spoken to them, that they had left but then returned.
</P>
<P>
   Dobrivoje Radovanovic, a lecturer in criminology at Belgrade
University, told Glas Javnosti newspaper that given the charges
provoked by the assassination, the authorities were eager to show
the investigation was progressing. ``It will be better for the
authorities that Arkan's murder be solved, because such events
could turn against them,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
