<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-18 19:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9448 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-HOUSE-CHAPLAIN-HNS &LR;      01-18 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSE-CHAPLAIN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CRITERIA FOR HOUSE CHAPLAIN CRITICIZED AS BIASED 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By JUDY HOLLAND   
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When the House began seeking a new chaplain last
year, the search committee's list of qualifications included the
statement that it would be ``extremely beneficial'' if the post
were filled by a ``dedicated spouse and parent,'' a provision which
would effectively rule out Catholic priests.
</P>
<P>
   The 18-member House committee later jettisoned the spouse-parent
standard after it was criticized but some Democrats say the
statement indicated an anti-Catholic mindset that has strained
congressional relations after Republicans leaders later rejected
the committee' choice, a Catholic priest.
</P>
<P>
   The committee labored for more than three months to whittle down
an initial list of more than 50 candidates and come up with three
finalists. Ranked No. 1 was Rev. Tim O'Brien, the Catholic priest,
followed by the Rev. Robert Drvorak, an Episcopalian priest, and
the Rev. Charles Wright, a Presbyterian minister.
</P>
<P>
   After receiving the committee's recommendations, House Speaker
J. Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., and Majority Leader Richard Armey,
R-Texas, bypassed O'Brien and Drvorak and selected Wright, ranked
No. 3 by the search committee. Hastert has said he and Armey
selected the candidate they were ``most comfortable with'' but he
has declined to expand on that statement.
</P>
<P>
   The House will vote Jan. 27 on whether to appoint Wright.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Anna Eshoo, D-Calif., a Catholic and a member of the
committee, said the spouse-parent provision ``does raise some flags
and it does ring some bells.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That does reflect kind of a singular and not very broad
experience in life,'' Eshoo said. ``It certainly doesn't include
Catholicism in Christianity.''
</P>
<P>
   `` Eshoo and other House Democrats are demanding that Hastert
explain why he and Armey rejected O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   ``If in fact, the speaker wanted to directly appoint who he
wanted, why in God's name did they appoint a committee to do tons
of work and then have it come to this,'' Eshoo said. ``If you
overturn a bipartisan decision of a committee, I believe you bear
the burden of proof. I still believe the burden of explanation is
on them.''
</P>
<P>
   Eshoo also said she was deeply troubled over the kinds of
questions that O'Brien was subjected to when he was interviewed by
the search committee, including a question from Rep. Steve Largent,
R-Okla., about whether the priest thought wearing his clerical
collar would offend non-Catholic lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Henry A. Waxman, D-Calif., a committee member, said he was
``bothered'' that some Republicans on the panel didn't seem open to
the idea of considering a Catholic priest as their chaplain.
</P>
<P>
   ``By defining a qualification based on a chaplain being a good
husband and father, it would by definition exclude a priest,''
Waxman said. ``It seemed to me insensitive.''
</P>
<P>
   The committee's list of criteria for the chaplain's post
originally read: ``While not a qualification, it is extremely
beneficial that the chaplain have a strong family life, and is a
dedicated spouse and parent. Through this, the chaplain will be
able to reach out to the spouse and children of members who often
need help in adjusting to life in Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   Committee members contributed their own suggestions about what
would make an ideal chaplain. The result was a three-page list of
characteristics.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Cal Dooley, D-Calif., a committee member and a Catholic,
said some members complained that the spouse-parent statement ``was
inappropriate and it would certainly be prejudicial against a
member of the Catholic clergy. There was an acceptance that it
wouldn't be fair and it shouldn't be a factor.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Earl Pomeroy, D-N.D., who co-chaired the chaplain selection
committee along with Rep. Thomas J. Bliley, Jr. R-Va., couldn't
recall which committee member introduced the parent-spouse angle
but speculated that it may have come from a lawmaker with ``an
evangelical Protestant background.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might have been inartfully worded, or maybe it was
malicious intent,'' Pomeroy said. ``I don't know what it was.''
</P>
<P>
   Pomeroy, who supported O'Brien for the post, said he was
disappointed that the candidate ``with the greatest consensus was
not selected,'' adding: ``I thought the opportunity to select a
very well-qualified Roman Catholic priest would have been great. I
think it was a lost opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   In a written ballot, committee members placed checks beside the
names of their top three candidates. O`Brien got the most votes,
followed by Drvorak and Wright.
</P>
<P>
   Just before the House recessed for the holidays Nov. 19, the
task force sent the three names to Hastert, Armey and Minority
Leader Dick Gephardt, D-Mo. While Gephardt cast his vote for
O`Brien, the two Republicans chose Wright who has been working with
the National Capitol Presbytery on prayer breakfast groups in
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Judy Holland can be reached at 202-298-6920 or by e-mail at
Judy &LR; hearstdc.com)
</P>
