<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SYRIA-PEACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANY SYRIANS UNCONCERNED BY LAG IN TALKS WITH ISRAEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By SUSAN SACHS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAMASCUS, Syria _ In this cold and rainy capital, just an hour's
drive from the contested Golan Heights, the suspension of peace
talks with Israel has left many Syrians remarkably unmoved.
</P>
<P>
   ``The peace process will continue and it won't take long before
it resumes,'' said Ghassam Jeroudi, 21, the manager of a photo
processing studio, on Tuesday. He shrugged off the latest breakdown
as little more than a bump in the road toward the inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, few Syrians were so sanguine about the prospects
or even the payoff of an agreement with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   After the peace effort was set in motion at a conference in
Madrid in 1991, there were few face-to-face meetings between Syrian
and Israeli negotiators. In 1996, talks between the sides broke off
completely, and they resumed only a month ago under the direct
sponsorship of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The talks are now in limbo, after the second round ended last
week with no agreement on the main issues: borders, water rights,
security and normalization of relations between the countries.
</P>
<P>
   Still, like Jeroudi, many people here now seem to take for
granted that one day, probably sooner than later, the state of war
that has endured for more than half a century, since Israel was
born, will end.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five years ago, nobody thought Israel wanted peace,'' said
Mazzen Desouki, a seller of gold chains and jewelry who has three
nephews in the army, one of them serving on the Syrian side of the
Golan. ``Now it's changed, and we see the Syrian and Israeli
negotiators meeting each other. For that, people start to speak
openly about peace.''
</P>
<P>
   The Syrian government line, to be sure, is that Israel has not
shown that it is serious, at least about Syria's core demand for a
withdrawal from the Golan Heights to the border that existed
between the countries before the war of June 1967.
</P>
<P>
   Still, even as they have denounced Israel for not acceding
unconditionally to demands for full withdrawal, the official
government-run newspapers have focused chiefly on Israel's
negotiating strategy.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli prime minister, Ehud Barak, has said he wants a
peace treaty with Syria that provides normal diplomatic and trade
relations, and accepts that the cost will include the return of
land, although the exact border remains a subject for negotiation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue is that Israel is dealing with these matters as if
it is in the bazaar, buying and selling,'' said Yousuf Makdesi, a
political analyst for the largest Syrian daily newspaper, Tishreen,
in an interview Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   There has been no official Syrian response to the cancelation of
the next round, which was scheduled to begin Wednesday in
Shepherdstown, W.Va., and there is no indication that Syria intends
to turn its back completely on the negotiations. It has agreed to
send experts to the United States to discuss technical issues, but
not its foreign minister, Farouk al-Sharaa, who led the Syrians in
the first two rounds of talks.
</P>
<P>
   Makdesi, a leading commentator for the government media, praised
the Clinton administration for its handling of the negotiations, an
indication of the enduring Syrian interest in using the talks with
Israel as a means of improving relations with the United States.
</P>
<P>
   He said a draft agreement drawn up by U.S. officials at the end
of the last negotiating session, a document meant to lay out the
positions of the two sides, effectively engaged the United States
as a more active participant in the peace talks. Syria has long
sought a direct U.S. role in the talks, while Israel has
traditionally pushed for direct negotiations with Arab states.
</P>
<P>
   ``By issuing the document, America has moved from the role of
mediator to the role of partner in the process,'' Makdassi said.
``In our political view, this means the U.S.A. is serious about
reaffirming its commitment to achieve a comprehensive and just
peace.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Kasaa shopping district, Tony Khouri said he looked
forward to just that.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a few years, we didn't feel that peace was really close,''
he said, as he surveyed the customers in his clothing shop, which
sells Syrian-made blue jeans and shirts. ``Now it seems we are
hearing something new. And when we have peace, everyone will be
more comfortable _ there will be more exports and imports, more
tourists. It will be good for the economy and for us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
