<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-18 19:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9457 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-WILLIAMS-DEAN-BOS &LR;      01-18 0548
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WILLIAMS-DEAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDUCATION FINANCE SPECIALIST TO HEAD WILLIAMS COLLEGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn.: Calif.; Schapiro is cq)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATE ZERNIKE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the nation's foremost experts on student financial aid
and the economics of higher education was chosen Tuesday as the new
president of Williams College.
</P>
<P>
   The college's trustees announced they chose Morton Owen
Schapiro, dean of the College of Arts and Letters at the University
of Southern California, to replace Harry Payne, who resigned
abruptly in October.
</P>
<P>
   The appointment is a return to Williamstown for Schapiro, who
began his teaching career in 1980 in the economics department of
the college. Colleagues and higher education leaders Tuesday lauded
him for his teaching, his scholarship, and his advocacy for higher
education issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is not only an excellent scholar, a fine teacher, and an
accomplished administrator, he is also a person with fine values
who understands so well why education matters,'' said William G.
Bowen, president of the Mellon Foundation and former president of
Princeton University. ``All of us concerned with the large purposes
that higher education serves in America have reason to be delighted
by this appointment. ... Williams is to be congratulated for having
recruited someone who can do great work while at Williams while
also advancing the nation's agenda for higher education.''
</P>
<P>
   Schapiro is a commentator on Public Radio International, as well
as a widely quoted expert on issues such as keeping college
affordable and changes in how schools use financial aid. He has
testified frequently before Congress on economic issues in higher
education.
</P>
<P>
   He is the author of several books, including, with former
Williams colleague Michael McPherson, ``The Student Aid Game,''
which was one of the first writings to identify how schools have
begun using aid as a way to enhance their rankings and reputations,
giving money to lure top students who don't necessarily need
financial aid, and abandoning decades-old practice of giving money
to the neediest students. Last summer, he and McPherson co-wrote an
opinion piece in the Chronicle of Higher Education arguing that
Congress should enact incentives for colleges to maintain a
need-based aid system, and urging the federal government to make a
formal commitment to helping the neediest students get the
financial aid they need.
</P>
<P>
   At USC, where he started as head of the economics department
before becoming dean in 1994, Schapiro continued to teach
everything from freshman economics courses to post-graduate
seminars. His third year there, he received the Senior Faculty
Award for Excellence in Teaching, Research, and Service.
</P>
<P>
   He said Tuesday he plans to continue teaching during his
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Morty is, above all, an outstanding teacher,'' said McPherson,
now president of Macalester College in Minnesota. ``He believes
deeply in liberal education, and he'll be completely back in his
element at Williams. Liberal arts colleges, including Williams,
face huge challenges in the coming decade. Morty Schapiro will help
Williams to preserve what's central to its purpose while leading
the kinds of change new circumstances require.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
