<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-18 19:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9461 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GORE-CAMPAIGN-ART-560     01-18 1127
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-CAMPAIGN-ART-560&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE PROJECTING NEW CONFIDENCE IN IOWA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BURLINGTON, Iowa _ After a bumpy start out of the gate, Vice
President Al Gore is acting once again like the Democratic
front-runner, and his aides say he can afford to.
</P>
<P>
   The surest and most obvious sign is that Gore is telling
audiences that he is going to win the Democratic nomination for
president. When a supporter at a black church yelled out on Monday
night, ``Run, Al, run!'' a revved-up Gore doubled over with
laughter and shouted back: ``I will! I will! I will! And with your
help, I'll win! I'll win! I'll win!''
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time that Gore, who has been in a beseeching
posture with voters for months, has made such a claim.
</P>
<P>
   But that was an unusual display. Gore is being careful these
days to contain his enthusiasm, lest he appear overconfident or
give the voters the sense that he expects a coronation.
</P>
<P>
   He has dropped his attacks, though, against his rival for the
nomination, former Sen. Bill Bradley, and is determined to give the
television cameras nothing but positive footage for the evening
news. This consists of the vice president beaming in front of
audiences that have been pumped up by the throbbing blasts of Tina
Turner belting out ``You're Simply the Best'' and Gore's upbeat
signature song from the 1992 campaign, Paul Simon's ``You Can Call
Me Al.''
</P>
<P>
   And he is stepping up his attentions to the leading Republican
candidate, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas. At rallies Tuesday, Gore
went further than his standard criticism that Bush would squander
the nation's budget surplus on a ``risky tax scheme.'' He said that
Bush would ``raid workers' pensions'' to pay for tax cuts and that
in Texas, the governor is ``waging war'' against organized labor.
</P>
<P>
   With less than a week until Iowa begins the nation's voting, the
polls show that Gore has a reason for confidence. Most recently, a
Los Angeles Times survey here put Gore at 58 percent, with 35
percent for Bradley. Internal Gore campaign polls show that Gore
leads Bradley in every category of voter except among those with
higher educations and more wealth. As a result, Bradley is faring
better in the college towns across Iowa, so Gore barnstormed across
these media markets in a bus tour today.
</P>
<P>
   Polls show that the Democratic race is still neck and neck in
New Hampshire, and a Bradley win there could send a strong message
to other states, like New York, where voters are perceived as more
open to Bradley's candidacy. But top Gore advisers also believe
that it is, as one said, ``mathematically impossible'' for Bradley
to secure enough delegates to win the nomination, and they are
turning their sights increasingly toward the general election.
</P>
<P>
   Gore advisers said the balance of power here in Iowa shifted to
Gore's favor after last Saturday's debate in Des Moines. That, they
said, is when Gore exposed Bradley as lax on farm issues.
</P>
<P>
   In the few days after that debate, Bradley appeared more
desperate, firing off one-day attacks on Gore _ for his support of
tobacco subsidies and for raising the specter of Willie Horton in
the 1988 presidential campaign. Gore advisers believe these hurt
Bradley more than they hurt Gore because Bradley appeared to be
violating his own assertion that he was a different kind of
politician who would not campaign using old votes and negative
appeals.
</P>
<P>
   A top Gore strategist said the goal is to drum up enthusiasm
among supporters but avoid negative news coverage. ``We want him to
set things on fire but not to self-immolate,'' this adviser said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Gore has been able to minimize the effects of the negative news
that has occurred, such as his reversal over whether the generals
he would appoint to the Joint Chiefs of Staff would have to support
his policy on gays in the military.
</P>
<P>
   Backstage, Gore is loose, light and ``laughing a lot,'' said his
close adviser, Andrew Cuomo, the secretary of housing and urban
development, who is campaigning with the vice president across the
state. ``He's at the top of his game,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Of Gore's tactical switch to ignoring Bradley instead of
demonizing him, Cuomo said that Gore has already convinced voters
that he has the experience and more thought-out positions on
issues. ``When you have won the case, you say `Thank you' and sit
down,'' Cuomo told reporters as the Gore campaign motorcade sailed
through a freakily spring-like, sun-drenched afternoon. ``You
continue to make your case, but since they are with you, it takes
on a different style.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of growling about Bradley, Gore is showing a touch of
whimsy. At a small labor gathering in Knoxville, where television
cameras outnumbered voters, Gore told the members of the American
Federation of Government Employees who were endorsing him: ``It
will be easy for me to be in your corner if you put me in an office
without any corners.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's campaign advisers are engaging in a campaign luxury _
lowering the expectations for Gore's showing in the Jan. 24 Iowa
caucuses. They do this by fretting in front of reporters over
Bradley's advantages _ a $1.6-million buy on Iowa television
(compared with $1.1 million for Gore), the perceived motivation of
Bradley's upscale supporters to get to the caucuses, and the
failure of the United Auto Workers union, the backbone of organized
labor in Iowa, to work actively on Gore's behalf.
</P>
<P>
   But behind the scenes, they are waging a ferocious grab for
precinct captains, motivating them by telling them to act as if
Gore is 5 points behind and must scramble to catch up.
</P>
<P>
   They have shifted into overdrive to identify Gore supporters and
are using mailings to prod them to the caucuses. And they are
flooding the state with surrogates for Gore, most notably members
of the Kennedy dynasty. Trekking to Iowa are Sen. Edward M.
Kennedy, Rep. Patrick Kennedy, former Rep. Joe Kennedy, Bobby
Kennedy Jr., an environmental lawyer in New York, and Kathleen
Kennedy Towson, the lieutenant governor of Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   Also on hand to make Gore's case: the model Christie Brinkley
and Sen. John Kerrey of Massachusetts, who served in Vietnam and is
especially helpful with military veterans.
</P>
<P>
   And the campaign has dotted the countryside with Burma
Shave-like signs, like this series outside Indianola: ``Grandma has
to decide between pills or food/ Putting her in a very foul
mood./Al Gore says to make Grandma happy/Make meds cheap and make
it snappy./Al Gore for President.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-18-00 1921EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
