u s BC-FBC-HERITAGE-COX     01-18 0389
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-HERITAGE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FBy Earnest Reese
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Heritage Bowl, which has been called the Black
College Super Bowl, appears to be in serious trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Held annually at the Georgia Dome the past seven years, the
event already had been hurt in by sagging attendance figures in
recent years. But the event might have received a knockout blow at
last week's NCAA convention in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Southwestern Athletic Conference (SWAC) commissioner Rudy
Washington was told by the NCAA that his conference would be
allowed to continue playing its league championship game, which was
held for the first time in December. But Washington also was told
that neither of the two participating teams would be allowed to
compete in any other post-season action.
</P>
<P>
   The probable result would be a Heritage Bowl matchup of a
third-place team from the SWAC against a third-place squad from the
Mid-Eastern Athletic Conference (MEAC).
</P>
<P>
   The conferences have sent representatives to the game for the
past seven years.
</P>
<P>
   ``To say the least, that leaves the bowl on awfully thin ice,''
Heritage Bowl director Craig Cason said. ``I don't think TV would
be interested in that kind of matchup.''
</P>
<P>
   Judging by attendance figures, fans have not been that
interested in most of the matchups since the bowl started in 1991.
With McDonald's as a title sponsor the past four years, bowl
officials had hoped the post-season battle between teams from the
historically black college conferences would have reached the
40,000-plus attendance mark as long as three years.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the average attendance over the past four years was
28,843. A month ago for Heritage Bowl IX, a crowd of 29,561 watched
SWAC champion Southern lose to Hampton, a team that finished third
in the MEAC.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could see this coming,'' Washington said. ``Atlanta just
didn't support it. We're going to work on it and see where we can
take it, because we've got some alternatives.''
</P>
<P>
   The first Heritage Bowl game, played in Joe Robbie Stadium in
Miami in 1991, drew 7,724; they watched Alabama State defeat North
Carolina A&AMP;T 36-13. The crowd improved to 11,273 for Heritage Bowl
II in Tallahassee, when Grambling beat Florida A&AMP;M 45-15.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
