<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-18 19:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9468 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-DELTA-PROFITS-COX     01-18 0661
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELTA-PROFITS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Delta profits dip as fuel prices take off
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Profits at Delta Air Lines fell nearly 10 percent
during its second fiscal quarter, as higher fuel prices pushed
industry earnings into a descent.
</P>
<P>
   Continental Airlines reported a 50 percent drop in quarterly
profits and announced plans for a $20 per round-trip ``fuel
surcharge'' to offset higher fuel costs, driven by the upturn in
oil prices since the middle of last year.
</P>
<P>
   The two big carriers posted earnings Tuesday, as did Southwest
Airlines, which also saw profits decline.
</P>
<P>
   Airline profits are expected to fall in 2000 after several
high-flying years. Fuel costs are a big factor, and industry
capacity growth is forcing more low-ball pricing to fill seats,
also hurting profits.
</P>
<P>
   The Continental surcharge _ essentially a fare hike listed as a
separate fee _ takes effect Feb. 1. But Continental could be forced
to scrub the surcharge if other major airlines don't match it by
then. None did so on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Continental said fuel costs rose 49 percent in the quarter that
ended Dec. 31, and warned it might lose money in the current
quarter without relief. Fuel is the second-highest expense after
labor at most carriers.
</P>
<P>
   At Delta the damage was less severe, with fuel costs rising 9.4
percent. Delta bought most of its fuel under purchasing contracts
negotiated while prices were low. It paid an average of 53.6 cents
a gallon, vs. 67 cents for Continental.
</P>
<P>
   Delta Chief Executive Leo Mullin said he was pleased with the
quarterly report and remains optimistic about the carrier's 2000
outlook. But he acknowledged Delta could face worse fuel inflation
as some of the hedging contracts expire later this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``If fuel prices do stay high...it would become a cost
challenge,'' Mullin said in an appearance on CNBC.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Delta posted a profit of $172 million, excluding
special items, or $1.24 a share in the quarter ended Dec. 31, down
from $194 million, or $1.29 a share, a year earlier. The results
easily beat the Wall Street estimate of $1.15 a share. Revenue rose
7.7 percent to $3.71 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Delta shares jumped $2.56 1/4 to $52.56 1/4 Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Delta's quarterly numbers showed a slight drop in passenger
yield, reflecting a weaker fare mix. Labor costs rose almost 10
percent, contributing to a 2 percent uptick in unit costs. On the
other hand, Delta enjoyed a 16 percent drop in commission costs as
it continues to cut travel agent payments. Like all airlines, Delta
endured a Y2K-induced slump in holiday travel that carried into
early January.
</P>
<P>
   Delta recorded one-time gains totaling $649 million, mostly from
the sale of shares in Priceline.com. It took a charge of $320
million for the planned early retirement of MD-90 and MD-11 jets,
although those planes will remain in its fleet for several years.
Including those items, Delta's quarterly profit was $352 million.
</P>
<P>
   Separately on Tuesday, Continental said it is in talks to buy
back the stake held by Northwest Airlines since a 1998 deal that
formed a marketing alliance between the two.
</P>
<P>
   Continental said it wants to continue the alliance but without
Northwest's ownership position. Northwest's 14 percent stake
carries 51 percent voting rights, although the deal was structured
to prevent Northwest from exerting management control.
</P>
<P>
   Continental chose the deal with Northwest over a buyout bid from
Delta. Continental's repurchase of the stake could raise questions
of whether it would become an acquisition target once again. But
analysts consider that unlikely for now, citing Continental's
stronger financial position and likely government opposition to
major airline mergers.
</P>
<P>
   A Delta spokesman declined comment.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Thurston writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
