<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-18 19:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9469 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-TECH-EZGOV-COX     01-18 0893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-EZGOV-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Counties go dot-com
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Two things bug Bryan Mundy: paper and lines.
</P>
<P>
   Companies such as CheckFree are using the Internet to make the
bill-paying process check-free. Online banking software firms like
S1 want to thin the Friday afternoon line at the bank. Both
companies are trying to convince others to think of the Internet as
the main medium for doing business.
</P>
<P>
   But no one has done the same for government in any substantial
way. Mundy's company, Ezgov.com, which was started in May, hopes to
make a business out of cutting red tape.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is catching on. In the next few weeks, the 8-month-old
firm plans to close cond round of venture capital funding,
between $25 million and $30 million. Ezgov.com would not say who
the investors will be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time I see mail or paper or people standing in line, it
makes my skin crawl because there's no reason for it,'' said Mundy,
Ezgov.com's co-founder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Government on the Internet is so wide-open. People are buying
books and airline tickets online. But no one is offering government
services,'' he said. ``Twenty years from now, all these things will
be done over the Internet. Someone's going to take us from now to
there, and we think we can be a part of that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta-based firm has signed deals with local governments,
including DeKalb County and Clarke County/Athens, as well as with
Riverside County, Calif., and Brazoria County, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Since August, DeKalb residents have been able to pay property
taxes and research deeds through EzGov.com.
</P>
<P>
   But Ezgov.com is not alone.
</P>
<P>
   IBM helped Arizona's Department of Motor Vehicles. A few
paper-based records management companies _ SDR Technologies and
National Information Consortium _ have shifted their business
models to the Web.
</P>
<P>
   A few start-ups also have attracted venture capital recently.
</P>
<P>
   Link2gov.com, a Florida company backed in part by Atlanta-based
iXL Enterprises, received $7.5 million last spring, including money
from GE Capital Partners and Flatiron Partners.
</P>
<P>
   Link2Gov.com, formerly Transsport.com, is automating some of
Washington, D.C.'s transactions, including vehicle registration
and, soon, parking ticket payments. The firm already offers the
ability to register for Georgia hunting and fishing licenses
online. The company expects to announce the ability to pay Mobile,
Ala., parking tickets online soon, said Joe Jones, a company
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Govworks.com, a New York-based firm, said it received a $19
million second round of venture capital in November. The firm
offers the chance to pay parking tickets and other local government
bills online.
</P>
<P>
   Ezgov.com was started in May by Mundy, 35, and Ed Trimble, a
31-year-old formerly with Andersen Consulting.
</P>
<P>
   The company employs 60 people working out of the same building
that, after renovation, will be the home of the new EarthLink
(following its merger with MindSpring).
</P>
<P>
   At Andersen, Trimble worked with clients such as Delta Air Lines
and MCI. In 1996, Trimble left to start InterArch Technologies,
which developed electronic-commerce applications. Mundy worked for
TicketMaster/CitySearch before joining Trimble at InterArch.
</P>
<P>
   Before investing more than $80,000 of their own money to get
Ezgov.com started, Trimble and Mundy researched the issue. They
said they asked people standing in line waiting to get their
vehicle tags renewed if they would rather be doing it from their
den.
</P>
<P>
   Then they talked to the people who run government agencies.
DeKalb County was the first to go online last fall.
</P>
<P>
   DeKalb saw the service as a way to become more efficient and cut
car pollution by reducing the number of people driving to a county
office to research property records or pay taxes, said Liane
Levetan, DeKalb chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Levetan said the county is considering offering the ability to
renew vehicle tags and pay water and sanitation bills and parking
tickets online.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm absolutely elated,'' Levetan said. ``The possibilities are
unlimited.''
</P>
<P>
   Ezgov.com also has attracted some big names. The board of
directors includes former New York Gov. Mario Cuomo, former
Congressman Jack Kemp and Zell Miller, former governor of Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, 67, has taken several board seats since retiring as
governor in 1999, including Georgia Power and Post Properties.
</P>
<P>
   Ezgov.com is his first high-technology start-up. Miller said he
was offered the chance to be on the board of two high-technology
start-ups when he first left office. He passed on them and later
regretted it, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a very high-tech person. I still have a hard time
sending e-mail,'' Miller said. ``But this one seemed to be the
perfect fit of where some of my knowledge and experience was.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller met with Trimble and Mundy at the Willard Hotel in
Washington last fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought they were really on to something,'' he said. ``I
never met a county official who didn't want to do something to make
it easier for his constituents. And I never met a constituent that
didn't want something made easier. I think it would be appealing
for everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Clothier writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
