r a BC-STORM-TRAFFIC-COX     01-18 0676
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STORM-TRAFFIC-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Meteorologist warns of 'black' ice on roads
 &HT;    By Travis Fain
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILEE, N.C. _ About an inch of snow fell Tuesday, causing a
round of closings and more than 70 automobile accidents in the
county, but few major problems.
</P>
<P>
   But the worst may be to come because of an expected freeze of
area roads, officials said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Commuters can expect to find hard-to-see ``black'' ice on the
roads this morning, though mostly sunny skies should clear things
up by this afternoon, according to Rick Brandy, a meteorologist
with the National Weather Service's Newport office. No new snow or
sleet was expected to fall last night, Brandy said.
</P>
<P>
   Local police ask motorists to drive slowly in what Brandy
expected to be ``pretty treacherous'' conditions. The Highway
Patrol suggests leaving plenty of room between cars and being
especially wary of shady spots and bridges where ice and snow melt
slower from the road. It's also important to go easy on the brakes
on icy spots to avoid losing control of the car, Highway Patrol
Sgt. John Tomer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you slam on your brakes on ice, you're just along for the
ride then,'' Tomer said.
</P>
<P>
   One-half to 1 inch of snow was reported across Pitt County
Tuesday, most of it falling between 6-10 a.m., Brandy said.
Employees at the city's water treatment plant measured eight-tenths
of an inch of snow Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   The snow brought ``just more fun and inconvenience at the same
time'' than serious problems, according to Greenville Assistant
City Manager Marvin Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Non-essential city employees were sent home at 3 p.m. and county
offices closed at 3 as well. East Carolina University canceled
Tuesday afternoon and Wednesday morning classes. Pitt schools were
closed Tuesday and were set to open 2 hours late today, unless
conditions worsen.
</P>
<P>
   City and county officials said Tuesday they'd decide today's
government office schedules early this morning. Closings will be
announced via local television and radio stations. Greenville bus
schedules and garbage and debris pickups should not be affected,
said Tom Tysinger, director of public works.
</P>
<P>
   The Highway Patrol reported 50 accidents in Pitt County by 1
p.m. Tuesday. Only one accident was termed major: a 10-car pileup
on the U.S. 264 bridge near Hastings Ford at about 7 a.m. One
person suffered injuries in that accident, Tomer said.
</P>
<P>
   In Greenville, 17 accidents were reported, 12 of them without
injury, according to police spokeswoman Melissa Bartlett. None of
the injuries were considered major and no multiple-car pileups were
reported, Bartlett said. Several minor accidents were reported in
other towns. Most of the wrecks involved drivers running off the
road into ditches, according to area police departments.
</P>
<P>
   Pitt County Memorial Hospital reported treating one person for
serious injuries from a car accident. The injuries were not
considered life-threatening, according to a hospital spokesperson.
</P>
<P>
   The N.C. Department of Transportation dispatched seven sand
trucks across the county Tuesday, concentrating on primary
highways, according to department supervisor Chad Fornes. As of
Tuesday night, no county roads were closed because of the weather,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Four sand trucks patrolled Greenville Tuesday and two truck
crews were on standby through the night, Tysinger said. The city's
snow plow wasn't needed, he said.
</P>
<P>
   For many Tuesday, life went on as usual despite the snow. Some
businesses didn't open and other owners reported a light morning,
but people stayed in their routines for the most part, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really wasn't all that bad,'' said Greenville resident
Beverly Sparrow, fresh from her grocery shopping just after noon.
``I mean, people panic.''
</P>
<P>
   Sparrow said she was on the roads by 9 a.m. She had an
appointment to keep at the beauty parlor, she said. She said she
was going to have her nails done later Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
