<HEADLINE>
HIGH COURT ALLOWS ALABAMA TO SEGREGATE HIV-POSITIVE PRISONERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ala., Miss., S.C., N.Y., Minn., Fla., Tenn., N.M., Conn.,
Ill.)   (bl)  
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court on Tuesday left intact a lower
court's ruling permitting Alabama prisons to segregate hundreds of
HIV-positive inmates and keep them from educational programs and
even from religious services where they might mix with other
prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   The justices turned down the prisoners' appeal without comment,
in an action that does not set a legal precedent.
</P>
<P>
   The inmates, supported by a coalition made up of public health
organizations and specialists in AIDS treatment, had argued that
the segregation violated federal disability law. They said the law
required individual assessments of each inmate's personality and
medical profile rather than a blanket assumption that all
HIV-positive inmates presented such a danger that there was no
``reasonable accommodation'' that could allow any to participate in
normal prison life.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Americans with Disabilities Act of 1990, those who
pose a ``direct threat to the health and safety of others'' can be
excluded from a program. The law defines ``direct threat'' as ``a
significant risk to the health or safety of others that cannot be
eliminated by reasonable accommodation'' or by modifying existing
policies.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit by the Alabama inmates was filed in 1985 under an
earlier federal law, the Rehabilitation Act, which also required
assessments of significant risk.
</P>
<P>
   The federal 11th Circuit Court of Appeals, in an 8-3 ruling last
April, concluded that the prison system's policy was justified
because AIDS is fatal, and ``death itself makes the risk
significant.'' The dissenting judges argued that the majority had
essentially adopted a ``no risk'' standard, instead of requiring
the state to demonstrate that a ``significant'' risk could not be
accommodated.
</P>
<P>
   Alabama was the only state prison system to segregate its
HIV-positive inmates when the suit was filed, but Mississippi and
South Carolina have now adopted similar policies. Alabama told the
Supreme Court that it has been notably more successful than states
without segregation policies in preventing the spread of AIDS
within its prisons.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The federal Bureau of Prisons does not use a segregation policy,
generally presuming that HIV-positive inmates can suitably be
housed and placed in programs with other inmates unless there is
evidence to the contrary. Nonetheless, the Clinton administration,
asked by the Supreme Court for its views on the Alabama case, urged
the justices last month not to hear the appeal.
</P>
<P>
   The administration said in its brief that while it had doubts
about the breadth of the appeals court's ruling, that judges were
generally correct to defer to prison officials judgments about
their ability ``to control prisoners in various settings and
programs.'' Determinations about specific programs were not
appropriate for Supreme Court review, the brief said, especially in
the absence of a conflict on the issue among the lower federal
courts.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The case, Davis vs. Hopper, No. 98-9663, had challenged the
inmates' exclusion from some 70 programs, including job training,
education and work-release. While the prison offers the
HIV-positive inmates some alternative educational programs, these
were much more limited, the inmates' brief said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL ON 2 OTHER CASES FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
