A9487 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-ISSUEADS-COX     01-18 0887
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISSUEADS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Issue ads getting more airtime although some politicos object
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The presidential campaign is revving into high gear
in Iowa and New Hampshire, and once again the airwaves are
crackling with political ads.
</P>
<P>
   But not all the advertisements are coming from the candidates. A
handful of special interest groups are buying up time to shape the
political debate or attack the contenders.
</P>
<P>
   Three groups with strong ties to the Republican Party have
launched attacks against publisher Steve Forbes and Sen. John
McCain (R-Ariz.), both of whom are seeking to defeat Texas Gov.
George W. Bush for the Republican nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes, who once chaired a nonprofit organization that spent
heavily on political issue advertising, is now pursuing a complaint
with the Federal Election Commission to fight back against the
issue ads running against him.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, an architect of campaign finance reform, is using the
ads by Americans for Tax Reform and National Right-to-Life to make
the case for reducing the role of special interest groups in
politics. ``I'm a threat to the iron triangle in Washington,''
McCain proclaimed at a campaign stop last week in Merrimack, N.H.
``That's big money, lobbyists and the legislative process.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sierra Club, meanwhile, which has a history of supporting
Democratic candidates, just completed an attack on Bush's
environmental record in ads running in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of issue advertising complain that it subverts campaign
finance laws because the political parties pay for them with ``soft
money,'' unregulated contributions from unions and corporations.
</P>
<P>
   Issue ads run by independent groups are paid for with unreported
contributions that can be tax-exempt for the organization.
</P>
<P>
   This year, analysts say, the first issue ads of the 2000
campaign appear to be continuing the trend set in 1998 when
interest groups and political parties became the source of most of
the negative advertising aired on television. Kathleen Hall
Jamison, director of the Annenberg Center for Social Policy, which
studies issue advocacy, said special interest groups, not the
political parties, have so far been the dominant players.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is less party advertising at this point than one would
have expected,'' Jamison said. And so far, organized labor, a big
player in the 1996 elections, has been silent, reflecting the
belief that grass-roots organizing is more effective. Spokesmen for
the two political parties in Washington said they view issue
advertising as a central role of the parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the responsibility of the party to bring to the fore
issues that the media would ignore,'' said Republican spokesman
Mike Collins.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic spokesman Rick Hess said, ``There is nothing wrong
with telling the truth about someone's record on an issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Typical of the special interest advertising this year, Jamison
said, is the Sierra Club spot attacking Bush on his environmental
record. Both ads feature an 11-year-old boy with asthma and
essentially accuse Bush of worsening the boy's condition because of
his failure to adopt tough environmental policies. So far, the
Republican National Committee is the only party organization to
wade into the Iowa caucuses and the New Hampshire primary. The RNC
is running ads in both places that criticize Vice President Al Gore
for suggesting he would select members of the Joint Chiefs of
Staffs based on their acceptance of allowing gays and lesbians to
serve openly in the military.
</P>
<P>
   ``Call Al Gore,'' the ad says. ``Tell him the only litmus test
ought to be about patriotism.''
</P>
<P>
   The ad prompted the Human Rights Campaign, a gay and lesbian
advocacy group in Washington, to air a rebuttal spot this week in
Iowa and New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to refocus the debate on gays in the military
around the issues of equality, fairness and justice,'' said Human
Rights Campaign spokesman David Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the toughest advertising of the year has been targeted
at Forbes and McCain. Forbes is preparing to re-file a complaint
with the FEC over two ads aired in Iowa and New Hampshire by the
Republican Leadership Council.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent Leadership Council ad accuses Forbes of
distorting record on taxes. ``Steve Forbes' attack ad
distorts the truth,'' the ad says. ``Our research shows that
Governor Bush signed the largest tax cuts in Texas history.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Dal Col, Forbes' campaign manager, called the Leadership
Council a ``Bush front group,'' and accused the organization of
coordinating the ad with Bush's campaign, which would likely be
illegal under FEC guidelines. Mark Miller, the director of the
Washington-based Leadership Council, denied there was any
coordination with the Bush campaign. He also denies that the
Council is a ``front group'' for Bush, although he acknowledged
that a majority of the group's members are supporting Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``You put 100 Republicans in a room and 70 percent are going to
be supporting Bush,'' said Miller. ``That's why he's winning.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Foskett writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga. Mark Sherman contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
