<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-18 19:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9488 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-SCOTUS-RDP-2NDTAKE-NY     01-18 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-RDP-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: brief said.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There were also these developments at the court Tuesday:
</P>
<P>
   State Immunity
</P>
<P>
   There was considerable fallout from the court's two rulings last
week on the balance of federal-state authority. The justices dealt
with several cases raising related questions that had backed up
while those two were under consideration.
</P>
<P>
   Four were age discrimination cases, like the case from Florida
last week in which the court ruled that states are constitutionally
immune from suit by the employees under the law against age
discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee, New Mexico, Connecticut and Illinois had all appealed
rulings that had rejected their claims of immunity, and the
justices summarily vacated those rulings while also turning down a
challenge to an immunity decision that Minnesota had won in the
lower court. The court also disposed of several cases under the
Drivers Privacy Protection Act, the law barring states from selling
motorists' personal information, which the justices upheld
unanimously last week.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhat less expected was the court's action in vacating the
decisions in two cases applying the Equal Pay Act to the states.
The justices order the two lower courts to study the cases again in
light of last week's ruling in an age discrimination case.
</P>
<P>
   The lower courts in both cases had rejected claims of immunity
that New York and Illinois had raised in defending suits under this
1963 law. In both cases, female professors sued state universities
on the ground that male colleagues in similar positions were being
paid more.
</P>
<P>
   In both State University of New York vs. Anderson, No. 98-1845,
and Illinois State University vs. Varner, No. 98-1117, federal
appeals courts had ruled that in passing the Equal Pay Act,
Congress had acted within its authority to enforce the equal
protection guarantee of the 14th Amendment and overcome the states'
immunity from suit.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, in Kimel vs. Florida Board of Regents, the court
ruled that the Age Discrimination in Employment Act could not
overcome the states' immunity because age was not a category to
which the Constitution gives special protection. Sex is such a
category, however, with official discrimination on the basis of sex
having been accorded ``heightened judicial scrutiny'' under the
court's precedents. So it appeared that the age discrimination
ruling might not dictate the outcome of the equal pay cases.
</P>
<P>
   However, questions remain because while the 14th Amendment's
equal protection guarantee bars only those official actions that
amount to intentional discrimination, the Equal Pay Act bars pay
differences on the basis of sex without requiring proof of motive.
Following the court's instructions Tuesday, the 2nd Circuit U.S.
Court of Appeals, in New York, and the 7th Circuit, in Chicago,
will study this question and decide how these cases fit with last
week's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   The court took no action Tuesday on the question of whether
states are immune from suit under the Americans with Disabilities
Act, raised in a pending case from Florida on which the justices
have evidently decided to deliberate further. That case is Florida
vs. Dickson, No. 98-829.
</P>
<P>
   Immigrants' Privacy
</P>
<P>
   The court let stand a ruling that New York City cannot bar its
employees from sharing information with federal immigration
officials about the immigration status of foreigners who seek city
services.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute revolved around the interaction of an executive
ordered issued by Mayor Ed Koch in 1989 and the revision of federal
welfare law that Congress passed in 1996. Under the executive
order, a city welfare worker could not reveal that an applicant was
not in the country legally. Under the federal welfare law, state
and local officials are prohibited from restricting the
transmission of such information.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately after that provision became law, New York challenged
it in federal court on the ground of state sovereignty. But both
the federal district court, in 1997, and the 2nd Circuit, in a
ruling last May, rejected the city's lawsuit and found that the
federal law preempted the executive order. In its appeal, New York
City vs. United States, No. 99-328, the city argued that Congress
had, in violation of the principles of federalism, ``commandeered
the city's legislative and executive policymaking apparatus.''
</P>
</TEXT>
