<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Snow forces school schedule adjustments
 &HT;    By T. Scott Batchelor
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, N.C. _ Tuesday morning snowfall meant fun for Pitt
County students but headaches for the school district's
administration.
</P>
<P>
   Officials already had lost 13 class days in the wake of massive
flooding from Hurricane Floyd. Reconfiguring the schedule left only
two days _ Feb. 21 and March 24 _ that can be used to replace days
lost to inclement weather.
</P>
<P>
   Pitt County Schools decided early Tuesday morning to cancel
classes because of the morning snows. Today's classes are scheduled
to begin two hours after usual start times.
</P>
<P>
   Superintendent Howard Sosne and the school board now will have
to come up with a plan for packing the proper number of hours of
instruction into the school year.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I think he's planning to do is discuss this with the
board and see if they want to use Feb. 21 as a make-up day or
explore options about 1,000 hours or 180 days,'' said schools
spokesman Barry Gaskins.
</P>
<P>
   State law normally requires 1,000 hours and 180 days of
instructional time. But in a nod to shortcomings caused by Floyd,
the state legislature gave school systems the option to provide
either 1,000 hours or 180 days, but not necessarily both.
</P>
<P>
   If that course is taken, school officials would add minutes to
enough days to compensate for the lost class day, Gaskins said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That in itself becomes complicated, but it is an option,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Without that option, Saturdays could become school days, said
Gaskins.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would probably be the last case,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials made the decision to delay school for two hours at
5:30 a.m. Tuesday, Gaskins said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then conditions got worse real quick,'' he said, prompting a
full shutdown of the system.
</P>
<P>
   While school leaders weighed how to fit the classroom hours, the
Howard family took advantage of the wintry weather and headed for
the snow-covered slopes of the large, earthen bowl at the corner of
Fifth Street and Reade Circle.
</P>
<P>
   Don and Joann Howard watched as their bundled up children,
Ginny, 6, and Lee, 10, both students at Elmhurst Elementary School,
careened down the powdered escarpment on plastic boards.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get to bring them out here and play, too,'' Joann Howard
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ginny launched from the hilltop and bulleted down the slope,
tumbling head over heels at the bottom.
</P>
<P>
   ``You wiped out,'' her mom yelled after her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mom, that was fun,'' the little girl shouted back. ``I want to
wipe out again.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee saddled up on his board once more, but he demanded an
audience for his exploits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Daddy, don't take your eyes off me _ watch this,'' and began
the accelerating slide across the compacted flakes to the bottom of
the ride.
</P>
<P>
   Surveying the white scenery all around, Don Howard remarked on
the snow.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is rare,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have so much fun,'' his wife said. ``We don't get it so
much to get tired of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
