<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCFLAG-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Clinton urges S.C. to pull flag
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. _ President Clinton added his voice Tuesday to
those opposed to the state of South Carolina flying the Confederate
flag atop its Statehouse, while a state senator refused to
apologize for his reference to the NAACP as ``that corrupt
organization known as the National Association for Retarded
People.''
</P>
<P>
   In remarks given to reporters aboard Air Force One as Clinton
flew to Boston, White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said Clinton
thinks the flag should come down.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not saying the Confederate flag . . . doesn't have some
historical meaning to it, but in this case it's wrong,'' Lockhart
said. ``It shouldn't be flown.''
</P>
<P>
   In South Carolina, a delegation that included former Gov. John
West met privately Tuesday with Gov. Jim Hodges on the flag issue.
Hodges is expected to address the flag issue during his State of
the State remarks to the Legislature today.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, as divisions within the state deepened over the flag,
state Sen. Arthur Ravenel refused Tuesday to apologize to the
National Association for the Advancement of Colored People, a day
after his widely perceived slap at the civil rights group helped
inspire a rally of 46,000 people marching against the Confederate
flag.
</P>
<P>
   Ravenel, 72, a Republican from Mount Pleasant, outside
Charleston, appeared in the Statehouse rotunda and said he was
guilty of a ``rhetorical error'' in his controversial swipe at the
NAACP on Jan. 8. However, he refused to apologize beyond a
back-handed retreat that he had issued a few days later in which
Ravenel, the father of a retarded person, apologized to ``retarded
folks of the world for equating them with the NAACP.''
</P>
<P>
   Ravenel read a statement Tuesday seeking to quiet the national
uproar that has given activists on both sides of South Carolina's
flag fight another point to argue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Immediately upon being told of my mistake, I apologized to all
those wonderful people laboring on behalf of the retarded with whom
I've worked for 40 years,'' Ravenel said. ``However, a chorus of
umbrage has arisen from others who choose to believe that my remark
was deliberate and directed at them.
</P>
<P>
   ``People of good will on either side of the controversy, being
appalled by the uproar, have asked me to help tone down the tenor
of this debate,'' Ravenel said. ``I have agreed. Enough said.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are things going on in South Carolina other than the
flag, you know,'' he said afterward. ``So we're all going to cool
it. I am, anyhow.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Did he apologize to the NAACP?'' asked state Sen. Darrell
Jackson (D-Columbia), a leading flag opponent. ``It is unacceptable
to me . . . I don't think he understands that when he insults the
NAACP, he insults our ancestors, our fathers, our mothers, church
leaders, many, many other folks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why can't he get the message that when you are wrong, you say,
I am sorry'?'' Jackson said. ``The longer he waits, the deeper he
gets himself into it. . . . To a man who loves the flag and loves
the history of this state, it seems to me he should realize that
his statements are hurting his cause.''
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Glenn McConnell (R-Charleston), a leading flag
supporter, said he was satisfied by Ravenel's statement. ``He is
reiterating that he did not mean to say it, that it was a
mistake,'' he said. ``In his opinion, he did not call them
retarded.'' McConnell said civil rights leaders recently have
insulted flag supporters, but have not apologized. He cited a sheet
entitled ``Heritage of Hate,'' which Jackson distributed Tuesday in
the state Senate.
</P>
<P>
   It quotes the Confederate Constitution and other documents from
the 1860s describing blacks as inferior and calling slavery
important to the South. Civil rights leaders say the Confederate
flag is a racist symbol of slavery, while its supporters say it
honors the Civil War dead.
</P>
<P>
   McConnell said Jackson's document ``makes it appear as though
everybody out in the field was fighting over slavery,'' said
McConnell, adding it ``is going to intensify'' the flag fight.
</P>
<P>
   Ravenel's remark had already stepped up the controversy Monday
when demonstrators marched on the Statehouse and demanded that
legislators remove the Confederate flag, the last to fly atop a
state Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is in your heart comes out of your mouth,'' said Lorna
Coakley, 40, of Mount Pleasant. She carried a placard aimed at
Ravenel's remark, reading, ``We shall overcome! The Slippery
Tongues!''
</P>
<P>
   She called the remark ``a blatant disrespect for other people,''
and said that she believed it ``backfired'' on Ravenel. ``It
spurred us on,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In a church rally preceding Monday's march, Nelson B. Rivers
III, the NAACP's national director of field operations, urged
supporters to avoid name-calling.
</P>
<P>
   He referred to Ravenel as ``nameless, faceless, hopeless.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Statehouse, where the Confederate flag flies atop the
dome, Fabia Owens, 38, of Columbia held a poster, reading, ``Vote
out the old, vote in the new. Senator Ravenel must go.''
</P>
<P>
   Owens called Ravenel ``poor quality. He does not need to be
sitting in that seat.''
</P>
<P>
   Etched with Ravenel's caricature, another placard read, ``A mind
is a terrible thing to waste.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Burritt writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
