<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-HUMOR-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN POLITICS, THE NIGHTLY MONOLOGUE CAN BE A NIGHTLY NIGHTMARE 
</HEADLINE>
 (jw) 
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ As the presidential primary and caucus season looms,
late-night television hosts are turning more and more to the
candidates, attacking their foibles and images with such barbed
glee that their shows have become required viewing among nervous
political strategists.
</P>
<P>
   The candidates and their aides can find the nightly monologues
by Jay Leno on NBC's ``The Tonight Show,'' by CBS's David
Letterman, who is recuperating from a bypass operation and expects
to be slinging barbs in about two months, by Conan O'Brien on NBC's
``Late Night,'' Bill Maher on ABC's ``Politically Incorrect,'' Jon
Stewart on Comedy Central's ``Daily Show,'' and on other programs,
at one level, funny, outrageous and obviously distortions of the
truth. At another level, though, the advisers say, the monologues
are playing a crucial, if flawed, role in shaping voters'
perception of candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the recent jibes: Gov. George W. Bush of Texas' campaign
slogan is ``governs like a Republican, parties like a Democrat.''
John McCain has such a temper that when asked to name his favorite
philosopher, he replied ``Latrell Sprewell.'' Vice President Al
Gore is so boring that when he painted a self-portrait it was a
still life. And Donald J. Trump just split up with his latest
model-girlfriend because she accidentally started a conversation _
that was not about him.
</P>
<P>
   Candidates are often terrified by the power of the late-night
television hosts to define weaknesses and quirks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their impact is incredible, and it's growing,'' Dan Schnur,
director of communications for the McCain campaign. ``During the
campaign season, you're often cowering at 11:30 _ what are these
guys going to say?''
</P>
<P>
   ``For a campaign like ours, Jay Leno is a lot cheaper than
polling,'' Schnur said. ``They often reflect what voters feel, and
their observations have a tremendous effect on how voters view the
candidates, much more so than the evening news programs. Audiences
watching Tom Brokaw or Dan Rather are wary about what they hear. By
11:30 they're relaxed, the monologues are like casual
conversations. They seep into people's consciousness.''
</P>
<P>
   Alex Castellanos, a Republican consultant, whose company,
National Media Inc., is buying commercial time for Bush, put it
another way: ``They have the power to create conventional wisdom in
politics; they'll set how a candidate is perceived in stone.''
</P>
<P>
   By every account, former Vice President Dan Quayle never
recovered from the avalanche of jokes about his intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once they have a take on you, once they decided what to mock
you for, it essentially becomes permanent and there's almost no way
of undoing it,'' said Mandy Grunwald, a top media adviser to
Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton's appearance last week on the Letterman show was
partly in response to Letterman's repeated jokes about her move to
New York to run for senator, and his on-air tauntings of her for
not coming on the show.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1992 presidential race, in which Ms. Grunwald was an
adviser to Bill Clinton, the campaign hoped each night that Leno
and Letterman would focus on the benign ``Big Mac'' jokes about the
candidate gorging himself on junk food instead of what she termed
``the other things'' _ Clinton's avoidance of the draft, his sexual
escapades and whether or not he had smoked marijuana.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Burnett, executive producer of the Letterman show, insisted
that ``we are completely apolitical.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no agenda,'' he said, ``other than do the best we can
do to get a laugh.''
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledged that his show and others had an impact. ``I
don't pretend we don't,'' he said, adding, ``We only take what
people understand about a candidate and make fun of it; we don't
really invent anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Leno said it made no sense to say that he had political power.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't change anybody's mind with comedy,'' he said. ``You
just reinforce what they already believe.''
</P>
<P>
   Leno said that he and his staff writers started the day with as
many as 500 jokes, all taken from events mentioned on television
news and in newspaper stories. They pare them down to 25 or 30 that
he may use.
</P>
<P>
   ``The audience has to know what you're talking about or else
you'll be sunk,'' said Leno, who described himself as a political
independent. ``You can't know more than anybody watching. And we've
found that once you get past secretary of state _ and even that's a
stretch _ no one knows what you're talking about.''
</P>
<P>
   Leno said that the television audience easily related to
Clinton's marital infidelity. ``Everyone knows someone who's
fooling around,'' he said. ``I can't really make jokes about atomic
weapons. People don't have them, don't know about them, don't want
to think about them. But fooling around by the president _ people
relate to that.''
</P>
<P>
   Burnett said that Bush was emerging as the prime source of jokes
for now because he was a significant candidate and because of the
impression, true or false, that he was a bit of a playboy in
college and grew up with easy privilege.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's now right at the precipice,'' Burnett said. ``If it's a
slow day it'll start to be the premise that people latch on to _
that George Bush may be a boob.''
</P>
<P>
   (Or, as Leno said on his show recently, ``George W. Bush
released his medical records today. It seems during the Vietnam War
he suffered memory loss when he crushed a beer can against his
forehead at a fraternity party.'')
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Some of the jokes are much more than mild jabs at missteps and
flaws. Pat Buchanan was treated to first-degree burns in the
hospital, Leno said in one monologue, because he stood too close to
a flaming cross.
</P>
<P>
   It is only in the last decade, especially with the plethora of
competitive late night comedy shows on network television and
cable, that political candidates and elected officials have borne
the brunt of so many jokes.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians, like Mrs. Clinton on the Letterman show, have
always sought to use television and the popular media to alter
their images. Richard M. Nixon, in 1968, made a cameo appearance on
NBC's ``Laugh-In'' and uttered the show's trademark line, ``Sock it
to me.'' During his 30 years on ``The Tonight Show,'' until 1992,
Johnny Carson made his share of political jokes and welcomed
numerous candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Among the candidates who have recently appeared on the programs
to show they could laugh along with everyone else were McCain, who
joked about his temper, and Bill Bradley, who joked about his
solemn personality.
</P>
<P>
   But many people in politics are not amused by the programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure Leno or Letterman can move a poll 5 or 6
points,'' said Lorraine Voles, former communications director for
Gore, from 1993-97, ``but part of the cynicism that people may feel
toward politicians can come from these shows.''
</P>
<P>
   But do the jokes always have an impact on the politicians?
</P>
<P>
   In the months leading up to his impeachment trial, Clinton was
the prime target of the jokes. (In a typical one from the other
night, Letterman said, ``President Clinton says he wants $30
million from Congress for contraception and family planning. Thirty
million dollars from Congress for contraception? It sounds to me
like somebody's going to go dating again.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the continuing barrage of jokes, Clinton's approval
rating went up.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-18-00 1958EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000118.0267 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-18 19:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9494 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-GUN-MAKERS-380(2TAKES     01-18 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUN-MAKERS-380(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUN TRADE GROUP PLANS TO BECOME POLITICALLY AND LEGALLY ACTIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ Feeling pressure from a succession of lawsuits
against gun makers, the trade organization that represents them is
collecting millions of dollars from its members for legal defense
and this week announced plans to support political candidates and
to lobby at all levels of government to fight greater gun
restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, the National Shooting Sports Foundation,
representing companies that make all manner of outdoor products as
well as firearms, had steered clear of political entanglements over
gun laws and elections, leaving the fight to the National Rifle
Association, an organization of gun owners whose interests can be
vastly different from manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   But in Las Vegas at the foundation's 22nd annual trade show,
Robert Delfay, the foundation president, said his group would join
the NRA in efforts to oppose forces that favor more laws and
regulations as a way to curb violent crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``Historically, we have not been politically active as an
industry,'' Delfay said in a state-of-the industry address Monday
night. ``That must change and will change. This upcoming election
will impact our industry, and we must have an impact on this
election.''
</P>
<P>
   More than symbolic, Delfay's remarks reflected a major shift in
strategy for the 39-year-old foundation, which represents more than
1,700 manufacturers and distributors of everything from camouflage
outfits to telescopic sites to the most elaborate of handguns and
rifles.
</P>
<P>
   To this point, the foundation has concerned itself chiefly with
commercial issues that affect products their members sell, like
regulations governing sales and distribution. By comparison, the
major thrust of the NRA has always been political and most recently
has been to support the enforcement of existing gun laws rather
than the passage of new ones. While the two organizations have many
interests in common, they diverge on some issues, like helping the
federal government track guns and exploring new technologies like
so-called smart guns.
</P>
<P>
   And now, recent lawsuits filed by the National Association for
the Advancement of Colored People and more than two dozen
municipalities, the first major assault on gun makers, have forced
the foundation to assert its own political agenda rather than to
rely on the NRA.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   As part of a new initiative, many members are contributing 1
percent of their gross sales to help the gun makers defend
themselves in the lawsuits, which are trying to force the companies
to make safer guns. The money has been coming in since the program
was announced at last year's trade show, and in an interview,
Delfay predicted that the donations could reach as much as $10
million a year.
</P>
<P>
   The recent threat of a federal lawsuit by the Department of
Housing and Urban Development to force the companies into an
omnibus settlement with the NAACP and municipalities, has spurred
further action by the industry group.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, Delfay said, the foundation has formed a
political action committee to influence elections in November.
Efforts are now under way, he said, to gather the names of
customers from member companies to establish an initial list of
500,000 people who would be encouraged to support gun-friendly
candidates for Congress and president, including any Republican who
opposes Vice President Al Gore or former Sen. Bill Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   In delivering the keynote address Monday night, former Sen. Alan
Simpson, R-Wyo., a gun enthusiast, encouraged industry officials to
get involved in the political process. He was especially critical
of the HUD lawsuit and said, ``You can do something about HUD. Get
yourself a new president, and you get yourself a new HUD.''
</P>
<P>
   He slipped in words of support for two candidates, promising,
``You won't hear any gun-control crap from George Bush and John
McCain, so remember that when you waddle off to the polls, for
God's sake.''
</P>
<P>
   It was an easy sell to gun makers in the audience, for whom the
gun wars have become a growing concern since October 1998, when New
Orleans became the first city to sue. Until then, the gun rights
banner was carried almost exclusively by the NRA, which spends
millions of dollars each year to influence elections at all levels
of government and fight passage of laws that would further restrict
gun ownership.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, 27 more jurisdictions have sued the gun makers, but
some have combined efforts, leaving 19 actual lawsuits to defend.
Of the four that have come before judges, three _ in Cincinnati,
Miami and Bridgeport, Conn. _ have been dismissed. In a fourth, by
Atlanta, the product liability claim was dismissed but a negligence
claim was allowed to proceed.
</P>
<P>
   ``My advice is stay the course,'' Douglas Kliever, the
foundation's general counsel, told members of the foundation.
``Above all, do not panic in the face of this litigation. The law
and fundamental fairness are on our side.''
</P>
<P>
   From the NRA's perspective, the new efforts by the shooting
group to exert political pressure can only enhance the power and
influence gun-rights proponents in the months ahead.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time an organization with the potential of the firearms
industry can participate in elections, it is a great assist to
everybody who believes in less gun control and more crime
control,'' said James Jay Baker, the NRA's chief lobbyist.
</P>
<P>
   He conceded that the NRA and the shooting federation might
disagree on some objectives. He described the two groups as a
``family at Thanksgiving dinner'' that might have differences. But,
he said, ``The lawsuits have certainly activated, invigorated and
expanded the industry to look at the political and legislative
landscape. We have noticed increased activity already.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides threatening their business operations, gun makers here
said the lawsuits also have made them a growing target of public
disdain. Many blamed organizations like Handgun Control, Inc., a
nonprofit organization that fights for tighter gun-control laws,
for orchestrating a campaign against them and distorting messages
that stress gun safety and crime prevention.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a security company for cities, states and homes,'' said
Ed Shultz, president of Smith &AMP; Wesson, one of the country's
largest gun makers. ``But we've been demonized.''
</P>
<P>
   For all that, however, Shultz and executives at other gun
companies said business has never been better. They said their
opponents' efforts to pass new laws and file lawsuits have rallied
their customers to buy more guns as a way to demonstrate support.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fair to say people are apprehensive about the future of
our industry,'' said Jeffrey Reh, general counsel to Beretta USA.
``Having said that, many times in the past when the fire arms
industry has come under attack, we have not only survived but
flourished. Our sales last year were very strong, and we project
them to be very strong this year, as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Reh pointed out that Beretta sells guns to police departments in
cities that are suing the industry, including Chicago, Los Angeles,
San Francisco and St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Just how and when comity might arise between the litigants is
unclear. Many company executives here said they do not even know
what a settlement might include. Delfay and other foundation
officials have already held informal meetings with federal and
municipal government officials to discuss a possible resolution.
</P>
<P>
   And, in time, some companies might be grow more anxious to
settle than others _ at least that was the impression conveyed by
Housing Secretary Andrew Cuomo, who has monitored the meetings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Keep in mind,'' Cuomo said in an interview from Iowa, ``there
is no one group. There is a spectrum. Some are more responsible
than others. Some are more political than others. All we want is
for them to design and distribute safer guns. Nobody wants to
outlaw guns. That is not the question.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
