<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia Review's Lindberg dies
 &HT;    By Rebecca McCarthy
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ Respected in literary circles for his intellect
and his editing abilities, Stanley W. Lindberg will be remembered
for his dedication to The Georgia Review, which he helped bring to
national prominence as its editor. But those who knew him best say
he will be missed most for the generosity, patience and nurturing
he showered on fiction writers, poets, reviewers and essayists _
anyone who loved literature and reading.
</P>
<P>
   Lindberg, 60, died Tuesday morning at Emory University Hospital
in Atlanta from complications following a lung transplant. He had
suffered with emphysema for a number of years before receiving a
donor lung at Emory in November 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stan was always so astonishingly welcoming,'' said poet Paul
Zimmer, who served as director of the University of Georgia Press
from 1978 to 1984. ``He was one of the great editors of our time,
and was also a beguiling and endearing man.''
</P>
<P>
   Lindberg's editorial talents were well-known across the country.
In 1999, he received the prestigious Nora Magid/PEN Award for
Editing, adding it to a raft of honors that included being the
first recipient of the Georgia Governor's Award in the Humanities,
a special award for continuing general excellence from the Georgia
Magazine Association and editing awards from the Coordinating
Council of Literary Magazines and the National Endowment for the
Arts.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it weren't for people like Stan, literary writing would go
down the tubes,'' said Robley Wilson, editor of The North American
Review. ``The Georgia Review is one of a few magazines that keep a
light in the window for good writing.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Lindberg's leadership, The Georgia Review's appeal
broadened to include articles on natural history, politics and
social science, and its circulation grew to more than 6,000. It won
a National Magazine Award in 1986 and has been a finalist in
various categories in other years. In its pages can be found both
well-known and little-known writers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stan paid no attention to names at all; it was the quality of
the work, period,'' said Oconee County, Ga., writer Philip Lee
Williams. ``That's the reason all of us who've been reading the
Review for years loved Stan. He was not only fair, he never
deviated from his standards for anybody. This not only made the
best writers write better, it gave hope to those trying to break
in.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams is on the board of directors of the Stanley Lindberg
Award, created last year to celebrate those who contribute to
Georgia's literary culture. Athens writer Terry Kay, another board
member, said that in losing Lindberg, ``we've lost a giant. He had
tremendous passion for the written word.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Corey, associate editor of the Review, worked with
Lindberg for 17 years. He recalls Lindberg's clear vision of the
kind of writing he wanted: It had to be excellent and enduring, and
it had to be readable.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could drop a copy of The Georgia Review on a chair in an
airport,'' Corey said, ``and somebody could pick it up _ an English
professor or a banker _ and it would be likely that person could
start reading a short story or an essay and be caught up by it. The
magazine has a high retention rate with subscribers. Once someone
reads it, they like what they read and keep on.''
</P>
<P>
   Born in Warren, Pa., Lindberg graduated magna cum laude from
Dickinson College in 1961, then served in Germany with the U.S.
Army for two years. He earned a Ph.D. in English from the
University of Pennsylvania in 1969, then taught at Ohio University,
where he co-founded The Ohio Review.
</P>
<P>
   He moved with his wife, Jeanne, and children Eric, Kristin and
Carl to Georgia in 1977 to edit the Review and join the English
department. He originated and coordinated The Georgia Review's
visiting lecturer series, bringing to campus speakers such as
Robert Bly, Robert Penn Warren, Sally Fitzgerald and Rita Dove.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the 1985 UGA Bicentennial, Lindberg conceived and
planned the ``Roots in Georgia'' conference, which drew 17 Georgia
writers to campus to discuss their works. Lindberg said once that
the conference was a warm-up for another event that proved a
literary triumph: assembling the living Nobel Laureates in
Literature as part of the 1996 Cultural Olympiad.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very time-consuming, but I think he loved working on
it,'' said Leslie Gordon, humanities co-ordinator for the Cultural
Olympiad. ``A spirit like Stan's ... it just doesn't die, the
people whose lives he touched, the writers he helped.''
</P>
<P>
   A memorial service is scheduled for 2 p.m. Saturday in the UGA
chapel. Among those speaking will be Athens writer Jim Kilgo, who
struggled Tuesday to articulate his grief. ``Stan had a generosity
of mind and spirit that I was a recipient of,'' Kilgo said. ``I
benefited from all of his gifts as an editor, but it was his gifts
as a man that truly enriched me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope the next editor will have the same high standards.''
</P>
<P>
   Rebecca McCarthy writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
