<SLUG> BC-GOP-2000-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
BUSH, McCAIN TRADE JABS ON TAX STANDS 
 
By R.G. RATCLIFFE 
and BENNETT ROTH 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSFIELD, N.H. _ In increasingly strident attacks on each
other's tax stands, GOP presidential rivals George W. Bush and John
McCain traded charges Tuesday that McCain would raise taxes on
average workers and Bush would tax the emerging Internet market.
</P>
<P>
   With both men offering New Hampshire voters tax-cut promises in
the final weeks before the Feb. 1 primary, Bush and McCain have
grown sharper in their efforts to undermine each other's
credibility as a tax cutter.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said McCain's plan to end write-offs for corporations that
offer benefits such as continuing education would effectively
increase taxes by passing the cost on to employees.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, meanwhile, sought to turn the tables on Bush by pledging
to support a permanent ban on Internet taxes and challenging the
Texas governor to do the same.
</P>
<P>
   In remarks at a Nashua Chamber of Commerce breakfast, it was
McCain's turn to talk tough on taxes as he brandished a pen to sign
a ``no Internet taxes'' pledge crafted by the New Hampshire
Citizens for a Sound Economy, a conservative fiscal watchdog group.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said he would not support taxes on Internet sales, ``not
now, not soon, never.'' And he added, ``I challenge all of the
candidates, including Governor Bush, to take the same pledge.''
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona senator was tougher on his chief presidential rival
in a written statement handed to reporters during his speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``By refusing to sign this pledge and rule out taxing the
Internet, Governor Bush is endorsing a tax increase that could
total over $160 billion by 2003,'' McCain stated.
</P>
<P>
   To back up those figures, the McCain campaign cited research by
a Cambridge, Mass., research firm, Forrester Research, which
calculated that sales on the Internet would total $3.2 trillion by
2003. Applying a sales tax rate of five percent to those sales
would amount to $160 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Three other GOP candidates _ Steve Forbes, Orrin Hatch and Gary
Bauer _ have signed the pledge, said CSE state director Richard
Killian.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he favors extending a moratorium on Internet taxes,
but that he would not rule out such taxes in the future. Many
states fear their sales tax revenue base could be eroded by
Internet shopping.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to make sure I understand what the world looks like
three to four years from now before I speak further,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've made it clear that I'm for extending the moratorium on
Internet taxes. Senator McCain needs to explain his tax cut plan to
the people, why raising taxes to the tune of $40 billion on
employer-related benefits is a tax cut,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush claims that by ending certain corporate write-offs on
employee benefits, McCain would cause the benefits either to be cut
off or the taxes on the benefits to be passed on to the employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you abolish employer-related benefits to pay for a tax cut,
it means working people are going to have to pay those benefits,''
Bush said. ``Either you get rid of the benefits by taxing them, or
you say that companies can't deduct them, in which case the
benefits will go away. I don't believe he (McCain) can have it both
ways.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said McCain has claimed the benefits portion of his plan
will cost corporations $40 billion. When reporters told Bush that
McCain's campaign said the cost was actually $4 billion, Bush
declared: ``Then his plan doesn't add up.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain said Bush is mischaracterizing his plan.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Spitzer, an Arizona state senator, tax lawyer and architect
of the McCain plan, said the idea is to end the deductions
employers can now take on tax-exempt benefits they give their
workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does nothing to the employees,'' said Spitzer.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, McCain has proposed cutting taxes by $237 billion over
five years. He has said it is irresponsible to cut taxes further
until the financial future of Social Security and Medicare are
taken care of.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's plan would deliver a five-year, $483 billion tax cut. He
says the only way to be certain that projected budget surpluses are
not spent by the federal government is to refund most of the money
to taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to groups of New Hampshire voters, Bush also subtly
attacked McCain for having one tax proposal in June and then coming
out with another last week. Bush said the plan he laid out in early
December has remained unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my plan today. This will be my plan next fall if I'm
the nominee of the Republican Party,'' Bush said. ``I can take the
heat.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
