<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BATTLE FOR GROZNY INTENSIFIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOZDOK, Russia _ Russian soldiers battled their way toward the
center of Grozny on Tuesday as the struggle for control of
Chechnya's capital entered an even fiercer phase.
</P>
<P>
   After a thunderous bombardment, Russian troops began moving
through Grozny's streets at dawn. It was the most intense ground
attack on the capital of the rebellious province of Chechnya in
nearly four months of fighting.
</P>
<P>
   Russian forces moved from the north, the east and the west in an
effort to fracture the rebel defenses and seize the heart of the
city. At times, Russian and rebel forces were within shouting range
of each other, just dozens of yards apart, according to Russian
television reports. Hurling epithets, the opponents fired at each
other at short range.
</P>
<P>
   Officially, Russian commanders insisted that they had not set a
deadline for recapturing Grozny, but some officers talked of taking
back the city in three or four days. There appeared to be general
agreement that the aim was to take Grozny before the presidential
election in Russia, scheduled for March 26.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are on the eve of the decisive storm of Grozny,'' said
Vyacheslav Ovchinnikov, the commander of Russia's Interior Ministry
troops, many of whom were fighting inside the capital.
</P>
<P>
   There was no way to verify the Russian claims of success. The
Russian military kept most reporters well away from Grozny
fighting. And the militants, who have been fighting from basements
and fortifications in the ruined capital, insisted they were
putting up fierce resistance.
</P>
<P>
   Also unknown was the fate of Grozny's civilians. As many as
40,000 civilians are believed to be still trapped in the city and
to have taken refuge in cellars, often without food, water or
medicine. Russian soldiers said they were trying to silence snipers
by blasting apartment buildings and houses in which they were
hiding, a tactic that increases the risk of civilian casualties.
</P>
<P>
   Alarmed by the escalating fighting, a group a soldiers' mothers
sent an open letter to Acting President Vladimir Putin, warning
that the air and ground assaults were claiming many innocent
victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``The military actions launched by the state's military
authorities in Chechnya are not helping to solve the conflict, and
are using methods outlawed by the Geneva convention of 1949 and
1977,'' the Union of Committees of Soldiers' Mothers said,
referring to the international accords intended to protect the
rights of civilians during war.
</P>
<P>
   In mounting its offensive, Russia's commanders are trying to
regain the initiative after a week of stalemate. Grozny was not the
only scene of bitter fighting. Russian troops and the militants
were also engaged in fierce skirmishes in the Argun Gorge, the
mountain ravine that connects the Chechen lowlands with Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   But Grozny was the main focus on Tuesday. Massive artillery and
air strikes, many carried out by Russian planes from the military
base here, just a few miles northwest of Chechnya, pulverized
apartment buildings and set some homes on fire.
</P>
<P>
   Then the ground attack began as Russian troops moved into Grozny
from the Staraya Sunzha region just north of the city. At the same
time, another group of troops entered the city from the Khankala
district east of Grozny.
</P>
<P>
   Russian military officials asserted that the forces had taken
some key objectives, including a bridge over the Sunzha River that
the rebels had used to supply their forces and to communicate with
their disparate forces.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian troops made their way toward the center of Grozny at
Minutka Square. Bislan Gantamirov, the leader of a Chechen
paramilitary group allied with Moscow, was reported to have twice
reached areas close to the city center before being forced to
withdraw.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time since the beginning of the second Chechen
campaign, our troops are in direct contact with the enemy,'' the
ORT television network observed.
</P>
<P>
   Aslanbek Ismailov, a deputy commander in chief of the rebels,
told Russian news organizations that the rebels intended to stand
their ground and would not abandon the city.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear, however, how many rebels still occupy Grozny.
The militants have made numerous attempts to break the Russian
blockade of the city, and they have also had their share of
casualties. Russian officers say the rebel force ranges from 500 to
several thousand.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the ranks of the militants have been reduced, as Russian
officers and Gantamirov's fighters suggest, it is far from clear
that the Russian military can subdue Grozny in a matter of days.
The militants are mobile, familiar with Grozny's streets, fight
well and make extensive use of snipers.
</P>
<P>
   Even a Russian breakthrough in Grozny would not signal a quick
end to the war. The Russians captured Grozny in the last war only
to have the militants take it back in a surprise counterattack.
</P>
<P>
   Further, there is still a sizable rebel force in Chechnya's
southern highlands. The militants have also shown their ability to
carry out raids and sabotage in the Russian rear areas. Militants
were fighting in Argun and Shali a little more than a week ago, two
cities in the lowlands that the Russians thought they had secured.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
