A9499 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-STORM-COX     01-18 0530
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STORM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Winter storm stretches along Eastern seaboard
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt and Gary Hendricks
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOCKSVILLE, N.C. _ Icy roads made traveling dangerous for the
second night in a row in North Carolina, which suffered the
Southern brunt of a winter storm that pushed temperatures to below
zero in the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is black ice and fog, ``said Tammy Burch, a cashier at
Horn's Auto/Truck Plaza just off I-40 near Mocksville, N.C.,
between Winston-Salem and Statesville. ``They are telling people
not to go out if they don't have to.''
</P>
<P>
   Trucker Steven Slatton, 43, said he counted 28 cars stuck on the
sides of the road during the three hours that it took him to travel
from Franklinton near Raleigh to Mocksville.
</P>
<P>
   The South was expected to begin warming back up today, but
below-freezing temperatures were expected to linger in the
Northeast most of the week.
</P>
<P>
   Flight cancellations and delays caused by the storm from Maine
to South Carolina forced delays at Hartsfield International Airport
in Atlanta early Tuesday, but operations were back almost to normal
in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Some delays of about 15 to 20 minutes persisted throughout the
day for flights coming into Hartsfield because of poor visibility
in Atlanta, according to Hartsfield officials. But as the weather
cleared, the delays dissipated, the airport said.
</P>
<P>
   The sudden storm dumped more than 6 inches of snow in the
Piedmont area of North Carolina, where many schools and businesses
were closed Tuesday. It surprisingly spared the western mountains,
which usually get the heaviest snowfalls.
</P>
<P>
   A 4-year-old girl who apparently got lost while playing with
friends in the snow Monday afternoon in a rural area south of
Chapel Hill was found alive but suffering from hypothermia about 10
a.m. Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's got a fight ahead of her, and we all need to be praying
for her,'' said Chatham County sheriff's Lt. Charles Blackwood, who
coordinated the search.
</P>
<P>
   The first major winter storm to reach the South this season
pushed out to sea off the South Carolina coast by Tuesday afternoon
but left lingering misery in the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   A Tuesday morning low of 38 below zero was reported at Enosburg
Falls, Vt. A low of minus 2 was reported as far south as Danbury,
Conn. New York City had gusty winds and temperatures in the teens.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, nearly 7,000 people stayed in homeless shelters
Tuesday, and two men described as homeless were found dead. One was
found on a loading dock Monday, when the temperature was 19 with a
wind chill of minus 16. The medical examiner said Tuesday he
apparently had died of exposure. The second man was found dead in
the backseat of a car he had apparently crawled into. An autopsy
was to be performed today.
</P>
<P>
   For the eastern seaboard, the drop in temperatures was dramatic.
</P>
<P>
   The high at Baltimore-Washington International airport on Sunday
had been 59. On Monday, the temperature got no higher than 29.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Burritt and Gary Hendricks write for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-18-00 2004EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
