<SLUG> BC-YANKEES-JETER-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES CLOSING IN ON $118.5 MILLION CONTRACT WITH JETER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT22 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ George Steinbrenner always has been reluctant to
invest long-term contracts in young Yankees players, but Derek
Jeter is a very special player and he is getting very special
treatment. The 25-year-old shortstop and the Yankees are close to
completing a seven-year, $118.5 million deal, which would be the
richest in baseball history.
</P>
<P>
   The negotiations could culminate within the next week in a
face-to-face meeting between Jeter and the Yankees owner, according
to a person familiar with Jeter's contract discussions. The Yankees
also are on the verge of finalizing a three-year, $25.5 million
deal with the pitcher Andy Pettitte, who, like Jeter, is eligible
for arbitration; the Yankees and other clubs exchanged proposals
with their arbitration-eligible players Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Jeter's representative and the Yankees are still negotiating the
construction of the shortstop's signing bonus, but if the final
numbers are close to the $118.5 million proposal, then Jeter's
average annual salary would be about $17 million per season.
Jeter's agent, Casey Close, declined to comment, as did Brian
Cashman, the Yankees' general manager.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Brown, a pitcher for the Los Angeles Dodgers, currently is
the highest paid player, after signing a seven-year, $105 million
contract in December 1998, for an average of $15 million per year.
</P>
<P>
   Though he has played just four full seasons, Jeter already is
considered one of the game's best players, and his achievements at
the outset of his career surpass those of some of the greatest
players ever. He accumulated 795 hits in his first four seasons,
more than Ty Cobb, Henry Aaron or Stan Musial, who are all in
baseball's Hall of Fame. Jeter has a lifetime average of .318, and
has scored 486 runs. The Yankees will seek their third consecutive
title this summer, their fourth championship in five years, and
manager Joe Torre has said repeatedly he believes Jeter would be
the Yankees' leader for years to come, inheriting the pre-eminence
that once belonged to Lou Gehrig and Joe DiMaggio.
</P>
<P>
   Jeter also possesses star quality, naturally thrives in the
spotlight, has good looks, outward confidence and a gracious manner
that has made him an idol among teen-age girls (teammates tease him
about the high-pitched screams that emanate from the stands when
Jeter's name is announced before each at-bats). It was as if Jeter
was made to play in New York and for the Yankees, teammate David
Cone said once.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Jeter's childhood dream was to play shortstop for the
Yankees, and nothing's changed that. But he is eligible for free
agency after the 2001 season, and Steinbrenner has never given his
young stars long-term contracts _ not Don Mattingly, not Dave
Righetti, not Bernie Williams.
</P>
<P>
   But Steinbrenner always has subscribed to the theory that you
succeed with superstars, in the American League standings and at
the box office, and retaining Jeter for the next seven years _ at a
high but fixed rate _ is a move that many baseball executives
believe is overdue. Steinbrenner waited for years to sign Williams
to a long-term deal, and when he finally gave in and gave Williams
an $87.5 million deal in November 1998, industry experts estimated
the delay cost the Yankees about $30 million. By the time Jeter's
proposed contract would expire, after the 2007 season, he might be
a veritable bargain, based on his salary.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming Jeter's deal is completed, he probably won't have the
largest contract in baseball for long, for the Seattle center
fielder Ken Griffey, Jr. and the shortstop Alex Rodriguez are
expected to seek deals in the range of $150 million later this
year. Kevin Garnett of basketball's Minnesota Timberwolves still
has the largest contract in the history of team sports _ a
six-year, $126 million deal. Michael Jordan made the highest
single-year salary, $33 million while playing for the Chicago Bulls
during the 1997-98 season.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees would forgo the arbitration process with Jeter and
Pettitte by agreeing to long-term deals, but they may face a
hearing with the closer Mariano Rivera and one-year settlements
with relievers Ramiro Mendoza and Jason Grimsley and the catcher
Jorge Posada and the reliever Jason Grimsley.
</P>
<P>
   Rivera asked for $9.25 million, while the Yankees' submission is
$7.2 million, a huge gap that could lead to arbitration. Mendoza
asked for $1.7 million, while the Yankees offered $1.1 million;
Posada is seeking $1.6 million, and the Yankees submitted a figure
of $1.1 million; Grimsley asked for $900,000, the Yankees offered
$650,000.
</P>
<P>
   Jeter asked for $10.5 million, a record request, even though
some in the Yankees' organization, which offered $9.5 million,
thought he might ask for more. But it figures that Jeter's
negotiations will be resolved long before the arbitration hearings
would begin in a few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The two sides are in the process of trying to arrange a
face-to-face meeting between Jeter and Steinbrenner, which usually
would be a simple matter. Jeter bought a house in Tampa, Fla., to
facilitate daily workouts in the off-season at the Yankees'
complex, where Steinbrenner appears frequently.
</P>
<P>
   But Jeter is scheduled to attend the wedding of teammate Jorge
Posada in Puerto Rico Friday, and if Jeter can't speak to
Steinbrenner Wednesday or Thursday, then the two could get together
next week.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte, 27, submitted an arbitration request of $8.45 million,
and the Yankees offered $6.5 million, but the three-deal deal
appears imminent. Pettitte, who could become a free agent after the
2000 season, pitched terribly in the first half of last season and
was on the trading block, and the Yankees arranged a deal with the
Philadelphia Phillies for three prospects. But Torre and Cashman
convinced Steinbrenner to keep Pettitte, who then went on to win
seven of his last 10 decisions and pitch effectively in the
postseason.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte is 81-46 in five seasons in the majors, and by signing
the left-hander, the Yankees would have some long-term stability in
their rotation. David Cone will again be eligible for free agency
after next year, as will Roger Clemens _ assuming that Steinbrenner
doesn't have an understanding to extend Clemens' current contract,
as many baseball executives believe. Orlando Hernandez, the
Yankees' best pitcher in the last two postseasons, has two years
remaining on his current four-year contract, at a rate of $1.85
million per season.
</P>
<P>
   As part of his new contract, Pettitte is expected to receive
salaries of $6 million, $6 million and $8.5 million for each of the
next three seasons, respectively, as well as signing bonuses. The
Yankees also will hold an $11.5 million option for the 2004 season,
with a $2.5 million buyout.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' payroll will surpass $90 million for the upcoming
season _ the largest in history _ but Steinbrenner, who hates the
suggestion that the Yankees' success is merely the product of high
spending, has been adamant in internal meetings to keep the payroll
under $100 million. The Yankees' recent trades of the pitcher
Hideki Irabu and the outfielder Chad Curtis likely will keep the
team below that level.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
