<HEADLINE>
ENTREMED TO FUND HOSPITAL CHAIR IN JUVENILE HEART DISEASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The company that's developing the experimental cancer
drug Endostatin says it will fund a Children's Hospital scientist
who has suggested that Endostatin has promise as a new kind of
weapon against heart disease.
</P>
<P>
   EntreMed Inc., of Rockville, Md., said Tuesday the two-year pact
provides an undisclosed amount of funding to Dr. Karen Moulton.
</P>
<P>
   She is a colleague of Dr. Judah Folkman, a Children's Hospital
researcher in whose laboratory Endostatin was discovered.
</P>
<P>
   EntreMed stock closed Tuesday at 41 3/8, up 7 5/8 on the Nasdaq
Stock Market, on news of the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Endostatin is a natural angiogenesis inhibitor found in the
body. Because it blocks the formation of new blood vessels that a
tumor needs to grow, it is being tested in human volunteers as a
new way of treating cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Endostatin's potential for treating heart disease emerged last
year, when Moulton showed in mouse studies that atherosclerotic
plaques that form in arteries need a blood supply in order to grow
_ and that Endostatin, by blocking these small blood vessels, can
halt the growth of plaques.
</P>
<P>
   Plaques, consisting of fats and connective tissue, can
dangerously narrow arteries and restrict blood flow. Plaques can
also rupture, triggering a heart attack or stroke.
</P>
<P>
   ``My work in this agreeement is still quite basic,'' Moulton
said.
</P>
<P>
   It will focus on understanding how the network of new blood
vessels develops in plaques and what factors in the body result in
their growth or destruction.
</P>
<P>
   Moulton spoke Tuesday from Snowmass, Colo., where she was
describing her work to a meeting of cardiologists.
</P>
<P>
   Among other possible applications, she said, cardiologists are
interested in Endostatin as a potential tool to prevent plaques
from reforming _ called restenosis _ after a heart artery has been
cleared with balloon angioplasty.
</P>
<P>
   In a prepared statement, Dr. John Holaday, president, chairman,
and chief executive of EntreMed, said the new agreeement
``reinforces our longstanding collaboration with Children's
Hospital, Boston.''
</P>
<P>
   EntreMed has provided about $16 million since 1994 to Children's
Hospital to support the work of Folkman's large Surgical Research
Laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   For more than 30 years, Folkman has been pioneering research
which has revealed the key role of angiogenesis in nourishing
tumors.
</P>
<P>
   He has also discovered a number of angiogenesis inhibitors that
are in early stages of human testing for use in anticancer
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Folkman holds no stock in EntreMed and receives no direct pay
from the company, an EntreMed spokeswoman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
