<SLUG> BC-NEENGLAND-WEALTH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INCOME GAPS LARGE IN NEW ENGLAND, REPORT SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN BARRY BOSTON GLOBE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a nation where the gap between rich and poor keeps widening
nine years into a sparkling economic expansion, New England's six
states show some of the country's widest and narrowest income gaps,
according to a new report.
</P>
<P>
   In Rhode Island, the poorest fifth of families saw their income
decrease 22 percent since 1988, while the wealthiest fifth saw
their incomes increase 28 percent _ making the Rhode Island income
gap the fastest-growing of any state's.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in Maine, the poorest fifth of families saw a 2
percent dip in income, and the richest fifth had a 5 percent
increase _ making Maine one of only four states where both top and
bottom incomes barely changed.
</P>
<P>
   The study, released Tuesday by two Washington nonprofits, paints
the picture of a nation where prosperity has nudged the rich and
poor into ever more distant worlds. In the late 1970s, there was no
state in the union where the income of the richest fifth was more
than 9.5 times the income of the bottom fifth _ now, that ``top-to
bottom ratio'' is higher than 9.5 in 24 states, and continues to
rise in all but three, according to the Economic Policy Institute
and the Center on Budget and Policy Priorities.
</P>
<P>
   Both Connecticut and Rhode Island have seen their income
distributions widen during the 1990s, while Vermont and Maine both
show very little change in the disparity between rich and poor.
</P>
<P>
   During a period of dramatic technological change _ which tends
to separate winners and losers economically _ neither distinction
is entirely good news, said analysts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in the middle of a technological revolution, and the way
that markets function is they create more inequality,'' said
Leonard Lardaro, an economics professor at the University of Rhode
Island. ``In an ideal situation, the disparity expands and then
hopefully the bottom pulls up.''
</P>
<P>
   But the authors of the study say the bottom isn't pulling up
fast enough _ especially for displaced manufacturing workers, who
are finding themselves stuck in lower-paying service sector jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1988 and 1999, Rhode Island lost 30 percent of its
manufacturing jobs, which earned an average of $34,000 a year, said
Nancy Gewirtz, director of the Poverty Center at Rhode Island
College. The service jobs that have contributed to Rhode Island's
record low unemployment rate earn, on average, $26,000, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty percent of Rhode Island families saw their incomes decline
over that period, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've built enormous malls that provided decent jobs for
construction workers, and now what's left?'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts blamed Rhode Island policymakers for relying too
heavily on the tourism industry to replace manufacturing, rather
than working to attract hi-tech firms, as Massachusetts did.
Massachusetts was among 15 states where the rich got richer and the
poor got poorer, but the gap is less dramatic than Rhode Island's _
the top fifth saw an increase in income of 18 percent, while the
bottom saw a decrease of 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The news came in very differently in Maine, the state with the
7th lowest income ratio between the richest and poorest families in
the nation.
</P>
<P>
   But the problems that dog Rhode Islanders loom equally in Maine,
which began losing shoe manufacturing jobs in the 1970s, then lost
textile manufacturing jobs in the 1980s, and is just beginning to
see paper manufacturing jobs decline, said Christopher St. John,
executive director of the Maine Center for Economic Policy.
</P>
<P>
   The difference, St. John said, could be simply that the
technological revolution _ with the skyrocketing salaries that
accompany booms _ has not quite hit Maine.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started from a base of much greater poverty, with a much
more compact income distribution, but we're headed in that
direction, of very rapid service sector growth,'' he said. ``To a
certain extent, you could say the Rhode Island and Massachusetts
economies are more modern.''
</P>
<P>
   The Center on Budget and Policy Priorities and the Economic
Policy Institute, which prepared the report using census data, are
non-profit groups which research policy that affects low- and
moderate-income people. Part of the goal of the study was to call
attention to the fact that ``manufacturing jobs, blue-collar jobs
that pay good benefits and what we would consider to be good wages
_ these jobs are being outsourced to overseas companies, and a lot
of these people are moving into the service sector,'' said Brian
Lustig, a spokesman for the Economic Policy Institute.
</P>
<P>
   State-by-state analysis showed that the average income of
families in the top 20 percent of income distribution was $137,500
_ more than 10 times as large as the average income of the poorest
20 percent, who earned $13,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
