<SLUG> BC-FBN-BELICHICK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS READY TO PAY TO GET BELICHICK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bill Belichick is clearly the man the Patriots want;
that was confirmed by sources among the 31 NFL owners who gathered
here Tuesday to approve Robert ``Woody'' Johnson as the new owner
of the New York Jets.
</P>
<P>
   If they must, the Patriots will pay compensation, because they
believe Belichick is the best candidate to run their organization,
but they will fight that as much as they can.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Belichick went before Tagliabue to plead his case for
being allowed to negotiate with other teams; Belichick resigned as
Jets coach and says he is no longer contractually bound to them.
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue, who attended one hour of the seven-hour grievance
hearing, said Tuesday he would pore through the briefs of the
hearing, then render a decision late this week.
</P>
<P>
   While Kraft dodged the Belichick subject in repeated questioning
by the media, Tagliabue did say, ``He just asked me this morning,
when we had the Finance Committee meeting, what was my timetable. I
told him what I had indicated to you earlier today.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the first official acknowledgement that the Patriots were
after Belichick and waiting for a resolution.
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue appears to want to get the issue resolved before Super
Bowl week, and Kraft also feels the sooner the better. The Patriots
have interviewed other candidates, but Kraft said they would ``wait
and see'' about interviewing more.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots kept an eye on the compensation situation involving
Marty Schottenheimer, who is still under contract to the Kansas
City Chiefs but was being considered by the Green Bay Packers. The
Chiefs originally asked for first-, second-, and third-round
choices before agreeing to one second-rounder. As it turned out,
Schottenheimer didn't take the job, and the Packers hired Seattle
offensive coordinator Mike Sherman.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, meanwhile, was approved by a unanimous vote of the
other owners, 29-0 (Atlanta and St. Louis were not present for the
vote).
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you have a great new owner here,'' said Kraft. ``He's
a passionate fan who wants to continue the tradition of the Hess
family and bring a champion here. It's great to see someone who's a
fan like he is own the team. He's so enthusiastic. I think it's
great for the fans of this region.''
</P>
<P>
   When the subject slid back to Belichick, Kraft said, ``I try to
talk about things I know a little bit about. I'm not qualified to
speak on it. I'll let the commissioner be our spokesman on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he would get the sides together to hash something
out, Tagliabue said, ``I don't currently plan to do that. My
current thinking would be to try and resolve the Belichick
arbitration by the end of the week. I don't expect to get to it
until tomorrow, but certainly by the end of the week I will expect
to get a decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Belichick's attorney, Jeffrey Kessler, argued that the Jets
never offered Belichick the proper title per his contract.
Kessler's interpretation is that Belichick was supposed to become
coach and director of football operations. The higher title now
belongs to Bill Parcells. Because of that, Kessler believes, the
contract should be void and Belichick should be free to go anywhere
he'd like, free of compensation.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots favor this interpretation.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson is now trying to persuade Parcells to stay aboard as
Jets coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love to have Bill Parcells coach another year, no
question,'' said Johnson, the heir to the Johnson &AMP; Johnson empire.
``He is a great coach. He has got two Super Bowls on his lawn, and
that says it all.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked if he had an idea which way Parcells was leaning,
Johnson said, ``Have you met Parcells? So you know the answer to
that. He is not a guy . . . if he doesn't want you to know, you
don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson did announce that Steve Gutman was remaining with the
Jets as president, and that Parcells thinks highly of Al Groh, who
would be Parcells's hand-picked candidate for head coach should he
not return.
</P>
<P>
   But the hiring of a coach may not happen so swiftly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would guess not,'' said Johnson. ``It's a critical time of
the year. To go through the landscape of coaching will take more
than 24 hours. We owe it to the fans to explore all options. We
really do. It's hard to find good coaches. There's only a handful
of choices. You have to make sure you make the right decision. He
has a very high opinion of Al Groh, there's no question.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson denied that he had offered Parcells up to $5 million to
stay as coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't remember making such an offer,'' said Johnson, who
said he spoke to Parcells for three hours last Friday and also had
a long conversation with him last Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is not the easiest person to read,'' said Johnson. ``In
fact, he's very difficult to read. He is a very unusual man and one
that has brought a life to this team, and we haven't had that for a
while.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
