<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-ROADBLOCKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRUG ROADBLOCKS UNCONSTITUTIONAL, COURT SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SACHA PFEIFFER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Massachusetts' highest court says roadblocks set up for
the sole purpose of snaring suspected drug dealers are
unconstitutional, saying they violate state protections against
unreasonable searches and seizures.
</P>
<P>
   In reaching its decision, the Supreme Judicial Court rejected a
government argument that intercepting illegal drugs outweighs any
invasion of privacy posed by a roadblock.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the court reaffirmed the legality of
roadblocks to check for drunk drivers, stressing that they, unlike
drug dealers, pose an immediate danger to the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absent an emergency or imminent threat to the lives and safety
of the public, roadblocks to interdict contraband,'' including
drugs, guns, pornography and other unlawful items, violate
constitutional protections against unwarranted searches and
seizures, said Justice Ruth Abrams, writing for the court in its
15-page opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Civil libertarians praised the ruling Tuesday, which they said
protects citizens from government abuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``A police state can set up roadblocks,'' said William Newman,
director of the western regional office of the American Civil
Liberties Union, which wrote a friend-of-the-court brief opposing
drug roadblocks. ``A democracy is not supposed to set up a
roadblock, seize citizens, and subject them to inspection and
interrogation unless there is an appropriate reason.''
</P>
<P>
   The ruling stems from what is believed to be the state's first
roadblock set up specifically to catch drug traffickers. Driving
down a one-way residential street in Holyoke in November 1997,
Hector Rodriguez was caught in a ``drug interdiction'' roadblock
organized by the Holyoke police department, State Police and the
local district attorney's office.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 58 drivers pulled over, only Rodriguez was arrested on a
narcotics charge: possession of the butt ends of two marijuana
cigarettes, which were found in his car by drug-sniffing dogs.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez later sought to suppress the marijuana evidence,
arguing that the roadblock violated his constitutional right to be
free from arbitrary interference by police. A District Court judge
ruled in Rodriguez's favor, but the Hampden County District
Attorney's office appealed to the state Appeals Court. The SJC
chose independently to review the case.
</P>
<P>
   In its ruling, the high court noted that the US Supreme Court
has allowed ``blanket suspicionless searches'' in cases where ``the
risk to public safety is substantial and real,'' such as at
airports and courthouses.
</P>
<P>
   And in 1985, the SJC ruled that sobriety roadblocks, in which
cars are randomly stopped and checked to screen for drunk drivers,
are necessary to reduce the ``carnage'' caused by drunken driving.
</P>
<P>
   While acknowledging that ``(t)he drug problem in the United
States is certainly grave,'' the court concluded that drug
roadblocks do not achieve an immediate enough effect to warrant
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unlike (sobriety) roadblocks, narcotics interdiction
roadblocks do not provide immediate protection to the public using
the roadways,'' the court wrote. ``Although apprehending narcotics
traffickers may have an eventual impact on the public safety, that
impact will necessarily be more remote and tenuous than the impact
of removing impaired drivers from the road.''
</P>
<P>
   The SJC noted Article 14 of the state constitution, which
prohibits unreasonable searches and seizures, was written in
response to British authorities conducting blanket searches of
colonists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Viewed in light of the Commonwealth's history, it is clear
that the Holyoke roadblock is precisely the type of search that the
drafters of article 14 sought to prevent,'' the court wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Holyoke is believed to be the first community in the state to
have set up a roadblock to screen for suspected drug dealers. In
the early 1990s, the city of Lawrence set up police checkpoints in
an effort to crack down on illegal drug activity, but did not
require motorists to stop or submit to searches. Instead, police
recorded registration numbers of passing cars.
</P>
<P>
   The danger of such roadblocks, said Newman of the ACLU, ``is
that people could be stopped for anything. The same analysis that
the Commonwealth used to justify this to could be used to justify
stops for parents who are behind in child support, people carrying
pornography, immigrants.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-18-00 2019EST &QL; 
