<HEADLINE>
NEWSPAPER GROUP URGES TEXAS JUDGE TO STRIKE DOWN BROAD RECORDS LAW 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ On the heels of a U.S. Supreme Court ruling that
makes information from driver's license applications confidential,
Texas newspapers Tuesday asked a state judge to strike down a
broader state privacy law.
</P>
<P>
   Media spokesmen said the 1997 state law, designed to restrict
public release of information from traffic accident reports as well
as driver's license applications, was unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   State District Judge Paul Davis, who enjoined the state from
enforcing the law a few months after it was passed, delayed a
decision on whether to make his injunction permanent.
</P>
<P>
   One section of the state law would require reporters and other
people seeking information about car accidents to provide the name
of a person involved in the collision as well as the date or
location of the mishap.
</P>
<P>
   Editors said that provision would make it difficult _ and
impossible in many cases _ for news organizations to obtain
essential information for news stories about public safety.
</P>
<P>
   Another provision of the Texas law would restrict the media _
under penalty of criminal sanctions _ from disseminating
information from accident reports on the Internet, which is now an
integral part of the news gathering and reporting efforts of most
news organizations.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Supreme Court last week unanimously upheld a 1994
federal law that bans states from disclosing information from
driver's license applications. The federal and more far-reaching
state law were passed to protect people from criminals and unwanted
solicitors.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Daily Newspaper Association and the Texas Press
Association conceded the high court's ruling on driver's license
applications. But they asked Davis to continue his injunction
against the broader restrictions in the Texas law and to block any
decision by the Texas Department of Public Safety to apply the
driver's license confidentiality provisions to traffic accident
reports as well.
</P>
<P>
   Media executives testified that the media has always had access
to accident reports.
</P>
<P>
   And David Donaldson, an attorney for the news organizations,
said the Internet restrictions amounted an illegal ``prior
restraint'' restriction on the media.
</P>
<P>
   Defending the state law, assistant Attorney General Heather
Horton said the dispute was really over privacy. She said the bill
granted citizens the right to keep certain information private and
to be ``secure in their homes.''
</P>
<P>
   Horton said the law didn't prohibit news reporters or other
people from obtaining accident reports.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only difference is they now have a few hoops to jump
through,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But media lawyers said the law, which was initially designed to
comply with the federal driver license privacy law, was
unconstitutionally amended to restrict access to accident reports.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush vetoed a separate 1997 bill that would
have restricted accident reports but signed the broader law.
</P>
<P>
   Donaldson said the governor either overlooked the extra
restrictions in the bill that he signed or felt that he had to sign
it so that Texas could comply with the federal law.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
