<DOCNO> NYT20000118.0285 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-18 20:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9518 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-JENNY-LIND-MUSIC-ART-     01-18 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JENNY-LIND-MUSIC-ART-2TAKES-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT THE THREE TENORS LEARNED FROM A SOPRANO  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 23) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(af) 
 Cori Ellison is dramaturg at the New York City Opera.  
 By CORI ELLISON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A recent search of the World Wide Web under ``Jenny
Lind'' turned up little that was edifying but plenty that was
utilitarian: cribs, furniture, ship figureheads, recipes, streets,
theaters and dams as well as a school, a hospital, a town and a
vocal competition, all named for the 19th-century Swedish
Nightingale.
</P>
<P>
   Though nobody today knows what she sounded like, Jenny Lind
lives on more vividly than many a more recent, recording-era diva
feebly commemorated in an ice cream sundae here or a chicken
fricassee there.
</P>
<P>
   If we still hear Lind loud and clear, it is mainly because her
career is the prototype for those of superstars today. Part
textbook, part cautionary tale, it was as minutely strategized _
and often as sincere _ as a modern political campaign. Were Lind
with us today, we would doubtless be treated to endless reruns of
her PBS television specials during pledge week, with the
Nightingale herself hammily hawking T-shirts and mugs during the
intermissions.
</P>
<P>
   One hundred fifty years ago Lind made a revolutionary tour of
the United States, and the American soprano Barbara Bonney has
seized the occasion of the anniversary to indulge her longtime
fascination with her Swedish predecessor.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday morning, Ms. Bonney will present a workshop, ``The
Legacy of Jenny Lind,'' at the Walter Reade Theater in Lincoln
Center as the first installment of her three-part survey of
Scandinavian song over the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The workshop will include a slide show assembled by Ms. Bonney
during her research at the Harvard Theater Museum, the American
Swedish Historical Museum in Philadelphia and the San Francisco
Music Library, and performances of songs written for or associated
with Lind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Julius Benedict's song `Greeting to America' was the result of
a contest to write a song in honor of Jenny's tour to America,''
Ms. Bonney said recently from her home in London. ``Wilhelm
Taubert's `Bird Song' was one of the Swedish Nightingale's favorite
numbers, and Isak Berg's `Herdsman Song' was famous for its
remarkable echo effect as well as for the sort of
Victorian-Scandinavian melancholy that was one of Lind's
trademarks. And `Hear ye, Israel,' from `Elijah' was tailored for
Lind by Felix Mendelssohn.''
</P>
<P>
   For all her ultimate fame and impact, Johanna Maria ``Jenny''
Lind began life humbly. Born out of wedlock in Stockholm in 1820,
she spent her early childhood shunting between relatives' homes
until, the story goes, a ballerina's maid heard the 9-year-old girl
singing through a window. Young Jenny was swiftly admitted to the
Royal Opera School, where she studied with Isak Berg and made her
stage debut in 1830, at 10.
</P>
<P>
   After appearing in many comedies and melodramas, Lind made her
formal operatic debut in 1838, as Agathe in ``Der Freischutz.'' She
soon tackled such diverse and taxing roles as Donizetti's Lucia and
Weber's -Euryanthe, Donna Anna in ``Don Giovanni,'' Pamina in ``Die
Zauberflote,'' Alice in Meyerbeer's ``Robert le Diable'' and Julia
in Spontini's ``Vestale'' (said to be her favorite).
</P>
<P>
   Did her crazy-quilt repertory display amazing versatility or
just the hubris-fueled mania that still infects ambitious singers?
All we know is that by the time she was 20, when she sang her first
Norma, she had not only attained some 400 performances but also
developed alarming signs of vocal wear, especially in her middle
register. Her baritone colleague Giovanni Belletti counseled her to
go to Paris and consult Manuel Garcia, the brother of the divas
Malibran and Viardot and a pioneer of the modern scientific
approach to vocal pedagogy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mademoiselle, you have no more voice,'' Garcia reportedly told
her. After three months of enforced silence, Lind studied with
Garcia for 10 months.
</P>
<P>
   She made a triumphant return to the Stockholm stage as Norma in
1842. All accounts report significant vocal and technical strides.
Yet Lind's tattered middle register would always remain relatively
weak. (``Veiled'' is the word most contemporaries used.)
</P>
<P>
   Adding Amina in ``La Sonnambula,'' Marie in ``La Fille du
Regiment'' and other roles to her repertory, Lind toured
Continental Europe. After singing in Berlin in 1844 at the
invitation of Meyerbeer, she conquered other German cities, Vienna,
and Copenhagen, where Hans Christian Andersen was said to have
fallen in love with her, vainly.
</P>
<P>
   Collaborating with Mendelssohn, the composer doubling as
conductor at the Leipzig Gewandhaus, in 1845, Lind found her
foremost musical soulmate. Though he did not live to write the
opera he had promised her, his ``Elijah'' stands as a potent
tribute, showcasing not only Lind's artistry but also her reputedly
splendid F sharp (a forte that most sopranos do not share and for
which they curse her).
</P>
<P>
   Lind's much-heralded London debut, delayed by titillating,
well-publicized contractual disputes, took place in 1847, before
Queen Victoria and Prince Albert. For this occasion, Lind cannily
chose ``modern music'' _ ``Robert le Diable'' _ avoiding the
merciless exposure of Mozart or bel canto.
</P>
<P>
   The audience responded with mild hysteria; the queen tossed Lind
a bouquet and recorded her ``triumph'' in a diary entry: ``She has
a most exquisite, powerful and really quite peculiar voice, so
round, soft and flexible, and her acting is charming and touching
and very natural.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone in London succumbed to ``Jenny Lind fever.''
``Atrociously stupid,'' William Makepeace Thackeray called the
soprano. ``I was thinking of something else the whole time she was
jugulating away,'' he wrote, adding that he had yearned to flee and
have a cigar.
</P>
<P>
   But Henry Chorley, one of the most credible 19th-century
critics, praised Lind's phenomenal breath control, glorious top and
shimmering high pianissimo. Most commentators conceded her
imperfect Italian and her limited dramatic range: from wistful to
pathetic, stopping short of heroic.
</P>
<P>
   Wagner noted her ``curious pensive individuality.'' Yet as with
most great singers, her appeal lay chiefly in her distinctive vocal
timbre _ what Chopin called ``a kind of northern lights'' _ which,
like the Bjoerling ``tear,'' the Caruso ``squillo'' or the Ponselle
``snarl,'' evoked an entire personality.
</P>
<P>
   The acclaim poured in. Verdi wrote the role of Amalia in ``I
Masnadieri'' for Lind, and she sang in the work's unsuccessful
premiere, in 1847 in London. And her popularity spread far beyond
opera audiences. She lent her homely name to such worldly items as
racehorses, lap dogs, dolls, a tulip, a pub and a whistling
teakettle.
</P>
<P>
   A railway tour of Britain, particularly a sojourn in Norwich at
the home of a Bishop and Mrs. Stanley, proved a turning point in
Lind's life. Something about churchy English Victoriana struck a
deep chord in her, solidifying her growing desire to quit the
``immoral'' opera stage for something more virtuous.
</P>
<P>
   No less important, Lind had hit on her recipe for success:
respectability. She was perfectly attuned to the middle-class
morality of England and its Puritan spinoff, the United States.
Donning lily-white gowns, shunning excessive makeup and jewelry,
and giving liberally and showily to charity, she made a high art of
her long-standing purity and earnestness, doing much to
rehabilitate the checkered image of female singers.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Pleasants wrote in ``The Great Singers,'' ``The
insignificant, snub-nosed, plain, simply dressed, hesitant,
unassuming, poor-little-me, pining for the northern homeland, pure
of heart and noble of thought, was the greatest of her roles.''
</P>
<P>
   Not yet 29, Lind made her final operatic appearance, in ``Robert
le Diable'' in London in 1849. Exhausted from overwork and two
broken marriage engagements, she was contemplating complete
retirement when she was approached by a representative of Phineas
T. Barnum, that legendary exploiter of American gullibility. No
matter that he was a musical yahoo and had never heard Lind; he
would market her as a curiosity, like Tom Thumb or a pair of
Siamese twins.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Lind was no Trilby to Barnum's Svengali. She wrote her own
contracts, handled much of her own publicity and retained complete
control over her repertory and colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   One of Barnum's dubious innovations was advance hype. He
generated all manner of bogus publicity about Lind, claiming that
she ``had changed all men's ideas of music as Bacon's system
revolutionized philosophy,'' that she had secretly married the Duke
of Devonshire and that her prim hairstyle concealed her lack of
ears.
</P>
<P>
   It worked like a charm. When Lind, along with the baritone
Belletti and the conductor Julius Benedict, sailed into New York
harbor in 1850, they were greeted by cheering throngs, serenades,
speeches and flowers, not to mention merchandising offshoots, as
documented in contemporary doggerel: &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (italics)Yes, all is Jenny Lind now,
</P>
<P>
   In ev'ry shop she's found;
</P>
<P>
   Jenny Lind you get there retail
</P>
<P>
   By the yard, quart, pint or pound.(end italics) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Beginning in New York and ending 18 months later in
Philadelphia, Lind traversed the eastern and southern United
States, racking up 93 concerts and $176,675 (more than $3.5 million
in today's currency). But this handsome profit was hard won. At
every stop she was obliged to receive a constant stream of beggars,
sycophants, aspiring musicians and autograph hounds.
</P>
<P>
   Fearful of sullying her angelic reputation, she never availed
herself of police protection. No wonder she also earned a
reputation for tetchy ill temper.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of her life was a denouement. In 1852, she married Otto
Goldschmidt, a devoted but second-rate German accompanist whom she
described as ``a model of virtue, industry and domesticity.'' She
bore three children, sang concerts in Germany and in England, where
she settled in 1858, and taught at the Royal College of Music from
1883 to 1886. But by the time she died quietly at her home in
Herefordshire in 1887, Jenny Lind had irrevocably changed the
topography of the music business.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-18-00 2024EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
