<HEADER>
A9521 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-ASSAD-BOS &LR;      01-18 0371
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-ASSAD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NAIVE DEFENSE OF ASSAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Americans who remember how rumors about Arab terrorists were
disseminated immediately after the bombing of the federal building
in Oklahoma City should recognize the need to overcome stereotyping
of Arabs and Arab-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   There is a genuine need for a group such as the American-Arab
Anti-Discrimination Committee. A Lebanese grandmother visiting her
family in America should not be detained for hours on arrival at
Logan Airport solely for the suspicious activity of being Arab.
</P>
<P>
   But the committee, also known as the ADC, did not serve
Arab-Americans when it objected last week to a statement by the
State Department's spokesman, James Rubin, who had said: ``We do
not regard Syria as a democracy . . . in any sense of the word. We
don't expect the Syrian government to submit any potential
agreement to the people of Syria for a referendum in the same kind
of way the Israeli government does so.''
</P>
<P>
   The ADC's complaint took a strange turn, repeating the
fundamental error of those who propagate anti-Arab stereotypes. The
ADC's chairperson, Naila Asali, said: ``Most Arab-Americans saw
Rubin's remarks as a condescending depiction of the Syrian people
in particular and the Arab people in general. Jamie owes all
Syrians and Arab-Americans a sincere public apology.''
</P>
<P>
   Asali's unfathomable mistake is to identify all Syrians and all
Arab-Americans with the dictatorship of Syria's ruler, Hafez Assad.
</P>
<P>
   Syrians, Lebanese, Palestinians, and Jordanians whose family
members have been imprisoned, tortured, or killed by Assad's
security services certainly would not agree with Asali. Indeed,
there are few Lebanese who do not regard Assad's occupation of
Lebanon as a kidnapping of their country. When they are able to
speak freely, many Syrians and Lebanese joke about presidential
elections in Syria, where Assad routinely receives 99.7 or 99.8
percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Syrians, nor Lebanese, nor Arab- Americans deserve to be
identified with Assad's police state. That is certainly not what an
American-Arab Anti-Discrimination Committee should be doing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-18-00 2026EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
