<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-18 20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9525 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-ASSESS-485&AMP;AD     01-18 1134
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-ASSESS-485&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: BARAK JUGGLES PEACE EFFORTS WITH SYRIA AND PALESTINIANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ When Prime Minister Ehud Barak first declared his
ambitious intentions to juggle the Palestinian and Syrian peace
efforts simultaneously, he said he could keep both balls in the air
and prevent them from touching, much less colliding. But that is
increasingly turning into a contortionist's trick.
</P>
<P>
   Barak has managed to keep both tracks alive by shuttling between
the camps, led by two Arab leaders, President Hafez Assad of Syria
and Yasser Arafat of the Palestinian Authority, who are longtime
adversaries. But the tracks unavoidably bump against each other.
</P>
<P>
   Time spent by the Israelis and the U.S. peace team on one takes
time from the other. Progress on one affects progress on the other.
Demands made and concessions wrung sit as mutual precedents.
</P>
<P>
   The problem was clearly shown Monday, when Syrian-Israeli
negotiations that had been scheduled to resume Wednesday in the
United States were canceled. Within hours of the cancellation,
Barak, his table cleared, was traveling to the Tel Aviv area for a
secretive night-time meeting with Arafat that ended up lasting four
hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we buy ourselves a little time to devote to the
Palestinians,'' an Israeli official said. The Israelis and the
Palestinians pronounced the meeting a success, and Arafat called it
a ``very important'' review of all outstanding issues.
</P>
<P>
   From the moment that Israeli-Syrian relations were revived in
December, the Palestinians thought that Barak did protest too much.
Every time that he assured them that his deep immersion in
Israeli-Syrian peace negotiations would not affect them, it
reminded them of the inherent conflict in time and energy.
</P>
<P>
   It was hard to ignore the interconnection, given that progress
between the Israelis and the Palestinians slowed immediately after
the Israeli-Syrian talks resumed. Israelis said the Palestinians
were dragging their feet. The Palestinians said the Israelis were
distracted _ and dragging their feet, too.
</P>
<P>
   When President Clinton invited Arafat to visit Washington this
week for what was to have been the third round of Israeli-Syrian
talks, he intended to reassure Arafat that the Palestinian peace
effort was still as important as ever.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Arafat, who will now be the only Middle East leader to
meet Clinton this week, is explicitly seeking affirmation that the
Americans will not let the Palestinian cause slide if the Syrians
advance, an adviser said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   From the other side, when Assad refused to send his emissary to
Washington for the talks that have now been canceled, it was at
least partly because Arafat was elbowing in on his show.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say Assad, 69, and Arafat, 70, see themselves in a kind
of competition to be the linchpin for peace in the region, although
Assad, newer to the peace game, does so with more ambivalence. And
both want to be courted and afforded international recognition.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Egyptian intermediaries have tried to persuade Assad's emissary
to Washington, Foreign Minister Farouk al-Sharaa, that he should
not see the Palestinians as competitors, a senior Egyptian aide
said. The Egyptians suggested that it would help win over Israeli
public opinion if Barak presented two peace treaties at once, the
aide added.
</P>
<P>
   But that is not necessarily the view in Jerusalem, and U.S.
officials also question it. Although negotiating on two tracks at
once is tough for the Israelis, making decisions on two tracks at
once could prove even tougher.
</P>
<P>
   Could Barak agree to give up the Golan Heights to the Syrians
and make concessions on Jerusalem to the Palestinians at the same
time? This was a question that he somewhat brushed off in the early
days of his premiership last summer, noting that a historical
moment had arisen that might allow him to do what his predecessors
did not dare. He seemed to believed that two nearly simultaneous
peace deals could create enough momentum to overwhelm domestic
opposition.
</P>
<P>
   But after a mass rally last week opposing Israeli concession of
the Golan Heights, the question restated itself in Jerusalem. How
much could the Israeli body politic absorb at once?
</P>
<P>
   ``In contrast to his earlier declarations, Barak today realizes
that it is impossible to conduct complex negotiations, which
include far-reaching territorial concessions on both fronts
simultaneously,'' Shimon Shiffer, a diplomatic correspondent for
Yedioth Arhonoth, a newspaper, said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   A senior Israeli official played down the idea that anything
would be simultaneous, saying the tracks would progress and slide
back at their own rates and at their own times. Like others, he
maintained the optimistic posture that the cancellation of
Israeli-Syrian talks is a snag and not a derailment. He also said
that Barak remained confident that a deal could be reached on both
tracks in a few months _ an agreement with Syria and a framework
agreement for a final peace with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Other officials expressed concern that an Israeli-Syrian deal
first would harden Barak and Arafat and make an Israeli-Palestinian
agreement more difficult. Barak, if he conceded the Golan Heights,
might feel compelled to take a tougher line on Jerusalem and the
settlements. And if Assad won back the Golan Heights, Arafat might
find it more difficult politically to make concessions to the
Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat, too, needs to sell a deal to his people, who are growing
increasingly skeptical about the prospects for a kind of peace that
could change their lives. Among the Palestinians, there is a
difference of opinion as to whether it is best to proceed speedily
or to slow down and wait out the Syrian track.
</P>
<P>
   As they aim for a deadline of Feb. 13 for a framework accord
that Barak set, Palestinian and Israeli negotiators have committed
themselves to working intensively toward that goal, even if it
appears increasingly unlikely that it will be met.
</P>
<P>
   But some Palestinians think that if they waited, they could end
up having the playing field back to themselves. International
pressure on Israel might ease if Barak made serious concessions to
the Syrians.
</P>
<P>
   But if the Syrian effort failed, or if enough time passed after
an agreement, that pressure might resurface, compelling Barak to
close the circle of peace, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Meanwhile, Arafat sits above the fray, waiting, not wanting to
close any of his options,'' a Western diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, it is a tricky balancing act for all three parties,
and after Barak suffered a setback this week, Israelis are noting
that the juggler cannot control the balls.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
