<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-PARLIAMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARLIAMENT LIBERALS PROTEST PUTIN APPOINTMENT OF COMMUNIST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN WHITMORE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Just hours after vowing that Russia would never return
to its totalitarian past, acting President Vladimir V. Putin
infuriated some of his pro-democracy allies by supporting a leading
Communist as speaker of the country's newly elected parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Liberal lawmakers marched out of the chamber in protest,
blemishing what had otherwise been a triumphant day for the new
Kremlin leader.
</P>
<P>
   The spectacle was Putin's first major political embarrassment
since becaming acting president on New Year's Eve after Boris
Yeltsin's abrupt resignation. For some it was a sobering
demonstration of how little is known about the new Kremlin leader's
political leanings.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a humiliation for Russian democracy,'' said lawmaker
Oleg Morozov, leader of a centrist pro-government party called
Regions of Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Morozov and others were protesting a backroom deal made between
the Communist Party, the largest faction in the legislature, and a
pro-Kremlin bloc called Unity, which holds the second largest
number of seats. Unity, a hastily assembled alliance of bureaucrats
and regional elites, is widely seen here as ``Putin's party.'' It
also has no clear political platform other than supporting the
acting president.
</P>
<P>
   The Communists and Unity together control a majority of the 450
seats in the State Duma, the lower house of Russia's parliament.
Using this dominance, the two froze smaller parties _ including
Putin's other allies _ out of negotiations and elected Communist
lawmaker Gennady Seleznyov as the legislature's speaker.
</P>
<P>
   Seleznyov served as speaker of the previous parliament, in which
the Communists and their allies had a majority. Widely seen as a
moderate, he proved adept at taming the hard liners in his own
party and reaching compromises with the Kremlin. Analysts here said
that Seleznyov's political affiliations are less important to Putin
than the fact that he will be able to deliver key votes for the
Kremlin and keep his party's true believers under control.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a pragmatic move. Seleznyov is somebody that Putin
will easily be able to control and use to get what he wants from
parliament,'' said Yevgeny Volk, a political analyst with the
Heritage Foundation in Moscow. ``Seleznyov may be a Communist, but
now he is Putin's Communist,'' Volk added.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Boris Nemtsov, leader of a liberal party that
supports Putin, called the deal ``a major political mistake that
will have very serious and negative consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   Nemtsov's party, called the Union of Right Forces, was among 137
lawmakers who walked out of parliament when it became clear that
the Communists and Unity had cut a deal that excluded them.
</P>
<P>
   In a televised interview, Nemtsov said that the Union of Right
Forces, the liberal Yabloko faction, and an opposition group called
Fatherland-All Russia would continue their protest by refusing to
accept any leadership posts or committee chairmanships.
</P>
<P>
   The Union of Right Forces and the Yabloko bloc had hoped to team
up with Unity to elect former prime minister Sergei Stepashin as
speaker. Fatherland-All Russia had nominated its leader, former
prime minister Yevgeny Primakov.
</P>
<P>
   By the time lawmakers finally got around to voting Seleznyov in
for his second term as speaker _ by a vote of 285 to nine _ most
seats on the right side of the parliamentary chamber, usually
occupied by liberal parties, were conspicuously empty. And although
the vote was legal, the scene of a nearly half empty legislature
voting for its leader appeared to lose a degree of moral
legitimacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened today was really profane. It was a collusion
that will prevent the State Duma from working effectively in the
future,'' Primakov said.
</P>
<P>
   The confrontational mood at the end of the new legislature's
first session contrasted sharply with the feel-good atmosphere that
prevailed in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   Putin opened Tuesday's session of parliament by calling for
cooperation between the Kremlin and legislature, after years of
acrimonious bickering during the Yeltsin's presidency. Putin's mere
presence in the chamber was seen as a gesture of compromise,
contrasting sharply with the disdain with which Yeltsin had treated
the legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Although Russia's president holds most political power, the
State Duma must approve the federal budget, approve prime ministers
and ratify treaties. The speaker is a key figure who runs
parliamentary sessions, controls the legislature's agenda and
presides over the chamber's staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need the widest support base in the State Duma. This is a
pragmatic position, not a political position. We will not divide
lawmakers into us and them,'' Putin said.
</P>
<P>
   A former KGB spy, Putin also sought to soothe the fears of those
who were apprehensive about his past in the feared Soviet secret
police.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those who speak about a possible dictatorship are themselves
dreaming of it. But their dream is impossible in modern Russia,''
Putin said.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech to lawmakers, the Kremlin leader embraced
pro-market themes. Putin said he favored a ``moderately liberal''
economic policy and urged the legislature to pass bills to improve
the country's investment climate and to allow land to be bought and
sold freely.
</P>
<P>
   Vladimir Pribylovsky, a Moscow-based political analyst, said the
angry public reaction by Putin's erstwhile allies was ``a very
serious blow for Putin's image.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I am sure he didn't anticipate such a strong reaction and a
solid opposition to Seleznyov's candidacy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Putin, who enjoys wide popularity here for his tough stance in
Russia's battle with Chechen separatist, faces snap presidential
elections on March 26 that most expect him to win.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
