<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-18 20:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9527 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-TV-OXYGEN-ART-2TAKES-     01-18 1215
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-OXYGEN-ART-2TAKES-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT DO WOMEN WANT? A NETWORK HAS AN IDEA  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 23) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Close to 25 years ago, Geraldine Laybourne decided
that children were being poorly served by television. Ms.
Laybourne, with a master's degree in elementary education from the
University of Pennsylvania, soon found a job with a fledgling cable
network called Nickelodeon.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next 16 years, Ms. Laybourne not only built Nickelodeon
into an $8 billion mini-empire but also altered the way children _
and, for that matter, their families _ viewed television. Among her
signatures were unusual and unsentimental shows like ``Rugrats,''
which tap into the humor, quirks and anxieties of ordinary
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the success of Nickelodeon, I asked who was the most
underserved audience,'' Ms. Laybourne, 52, said. ``There are many
channels designed now for kids. And teens. And men. Who is the most
underserved audience? Women, of course.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Laybourne's response, a high-risk 24-hour cable venture
called Oxygen, will make its debut on Feb. 2 in a half-dozen major
cities and suburban areas (but not New York and parts of Los
Angeles). It will be aimed at women who are in control of their
lives, have money to spend and are eager to find an outlet on
television and on Internet sites that will address their health
issues, finances, relationships and problems with raising children.
</P>
<P>
   Do women really need another cable network? Do they really need
another Internet site? Such questions are almost heresy in the
entertainment business, not least because of Oxygen's pedigree.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Laybourne's partners are Marcy Carsey, Tom Werner and Caryn
Mandabach, who run one of television's most successful production
companies, responsible for such series as ``The Cosby Show,''
``Roseanne,'' ``A Different World,'' ``Grace Under Fire,'' ``Third
Rock From the Sun'' and ``Cybill.'' The other partner, Oprah
Winfrey, is one of the most formidable figures in American popular
culture.
</P>
<P>
   Besides these rich and successful associates, Oxygen has several
high-profile financial backers. These include America Online and
Paul Allen, the co-founder of Microsoft. Another investor is
Bernard Arnault, the chairman of the French conglomerate LVMH,
whose luxury goods _ Christian Dior, Givenchy, Louis Vuitton _ are
obviously in tune with the affluent audience Oxygen's channel and
World Wide Web sites anticipate.
</P>
<P>
   Given this support, you would expect the network to face smooth
sailing. But the waters look choppy for Oxygen.
</P>
<P>
   The other basic 24-hour cable network developed for women,
Lifetime, which is owned by the Walt Disney Co. and Hearst Corp.,
is seen in 75 million homes. By contrast, Oxygen will be available,
at the outset, in only 10 million households, because Ms. Laybourne
and her staff have not been able to come to financial terms with
cable companies in some of the largest markets or because the cable
operators are unwilling to commit to a network whose shows they
have not seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a crowded cable marketplace, Gerry has to carve out her
niche,'' said Christopher Dixon, a media analyst at Paine Webber.
``The critical issue for any launch is how many subscribers you
have. Until you get 25 to 30 million subscribers, you won't have
the kind of critical mass that attracts major national
advertisers.''
</P>
<P>
   Oxygen's inability to find a home in New York or Los Angeles is
partly because of the crowded cable landscape and partly because
the network is asking cable companies to help pay the costs of
programming, all of which is original. Even more significant is the
matter of creating the programs that will lure viewers. No one can
be quite sure what women, en masse, want to see on television.
</P>
<P>
   The Lifetime network has found a successful set of formulas:
reruns of shows like ``Golden Girls,'' ``Designing Women'' and
``Chicago Hope''; series like ``Any Day Now,'' about the enduring
friendship of two women, one black and one white, in Birmingham,
Ala.; original escapist movies, often characterized by women in
some kind of jeopardy, as well as ``Intimate Portrait'' biographies
(Bette Midler, Lady Bird Johnson, Gloria Steinem, Katharine Graham)
and documentary specials on subjects like breast cancer and the
crisis in child care. The network seems to be directed at an older,
less hip audience than the one Oxygen is reaching for.
</P>
<P>
   Carole Black, the president and chief executive of Lifetime,
said that Lifetime's success _ it ranks sixth among basic cable
networks in prime time, according to Nielsen figures _ can be
attributed to its clear assessment of the audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women multitask,'' said Ms. Black, who had been a top
television marketing executive at Disney and the general manager at
KNBC-TV in Los Angeles. ``They're very busy. They're worrying about
everyone else _ their significant other, their children, their
parents, their friends. They have very little time to themselves.
They need a place to go where they can be themselves, where they
can feel understood, have fun, learn something and feel
supported.''
</P>
<P>
   Initially, executives at Lifetime and Oxygen were fairly candid
about each other's shortcomings. But lately mutual criticisms have
been muted. Officials at both companies say that magazines and
newspapers are poised for a cat fight to develop between Oxygen and
Lifetime, perpetuating every cliche about competition among women.
</P>
<P>
   Oxygen faces competition not only from Lifetime but also,
depending on the viewer's age and income, from Romance Classics,
the Food Network, HGTV as well as MTV, VH1 and other networks with
talk shows and series aimed at women.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm anxious to see what Oxygen has on,'' Ms. Black said. ``The
people behind it are so smart and have been very successful. But
everyone's going after women now. Including the broadcast
networks.'' (She is right: shows like NBC's ``Providence'' and
``Will and Grace,'' and CBS's ``Judging Amy'' have been unexpected
successes, those networks say, because of their substantial female
audience.)
</P>
<P>
   Oxygen has no plans to rerun old television series. Although Ms.
Laybourne has said that Oxygen is not seeking a specific age group,
the shows seem to be skewed toward women from 18 to their mid-40s.
</P>
<P>
   The original programming _ 55 hours a week, hardly all of it
heavyweight _ includes ``Pure Oxygen,'' two hours of news and
entertainment features from New York, which will be broadcast five
days a week. There is also ``X-Chromosome,'' cable television's
first prime-time animated series for women; ``Pajama Party,'' a
weekly, late-night talk and variety show conceived to celebrate,
with humor, what grown women are confronting in their personal and
business lives; ``Trackers'' an afternoon show that involves roving
teen-age girls with digital cameras who create episodes that deal
with fashion, movies, boys and getting into college; an updated
version of the 1950s game show ``I've Got a Secret;'' and programs
given over to exercise and sports, yoga and cooking.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
