u i BC-IRAQ-EKEUS-BOS &LR;      01-18 0658
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-EKEUS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN OPPOSITION TO EKEUS DISUPTS UN BAGHDAD POLICY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE LAURIA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Again flexing its muscles with the United
States, Russia formally blocked Washington's choice to head a new
Iraq weapons inspection team Tuesday, throwing UN policy on Baghdad
into disarray.
</P>
<P>
   Fellow Security Council members China and France joined Russia
in opposing Secretary General Kofi Annan's appointment of Swedish
diplomat Rolf Ekeus to lead the weapons team.
</P>
<P>
   Ekeus, who relentlessly monitored Baghdad as UN weapons
inspection chief from 1991 to 1997, was seen by Annan and
high-profile US Ambassador Richard Holbrooke as vital to trying to
prevent Iraq from building its stocks of long-range missiles and
biological and chemical weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The previous UN team left Iraq in December 1998 ahead of US and
British bombing raids, intended to force Iraq to cooperate with
them. They never returned. The Security Council created a new
inspection unit last month and gave Annan 30 days to nominate its
head. After exploring more than 25 candidates, the secretary
general put forth Ekeus' name.
</P>
<P>
   Russia wants economic sanctions against Iraq to be lifted,
ostensibly on humanitarian grounds, though Russia's battered
economy could certainly use the $7 billion in Soviet-era debt that
Baghdad owes it as well as any new business that might be cemented
with Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's UN ambassador, Sergei Lavrov, said any candidate must
be someone Iraq could work with. Baghdad rejects Ekeus as ``old
wine in a new bottle.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, Russia has shown a willingness to stand up to
Washington, reversing its no-first strike nuclear policy and
persisting despite international criticism with its offensive in
Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   American diplomats say Russia's rejection, firsested in a
letter to Holbrooke Monday night, was the first time a secretary
general's appointment was stopped by a Security Council member.
Holbrooke said he will continue to fight for Ekeus' approval.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, France and China swiftly joined Moscow in opposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted a new body and a new body means of course a new
person in charge,'' said French UN Ambassador Alain Dejammet. His
nation hopes to take advantage of lucrative gas and oil contracts
with Iraq once sanctions are removed.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese diplomats here say Beijing favors a candidate from the
developing world.
</P>
<P>
   The Security Council imposed an oil embargo and other commercial
sanctions on Iraq after its August 1990 invasion of Kuwait.
According to Security Council resolutions, those sanctions cannot
be lifted until UN weapons inspectors declare Iraq to be rid of its
nuclear, biological, chemical and long-range missile programs.
</P>
<P>
   The Security Council Tuesday decided not to ask Annan for a new
nomination. Instead it will consider previous candidates as well as
new names that might arise.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley Kober, a research fellow at the Cato Institute in
Washington, said anger in Russia toward the United States is
actually greater now than during the Cold War. ``Back then it was a
conflict of elites between the two countries and the people had no
animosity towards the US,'' Kober said. ``Now this anger is
bubbling up from the people.''
</P>
<P>
   Kober cited a recent poll showing 87 percent of Russians
believed the US is taking advantage of Russia's economic plight to
strengthen its position in the world. Only 10 percent saw President
Clinton as a friend of Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, American and Russian diplomats sought to play down
differences between their countries. Holbrooke said Washington and
Moscow ``agree on some issues and disagree on others'' and would
not be drawn into placing Moscow's defiance on Iraq as part of an
overall pattern.
</P>
<P>
   Lavrov said publicly he saw no linkage between Moscow's position
on Iraq and its other policies towards the United States.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-18-00 2029EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
