<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-18 20:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9529 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-TV-OXYGEN-ART-2NDTAKE     01-18 0796
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-OXYGEN-ART-2NDTAKE-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
  
 LOS ANGELES: and cooking.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Candice Bergen will have a talk show called ``Exhale,'' with
guests like David Hockney, Madeleine Albright, Frank Gehry and Tina
Turner. Ms. Bergen, who is 53, is expected to deal with issues of
interest to older women as well as the younger set.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Winfrey will have a Sunday night talk show and ``Oprah Goes
Online,'' a program that will detail how she is learning to work
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   All of the shows will be integrated with Oxygen's online sites.
Indeed, the Web is integral to the success of the network, Ms.
Laybourne said. She explained that 13 online sites devoted to women
will serve as way stations for Oxygen, sharing useful information,
allowing viewers to interact with the network's shows and,
significantly, to offer opinions and information to Oxygen
executives.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want feedback,'' Ms. Laybourne said. ``We want audiences to
be as involved in the creation of Oxygen as we can get them.''
</P>
<P>
   (Ms. Laybourne used a similar technique at Nickelodeon, where
she turned to research panels across the country to find out what
children wanted from television and what they thought of the
network.)
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Mandabach put it another way. ``Women are more online now
than men,'' she said. ``Women buy 85 percent of the goods and
services. They buy 66 percent of the cars. In the discussion of
what Oxygen is and what we can be, we want to listen and learn from
these women. And that's what the company is about.''
</P>
<P>
   But even the experienced and successful partners at Oxygen are
plainly nervous about the network's debut. ``We are going to make
mistakes, we're learning,'' Werner said. ``Our heart is in the
right place here. I'd say, don't judge us too severely right off
the bat.''
</P>
<P>
   With its backers, Oxygen's valuation, even before the first show
is broadcast, is estimated at more than $1 billion. The company has
about 560 employees, mostly in New York and Los Angeles. It has set
aside about $450 million for original programming. AOL, an investor
in the venture, exchanged cash and three Web sites for women for a
stake in the company. Tele-Communications, the nation's No. 2 cable
operator, now part of AT&AMP;T, has pledged to deliver seven million
cable subscribers over two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been cooking in my head for a long time,'' said Ms.
Laybourne, whose husband, Kit, a filmmaker, is directing the
development of animation at Oxygen. (They have two grown children.)
``How do you figure out something to do with the Internet? How do
you figure out something to do with women, who are 52 percent of
the population?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, I thought the hurdles would be much worse,'' Ms.
Laybourne said, cool and assured. ``I hope I don't sound smug. I
suspected we'd start off on a much smaller scale and prove
ourselves every step of the way. What I found was, very early, my
partners wanted to tackle the big picture right off the bat.''
</P>
<P>
   Oxygen, most certainly, is the biggest risk in Ms. Laybourne's
career. Her success at Nickelodeon led to a somewhat unhappy two
years as president of Disney/ABC cable networks. (During that time
Ms. Laybourne was chairwoman of Lifetime.)
</P>
<P>
   In the Disney job, which ended in 1998, Ms. Laybourne saw her
efforts founder and realized that she wanted to establish a company
on her own. Within months, the Carsey-Werner-Mandabach team joined
her, and later, Ms. Winfrey, who has said she was attracted by
Oxygen's mission to inspire women.
</P>
<P>
   (Ms. Laybourne has said that the name ``Oxygen'' came about
after she woke up one morning gasping for air and concluded ``that
we all needed more breathing room.'' Also, she said, ``I didn't
want a girlish name or what Oprah would call a pinkish name.'')
</P>
<P>
   Oxygen's business priority now is to expand its number of cable
outlets and, especially, to find one in the media capital, New
York. Without New York, Oxygen has diminished clout. But Ms.
Laybourne was noticably buoyed by the news that AOL planned to
merge with Time Warner.
</P>
<P>
   AOL is a significant partner in Oxygen. Robert W. Pittman, the
president of AOL, was not only Ms. Laybourne's original boss at
Nickelodeon but also a close friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Robert Pittman got us established on the Internet,'' she said.
``AOL was our first deal.'' Pittman is expected to play an
important role in the new company. And with Time Warner's cable
outlet, which is dominant in the New York area, Oxygen's voyage
into New York may be smoother.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a matter of time,'' Ms. Laybourne said of her company's
finding a place in New York and Los Angeles. ``It's been a long
time since anything truly fresh, with original programming, was
added to the cable landscape. Once people see what Oxygen is all
about, we'll be welcomed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
