<HEADLINE>
HEINRICHS NAMED US WOMEN'S SOCCER COACH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   She figured she would stay at Virginia for another four, five,
six years, then take a shot at coaching the national team. Then the
federation people asked her to write a what's-my-vision paper for
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought okay, no harm in that, I'd love to,'' April
Heinrichs said Tuesday, after she was named the first female coach
of the US women's soccer team and technical director for the entire
program for the next four years. ``And here I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Heinrichs, who captained the team that won the first World Cup
in 1991, succeeds Tony DiCicco, who stepped down in November after
directing the Americans to both the Olympic gold medal and World
Cup title during the last quadrennium.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's exciting to take this position,'' said the 35-year-old
Heinrichs, who will be responsible for both this summer's Olympic
team and the 2002 Cup squad. ``It gives me great pride to come full
circle from player on the national team to coach.''
</P>
<P>
   The circle came around unexpectedly early for Heinrichs, who
leapfrogged Lauren Gregg and Jay Hoffman, DiCicco's top assistants,
to become only one of three females worldwide (along with Sweden's
Marika Domanski Lyfors and Germany's Tina Theune-Meyer) to head
women's national teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``April was the best choice and is the best person for the
job,'' said federation president Dr. S. Robert Contiguglia.
Contiguglia denied that Clive Charles, the men's Olympic (i.e.
under-23) coach turned down the job. ``That's not the case,'' he
said. ``Clive decided to stay with the Olympic team.''
</P>
<P>
   Contiguglia also denied that the federation gave Heinrichs the
job, following three male head coaches, to avoid a gender
discrimination lawsuit. ``That's the first I've heard of that,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Heinrichs' credentials were unquestioned. She was one of
DiCicco's assistants with the 1995 World Cup and 1996 Olympic teams
and coached the under-16 team for three years. She had a 116-70-18
collegiate record at Princeton, Maryland and Virginia, where she
led the Cavaliers to four NCAA tournament appearances in as many
seasons. And Heinrichs was one of the pioneers of the US team,
playing for six seasons and starring alongside Michelle Akers and
Carin Gabarra as strikers on the 1991 Cup team.
</P>
<P>
   ``April has been such a constant source of light and respect for
the team,'' said midfielder Julie Foudy, who played with Heinrichs
in 1991. ``She is an incredible leader, a gifted motivator and a
great tactician. The team was very excited when she was named
coach.''
</P>
<P>
   Heinrichs actually is inheriting two teams -- the Cup champions
who've declined to play for the US during their ongoing contract
dispute and the B squad of collegians and high-schoolers who just
outplayed the Australians, Swedes and Czechs for the Australia Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``My biggest challenge will be to whittle down a player pool of
41 to 16 for the Olympics,'' said Heinrichs, whose immediate task
is to put a squad together for a Feb. 6 match with archrival Norway
in Ft. Lauderdale.
</P>
<P>
   Though Heinrichs will be in the delicate position of coaching
seven former teammates (Akers, Foudy, Mia Hamm, Joy Fawcett,
Kristine Lilly, Brandi Chastain, Carla Overbeck), she says she
doesn't expect any problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``I coached them in 1995 and 1996,'' she said. ``I thought we
had a healthy player-coach relationship and I'm looking forward to
picking up where we left off.''
</P>
</TEXT>
