<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT'S STRONG 4TH-QUARTER EARNINGS BOOSTS NASDAQ
</HEADLINE>
  (See also MICROSOFT-EARNINGS, MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST) 
(rk) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stocks were mixed Tuesday as investors took profits
out of blue-chips even as they continued to plow money into high
technology shares.
</P>
<P>
   The divergent patterns in stocks occurred against a backdrop of
rising interest rates, which moved to their highest level in 2{
years. For the first time since 1994, yields on the Treasury's
10-year notes briefly climbed above the yield on benchmark 30-year
bonds. By late in the day, both securities were quoted at a price
that yielded 6.75 percent. The yield of the 30-year bond was up
from 6.69 percent Friday. The 30-year Treasury bond fell 22/32, to
92 3/32.
</P>
<P>
   Led by Microsoft, which reported better-than-expected
fourth-quarter profit after the close of trading, the Nasdaq
composite index narrowly missed setting a record.
</P>
<P>
   The index gained 66.54 points Tuesday, or 1.64 percent, to
4,130.81, just below the Jan. 3 record of 4,131.15.
</P>
<P>
   But investors turned their backs on most of the stocks that make
up the Dow Jones industrial average.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow, which set records Thursday and Friday, fell 162.26
points, a drop of 1.38 percent, to 11,560.72. Only eight of the 30
stocks that make up the index gained in price. Financial service
company stocks led the decline.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 stock index fell 10.01 points, or 0.68
percent, to 1,455.14.
</P>
<P>
   The small-cap Russell 2000 index bucked the trend, and
maintained its status as the best-performing major market index so
far this year.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell rose 5.90 Tuesday, or 1.2 percent, to 513.46.
</P>
<P>
   ``The underpinnings for strength in the market are still
there,'' said Michael Clark, head of U.S. stock trading at Credit
Suisse First Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we are going to be in a trading range for the next six to
eight weeks, due to worries about the Federal Reserve and a
relentless supply of new and secondary stock issues. There is not
much reason to take stocks higher until we get a new perspective on
how higher rates will impact earnings this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Applegate, chief investment strategist at Lehman
Brothers, said Tuesday that earnings will remain strong this year,
and that he expects high-flying technology stocks to retain their
position as market leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big cap beats small cap, growth beats value and the leadership
will stay narrow,'' Applegate said at a meeting with reporters.
``Earnings, not valuation, will drive the market this year.''
Applegate said that in the aggregate corporate earnings should rise
14 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   Bond market analysts said the brief inversion between 10-year
and 30-year Treasury securities was largely because of technical
factors. But there is a broad consensus that the Federal Reserve
will be pushing up short-term interest rates very soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market has built in a half-point increase, whether it
comes in one or two moves'' by the Fed, said Donald J. Fine, chief
market analyst at Chase Asset Management. ``If after doing that the
economy shows no signs of slowing, they will tighten again.''
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Fed's policy-making Open Market Committee are
seen as likely to approve a rate increase when they hold two days
of meetings that begin Feb. 1.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, fourth quarter earnings reports are living up
to forecasts, and in many cases are exceeding expectations. Still,
a number of stocks were punished Tuesday after reporting strong
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   J.P. Morgan, a Dow component, was a case in point. The stock
fell 4 11/16, to 123 5/16, even though the big financial services
company's fourth-quarter results were better than Wall Street had
forecast.
</P>
<P>
   Citigroup, which also posted better than expected earnings, was
also punished, but not so severely: the stock closed at 57 15/16,
down 1/16.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft was one of the few Dow stocks to show life Tuesday,
jumping 3 1/16 to 115 5/16 on the expectation its fourth quarter
results would be strong.
</P>
<P>
   The software giant did better than consensus estimates,
reporting fourth-quarter earnings of 44 cents a share, compared
with an average estimate of 42 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the gains were below the 49 cent-a-share ``whisper''
estimate. In after-hours trading, Microsoft gave up all of its
gains and more. Late Tuesday the stock was quoted at 112, down 3
5/16.
</P>
<P>
   And Motorola, whose shares rose sharply on Friday on
expectations of strong fourth-quarter results, saw investors take
much of those gains back Tuesday after its numbers failed to meet
the rosiest forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   The stock fell 6}, to 144\.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
