<HEADLINE>
BONFIRE COMMISSION HIRES CALIFORNIA FORENSIC CONSULTANT 

</HEADLINE>
 BC- BONFIRE-PROBE -HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN WILLIAMS 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLLEGE STATION, Texas _ A California forensic consultant hired
Tuesday to sort out human error in November's deadly Bonfire
collapse said he will investigate all possible causes, including
the administration of Texas A&AMP;M University.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our investigation will not ... stop at a certain point,'' said
Chong Chiu, chief executive officer of Performance Improvement
International. ``Whatever will impact the culture of the event, we
will investigate.''
</P>
<P>
   Chiu's comments came a week after school President Ray Bowen
indicated he will resign if it is determined his administration is
at fault through poor supervision of the event which largely is
student sponsored.
</P>
<P>
   According to documents released since the Nov. 18 calamity, at
least two university policies were not followed as students erected
the massive hard timber pile to be burned before the Texas-Texas
A&AMP;M football game.
</P>
<P>
   Two students working on the Bonfire the night of the collapse
were found to have alcohol in their systems despite a school ban on
alcoholic beverages during Bonfire construction.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the unfinished tower had an estimated height of 59 feet
when it collapsed with four of its five levels completed. In the
late 1980s, the school capped the height at 55 feet amid safety and
environmental concerns.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear whether the height played a role in the Bonfire
falling. A preliminary engineering report released last week
indicated that students built the first level built on uneven
ground, causing it to lean. The three other levels above the first
or ground level were built parallel to the center pole that anchors
the structure.
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath of the collapse, which killed 12 and injured
27, Bowen and school officials have appointed a special commission
headed by Houston contractor Leo Linbeck Jr. to determine the
cause.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, the commission agreed to hire Performance Improvement
International to join three other firms retained two weeks ago to
determine the cause of the accident.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the other consulting firms will look largely at the
design and construction of the Bonfire. The third firm, Kroll
Associates, will coordinate the efforts. Kroll has established a
toll-free hotline for information or anonymous tips regarding the
Bonfire. The number is 1-888-765-3977.
</P>
<P>
   Performance Improvement International of San Clemente has
investigated accidents around the world, including an analysis of
human performance for the 1998 San Francisco blackout and a study
into a 1999 electricity tower collapse in Taiwan that severely
disrupted the economy there.
</P>
<P>
   Chiu said that in all failures, there is usually a human factor
that leads to accidents. Sometimes the human factor plays a direct
role, or sometimes it is a culture that surrounds an event, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't set out to blame anybody, we set out to determine
what happened,'' Chiu said.
</P>
<P>
   Chiu, who has looked at the human causes for other accidents
such as Three Mile Island (Pennsylvania) nuclear accident, said
Bowen's comments about resigning would not affect his company's
work.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter,'' Chiu said. ``To us we are transparent to
emotion, we just look at the facts. Because he made a comment after
the event, to us, that won't be a causal factor to the event. We
will look at all the facts.''
</P>
<P>
   After the commission hired Performance Improvement
International, Linbeck said the consultants have had concerns about
getting involved in lawsuits, should any be filed.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, state Rep. Ron Wilson, D-Houston, said he will seek
an exception in the 2001 Legislature to a state cap that limits the
school's liability to a total of $500,000 should any victims or
their families sue the school.
</P>
<P>
   Linbeck said the consultants wanted indemnity protecting them
from litigation, a safety net the school cannot provide. And they
want the school to pay them should they be sought as expert
witnesses in any lawsuits once their investigation is completed.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, commission members and university officials are
struggling with the ramifications of hiring consultants. Though the
commission has selected them, the school will pay for them. The
university will use money drawn from interest earned on
investments, not tax dollars.
</P>
<P>
   A final budget for the investigation will not be known for at
least two weeks but Linbeck has estimated the bill might reach
$500,000. That figure could go even higher if the consultants are
paid for time consumed with lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   University spokeswoman Cindy Lawson said the school ``would do
the right thing'' about paying the consultants, though she was not
sure if there would be a ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   The payment issue raised questions about whether the consultants
are working for the commission or for the university, which might
find itself a defendant in a lawsuit. The relationship could create
a situation where the school pays the consultants to testify
against it should the university be found at fault, Linbeck said.
</P>
<P>
   Linbeck, who is also chairman of Texans for Tort Reform, said
that the consultants, though paid by the university, are charged
with finding out exactly what happened. He said they will not to
create a finding amenable to university desires.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we thought at any time in the investigation that any member
of the team was skewing their work in a direction that had another
objective in mind ... we'd find a way to get rid of them,'' Linbeck
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
