<HEADLINE>
RAYTHEON SHARES PUMMELED AFTER IT PREDICTS EARNINGS SHORTFALLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Raytheon Co. may miss earnings forecasts this year by up to $220
million, stunning investors who thought the company had put its
worst news on the table three months ago.
</P>
<P>
   The market quickly punished Raytheon's class B stock, which fell
25 percent Tuesday to close at 19, its lowest price in more than
seven years.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon also warned of fourth-quarter shortfalls, blaming
accounting problems, credit downgrades, and overseas sales woes,
and said it plans to restate financial results for the past three
years after a review of its commercial-aircraft business.
</P>
<P>
   The news followed pledges by Raytheon chief executive Daniel
Burnham to restore the company's credibility among investors after
a string of bad-news surprises last fall. Many problems related to
difficulties Raytheon has had integrating acquisitions, leading to
a restructuring and the layoff of 2,380 workers _ a figure that
came to include up to 300 from a microelectronics plant in Quincy,
Mass.
</P>
<P>
   But following Tuesday's news, some analysts now worry those
remedies might not be enough, or will take longer to turn the
company around.
</P>
<P>
   The latest news ``Doesn't inspire confidence that the company
knows what's its doing in the individual business units,'' said
Heidi Wood, analyst at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter. She downgraded
the company to ``neutral.''
</P>
<P>
   Wood said she was chiefly concerned whether Raytheon had made
enough progess meshing computerized financial controls, which at
one point it kept on 50 different computer systems.
</P>
<P>
   Any details would help, others said. ``It's still really tough
to gauge where they are,'' said Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette
analyst Joe Nadol, who had previously downgraded the company to
neutral.
</P>
<P>
   In a pointed note to clients Tuesday he said the rating would
stand ``until we feel that all of the bad news is out and the
company has its act together.''
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, Raytheon said it expects fourth-quarter earnings
of between 20 to 25 cents per share, or between $67.7 million to
$84.6 million, versus the 59 cents, or $199.6 million, expected on
average by 13 analysts surveyed by Nelson's Investment Research.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly as a result, Raytheon said, 1999 earnings will be between
$1.15 and $1.20 a share, versus the $1.40 to $1.50 a share Raytheon
said to expect last October.
</P>
<P>
   For 2000, Raytheon said it expects to earn between $1.60 to
$1.75 a share, down from between $2.10 to $2.25 per share it said
in October it expected to earn this year. The company has about
338.4 million shares outstanding. Raytheon said it ended 1999 with
a record order backlog, up about 15 percent from the year-earlier
level, and said it had net debt of $9.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   In a press release Tuesday Raytheon spelled out many issues,
some new and some recurring, but said little about root causes.
Spokesman David Polk declined to elaborate execpt to say executives
would be more forthcoming when the company releases its formal
financial results on Jan. 25.
</P>
<P>
   The release mentioned ``further erosion in international
opportunities for certain missile programs and missile defense
systems, especially Patriot,'' the air-defense missile whose
slowing sales it blamed last fall. Raytheon also cited higher
interest expenses resulting from a credit rating downgrade in
November, a higher effective tax rate, and delays in gaining
certifications for its Premier I business jet.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Raytheon reported ``production and shipment delays
on 19 aircraft, as well as cost growth,'' at its Wichita civilian
aircraft company. All 19 planes are expected to be shipped this
year, Raytheon said.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon said reviews at the aircraft unit follow the
introduction of a new accounting standard, and said it plans to
restate the company's full results back to 1997 by the end of this
week. The impact will be no more than 6 cents per share per year,
Raytheon said.
</P>
<P>
   The aircraft's problems worried analysts, who noted it had
previously reported few problems, unlike Raytheon's defense
segments or its engineering and construction business in Cambridge,
Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon also blamed a delay in the signing of a radar contract
with the British military. The company announced the contract win
last June, but didn't finalize the work until Dec. 17, therefore
booking revenue later than expected.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's disclosures prompted Duff &AMP; Phelps Credit Rating Co.
to lower its outlook for Raytheon to negative from stable, noting
the company had missed its debt-reduction target by $200 million.
The agency also noted the shortfalls could prompt Raytheon to sell
more of its business units, an option it said provides the company
some ``financial flexibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week Raytheon agreed to sell a flight training business to
L-3 Communications Corp. for $160 million.
</P>
<P>
   In July Raytheon's widely traded class B shares reached a high
of 74-15/16 on enthusiasm for Burnham, who took over in 1998, and
on the strength of missile replacement orders following NATO's air
campaign against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   But on Oct. 12 shares fell 44 percent to 24 1/4 after Burnham
said the company would miss some ambitious profit targets.
</P>
<P>
   The stock has mostly remained in the 20s since as investors
awaited updates about the effectiveness of Burnham's restructuring
that, among other things, split into several pieces the big
Raytheon Systems Co. defense unit. Absent those details, analysts
have seized on the progress of individual programs for hints.
</P>
<P>
   One test is Raytheon's share of a space-based missile defense
system being developed by the Pentagon known as the
``exoatmospheric kill vehicle.'' The device is scheduled for its
second test shot Wednesday night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
