<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-18 20:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9539 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-COKE-MARKETPLACE-ART-     01-18 1225
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-MARKETPLACE-ART-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: NEW DIRECTIONS AT COCA-COLA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT27 has been sent Jan. 18 to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In what amounts to a rare admission of failure, Coca-Cola Co. is
trying to make itself into a friendlier company that will adapt
more to local markets around the world.
</P>
<P>
   The new strategy, emerging from Coca-Cola's recent announcements
and from conversations with people close to the company, involves a
string of personnel moves and related actions intended to improve
its standing on Wall Street and repair its reputation with
consumers, regulators, bottlers and others with whom its
relationships have been damaged over the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, the company announced that Jack Stahl, who has headed
Coke's business in North America, will become second in command to
Douglas Daft, who was chosen for the chief executive's job in
December. The widely expected announcement and hints of a bigger
shift at the soft drink giant pushed the stock up $3.938 to $65,
well above its October low of under $48.
</P>
<P>
   The changes _ some as obvious as relocating executives outside
of Atlanta _ will affect the company's marketing strategies, both
in the kinds of products it sells and the way it sells them.
</P>
<P>
   Other changes seem designed to improve relations between Coke
and its bottlers, relations that have been strained recently by
rapid increases in the cost of concentrate in the United States and
demands for capital investment from bottlers abroad that were
mandated by Coke executives in Atlanta. The stock price of
Coca-Cola Enterprises, the largest Coke bottler, has lost 40
percent of its value in the last year because of depressed profits
in the bottling system.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're starting to see new marching orders, which are coming
from the board and from Daft and Stahl,'' said Bill Pecoriello, a
beverage stocks analyst with Sanford C. Bernstein &AMP; Co., which does
not underwrite stock offerings. Pecoriello issued a lengthy report
Tuesday in which he said Coca-Cola was going through ``the biggest
`sea change' with regard to all aspects of its business in nearly
20 years.'' The company will trim its 29,000-person workforce by at
least 2,000 and scale back its goals for case sales to more
realistic levels, he said after interviewing Coke bottlers and
others in the industry.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   A Coca-Cola company spokesman said Tuesday that ``management has
been looking at the business for some time,'' but declined to
confirm the details of Pecoriello's report.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   After a board meeting in Atlanta on Tuesday, the company said
Stahl, 46, will become president and chief operating officer in
April when Daft officially takes over. M. Douglas Ivester, Coke's
outgoing chairman and chief executive, steadfastly insisted during
his short tenure that he did not need a second in command.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are going to see a more traditional CEO-COO relationship
with a management team approach,'' said James B. Williams, a Coke
director. ``It's going to be an effective and a different
approach.'' Asked whether power had been too concentrated under
Ivester, he said: ``Each CEO has to to establish his own management
style.''
</P>
<P>
   Daft moved quickly to retain Carl Ware, the company's highest
ranking black executive, who had resigned in November after a
management shuffle that pushed him aside. Ware's departure
concerned some in Atlanta's civil-rights community, particularly
since Coke is the subject of a racial-discrimination lawsuit filed
by several black employees. Earlier this month, Ware was named
executive vice president in charge of corporate affairs and
government relations.
</P>
<P>
   A recurring theme since Daft's appointment has been
decentralization, first signaled by the announcement earlier this
month that executives in charge of Asian and European operations
would live not in Atlanta, but in their territories.
Decentralization will also be key in marketing, where local tastes
and local brands are expected to play a larger role than they have
in the past. Coke's expansion into overseas markets has for years
led with Coca-Cola, regardless of local preferences.
</P>
<P>
   Japan has been the notable exception to that strategy; Coke is
outsold there by Coca-Cola's canned coffee and tea products, which
are among some 200 company brands. Daft, who was group president
for Asia until his promotion, earlier this month named the No. 2
executive in Japan, Stephen C. Jones, as Coke's chief marketing
officer.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason for the shift is that Coke finds itself
increasingly challenged by cheaper local brands in markets from
Eastern Europe to Brazil and parts of Asia. Instead of its longtime
rival Pepsi-Cola, Coke's chief competitor has turned out to be
lower-priced soft drinks, if not water or juice.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no doubt that Doug Daft is moving lightning-quick to
get the Coca-Cola Co. heading in the right direction again,'' said
Michael Branca, a beverage stocks analyst with Lehman Brothers,
``putting his best players in positions to make a difference, in
areas where Coke has struggled in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Ivester, the company's global ambitions frequently angered
local officials. Plans to expand by acquiring the Cadbury Schweppes
brands were partly stymied by objections from regulators as far
flung as Mexico, Australia and the European Union.
</P>
<P>
   Ivester is credited with pushing the consolidation of Coke's
bottlers in the United States and abroad _ something that led to
more efficiencies and initially impressed investors. But analysts
have criticized the company recently for exhorting bottlers to
invest heavily in manufacturing plants and other equipment, based
on sales targets that became increasingly unattainable as economies
around the world sputtered. ``It's critical to see the bottlers
improve their returns on invested capital,'' said Andrew Conway, a
Morgan Stanley analyst.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   At a conference for investors sponsored by Morgan Stanley late
last year, the chairman and chief executive of a large European
bottler gave a presentation that many in the audience considered
the most abject that they had heard in years from anyone in the
relentlessly optimistic Coke system. The executive, Neville Isdell,
put up what he called ``our Kleenex tissue slide,'' a list of
obstacles like the war in Kosovo that the bottler, Coca-Cola
Beverages, had run into since it went public in July 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But another problem Isdell mentioned was an enormous $1.5
billion in capital spending, which was ``too far ahead of the
market,'' he conceded. Among those expenses: vending machines,
nearly twice as many by last year as the company had in 1997. The
bottler posted a loss in the in the first half of last year.
</P>
<P>
   One analyst said such problems would continue unless Coke merges
its operations with those of its bottlers. ``Coke's problems are
related to the bottling system, which subsidized Coke's earnings
and are now being subsidized by Coke,'' said Albert Meyer, an
analyst at David Tice &AMP; Co., who has been a steady critic of Coke's
accounting practices.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
