<SLUG> BC-AILING-HMO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTMENT BANK EXPLORING OPTIONS FOR HMO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX AND STEVEN WILMSEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Salomon Smith Barney Tuesday began scouting for options
to save Massachusetts' largest HMO from bankruptcy, either by
finding $150 million or so in cash to resuscitate Harvard Pilgrim
Health Care, or by identifying a buyer for the $2.8 billion-a-year
health plan.
</P>
<P>
   A Salomon Smith Barney team led by Thomas Green, who was former
Attorney General Scott Harshbarger's chief deputy, is expected to
tell state officials as early as next week what firm possibilities
exist. But the public may not be told until some indefinite time in
the future.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts Attorney General Thomas Reilly would not disclose
Tuesday how Salomon Smith Barney, an investment firm, is being
paid, offering only general reassurances that ``the fee structure
does not in any way favor one option over another.''
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general stressed that ``no public money is involved
here,'' and that Salomon Smith Barney ``will be compensated from
the assets of Harvard Pilgrim.''
</P>
<P>
   Some observers of Harvard Pilgrim's 2-week-old financial crisis
have said that the customary method of compensating investment
bankers, as a percentage of the value of the ultimate deal, might
favor a sale of the nonprofit insurer rather than a more limited
recapitalization plan.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly said in an interview that preliminary contacts had
already been made with possible rescuers, ``but we've got to
determine what's real.''
</P>
<P>
   Salomon Smith Barney, which Reilly said has the world's largest
health care practice among investment bankers, will ``test the
marketplace'' to get ``a firmer feel for which of these options are
real,'' added J. David Leslie, a private insurance specialist who
has been named special assistant attorney general for the Harvard
Pilgrim crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our primary goal,'' Reilly said, ``is to recapitalize Harvard
Pilgrim,'' that is, to find investors who can provide the
wherewithal to keep the health plan going as a nonprofit.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly refused to attach a dollar figure to that goal. ``We have
a general sense of what it would take,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Under a Harvard Pilgrim bond issue that was to have gone to
market last week, the health maintenance organization would have
realized about $120 million from the sale of five of the eight
Boston-area health centers leases to Harvard Vanguard Medical
Associates, a spinoff group now an independent company.
</P>
<P>
   The bond issue was aborted by the sudden news that Harvard
Pilgrim's 1999 losses were nearly $60 million higher than
previously thought, a disclosure that prompted Reilly and state
insurance Commissioner Linda Ruthardt to ask the Supreme Judicial
Court to place the health plan in receivership.
</P>
<P>
   The eight health centers represent Harvard Pilgrim's most
accessible capital assets. A recent independent appraisal put their
value, on a current-use basis, at $144.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   Health care specialists who have reviewed Harvard Pilgrim's
finances say that amount would return the HMO to solvency. However,
it is not clear whether it would be sufficient to clear up the
nonprofit HMO's long-term problems, following this month's
disclosure that 1999 losses could reach $177 million.
</P>
<P>
   If recapitalization of Harvard Pilgrim turns out not to be
possible, Reilly said the investment firm should be ready with
names of possible buyers, who could include out-of-state for-profit
companies. ``Everything is on the table,'' Reilly said.
</P>
<P>
   Everything, he added, except state funding. ``The options we
have asked the investment bankers to pursue, those we're most
interested in, do not involve any spending of state money.''
</P>
<P>
   One local health care finance specialist said potential
investors might be attracted by the promise of some state support,
such as a loan or bond guarantee backed by the full faith and
credit of the commonwealth.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly would not rule out a state loan guarantee. ``It's
premature to talk about it,'' said Dean Richlin, Reilly's chief
deputy.
</P>
<P>
   One reason Salomon Smith Barney may have had an inside track,
among the three firms that were finalists for the Harvard Pilgrim
job, is that it is intimately familiar with Harvard Pilgrim's
current finances, having performed due diligence on the recent
aborted bond issue, which was sponsored by the Massachusetts Health
and Educational Facilities Authority, an agency that arranges
financing for nonprofits.
</P>
<P>
   Salomon also handled Harvard Pilgrim's 1998 sale of $195 million
in HEFA bonds, mostly a refinancing, according to Robert Ciolek,
the agency's executive director.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
