<HEADLINE>
FED SURVEY SHOWS MORE STOCK OWNERSHIP, GREATER WEALTH GAP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A soaring stock market fueled an unprecedented increase in
wealth for Americans between 1995 and 1998 as the number of
families owning stock rose to record levels, according to a Federal
Reserve Board survey charting changes over the three-year period.
</P>
<P>
   While the nation is enjoying a golden era of economic prosperity
and low unemployment, the Fed's 1998 Survey of Consumer Finances
also found evidence the boom has been stingy in distributing the
wealth to low-income wage earners, who fell behind because they
lacked the wherewithal to invest in stocks. In a troubling trend,
Americans across the income spectrum are more deeply in debt than
they were in the early part of the decade, though debt burdens are
heaviest for low-income individuals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rich are getting richer, and they are getting richer
faster than the poor,'' David Wyss, economist for Standard &AMP; Poor's
DRI, an economic consulting firm in Lexington, Mass., concluded
from the report.
</P>
<P>
   While middle-class and wealthy Americans' prosperity rose in
concert with the great bull market of the 1990s, what distinguished
the Fed's 1998 survey was the enormity of gains compared with past
surveys. In 1998, Americans' wealth far surpassed levels reached in
the late 1980s, when the stock market also was rising rapidly. The
Fed has conducted the survey every three years since 1989.
</P>
<P>
   ``While income continued a moderate upward trend'' in recent
years, ``net worth grew strongly, and the increase in net worth was
broadly shared by different demographic groups,'' the Fed report
said. Financial gains were especially large among middle-aged and
retired Americans in their peak saving and investing years.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, experts said, points to the growing dependence of
Americans on the stock market for their financial well-being. The
market has achieved a new record every year since 1995, producing
profits that could evaporate rapidly if there were a correction.
</P>
<P>
   Stock profits through 1998 were enormous. The value of stock
mutual funds and individual shares held by top-earning Americans
surged, at the median, to $150,000 in 1998 _ up 75 percent over the
past three years and triple levels a decade ago. Middle-class
Americans saw their stock portfolios grow 35 percent over the past
three years, to $11,500, while low-income earners posted small
gains in the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, median family wealth _ the net worth for a family
that fell smack in the middle of all Americans _ rose 17.6 percent
from 1995 through 1998, a period in which the Dow Jones industrial
average surged from 3700 to more than 9200. That was more than
twice the growth rate of median family wealth for the prior three
years, 1992 to 1995. (The survey uses net worth to measure wealth.
Net worth subtracts a family's liabilities, such as a mortgage,
from its assets, such as real estate, stocks, and other
investments.)
</P>
<P>
   Looked at another way, wealth shot up even more. Average net
worth _ which gives more weight to the portfolios of the wealthy,
such as Microsoft Corp. chairman Bill Gates or Internet executives
_ than do median figures, rose nearly 26 percent and reflected the
ballooning portfolios of the elite.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed's survey was based on detailed interviews with 4,300
families. Although officials did not disclose individuals included
in the survey, the study was supplemented with tax records to
provide better information on the difficult-to-decipher holdings of
the richest Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Driving big increases for some was a record number of US
families _ nearly half _ who owned stock, either directly by
purchasing individual shares themselves, or through mutual funds
and retirement accounts. A decade ago, less than a third of
American families held stock. (Stock options, which are difficult
to value, were not included in wealth totals.)
</P>
<P>
   Investing in individual stocks, which lost favor when Americans
began pouring money into mutual funds in the early 1980s, made a
comeback, which experts said may be due to the growing popularity
of on-line brokerage accounts, day trading, and Internet stocks.
Direct investments in shares accounted for nearly 23 percent of all
financial assets in 1998, a 7 percentage-point jump in three years.
Mutual funds, which also included huge stock portfolios, were
little changed at 12.5 percent of all financial assets.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have been saying for decades that it would be a good
thing when workers . . . were stock owners,'' said John Weicher, a
senior fellow at the Hudson Institute. That trend toward more stock
ownership ``is good news.''
</P>
<P>
   Going against the broad trend of Americans getting ahead were
the figures for those who earn $25,000 or less. Even though some
had stock profits, the median net worth of low-income Americans
declined by 20 to 25 percent from 1995 to 1998. The median net
worth also dipped for minorities, in contrast to big gains among
those with higher incomes and among white Americans.
</P>
<P>
   But even for those whose portolios are flush, longer-term trends
are less spectacular, said Edward Wolff, a leading expert on wealth
data. The Gulf War recession and a sagging stock market in the wake
of the 1987 correction took away much of the gains earned in the
stock market runup of the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of (the gains are) just catch-up to where it should've
been,'' said Wolff, an economics professor at New York University.
Looking at gains over the past decade are ``not as spectacular as
looking to '95 to '98.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, debt levels are up sharply. Nearly 13 percent
of Americans spend more than 40 percent of their income on debt,
including mortgages on homes. That is up from a 11 percent or less
in all prior year's surveys. ``People are mortgaging themselves to
death so that they can buy a slightly bigger car,'' Wolff said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite wider ownership of stocks, Weicher of the Hudson
Institute estimated that a quarter of Americans' wealth still rests
in their homes, with only about 9 percent in stocks. A record
two-thirds of all families own their primary residence, the Fed
survey said. More are also entering the financial mainstream: 90
percent of families now have a checking account.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
