<DOCNO> NYT20000118.0311 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-18 20:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9547 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-AFC-BRUNELL-COX     01-18 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-AFC-BRUNELL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Brunell not ducking a rematch
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE, Fla. _ Mark Brunell was waiting a minute or two at
his locker during the Jaguars' lunch break Tuesday. He was trying
to stand still as he waited for reporters to assemble.
</P>
<P>
   So much is on the line and so much energy is ready to be
expended in a quest to beat the Tennessee Titans in Sunday's AFC
Championship Game. When Brunell eventually got to talking, he
bounced impatiently on his feet, emphasizing each word.
</P>
<P>
   They Jaguars aren't ducking anything. After two losses to
Tennessee this season, they get a third try to beat the Titans,
with everything on the line.
</P>
<P>
   And here Mark Brunell is, knowing that the road to the Super
Bowl ends in Atlanta and wanting no part of waiting. ``I guess you
could call it `unfinished business,''' Brunell said. ``We would
have hated to finish the season without having gotten another shot
at these guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Brunell occasionally rubbed his left kneecap as he
spoke, he insists that the knee is sound. And he can thank the
Miami Dolphins for that. In the 62-7 laugher of a divisional
playoff Saturday, Jaguars coach Tom Coughlin was able both to win
big and to rest Brunell. Surprisingly mobile for a man who had been
injured by the Titans in Week 15, Brunell played just 18 minutes
Saturday. He completed 5 of 9 passes for 105 yards and two scores,
and the Jaguars led 38-0, so the quarterback took a seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``The knee feels great,'' Brunell said. ``The game against Miami
couldn't have gone better, as far as the knee is concerned. I got
hit a couple of times, but it felt strong, and I was able to move
around a little bit. I expect it Sunday to be 100 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   That is great news for the Jaguars, who have watched Brunell
push them to 13 winning fourth-quarter drives over five seasons.
Although the Titans have beaten the Jaguars twice, the game that
will determine a Super Bowl assignment is more likely to resemble
the 20-19 type in Week 3 than the 41-14 blowout in Nashville last
month.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mindset is that it's a new game,'' Brunell said. ``One,
I'm glad that we're at home. And certainly, we're facing a team
that's playing great football right now. Defensively, they're
incredible. They have every reason to have confidence coming in
here.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jaguars probably could have gotten past the Dolphins with
backup Jay Fiedler, but they aren't likely to conquer the Titans
without their best quarterback. In five seasons with the Jaguars,
Brunell has assumed a position in the passing statistics alongside
Joe Montana, Steve Young and Brett Favre.
</P>
<P>
   Or as Jacksonville offensive tackle Leon Searcy says, ``Mark's
the man who puts food on my table. He's the breadwinner. Without
him, the family's not complete.''
</P>
<P>
   With the players around him having matured since a 20-9 loss to
New England in the 1996 AFC title game, Brunell senses that the
outcome will not be the same this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We aren't the young team we were that '96 season,'' he said.
``Some guys have been around for a while and have played in big
games before. A lot of that shows up in how the younger players
watch the older players prepare. Putting in extra time. More film.
Working a little extra hard. Getting a little more excited. That's
real important.''
</P>
<P>
   So are the mind games that will be played in the media all week.
The Titans must wonder how they can be 7-point underdogs while
representing the only two losses on Jacksonville's record. Not to
mention hearing all the Jaguars proclaim that they wanted the
Titans all along.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure they're taking it (from us) as that being a cocky
statement, but it really isn't,'' Brunell said. ``We would like to
play them because they beat us a couple of times. It's really as
simple as that. It's not an in-your-face kind of comment. We wanted
another shot at the team that beat us pretty bad and also beat us
here at home. It would be a way to complete our season if we could
beat them and answer a few questions as to who's the better team.''
</P>
<P>
   The leader emerging from him, Brunell said, ``We've got great
character on this team. This has been our closest team so far. Guys
have got a lot of leadership on this team, a lot of accountability.
Nobody wants to let the other guy down, and that might be the most
important thing about a team. Nobody wants to be the one to mess it
up for everybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Sheeley writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
