<HEADER>
A9554 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-BRADLEY-CAMPAIGN-ART-     01-18 0683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-CAMPAIGN-ART-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY PROMISES TO CONTINUE CAMPAIGN AT LEAST THROUGH `SUPER
TUESDAY'
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT10 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   IOWA CITY, Iowa _ Former Sen. Bill Bradley vowed on Tuesday to
continue his insurgent campaign for president through at least the
March 7 ``Super Tuesday'' primaries even if he loses to Vice
President Al Gore in the first two events of the nominating season
in Iowa and New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's remarks suggest that Gore, considered the favorite for
the Democratic nomination, cannot count on knocking Bradley out of
the race quickly and could face an extended campaign that would
leave the eventual winner penniless.
</P>
<P>
   Polls show Bradley trailing Gore by a wide margin in Iowa, which
holds its caucuses on Monday. But the two are thought to be running
even in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Gore said they have always expected Bradley to fight on
until the March 7 primaries, which include New York, where Bradley
played professional basketball for the Knicks from 1967 until 1977.
California, Ohio, Georgia and seven other states also vote on March
7, which Bradley refers to as the ``national primary.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley made his remarks on Tuesday in response to questions
about how he compares with insurgents of the past, particularly
Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, the Massachusetts Democrat who challenged
President Jimmy Carter in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy lost in Iowa, 59 percent to 31 percent, and never gained
the momentum he needed to unseat Carter. Nevertheless, with limited
resources, he managed to win the New York and California primaries
and kept his campaign going until the convention, though Carter's
nomination had become a foregone conclusion by then.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Bradley said he was different from Kennedy because
he has matched Gore in fund-raising while Kennedy lacked the
resources to sustain a national campaign after his poor Iowa
showing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question was, did he have resources to go on,'' Bradley
said of Kennedy. ``I'm not sure he did.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There really is a separate national campaign,'' he continued
during a news conference in a high school in this university town.
``And we have the resources to compete in that campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bradley campaign also announced on Tuesday that Gov. John
Kitzhaber of Oregon will on Wednesday become the first sitting
governor to endorse Bradley. ``He thinks Senator Bradley's got the
right approach on health care,'' said Bob Applegate, a spokesman
for Kitzhaber, a physician.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Aides to Gore say they think Bradley has had a poor couple of
weeks in Iowa. They assert that Gore decisively won a Jan. 8 debate
in Des Moines, has effectively attacked Bradley's positions on farm
policy and has won over many undecided Democrats by picking up the
endorsement of Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore aides also contend that recent attacks by Bradley
against Gore's record, including his votes in Congress on tobacco
legislation 15 years ago, show that Bradley is worried that the
race is slipping away.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore's supporters are also concerned that Bradley could win
just enough delegates on March 7 to block Gore from clinching the
nomination. The campaign could then drag into the March 14
primaries in Texas, Florida and four other southern states.
</P>
<P>
   While Gore's supporters are confident the vice president can
knock Bradley out of the race on March 14, they are also worried
that the added expense of carrying the fight south will leave his
campaign bankrupt. For that reason, they say, pressure will grow on
Bradley to drop out if he loses in both Iowa and New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are in a quixotic mission that can only drain
Democratic time and resources, you might come to the conclusion
that it would be to the benefit of the party and the country to get
out,'' said Rep. Robert Menendez, a New Jersey Democrat who is
supporting Gore.
</P>
</TEXT>
