<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-18 20:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9556 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-HOUSTON-CASSERLY-     01-18 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-HOUSTON-CASSERLY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN McCLAIN  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
Former Washington Redskins general manager Charley Casserly will be
hired as the vice president of football operations for Houston's
NFL expansion team, sources said Tuesday.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Casserly, who won three Super Bowl rings during his 22 years
with the Redskins, could be introduced as early as today, a league
source said.
</P>
<P>
   Owner Bob McNair and executive vice president Steve Patterson
were in New York on Tuesday for an NFL meeting, and they were
expected to return to Houston today for the announcement.
</P>
<P>
   Casserly's multiyear contract is expected to be signed when he
comes to Houston for the announcement. A source close to McNair
said details were still being worked out Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Casserly, who spent his entire NFL career with the Redskins
before new owner Daniel Snyder fired him before this season, will
run the personnel side of the operation. The first head coach won't
be hired until after the 2000 season at the earliest, with the team
set to begin play in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Casserly was one of only two candidates interviewed by McNair
and Patterson. Joe Mack, who helped start up expansion teams in
Carolina and Cleveland, was the other candidate.
</P>
<P>
   McNair said he was impressed with Casserly from the first time
they talked on the telephone. McNair said he was even more
impressed when they met in person 10 days ago.
</P>
<P>
   Casserly also talked with the Jets and Saints. A league source
said the Steelers tried and failed to get him to interview this
week for the job vacated last week by director of football
operations Tom Donahoe, who resigned after losing a power struggle
with coach Bill Cowher.
</P>
<P>
   Cowher and Casserly are good friends after serving on the NFL
competition committee for years.
</P>
<P>
   The league source said Casserly spoke with a couple of teams on
the telephone but wouldn't agree to interview in person because he
was so close to completing a deal with McNair.
</P>
<P>
   McNair said from the start that his first choice was to hire
someone who had been successful running the football side of the
operation. Later, he said he wanted someone with experience in
scouting, contracts, the salary cap and free agency. Casserly ran
the whole show in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   This season was the ideal time for Casserly to be out of work,
because the Redskins won the NFC East and advanced to the second
round of the playoffs. Almost every move Casserly made before he
was fired paid off this season.
</P>
<P>
   Even though he was out of a job, Pro Football Weekly voted him
the NFL Executive of the Half-Season.
</P>
<P>
   Casserly traded for quarterback Brad Johnson. Two receivers
Casserly drafted _ Michael Westbrook and Albert Connell _ had their
best seasons. Running back Stephen Davis, another Casserly pick,
developed into one of the best in the league.
</P>
<P>
   Casserly elected to wheel and deal in the draft. He ended up
with Georgia cornerback Champ Bailey, who was exceptional. And,
most important of all, Casserly left Washington with three No. 1
picks in the April draft.
</P>
<P>
   By firing Casserly with a year left on his contract, Snyder
actually did him a favor. Casserly worked for ESPN Radio, and he
had a lot of time on his hands to prepare for his interview with
McNair, who said he was impressed with how organized Casserly was.
</P>
<P>
   Because Casserly didn't have an NFL job this season for the
first time since he was hired in 1977 as an unpaid intern by late
Redskins coach George Allen, he was able to get his foot in
McNair's door first. And Casserly took advantage of being first in
line.
</P>
<P>
   After speaking with McNair on the telephone several times over
the months, Casserly had his first face-to-face meeting with McNair
in Houston 10 days ago.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Casserly and his wife, Bev, and daughter, Shannon, came to
Houston last Thursday and didn't leave until Sunday. While Casserly
continued to meet with McNair, his wife and daughter looked at
neighborhoods and schools.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
