A9557 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-AFC-TITANS-COX     01-18 0528
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-AFC-TITANS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Titans at home on road
 &HT;    By Karen Rosen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. _ Marcus Robertson sought out fellow defensive
back Samari Rolle after the Titans put away the Colts on Sunday
night to earn a trip to the AFC Championship Game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked at him after the game,'' Robertson said, ``and I
said, 'We've got the Jacksonville killer, so we're going to be all
right.'''
</P>
<P>
   Rolle has four career interceptions _ all against the Jaguars in
Tennessee's two victories over Jacksonville this season. He had the
game-ending interception in the 20-19 win Sept. 26. On Dec. 26,
Tennessee won 41-14 in Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   But as the Titans prepare to face the Jaguars for the third
time, history is not on their side. They're still considered David
to the Jaguars Goliath.
</P>
<P>
   Since the AFL and NFL merged in 1970, no team has beaten the
same team three times in one season with the final win coming on
the road. Sunday's game will be at Alltel Stadium. Of the 12 teams
who had a chance to sweep, seven did it, but only with the last
game at home.
</P>
<P>
   However, Tennessee is comfortable on the road, a result of the
team's two-years of wandering before it settled into its permanent
home here. The Titans played in Memphis and at Vanderbilt Stadium
in Nashville before Adelphia Coliseum opened.
</P>
<P>
   That odyssey, said running back Eddie George, ``toughened us
up... for everything that we're battling now. For two years, every
game was a road game. We played in a lot of hostile environments _
including our home games.''
</P>
<P>
   But while the Titans are confident entering Sunday's game,
they're not brashly guaranteeing a win.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why they ``own'' the Jaguars, winning four out of five
games in Alltel, George laughed. ``That's you saying that,'' he
said. ``We'll go down there with a good game plan and try to get a
win.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the teams are familiar with each other's tendencies,
``I don't think there's going to be any surprises,'' said
quarterback Steve McNair, who had five touchdown passes in the
second win. ``It's just a matter of winning the one-on-one
battles.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the Titans' dominance, Jacksonville is favored to win
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like being the underdogs,'' receiver Yancey Thigpen said.
``When you're underdogs, nobody expects you to win. Around here,
our motto is, `Expect the unexpected.' ``
</P>
<P>
   As well as the expected, which is that Jacksonville wants to
avoid the disgrace of losing three times to the Titans.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's something hard to live with,'' Thigpen said. ``If we
limit the turnovers, and so do they, it's going to be whoever wants
it the most, who can pound on each other most, and cause the other
one to `give,' basically.''
</P>
<P>
   Robertson said the ``bitter rivalry'' has been heating up ever
since the Jaguars played their first franchise game against the
then-Oilers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We love competing against each other,'' he said. ``There's a
lot of trash (talk), believe me. Guys are on the telephone now.''
</P>
<P>
   Karen Rosen writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
