u w BC-SCOTUS-VOTE-HNS &LR;      01-18 1143
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-VOTE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH COURT HANDS TEXAS HISPANICS A MAJOR VOTING DEFEAT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Hispanic voters in the Houston and San Antonio
areas Tuesday lost a Supreme Court challenge to their local school
boards' method of electing members, which the Latinos claimed saps
their voting strength.
</P>
<P>
   The justices' refusal, without comment, to hear the voters'
appeal marked a stunning defeat for Hispanics in the Pasadena and
Alamo Heights school districts who saw the Supreme Court as perhaps
their last hope to ensure adequate Latino representation on the
boards.
</P>
<P>
   The Pasadena Independent School District, which includes parts
of Houston, has had only one Hispanic trustee, and the Alamo
Heights Independent School District has had none.
</P>
<P>
   The Hispanic voters are now left to seek relief legislatively
when districts are redrawn after this year's census, said the
Latinos' attorney, Jose Garza of McAllen.
</P>
<P>
   The Hispanic voters had challenged the at-large election systems
in the Pasadena and Alamo Heights districts, saying the voting
schemes diluted Latinos' electoral influence and prevented
Hispanics from getting elected.
</P>
<P>
   But the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in New Orleans
disagreed last winter, prompting the voters' ill-fated appeal to
the justices.
</P>
<P>
   Hispanics comprise a high percentage but not a majority of the
two school districts.
</P>
<P>
   Latinos, for example, make up about 30 percent of the Pasadena
Independent School District, which covers 85 square miles of
southeastern Harris County and includes parts of Houston, South
Houston and Pasadena.
</P>
<P>
   Hispanic students make up 42 percent of the student body. A
seven-member board of trustees governs the district.
</P>
<P>
   About 18 percent of the Alamo Heights Independent School
District near San Antonio is Hispanic. But Hispanics account for
about 24 percent of the student body.
</P>
<P>
   Like Pasadena, a seven-member board of trustees governs the
district.
</P>
<P>
   Citing the population figures, the 5th Circuit said Pasadena and
Alamo Heights could not have weakened the Hispanics' vote because
no election precinct could reasonably be drawn in which Latinos
would comprise more than half the population. Because having
majority voting strength was never a possibility, Hispanics cannot
say their votes have been dampened, the court said.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the school district hailed the high court's decision
to leave the electing method intact.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very pleased with the outcome. It is what we expected,''
said Kirk Lewis, a spokesman for the Pasadena school district.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've known from the beginning that we were in compliance with
the voting regulations. We have done everything we can do make
voting more accessible to all of our community. Our board and our
community believe in the at-large system because it makes all seven
board members responsible for the entire community not just one
segment.''
</P>
<P>
   Carmen Orozco, the only Hispanic member on the school board,
said she, too, was pleased with the high court's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very happy with it because I know that we were not
discriminating either in our voting or in the use of our funds in
our school district. We are serving all of our children equally. At
this point I would say I'm extremely happy with the outcome,'' said
Orozco, 63, a retired executive secretary, who has been on the
board almost 13 years.
</P>
<P>
   Orozco said she was to be elected to the school board even
though she is a Hispanic female because of her involvement in the
district for 18 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that anyone can be elected to the school district if
they campaign with the interest of children at heart and not with
any other political agenda,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Celestino M. Perez Jr., who was a plaintiff in the case and
represented the group Pasadena Citizens for Equitable
Representation, could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   The 5th Circuit, in the decisions the justices let stand, also
rejected the voters' argument that the federal Voting Rights Act's
protection of minorities required school districts, in some
instances, to count all Hispanics, including non-U.S. citizens,
when determining the population of voting precincts.
</P>
<P>
   The inclusion of Hispanic non-U.S. citizens would have increased
the Latino populations in Pasadena and Alamo Heights, thereby
enabling the school districts to draw majority-Hispanic precincts,
the voters said. But the 5th Circuit said the law protects only the
voting rights of U.S. citizens.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question that it would be patently absurd'' for a
court to count noncitizens among a population of eligible voters,
Pasadena's attorney, Bernard Brooks of nearby Stafford, said
Tuesday. ``The Voting Rights Act only protects those people who can
vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Alamo Heights' attorney, C. Robert Heath of Austin, echoed
Brooks in saying the 5th Circuit correctly interpreted the Voting
Rights Act and that the justices properly rejected the appeal.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court's rejection of the appeal was also a loss for
the Clinton administration, which had urged the justices to
interpret the Voting Rights Act broadly to give Hispanics greater
electoral strength.
</P>
<P>
   The administration, in a legal brief to the high court, said the
5th Circuit wrongly decided that a minority group's voting strength
can be weakened only if that group could reasonably comprise a
majority in at least one precinct. The Voting Rights Act protects
the electoral strength of closely knit minority groups, such as
Hispanics, even when they constitute a small but vocal minority,
the administration wrote in its brief.
</P>
<P>
   By protecting the voting strength of Hispanics, the law
preserves the possibility that a small number of white voters could
cross over and help a minority of Hispanics elect a Latino board
member, wrote U.S. Solicitor General Seth Waxman, the
administration's top lawyer before the high court.
</P>
<P>
   But a weakening of that Hispanic vote would make it
significantly more difficult for a Latino candidate to garner
enough white crossover votes, he added.
</P>
<P>
   The administration, however, broke from the Hispanic voters in
urging the justices to reject the argument that non-U.S. citizens
could be calculated under the Voting Rights Act. The federal law
bars any practice that denies or abridges ``the right of any
citizen of the United States to vote on account of race or language
minority status,'' Waxman wrote, adding that the statute makes no
reference to noncitizens.
</P>
<P>
   Congress passed the 1965 law to remedy discrimination against
blacks and other minorities seeking to assert their constitutional
right to vote. The statute expressly prohibits states and local
jurisdictions from diluting the voting strength of minorities.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
