<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-18 20:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9561 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-DEBATES-RDP-2TAKES-NY     01-18 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEBATES-RDP-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE LACK OF VIEWERS, DEBATES PLAY CRUCIAL ROLE IN CAMPAIGN
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: 2nd Take is scheduled to move by 9:30 p.m. ET) 
(sw) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa _ At first glance, the results after the first
round of more than a dozen presidential debates do not seem
encouraging: Most of them attracted fewer television viewers
nationwide than Dilbert, the cartoon about a grumpy office worker
which last week ranked 146 in the Nielsen ratings _drawing about
1.8 million viewers. The debates were lucky to pull more than 1.5
million.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, politicians and strategists say the debates have been
the most crucial factor in framing the political dynamic in the
run-up to the Iowa caucuses on Monday. The encounters have set the
tone for the television news coverage, which reaches far greater
audiences, and have highlighted the substance over which the
candidates have engaged.
</P>
<P>
   It was at those forums that the candidates articulated their
views _ at times in impenetrable detail _ on matters ranging from
tax cuts to health care to campaign reform to whether John Rocker,
the Atlanta Braves pitcher, needs psychotherapy.
</P>
<P>
   Rarely in presidential politics have so many candidates taken
part in so many debates before the voting begins in the Iowa
caucuses. The major Republican contenders participated in seven
debates; the Democrats held six.
</P>
<P>
   It is a striking contrast to four years ago, when there was no
Democratic contest and the Republican competition was shaped more
by 30-second television attack commercials that dominated the
airwaves here and in New Hampshire. There were only three
Republican debates before the voting in Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   ``In `96, you had a situation where the ads _ and response ads _
were dictating the terms of the campaign,'' said Tony Fabrizio, who
was the pollster for Bob Dole, the Republican nominee four years
ago. ``Now it's the debates.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Mark McKinnon, the chief ad-maker for Gov. George W. Bush
of Texas, conceded that the debates have had greater impact than
the commercials. ``The debates have greater credibility because
people see them as unfiltered,'' he said. ``And there is a larger
microphone from the press to the public on these debates than there
ever has been before.''
</P>
<P>
   Politicians, academics and civic groups all praised the frenzy
of debates for elevating the discourse _ and giving the public a
genuine opportunity to observe the people competing to be the next
president. They also said that some candidates took advantage of
the opportunity to remake themselves before the public.
</P>
<P>
   For example, many strategists said Vice President Al Gore used
the hours of television exposure to articulate the differences
between his health care plan and that of his rival, former Sen.
Bill Bradley. Others argued that the debates allowed Bradley, who
was far less known than the vice president, to make his pitch to a
broader audience than he would roaming Iowa and New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   The tiny fraction of Americans who watched the encounters was
also treated to a rare, sometimes even spontaneous, glimpse at the
evolution of candidates for president.
</P>
<P>
   Viewers witnessed the transformation of Bush from an awkward,
taut politician to one who _ while still on guard _ grew
increasingly self-assured.
</P>
<P>
   They observed Sen. John McCain of Arizona keeping his cool as he
smiled broadly through intense questioning about his campaign
reform proposal _ and his own fund-raising practices.
</P>
<P>
   They watched as Gore progressed from a combative, perhaps
overanxious, persona to one of calm and confidence. And they saw
Bradley evolve from a passive debater who did not even respond to
Gore's broadsides to an assertive, at times sarcastic, combatant
who in their last debate here Monday night ridiculed the Clinton
administration on the issue of racial profiling.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had the effect of a mini-series _ the same characters
kept coming back in new installments,'' said Alan D. Schroeder, a
journalism professor at Northeastern University in Boston who is an
authority on presidential debates. ``In every case we learned
something because debates, by definition, offer insight into the
candidates that the candidates don't necessarily want us to have.''
</P>
<P>
   As healthy as the debates may have been for the electorate, they
were not necessarily helpful to the candidates. As an example,
Steve Forbes, the wealthy publisher, often seemed lost in the
sparring between Bush and his other rivals, and was largely unable
to use the forums to embolden his campaign. Of course, the success
of the politicians is in the eye of the viewer.
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans argue that the events planted doubts about
Bush's command of issues. Others say that with every encounter, he
grew more impressive. ``Any one who is skeptical about Governor
Bush's ability to speak in complete sentences _ that was put to
rest a while ago,'' said Kellyanne Fitzpatrick, a Republican
pollster.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Shrum, a veteran media adviser who works for Gore, said
the debates were of immense importance. He said despite the
relatively small viewership, and sometimes critical news coverage
of his candidate's performance, the events allowed Gore to win over
voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a tremendous disconnect in almost every debate
between how I think voters reacted and a lot of political reporters
and commentators reacted,'' Shrum said.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
