<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jaguar notebook: Defining the difference between miracles and
destinies
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE, Fla. _ The Jacksonville Jaguars seek a
clarification. There are differences between miracles, fate and
real life, something they wish to impart to Tennessee and the
``Team of Destiny'' theme emanating from Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to have a revelation anytime a miracle comes
about,'' Jacksonville tackle Leon Searcy said. ``What happened in
Tennessee against Buffalo (in the first round) was something
immaculate, something unexplainable. They have every right to feel
that way. We can't cheat them of that. They did achieve a
miracle.''
</P>
<P>
   And was it another miracle that the Titans beat the Jags twice
in 1999?
</P>
<P>
   ``That wasn't a miracle,'' Searcy said, clarifying. ``They just
had our number.''
</P>
<P>
   There's a difference, just as there is a different between the
emotion that has come to boil so soon between these two teams.
</P>
<P>
   Some say it borders on hatred. ``I guess you could say that,''
wide receiver Jimmy Smith said. ``But I just think most of all it's
just a rivalry, a divisional rivalry, We both made it to the AFC
Championship. You could say the rivalry continues.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's some flashes of arrogance. There always is,''
Jacksonville coach Tom Coughlin said. ``Some talk. No question
about that. Because we are familiar with one another, there's a
nastiness about the way in which each team plays one another.
</P>
<P>
   ``But they're a team that sets the tone physically. You're going
to have to answer that bell, if you're going to beat them.''
</P>
<P>
   Preparations
</P>
<P>
   Despite two previous meetings, the second of them just three
weeks ago, the Jaguars staff began doing its game plan from scratch
for the Titans. Asked if he thought that his team did anything
particularly well in the 41-14 loss at Tennessee on Dec. 26,
Coughlin replied, ``We got there on time and were ready for the
kickoff.''
</P>
<P>
   A number of Jaguars confessed to having replayed that 27-point
rout in their minds in the passing weeks. Asked how the game might
go if he could play it over, safety Carney Lake thought a long
moment and replied, ``Well, we'd win.''
</P>
<P>
   Fresh market
</P>
<P>
   Some 3,000 seats for the AFC Championship put on sale Tuesday
were gone before lunch, as Jacksonville scalpers get a first chance
to press a new NFL market. Posted on-line offers for tickets have
reached $500, while professional brokers were seeking $650.
</P>
<P>
   The Jaguars season-ticket base of 45,000 were given first chance
at extra tickets after last Saturday's divisional semifinal win
over Miami. Another 12,000 seats were sold that way, and, after the
NFL claimed its allotment, roughly 4 percent of Alltel Stadium's
75,600 tickets remained for public sale.
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   The Jags scored just four more points than Tennessee this season
but held opponents to 107 fewer. . . . Asked about the carry-over
from the 62-7 win over Miami on Saturday, Jacksonville guard Zack
Wiegert said, ``That game ended 10 minutes after we came into the
locker room. No one was really celebrating that win. Everyone was
talking about, 'We've got to do it next week.' `` . . . Although
just a five-year-old franchise, Jacksonville has grown up fast. Of
the 53 players on their current roster, 34 players had seen
postseason experience before this month. Fifteen current Jags
played in the 1996 AFC title game, a 20-6 loss at New England. . .
. Jags quarterback Mark Brunell has a career 60 percent completion
rate against the Titans/Oilers, good for 1,464 yards _ a 209-yard
average in seven starts _ with eight touchdowns but 10
interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Stinson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
