<HEADLINE>
BOURQUE PRACTICES, DESPITE MOUTH INJURY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Not 24 hours earlier, Ray Bourque had been on the
FleetCenter ice, taking a deflected slapshot in the mouth that
knocked out three of his teeth and required 11 stitches in his
upper lip. He needed more stitches for the damage inside his mouth.
</P>
<P>
   Bourque left the game against Atlanta after being struck late in
the first period, and coach Pat Burns wasn't sure how long his
captain would be out of action.
</P>
<P>
   Burns got his answer Tuesday when Bourque joined his teammates
at the FleetCenter for practice. Few had expected him to be there,
but the 39-year-old veteran of 21 National Hockey League seasons
couldn't figure out what the big deal was. When asked why he
practiced, Bourque answered, ``Why not?''
</P>
<P>
   Bourque's lip was still very swollen but, he said, ``I'm not in
pain. It's a long way from my legs. I could skate, I can play. I
would've liked to have come back and played (Monday). But I guess
that wouldn't have been very smart.''
</P>
<P>
   Bourque will be in the lineup Wednesday in Atlanta. There isn't
much that can be done until his lip and gums heal and the swelling
goes away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to go to the dentist and have a few things done, and now
they've got to wait to give me a temp until my gum heals up,'' he
said. ``It's a crazy game sometimes. You know you've been hit and
you know you've lost some teeth. It's not the first time. I've had
sticks hit me and pucks hit me. I've never shattered my teeth like
this.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's coming is half a dozen visits to the dentist, and
that's not much fun. I just have to find time to do it. We'll see
how good the temporaries look.''
</P>
<P>
   The injury occurred when Thrashers center Ray Ferraro teed up a
slapper from inside the blue line, and Bourque put his stick out to
block it. The puck rode up the stick and struck him flush in the
mouth.
</P>
<P>
   It's actually something that happens a lot, said Bourque, but
his half-visor often protects him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The visor has saved me many times,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Burns wasn't surprised to see Bourque back so quickly. It's just
the way he is.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he could've, he probably would've come back for the third
period if they would've let him,'' said Burns. ``We'd have some
guys who would be out for a month with that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I liked the way he stood up and shook off the trainers, like,
`I'll skate under my own will power.' The young kids should look at
that. Sometimes you see guys go down and they've got to get the
stretchers out there. He just shook the guy off and said, `I'm
going to the bench.' So you have to respect that.''
</P>
<P>
   The coach doesn't envy Bourque for what lies ahead: namely, the
drilling necessary to repair his mouth.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worst part is what he has to go get done now,'' said
Burns. ``To get those anchors put in. That hurts. That's no fun.
They'll have to let the swelling go down before they can put those
anchors in.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a competitor and he's one of the old-school guys. And he
loves to play the game. Him and (Dave) Andreychuk. Look at
Andreychuk _ his knee popped out and he was back out there (two
games later) scoring the tying goal (against Atlanta).''
</P>
<P>
   Bourque's presence at practice wasn't lost on the young members
of the team. Joe Thornton was surprised and impressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's probably been my biggest fear, losing all my teeth,''
said Thornton, who has a chipped front tooth from hockey but
nothing worse. ``You can't do anything about it. He had a
mouthguard in. It's one of those fluke things. You see Dr. (Bert)
Zarins picking up his teeth on the ice. I don't know in what other
sports you can see that stuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he's out there, he doesn't want to miss a day, he doesn't
want to miss a beat. It's unbelievable how he works. He's a
machine. (The lesson is) never take a day off and that's why he's
been so successful for so long. He wants to be the best he can be,
and if we can be half of what he is, we'll be all right.''
</P>
<P>
   For Bourque, it's just business as usual.
</P>
<P>
   ``This can be fixed,'' he said. ``A lot of us with broken teeth
end up looking better because they make them better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
