u e BC-SOPRANOS-COX     01-18 0873
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOPRANOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 - COX &HT;    ``The Sopranos'' hits the mark
 &HT;    by Kevin J. Thompson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Take a juicy, yet familiar mob tale, add
a delicious twist of black humor, mix in chaotic family life and
hire a balding, overweight actor as your star.
</P>
<P>
   Whaddya get? Bada bing! The biggest %(at)!!! phenomenon cable
television has ever seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Sopranos,'' HBO's white-hot mob series, is no longer just
a TV show. It's an event. A happening. A juggernaut. Sixteen Emmy
nominations. Universal critical acclaim. Widespread viewer
acceptance. Fan letters from Stephen King and Elvis Costello. The
best TV show _ ever. Well, not quite, but the kudos have gone that
far.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Sopranos,'' which kicks off its second season today at 9
p.m., is possibly one of the most praised shows in television
history.
</P>
<P>
   HBO certainly spared no expense to tout its programming crown
jewel, shelling out $10 million to pump up interest in the eagerly
anticipated sophomore season. Ads were plastered everywhere _
magazines, billboards, buses, newspapers, other cable channels.
There were lavish premiere parties in New York and Los Angeles. A
fake Soprano Waste Management garbage truck was even sent to
shopping malls to lure potential HBO subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the most comprehensive campaign we've ever done,'' says
Chris Donlay, an HBO spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The question is: Why has a show about an angst- ridden,
middle-aged mob capo with all sorts of family problems captured our
imagination?
</P>
<P>
   The answer is simple. When you strip away the violent whackings,
shady dealings and four-letter words, ``The Sopranos'' is really
about family. It's that essential ingredient that makes the show
work so well. While Tony Soprano (James Gandolfini) has a job most
of us can't relate to, we can identify with him as a father. A
husband. A son. He's an ordinary guy who wants to enroll his
daughter in a good college. He has an overbearing mom who's quick
to berate and criticize. He suffers from medical problems stemming
from the stress in his life. He needs someone to talk to.
</P>
<P>
   Does any of this sound familiar?
</P>
<P>
   `` 'The Sopranos ' has taken a familiar genre, the Mafia drama,
and given it an unexpected twist, a semi-humorous twist,'' says Tim
Brooks, co-author of ``The Complete Directory To Prime Time Network
and Cable TV Shows.'' ``That's what 'The Godfather' did. The genre
was typed as something dark and gruesome, but 'The Godfather ' gave
us a whole new look at that world. Every time you turned over a
rock, you found something you didn't expect to see. 'The Sopranos '
has also reinvented that genre.''
</P>
<P>
   Jason Dalley, a West Palm Beach criminal defense attorney who
has defended some Soprano types, says he watches the show as often
as he can. He particularly likes how the writers have humanized
Tony and turned what could have been a one-dimensional character
into a complex one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most mob guys just come home to dinner to show their face,''
says Dalley. ``But for Tony, his home life is important. That makes
him more real. As long as you're not on his wrong side, he's a
pretty decent guy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Sopranos `` producers are definitely thrilled with the
accolades. ``Last year, when we were doing the show, we were
entertaining ourselves, and we just hoped that everyone would get
it,'' says Ilene S. Landress, one of the series' producers. ``You
see a couple of good reviews and you get excited, but never in your
wildest dreams can you imagine getting this sort of attention
across the board. Then you say, `Oh my God, it'll probably never be
this good again.' ``
</P>
<P>
   But could ``The Sopranos `` be this good on network television?
Probably not. Certainly not in its current form (nudity,
four-letter words, whackings). Ironically, Fox had first dibs on
``The Sopranos,'' but passed. Despite all the hype, only a paltry
2.8 million viewers watched ``The Sopranos `` each week during its
initial run last January. While that number was good enough to make
``The Sopranos `` one of the most watched shows on cable
television, the same amount of viewers watched the awful ``Clueless
`` each week on network TV. And ``Clueless `` ranked a dismal No.
147 out of 178 shows.
</P>
<P>
   So, what next for the Mafia's First Family? How do you top last
season?
</P>
<P>
   The answer: You don't.
</P>
<P>
   Landress says there won't be many changes. You will see two new
regular cast members, however. Aida Turturro (''Deep Blue Sea'')
joins the cast as Tony's scheming sister (a chip off the 'ol mom,
that one) and David Proval (''The Shawshank Redemption'') is Richie
Aprile, the quick-fisted brother of deceased mob boss Jackie
Aprile. Film director Peter Bogdanovich will also have a recurring
role as Dr. Melfi's (Lorraine Bracco) shrink. Tony and his cronies
will also take a business trip to Sicily later this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very important for us not to change too much,'' says
Landress. ``Whatever we were doing right, and we're not sure what
that was, we just wanted to keep doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Let the second season begin.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin J. Thompson writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
