<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Titans notebook: Big hitter Bishop has best game
 &HT;    By Karen Rosen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nashville _ At 5 feet 9, strong safety Blaine Bishop is the
shortest defensive starter on the Titans, but he posts some big
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop had a team-high seven tackles and broke up two passes
Sunday against the Colts in a 19-16 win. Before his hometown crowd
in Indianapolis, the former Pro Bowler had ``probably his best
career ballgame,'' said coach Jeff Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants to hit, he makes no bones about it,'' said Tennessee
running back Eddie George. ``No matter how big you are, he wants to
knock your head off. I'm glad he's on my team.''
</P>
<P>
   Said free safety Marcus Robertson, ``He is tough, man. He's the
iron man.''
</P>
<P>
   But he's not a miracle worker. Bishop could manage to acquire
only 31 tickets to Sunday's game, after getting requests for 70.
</P>
<P>
   Leg up
</P>
<P>
   The story goes that Al Del Greco was on his way to accept a
corporate job in Birmingham when he was offered the kicking job
with the Oilers. But he might have been ready for that suit and tie
the way his kicks were going the week before the Indianapolis game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wednesday and Thursday he was struggling and down on himself
because things weren't going right with his kicks, and he was
pulling a lot of balls,'' said punter/kickoff man Craig Hentrich,
who is the holder on placement attempts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was kind of mad,'' Del Greco said. ``It was like, `Man, I've
waited six years to get here and I'm going to kick like this?' It's
everybody's dream to get here, and once you get here you want to do
well.''
</P>
<P>
   And he did. The 16-year veteran out of Auburn was 4-for-4
Sunday, with field goals of 49, 37, 25 and 43 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Del Greco said he corrected the problem when the Titans moved
into the indoor facility.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always liked kicking in domes,'' he said. ``Atlanta is a
dome, isn't it?''
</P>
<P>
   Valuable piece of paper
</P>
<P>
   Former Georgia Tech offensive lineman Craig Page moved from the
practice squad to the 53-man roster when tight end Mike Roan was
placed on injured reserve. Roan had surgery Tuesday for a herniated
disc in his neck.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't expecting it at all,'' said Page. ``I feel like it's
a good reward. I worked hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Page was inactive at Indianapolis, but he made the trip and
visited with Colts practice squad linebacker Nate Simpson, his
college roommate at Tech.
</P>
<P>
   Stay away from the airport
</P>
<P>
   Win or lose, the Titans have arranged a homecoming party Sunday
at Adelphia Coliseum in an attempt to avoid the mob scene that
occurred at the airport after the Indianapolis game.
</P>
<P>
   The team will be routed directly from its charter flight onto
buses without going through the terminal.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, as many as 10,000 people crammed the airport. One
woman fell from an escalator, which airport officials say had
stopped and then restarted at an accelerated pace. She was treated
at a hospital and released. Two children were also slightly
injured.
</P>
<P>
   The party will start at 3:30 p.m., and the NFC championship game
will be shown on a large screen.
</P>
<P>
   Horror show
</P>
<P>
   While watching Jacksonville hammer Miami 62-7 in the other AFC
divisional playoff, running back George had sympathy for the
Dolphins, but wouldn't have wanted to be in their shoes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw them stacking on the points,'' he said, ``and I was
like, `It's a long day for Miami. I'm glad that we're not down
there right now.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Karen Rosen writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
