<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EGYPTIAN-ART-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FINAL RESTING PLACE FOR ANCIENT RELICS (IN BOSTON)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 23) 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 Paula Deitz is the editor of The Hudson Review.  
 By PAULA DEITZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Museum galleries were not the destination the Egyptians
had in mind when they made elaborate preparations to send deceased
royalty on the journey to the afterlife.
</P>
<P>
   While exhibitions of Egyptian art, like the well-traveled
``Treasures of Tutankhamen'' in the 1970s, usually emphasized the
excavation and discovery of artifacts in ancient tombs, the museums
that presented such objects were faced with the question of how to
display them. Most opted for an atmosphere that was tantamount to
reburial: dark, mysterious, tomblike spaces.
</P>
<P>
   In installing the Museum of Fine Arts' permanent galleries for
Egyptian funerary arts and the art of the ancient Middle East, the
architects Jung/Brannen Associates of Boston followed this approach
but with a difference. Instead of the dense spaces typical of such
galleries, they have created rows of transparent columns filled
with light that serve as exhibition cases.
</P>
<P>
   In the vastness of the darkened gallery, these illuminated cases
are like windows on the objects beyond. Seven hundred objects are
on view.
</P>
<P>
   While other collections in the museum were acquired by donation
or purchase, the Egyptian section, consisting of 40,000 objects,
has maintained its direct link to archaeological sites. In 1872,
two years after the museum was founded, it purchased 4,000 objects
from a Boston collector that formed the core of its Egyptian
collection.
</P>
<P>
   In 1905, the museum joined Harvard University in sponsoring an
archaeological expedition in Giza that yielded treasures for 40
years. Dr. Rita E. Freed, curator of Ancient Egyptian, Nubian and
Near Eastern Art at the museum, has led many archaeological digs,
and the department has compiled 200 volumes of field notebooks and
60,000 glass negatives.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for Jung/Brannen, Joseph Mamayek, its director of
architectural design, had lived in Turkey and had spent three weeks
in Egypt on a traveling fellowship in 1989 studying and sketching
the columns at Karnak and the hieroglyphics in the Valley of the
Kings. It was the experience of visiting tombs that suggested to
him that he could use stony gray walls in the new galleries to
convey the shadowy appearance of tombs reflecting the glare of
torchlight.
</P>
<P>
   A statue of Osiris, god of the nether world, stands at the new
Egyptian gallery's entrance as the gatekeeper of the tomblike
setting. Within the gallery, there are 13 mummies. In addition to
three coffins for a Theban aristocrat that fit into one another _
the middle one elaborately painted with a face and wig _ there are
mummy cases for both a barber, Nes-Ptah, and his wife, that have
found their eternal resting place in the museum.
</P>
<P>
   At the far end of the gallery, the eight-foot-high stone
sarcophagus for General Kheper-Re has been placed in a standing
position, rather than supine as is customary.
</P>
<P>
   In the darkness, small objects glow in the wall cases _ funerary
jewelry like gold fingernail covers and a gold pectoral in the
shape of a vulture with outstretched wings inlaid with some 400
pieces of carnelian and glass.
</P>
<P>
   One attraction of Egyptian funerary art is that it also
documents the lives of ordinary people. In the hieroglyphics and
wall reliefs, stories are told: on one limestone relief, a royal
butler and his wife make offerings to a god in his shrine.
</P>
<P>
   To enter the adjoining gallery devoted to artifacts from the
Middle East, the visitor passes through an archway decorated with
rosettes that suggests a re-creation of the Great Ishtar Gate
(Ishtar was the goddess of love and war) from the Babylon of
Nebuchadnezzar II (604-561 B.C.). Although it lacks the grandeur of
the reconstruction of the original gate at the Pergamon Museum in
Berlin, it establishes another atmosphere, that of an ancient
courtyard in Mesopotamia at dusk with the last gleam of light
glowing behind the crenelated walls.
</P>
<P>
   And just as the processional path to the original gate is lined
with tile reliefs of striding lions, the lion on view here, in
turquoise, cream and yellow glazed brick, is enough to evoke the
presence of the others.
</P>
<P>
   From alabaster wall reliefs of winged deities from Assyrian
palaces, to coins from Iran, to animal-shaped bronze bridle
ornaments from Turkey, the objects are arranged chronologically
rather than by region, giving an indication of the flow of
influences. No other statue exudes the power of the dark green
diorite carved head of Gudea, ruler of Lagash; and a stone vessel
in the form of a hare, circa 6400-5900 B.C., is the oldest artifact
in the museum.
</P>
<P>
   When the architects discovered that there was too little wall
space for a map of the region that would show an area 6,000 miles
in circumference, spanning 6,000 years, Mamayek turned necessity
into a virtue. Using slates of different colors _ ocher for land
and gray for water, like the Nile, the Tigris and the Euphrates
Rivers _ he created a map that takes up the entire center of the
gallery floor. It has been a favorite spot for children to sit when
they are not wandering among the mummy cases.
</P>
<P>
   Mamayek sees it as a kind of metaphor for the desert, as if, he
said, ``one drew a map in the sand with a stick.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
