<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-18 21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9571 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-SAPP-HNS &LR;      01-18 1033
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SAPP-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TERRY BLOUNT  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
Tampa Bay defensive tackle Warren Sapp sat in his living room
Sunday afternoon watching the St. Louis Rams put points on the
scoreboard like a pinball machine stuck in extra-play mode.
<TEXT>
<P>
   When it was over, the St. Louis offense had reached the end zone
six times _ five by air and once on the ground _ in a 49-37 victory
over Minnesota. But Sapp was unimpressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, they haven't put them up against us, and that's all that
matters,'' Sapp said. ``What matters is we're 60 minutes away from
the greatest show on earth. We're not done yet.''
</P>
<P>
   To reach that show _ Super Bowl XXXIV in Atlanta _ the
Buccaneers will have to prove on Sunday at the Trans World Dome in
St. Louis that they can stop the most potent offense in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   The NFC Championship Game will be the ultimate test for the
NFC's top defense. The Bucs were up to the challenge against
Washington, keeping the No. 2 offense in the league out of the end
zone in a 14-13 win at Tampa Bay on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   But few people believe 14 points will be enough to defeat the
Rams, who have averaged 34 points per game this season. A Tampa Bay
victory probably will require another superb effort by the defense,
including the big guy in the middle of the line _ the 6-2,
303-pound Sapp.
</P>
<P>
   Last week Sapp became the first Tampa player to win the
Associated Press Defensive Player of the Year award since Hall of
Fame defensive end Lee Roy Selmon in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just to be mentioned in the same breath with Lee Roy Selmon
means I'm doing my job,'' Sapp said. ``For a long time, he set the
standard around here on how to play defense. Maybe the torch has
passed. I want to keep up the tradition he started of great defense
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Sapp, 27, ended the regular season with 12{ sacks, just shy of
Selmon's team record of 13 set in 1979. But Selmon got his sacks as
a defensive end in a 3-4 alignment. Sapp is a defensive tackle in a
4-3, a much tougher role in which to produce sacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very proud of Warren for what he did to get better after
last season,'' said Tampa Bay coach Tony Dungy. ``He set his mind
to doing everything he could to be the best he could be.''
</P>
<P>
   Sapp had seven sacks last season, when the Bucs were 8-8. Tampa
Bay is 12-5 this season thanks in part to the improved play of
Sapp, who is 20 pounds lighter than his 1998 playing weight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last season I was too fat and too slow,'' Sapp said. ``I was
out of shape, and I wasn't close to being able to make plays.
Sometimes late in games I would line up knowing I couldn't make a
play. But this year I've been able to chase people down for four
quarters. I'm giving the fans their money's worth.''
</P>
<P>
   Sapp has given the Bucs everything they could have hoped for
since they took a chance and made him a first-round draft choice
with the 12th overall pick in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   He was a Lombardi Award winner his junior year at Miami and was
expected to be the first player picked in the draft, but a positive
drug test caused 11 teams to choose someone else in the first
round.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing that really hurt me was the talk about
cocaine,'' Sapp said. ``It wasn't true. I dabbled with marijuana,
like a lot of guys in college do. I admitted it. I told the
truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Sapp remembers every player who was chosen ahead of him, and he
quickly points out that only one _ Jacksonville offensive tackle
Tony Boselli _ has equaled his level of performance.
</P>
<P>
   Sapp admits he still has bitter feelings about what happened on
draft day, but he also thinks it may have made him a better player
because he wanted to prove the other 11 teams were wrong by not
selecting him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always in the back of my mind,'' Sapp said. ``I tote it
with me, no doubt about it.''
</P>
<P>
   It serves as added motivation for a man who has the possibility
of a Super Bowl ring to motivate him now. Sapp was instrumental in
Tampa Bay's win Saturday, coming up with a key sack and later
getting a fumble recovery that set up the winning TD drive for the
Bucs.
</P>
<P>
   Both Tampa Bay touchdown drives came after the defense caused
turnovers, but that's nothing new. In the last three games, the
defense has forced eight turnovers that became scoring drives for
the Tampa Bay offense.
</P>
<P>
   The two TDs against the Redskins came after Tampa Bay got behind
13-0 and Sapp gave a pep talk to the defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `We need to turn this into a war, an absolute war.' We
loaded our guns,'' Sapp said. ``We were in the huddle saying we
hadn't made a play yet to get the offense rolling. We know this
team is built around us making plays, so somebody had to step up.''
</P>
<P>
   Safety John Lynch came up with an interception that started the
turnaround before a sack by defensive end Steve White caused a
fumble that Sapp recovered.
</P>
<P>
   It will take more of the same if the Bucs hope to slow the
explosive St. Louis offense, led by quarterback Kurt Warner, the
league's Most Valuable Player this season.
</P>
<P>
   Sapp believes the Tampa Bay defense is up to the task and has
the talent to counter the Rams' top offensive stars _ Warner,
running back Marshall Faulk and receiver Isaac Bruce.
</P>
<P>
   Along with Sapp, the Bucs will send linebacker Derrick Brooks
and Lynch to the Pro Bowl. The defensive line of Sapp, White, Brad
Culpepper and Chidi Ahanotu may be the best in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just a representative of the unit,'' Sapp said. ``That's
the way I've always looked at it. There are a lot of great players
on this defense, and great players have to do great things that
change the outcome of games.''
</P>
<P>
   Sapp and his defensive teammates have changed the outcome of a
lot of games this season. Eight times the Bucs allowed 10 points or
fewer.
</P>
<P>
   Only twice this season has a team scored three touchdowns
against Tampa Bay. St. Louis has done that in all 17 games, so
everyone is going to see if a great defense can stop a great
offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll take my chances with our defense anytime,'' Sapp said.
``And our offense gets it done every time we give them a chance. I
don't know if we're a team of destiny, but I know we're a team of
heart and desire.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
