<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY JUST HOPES TO DO WELL IN IOWA CAUCUSES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ALAN BERNSTEIN 
and PATTY REINERT 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IOWA CITY, Iowa _ In the span of a few minutes Tuesday, Bill
Bradley preached idealism about government and realism about his
chances of winning the Iowa caucuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't say anything about winning in Iowa,'' Bradley said at
a news conference in a music room at West High School.
</P>
<P>
   He was responding to a question about his campaign staff having
talked wistfully once about Bradley upsetting Vice President Al
Gore in the Jan. 24 Democratic presidential caucuses.
</P>
<P>
   With polls showing Gore holding onto a lead of about 20
percentage points in voter surveys, Bradley said he merely hopes to
do as well as Sen. Ted Kennedy did against President Jimmy Carter
in 1980. Kennedy garnered 31 percent of the caucus vote in an
unsuccessful campaign to wrest the Democratic nomination from the
incumbent.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a difficult state when you are up against entrenched
power,'' Bradley said. ``We don't have the apparatus. The apparatus
is with the vice president. But we do have a lot of enthusiasm
among people and the real question is can we reach out to enough to
get them to the caucuses, and that remains to be seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's lead comes partly thanks to support from labor unions and
Iowa elected officials such as Sen. Tom Harkin. Organization is
important in the caucuses because to cast a vote, residents must
participate in a lengthy evening meeting rather than just punch a
ballot in the voting booth. The better-organized candidates turn
out more participants.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said his goal all along has been to ``do better than
expected in Iowa.'' His campaign is hoping for a lift a week later
in New Hampshire, where most polls show him leading Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, for his part, appeared confident and relaxed Tuesday,
joking with college students in Indianola and picking up a labor
endorsement in Knoxville.
</P>
<P>
   And he turned his attention, briefly, to Republican candidate
George W. Bush, telling about 40 members of the American Federation
of Government Employees that Bush has ``waged war'' on organized
labor in Texas and ``wants to raid government pension plans'' to
finance a tax plan intended to help the wealthy.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and other Republican candidates, he said, would risk the
strong economy nurtured during the Clinton-Gore administration by
clinging to old ideas of the Reagan and Bush years, recommending
tax cuts and spending plans that amount to ``the hair of the dog
that bit us.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to AFGE union members packed in the local VFW Hall,
Gore didn't mention Bradleye, but said the presidency isn't
just about big ideas or concentrating on a few select projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an all-out commitment day-by-day, fighting for real
people with real problems,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's news conference came on the heels of his address to an
assembly in the high school auditorium. There, his message was the
opposite: Don't settle for second best.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley repeated his theme that he is the bold candidate in the
race _ with his proposals on health care, gun control and campaign
finance reform _ while Gore is only ``nibbling around the edges''
of those issues.
</P>
<P>
   In near-spiritual tones, Bradley said he wants to be president
to achieve ``a world of new possibilities guided by goodness'' and
that his campaign ``is about asking good people to step forward so
that all of our voices could he heard.''
</P>
<P>
   The students sat in a silence that could most charitably be
described as respectful, not breaking into applause until Bradley
answered a question from the audience by saying South Carolina
should stop flying the Confederate flag over state buildings
because ``slavery was our original sin, just as race remains our
unsolved dilemma.''
</P>
<P>
   To reporters later, Bradley said Texas' new university
enrollment program, which guarantees admission to high school
seniors who rank in the top 10 percent of their class academically,
doesn't give universities the flexibility they need to attract
minorities.
</P>
<P>
   In the best high schools, he said, those just below the
threshold might be left behind even though they might be more
qualified than students at other schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think (the Texas rules) are as good as your straight
affirmative action,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
