<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: ANTI-PUNISHMENT LAW
</P>
<P>
   Parents who smack their children on the head or beat them
anywhere on their bodies with objects like canes or belts could
face jail under a new law being formulated by the government.
Britain has to bring its laws into compliance with decisions
outlawing corporal punishment by the European Court of Human Rights
despite polls showing that most British parents are against the
changes.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: PINOCHET RULING DUE
</P>
<P>
   Britain told Chile it was free to send a plane to pick up Gen.
Augusto Pinochet, but it withheld a decision on whether or not to
free him until later in the week. Home Secretary Jack Straw said he
needed the coming days to consider petitions from rights groups and
countries like Spain, France, Belgium and Switzerland that have
called for the former Chilean dictator's extradition. Opponents of
his imminent release want the right to see medical reports on which
Straw, above, based his decision that General Pinochet, 84, was
unfit to stand trial.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: DIANA WALKWAY
</P>
<P>
   The government will build a seven-mile walkway in London through
St. James' Park, Green Park, Hyde Park and Kensington Gardens to
commemorate the life of Diana, Princess of Wales. The $2.8 million
project, to open in July, will include 70 plaques marking moments
in her life and places associated with her.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE: COVERING STORM DAMAGE
</P>
<P>
   Paris has decided to sell off some of its assets to pay for the
more than $70 million worth of damage the city suffered in two
storms that hit at Christmas. Mayor Jean Tiberi said Paris would
sell city-owned land and two hotels as well as its stake in a power
company. ``We are doing this so that it does not cost Parisians one
additional franc in taxes,'' Tiberi said.
</P>
<P>
   SPAIN: BASQUE ATTACK PREDICTED
</P>
<P>
   Interior Minister Jaime Mayor Oreja said the Basque separatist
group ETA would attempt a terrorist attack before the March 12
general elections to try to take revenge on the center-right
government, which is leading in the polls. The rebels halted their
14-month unilateral cease-fire last November, and the police have
since arrested several suspected rebels and seized explosives.
</P>
<P>
   HONG KONG: CHANGE OF NAME
</P>
<P>
   The New China News Agency, a state-run body, has been Beijing's
de facto consulate in Hong Kong since 1947. Now, two years after
Hong Kong reverted to China, the Hong Kong branch is changing its
name to more accurately reflect its role. The agency will be called
the Liaison Office of the Central People's Government in the Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   IVORY COAST: U.N. ENVOY
</P>
<P>
   Secretary-General Kofi Annan has sent a special envoy, Ibrahima
Fall, to Ivory Coast to encourage the new military rulers to return
to constitutional rule, Annan's spokesman, Fred Eckhard, said.
Ivory Coast's leader, Gen. Robert Guei, seized power last month.
</P>
</TEXT>
