<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-18 21:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9579 &Cx1f; tth-z
r a BC-BRADLEY-INTERVIEW-SPI     01-18 1226
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-INTERVIEW-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONFIDENT BRADLEY STICKS WITH HIS THEMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WATERLOO, Iowa _ As his campaign bus headed down U.S. 63, Bill
Bradley talked about the succession of debates that have pitted him
against his Democratic presidential rival, Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``The debates remind me of a joke that Woody Allen once told
about when he learned speed reading,'' Bradley said. ``He went out
and read Tolstoy's `War and Peace.' Later asked to describe the
novel, Allen said what he remembered was that it was about
Russia.''
</P>
<P>
   What Bradley hopes voters will remember is that the debates were
about issues. For many Iowa and New Hampshire voters, debates
provide the main snapshot of the candidates vying for the
Democratic nomination to succeed Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Gore comes armed with sound bites and statistics, plants human
props in the audience and rips apart Bradley's health care plan.
Bradley is sticking to his themes with a deep _ perhaps misplaced _
confidence that America is ready for campaign finance reform,
registration of handguns and bold action to get its children out of
poverty.
</P>
<P>
   In a lengthy interview, the onetime New York Knicks forward gave
the sense of somebody not inclined to retool himself, confident of
his game and believing the country is ready for his agenda.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I am suggesting is common sense,'' he said. ``What we
have to do is take this moment, and deal with issues while
prosperity gives us the chance. ... People know our health care
system is in distress. They know premiums are going up. ... They
know what gun violence has done in our schools. They know, given
the fund-raising scandals in 1996, that money is distorting the
political process.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley wants to change that process through campaign finance
reform, but pledges to go farther and retool what has become a
media-driven presidency.
</P>
<P>
   The current model was established by Ronald Reagan. During
Reagan's presidency, aides met daily to design a presidential
appearance or announcement that would win the day's ``bit'' _
getting TV coverage and driving the day's news cycle.
</P>
<P>
   The pace has, if anything, been accelerated by the daily stream
of statements out of Clinton's White House. It was Clinton, for
example, who personally announced plans to extend federal
protection to slopes above the Columbia River in eastern
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``As president, I would strive to be on television _ less,''
Bradley said. ``I would delegate a lot of authority so that my
subordinates would get a lot of airtime. As president, you
shouldn't dominate everything. For example, the secretary of the
Interior should take the lead in making statements on taking down
dams from the Elwha River'' on Washington state's Olympic
Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know from the 1930s, that Franklin Roosevelt's voice counted
for more because he was not speaking every day. When he did address
the nation, people knew it was important and were anxious to hear
what he had to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Several of Bradley's proposals _ notably handgun registration
and public financing of federal campaigns _ have been dismissed as
impossible to achieve in the charged, bitterly partisan atmosphere
of today's Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's what people in Washington, D.C., always say,'' Bradley
observed. ``They can't see change if its stimulus comes from
outside Washington, D.C. It's not that way in Washington state.
Look at your economy. Only in Washington, D.C., are limits put on
the imagination that are rigid.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley sees Gore as a product of those limits and a politician
disinclined to tangle for keeps with the capital's entrenched
interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is more cautious. In this campaign he has taken a more
cautious approach,'' Bradley said. ``He demonstrates time and again
his inclination to do the safe thing rather than exercise the
leadership that transforms.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley reflects that he has been ``on the road'' across America
for 30 years as a basketball player, and later as a politician, and
as a teacher and businessman after 18 years representing New Jersey
in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a goodness in most of us,'' he reflected. ``Of course,
there has always been a nativist sentiment in America. I find that
a small, vocal segment of America. ... But, on the whole, people
are generous, tolerant, and open. They are aware of (public
figures') strengths and will tolerate the flaws and weaknesses as
long as we say what we believe.''
</P>
<P>
   Just a year ago, Bradley was visiting Seattle on the day that
his presidential committee officially came into existence.
Typically, he made no formal announcement and held no news
conference.
</P>
<P>
   At one meeting, a luncheon at the Seattle Hilton, Bradley
acknowledged that he would lose to Gore if the nomination race were
decided by the Democratic Party's current members and financial
supporters.
</P>
<P>
   What he had to do, Bradley argued, was attract new donors and
reignite enthusiasm for politics among Americans grown cynical
about the money games of Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   He has succeed to an extent that nobody would have believed a
year ago. The Bradley campaign in Iowa is built on such voters as
Jim Mahoney, a teacher at Johnston High School north of Des Moines.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people, including myself, have been sitting back and
not taking an active role in politics,'' Mahoney said. ``He has
drawn me back in. We need better values in our government.''
</P>
<P>
   Retired nursery school teracher Jo Leffler will move slowly with
her walker to next Monday's caucus. ``I just can't believe he is
not who he says he is, and he is so much what the country needs,''
Leffler said after hearing Bradley speak.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has, however, a deep reservoir of support among committed,
active Democrats who see him as a man who has done the Clinton
administration's heavy lifting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not dislike for Bradley _ I'm glad he's running _ but I
look at what the vice president has done and feel he's ready for
the job. I'm rather traditional,'' said Nick Eakins, concierge at
the Hotel Pattee in Perry.
</P>
<P>
   Activists like Eakins have given the vice president a
substantial lead in pre-caucus polls. With heavy backing from
labor, Gore also has the organizational muscle to turn out his
troops.
</P>
<P>
   How strong of a second-place showing must Bradley achieve to win
the expectations game in Iowa? The only remote parallel among
Democrats was 1980, when Sen. Edward Kennedy challenged President
Jimmy Carter. Carter won 59 percent to Kennedy's 31 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Hart took only 16 percent in 1984, trailing far behind
former Vice President Walter Mondale's 49 percent. But Hart's
second place showing was considered a breakthrough, and propelled
him toward an upset of Mondale in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   ``The proof will be in what the electorate says. ... Have we
reached people with the right sense of urgency?'' Bradley asked.
</P>
<P>
   He's not likely to go away, even if Gore wins big on Monday.
Writing in his book, ``Time Present, Time Past,'' Bradley mused on
his Scotch-Irish ancestry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being Scotch Irish is to recognize that once or twice or
several times in your life, defeat will seem certain,'' he wrote,
``but never to give up when faced with this moment, instead to
persevere, to advance ... .''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-18-00 2108EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000118.0332 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-18 21:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9580 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CONSULTANTS-EQUITY-AR     01-18 0609
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSULTANTS-EQUITY-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: two years.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the trend seems unstoppable, it also raises thorny
conflict-of-interest issues that will not go away, either.
Accountants and lawyers, after all, are generally barred by law
from being part owners of clients. For years, the big consulting
firms generally followed suit. They have also built fire walls of
silence around projects, forbidding consultants to talk with
colleagues about them. This confidentiality enabled them to work
for rival companies simultaneously. Andersen, for example,
currently does work for Federal Express, the U.S. Postal Service
and United Parcel Service.
</P>
<P>
   But when the consultants own a part of a client, rivals could
become more reluctant to trust those fire walls. The consulting
firms, in turn, may then have to make clearer decisions about which
companies they work with.
</P>
<P>
   The increased acceptance of equity stakes ``will put pressure on
consultants to pick their spots a little bit more carefully,'' said
James Citrin, a former McKinsey consultant who is now the managing
director of the Internet practice at Spencer Stuart, a large
executive search firm.
</P>
<P>
   Acknowledging those concerns, many firms, including McKinsey,
say they plan to sell the investments within a few years, to avoid
becoming too closely aligned with a client. ``In no case do we ever
want to become a long-term stakeholder,'' said Andreas Biagosch, a
director in McKinsey's Munich office.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, skeptics say such close links between advisers and
clients create many potential problems. In the 1980s, for example,
Bain, which once refused to work for two firms in the same industry
and would send dozens of consultants into a single company,
suffered a major hit to its reputation when consultants who had
taken on formal titles at Guinness were implicated in a British
stock scandal.
</P>
<P>
   The new arrangements will make similar situations more likely,
said Lewis Pinault, a former partner at Coopers &AMP; Lybrand who also
worked at Boston Consulting and Gemini Consulting. They will also
give clients new reason to doubt the fire walls, which he said
often come down after a project has ended. ``The history of fire
walls before this e-commerce boom is not really a healthy one,''
said Pinault, the author of ``Consulting Demons,'' a critical look
at the industry, which is soon to be published by HarperBusiness.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is particularly sensitive at the consulting units of
the large accounting firms. The Securities and Exchange Commission
bars those firms from investing in companies they audit or in
companies whose other part owners they audit. Scrutiny is likely to
be high. This month, the SEC released a report saying that more
than 50 percent of Pricewaterhouse's partners had violated rules
prohibiting them from holding personal investments in companies the
firm audits. A federal agency is now investigating whether the
problem is widespread at other firms, as well.
</P>
<P>
   Consulting executives said many of the questions about conflicts
of interest are not new. ``Clients have always lived with us
dealing with their competitors,'' said Scott Hartz, the top
consulting executive at Pricewaterhouse.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid new problems, consultants said they would choose their
investments carefully and establish clear rules within their firms.
``We will try never to invest in or have in our portfolio companies
that compete with one another,'' Wilson of Andersen said. But, he
acknowledged, ``that's very, very hard to do; it's inevitable that
there will be collisions down the road.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll solve that problem when we get there,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-18-00 2108EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000118.0333 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-18 21:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9581 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-NFC-RAMS-COX     01-18 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFC-RAMS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Vermeil likes 'clockwork' kicker Lowery
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ On Jan. 30, 1994, Nick Lowery was exactly where he
wanted to be. In the Georgia Dome, Super Bowl XXVIII, Cowboys and
Bills. One problem: Lowery had the worst seat in the house: A seat.
</P>
<P>
   ''I remember going to the game,'' said Lowery, the No. 5 scorer
in NFL history, ''and I had a migraine headache the whole game
because I wanted to be on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   That hope evaporated a week earlier, when Lowery and the Chiefs
lost the AFC Championship Game in Buffalo. Six years later, at age
43 and three years since he last kicked in an NFL game, Lowery
might finally reach the Super Bowl, in the most unlikely manner.
</P>
<P>
   ''I thought I did OK for an old man,'' Lowery said. He was one
of three kickers the Rams brought in Tuesday morning to try out if
regular placekicker Jeff Wilkins can't kick in Sunday's NFC
Championship Game against Tampa Bay. Wilkins reaggravated the
patella tendinitis in his left knee in the divisional playoff win
over Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   If Wilkins can't kick, head coach Dick Vermeil will choose
Lowery over two 25-year-olds: ex-FSU star Scott Bentley, who kicked
off in two games this season for the Chiefs, and Marshall Young,
who kicked at UTEP and has tried out for a couple of NFL teams.
Although Vermeil hopes Wilkins can kick and won't make a decision
until Thursday, he will go with Lowery if needed.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our preference is to stay with our guy, if we can,'' the coach
sai Wilkins reinjured himself on the opening kickoff, his first of
eight against Minnesota; missed his only field-goal attempt, a
42-yarder; and had an MRI on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was way off, compensating for his sore leg,'' Vermeil said.
``If he's going to kick like that, he can't kick for us. But if he
can kick a field goal and ignore the pain, he'll be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   If not, Vermeil will use Lowery as a replacement kicker in the
biggest game in St. Louis football history. He would earn a playoff
share only, with no salary to count toward the 1999 cap.
</P>
<P>
   ''I thought my performance was really good,'' said Bentley, who
showed the strongest leg during a 30-minute workout. He made all of
his field goals, including a 52-yarder. ''My kickoffs were
obviously the strongest of the three. That's the good thing about
being young.''
</P>
<P>
   But Vermeil wants experience, and youth and conditioning are
less important for a game or two. ''I would always be comfortable
with Nick Lowery,'' said Vermeil, who worked as an analyst on
television while he was out of coaching. ''I always thought he was
the best, most accurate. The numbers I kept on him were equivalent
to the best ever. I had a lot of confidence in him.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's clockwork, that guy. Whether he can do it now, I don't
know.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I hope to get a chance to find out,'' Lowery said. ''I have
not kicked a whole lot.''
</P>
<P>
   It showed Tuesday. Lowery, who has been working as a TV
sportscaster, has kicked once in the last several months, on Dec.
19. He hasn't kicked with a holder in a year and a half. That was
in June 1998, when Lowery had a tryout with the Rams and impressed
Vermeil but wasn't signed.
</P>
<P>
   So Lowery was surprised _ ''You bet'' _ when Vermeil called
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Lowery said his knees feel better than they have in years. ''I
don't think I have the cumulative fatigue of a year of kicking. I
just have to get into a rhythm,'' he said. He would love to be
reunited with the Rams special-teams coach, Frank Gansz, for whom
Lowery played in Kansas City, and work with a good holder, Mike
Horan. ''I hope the only thing that matters is, 'Who's the best guy
for the job?' '' Lowery said. ''It's a great team here. The car's
already running, and I've just got to do my part if I get a
chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack Wilkinson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
