</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-RAMS-NOTES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RAMS NOTEBOOK: Bucs not only `D,' Bush says
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ And you thought it's St. Louis' offense vs. Tampa
Bay's defense for the NFC championship? Think again. In the court
of public opinion, Devin Bush comes to the Rams' defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we play other teams,'' Bush said, ``all you hear about is
the other team's defense.''
</P>
<P>
   As in, how in the world is the other team's defense going to
stop St. Louis' out-of-this-world attack? This is understandable
considering the Star Wars weaponry _ Kurt Warner, Marshall Faulk,
Isaac Bruce. Bush understands that.
</P>
<P>
   But the ex-Falcon _ reduced to a nickel back in his fourth
season last year in Atlanta before signing a four-year, $7.2
million free-agent contract with St. Louis _ complains, ``The only
thing we get sick of is we get ignored. All you hear about is
everybody else's defense but ours. We feed off that. We don't let
that get us down. If opponents take us lightly, we try to come up
with the knockout blow.''
</P>
<P>
   It's no different this week. It's the Bucs' defense _ No. 1 in
the NFC, hasn't allowed a touchdown in 10 quarters _ against the
Rams' pinball machine.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, starting at free safety in place of the injured Keith
Lyle, counters, ``We're No. 1 in the NFL against the rush (74.3
yards a game). We're No. 1 in scoring defense (eight touchdowns).
What does that say about our defense?
</P>
<P>
   ``We run just as fast (as Tampa Bay),'' said Bush. ``Play just
as hard as they do. We're in the same category as they are.''
</P>
<P>
   Slicing prices
</P>
<P>
   In a city known for its Italian food, the most popular place to
eat Monday was . . . Domino's Pizza.
</P>
<P>
   Yes. Thousands of Rams fans took advantage of the ``Rams
Touchdown Takedown'' promotion at local Domino's stores in the wake
of last Sunday's 49-37 win over Minnesota. The pitch: A dollar off
pizza prices on Mondays for every Rams touchdown the day before.
After seven TDs against Minnesota, a $7.99 medium cheese pizza cost
99 cents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting slammed,'' Greg Neichter, who owns 32 of the 79
local Domino's outlets and concocted the promotion, told the St.
Louis Post-Dispatch. Neichter predicted a loss of $1 million
Monday, ``But we have no regrets. This is our way of doing
something nice for the St. Louis fans.''
</P>
<P>
   Several Domino's had to close briefly because of the crush.
Steve Hively, who owns one Domino's, said he baked 200 pizzas by 2
p.m. Monday _ 160 more than usual.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing is that they won,'' said Hively.
``But after five touchdowns, I was praying for field goals.''
</P>
<P>
   And for dessert . . .
</P>
<P>
   And how did Warner, the only undrafted player to become the NFL
MVP and surely the most modest, celebrate after completing 27 of 33
passes for 391 yards and five touchdowns against Minnesota? He went
home, had a pizza with his family and watched a movie on the Disney
Channel while eating popcorn.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's par,'' coach Dick Vermeil said of his quarterback,
who'd spent Saturday baking a birthday cake for his daughter,
Jessica. ``He's not ready to celebrate. He knows he has more to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Vermeil was actually worried about Warner before the Vikings
game. ``I was scared because the last few days (of practice) he
didn't throw the ball real accurately.''
</P>
<P>
   Not Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``In pregame warmups, he was hummin' it,'' Vermeil said. ``I've
never been around anyone who can throw the ball as accurately as he
can.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack Wilkinson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
