</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-INTERNET-TAX-590&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
  
 McCAIN PROMISES NEVER TO TAX INTERNET COMMERCE  
(sw) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL and FRANK BRUNI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain of Arizona signed a pledge on Tuesday never to
tax commerce on the Internet and challenged Gov. George W. Bush of
Texas to make the same promise, as the two Republican rivals fought
over tax cuts two weeks before the nation's first primary in New
Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   Bush rebuffed his challenger, saying that he wanted to
``understand what the world looks like three to five years from
now.'' And he put his own emphasis on the tax debate by featuring
two residents in Pittsfield, N.H., whom he said would benefit more
under his plan for a $483 billion, five-year tax cut than under
McCain's proposal for a nearly $240 billion reduction.
</P>
<P>
   As he campaigned on Tuesday, Bush talked causticly about how
McCain put out a tax proposal last summer and then released a
revised and more complete plan last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a Washington mindset that says: I'll lay
something out and then, if it takes on a little water, I'll amend
it and keep amending it,'' Bush said in Concord, N.H.. ``At least
the way I do it is _ I think through all the ramifications.''
</P>
<P>
   The day of dueling news conferences showed both men using a
signature Republican issue as they fought for advantage in a tight
New Hampshire race that could either propel McCain's insurgent
campaign or seal Bush's status as his party's front-runner. Several
polls have shown McCain leading in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has long called for a ban on taxes on the Internet. But
he highlighted his stand on Tuesday by signing a poster-sized
blowup copy of an ``E-Freedom declaration'' at a breakfast of the
Greater Nashua Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   He called technology the engine of the nation's economic growth
and warned against harming ``this baby in its cradle.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I challenge all the candidates, including Governor Bush to
take the same pledge,'' McCain said, ``not for a moratorium, not
for two years, not for five years, but a permanent, a permanent ban
on Internet taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``E-Freedom declaration,'' which is being promoted by
Citizens for a Sound Economy, an antitax group that often helps
showcase Republican antitax efforts, commits signers to a permanent
ban on Internet access, sales or use taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Many governors oppose a ban for fear that as more and more
commerce goes online the shift could drain state coffers of sales
tax revenues. So the McCain campaign was trying to create a tricky
conflict for Bush, who counts many Republican governors as some of
his staunchest supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has said that he favors a moratorium on Internet taxes and
he said on Tuesday that he would consider extending the moratorium
to five years from three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to make sure I understand what the world looks like
three to five from now,'' he said, ``before I speak further.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain also said that ``nobody's predicted where this technology
is going correctly for the last few years so I'm not sure that
anything can predict it correctly.'' But he insisted that the
Internet would ``churn'' the economy and produce a growth in sales,
not just a shift from shopping in stores to shopping online.
</P>
<P>
   For a moment on his campaign bus, he seemed to hedge on his
pledge, saying that if there were an economic downturn, ``we may
have to look at anything.'' Then he got back on message, saying,
``but I certainly don't believe the Internet is the way to go.'' He
scoffed at the concerns of governors saying, ``Mind you all these
governors that don't want to do that are all running surpluses.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Bush's aides have been combing McCain's tax plan in search of
debating points, and the governor accused the senator of including
a hidden increase of $40 billion in his proposal because it would
end certain deductions that employers can now take on tax-exempt
benefits they give their workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't agree with leaving money in Washington, D.C.,'' Bush
said, ``and I darned sure don't agree with saying that you're going
to take $40 billion in employer-related benefits and have the
people pay tax on them. I think that's a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign repeated the themes in a new commercial that
starts on Wednesday in New Hampshire. While the commercial does not
mention McCain by name, it is Bush's first one focusing on his
leading rival's tax plan.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the McCain campaign called the advertisement a
negative attack.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said on Tuesday that the governor had repeatedly made
accusations about his tax plan ``that have proven to be false.'' He
said his plan would close loopholes that allow corporations to
write off such benefits as golf club and spa memberships and
parking and would not affect health and education benefits. His
aides said the deductions were worth about $4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, McCain repeatedly drew applause in Nashua, N.H.,
and at an armory in Rhode Island when he said that his smaller tax
cut would help the middle class while still allowing the government
to devote much of the federal surplus to shoring up Social
Security, Medicare and start retiring the $5.6 trillion national
debt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe from a philosophical standpoint as families and as a
nation that it is important for us when we go though bad times and
accumulate debts,'' he said, ``that in good times that we as
families and responsible citizens repay those debts.''
</P>
<P>
   He charged, ``Governor Bush's plan has not one penny for Social
Security, not one penny for Medicare and not one penny for paying
down the debt.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's swing into New Hampshire was his last before devoting his
attention to the Iowa caucuses on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   McCain also left the state, arriving in New York City on Tuesday
afternoon for three fund-raisers expected to collect about
$300,000. The first was at the Luncheon Club on Wall Street. The
two other receptions were being held by Edgar Bronfman Jr., the
chief executive of Seagram, and Michael Bloomberg, the media
executive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-18-00 2110EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000118.0337 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-18 21:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9587 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-COKE-STAHL-COX     01-18 0967
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-STAHL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stahl lands No. 2 job at Coke
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's official.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Stahl will become Coca-Cola's new president and chief
operating officer in April.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jack Stahl's dynamic leadership has been proven for more than
two decades,'' Douglas Daft, the company's current president, said
in a statement Tuesday after recommending Stahl for the post during
a board of directors meeting in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Stahl, the 46-year-old head of the company's operations in North
America and Latin America, will become Coca-Cola's 20th president
after the April 19 board meeting. That is when the board will elect
Daft to the top spot of chairman and chief executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're running an operation as broad-based as Coca-Cola,
two heads are better than one, if you have the right two heads,''
said Manny Goldman, global beverage analyst with Merrill Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this case, Daft and Stahl complement each other. Daft has
tremendous international experience operationally, and Stahl has
significant experience operationally in North America and
financially worldwide,'' Goldman said. ``In addition, Jack has very
strong relations with Wall Street.''
</P>
<P>
   A Daft-Stahl team will re-establish the No. 1 and No. 2
management structure that was missing during the first two years of
M. Douglas Ivester's tenure as chairman. Ivester did not name a
president when he left that post to become chairman following the
death of Roberto C. Goizueta in October 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Daft only became president last month after Ivester announced
that he would prematurely retire in April.
</P>
<P>
   Ivester was criticized by some analysts for not naming a
president, which they believe contributed to some of the problems
the company faced under his watch. Some analysts speculate that
those problems, combined with his refusal to name a No. 2 person,
led key board members to seek his resignation.
</P>
<P>
   For years, under the dynamic duo of Goizueta and former
President Donald Keough, the company was known for its stellar
management and financial performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was interesting that Daft referred to a partnership with
Stahl in his statement,'' said John Sicher, editor and publisher of
Beverage Digest. ``It begins to give us insight into what kind of
working relationship they will have and the management style at the
top of the company.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday the board also elected new executive vice presidents,
who will sit on a six-member management executive committee that
will set company policy and establish a strategic direction.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Daft and Stahl, members of the committee are
James Chestnut, head of Operations Support; Charles Frenette,
president of Greater Europe Group; Joseph Gladden, general counsel;
and Carl Ware, head of Global Public Affairs and Administration.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone on the executive committee, except Gladden, has gotten
a new job with the company over the past few months.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doug has a bright team in place to take the company forward,''
said board member Jimmy Williams. ``Jack is clearly an ideal
choice. Everybody is excited about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, Daft, bottlers and analysts all cited Stahl's 20 years
of experience at the company as a key attribute.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jack has flourished in two positions of tremendous importance
and responsibility,'' Daft said. ``First, as the company's youngest
chief financial officer at age 36 and recently as the president of
our key U.S. and Canada operations.''
</P>
<P>
   During Stahl's tenure running Coke in North America, which he
has been doing since 1994, the operation has contributed a greater
share of the company's profits. In 1993, before Stahl took over,
North America accounted for 22 percent of the profits. In 1998 it
grew to 27 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coke in the U.S. way outperformed Pepsi during Stahl's years
at the helm,'' said Sicher, of Beverage Digest. ``From 1995 to
1998, Coke's market share increased 2.2 points, while Pepsi's
increased a half a point.''
</P>
<P>
   Stahl, who is known as having good interpersonal skills, is
popular with bottlers.
</P>
<P>
   ``By and large, the bottlers like him,'' said Bob Lovell, vice
president of marketing for Birmingham-based Coca-Cola Bottling
Company United, the system's fourth-largest U.S. bottler. ``He's
very candid, and he listens well. He follows up on what he says
he'll do.''
</P>
<P>
   Lovell and others describe Stahl as bright and articulate, with
a good sense of humor.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Boston, Stahl holds a bachelor's degree in economics
from Emory University and a master's degree from the University of
Pennsylvania's Wharton School of Business.
</P>
<P>
   He spent two years with the Arthur Andersen accounting firm
before joining Coke in 1979 as an investor relations specialist. A
year later he became manager of investor relations and pension
investments. In 1981 he was named executive assistant to the chief
financial officer.
</P>
<P>
   From there it was a slow but steady rise up the corporate
ladder.
</P>
<P>
   In 1985 he was promoted to manager of planning and business
development. Three years later he was elected vice president and
controller. In 1989 he became chief financial officer. Five years
later he became head of the company's North America operations.
</P>
<P>
   Less than three months ago he was given the added responsibility
for Latin America, as well as for the company's Minute Maid
operation.
</P>
<P>
   Stahl also is a co-chairman with Ware of the company's Diversity
Advisory Council, which Ivester created following the filing of an
employee racial discrimination lawsuit against the company last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Stahl is married and has two children.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Unger writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
