</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CITIGROUP-SCHRODERS-530&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITIGROUP TO BUY SCHRODER'S INVESTMENT BANK UNIT, MERGE IT WITH
SALOMON 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By PATRICK McGEEHAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a hurry to become more competitive in the
exploding investment banking business in Europe, Citigroup said
Tuesday that it would acquire the last independent investment bank
in London from Schroders PLC for about $2.21 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Citigroup, the largest financial-services company, also
announced that its net income for the fourth quarter rose to $2.62
billion, or 75 cents a diluted share, from $677 million, or 19
cents a share, in the fourth quarter of 1998. The year-ago profit
was depressed by trading losses and restructuring charges and
expenses related to the 1998 merger of Citicorp and Travelers
Group, which created Citigroup.
</P>
<P>
   Citigroup also said that it would raise its quarterly dividend
14 percent, to 16 cents a share from 14 cents. Investors reacted to
all of the news out of Citigroup by sending its shares to a 52-week
high of $58.50, up 50 cents. The earnings exceeded analysts'
consensus forecast of 70 cents a share, according to First
Call/Thomson Financial.
</P>
<P>
   The company's purchase of Schroders' investment banking business
is being structured as a merger of that operation with Citigroup's
Salomon Smith Barney investment banking unit. In Europe, the
combined operation will be known as Schroders Salomon Smith Barney
and will be co-managed by executives from each firm.
</P>
<P>
   Sanford Weill, chairman and co-chief executive officer of
Citigroup, said the deal ``will put us two or three years ahead of
where we would have been'' on the path to being a leading
investment bank in Europe. As the business of advising corporations
on mergers and acquisitions has boomed in Europe, Salomon has
fallen far behind the two New York-based investment banks that are
dominating that business, Morgan Stanley Dean Witter &AMP; Co. and
Goldman Sachs Group.
</P>
<P>
   Citigroup has agreed to pay about $220 million in incentives to
retain hundreds of Schroders' most important employees, said
Michael Carpenter, chairman and chief executive of Salomon Smith
Barney. Most of those employees did not own significant amounts of
stock in Schroders, whose founding family owns about 48 percent of
its stock.
</P>
<P>
   To seal the deal, Citigroup rolled out its newest heavy hitter:
former Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin. At a dinner Saturday night
in the Marlborough Suite at the Dukes Hotel in London, Rubin,
chairman of Citigroup's executive committee, assured Schroders'
executives that Salomon no longer was the ``rough-and-tumble''
trading operation it had been 10 years ago, said a person who was
there.
</P>
<P>
   It was important for Rubin, who was a partner at Goldman, Sachs
long before it went public last year, to put ``his personal
imprimatur'' on the deal because Schroders executives saw their
firm as a collegial partnership, said another person who was at the
dinner. ``He brought a fresh set of eyes to the strength that
Citigroup has around the world,'' this person said.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, Citigroup plans to fold the smaller Schroder &AMP; Co.
investment banking unit into Salomon Smith Barney, a move that
Citigroup executives acknowledged would result in the loss of a
considerable number of jobs. ``In the U.S., we have significant
overlap,'' Carpenter said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The proposed deal would leave Schroders PLC as a public company
in London specializing in money management for institutions and
wealthy people. But Win Bischoff, the German-born chairman of
Schroders who was knighted in December, will take the new position
of chairman of Citigroup Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Klein, who will be co-head of investment banking in
London for Schroders Salomon Smith Barney, said the decision to
acquire Schroders grew out of a strategic review of Citigroup's
options in August. The firm committed to building its European
banking operation fast, sending top managers over from New York and
hiring about 65 investment bankers in the next four months.
</P>
<P>
   Schroders then was considering building up its presence in New
York by acquiring Beacon Group, an investment banking boutique run
by former Goldman Sachs partner Geoffrey Boisi, and putting Boisi
in charge of Schroder &AMP; Co. Instead of working for Schroders, Boisi
wound up advising the firm on its deal with Citigroup.
</P>
<P>
   Just before Christmas, Bischoff contacted Carpenter and invited
him to make an offer before Schroders' board met Jan. 6. After
that, the two sides negotiated the deal, meeting mostly in the New
York area, sometimes at Citigroup's corporate retreat in Armonk,
N.Y. Carpenter said he went to London last week, using the
``cover'' that he was there to receive a ``bank of the year'' award
from a financial publication, and stayed around to wrap up the
talks over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``This doesn't finish it for us,'' Klein said. ``We still have
some significant building to do on the continent.''
</P>
<P>
   Strong growth in investment banking fueled Citigroup's
surprisingly strong performance last quarter. The firm's corporate
and investment bank, which includes Salomon Smith Barney, earned
$1.31 billion, up 136 percent from $553 million a year before. Its
consumer businesses, including branch banking, credit cards,
insurance and consumer finance, had operating income of $1.17
billion, up 35 percent from $872 million a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The numbers were very solid, though probably skewed more to
Salomon Smith Barney than to the consumer businesses,'' said Judah
Kraushaar, an analyst at Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. ``They have very good
revenue momentum and a lot of positive operating leverage.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
