</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAINEWEBBER-SCHWAB-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAINEWEBBER AND CHARLES SCHWAB REPORT VIBRANT EARNINGS GAINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ PaineWebber Group posted better-than-expected
quarterly earnings driven by active financial markets. PaineWebber
said its fourth-quarter earnings increased 66 percent, to $166.3
million, or $1.07 a diluted share, from $100.4 million, or 63 cents
a share.
</P>
<P>
   The firm's net revenue _ revenue minus interest expense _
increased 27 percent, to $1.39 billion, from $1.1 billion in the
fourth quarter of 1998. The amount of customer assets at the firm,
a key source of recurring revenue, rose 12 percent in the quarter
to $423 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Marron, chairman and chief executive of PaineWebber, said
customers are embracing the firm's integration of the Internet into
its business. ``Affluent clients now want to be able to see their
accounts online,'' he said, adding that the amount of assets in the
firm's online accounts increased 40 percent last quarter to more
than $140 billion. About 20 percent of that money is new to the
firm, he said.
</P>
<P>
   As expected, the Charles Schwab Corp. reported fourth quarter
net income of $170 million, or 20 cents a diluted share, up 60
percent from $106 million, or 12 cents a share, in the fourth
quarter of 1998. San Francisco-based Schwab said three weeks ago
that its earnings would exceed analysts' expectations, then
announced last week that it would use $2.73 billion of its stock to
acquire U.S. Trust Corp., a New York-based private bank.
</P>
<P>
   Schwab said its revenue for the quarter rose 43 percent, to
$1.13 billion as the average number of daily trades its customers
made surged to an all-time high of 234,000 a day in December.
Almost three-quarters, 73 percent, of all trades at Schwab were
made online last quarter, up from 61 percent a year before.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
