<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BUCS-NOTES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BUCS NOTEBOOK: Speedy foe impressive to Dungy
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ Tampa Bay players were rewarded with a day off
Tuesday, but coach Tony Dungy and the rest of his staff were in the
team's headquarters to review film of the St. Louis Rams.
</P>
<P>
   Dungy seems more impressed with his foe in Sunday's NFC
Championship game with each new tape he watches.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis ``is a very explosive team _ that is the No. 1 thing
you see,'' he said. ``You see speed and explosiveness in every area
of their team. That is how we tried to build our team, and they
have done real well at it.The big question
</P>
<P>
   In baseball, good pitching usually beats good hitting. In
football, what happens when a good offense goes against a good
defense? St. Louis has the No. 1 offense in the NFC, while Tampa
Bay has the top-ranked defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what happens; you guys will have to research and
tell me what happens when that is the case,'' Dungy said. ``I
really don't know. (But) being a defensive coach, I'd like to think
defense'' has the advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Enjoy the moment
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's the laid-back style of team leader Warren Sapp.
Whatever the case, Tampa Bay's players appear loose and relaxed.
It's not usually the personality of an NFL team approaching the
pressure-packed conference championship game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them to just enjoy it,'' Dungy said. ``It's something
that goes with the territory. You have to enjoy it, but you also
have to know what we are really here for _ that's to prepare and
get ready for the Rams.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this kind of thing doesn't happen all the time. You don't
play in the NFC Championship every week, so you need to enjoy it.''
</P>
<P>
   Dungy had been concerned that the team had gotten out of control
before last weekend's game against the Redskins.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since we had a bye in the first round, we had to wait two
weeks to play, and our guys were very hyped,'' Dungy said. ``This
week, thankfully, we are on a more normal schedule. The thing I
tell the (players) is that this is still a football game, even
though it's the NFC Championship. It's really not a lot different
(from) the other 17 games we've played.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta wannabe
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay backup quarterback Eric Zeier, who will be an
unrestricted free agent after the Super Bowl, again confirmed this
week that he is willing to listen to Falcons officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, having the chance to go back and play in front of
my friends and family would be good,'' said Zeier, a five-year
veteran. ``I don't know what is going to happen after the season.
I'm in a great situation here (in Tampa). I love this time; I love
this organization. We'll just have to wait and see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Two coaches' approaches
</P>
<P>
   Dungy has earned the respect of his players for his
non-confrontational methods and his refusal to single out and
criticize players through the media. The same cannot be said for
the coach of last week's opponent, Norv Turner of the Redskins.
</P>
<P>
   Turner remains the subject of criticism in Washington for
singling out veteran snapper Dan Turk in the 14-13 loss. Turk made
a bad snap that cost Washington a chance to kick a game-winning
field goal with 1:17 left.
</P>
<P>
   ``One guy didn't get the job done, not the whole special-teams
unit,'' Turner said.Brett Conway
</P>
<P>
   Turk was so upset that he skipped the team flight Saturday night
and remained with friends in South Florida. He was a no-show at
Washington's season-ending team meeting Monday and wants to be cut
from the team.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Carvell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
