<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-18 21:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9597 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-YALE-TECHNOLOGY-330&AMP;A     01-18 1037
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YALE-TECHNOLOGY-330&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT YALE, A $500 MILLION INVESTMENT IN SCIENCE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn. Mass., Calif., N.Y., N.J.)  (rk) 
 By KAREN W. ARENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Concerned that it will not be able to stay in the top academic
ranks without a greater presence in science, Yale University plans
to announce Thursday that it will invest $500 million in science
and engineering facilities, including the construction of five new
buildings and the renovation of several old ones.
</P>
<P>
   Universities everywhere are spending heavily on genomics
centers, computer labs and other facilities to foster cutting-edge
scientific fields, but Yale's $500 million commitment appears to be
one of the largest one-time building plans ever.
</P>
<P>
   Yale's decision to try to become more of a science and
technology powerhouse illustrates the growing importance that
universities are placing on scientific research. It also represents
a serious bid to reposition Yale's reputation; it is better known
for its prominence in the humanities, social sciences and arts, and
for its professional schools, than for its work in the sciences.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yale is committed to remain on everyone's short list of the
best universities in the world,'' said Richard C. Levin, Yale's
president, an economist who studies technological innovation. ``In
the 21st century, you must excel in science and engineering to
maintain that position.''
</P>
<P>
   Modern space for scientific research is crucial, Levin said, in
attracting top professors and students. ``We find ourselves in
stiffer competition in the sciences than in other fields,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   E. William Colglazier, executive officer of the National Academy
of Sciences, said many universities were recognizing the need to
spend more money on science. ``I think this is the wave of the
future, and we'll see more of these announcements,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a reflection of the fact that science and technology
are reshaping the world, and the universities need to make these
types of investments to remain in the forefront,'' he added.
``Unfortunately it's expensive, but universities like Yale have
decided they have to make this kind of investment.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Aided by its medical school, Yale is stronger scientifically
than its reputation might suggest, Levin contends. He said it was
among the top four universities in grants from the National
Institutes of Health and among the top four in scientific articles
most cited by others. Most of its science and engineering
departments are ranked among the top 12 nationally, he said, and
two _ physiology and pharmacology _ are No. 1 in graduate
department rankings.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty-three Yale professors are members of the National Academy
of Sciences, placing it fifth after Harvard (158), the University
of California at Berkeley (115), Stanford (111) and the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology (100). But the Yale faculty
includes only one Nobel laureate in the sciences: Sidney Altman,
who won the Nobel Prize in biology in 1989 for research on RNA.
</P>
<P>
   About a quarter of Yale's 5,200 undergraduates are in science or
engineering, up from about 17 percent a decade ago, and about a
third of its 1,800 graduate students are in those fields.
</P>
<P>
   The university has begun to try to upgrade its science offerings
in recent years. Levin announced his intention to strengthen
engineering when he became president in 1993, and he brought in Dr.
D. Allan Bromley, a nuclear physicist and former science adviser to
President George Bush, as a dean.
</P>
<P>
   The new construction plan grew out of a report last fall on
Yale's needs for expansion and renovation of its physical plant.
Yale has erected only two new science buildings in the last 30
years, one connected to the medical school and the other for a
structural biology center. The new buildings will expand the
university's science and engineering space by about 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Of the $500 million investment, about 40 percent will go for new
buildings, and the rest will be used to refurbish existing space.
The money will come on top of existing spending in science and
engineering.
</P>
<P>
   Many other colleges and universities, including Haverford,
Hofstra, Middlebury, Princeton, Williams and Wooster, have
announced new science centers in recent years, and some are
undertaking more than one.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard, for example, has said it plans to spend about $200
million over the next five years on five new and refurbished
science centers, including one for physical sciences and one for
life sciences. It recently opened a new computer sciences building
and is nearly finished with a new chemistry laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Yale plan covers only capital spending, Levin said
it would probably result in more hiring and spending in these
disciplines, too. He said the university had already committed to
adding four positions in engineering and six in the biological
sciences, which it is filling now.
</P>
<P>
   The new buildings, which Yale hopes to complete in six to eight
years, will include facilities for chemical, biological and
environmental research as well as for engineering and for the
School of Forestry and Environmental Studies. Yale also plans to
build two lecture halls for introductory science courses.
</P>
<P>
   A $24 million gift from John Malone, chairman of Liberty Media
and a 1963 graduate of Yale's engineering program, will help
finance the new engineering building, and Yale hopes to attract
other private gifts. In the meantime, it will borrow to pay for
construction.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut officials are cheering Yale's new building plan.
Gov. John Rowland and his senior economic adviser, Arthur Diedrick,
will join Yale officials Thursday morning for the formal
announcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great thing for Connecticut,'' Diedrick said Tuesday,
adding that research at the university had led to the creation of
35 companies over the last decade and that an expanding research
base could lead to even more.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will just further education in Connecticut in the
sciences and engineering,'' Diedrick said, ``which will be greatly
needed, as economic development focuses more on science and
technology fields.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
