<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-18 21:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9601 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-NY-CITY-BALLET-2TAKES     01-18 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CITY-BALLET-2TAKES-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOMEONE TO STEP IN FOR FARRELL?  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 23) 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 Harris Green's previous article for Arts &AMP; Leisure was about
American Ballet Theater's ``Corsaire'' on PBS.  
 By HARRIS GREEN 
  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ New York City Ballet's post-``Nutcracker'' winter
season is barely four weeks old, yet among a growing body of
regular balletgoers there is already a sense of completion about
it, thanks to the 23-year-old principal dancer Maria Kowroski. She
is assuaging and possibly wiping out nagging doubts that in some
quarters had verged on dread.
</P>
<P>
   This unease arose a few years ago when Kyra Nichols and Darci
Kistler began to relinquish the precious repertory of Balanchine
roles that Suzanne Farrell had either created or made her own.
Simply put, people were asking: ``Who else can now perform these
ballets with an authority, a grandeur and a daring similar to
Farrell's?'' And authority, grandeur and daring similar to hers are
all anyone has a right to expect; to ask for her equal would be
greedy, as well as preposterous.
</P>
<P>
   So far this season, most of the Farrell roles have been in very
good hands indeed. Ms. Nichols has been idle, but Ms. Kistler
continues to dominate the empty stage in the finale of ``Vienna
Waltzes'' with her exquisite arms and supple back.
</P>
<P>
   Miranda Weese and Wendy Whelan gave gratifying performances in
``Mozartiana'' and ``Tchaikovsky Piano Concerto No. 2,''
respectively. Both danced with a scrupulous, fearless assurance
that made one eager to see their subsequent performances for the
extra subtleties that seemed certain to come.
</P>
<P>
   Recalling the imperious flexibility of Helene Alexopoulos in
``Monumentum pro Gesualdo'' last season, and watching her boneless
mastery of Peter Martins' extraordinary demands in ``The Waltz
Project'' earlier this month, one looks forward to her future
assignments as well.
</P>
<P>
   The company's women are unusually strong this season. Despite
injuries _ Monique Meunier, Alexandra Ansanelli and Riolama Lorenzo
are hurt _ and influenza, City Ballet could count on outstanding
dancers like Jennie Somogyi, Jenifer Ringer, Pascale van Kipnis and
Rachel Rutherford, among others.
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of Ms. Kistler, however, they are not
particularly tall and therefore lack the amplitude that made a
Farrell performance bigger than life. Ms. Kowroski's height (5 foot
9 inches off point) is one of several reasons she has been the
center of attention ever since her appearance at the School of
American Ballet's 30th Annual Workshop Performances in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   As the dancer who dominates the man in the final Dark Messenger
section of Balanchine's ``Serenade,'' a role still in her
repertory, she possessed a surprisingly mature assurance. But it
was in his ``Western Symphony,'' one of those works he had
dismissed as an ``applause machine,'' that she had her maximum
impact. High as the students' energy level was in ``Symphony,'' it
did not peak until Ms. Kowroski charged onstage, the embodiment of
daring and assurance, powered by the longest legs in sight and a
yeasty delight in performing.
</P>
<P>
   (Before enrolling in SAB two years earlier, at age 16, she had
studied at the School of Grand Rapids Ballet for nine years and had
often danced in the Michigan company's ``Nutcracker.'')
</P>
<P>
   Such authority, not to mention such legs, guaranteed that her
joining the City Ballet corps in January 1995 would not lead to
anonymity in the ranks. The ballet master in chief, Martins,
immediately began grooming her for prominent roles.
</P>
<P>
   The soloist James Fayette recalls how quickly his surprise at
being asked to partner this novice turned into admiration. ``She
was totally focused in rehearsal,'' he says. ``She related to her
partner _ she looked you in the eye. And she was humble. You know,
you cannot escape history at City Ballet; you look at the score and
you read, `Suzanne jumps.' Maria knows the obligations that go
along with our repertory.''
</P>
<P>
   Assuming the mantle of Suzanne Farrell _ or perhaps one should
say ``the shawl,'' Ms. Farrell's preferred wrap _ holds no terror
for Ms. Kowroski. Asked about the Farrell roles, four of which she
has danced to date, she says: ``It's an honor to do them. For me
they are no burden or obligation but a challenge. And I like
challenges. In rehearsal I'm not comfortable until I feel I'm
perfect. When I get that assurance, then I can take chances
onstage.''
</P>
<P>
   Talk of a Farrell successor, exceedingly hopeful in 1995, began
in earnest a little over two years later, after Ms. Kowroski was
made a soloist. Already she had brought a similarly regal authority
to Titania in the pas de deux with the Cavalier in Balanchine's
``Midsummer Night's Dream'' and a similarly nacreous quality in
repose on her seashell couch.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The first week of the current winter season demonstrated Ms.
Kowroski's growing command of a broad repertory. On the same
evening that she was an Austrian maiden, swooning in the moonlit
forest of ``Vienna Waltzes,'' she assumed various serpentine and
insectile shapes in ``The Waltz Project'' and, with her arms
seemingly joined at the elbows and her legs at the knees, twitched
alarmingly as Charles Askegard toted her offstage.
</P>
<P>
   ``That hurt,'' she admits when asked about the contortion. (She
is fortunate to have someone as tall as Askegard as a frequent
partner, even if their long legs create problems in rehearsals.
``We spend a lot of time kicking each other,'' he says, with genial
stoicism.)
</P>
<P>
   Two days later she was presiding over the second pas de trois in
``Agon'' with cool authority. Her awesome extension was so
rock-solidly balanced on point that her partners, Arch Higgins and
Stephen Hanna, could have taken twice as long to offer support.
</P>
<P>
   Perfectionist though she is, Ms. Kowroski in class is invariably
collegial. It was this quality that caught the attention of the
Broadway choreographer Susan Stroman last spring when she was
casting ``Blossom Got Kissed,'' her contribution to City Ballet's
50th-anniversary season and the last of three ballets collectively
titled ``Duke!'' (because all were set to Duke Ellington's music).
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Stroman had in mind a character so out of it that she wears
a tutu to a jazz club, where she ``learns rhythm and finds love
with a triangle player.''
</P>
<P>
   Because City Ballet was constantly rehearsing and performing a
record number of works at that festive time, however, Ms. Stroman
did not have the luxury of conducting individual auditions. ``I was
familiar with the dancers, of course,'' she says. ``I knew Robert
La Fosse could play the musician. I knew the type I wanted for
Blossom. I decided to watch four company classes, looking for
performers who had personality and could perform through the beat
as well as on it. Maria was so tough and serious but so obviously
happy to be there and so outgoing with her fellow dancers that I
knew she was the one.'' (Asked why she thought she had been chosen,
Ms. Kowroski says, ``I think Susan saw me cutting up during a
break.'')
</P>
<P>
   The combination of Ms. Stroman's showmanship, Ellington's music
(belted out by the Lincoln Center Jazz Orchestra under David
Berger) and Ms. Kowroski's characterization made ``Duke!'' one of
the few exhilarating triumphs of that hectic season. Promotion to
principal followed within weeks. This month she was scheduled to
add four new roles to her repertory of around 30 ballets.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Satisfaction is fleeting for the perfectionist, however.
Although she has a steady boyfriend, the City Ballet corps dancer
Stuart Capps, and is appreciated by one of the world's major
performing-arts institutions, she will look positively stricken if
asked about her failure to whip off all 32 of the obligatory
third-act fouettes in Martins' ``Swan Lake.''
</P>
<P>
   Assurance that her characterizations of Odette and Odile had
been wholly convincing brings little consolation. ``I just wasn't
strong enough,'' she says, then adds quietly and firmly, ``I'm
going to work on those fouettes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
