</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPE-PROTESTANTS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT VATICAN'S INTERFAITH CEREMONY, RIFTS REMAIN OBVIOUS
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds.: Corrects title of World Alliance of Reformed Churches in 6th
graph.)  
(jw) 
 By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Indulgences, the Roman Catholic practice of remitting
punishment for sins in exchange for prayer, repentance and, in the
Middle Ages, even money, helped set off the Protestant Reformation.
</P>
<P>
   Five hundred years later, indulgences remain a sticking point
between Catholics and Protestants. On Tuesday, a few of the world's
largest Protestant denominations boycotted a religious ceremony
that the Vatican described as the ``most significant ecumenical
event'' of this Holy Year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, it was. Metropolitan Athanasios, a representative
of the orthodox patriarch of Constantinople, and George Carey,
archbishop of Canterbury, helped Pope John Paul II push open the
Holy Door of St. Paul Outside the Walls Basilica.
</P>
<P>
   It was the fourth and final such ceremony celebrating the start
of a Jubilee, or Roman Catholic Holy Year. On Christmas Eve, the
pope opened doors at St. Peter's Basilica, and subsequently opened
doors at two other major basilicas in Rome where Catholic pilgrims
can earn indulgences during the Holy Year. Tuesday's ceremony was
the only one that actively involved non-Catholic leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives from 22 Christian churches, including the
Lutheran World Federation, attended the service, one of the largest
interfaith gatherings since the Second Vatican Council. But some
Protestant leaders, among them Baptists, Presbyterians and
Calvinists, chose to skip an event they viewed as an affront.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Reformation was provoked by an indulgence campaign, so
associating a jubilee indulgence with Holy Year celebrations seemed
like a retrograde step by the Vatican,'' explained the Rev. Paraic
Reamonn, spokesman for the World Alliance of Reformed Churches,
based in Geneva, which represents 75 million Protestants, mostly
Presbyterian and Calvinist.
</P>
<P>
   The ceremony signaled both the progress of interfaith dialogue
over the last 30 years and some of the stumbling blocks. But it
also illustrated the contradictions that have run through John Paul
II's papacy. No pope has worked harder to mend the rifts between
Christian churches. The presence of so many Orthodox religious
leaders, as well as the head of the Lutheran church worldwide,
testified to his diplomacy. At the same time, however, John Paul II
has rigidly upheld church dogma and Catholic traditions, including
indulgences, that antagonize other faiths.
</P>
<P>
   Even the Anglican Church, which is closer to Rome than most
Protestant denominations, conceded that deep divisions simmer
beneath the surface.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought it was important to work toward a closer
relationship between our two churches,'' said the Rev. Paul Avis,
general secretary of the Church of England's Council on Christian
Charity, explaining the archbishop of Canterbury's participation,
``without concealing that serious difficulties remain to be
overcome.''
</P>
<P>
   The Anglican decision to ordain women is one source of friction
with Rome, but there are others, including the authority of the
pope.
</P>
<P>
   In October, the Vatican and Lutheran World Federation signed a
landmark joint declaration, saying they were in agreement on most
major points of doctrine, though not all. But many Lutheran
churches refused to go along. The more outspoken critics, including
the second largest American branch, the Lutheran Church-Missouri
Synod, said they were not invited to the event Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The pope has stressed that he wants ecumenicism to be a keynote
of the Jubilee, and that was the main reason he twinned Tuesday's
ecumenical service with the opening of a Holy Door. Since the first
Jubilee in 1300, popes have granted plenary indulgences to pilgrims
who visit holy sites in Rome. The sale of indulgences, which helped
drive Martin Luther to break with Rome in 1517, was stopped soon
after, but their religious value was reaffirmed at the Council of
Trent. Especially after the Second Vatican Council reforms,
progressive Catholics sought to play down indulgences, viewing them
as hindrances to ecumenical dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   For the year 2000, however, John Paul II has highlighted the
importance of indulgences, broadening the ways they can be earned,
including attendance at Tuesday's ceremony at St. Paul Outside the
Walls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, that was a bit much,'' said the Rev. Domenico
Tomasetto, a Baptist pastor who is president of the Federation of
Evangelical Churches in Italy and declined to attend. ``The
Protestant church was born to protest indulgences.''
</P>
<P>
   The 79-year-old pope was clearly elated by Tuesday's ceremony,
walking at an unusually brisk pace down the aisle of St. Paul's,
and delivering his homily on the need to repent for divisions
within Christianity in a clear, firm voice. He improvised a new
ending to his prepared remarks, saying, ``Unity, unity, maybe even
we, leaving this basilica, can say unity.''
</P>
<P>
   But some still detected roots of division. ``The Vatican seems
to be facing in two directions: there are genuine ecumenical
feelers, and there are unilateral steps that go backward,'' Reamonn
said. ``Sometimes it seems that for at least some in the Vatican,
Christian unity can be achieved by everybody else becoming Roman
Catholic.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
