<SLUG> BC-PRISONS-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAX TRAINING HARMING TEXAS PRISON GUARDS, SAYS REPORT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY WALT 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Training for state prison guards has been so
severely curtailed in recent years that the officers' lives are in
``grave danger,'' the director of training for the prison system
has warned.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Gov. George W. Bush, Charles D. Godwin, training
director for the Texas Department of Criminal Justice, accused his
bosses not only of diverting training funds to other prison
expenditures but also of lying to the governor and the public about
the seriousness of the situation.
</P>
<P>
   His letter and an accompanying report outline 32 staff assaults
since November 1998 that he said could easily have resulted in
deaths _ including an assault in which an officer was stabbed with
a 26-inch steel rod and another in which a prisoner tried to throw
an officer off the second tier onto a concrete floor.
</P>
<P>
   Godwin posted a signed summary of his report to the governor on
the Internet at www.tdcjid.com _ an unofficial agency Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile on Tuesday, the 230,000 member Texas AFL-CIO urged
Bush to call a special legislative session to address a shortage of
guards at state prisons. TDCJ has about 1,000 vacant guard
positions throughout the state, a reflection of rapid expansion of
prisons in recent years plus a booming economy that has offered
Texans a variety of job choices with higher pay and better working
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   The AFL-CIO's approval of a special session resolution came a
week after prison guards presented Bush's office with a petition
urging him to call the Legislature into session. The Texas
Legislature isn't scheduled to meet again until January 2001. Bush
has said he will not call a special session but he does support
higher pay for guards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush, the TDCJ administration is deceiving you, as
well as the public in Texas,'' Godwin wrote in a letter dated Jan.
12. ``I have in the past witnessed attempts by TDCJ administrators
to deceive members of the Board of Criminal Justice. I believe you
likewise have been deceived by TDCJ officials as to the seriousness
of the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Safety of prison guards has become an increasingly public issue
in recent weeks following the murder of correctional officer Daniel
Nagle, the inmate takeover of a Beeville prison last month and the
stabbing earlier this week of a guard at a facility in Huntsville.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Godwin said, Nagle's murder and the subsequent takeover
of the McConnell Unit by some prisoners ``are the direct results of
dangerous trends in security over the past several years.''
</P>
<P>
   Nagle's death is still under investigation. TDCJ spokesman Glen
Castlebury said Tuesday a report on the McConnell Unit uprising is
expected to be completed by the first week in February.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, Officer Ernest Coleman, 41, was stabbed in
the stomach with a pencil by a convict at the Byrd Diagnostic Unit
in Huntsville where incoming male prisoners are processed.
</P>
<P>
   ``TDCJ officials say there is a lack of funds within the agency
to address these issues (of recruiting, training and retention),''
Godwin added. ``This is another lie. It is not a lack of funds; it
is the low priority placed on the lives of the officers by the TDCJ
administration.''
</P>
<P>
   Godwin's letter prompted an immediate and strong response from
Criminal Justice Board Chairman Alfred ``Mac'' Stringfellow of San
Antonio, who wrote Godwin, saying that his ``serious accusations''
require the board to investigate the matter. But he also warned
that if Godwin's accusations are wrong, ``they are defamatory,
irresponsible and at a minimum inconsistent with your current
position as ... director of training.''
</P>
<P>
   Stringfellow also ordered Godwin to attend the board meeting
later this week to defend and support his allegations.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Godwin also called for the resignation of TDCJ
Executive Director Wayne Scott and the entire Texas Board of
Criminal Justice.
</P>
<P>
   Godwin, no stranger to controversy with his bosses, said he
fears he will be fired from his job for speaking out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody's got to get their attention,'' he said. ``And I've
already got the reputation as a whistle-blower. I'm not held in
favor with the administration anyway. I figured somebody had to do
it and it might as well be me. So many people in the agency fear
retaliation.''
</P>
<P>
   Godwin said TDCJ's own reports on staff assaults dispel prison
administrators' contentions that there is no threat to prison
security or officer safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at the assault rate and if you look at the
increasingly violent nature of assaults, then you know that is not
a true statement,'' Godwin said.
</P>
<P>
   Assaults are at least 10 times more frequent than they were in
1988 and they are increasingly violent, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Castlebury said the rate of assaults with a weapon has, indeed,
increased from 4.3 per 10,000 inmates in 1997 to 7.4 per 10,000 in
1999. ``Weapons'' include throwing of bodily fluids and other
liquids at guards, the two most common types of assaults, according
to TDCJ officials.
</P>
<P>
   But he attributed the cause to the fact that TDCJ is locking up
more violent criminals for longer periods of time _ not to cutbacks
in training.
</P>
<P>
   He declined to comment further on any other allegations that
Godwin raised.
</P>
<P>
   ``The TDCJ administration cut training hours, lowered academic
standards, denied requests for additional instructors, reduced the
training budget, spent dedicated training funds on other programs,
canceled renovations, delayed construction of new training
facilities and did not pursue recommended recruiting and retention
strategies all during this period of rapidly increasing inmate
assaults on correctional employees,'' Godwin said in his report to
the governor.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
