<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-18 21:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9607 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-DEBATES-RDP-2NDTAKE-N     01-18 0455
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEBATES-RDP-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 DES MOINES, Iowa: Shrum said.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   But no one has disputed that the debates generated interest from
the press. A national poll by the Shorenstein Center at Harvard
University found that the rash of debates last week spawned the
heaviest news coverage thus far of the presidential campaign. The
survey found a doubling from the previous week of the number of
Americans who could recall having seen, read, or heard a campaign
news story.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our polling suggests that at the end of this first salvo of
debates, the candidates' images have changed as a consequence,''
said Andrew Kohut, director of the Pew Research Center for People
and the Press. ``Gore's stronger standing in a number of polls
reflects that.''
</P>
<P>
   While there were memorable flashes _ like Gore's dare to Bradley
to eliminate television advertisements and Bush's saying Christ was
his favorite philosopher-thinker _ no candidate committed a
career-breaking blunder or scored with a one-liner that catapulted
him ahead in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``They both have improved,'' Sen. Joseph R. Biden Jr. of
Delaware, who ran for the Democratic nomination in 1988, said of
the two Democrats. ``You would declare a winner based on what style
appeals to you.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a decided difference between the Democratic and
Republican events. The Democrats had far more opportunity to delve
into policy minutia because there were only two candidates. The
Republican forums were often unwieldly because six candidates were
vying to be heard.
</P>
<P>
   In random interviews with voters in New Hampshire, many said
they were pleased there were so many debates, but grumbled that too
many Republicans who were far behind in the polls _ namely Sen.
Orrin Hatch of Utah, Gary Bauer and Alan Keyes _ got equal billing.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were just too many people,'' said Perry Shaw, 48, who
runs a supermarket in Dover, N.H. ``They weren't able to get their
points across. It's non-productive.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the debates were so distinct in format and substance that
they offered viewers an opportunity to observe how the contenders
could handle wildly different situations. The most watched debate _
about 4.5 million viewers, according to Nielsen _ was the
Democratic encounter on ``Meet the Press'' on Dec. 19; only 450,000
tuned in to a Democratic debate here on Jan. 8.
</P>
<P>
   ``The formats have been a let a thousand flowers bloom kind of
thing,'' said Tom Hannon, the political director for CNN, which
broadcast several of the debates. ``If you were following these
like soap operas, you'd have a good sense at the end of these of
the personality of Bradley and Gore and Bush and McCain in a way
you can't get from the minute-and-a-half spots on the evening
news.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
