<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFC-BUCS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Emanuel to Falcons fans: 'How do you like me now?'
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ Tampa Bay reciever Bert Emanuel is not a
trash-talker or filled with vengeance. But he has a message for
Atlanta Falcons fans who criticized his reasons for leaving the
team as a free agent two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``How you like me now?'' Emanuel asked quietly with a grin on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The soft-spoken Emanuel looked as is had a made a big mistake by
departing the Falcons. One of the main reasons he decided to sign
with the Buccaneers was to play for a team that had a chance to
reach the Super Bowl. Tampa Bay had advanced to the NFC
quarterfinals the year before.
</P>
<P>
   However, during Emanuel's inaugural season with Tampa Bay, it
was the Falcons _ not the Bucs _ who were playing in Super Bowl
XXXIII.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, it was like, `In your face,' '' Emanuel said.
``People said `You left too early _ now we (the Falcons) are in the
Super Bowl, and you are at home watching us.'
</P>
<P>
   ``But it is kind of reverse fortune now,'' he said. ``We're one
win away (from the Super Bowl), and they are at home. It is pretty
much a dream come true. It's a time to enjoy and savor, because you
may never have a moment like this again in your career.''
</P>
<P>
   Emanuel is determined to enjoy the moment because he has had
on-field problems his two years in Tampa Bay. He caught a
career-low 41 passes in the 1998 season and missed five games
because of various injuries. He watched the Falcons play in the NFL
championship game one day after being released from the hospital
with rib and kidney injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was good to see some friends and (former Falcon) teammates
that had been through the tough times make it to the Super Bowl,''
Emanuel said. ``It was good to see guys like Jessie Tuggle rewarded
like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Emanuel said that, while watching the Super Bowl from the sofa
of his Alpharetta home, he felt no regrets about leaving the
Falcons. On Tuesday, though, Emanuel admitted that he had been a
``little bit envious.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that is only natural when you leave a team, and then
they go the Super Bowl and you are at home watching them,'' Emanuel
said. ``But it was never to the point where I felt like I had made
a bad decision _ never that.''
</P>
<P>
   This season has been another series of struggles for Emanuel. He
has been hindered by a right hamstring strain and sat out five
games and played only sparingly in five others. He has looked
nothing like the explosive talent that led the Falcons in receiving
in the 1996-97 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you told me two years ago some of the things I would've
gone through down here, I probably wouldn't have agreed to go
through with it,'' Emanuel said. ``I've been through a lot of
adversity, but I wouldn't change a thing. It has made me a better
player and a better person. I've grown a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that this week Emanuel is healthier than he has
been since joining Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy that he's here,'' Bucs offensive coordinator Mike
Shula said. ``Statistically, he hasn't seemed as productive as he
would've wanted to be. But he means a lot to this team. He has made
some big plays and is a great influence on our younger recievers.
He's playing his best ball right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Carvell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
