<HEADER>
A9610 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-NEO-NOIR-FILMS-2TAKES     01-18 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEO-NOIR-FILMS-2TAKES-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NEW NOIR: IN THE DAYLIGHT, BUT STILL DEADLY  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 23) 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 David Everitt is the author of ``The Manly Movie Guide'' and ``For
Reel,'' published this month.  
 By DAVID EVERITT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Film noir carries the 1940s and 1950s within its tales of
treachery and murder, in its cavernous city streets photographed in
shadowy black-and-white. The men wear trenchcoats and sardonic
grimaces.
</P>
<P>
   The women sport platinum-blonde hairdos and harbor malicious
schemes. And there is enough cigarette smoke to make anti-tobacco
lobbyists apoplectic. Yet despite its post-World War II stamp, noir
has managed to stay alive, and not merely as film-buff fare.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Humphrey Bogart, Richard Widmark and Barbara Stanwyck
have been replaced on screen by the likes of Harvey Keitel, Dennis
Hopper and Linda Fiorentino. In films like ``Reservoir Dogs'' and
``The Last Seduction,'' these actors follow their predecessors into
the depths of a dark, dangerous world.
</P>
<P>
   Only now their lonely travels take them to bright, contemporary
settings rather than fleabag hotels and last-stop saloons. Film
noir has gone from retro to neo, and on Feb. 18, Film Forum begins
a seven-week festival to commemorate this resurgence.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Neo-Noir'' series includes acclaimed recent movies _
``Fargo,'' ``Pulp Fiction,'' ``One False Move'' _ as well as
lesser-known features like ``Red Rock West'' and, for fans of the
outre, a forgotten Sal Mineo film called ``Who Killed Teddy Bear?''
Among the directors whose dark visions will be offered are Joel
Coen, Quentin Tarantino, Steven Soderbergh, Roman Polanski and Abel
Ferrara.
</P>
<P>
   Excursions into the noir world have always included vivid sex
and violence. But where seduction was once a fully clothed affair,
and death took place among the shadows, today's noir stylists leave
less to the imagination.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Goldstein, Film Forum's director of repertory programming,
admitted with some tongue-in-cheek relish that he had used the
sleaze factor as a criterion in selecting films for the series.
``Seduction, betrayal and greed _ those had to be major themes,''
he said. ``And a good dose of sex and sadistic violence.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein and his programming partner, Michael Sayers,
discovered another element that distinguishes neo-noir filmmakers
from those whose work they seek to emulate. ``When they were making
what we now call classic noir, they didn't know they were making
film noir,'' Goldstein said. ``They were making thrillers or crime
movies. Now it's a recognized genre, so filmmakers are
self-consciously making noir.''
</P>
<P>
   The classic noir period ended in 1958, according to Foster
Hirsch, author of ``Detours and Lost Highways: A Map of Neo-Noir,''
the inspiration for the Film Forum series. It was in 1958 that
Orson Welles made ``Touch of Evil,'' which gathered many of the
noir trademarks _ paranoia; double-dealing; bleak, baroque
camerawork _ and ratcheted them up to delirious extremes.
</P>
<P>
   Hirsch regards the movie as the final statement of the genre's
conventions and a convenient demarcation, although he pointed out
that ``things don't happen that neatly.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The impulse behind noir didn't suddenly stop after `Touch of
Evil,' '' he said.
</P>
<P>
   What emerged in the 1960s and 1970s was a new way to express
that impulse. The first change was the addition of color. ``The
classic phase was totally identified with black-and-white,'' Hirsch
said. ``In fact, people would ask: `How can you have film noir in
color'? My contention is that you can.'' Noir, Hirsch asserts, can
also be realized on a wide screen, even though the original
classics achieved their claustrophobic mood by squeezing images
into the nearly square dimensions of older screens.
</P>
<P>
   One of the first movies to demonstrate the new approach was John
Boorman's ``Point Blank'' (1967), a brooding crime story starring
Lee Marvin that was filmed not only in color and on a wide screen
but, to a great extent, in broad daylight. More recently, the most
significant milestone was Lawrence Kasdan's ``Body Heat,'' made in
1981.
</P>
<P>
   The film combined a modern sensibility with a vintage-style
story about a scheming femme fatale, and it brought the term
neo-noir into the critical lexicon.
</P>
<P>
   While wide-screen color and a new explicitness have updated the
genre, audiences remain intrigued for essentially the same reasons
they always were, according to Hirsch. ``There is an appeal of
story about characters who are thrown into a kind of nightmare
scenario. I don't know that that ever goes out of style.''
</P>
<P>
   Walter Hill, whose 1978 thriller ``The Driver'' is included in
the Film Forum program, agrees that there is a timeless attraction
to characters dogged by cruel circumstance and fate. ``As much as
these movies are hard-bitten and without illusions, there's also a
romanticism about that stance,'' he said. ``Doomed romanticism, I
guess, is something we think of as Byronic, but it's obviously a
lot older than that, as old as the Greek tragedies, really.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   For audiences of the '80s and '90s, the doomed protagonist may
have had a special significance. Typically, this character is white
and male. Often, in films like ``Fatal Attraction'' and ``A Simple
Plan,'' he is middle-class. Almost always he damns himself by
giving in to temptation _ either a proposition from an alluring
woman or a scheme to make easy money (often engineered by an
alluring woman).
</P>
<P>
   Some who have studied the genre see a parallel here between the
classic and neo periods. The writer-director Paul Schrader, who has
two films in the ``Neo-Noir'' series (``Taxi Driver'' and ``Light
Sleeper'') and who published an extensive critique of film noir in
1972, pointed out that American men in the late 1940s were uneasy
about the independence women had acquired during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was something scary sociologically going on with that
empowerment that had occurred during the war,'' Schrader said. ``So
this black widow character, this femme fatale, was partly a way to
address this new balance in the sexes. And, of course, that
empowerment for women has kept pace, and every generation needs to
reformulate these kinds of metaphorical fantasies involving male
fears.''
</P>
<P>
   Men who like their sociology hot and pulpy may be the primary
audience for noir, both classic and neo, but women don't
necessarily take umbrage at the genre's larcenous vixens. John Dahl
said that while making ``The Last Seduction,'' he expected the
villain portrayed by Linda Fiorentino to repel female viewers. But
audience reaction surprised him. ``I talked to some men who were
just offended by her, and I talked to a lot of women who said: `Oh,
I love that woman. She was as bad as she wanted to be and nobody
could stop her.'''
</P>
<P>
   However much neo-noir crosses gender lines, the genre's greatest
admirers may well be the people who make the films. To a certain
extent, neo-noir appears to be filmmaker-driven. While an
occasional title _ ``Fargo'' or ``Pulp Fiction'' _ qualifies as a
mass-market hit, most neo-noir films attract a smaller audience.
</P>
<P>
   Still, these movies continue to be made. One obvious attraction
for filmmakers is the economics: noir-style films require few sets,
small casts and no digital effects. A young director with meager
resources could not find a leaner entree into the movie business.
</P>
<P>
   And the stories themselves, Hill believes, hold a special
allure. ``The very large audiences tend not to respond terribly to
this, but noir is a form that is almost the antithesis of
traditional Hollywood filmmaking, in that it accepts the
inevitability of fate,'' he said. ``There is probably no idea less
harmonious with the usual Hollywood storytelling ideal. And never
to be overlooked is the perversity factor in people who make
movies. They like to push against what everyone else is doing.''
</P>
<P>
   They also like to show off, and noir gives them the chance.
``One of the things that's most intriguing about noir is the
absolute command you must have over the medium,'' Hill said. ``You
must control almost every comma, and everything is kind of invented
and artificial. In a sense, a stylistic exercise for the
filmmaker.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, the exercise can go a bit too far. Aficionados of the
genre point to movies that slavishly copy the classic style and
dismiss them as ``faux noir.'' Dahl uses the term to describe
movies in which the directors explore every conceivable form of
stark, dramatic lighting, but fail to generate suspense or
involvement with the characters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Filmmakers fall in love with the style of noir, the
Venetian-blind lighting, the smoke,'' Dahl said, adding, ``It
doesn't really get under your skin.''
</P>
</TEXT>
