<HEADLINE>
NEW HAVEN TAKES ON WALES, AND WINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds., for use with YALE-TECHNOLOGY)  
 (HLW)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A college by any other name would surely attract less attention.
</P>
<P>
   Yale University in New Haven has persuaded Yale College in
Wrexham, Wales, to change its name, apparently concerned that the
27-year-old British ``further education facility,'' which offers
nondegree programs, might be mistaken for the Ivy League
institution founded in 1701.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's confusion about whether they are us or not,'' said
Linda Lorimer, the secretary of Yale University, according to
Tuesday's Yale Daily News. ``Who's to know whether they're
connected with us?''
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the Welsh college are nonplused. ``We are a mere
drop in the education ocean compared to Yale,'' Emelyn Jones, the
principal, told the newspaper, adding that the idea of a mix-up was
``preposterous.''
</P>
<P>
   The Welsh college's Web site, www.yale.ac.uk, says the school
was named for Elihu Yale, the American university's benefactor, who
is buried in Wrexham. But Jones said his institution was named
after the hills that surround it, which have been known for
hundreds of years as lal (pronounced ``y'ALL,'' according to The
Yale Daily News).
</P>
<P>
   ``Yale'' is a trademark registered to the Connecticut
university, and administrators there had apparently threatened
legal action. Because of the pressure from its more famous
namesake, the Welsh school will hereafter be known as Coleg lal
Yale College, Wrexham. Signs and brochures will be replaced as the
new name takes hold.
</P>
<P>
   The people who make those locks better watch out.
</P>
</TEXT>
