<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HAWKS19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hawks' Wilkens optimistic despite rough start
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ More than a quarter-century into a Hall of Fame
coaching career Lenny Wilkens said Tuesday that he remains eager
for the battle.
</P>
<P>
   After preparing his team for tonight's game with the
Philadelphia 76ers, the Hawks coach indicated he will not back away
from his mission to turn a revamped underachieving Hawks team into
a winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still believe we can get it done,'' he said. ``Two or three
wins against good teams and I think it will turn itself around.
Confidence is contagious. Once they believe in themselves and what
we're doing, it will change.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks are 13-23, 13th in the 15th-team Eastern Conference.
They've lost 14 of 18 and on their present course would become a
lottery team. That's not what management had in mind last summer
when it dealt away starting guards Steve Smith and Mookie Blaylock
and future draft picks for four veterans and a high pick last June.
In fact, if they remain in lottery territory any pick nine to 13
would fall to the Los Angeles Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   The coach says that won't happen. ``I'm going to see that it
doesn't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   At 62, Wilkens has reached an age when many successful men with
financial means take a step back. He has a new home nearing
completion in Seattle where his grandchildren live. He enjoys ocean
cruises with his wife, Marilyn. But in his 27th season as an NBA
head coach and with 2 1/2 years remaining on his final Hawks
contract at $5.27 million a season, Wilkens indicates it is not
time to go.
</P>
<P>
   He admits that he occasionally wearies of the fight. ``Look,
like anyone else, I have my moments. I'll admit that. It can be
discouraging. But I'm an optimistic person. I'm very positive. I've
always been that way and I intend to fight through this.''
</P>
<P>
   But what can Hawks fans expect if the 13-man roster does not
turn things around in what stands to be the franchise's worst
season since a 34-48 record in 1984-85?
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be changes,'' Wilkens said. Pointing to the
wood-paneled dressing room, he noted, ``There will be changes and
it will be in there. I am convinced we have the talent. The
question, then, is whether the chemistry is right. If we don't have
the right chemistry, then we have to change.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked to define chemistry, he said it is the ability of his
players to function and win together. ``It's not there right now. I
see that we can compete and I think the guys have shown they can
play hard together, but not that they can win. I think that's
coming. I'm encouraged, actually, by some of the things we did (in
a three-point loss to Philadelphia last Saturday and a six-point
defeat against Milwaukee Monday).
</P>
<P>
   ``We got great play from our bench Monday, the dynamic
performance from Jason (Terry), LaPhonso (Ellis) and Lorenzen
(Wright) that I had expected. I want that to continue.''
</P>
<P>
   However, he said he is not getting the leadership he expects
from veterans Dikembe Mutombo and Alan Henderson, whose fits of
pique have punctuated virtually every loss in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them I won't tolerate confrontations with the
referees,'' Wilkens said, noting Henderson's three episodes in
Monday's game. ``That's not going to continue. These are two
bright, competitive guys. They know better. I expect them to show
the way to the other guys on the team.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, he said, he indicated he will deal harshly
with players who are demonstrably unhappy with their roles on the
team.
</P>
<P>
   Without naming individuals, he said, ``I'm not going to allow
them to hang their heads. No. When a teammate is getting shots and
you're not, you don't hang your head. When he misses a shot, you
support him. When you miss a shot, you keep your head in the game.
I'm not going to have players with their heads down because they're
not happy with minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the problems he deals with, he said, is the diverse
backgrounds on this team. ``Many of them have not been in a winning
program. I've given them time to make adjustments. Now, it's time
to get the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   A week after recovering from a severe bout of flu, Wilkens looks
healthier and sounds like a man who is eager for the task.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the talent we have,'' he said. ``I like our young
players. Kids like Jason have a chance to be really good, so
they're going to get their time on the floor. That's cost us a few
games, but we won't back away. In time, that's going to help us
turn this thing around.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Denberg writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
