u f BC-MICROSOFT-EARNINGS-(T     01-18 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-EARNINGS-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT REPORTS 23 PERCENT GAIN IN EARNINGS, BUT STOCK FALLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (See also MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST)  
 (bl)  
 By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Microsoft Corp. on Tuesday reported second quarter earnings that
exceeded Wall Street analysts' expectations, but was punished by
after-hours traders for having missed more optimistic ``whisper
numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   While sounding its usual cautionary notes about corporate PC
demand and slowing revenue growth, Microsoft reported solid results
amid a sea of recent distractions, including last week's news of
the merger of Time Warner and America Online, the passing of the
chief executive title from Bill Gates to Steven Ballmer and
Tuesday's filing challenging the findings of a federal judge that
the company is an abusive monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft reported its results after the close of the market. In
Nasdaq trading, its shares closed at $115.3125, up $3.0625. But in
afterhours trading, shares fell to $112.75.
</P>
<P>
   For the quarter ended Dec. 31, Microsoft reported earnings of
$2.44 billion, or 44 cents per diluted share, up 23 percent
compared with $1.98 billion, or 36 cents a share, in the comparable
period a year ago. Revenues rose 18 percent to $6.11 billion from
the $5.20 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Second quarter 2000 earnings include a one-time charge of
approximately 3 cents per share related to last week's settlement
of an antitrust lawsuit brought by Caldera Inc. Excluding this
charge, diluted earnings per share grew 31 percent to 47 cents a
share.
</P>
<P>
   The consensus expectation among analysts had been 43 cents,
according to First Call. Whisper numbers on the street Tuesday
ranged from 47 cents to 49 cents.
</P>
<P>
   There was also a 2 cents a share reduction in earnings related
to new accounting practices for employee stock options; this change
will continue to affect Microsoft earnings.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Rick Sherlund, an analyst with Goldman Sachs, said the quarter
included about 4 cents a share in unanticipated investment income,
essentially accounting for all of the earnings above the consensus
estimate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The revenues are in line with our expectations, and excluding
the investment gain, so were earnings. It's a respectable
quarter,'' he said. ``Investors are likely to look forward to the
launch of Windows 2000 to create more momentum going forward.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Windows 2000, the business-class operating system that is a
successor to Windows NT, is scheduled to ship on Feb. 17. Windows
2000 is a critical product for Microsoft because, as the company's
operating system for powerful network server computers, its success
will determine the company's ability to compete in the crucial
Internet market on an equal footing with Sun Microsystems Inc., IBM
and various vendors of the Unix operating system.
</P>
<P>
   Sun and IBM have flourished on the Internet, in part because of
reports that Windows NT was not robust enough or secure enough for
the kinds of demands the Web places on servers.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the ship date, the third quarter will reflect only
partial revenues from Windows 2000, John Connors, Microsoft's new
chief financial officer, said in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to take time for the revenue stream to build with
Windows 2000 because it's a business product rather than a consumer
product,'' he said. Business products have longer sales cycles and
slower adoption rates because corporate users take longer to
evaluate software and modify internal programs.
</P>
<P>
   Connors said investment income had been unusually high due to
the sale of certain assets as well as merger activity that
triggered gains from other holdings. ``I don't expect the same
level of non-operating income every quarter, but you guys should
expect some quarters with a fairly high number,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   With Microsoft, analysts pay particular attention to deferred
revenue, which increased about $130 million from the September
quarter to $4.26 billion. This was in contrast with the September
quarter, which showed a decline from the June quarter. The reason
that analysts focus on this item is that they regard it as a
financial cushion: the time when Microsoft recognizes revenue on
its software licenses to corporations can sharply affect the
quarterly earnings. Recognizing more revenue in a particular
quarter can give a one-time lift to that quarter's earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft has three major segments: productivity applications
and software developer tools; Windows operating systems; and
consumer and other. Revenue from applications and developer tools
increased 28 percent to $2.8 billion in the December quarter. At
$2.44 billion, Windows revenue was up just 6 percent, and Microsoft
said the slower growth reflected reduced corporate PC purchases due
to preparing computer systems for the rollover to the year 2000,
and deferred operating system sales in anticipation of Windows
2000.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer and other includes learning and entertainment software,
PC input devices like mice and keyboards, training and
certification fees, consulting and the online services. Revenue for
these businesses in the December quarter was $872 million, up 23
percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
