u a BC-NASA-SHUTTLE-HNS &LR;      01-18 0424
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASA-SHUTTLE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSULATING TILES MAY BE STICKING POINT TO NEXT SHUTTLE MISSION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASA provisionally set Jan. 31 for the launching of its first
space shuttle flight of 2000, a bid to map the Earth's surface with
space-borne radar.
</P>
<P>
   Plans to launch the shuttle Endeavour at month's end will depend
on a reassessment of the adhesive used to bond dozens of
irregularly shaped insulating tiles to the spacecraft, said NASA
spokesman Bruce Buckingham.
</P>
<P>
   The issue arose when the shuttle Discovery returned to Earth
from its Hubble Space Telescope repair mission Dec. 27 with a tile
missing from its right wing flap.
</P>
<P>
   A post-flight analysis revealed the Discovery tile was applied
with an improper amount of adhesive, Buckingham said.
</P>
<P>
   During their formal review of mission preparations for Endeavour
at Kennedy Space Center on Tuesday, shuttle managers agreed to a
Jan. 31 liftoff if engineers can complete a reappraisal of the
bonds on similar tiles aboard Endeavour.
</P>
<P>
   Largely a review of paperwork supplied by the workers as
documentation when the tiles were originally applied, the appraisal
should take at least several more days, Buckingham said.
</P>
<P>
   The tiles and larger insulative blankets on the exterior of the
space shuttle protect it from the 3,000-degree temperatures
generated by friction during the shuttle's re-entry of the Earth's
atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   Once in orbit, Endeavour's astronauts plan to work
round-the-clock in teams for 11 days scanning the Earth's surface
with a large radar secured within the shuttle's payload bay.
</P>
<P>
   Two antennas, one extended over the side of the shuttle's cargo
bay on the tip of a 195-foot boom and a second within the ship will
collect and record the radar signal returns.
</P>
<P>
   After the flight, scientists on the ground plan to use computers
to convert the signals into three-dimensional maps.
</P>
<P>
   If successful, the effort should produce a map of unrivaled
accuracy of all the Earth's terrain between the arctic and
Antarctic circles.
</P>
<P>
   Originally scheduled for last September, Endeavour's was one of
three shuttle missions delayed last year.
</P>
<P>
   The space agency suspended shuttle flights after Columbia
experienced an electrical short seconds after liftoff.
</P>
<P>
   When the short was traced to chafed insulation on wiring in
Columbia's fuselage, shuttle managers ordered inspections and
repairs of the electrical conduit in all of the ships.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
