<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-18 21:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9621 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-R-AND-B-MUSIC-ART-3TA     01-18 0992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-AND-B-MUSIC-ART-3TAKES-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUT OF THE RUT AND INTO A NEW GROOVE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 23) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By BEN RATLIFF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As found on the Billboard charts and radio stations like New
York's Hot 97, today's R-and-B mostly denotes a tight formula:
single-string acoustic guitar licks over synthetic blipping beats
like an Atari Pong game, the airbrushed vocals of a lead singer
indignant over a sexual promise that's been withheld and a bland
group of backup singers taking the chorus in unison while the
leader sings sub-Stevie Wonder melisma.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the musical blueprints, as developed by producers like
Timbaland and Babyface, are fascinating _ but only until they are
copied to death. With such homogeneity, it's becoming very hard to
tell one performer from another in mainstream black music.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, D'Angelo's new single ``Untitled'' has just
been added to commercial playlists across the country, and it
sounds nothing like the above description. Slow and insinuating,
its vocals violate a cardinal rule of commercial music by being
mixed deep into the track.
</P>
<P>
   It's based on a live studio jam; it begins with a false start,
and it ends with an abrupt cut-off during a crescendo. In the
middle of formulaic, machinelike music that sounds as if it was
made by committee, you're suddenly presented with a mysterious
song, with handcrafted defects all over it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Untitled'' is a signal that can't be missed; something this
radical can't just drop out of the sky alone. There's a widening
groundswell of R-and-B artists _ and even some who fit more
naturally in the category of hip-hop _ who are sounding like an
antidote to the sameness problem: their records are more
well-rounded, more musicianly, more complete. They make a mature
music, and a family music, for living rooms, rather than for the
streets.
</P>
<P>
   In their subject matter there is room for self-doubt, anger,
beatitude, whimsy and religion _ not just slick come-ons or
aggressive bluster. It's increasingly album-oriented as opposed to
singles-oriented. Importantly, it marks a gradual return in black
pop to the use of instruments instead of electronics. And it isn't
even always sung in English.
</P>
<P>
   It's not just that some of these performers are infusing their
new music with 30-year-old grooves; they are expanding the entire
personality of R-and-B. Some, like D'Angelo and Maxwell, are rising
to the the challenge of becoming complete singer-songwriters; some
are beginning to look beyond the standard sound of American
R-and-B, adding jazz elements or reaching out to black music of
other cultures.
</P>
<P>
   Hip-hop is changing, too, with so-called alternative performers
like Mos Def, Q-Tip and the Roots suddenly making the best current
albums of the genre. Perhaps you could call it all-natural R-and-B,
referring to the patience and wisdom in this new music as well as
to the general absence of glossy pop hysteria and to the Afro hair
style affected by some of the performers.
</P>
<P>
   If the fluky breakout successes for this kind of music have
arrived in a trickle _ Arrested Development in the early '90s,
Maxwell in 1996, Erykah Badu in 1997 (Lauryn Hill's success in 1998
wasn't exactly unexpected) _ now seems like the moment for the
floodgates to open. Tastes have changed in its direction.
</P>
<P>
   Macy Gray's recent debut, ``On How Life Is,'' a lushly produced
album rich with 1970s Chaka Khan references _ but also containing
strong hints of more underground sources from the era, like the
singer Betty Davis _ has just been nominated for two Grammy awards;
it's a record for knowledgeable music fans as well as casual radio
listeners. Angie Stone's promising debut record, ``Black Diamond,''
has slowly gained sales and radio play since its release four
months ago.
</P>
<P>
   And D'Angelo's long-awaited new album, ``Voodoo''
(Cheebasound/Virgin V2-48499), to be released on Tuesday, could be
the succes d'estime that proves the force of this new music: it is
a largely unslick, stubbornly idiosyncratic and genuinely great
album that has already produced two hit singles.
</P>
<P>
   Official names haven't stuck to any of these artists who
somewhat defy the radio formulas. Neo-soul is too reductive; rare
groove, as it's often called in England, is too record
collector-ish. ``I've been called alternative, retro, all kinds of
things like that,'' said the singer, guitarist and producer Raphael
Saadiq, formerly of the band Toni Toni Tone and now of a new band,
Lucy Pearl, whose first album comes out in May.
</P>
<P>
   For a decade, Saadiq has combined old R-and-B with current
production sounds and whiffs of hip-hop, and two years ago Toni
Toni Tone finally broke up, a victim of radio's narrowness. ``Maybe
they need to have a new category, `R-R-and-B,''' he said, ``real
rhythm `n' blues, for music that has a lot of feeling going into
it, almost like underground R-and-B.''
</P>
<P>
   Saadiq's dream for a new radio format is all music by bands, as
opposed to music with electronic rhythm sections. ``Call it `hot
real music' or something,'' he suggested. ``I think a lot more
people would start playing instruments as a result.''
</P>
<P>
   Wherever there are twists on the current formulas of black
music, there are only euphemisms to describe it. First, there's
that umbrella term ``urban'': no record company or chartmaker wants
to own up to segregating music by race, so a sociological category
serves instead. One also hears the term ``progressive,'' which
means music that can be liked beyond teendom: nobody wants to lose
a share of the enormous, heavy-spending youth market for black
music by using that taboo word, adult. And, finally, there is the
term that has lost all its flavor yet continues to be used in the
business: alternative.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Alternative, in this context, denotes music that appeals to
black and nonblack, male and female, brand-new and retro tastes.
Here you see the first confusion: what's so alternative about a
potential audience that wide? But buried deeper in that confusion
is some cultural alchemy, a point at which music made by black
artists ceases to be ``black music'' and their songs are not
suitable for black radio; performers like Lenny Kravitz, Me'Shell
Ndegeocello and Dionne Farris have fallen into this trap.
</P>
<P>
   One ought to avoid calling this music ``alternative'' outside
the argumentative purposes of this article. Black artists tend to
distance themselves from the word and its connotations of white
performers, rock's musical ingredients and the aesthetic of
self-marginalizing. But the word still links to a pressing issue.
</P>
<P>
   It remains difficult to get this new between-the-cracks music on
the radio and in the hands of mainstream American record buyers.
Since the Telecommunications Act of 1996, corporate consolidation
within the radio industry has severely reduced adventurous
programming. The number of current records on an average commercial
black station's playlist, said Tom Bracamontes, senior vice
president of promotion at Virgin records, has dropped by nearly a
third. ``Not only is music on the fringes of R-and-B going to lose
out,'' said Bracamontes, ``but even regular mainstream R-and-B is
going to lose out.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are ways of defeating the rules of the system,
through the long-term effort of record labels and performers
themselves. Virgin took a year to market the French band Les
Nubians to black stations across the country with an adult
audience, and the life of the band's single, ``Mekeda,'' has been
extended: it's now being pitched to hip-hop mix shows.
</P>
<P>
   The Roots continue to perform incessantly, even setting up shop
every week in various clubs to present shows that act as workshops.
The last few years have also seen a growing number of R-and-B
artists turn away from the system and form their own labels to
release their new material _ a roll call that includes not only the
Artist Formerly Known as Prince, but also Saadiq, Dionne Farris and
the new singer N'Dambi.
</P>
<P>
   The shabby state of live performance is also forcing change.
Last year one could witness the spectacle of the singer Ginuwine,
who had a top-10 R-and-B radio hit at the time, performing to a
half-empty audience at the Manhattan club Tramps. Behind him, an ad
hoc band copied his recordings exactly; there was a drummer, but a
rhythm machine anchored the grooves.
</P>
<P>
   One got the sense that Ginuwine could be an exciting performer
if only live performance made more business sense to him, and the
club would be full if the audience for black music had a little
more faith that live shows in general were worthwhile.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, the drummer for the Roots, Ahmir Thompson (aka
Questlove), has started to pop up on all sorts of records, from
Erykah Badu's ``Baduizm'' to the Congolese-French group Zap Mama's
``Amazone''; his participation seems to ensure that a record will
sound both new and different, and there are sure to be others like
him in his wake. Truth be told, he's often too metronomic, holding
one pattern steady through almost an entire song. But the
difference in hearing music with a human drummer again is
immeasurable _ it's warmer, more vulnerable, more interesting.
</P>
<P>
   It's Thompson's drumming that threads together the songs on
D'Angelo's ``Voodoo.'' A full five years (an eternity in the career
of a black pop artist) after his first album, ``Brown Sugar,''
D'Angelo (Michael D'Angelo Archer) took two years of daily
recording sessions to construct his new album, yet anyone who has
heard the stories of his studio indulgences may be surprised by the
album's streamlined economy.
</P>
<P>
   He spent that time establishing a telepathic live feel between
the members of his band, which included, aside from Thompson, the
jazz trumpeter Roy Hargrove, the jazz guitarist Charlie Hunter and
Saadiq. At their best, the record's songs begin without fanfare, as
if they're drifting into hearing range from the floor below. The
main evidence of studio indulgence is the heavy multitracking of
D'Angelo's voice: you hear seven or eight D'Angelos, in falsetto,
muttering, chanting, out of sync; they soar freely atop the music
like doves in an aviary.
</P>
<P>
   The album's first single, ``Left and Right,'' hedged bets: it
was the only track that used hip-hop, and it brought in the rap
stars Method Man and Redman. Though the song is a shrewd effort to
have it both ways, retaining the slinky, subtle feel of D'Angelo's
music while incorporating hip-hop in its second half, it's also the
album's weakest track. The rest of ``Voodoo'' is not, per se, an
attempt to bring back the music of the '70s; it's an attempt to
recall a time when long tracks and unique group sounds were
radioworthy popular culture, and pop radio wasn't so segmented by
race.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews, D'Angelo has described it as evoking the ``second
phase'' of musicians like Marvin Gaye, Sly Stone and Curtis
Mayfield _ the point where they had already had success with
mainstream pop and were ready to experiment a bit. It says much
about today's competitive record and radio business that D'Angelo
was ready to make that shift on his second record.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Since the '60s, paradigm-shift moments in black popular culture
have frequently been announced. Some of this new ferment seems
reminiscent of the late 1980s, when the writer Trey Ellis, in an
influential article in the literary journal Callaloo, proclaimed a
culturally mulatto ``New Black Aesthetic.''
</P>
<P>
   He pointed to bands like Living Color and Fishbone, filmmakers
like Spike Lee and the Hudlin brothers, playwrights like George C.
Wolfe _ all of whom expressed a ``casually nonchalant'' attitude
about race; these were artists liberated by the feeling that they
did not have to perform according to what was expected from them as
blacks.
</P>
<P>
   But while the dominant strain of Ellis's essay is of black
artists joyfully crashing the temples of white culture _ Living
Color's freedom to play rock `n' roll, Tracy Chapman's to play
coffeehouse folk and so on _ the emphasis of the current crop of
``R-R-and-B'' musicians is to rediscover what was so good about the
black music of their youth, and how it was incorporated into the
wider scope of American culture.
</P>
<P>
   But one victory begets another, and it seems likely that more
barriers will be broken down; possibly the next step for these
artists will be to find meaningful ways to connect American black
pop with the rest of their cultural heritage, as well as with black
music of other cultures.
</P>
<P>
   Jazz musicians have already hooked up with Maxwell and D'Angelo;
Lauryn Hill has apparently expressed interest in working with the
protean Brazilian musician and cultural hero Carlinhos Brown; she
and D'Angelo both worked in the studio last year with the Nigerian
bandleader Femi Kuti. Instead of dwelling on the limitations and
frustrations of the idea of alternative black pop, it might be
better to focus on its positive side: its incredible capaciousness.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine a listener-supported radio station or Internet station
of the near future that played not only Macy Gray and D'Angelo, but
also their sources _ Curtis Mayfield, Jimi Hendrix, Marvin Gaye,
Rufus. And also Al Green and Shirley Caesar (gospel music, and in
fact all religious devotion, is ``alternative'' these days); Billie
Holiday, John Coltrane and Betty Carter (jazz _ misunderstood and
underappreciated, yet one of America's dearest notions _ remains
our ultimate alternative music); the sweet Afro-Peruvian grooves of
Susana Baca, the Brazilian funk of Jorge Ben; Cassandra Wilson's
sophisticated projects of folk Americana.
</P>
<P>
   Black pop has been a producer's game for the last two decades;
now it's musicians who are starting to shape a wider aesthetic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
