</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JETS-OWNER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON DAY 1, JETS' OWNER ZEROS IN ON PARCELLS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Minutes after being approved by the NFL as the Jets'
new owner, Robert Wood Johnson IV promised to make a decision on
Bill Parcells' status by the weekend, find a new home for the team
by 2008 and said that he would have a hands-on approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a critical time of the year, but to go over the whole
landscape of coaching is going to take more than 24 hours,''
Johnson said at a news conference at the Waldorf-Astoria. ``I think
we owe it to the fans to explore all options. It's hard to find
good coaches. There's only a handful of them. You've got to make
sure you make a careful decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson _ ``you can call me Woody'' _ said that if Parcells
declined to return as coach, he wanted him to still have a major
role with the team. He has met or spoken with Parcells every day
since last Wednesday, including a three-hour talk last Friday. He
planned to meet with him again Wednesday or Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is not the easiest person to read,'' Johnson said. ``In
fact, he is very difficult to read. But he is a quick study, very
direct, very honest.''
</P>
<P>
   Is Johnson optimistic he can convince Parcells to return?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love to have him coach,'' Johnson said. ``We will know _ I
guarantee we will know _ by the end of the week.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was vague about who else might coach the team. Parcells
is thought to believe that Al Groh, the linebackers coach, should
succeed him. Groh and most of the coaches are in Mobile, Ala.,
during Senior Bowl week. They will return Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill has a very, very high opinion of Al Groh,'' Johnson said.
While Johnson has read various reports that Groh was a likely
candidate, he said that Parcells had not brought that up.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I can see their relationship is one of trust,'' Johnson
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think with any good leader selection, you have to look at
all opportunities. So we will be very careful in trying to assess
what is best for the team and the fans. We will look inside and
outside.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson admitted that if he goes outside the organization, there
would be less continuity.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson suggested he would be a sleeves-rolled-up owner, for
now.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are two things that I have to do in a short period of
time,'' he said. ``One is to get the operational elements in shape,
and I have talked to Steve Gutman, who has been at the Jets for
over 20 years and he has agreed to stay on. He is a terrific guy.
He knows more about the NFL than almost anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was less talkative about the Bill Belichick situation.
He said because it was a ``semilegal'' situation he was leaving it
in the hands of Commissioner Paul Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was clear about the Jets' move from the Meadowlands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eight years from now,'' he said, ``they will be playing
somewhere else.'' That is when the team's lease expires.
</P>
<P>
   Before the league's owners voted unanimously to have him join
their club, Johnson told the finance committee of his commitment to
moving the Jets into their own stadium.
</P>
<P>
   According to Tagliabue, Johnson spoke of ``getting that last
ounce of adrenaline out of the players onto the field sometimes
falls to the fans as the 12th man, and he feels very strongly that
if they had their own stadium, that would be something that would
energize the Jets' fans even more.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, asked at a news conference about renewing the lease,
Johnson minced no words: ``I don't think that is going to be one of
our options of choice.''
</P>
<P>
   He brought up the Jets' long-standing gripe that they play 16
road games because they have always performed in someone else's
stadium. Shea Stadium was built for the Mets and Giants Stadium, of
course, was built for the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every game they have played for the last 39-plus years have
been away games,'' Johnson said. ``They have never had the
home-field advantage, so to speak. So I think this is going to be a
critical decision we look at down the line after we get some of
these other questions answered.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson wore a gray suit and contrasting Jets-green tie as he
fielded more questions in 20 minutes from the news media than the
late news media-shy owner, Leon Hess, did in 37 years with the
team. Hess died last May, and his estate sold the team for $635
million.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson is the Jets' third owner. They were created as the
Titans along with the American Football League in 1960. Harry
Wismer, a well-known sportscaster of the day, was the president. He
ran a ticket office out of his New York apartment and often did not
pay the players. The league actually met several payrolls before
the team landed in bankruptcy court.
</P>
<P>
   From there, five men, brought together by their common interests
in horse racing, banded together to buy the team for $1 million in
1963. Hess was one of the original five.
</P>
</TEXT>
