<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-18 21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9630 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-CARMINA-BURANA-COX     01-18 1406
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARMINA-BURANA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    '''Carmina Burana''': A choral classic
 &HT;    By Charles Passy
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Here's what the legendary conductor
Leopold Stokowski had to say about Carl Orff's ``Carmina Burana''
when he introduced the work to New York and Boston audiences in
1954: ``I believe that Orff's genius _ an extraordinarily personal
blending of pagan and modern feeling _ will be recognized by future
generations as a major departure in the development of the art of
music.''
</P>
<P>
   And here's what Florida Philharmonic Music Director James Judd
has to say on the occasion of the orchestra's performances of the
choral classic this week: ``It's a hugely wonderful, empty work.
It's sheer entertainment.''
</P>
<P>
   In a way, both conductors are right. ``Carmina Burana,'' which
premiered in 1937 when the German-born Orff was 42, is now
recognized as one of the quintessential musical testaments of the
20th century. Combining the ritualistic modernism of Stravinsky
with an almost minimalist aesthetic, it served as a model for
numerous other composers, including such greats from the late 20th
century as Philip Glass and Henryk Gorecki.
</P>
<P>
   But it's a work of disarming simplicity and ribald pleasures _
and thus one of a handful of classical pieces that have truly
crossed over into the pop mainstream. You can hear ``Carmina
Burana'' almost everywhere these days: in soundtracks to movies
ranging from ``Excalibur'' to ``The Doors'' to ``The General's
Daughter.'' In dance clubs, where it's often mixed with a disco
beat. Even Michael Jackson used it to open his ``Dangerous'' tour.
</P>
<P>
   And if you caught the trailer to the South Park movie, that's
Carl Orff's music that was accompanying the news of Kenny's death.
Of course, ``Carmina Burana'' has become such a fixture in movie
trailers, its usage in this instance was intended to mock its usage
elsewhere. It's like a sure-fire way of saying, ``Attention must be
paid.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it goes to the same reason that people like Wagner,''
says Dan Goldwasser, an editor of the Soundtrack.net Web site.
``It's large, powerful music that captures the essence of an
emotion.''
</P>
<P>
   But most of the listeners who have heard ``Carmina Burana'' in a
pop context _ and even then, they're probably hearing only the
opening chorus, O Fortuna, its most famous excerpt _ are likely to
know little about the full, hourlong work or its composer. Indeed,
even classical buffs may be caught off guard when they hear details
about Orff's past, including his connections to Hitler's regime and
his ground-breaking educational methodology combining music and
movement.
</P>
<P>
   And if anyone bothered to read an English translation of the
lyrics to ``Carmina Burana,'' which are in Latin and what's called
Middle High German, they might need to brace themselves. They're
not exactly G-rated.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the news went out that all these commercial forces are
using this obscene work, it would be rather amusing,'' says Judd.
``An obscene work by a Nazi, no less.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Carmina Burana'' is based on a group of poems from the 13th
century; the title translates as Songs of Beuren, a reference to a
region in Germany where they supposedly originated. Written by
defrocked monks and minstrels, they are hearty tales of love, sex,
drinking and gambling _ the very stuff that defined medieval times.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Orff (1895-1982) was hardly that adventurous. A
devout Roman Catholic and lifelong resident of Munich, he was a man
who, in the words of one of his musical associates, ``loved the
simplicity of life.''
</P>
<P>
   ``His house was not filled with precious antiques, but farmer's
furniture,'' says John van Kesteren, a world-renowned tenor, now
based in Tequesta, who worked with Orff numerous times.
</P>
<P>
   But Orff had a distinct musical vision. Although clearly a
product of the 20th century, he was not a modernist per se and
refused to follow the atonal path of Berg, Webern and Schoenberg.
Instead, he preferred a sonic world of almost primitive passion:
While he was clearly influenced by Stravinsky in this regard _ it's
no accident the Florida Philharmonic will play ``The Rite of
Spring'' on the same program _ he was also drawn to non-Western
music, especially the rhythmically rich African and Indonesian
traditions.
</P>
<P>
   Orff established his career in the 1920s when he created the
Orff-Schulwerk method, an educational discipline that combined
music, dance and gymnastics. Even to this day, it remains a popular
way to introduce children to the arts: ``Orff instruments'' are
frequently found in kindergartens and pre-schools.
</P>
<P>
   In the '30s, Orff sought to expand his concepts, bringing them
to the stage for an adult audience. Despite the fact that it's
typically presented today in a concert setting, Orff always
intended ``Carmina Burana'' to be a work of theater, a ``scenic
cantata'' as he called it, making full use of dance and scenery.
The piece is subtitled, ``Profane songs for singers and vocal
chorus with instruments and magical pictures.''
</P>
<P>
   But because of the strength of the music _ Orff set about 25 of
the 250 poems in the manuscript _ orchestras have been able to
dispense with the visual accompaniment. Responding to the primal
message of the text, Orff created a ferocious animal of a score.
The appeal can be summarized in a word: ``'Carmina' has the
rhythms,'' says van Kesteren of the pulsating piece. And given the
emphasis that pop music has placed on rhythm over melody, the tenor
says it's no surprise that it's found a place in the mainstream.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the German public always appreciated Orff, particularly
the Nazis, who found the pagan element in his music very
``un-German.'' Van Kesteren believes that Orff wrote the work
partly as a diatribe against the Nazis. ``He saw it as a fight
against the establishment. The Nazis were very clean . . . Orff was
much more interested in having fun,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Orff did make his peace with the German government and
accepted musical commissions from Hitler's henchmen, even if he
tried to distance himself from the Nazis after World War II. Van
Kesteren believes, ``Orff was a free-thinking man . . . He was
neutral as far as he told me,'' but he adds that the composer might
have gone along with the Nazis for the sake of survival.
</P>
<P>
   Is ``Carmina Burana'' a challenge to perform? Not really, says
Judd, who explains that the music has a blunt,
straight-from-the-page quality. ``It's in rather block form,'' he
adds, noting that the rhythms rarely change mid-section. The
biggest difficulty the conductor has is finding a good children's
chorus _ again, Orff's roots were in education, so it's no surprise
he included a place for young singers in ``Carmina.'' And the
conductor notes that the solo vocal parts _ for soprano, tenor and
baritone _ are ``grotesquely high,'' placing some unique casting
demands.
</P>
<P>
   Van Kesteren adds that tenors often make the mistake of trying
to ``finesse'' the work. In contrast, Orff wrote the part that way
precisely because he wanted it to sound crude. ``It should not be
sung beautifully,'' he emphasizes, noting he just accepted an
engagement to sing it in Ottawa next year.
</P>
<P>
   While Carmina established Orff's international reputation, it
was hardly the end of the line for the composer, who lived well
into his 80s. The choral work became the basis of a trilogy,
``Trionfi,'' that included ``Catulli Carmina'' (''Songs of
Catullus,'' 1943) and ``Trionfo di Afrodite'' (''The Triumph of
Aphrodite,'' 1953). There were other choral works and operas as
well, but nothing that enjoyed the reputation of Carmina, which was
also the basis for a 1959 ballet by John Butler and a 1970s film by
Jean-Pierre Ponnelle (Van Kesteren appeared in it). And then there
are the ancillary usages _ in movies, TV, etc.
</P>
<P>
   It's gotten to the point that filmmakers have started asking
composers to create Carmina clones in order to avoid paying
royalties, explains Dan Goldwasser, the soundtrack expert. Thought
you heard Carl Orff's score in the Civil War movie Glory? Actually,
it's a knock-off by Titanic composer James Horner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes it sounds like it, but it isn't it. They change four
notes,'' says Goldwasser.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Passy writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla. E-mail: charlespassy(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-18-00 2139EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000118.0371 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-18 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9631 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-SIMON-RATTLE-MUSIC-2T     01-18 1249
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIMON-RATTLE-MUSIC-2TAKES-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAESTRO OF THE MOMENT AND STILL GROWING  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 23) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JAMES R. OESTREICH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If, as Simon Rattle likes to say, conductors don't really become
competent before their 60s, what might the bidding war be like in
2015?
</P>
<P>
   Sir Simon, who turned 45 on Wednesday, was for a decade or so
considered the heir apparent to succeed Seiji Ozawa as music
director of the Boston Symphony Orchestra in the event of a
vacancy. In recent years, as the likelihood of that eventuality
kept receding into an indefinite future, both Sir Simon and the
orchestra seemed to cool toward the prospect, and he was avidly
courted by the Philadelphia Orchestra to succeed Wolfgang
Sawallisch in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Then last June, a day after it was announced that Ozawa would
finally leave Boston in 2002 to direct the Vienna State Opera, the
Berlin Philharmonic elected Sir Simon (italics)its(end italics)
music director as of the same year.
</P>
<P>
   And these were only the more prominent bidders for his services:
not bad for a fledgling maestro. Then again, in experience if not
in age, he is anything but a fledgling.
</P>
<P>
   He conducted the City of Birmingham Symphony Orchestra from 1980
to 1998 with a single-mindedness and dedication that went out of
fashion decades ago, and he is widely credited with having
transformed it from a provincial band into, on any given night, one
of the finest and most adventurous ensembles in England. He is also
a principal guest conductor of the period-instrument Orchestra of
the Age of Enlightenment, a frequent presence at the Glyndebourne
Festival and elsewhere in Britain, a recent favorite of the Vienna
Philharmonic and the Salzburg Festival, and the darling of EMI
Classics.
</P>
<P>
   The big loser in the recent bidding war, at least for the
moment, appears to have been the Philadelphia Orchestra. But
presumably no hard feelings will erupt amid the musical cataclysms
when Sir Simon conducts the expanded orchestra, a large chorus and
vocal soloists in Schoenberg's ``Gurrelieder'' on Monday evening at
Carnegie Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be an encounter group,'' Sir Simon said, referring not
so much to any potential friction as to the sheer crowd of
performers destined for the Carnegie stage, which will be extended
for the purpose. Sir Simon, for his part, voices regret at the
missed connection in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apart from the point where I decided to leave Birmingham,
(italics)not(end italics) to go to Philadelphia, to decide that
this was not for me, was one of the hardest calls,'' Sir Simon said
in his room at a hotel near Carnegie Hall on a recent visit to New
York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether, when it came to it, they actually would have asked
me, I don't know,'' he quickly added, perhaps remembering the
etiquette of such courtships. Generally, public discussion of
candidates and especially of offers made is conspiratorially
avoided to keep the maestro ultimately chosen from feeling like a
consolation prize.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph H. Kluger, the president of the Philadelphia Orchestra,
gave the party line: ``We've had a lot of exploratory conversations
with a lot of conductors. In the case of Rattle, we have a close
relationship with him, and we are pleased that he is committed to
returning in the spring of 2002 and on a regular basis
thereafter.''
</P>
<P>
   In an odd anticlimax, after that once intimate connection, the
Boston Symphony seems to have played no part in Sir Simon's
thinking. ``I don't think anyone really has a clue what goes on in
Boston,'' he said of the orchestra he conducts from Thursday
through Saturday at Symphony Hall in Boston. ``It's a mystery to me
after all these years.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Volpe, who became managing director of the Boston Symphony
in 1997, said: ``I don't know the whole history, but he's an
important conductor we've had a relationship with. His life is
changing, and our lives are changing with Seiji's departure, but we
hope to continue a relationship subject to his willingness to
conduct here.'' Be that as it may, no Rattle appearances are
scheduled there after this week.
</P>
<P>
   For him, in any case, Sir Simon explains, the choice came down
to America versus Europe. American wooers had anticipated that his
two young sons, Sacha and Eliot, now living in San Francisco with
his first wife, the American soprano Elise Ross, would be part of
the draw. But Sir Simon points out that by the time any American
post would open up, in that eventful year 2002, his older son,
Sacha, will be approaching college age and probably headed
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   As Sir Simon's concentrated activity in Birmingham showed, he
does not deal in half measures or take his responsibilities
lightly. And he is aware of the added social obligations that fall
to a music director in America: at a minimum, the need to cultivate
corporate sponsorship and community support. In fact, he sees the
role as much more, something approaching ``social engineering,''
though he backed off the term.
</P>
<P>
   ``An orchestra in a modern city has to be somehow a moral
center, a center for healing these desperately divided places,'' he
said in a monologue delivered mostly sotto voce and with long
pauses for rumination. ``And with all the wonderful music-making
that there is in this country, it is still way off the periphery of
most people's thought. It's not on any kind of political or social
agenda, and it must be.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realized that to do this, I would have to live in America
and visit Europe for two or three weeks a year. If I wanted to have
a life and a marriage, and some kind of interior life as well, it
was a natural choice between the two continents, and I chose
Europe, rightly or wrongly.''
</P>
<P>
   There was also a ``philosophical point,'' Sir Simon added: ``I
wanted for now to be closer to the source of the music.'' Read
Vienna and Berlin. So Sir Simon, a native of Liverpool, intends to
remain in London with his second wife, Candice Allen, also an
American, as he establishes his musical home in Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   Not that only sweetness and light await him there. Indeed,
alarmist reports have appeared in the English press about the
parlous state of the orchestra and its financial base.
</P>
<P>
   ``They may make the sweetest noise on earth and symbolize all
that is enviable in German cultural affluence,'' Norman Lebrecht
wrote in a typical lather in The Daily Telegraph in London last
October, ``but behind the gleam of golden instruments the Berlin
Philharmonic are not a happy band.''
</P>
<P>
   Lebrecht went on to cite various causes or effects: the
announced departure next year of the longtime intendant, Elmar
Weingarten; the defection of several top players among the total of
nine vacancies; and reduced earnings due in large part to a decline
in recording projects and record sales, all within a climate of
greater governmental scrutiny and straitened public subsidies for
the arts in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   At the mere mention of alarmist reports, even before the name of
Lebrecht, the author of the ultimate alarmist tract, ``Who Killed
Classical Music?,'' had been raised, Sir Simon said with a touch of
sarcasm: ``You've certainly never read anything by Norman before,
have you? Those Brits who've learned the meaning of the word
`Schadenfreude' enjoy it. There's no doubt that there are problems
to solve. At the moment, it's not a very well-organized ship. It
plays wonderfully, but it's rather chaotic. Yet that's partly what
this job is about.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-18-00 2141EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000118.0372 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-18 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9632 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-ASTRONOMY-COX     01-18 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASTRONOMY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Look to stars for stunning sky sights
 &HT;    By Michael Alicea
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ If you got a telescope over the
holidays, you've probably spent the past couple of weeks trying to
figure out just where to point it. Here's some help.
</P>
<P>
   And no, we don't mean the moon. Let's go farther out.
</P>
<P>
   No . . . past Jupiter and Saturn . . .
</P>
<P>
   Pluto and Charon?
</P>
<P>
   Nothing to see there anyhow. Farther!
</P>
<P>
   Let's find something unusual to test your new gift. The winter
sky has a few stars to offer:
</P>
<P>
   _ Mu Cephei: This variable star in the constellation Cepheus is
named for the mythical king of Joppa, husband to Cassiopeia and
father to Andromeda.
</P>
<P>
   Although Mu Cephei isn't one of the brightest objects in the
sky, it easily can be called one of the most alluring for its color
and for the fact that it is a variable star, which means that its
apparent brightness changes over time. Some variable stars can
change their brightness over a matter of hours, but in Mu Cephei's
case, it takes some time to see the difference _ which is about
four times brighter at its maximum than at its minimum.
</P>
<P>
   Mu Cephei is a red hypergiant star. It is the largest star we
know of in the night sky. It has a radius 2,536 times that of our
own star, Sol. If Mu Cephei were where Sol is, it would fill the
solar system to the orbit of Saturn! On top of that, it is 38,000
times brighter than Sol. We should be glad it lies 1,550 light
years away.
</P>
<P>
   Sir William Herschel named Mu Cephei the Garnet Star, for
reasons that will become apparent once you look at this deep red
gem.
</P>
<P>
   The constellation Cepheus, where Mu Cephei resides, is in the
northern sky during the winter months, between the constellations
Ursa Minor and Cassiopeia.
</P>
<P>
   _ Capella: Latin for ``little she-goat,'' Capella is also known
as Alpha Aurigae.
</P>
<P>
   Capella is the sixth brightest star in the sky, but it really
isn't one star at all. It's two stars, both yellow giants _ 16
times bigger than our sun. But don't strain your eyes looking for
the twin, it's not visible even through your telescope.
</P>
<P>
   Capella is important to navigators here on Earth, as it is the
closest bright star to the North Star, Polaris in Ursa Minor, and
it can be seen for at least part of the night every month.
</P>
<P>
   Capella lies within the constellation Auriga, which is in the
northeastern sky.
</P>
<P>
   _ Mira: Mira, ``beautiful'' in Latin, is a red giant star within
the constellation Cetus the Whale.
</P>
<P>
   Humans have been watching this star for centuries. It expands
and contracts _ shrinking and cooling over a period that lasts 332
days. Each time it expands, it becomes a stunning deep red star,
and the brightest one in the constellation. At its minimum, Mira
cannot be seen by the unaided eye, so telescopes do come in handy
after all.
</P>
<P>
   Mira is 220 light years away and can be up to 500 times more
luminous than our sun. If Mira were where Sol is, we wouldn't be
here at all. It is 300 times more massive than Sol, so it would
fill in our system to the orbit of Mars.
</P>
<P>
   Mira, and Cetus, are in the southwestern sky.
</P>
<P>
   _ Betelgeuse: Betelgeuse, ``shoulder of the giant,'' or ``hand
of al-jauza'' _ depending on whom you ask _ can also be known as
the ``Martial Star.'' By any name, this orange-red supergiant star
lies in the constellation Orion and could possibly be the most
recognized star after Sirius _ if only for its ``Hollywood'' name.
</P>
<P>
   Betelgeuse is the first star to be seen as a disc _ not as a
point of light _ by the Hubble Space Telescope on March 3, 1995.
This would make one think that it is MASSIVE, but it's teeny
compared with Mu Cephei _ only 630 times bigger than Sol. That
would make it as big as the orbit of Jupiter if placed in Sol's
stead, but it is 60,000 times more luminous than Sol. Take that Mu
Cephei!
</P>
<P>
   Betelgeuse, sad to say, is on its way out of stellar existence.
It is thought to be the next star that will go supernova in our
galaxy. When will that happen? Who knows. But, get in your gazes
while it's still intact.
</P>
<P>
   Orion rises in the eastern sky throughout the winter season.
</P>
<P>
   _ While in Orion: The constellation Orion has one more wonder to
offer: The Orion Nebula.
</P>
<P>
   The Orion Nebula is a large body of rarified gas, thinned out
and less dense gas, that is fueling the birth of new stars within
its boundaries. In fact, we can observe most nebulae only because
of the young, hot stars lighting them up from the inside.
</P>
<P>
   The Orion Nebula will appear in a hazy patch of three ``stars''
just below the line of three stars that form Orion's ``belt.'' In
the older illustrated maps of the heavens, this region is
represented as Orion's sword, hanging from the belt. In your
telescope, some haziness will surround the stars, but the general
shape of the nebula will be most apparent. It is a beautiful thing
to see.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't forget: On Thursday, South Florida _ and the entire
country _ will be treated to a total lunar eclipse beginning at
9:08 p.m. The moon will move deeper into the earth's shadow layers,
until it reaches totality at 11:09 p.m. At this time, the moon will
appear reddish-copper by the light of the earthshine reaching the
lunar surface. Look for stars normally washed out by the full
moonlight to appear for a cameo during this time.
</P>
<P>
   The moon will slip back into the inner and outer shadows
beginning at 12:20 a.m. Friday morning, and finally become full
again at 1:23 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Enjoy this spectacle. It won't happen again until May of 2003.
</P>
<P>
   Happy hunting.
</P>
<P>
   Got a question about the heavens? Send it to Astronomy, The Palm
Beach Post, 2751 S. Dixie Highway, West Palm Beach, Fla. 33405, or
e-mail michaelalicea (at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
