<DOCNO> NYT20000118.0373 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-18 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9633 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-SIMON-RATTLE-MUSIC-2N     01-18 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIMON-RATTLE-MUSIC-2NDTAKE-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: is about.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is also about change, in repertory and in the ways the
orchestra does business as it enters the 21st century. ``It's been
made abundantly clear that they feel they cannot simply dig the
same old gold mine, however wonderful,'' Sir Simon said, mixing
metaphors with abandon. ``They need more feathers in their
plumage.'' But not much else, evidently, has been made clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``The job is like being the pope,'' Sir Simon said, ``except for
the celibacy, I (italics)hope.(end italics) Nobody talks to you. I
have no contract. Nobody mentioned to me what the job description
was, how many concerts, what I'd be paid, if I'd be paid, what my
rights were, what my rights weren't. And it was just absolutely
considered, as it has always been, that you would be so thrilled to
have the job that you wouldn't ask.''
</P>
<P>
   To this day, he says, he does not know what he will be paid, but
neither is he worried. ``We conductors are all paid
(italics)fine,''(end italics) he said.
</P>
<P>
   In a concerted attempt to get a life outside conducting, he
plans to curtail his activities outside Berlin. ``It's really very
simple,'' he said. ``I don't want to work much more than seven
months of the year, just because I don't think you can stay
creative. In my 30s possibly, but now I need more and more time,
and more and more time to do things that aren't music, to read and
to discover.''
</P>
<P>
   He expects the Berlin job to require about five months a year,
including the annual opera performances in Salzburg at Easter. For
the rest, he plans to continue his work with the Vienna
Philharmonic, which he calls a great learning experience. In fact,
he is scheduled to record all the Beethoven symphonies with the
Vienna Philharmonic in 2002 for EMI, a prior commitment that a
record-hungry Berlin Philharmonic must surely eye wistfully, even
though it may counter with yet another Beethoven cycle of its own,
led by its current maestro, Claudio Abbado, on Deutsche Grammophon.
Sir Simon also intends to continue his work with the Orchestra of
the Age of Enlightenment and the Philadelphia Orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   His work as an orchestra builder in Birmingham was altogether
admirable, and widely recognized as such. In Berlin matters will
probably be different. Whatever disarray the orchestra may now be
experiencing, it persists in the public mind as a great orchestra
in little need of rebuilding.
</P>
<P>
   ``The possibilities are so enormous,'' Sir Simon himself said.
``Unless I haven't been listening carefully enough, there isn't
another orchestra that has such individual soloistic skill in
depth. If they had any more technique, they'd be an international
menace.''
</P>
<P>
   But he also insists that there is never an end to orchestra
building: ``Just like a house, many things need constant
maintenance, and some of it is as basic as daily oral hygiene.''
</P>
<P>
   However all of that may be, in Berlin Sir Simon's reputation is
likely to ride most heavily on the quality of his interpretations,
and here, his history is spottier. ``Sometimes he smothered the
music with enthusiasm, and sometimes that enthusiasm brought
results so stupendously good that no one would have thought it
possible,'' the English critic Nicholas Kenyon wrote in 1987 in his
book ``Simon Rattle: The Making of a Conductor.''
</P>
<P>
   Kenyon, who is now the director of the BBC Proms in London,
still holds much the same opinion. ``The performances either work
or they don't,'' he said from London the other day. ``Some of them
are incredibly exciting, but there isn't a comfortable level of
reliability.''
</P>
<P>
   This listener recalls only one of the incredibly exciting
variety _ a Mahler Seventh Symphony with the Vienna Philharmonic in
1995 at the Concertgebouw in Amsterdam _ and several instances of
suffocation, whether by enthusiasm or calculation. This, at any
rate, appears to be the prime area for whatever learning and growth
Sir Simon has yet to accomplish.
</P>
<P>
   With so much attention devoted to exotic repertory early in his
career, he was admittedly slow to come to the bread-and-butter
Germanic repertory. And although his work in Vienna and Berlin has
done much to remedy that gap, Kenyon points out that Sir Simon has
yet to devote significant attention to Bruckner, so beloved of
Berlin. Then again, Kenyon suggests, ``perhaps it's time to give
Bruckner a rest.''
</P>
<P>
   But he rightly points to another area in which Sir Simon is
likely to make his mark in Berlin. ``He could change concert life
there,'' Kenyon said. And indeed, Sir Simon went far beyond
orchestra building in Birmingham with his programming and repertory
adventures, his audience development and his fostering of
contemporary music.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he plays into Berlin as a new cultural center, there is
quite a lot he can do,'' Kenyon said. ``He can do what Abbado was
sort of expected to do but never did. He can address the issue of
how we are going to run a symphony orchestra in a major European
capital in the 21st century.''
</P>
<P>
   And once all that has been achieved? ``To come to America,'' Sir
Simon said, ``would have been something either for a younger man or
for an older man.'' In, say, 2015, as a fully ripe and wise
maestro?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
