<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-18 21:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9634 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-JEBBUSH-EVERGLADES-CO     01-18 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JEBBUSH-EVERGLADES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush proposes $2.3 billion Everglades plan but leaves gaps
unfilled
 &HT;    By Robert P. King
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   EVERGLADES NATIONAL PARK, Fla. _ Drawing cheers from
environmentalists, but leaving some key questions unanswered, Gov.
Jeb Bush outlined a $2.3 billion plan Tuesday for financing more
than half the money Florida will need to help restore the
Everglades.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he opposes paying for the plan with higher property
taxes, except as a last resort. But he'd consider allowing water
managers to impose fees on the gallons people and businesses use.
</P>
<P>
   The only certainty in Bush's proposal is his call for the state
to spend $1.25 billion by 2010 to begin building a massive network
of reservoirs, filter marshes and storage wells. That money would
come from general state taxes, existing land-buying programs and
interest on a proposed Everglades trust fund.
</P>
<P>
   An additional $1 billion _ earning $82 million in interest _
would come from residents in South and Central Florida, also by
2010. But Bush declined to spell out how to raise that money,
leaving that decision largely up to the South Florida Water
Management District, along with the region's cities and counties.
</P>
<P>
   The plan also doesn't say where Florida would get the money it
needs for the restoration for the decade after 2010 _ an estimated
$1.7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   But make no mistake, Bush told lawmakers, environmentalists and
park managers: Florida is ready to join the federal government in
saving the Everglades.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody knows that this is a long-term commitment,'' said
Bush, wearing khakis, hiking boots and an open-necked burgundy
shirt. He stood for the cameras in front of a vista that was scenic
but not entirely natural _ a cypress and cattail-lined pond
excavated years ago for the park's visitor center.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of almost all the state's major environmental groups
cheered the announcement, as did the sugar industry and U.S. Sen.
Bob Graham.
</P>
<P>
   Congress is expected to vote this year on a $7.8 billion
Everglades restoration blueprint, which also aims to store the
water that South Florida's farms and cities will need in the next
half-century.
</P>
<P>
   The state and federal governments expect to split the costs
50-50. But environmentalists have said the plan is probably doomed
in Washington unless the state approves a concrete method this year
for financing its share of the money.
</P>
<P>
   Most environmental groups had pressed for the state to provide
at least $100 million each year. Bush's plan would average $125
million per year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were expecting a show of leadership from the governor, and
I think that's what we got,'' said Shannon Estenoz, co-chairwoman
of the Everglades Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   She added she's not worried that the plan outlines money for
only the first decade: ``It's kind of like building an aircraft
carrier _ once you build half of it, it's hard to stop.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Lee, senior vice president of the Florida Audubon
Society, said a decade is about as far in the future as Bush could
reasonably commit the state _ especially since the governor is
limited to two four-year terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Gov. Bush has done everything a governor could do,''
Lee said.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Save Our Everglades leader Mary Barley chastised
Bush for not outlining money for the entire restoration.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a 10-year project _ it's a 20-year project,'' said
Barley, an Islamorada Republican who has been a harsh critic of
Bush's actions on the environment. ``Do you just say, 'I'm going to
take out a 10-year mortgage ... and 10 years from now I'm going to
get the rest?'''
</P>
<P>
   The Bush plan leaves huge decisions facing the water district,
which levies $272 million in property taxes in all or part of 16
counties.
</P>
<P>
   For the Everglades restoration, the district would need about
$100 million each year _ while it pursues other projects, such as a
possible $1 billion cleanup of Lake Okeechobee, and maintains an
aging flood control system.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the Everglades money would most likely come from the
dozens of cities and counties that would share water from the
project. The district also could steer money and employees from
lower-priority projects, or go after about $40 million that state
transportation planners spend each year on environmental programs
in South Florida.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush, who can veto the water managers' budget, said he wants
to avoid one of the most mentioned proposals: increasing the
district's property tax rate.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he would consider another idea: Charging a fee of some
sort on water used by businesses, utilities and others. ``That's an
option that I think is appropriate,'' Bush said later Tuesday in
Tallahassee.
</P>
<P>
   Robert P. King writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla. Shirish Date contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
