<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nation's Long Prosperity Raises Household Incomes
</P>
<P>
   In its most detailed look so far at how families have fared
during the nation's long run of prosperity, the Federal Reserve
said the strong economy pushed more households into the middle
class, and that the booming strong market showered benefits on all
but the lowest income groups. The report, based on an in-depth
survey of the finances of more than 4,000 households in 1998 also
found a sharp increase in the percentage of families owning stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon Lowers Its Outlook Again
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon said it expects to earn 20 to 25 cents a share in the
fourth quarter of 1999, less than half of what Wall Street analysts
had forecast. In its third profit warning since September, the
company also said its earnings for all of 1999 and 2000 will be
less than its most recent forecast. It was the latest sign that the
giant military contractors created by mergers in the 1990's are
proving difficult to manage.
</P>
<P>
   Dow Jones Falls, but Nasdaq Gains
</P>
<P>
   Stocks were mixed as investors took some profits but continued
to buy shares of high-tech companies. The Dow Jones industrial
average fell 162.26 points, to 11,560.72, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's
500-stock index slipped 10.01 points, to 1,455.14. The Nasdaq
composite index gained 66.54 points, to 4,130.81.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft Posts $2.44 Billion Profit
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft said it earned $2.44 billion, or 44 cents a share, on
sales of $6.1 billion in its second quarter, but the numbers failed
to impress Wall Street and the company's shares fell in after-hours
trading.
</P>
<P>
   ABN Amro to Cut Work Force
</P>
<P>
   The Dutch banking giant, ABN Amro Holdings, said it would
eliminate more than 10 percent of its work force as part of a major
reorganization plan aimed at cutting costs. The bank also said it
would upgrade its online banking operation to replace the branches
that would be closed in the cost-cutting move.
</P>
<P>
   The Drawbacks of Dot-Com Work
</P>
<P>
   When Forsyth Alexander left her job in publishing for a job at
an Internet start-up, she thought the job opportunities, the
excitement of the cyberworld and the stock options would make up
for the low pay. But as she and other workers, recruiters and
consultants are discovering, the near-anarchy and brutal hours at
Internet start-ups are not for everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Promotional Ads for Olympics Start
</P>
<P>
   The International Olympic Committee's campaign promoting the
Olympics begins Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Protests Likely at Economic Forum
</P>
<P>
   International business and political leaders, including
President Clinton, will gather in Davos, Switzerland, next month
for an annual five-day meeting sponsored by the World Economic
Forum on the theme of globalization. As during recent trade talks
in Seattle, protesters may attempt to disrupt the gathering.
</P>
<P>
   Banks Report Increased Earnings
</P>
<P>
   The Bank of America, J.P. Morgan &AMP; Co. and Wells Fargo posted
higher fourth-quarter earnings driven by investment-banking fees
and trading. But bank stocks slid after bond yields rose to their
highest level in two and a half years on concern the Federal
Reserve may raise interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   Trade Dispute Over Aircraft Noise
</P>
<P>
   The United States will ask the United Nations to resolve a
battle with Europe over aircraft noise that Washington says has
already cost American companies $2 billion and could escalate into
a trade war.
</P>
</TEXT>
