<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-INSURANCE-ADS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARRY AND LOUISE COMMERCIALS RETURN WITH A HEALTH INSURANCE PLAN  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Harry and Louise, featured in television
commercials that helped kill President Clinton's plan for universal
health insurance in 1994, are back.
</P>
<P>
   They still work for the insurance industry, but now, in a new
television commercial, they prod Clinton, Congress and political
candidates to do something about the problem of 44 million
Americans without health coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's huge,'' Harry says. ``An epidemic.'' He insists, ``We
can't leave working families and kids without insurance.''
</P>
<P>
   Louise replies that ``someone actually has a workable plan,''
and she praises the plan devised by the Health Insurance
Association of America. ``It has tax relief for workers and small
businesses, and special help for the working poor,'' she adds.
</P>
<P>
   Charles N. Kahn III, president of the association, said that
Republican candidates for president had ``basically ignored'' the
issue of the uninsured in recent months. ``Republicans are
floundering on the issue, to be frank,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Kahn said the Republican nominee would have to address the
issue because the Democratic candidates for president, former Sen.
Bill Bradley and Vice President Al Gore, had made health insurance
coverage a defining issue in their campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   The number of Americans without health insurance continues to
increase by about a million a year, even though the economy is
strong and the unemployment rate is at a 30-year low.
</P>
<P>
   The insurance industry's plan would make it easier for people to
buy private insurance, with new government subsidies for low-wage
workers and new tax credits for small employers. The proposals
would amount to a large federal subsidy for the industry, but
insurance executives said most of the money would be passed on to
doctors, hospitals and others who provide health care.
</P>
<P>
   Insurance companies see threats from both left and right. They
fear that liberal Democrats will try to supplant private insurers
with some type of government-run health program. They say that some
conservative Republicans would undermine the employer-based health
insurance system by creating tax incentives for people to buy
health insurance as individuals, rather than through large groups
organized by employers.
</P>
<P>
   Kahn said the industry was spending $1 million on newspaper
advertisements and television commercials, scheduled to run on CNN
nationwide and on some network affiliates in the Washington area in
the next 10 days. More advertising may follow, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The industry spent $17 million on the original Harry-and-Louise
campaign, which featured 14 television commercials from September
1993 to August 1994. In those advertisements, Harry and Louise
criticized Clinton's proposals as complex and bureaucratic.
</P>
<P>
   The same actors appear in the new spots, which were produced by
the same company, Goddard Claussen, now a unit of Porter Novelli,
which in turn is a unit of the Omnicom Group. Harry and Louise were
catapulted to national fame when Hillary Rodham Clinton attacked
their sponsor in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Kahn denied that his organization was making a radical shift. In
1993 and 1994, he said, the association supported Clinton's goal of
universal insurance coverage and, at that time, even supported
proposals to require employers to provide or obtain coverage for
employees.
</P>
<P>
   On a related issue, White House officials said Tuesday that
Clinton would again propose tax credits for people providing
long-term care to relatives with chronic illnesses and
disabilities. But, they said, the maximum tax credit would be three
times as big _ $3,000 a year, instead of the $1,000 proposed last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Experts on aging praised the president's proposal last year. But
many described it as a symbolic statement because, they said, many
people with chronic illnesses require home-care services costing
tens of thousands of dollars a year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
