<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-18 21:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9637 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-JETER-EXCEPTION-N     01-18 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-JETER-EXCEPTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON BASEBALL: JETER IS THE EXTRAORDINARY EXCEPTION
</HEADLINE>
  (With YANKEES-JETER) 
(rk) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Derek Jeter stares straight into your eyes when he is
involved in a one-on-one conversation with you, whether the topic
is college basketball, another chilly day in New York or his future
with the Yankees. Jeter's pale green eyes rarely stray because he
is absorbing every sentence. Do not try to figure out Jeter's gaze.
He will not allow it.
</P>
<P>
   Jeter was standing in a corner of a private room at the Official
All Star Cafe last Saturday, talking, then listening and staring.
The discussion shifted from thoughts about spring training to his
contract status and how it would be logical for George
Steinbrenner, the Yankees' principal owner, to sign Jeter, his
25-year-old shortstop, to a multiyear deal now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to play here,'' Jeter said. ``Eventually, I think it
will all work out.''
</P>
<P>
   With those simple, smooth comments, Jeter stopped staring and
looked away. Maybe it was a sign. Maybe it was Jeter's way of
hinting that he was close to agreeing to a seven-year, $118.5
million contract, which would make him the highest-paid player in
major league baseball. When Jeter stopped staring, it might have
been because he had almost revealed too much about himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll never catch me bragging,'' Jeter said that day. ``I
won't do that.''
</P>
<P>
   But Jeter could and he should because he is a remarkable player,
and this contract is one that the Yankees must complete. When it is
Steinbrenner's money, not mine, it is simple to write that Jeter is
worth $118.5 million, a staggering sum. It is easy to explain how
Jeter, who is already working out in Tampa, Fla., for the 2000
season, will only get better and how his salaries will only
increase if he continues going through the arbitration process and
then gets a whiff of free agency after the 2001 season. It is so
simple because it is all so true.
</P>
<P>
   Players like Jeter, who has the combination of immense talent,
incredible competitiveness, undeniable grace and the unbelievable
appeal that has made him the most popular Yankee, are extremely
rare. Four years ago, Steinbrenner might have envisioned the future
when he watched Jeter's full rookie year and said, ``There's not a
better shortstop in the game today than Derek Jeter.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure, Seattle's Alex Rodriguez and Boston's Nomar Garciaparra
are serious stars in the shortstop equation, too, but Steinbrenner
would definitely make the same remark today and be right. Jeter
does not have as much power as Garciaparra or Rodriguez, but he has
evolved into the best all-around player, he plays in New York and
he has three World Series rings. Steinbrenner has always hesitated
to sign young players to long-term deals before they are eligible
for free agency, but he is about to make a shrewd exception for
Jeter.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond Jeter's .349 average, 24 homers, 102 runs batted in and
134 runs scored last season, the main reasons he could make almost
$17 million a season are his intangibles. Jeter is more likely to
play point guard for the Knicks than to ever embarrass the Yankees.
He was smart enough to leave a bar when someone shouted a racial
epithet at him a few years ago. He signs more autographs than any
other Yankee, and he has blossomed into the future captain of the
team with a cool clubhouse presence.
</P>
<P>
   A person close to Jeter said that Jeter has told his close
friend Rodriguez, who can be a free agent after the 2000 season, to
pursue his market value but not to let the contract motivate him:
do not be overly consumed with being the first $200 million player;
do not let the contract define you as a player.
</P>
<P>
   Jeter is acting that way by making some concessions in his deal
with the Yankees. Several baseball executives and agents recently
speculated that Jeter could earn from $135 million to $200 million
in deals of 8 to 10 years. But Jeter does not want to wait to see
what Rodriguez or Ken Griffey Jr. gets. Jeter does not want to test
free agency or sign for just five years so that he can rumble into
the always-escalating vault again. He wants to be a Yankee forever.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no secret I love playing in New York,'' Jeter said last
Saturday. ``I'd love to play in New York for the rest of my career.
But it's a business and I understand that. I don't worry about
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner wants to meet with Jeter in Tampa before the
contract is made final. That will be easy to arrange since Jeter
bought a house there so he could work out at the Yankees'
facilities five days a week. Steinbrenner knows how to find Jeter,
who will be hitting or throwing and staring straight back at him.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
