<DOCNO> NYT20000118.0378 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-18 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9638 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-F16-CRASH-COX     01-18 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-F16-CRASH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Vulture caused crash of F-16
 &HT;    By Molly Hennessy-Fiske
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ A turkey vulture that hit the canopy of
an F-16 caused the July crash that killed an Air Force Reserve
pilot in Okeechobee County, according to a report released by Air
Force investigators Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Maj. Samuel D'Angelo was a seasoned pilot who had patrolled the
no-fly zone over Iraq in April. The accident, which happened during
a low-altitude flight with the F-16 traveling at 500 mph, is among
a small number of fatalities recorded as being caused by bird
strikes. Federal experts say such rare occurrences are a
consequence of stealthier, more silent aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the only aircraft that's vulnerable to birds,'' Col.
Chip Taylor, who helped coordinate the investigation, said Tuesday,
``As long as we have flying machines and flying animals in the sky,
we're going to have accidents.''
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said D'Angelo, 40, of Key Largo, Fla., left
Homestead Air Force Base en route to Avon Park Bombing Range with
three other F-16s at 10:42 a.m. July 1 and would have arrived about
an hour later.
</P>
<P>
   Maj. Gregory Lee and Lt. Col. Derek Rydholm flew 2 or 3 miles
ahead of D'Angelo and Maj. Keith W. Beam, who was in a separate
plane, approaching the Okeechobee County landfill about 15 miles
east of their destination at 11:30 a.m. when D'Angelo's plane
suddenly went down in a remote cattle ranch.
</P>
<P>
   The report shows the crash was not a result of error on the part
of D'Angelo, who had flown 727s with American Airlines since 1992
and received numerous Air Force commendation medals, an Air Force
achievement medal and the National Defense Service Medal. Taylor
said D'Angelo had flown the same route with his three fellow pilots
before, and that the training mission was fairly routine.
</P>
<P>
   The report shows the landfill D'Angelo skirted before the crash
was host to the culprit, most likely a turkey vulture, although the
group also noted high concentrations of black vultures, white ibis
and cattle egrets.
</P>
<P>
   According to Air Force Bird Aircraft Strike Hazard Team records,
turkey vultures have been responsible for more than 348 bird
strikes since 1985. Of the 18 species the team tracks, only
mourning doves and horned larks caused more accidents. Taylor said
the vultures are not only dangerous, they are also costly _ the
third costliest bird to run into. Because they are so large, they
cause more damage, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Air Force safety tests include shooting a four-pound ``bird-like
substance'' at a speed of about 360 mph into the canopies of $20
million F-16s like the one D'Angelo was flying. But Taylor said the
tests can only simulate real-world circumstances. Birds may be
bigger, and an F-16 often flies faster.
</P>
<P>
   ``The aircraft is designed for maneuverability. It's not
hardened,'' Taylor said of the F-16, a plane he has flown for about
14 years, ``The basic concept is 'Don't get hit.' ``
</P>
<P>
   D'Angelo and his fellow pilots were practicing evasive maneuvers
at the time of the accident, flying at about 500 to 1500 feet above
the ground, Taylor said. Beam, who flew directly over the landfill,
did not report seeing any birds, and although no bird remains were
recovered at the crash, Taylor said the force of the impact on the
canopy matched that in previous bird strike cases.
</P>
<P>
   According to Bird Strike Committee U.S.A., a research group
formed in 1991 by Federal Aviation Administration scientists and
engineers, there have been only about 300 fatalities reported for
civil or military planes nationally since 1960. Of those, most
resulted from birds being sucked into plane engines, according to
Richard Dolbeer, who chairs the committee. The Ohio-based group
recently started working with an engineering firm in Washington to
develop aircraft radar that could emit sounds to warn birds away as
planes approach, similar to the way propellers on older craft did
50 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were few airstrikes then because planes were propeller
driven, noisy and slow,'' he said, ``Today there may be a lot of
noise behind the plane, but up front they're pretty quiet and
they're traveling at a much greater speed.''
</P>
<P>
   Molly Hennessy-Fiske writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla. E-mail: mollyhennessyfiske(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
