<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: CHICKS NIX HOSE ON STIX 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By MAUREEN DOWD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   On my birthday, my girlfriend Alessandra and I raced over to
Saks Fifth Avenue to find miracle wrinkle creams.
</P>
<P>
   We careened up to the Estee Lauder counter. The woman there
suggested a shiny gook you smear on your face to create the
illusion of soft pink light dangling over your head.
</P>
<P>
   We bought it.
</P>
<P>
   Then we moved on to the Creme de la Mer counter. Standing before
an aquarium, the saleswoman gave us the back story. She said the
seaweed concoction had been developed by a handsome rocket
scientist who had had his face burned off in an accident while he
was testing fuels for NASA. He worked for 12 years in his garage to
come up with a cream that would get his face back. I said it
sounded too ``Phantom of the Opera.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It has healing powers,'' the saleswoman said portentously.
</P>
<P>
   I hesitated. It was $155 for two ounces. ``It's so expensive,''
I said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sharon Stone uses it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   We bought it.
</P>
<P>
   I had always thought one of the blandishments of feminism would
be a more flexible and capacious notion of female beauty. I was
wrong. The philosophers and poets may have equated beauty with
truth and goodness. But in the world of implants, collagen and
starlets so thin that an Altoid constitutes a hearty meal, Barbie
is bigger than ever. We went straight from Jayne Mansfield to
Pamela Anderson Lee.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of broadening the choices of how to look good, we have
only broadened the ways we try to look alike. We spend $8 billion a
year on an infinite number of creams designed to make us
conformists with perfect complexions.
</P>
<P>
   Women's magazines have only two topics: how to trap men, and how
to look good enough to trap men.
</P>
<P>
   Kroger, the nation's largest grocery store chain, decided to
sheathe Cosmopolitan in a blinder rack, the sort that hides
Penthouse, to spare shoppers racy headlines such as ``Sex Tricks:
20 Earth-Quaking Moves That Will Make Him Plead for Mercy _ and Beg
for More.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have gotten hundreds and hundreds and hundreds of e-mails
and calls to our headquarters thanking us,'' says Gary Rhodes, the
Kroger spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   But if Kroger wants to crusade on this, it will have to toss all
the women's magazines. February's Glamour features a cover story on
``Sex and Size: How to Maximize your Pleasure Match.''
</P>
<P>
   The evening news, once the domain of stories about budget
deficits and guerrilla wars, now dwells on diets and laser surgery.
</P>
<P>
   When I try to keep up on beauty news, I get frightened and
confused. Harper's Bazaar has a story recommending ``precision
liposuction'' involving ``multiple micro reductions of hard-to-tone
areas.'' Then on Tuesday USA Today had a front-page story about the
alarming increase in death by liposuction. ``We're on top of this
problem,'' said Jack Bruner, a Sacramento doctor who is the
chairman of the plastic surgeons' liposuction task force.
</P>
<P>
   Liposuction task force? Women in the 50s vacuumed. Women in the
00s are vacuumed. Our Hoovers have turned on us!
</P>
<P>
   Harper's bubbles that ``programmed water and nuclear submarine
materials are finding their way into your face cream.''
</P>
<P>
   I would rather smear fissionable materials on my face than
figure out what's going on with pantyhose. The New York Post
reports that only the most gauche women still wear hose, even in
winter. Suffering for beauty is one thing. But gangrene for beauty?
</P>
<P>
   The article explained that women spurned hose as too binding.
But now that they have given up hose, they have started wearing
more foundation garments, because they want the control of hose
without the hose.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard of women cutting the legs off of hose and just
wearing the control tops,'' said Linda Welles, the editor of
Allure.
</P>
<P>
   I was still trying to make sense of nylon sales dropping and
girdle sales rising when I got to the end of the article, which
reveals what they will be wearing this spring: hose.
Cashmere-and-herringbone-textured hose.
</P>
<P>
   The fashion slaves of New York have taken leave of their senses.
Bare legs in Arctic temperatures; cashmere-and-herringbone-swathed
legs in tropical temperatures.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind. We'll buy that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
