<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CRIME-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON PROMOTES $200 MILLION ANTI-GUN PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ President Clinton's penchant for devouring his way
through a city made a return during his visit here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   After a speech at the Orchard Gardens Community Center, where he
promoted a $280 million proposal to crack down on the use of
illegal guns, Clinton seemed to have worked up quite an appetite.
Instead of cooling his heels at the Boston Park Plaza Hotel before
an evening fund-raiser, he asked Mayor Thomas M. Menino to take him
to get something to eat.
</P>
<P>
   They ended up at Mike's City Diner in the South End, where he
chowed down on ham and scrambled eggs, a big bowl of grits,
cornbread and rye toast.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ate like a horse,'' he said. ``I need a nap.''
</P>
<P>
   His lunch-time companions, Senator Edward M. Kennedy and Menino
both ordered ham and cheese omelettes.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton had visited Roxbury, a neighborhood crippled by crime
and drugs, not to highlight its failures but rather to celebrate
its success in combating youth violence.
</P>
<P>
   The president plans to ask Congress to approve funding to hire
500 new agents and inspectors for the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco
and Firearms to target illegal gun dealers and traffickers and
1,000 new state and local prosecutors to work on gun-related cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are trying to send a message, an unambigious message, to
people who violate the law: if you commit crimes with guns or
violate gun laws, you will pay a heavy price. No city has sent that
message more clearly than Boston,'' said Clinton, flanked by more
than a dozen Boston uniformed police officers and political leaders
gathered in the center's gymnasium.
</P>
<P>
   The next order of business for Clinton was attending a $25,000
per couple fund-raiser at the suburban home of Alan Solomont. The
event at the home of the former Democratic National Committee
finance chairman in Weston raised $600,000.
</P>
<P>
   The anti-gun proposal he unveiled Tuesday is part of his effort
to make gun control a top priority for his last year in office. It
is also a direct response to criticism from some Republicans and
the National Rifle Assocation that his administration has
emphasized gun restrictions over greater enforcement of existing
gun laws.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton says the $280 million proposal, which will be included
in the fiscal 2001 budget he will send to Capitol Hill next month,
is designed to build on community policing and other efforts taken
by his administration that have created a 25-year low in the crime
rate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want America to be the safest big country in the entire
world,'' he said. ``We can do that _ not with a silver bullet, but
by continuing to build on what has worked.''
</P>
<P>
   Other features of the proposal include funding 100 more federal
gun prosecutors in the offices of the US attorneys; expanding a gun
tracing program in Boston and 37 other cities to 50 cities,
tripling funding for ballistics testing, and doubling funding for
so-called ``smart gun'' technology designed to limit a gun's use to
its owner or other authorized users. He also proposed providing $10
million in Justice Department matching grants to support local
media campaigns on gun violence and gun safety.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy and Menino, who met Clinton at Logan International
Airport, acknowledged that by focusing on gun enforcement rather
than restrictions the proposal is limited and perhaps punitive.
But, Kennedy said, ``It may be built on. There will probably be
support to sort of build on.''
</P>
<P>
   The president ended his day at Solomont's home with 40 people
who contributed to the Democratic Party coffers.
</P>
<P>
   After a chorus of Weston Middle School students serenaded the
president with Jim Croce's ``Time in a Bottle'' and the civil
rights anthem ``We Shall Overcome,'' Clinton rose from his chair by
the fireplace to exhort the party faithful to stay the course
through November.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to the lament of ``not enough time'' in Croce's
ballad, Clinton said, ``We do have time to do the things we want to
do, as a country and as a people.''
</P>
<P>
   The president, along with Democratic National Committee chairman
Edward Rendell, said the country's combination of ``economic
prosperity, social progress, and self-confidence'' bodes well for a
Democratic victory this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Decmocratic Party has been reformed, reenergized and
reborn in the last seven years in a way that is entirely consistent
with our history and with our values.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said his ``unfinished business'' includes legislation on
a patients' bill of rights, hate crimes, and gun control, and that
increased tolerance among all Americans will continue to be a
priority through his last year in office.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to expand the real family of America,'' Clinton said.
``We have more in common than whatever divides us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
