<HEADER>
A9643 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-DAVIDIANS-COX     01-18 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAVIDIANS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Government fails to meet court-ordered deadline to surrender all
Davidian evidence
 &HT;    By Mark England
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ The government failed to meet a court-ordered
deadline Tuesday to produce all evidence in a wrongful-death
lawsuit filed by surviving Branch Davidians _ even with the
shipping of 50 boxes of documents over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for plaintiffs' attorney Mike Caddell confirmed his
Houston office received the documents Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got about that number,'' the spokesman said. ``We haven't
had time to count them yet.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Walter S. Smith Jr. of Waco ordered the
federal government to produce evidence related to the deaths of
David Koresh and 75 followers by Jan. 15. However, U.S. Attorney
Michael Bradford of Beaumont said federal rules allow for the
deadline to be extended.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under federal rules, if the deadline falls on a weekend, it
can be extended to the next working day,'' Bradford said. ``Since
Monday was a holiday, the deadline would extend until Tuesday.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradford said classified documents from the Department of
Defense, as well as records from the U.S. Attorney's office for the
Western District of Texas, are all that remain to be turned over.
</P>
<P>
   ``My understanding is that those are the only materials not
produced,'' Bradford said. ``We did a considerable amount of work
over the weekend. There are about 2,500 documents previously
classified. By law, we can't produce classified documents. We're
going through them to see if we can pull out the portions that are
classified so the rest can be produced. The process has not been
completed.''
</P>
<P>
   The originals of photographs taken from the U.S. Attorney's
office in Waco have been turned over to Smith, Bradford said.
However, the government is still reproducing them for the
plaintiffs. That work should be completed Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hired a private contractor to make copies of everything,''
Bradford said. ``Going back through them, we discovered 31 boxes of
materials for which they failed to make copies. We sent the company
down to Waco to make those copies. We're told they'll finish that
process by tomorrow (Wednesday). We still have to go through and
review them for possible privileged information as well as for
duplicative photographs.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradford decline to estimate when the remaining documents will
be given to the plaintiffs.
</P>
<P>
   In a motion filed Tuesday, Caddell questioned whether the
government was turning over the originals of documents to the
court, as ordered by Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Caddell noted that in a memo to Bradford, a Justice Department
official reported that the FBI's laboratory was duplicating the
negatives of photographs taken by a former agent. The memo
concluded, ``... we expect to be able to ship a copy of them to the
court on Jan. 18, 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   That, according to Caddell's motion, ``raises grave concerns
whether the other negatives that are already apparently on file at
the courthouse in Waco are originals or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradford, however, maintained Tuesday that the government is
supplying the court original documents.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this instance, a former FBI agent had taken photographs (at
Mount Carmel) with a personal camera,'' Bradford said. ``The FBI
just found out about it. They got the negatives from him and
notified the court. The filing done with the court had language
that made it sound like copies of the negatives were being produced
for the court. In fact, we will produce the originals for the
court. If he (Caddell) had called, we would have told him that. The
language is confusing, however.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Caddell asked Smith to fine the government $50,000 if
it failed to meet the document deadline. Caddell argued he would
need the money to hire employees to go through the last-minute
documents.
</P>
<P>
   In another motion filed Tuesday, Caddell asked the court to
compel officials at the ATF and the Department of Defense to answer
on-the-record whether any of their agents fired shots at the Branch
Davidians on April 19, 1993. The FBI has already denied that its
agents fired a shot on the final day of the 51-day siege.
</P>
<P>
   Caddell noted that one of the Delta Force members at Mount
Carmel was described as a combat specialist.
</P>
<P>
   The two other Delta Force members present were communications
specialists, according to Caddell's motion, who testified during
their depositions that the third Delta Force member was not seen
until after the fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Further, when he appeared, he was described as looking
'tired,' 'somewhat disheveled,' and 'red-eyed,' according to the
motion.
</P>
<P>
   Mark England writes for The Waco Tribune-Herald, Waco, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
