A9649 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-ROBERDS-BANKRUPTCY-CO     01-18 0615
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBERDS-BANKRUPTCY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Roberds CEO promises compassion for workers, families
 &HT;    By Tim Tresslar
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST CARROLLTON, Ohio _ Melvin Baskin, chief executive for the
embattled Roberds Inc., says compassion will be critical as the
retailer wends its way through the bankruptcy reorganization
process.
</P>
<P>
   The 24-store furniture, electronics and appliance retailer plans
to file court documents today seeking protection from creditors
through Chapter 11 of the federal bankruptcy code. Baskin declined
Tuesday to detail the company's specific strategy for emerging from
bankruptcy proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Roberds managers gathered workers Tuesday in Tampa, Fla., and
Cincinnati to explain the company's plans to shutter stores in
those places. Baskin went to Tampa; Robert Wilson, Roberds'
president, broke the news to the Cincinnati staff.
</P>
<P>
   Baskin thought it important that he travel to Tampa to explain
the decision to shut the market's eight stores and distribution
center. It's one of many Florida trips Baskin plans to make as the
company closes up shop there.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're entitled to have that information as fast as they
can,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Baskin knows first-hand what its like to work for a company
embroiled in bankruptcy proceedings. The 56-year-old executive
worked for Federated Department Stores, parent company of Lazarus,
when the company went through its own reorganization.
</P>
<P>
   The process taught him the need for an open door, clear
communication and compassion for those affected, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The actions that we have announced today have been very
difficult, as they affect many outstanding, dedicated employees and
their families,'' Baskin said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Baskin came to Roberds as president and chief executive officer
in July 1998, later shedding the president's title but joining the
board of directors. Bask to Roberds after a stint with
convenience store chain Farm Stores Inc. His retail resume before
that included stints with Bruener's Home Furnishings Corp., The
Bombay Co., Kay Jewelers and Neiman-Marcus.
</P>
<P>
   Baskin, chosen from a field of 60 candidates, succeeded James F.
Robeson, who stepped in as interim chief executive after founder
Kenneth W. Fletcher resigned in November 1998. Fletcher remained
with the company as chairman and a consultant until his death in
January 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Baskin inherited a company challenged by losses and dropping
stock prices. The board, which includes local business leaders such
as banker Jerry Kirby, former NCR executive Gilbert Williamson and
real estate executive and Roberds co-founder Donald Wright, brought
Baskin in at a salary of $400,000 with a $25,000 bonus and stock
options.
</P>
<P>
   Baskin's strategy for turning around the company included
cutting costs, improving merchandise selection, emphasizing
high-margin furniture products and instituting performance
standards for sales staff.
</P>
<P>
   The company made numerous efforts to save itself, but lost an
average of $1 million per month between January 1998 and September
1999. Executives also saw performance improve in the first half of
1999. The company continued to post losses, but smaller ones than
during the previous year. During the third quarter, the company
posted a $3.3 million loss compared with $1.2 million during the
same period in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of the company's bankruptcy filing, Baskin said he
came to the tough job with his eyes open.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, I knew what I was coming into,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Tresslar writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
E-mail: tim_tresslarcoxohio.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
