<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-18 22:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9651 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-CATHERINE-KEENER-FILM     01-18 1162
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CATHERINE-KEENER-FILMS-ART-2TAKES-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEING CATHERINE KEENER AND MAKING IT LOOK EASY  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 23) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(af) 
 Margy Rochlin's most recent article for Arts &AMP; Leisure was about
the WB network.  
 By MARGY ROCHLIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was in 1986 that Catherine Keener decided that sitcom humor
might not be her calling. At the time, she had just got her first
real break _ making her network debut as the eldest of three
daughters in a pilot called ``The Alan King Show.''
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, she found herself on a CBS soundstage, worrying about
how she was going to get a live studio audience to laugh at a lame
joke.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was something about blue chip cookies for the blue chip
crowd,'' said Ms. Keener, who turned to ``Gilligan's Island'' in
her time of need. ``I didn't know how to make it funny. So I
remember that I kind of clenched my jaw like I was Mrs. Howell or
something.'' It didn't work. After the taping, Ms. Keener was
ordered to something like sitcom detention. ``Everybody went home
and I was there until, like, two in the morning, trying to get it
right.''
</P>
<P>
   Given the 40-year-old Ms. Keener's body of work since then, the
fact that she held herself, and not the material, accountable
sounds like a better joke than the one about the cookies. Whether
in a starring role as a helplessly distracted indie starlet in a
shoestring production like ``Living In Oblivion'' (1995) or in a
glorified supporting turn as a magician's assistant and the ex-wife
of an escaped convict in the 1998 crime caper ``Out of Sight,'' Ms.
Keener's ability to be effortlessly hilarious is all about
appearing as if she's never trying too hard.
</P>
<P>
   It's a brand of acting that Spike Jonze, who directed ``Being
John Malkovich,'' the dryly surreal hit in which Ms. Keener stars,
categorizes as ``un-flashy. Very real, but complicated.
Naturalistic. More like you're watching a person as opposed to a
character.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Being John Malkovich'' is about Craig Schwartz (John Cusack),
a puppeteer turned file clerk who discovers a portal that allows
people to view the world through the actor John Malkovich's eyes
for 15 minutes. In it, Ms. Keener plays Maxine, a co-worker of
Craig's who is flip, controlling and smug about her own sex appeal
in a way the outspoken but self-doubting '90s women Ms. Keener
often plays never are.
</P>
<P>
   Around mid-movie, Craig and his housepet-doting, frumpy spouse,
Lotte (Cameron Diaz), both become romantically obsessed with
Maxine. Jonze, who credits his wife, Sofia Coppola, for coming up
with the idea of hiring Ms. Keener, always felt that Maxine was
much trickier than she looked.
</P>
<P>
   ``In certain scenes, Maxine barely has any dialogue at all,''
Jonze said. ``And the dialogue she does have is quick and to the
bone. To make that kind of character feel not one-dimensional, I
thought would be really hard.'' He said Ms. Keener was so convinced
she was wrong for the part that she kept proposing she be Lotte and
Jonze give the role of Maxine to Ms. Diaz, her close friend.
</P>
<P>
   Once Ms. Keener stopped resisting, though, Jonze reveled in a
leading lady who would come to work, change into sleek Helmut Lang
attire and a don't-touch-me demeanor, and do something totally
unexpected in every scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``In one take, she just slapped Malkovich on top of the head,''
Jonze said of a scene in which Malkovich and Maxine make love on
his apartment sofa. ``It made a loud, smacking sound. She could
have prepared that before, but I doubt it. She was just in the
moment. Like, Malkovich's bald head was right in front of her and
she (italics)slapped(end italics) it. It was just perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Ms. Keener's on-screen vitality often has nothing to do
with her line readings. Sometimes, it's all about her well-timed
exhalations. One of her most memorable moments in ``Your Friends
and Neighbors,'' Neil La Bute's 1998 withering look at modern
relationships, comes when she dismisses her
soon-to-be-ex-boyfriend's weaselly attempts to reconcile with a
simple, corrosive (italics)pfffftttt.(end italics) Then there is
her gift for physicality, for tweaking a potentially forgettable
bit by tilting her head or flashing a smile that seems completely
out of context.
</P>
<P>
   ``She uses her whole body to play a scene,'' said the
writer-director Nicole Holofcener, whose 1995 feature debut,
``Walking and Talking,'' starred Ms. Keener and Anne Heche as
childhood best pals struggling to take their friendship into
adulthood. ``She does these things that are so lovely and unique.
Things you can't write. Things you can't say to an actress, like,
`When you run into the lake, make your arms go up and down like a
chicken.' If a director said that to an actress, she'd look at them
like they were crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Holofcener is currently trailing the writer-director Tom
DiCillo by 4 to 1 in the race to cast Ms. Keener in every one of
their movies. (Ms. Keener appears in DiCillo's ``Johnny Suede,''
``Living in Oblivion,'' ``Box of Moonlight'' and ``The Real
Blonde.'')
</P>
<P>
   If all goes well, though, Ms. Holofcener will narrow the margin
late this spring when she begins shooting her as-yet-untitled
second film, in which Ms. Keener will appear as the angriest of
three siblings _ a part written with her theatrical strengths in
mind.
</P>
<P>
   Don Coscarelli had better get cracking, though. His only film so
far with Ms. Keener is ``Survival Quest,'' a 1989 low-budget
action-thriller about dueling teams of Outward Bound-ish
adventurers. On the other hand, he can lay claim to giving Ms.
Keener her first co-starring feature role, albeit one that involved
activities she would probably rather not repeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of physical challenges,'' said Coscarelli,
who recalled Ms. Keener, then a gap-toothed young actress with
waist-length hair. She wanted so much to make an impression on him
that she showed up at both her audition and her callback dressed in
a camping outfit of khaki shorts with a backpack. ``She'd be
rappelling down a sheer rock face, eating worms, throwing herself
into dangerous rapids and almost killing herself on a daily
basis.''
</P>
<P>
   Early in the rehearsal process, Ms. Keener was at a
rock-climbing class for the ``Survival Quest'' cast at Angeles
Crest Forest, on the outskirts of Los Angeles, when she spotted a
handsome, dark-haired young man who had managed to scale a steep
cliff. Or most of it, at least.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was stuck,'' said Ms. Keener. ``He couldn't get up or down.
So he had to be rescued. And I thought: `Oh, look at the hot- dog.
Serves him right.' I didn't know he was one of the actors.''
Someday this will be a story Ms. Keener can tell her son, Clyde,
now 6 months old _ about how Mommy met Daddy, aka Dermot Mulroney
(``My Best Friend's Wedding''), her husband of nine years.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   For the record, Mulroney's first question to Ms. Keener showed a
certain prescience. ``You're a middle child, aren't you?'' he asked
her.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, she is. The third of Jim and Evelyn Keener's five
children, Ms. Keener grew up in the Little Havana section of Miami,
the youngest of a huge pack of cousins who always hung out
together. Until her teens, Ms. Keener was the family ``good girl,''
the one who would give half of whatever she ordered to her father
on their after-church Burger King stops.
</P>
<P>
   She was afraid that his owning Slumber Plus, a bedding store,
did not bring in enough money for him to pay for so many Whoppers.
The teachers at Monsignor Edward Pace High School, though, might
offer up a less angelic image.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was lippy,'' said Ms. Keener, who was temporarily expelled
in the 11th grade and was considered a chief instigator in her
crowd of ungovernable teen-age girlfriends, ``but not the supreme
leader. I wasn't the worst.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, her grades were good enough to get her into Wheaton
College, an expensive women's school in Norton, Mass. Tight on
money, she roomed with an aunt who lived nearby. Her classmates
were so affluent, they made her feel ``different, out of place.
Just this chick from Miami.''
</P>
<P>
   She majored in English and history. ``The theater never called
to me,'' she said. In fact, when she enrolled in a theater ensemble
class her sophomore year, it was only because the photography
workshop she coveted was closed. Although she liked being onstage
and even won some acting awards, it was not as if her game plan was
set.
</P>
<P>
   After graduation, she moved to New York and worked as an
assistant to the casting agent Gail Eisenstadt. When NBC relocated
Ms. Eisenstadt to Los Angeles, Ms. Keener went with her. Then, in
1986, after learning she had lung cancer, Ms. Eisenstadt had a
heart-to-heart with Ms. Keener, convincing her green-eyed protegee
that acting was within her reach. A few pulled strings later, Ms.
Keener was bouncing alongside Rob Lowe and Jim Belushi, improvising
her Screen Actors Guild-card winning chant, ``Go! Go! Go! Chug it!
Chug it!'' in a drinking contest scene in ``About Last Night ... ''
</P>
<P>
   These days, Ms. Keener finds herself on the receiving end of the
cheering. On Jan. 8, the New York Film Critic's Circle gave her a
best-supporting-actress award for ``Being John Malkovich.'' And
this Sunday night, a limousine will ferry Ms. Keener and Mulroney
from their Hollywood Hills home to the Beverly Hilton Hotel for the
Golden Globes awards ceremony, at which she is up for best
supporting actress for the role of Maxine.
</P>
<P>
   That does not necessarily make her an award hopeful. Or so it
seemed a couple of weeks ago when Ms. Keener, dressed in a pale
blue sweatshirt and blue jeans, sat eating a bowl of chicken soup
at Victor's Square Delicatessen in East Hollywood. She was so
conflicted about the current Keener lovefest and what it portends
for her future that it was affecting the decibel level of her loud,
gravelly voice.
</P>
<P>
   When asked why she was whispering some of her responses, Ms.
Keener said: ``Maybe I'm embarrassed to say I already get really
good parts. And that I'm lucky. And that I don't know what the next
step will be.''
</P>
<P>
   Matthew Warchus, who directed Ms. Keener in her latest film,
``Simpatico,'' which opens on Feb. 4, feels that she need not worry
about steps. ``So many potential employers are already fans of
hers,'' said the London-based Warchus. ``She probably can get
almost anything you could wish for in terms of serious acting
challenges, really.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Simpatico,'' based on Sam Shepard's 1994 play of the same
name, Ms. Keener is a lonely supermarket checkout clerk who finds
herself traveling to Kentucky and serving as unwitting bag man to a
disgraced racehorse commissioner, played by Albert Finney. Ms.
Keener admits to having watched ``Tom Jones,'' the 1963 movie in
which Finney came to fame, at least ``a thousand times.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's so cool, that man,'' said Ms. Keener. ``I just revere
him. The first day I worked on the movie I was in a scene with
Albert on the track at Churchill Downs.''
</P>
<P>
   Does it get any better than acting opposite one of England's
foremost talents?
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of those moments where you're thinking, `I just
can't believe where my life has led me,''' she replied.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
