<DOCNO> NYT20000118.0388 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-18 22:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9653 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-QUINTUPLETS-OHIO-COX     01-18 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUINTUPLETS-OHIO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    5 minutes, 5 babies: Family faces changes 3 boys, 2 girls are
only the third set of Ohio quintuplets
 &HT;    By Kevin Lamb
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The first quintuplets known to be born in
Southwest Ohio were breathing with minimal help from machines
Tuesday, and their parents were breathing sighs of relief.
</P>
<P>
   Michelle DiLullo, 33, gave birth to three healthy boys and two
healthy girls by Caesarean section at Miami Valley Hospital between
7:27 and 7:32 a.m. Tuesday. The babies were born 10 weeks
premature, on the target date doctors set weeks ago. Their weights
ranged from 2 pounds, 8 ounces to 3 pounds, 3 ounces, which is
almost too big to be included in statistics on high-risk premature
infants.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can have unexpected problems with any prematurity, but at
30 weeks gestation, the incidences of complications are fairly
low,'' said Dr. Marc Belcastro, director of Miami Valley's neonatal
intensive care unit (NICU).
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't surprising that the quints were on respirators. They
were at ``fairly easy settings,'' Belcastro said, and are expected
to spend two to 2 months in the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   The quints were born on the 90th birthday of their
great-grandfather, Fred DiLullo, and two days before the second
birthday of their brother, Anthony. All six DiLullo children were
conceived with the help of fertility treatments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very glad it's over, as is my wife,'' said father Michael
DiLullo, also 33. The Sidney resident felt ``slightly overwhelmed''
and ``very joyful'' but mindful that the next few days will be
critical. Quintuplets are 30 times more likely to die in the first
month of life than single babies, according to the National Center
for Health Statistics (NCHS).
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in the health care field, so I'm aware of a lot of the
complications and risks,'' said Michael, a pharmacist at Wilson
Memorial Hospital in Sidney. ``That's kind of good and bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Only two sets of quintuplets had been born previously in Ohio,
the Ohio Department of Health said. The United States had 79 quints
and higher-order multiple births in 1997, the NCHS said, up from an
average of 20 in 1990-92 but down from 81 in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are supposed to be the first millennium quints in the
U.S.,'' said Dr. Parviz Daneshjoo, the medical director of Miami
Valley's fertility center, who delivered the babies with Dr. Bruce
Banias, a fetal medicine specialist. Daneshjoo called the delivery
``perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   Seventy percent of quints are born before 28 weeks, Banias said,
``so we were very fortunate with Michelle to get to this point.''
Beyond 30 weeks, he said quints tend to outgrow the supply of blood
and nutrients available in the uterus.
</P>
<P>
   As fertility treatments have gained popularity, multiple births
of three or more increased in frequency by 404 percent in the
United States from 1980 to 1997, the latest year for which the NCHS
has figures. The number of single births rose by only 6 percent in
that period.
</P>
<P>
   Michelle DiLullo has become pregnant both times Daneshjoo
treated her with fertility drugs to induce ovulation, for which
success rates are typically 20 percent. Mothers almost never have
multiple pregnancies after previously delivering single babies, and
Michelle didn't show signs of several births during the treatment,
said Daneshjoo, who has helped induce nearly 2,000 pregnancies in
24 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought there would be more than three,'' Daneshjoo
said. Both parents have had twins in their families, so Michael
said they weren't surprised that an ultrasound at four weeks
indicated twins or triplets.
</P>
<P>
   But two weeks later, an ultrasound revealed four embryos, and a
more sophisticated image the next day turned up the fifth. ``So we
went from a shock scenario to an utter shock syndrome within 24
hours,'' Michael said. He was so stunned, he didn't say a word in
that 45-minute meeting with Daneshjoo.
</P>
<P>
   After it sunk in, ``We had a lot of emotions going,'' he said.
The DiLullos discussed their hopes and fears with each other, their
friends, family and pastor, Jonathon Schriber of St. John's
Lutheran Church in Sidney.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had such a beautiful, caring and bonded family that made
this possible,'' Daneshjoo said. ``In spite of all the things I
told them, the risks, they decided to go through with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides their faith, St. John's has helped the DiLullos with ``a
backbone of support,'' Michael said. ``These babies are going to
have a lot of adopted grandmas from the church.''
</P>
<P>
   Big brother Anthony has ``talked to them through the belly
button. He's patted them and hugged them,'' Michael said, hoping he
will at least somewhat understand he's no longer the family's
center of attention. ``We'll have to have some times that are
strictly for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Michelle, a stay-at-home mom, saw the babies within hours of
their birth. ``We made it,'' Michael said his wife of six years
told him. After 12 weeks of bed rest and 5 weeks in the hospital,
she'll be going home in three days.
</P>
<P>
   The house with ``three very small bedrooms'' is on the market,
although Michael doubts that any house they find will have enough
bedrooms and bathrooms. After all, they'll have two 16-year-old
girls one day.
</P>
<P>
   In order of birth, the babies are named Daniel Fred, John David,
Angelina Marie, Lauren Renee and James Andrew. Most of the names
came from their parents' families, Michael said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today was the most important thing,'' Michael said. ``Through
God's grace, we were able to get through this without any
complications. All this other stuff is inconsequential.''
</P>
<P>
   How to help
</P>
<P>
   _ St. John's Lutheran Church in Sidney, Ohio, has established
the DiLullo Five Fund to help Michael and Michelle DiLullo with the
expenses of their quintuplets Tuesday. Donations can be sent to The
DiLullo Five Fund, St. John's Lutheran Church, 120 W. Water St.,
Sidney, OH 45365.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Lamb writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
