<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-SCANDAL-1STLD-WRITETHRU-800(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOHL RESIGNS AS HONORARY CHAIRMAN OF CHRISTIAN DEMOCRATS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ADDS 5th graf with Kohl retaining seat in parliament.) 
 (rk) 
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ Former Chancellor Helmut Kohl resigned his post as
honorary chairman of Germany's Christian Democrats on Tuesday after
the party's leadership turned on him with extraordinary vehemence
and accused him of ``violating his duties'' by refusing to name
people who secretly gave him money.
</P>
<P>
   Kohl's resignation came shortly after the executive committee of
the party instructed him to give up his post if he persisted in his
refusal to clarify the source of secret payments of more than $1
million he received when he was chancellor and party leader during
the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   The party statement, made after a five-hour emergency meeting of
the leadership, amounted to a rebuke of a man whose stature
appeared untouchable just two months ago. But it was far from clear
whether Kohl's resignation would arrest the party's rapid political
slide.
</P>
<P>
   ``The decision to resign is not an easy one,'' Kohl said in a
statement. ``I have been a member of the Christian Democratic party
for 50 years. The party is and will remain my political home.''
</P>
<P>
   Kohl retains his seat in the lower house of parliament, which
shields him from criminal prosecution unless parliament votes to
lift his immunity.
</P>
<P>
   Indicating his continuing defiance, Kohl added: ``But I am in no
position to meet the party's demand that I break the promise I made
to those who financially supported my work in the Christian
Democratic party.''
</P>
<P>
   Kohl's fall from grace amounts to one of the most precipitous in
modern European politics. As the chancellor of German and European
unification, he had towered above his contemporaries.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday he said: ``I have served in important offices over four
decades. In so doing, I have also made mistakes which I have
publicly acknowledged. I have always tried to do my duty.''
</P>
<P>
   The Christian Democrats are in the midst of what the party
leader, Wolfgang Schaeuble, Tuesday called ``one of the worst
crises of our history'' as a result of the revelation of secret
cash payments, overseas accounts and other irregularities during
the 16-year rule of Kohl that ended in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Schaeuble, who has himself admitted accepting a bag containing
100,000 marks ($52,000) from a fugitive arms broker, had been
widely expected to resign Tuesday. But a statement expressed the
``full confidence'' of the executive committee in Kohl's
57-year-old successor.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Schaeuble's position still appears acutely vulnerable.
His survival, pending a party congress in April, appears to owe
more to the absence of a viable successor than to any real
confidence in him. Two members of the 17-member executive committee
voted against the motion supporting him and one abstained.
</P>
<P>
   Bungled explanations this week attributing some of the money
found overseas to contributions by Jews have further compounded the
party's plight and poisoned the atmosphere with accusations of
anti-Semitism. The party Tuesday took the unusual step of
apologizing ``to our Jewish compatriots.''
</P>
<P>
   The disarray has been such that Germany's normally tight-knit
political system, marked by cozy arrangements between banks,
industry and political parties, has shown signs of unraveling.
</P>
<P>
   Schaeuble tried hard Tuesday to focus attention on his longtime
mentor, Kohl, who has admitted accepting more than $1 million in
secret payments to the party during the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   The former chancellor, who unified Germany and then hitched the
country to the fate of Europe by abandoning the mark in favor of
the euro, is under criminal and parliamentary investigation for
taking the secret payments, but has said he will not violate the
``word of honor'' he gave to the contributors that their identity
would not be revealed. Under German law, any donation to a party
that exceeds $10,500 must be declared.
</P>
<P>
   Some newspaper and television channels have taken to calling the
once sacrosanct Kohl ``Don Kohleone,'' a reference to the
corruption scandals, some of them Mafia-linked, that brought down
Italy's Christian Democrats in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   But there is as yet no evidence that Kohl put the money to any
uses beyond that of cementing loyalty and bolstering local branches
within the party. Only if the identities of donors eventually
become known might it be possible to establish links between
payments and favors.
</P>
<P>
   The Christian Democrats are well aware that Kohl's defiance is
intensely damaging to them because it makes a swift conclusion to
the scandal impossible and provides cheap ammunition to the Social
Democratic chancellor, Gerhard Schroeder, now revived as a leader
after a generally dismal first year in office.
</P>
<P>
   ``The executive is convinced that Helmut Kohl is violating his
duties as honorary chairman if he continues to refuse to contribute
to the resolution of the crisis and the clarification of errors,''
the party statement said. ``As long as he does not make this
contribution, he should lay down his post as honorary chairman.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Schaeuble, who uses a wheelchair since he was injured in an
assassination attempt a decade ago, said he had spoken to Kohl by
telephone before the meeting. ``His response made this statement
necessary,'' Schaeuble said, suggesting growing exasperation with
Kohl's defiance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing is respect for the law,'' he added. ``And that
goes for the honorary chairman, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Volker Ruehe, a former defense minister in Kohl's Cabinet, is
among the many leading Christian Democrats anxious for decisive
action to resolve the scandal. Long the favorite to win an
important state election next month in Schleswig-Holstein, he is
now trailing the Social Democratic candidate.
</P>
<P>
   It is this sort of political repercussion that has made a host
of younger Christian Democrats anxious for change, including
Schaeuble's departure. One of them, Christian Wulff, has called for
a wave of resignations. In effect, the party's crisis is now
certain to last until the congress in April.
</P>
<P>
   `` Mr. Kohl's silence exposes the party to the wildest
speculation and damages it greatly,'' said Heiner Geisler, the
former secretary-general of the Christian Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   The party Tuesday apologized ``to our Jewish compatriots'' over
its hapless attempt to explain the illegal use of foreign bank
accounts by the leadership in the state of Hesse. Earlier this
week, the longtime treasurer of the party in Hesse, Casimir Prinz
zu Sayn-Wittgenstein, said the money came from bequests from
``Jewish citizens who passed away and wanted to show their
appreciation for the old city of Frankfurt.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the money, totaling about 17 million marks ($8.8
million) represented the untaxed capital gains on money illegally
smuggled out the country under the former Christian Democrat leader
in Hesse and former interior minister, Manfred Kanthner. The funds
appears to have no link to Jews or to Jewish contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Kanthner resigned from the Bundestag on Monday, saying that he
was determined ``to end the witch hunt.'' Tuesday the party said:
``The German Christian Democratic Party, as well as the Hesse
branch, apologizes to our Jewish compatriots for the gaffe with
regard to foreign bank accounts.''
</P>
<P>
   Surveying this general disintegration of what has long been
Germany's best-oiled political machine, Schroeder Tuesday allowed
himself a tone verging on smugness: ``These decisions have neither
contributed to a clarification nor to the advancement of the
housecleaning of the Christian Democrats. The government will see
to it that the image of the Federal Republic abroad is not
damaged.''
</P>
</TEXT>
