<SLUG> BC-GALPIN-CARS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALPIN MOTORS ADDING MAZDA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY SUZIE ST. JOHN 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Galpin Motors, the nation's top selling Ford
dealer, will add Mazda to the company's collection of brands,
officials said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The move should be good news for Mazda owners in and around the
San Fernando Valley area of Los Angeles, who must drive to Thousand
Oaks, Santa Monica or Culver City for dealer service after Keyes
Motors in Van Nuys traded that brand in for the Hyundai nameplate
last month.
</P>
<P>
   Mazda had indicated it wanted to remain in the San Fernando
Valley. Terms of the deal were not disclosed. Mazda officials could
not be reached.
</P>
<P>
   Galpin Vice President Brad Boeckmann, son of Galpin Motors owner
Bert Boeckmann, said the fact that Mazda is not well-represented in
the Valley makes the need for a showroom even more expedient.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our intention is to take it on as soon as possible but it
depends on how quickly we find something that works. We also have
to make sure we have our people go through the proper training so
they can help the customers make a good decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Galpin is searching for a short-term facility to house the
200-plus Mazdas while the former Lincoln-Mercury and Jaguar
showroom at 15430 Roscoe Blvd. is refurbished.
</P>
<P>
   Lincoln, Mercury and Jaguar cars will be moving into a new
facility being built across the street. Construction is scheduled
to start next month and take about 10 months to complete.
</P>
<P>
   The new showroom will be a three-story building totaling 140,000
square feet including the parking spaces. The first floor will
sport the Lincolns and Mercurys, the Jaguars will be on the
mezzanine level and inventory parking is planned for the roof.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be very customer-oriented; a place where people walk
in and feel very comfortable,'' Brad Boeckmann said.
</P>
<P>
   The plans include a snack bar and coffee bar, a children's
playroom and customer workstations with Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   Bert Boeckmann has owned the land that the new showroom is being
built on for 20 years and uses it to store cars from the various
Galpin stores. Those cars will now be shipped to property near the
Van Nuys Airport.
</P>
<P>
   Once the Lincoln Mercury transition is made, the old showroom
will be updated to turn it into a Mazda store.
</P>
<P>
   ``The building itself had already undergone some renovations a
while back but it will need some minor cosmetics,'' Brad Boeckmann
explained.
</P>
<P>
   Galpin Ford dates back to 1946 when Frank Galpin opened for
business in San Fernando. Six years later Bert Boeckmann started
working there as a sales associate and went on to buy it from
Galpin. He moved it to its current location in 1966.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
