<SLUG> BC-TRUCKSTOP-FIRE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fire kills 2 men at truck stop
 &HT;    By Mark England and Brian Gaar
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ The bodies of two men were recovered Tuesday
afternoon from Ed's Truck Stop No. 4 in Elm Mott, off Interstate
35, hours after the 2 a.m. fire that claimed their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Employees of the truck stop said the victims were two fellow
workers, Freeman Bibbs and Antonio Salazar.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities sent the bodies to Austin, Texas, for autopsies. No
cause has been determined for the fire that destroyed the back of
the truck stop, which contained a lounge, storage facility and
upstairs area where employees slept. The truck stop's newer
section, featuring a restaurant and mini-mart, only suffered smoke
and water damage.
</P>
<P>
   Firefighters from Elm Mott, Bellmead, Lacy-Lakeview, Gholson,
Chalk Bluff and Leroy helped put out the fire, which raged for more
than two hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we got here, it was fully engulfed,'' said Elm Mott
firefighter Bobby Chappell. ``There was boiling smoke and flames
shooting out from the top. We tried to knock it down and keep it
from going into the restaurant and store.''
</P>
<P>
   Cashier Lorenzo Sisneroz said a truck driver reported smelling
smoke in a rest room about 2 a.m. Tuesday. Sisneroz sent a waitress
to warn Bibbs and Salazar, reportedly sleeping in rooms above the
lounge where truckers took showers, watched TV and made phone
calls.
</P>
<P>
   When the woman opened the door into the lounge, though, she
found it filled with smoke and flames.
</P>
<P>
   She yelled out the names of Bibbs and Salazar, but no one
answered, Sisneroz said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I called 9-1-1,'' Sisneroz said. ``She hollered and hollered,
but there was no answer. That was it. It was too hot to go inside.
It was in flames. I ran everybody out of the restaurant and store.
We just had to watch it burn. We couldn't do nothing about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Justice of the Peace David Pareya of West said both fire victims
were found upstairs. Pareya estimated the older victim was in his
60s; the younger victim, his early 20s. Both were ``burned beyond
recognition,'' Pareya said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears that they were either in or near their beds at the
time,'' Pareya said. ``Apparently, they just didn't have time to
react.''
</P>
<P>
   Pareya said the upstairs area had an exit _ a door leading to a
portico.
</P>
<P>
   Mark England and Brian Gaar write for The Waco Tribune-Herald,
Waco, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
