<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-SPORTSNET-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAY GOLF AGAINST TIGER WOODS ONLINE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOMMY CUMMINGS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Soon, you'll be able to mosey up to the water cooler on Mondays
and casually tell you're co-workers how you outplayed Tiger Woods
in the latest PGA Tour event.
</P>
<P>
   And this time, your co-workers won't look at you as though
you're a pathological liar.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Woods PGA Tour Collection, a video game for personal
computers developed by EA Sports, has been designed to allow gamers
to play online during real PGA Tour events and compare their
performances against actual professional golfers, including Woods,
in near-real-time at PlayAgainstThePros
(www.playagainstthepros.com).
</P>
<P>
   According to a demonstration at the Las Vegas Invitational,
online players will be able to take their shots vs. the pros 60 to
90 seconds after he takes a shot _ all within the game's
environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time that consumers are going to be able to
play and compete in real-time against pro athletes,'' said Kathy
Frazier, public-relations manager for the Tiger Woods PGA Tour
Collection at Redwood City, Calif.-based EA Sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a pretty big deal for us.''
</P>
<P>
   As demonstrated in Las Vegas, EA Sports will employ two to four
trackers per hole to record the data from the course and relay the
information to the clubhouse via a two-way e-mail device. The
information is immediately uploaded online, and then it's up to you
to outstroke Woods.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Woods PGA Tour 2000 has been beta-tested with rave reviews
on online gaming sites, but its official launch is scheduled for
the AT&AMP;T Pebble Beach (Calif.) Invitational on Feb. 3-6. Five more
tour events are planned, but gamers will be only able to compete
against Woods, Mark O'Meara and two unidentified golfers for now,
EA Sports confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   Because the data is rushed for upload, it isn't precise. But
developers predict the use of global positioning systems to place
the ball in near-perfect spots and account for weather conditions
in the game's updates. Online players can also play against the
pros from archived games.
</P>
<P>
   Gamers won't be able to use the online version until Feb. 1, but
they can register. Online players will be eligible for prizes,
including new cars.
</P>
<P>
   So for those who don't believe you beat Woods over the weekend,
show them the brand new car you won.
</P>
<P>
   PENALTY-BOX CHAT: ESPN2 and ESPN.com took multimedia
interactivity a step further this month when it asked online
viewers to chat with selected players from a Colorado
Avalanche-Chicago Blackhawks game.
</P>
<P>
   The Jan. 9 telecast attracted 10,304 questions for the players
and ESPN2's on-air analysts in less than three hours, according to
ESPN.com.
</P>
<P>
   Before the second and third periods, ESPN.com users participated
in audio chats with players Tony Amonte and Joe Sakic, who were
chosen in an ESPN.com user poll before the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``This special event is just the tip of the iceberg in terms of
future television-Internet editorial integration opportunities,''
said John Marvel, executive editor of ESPN.com.
</P>
<P>
   START HERE, JERRY: If Cowboys owner Jerry Jones turns to the
'Net for his next coach, the choices are slim (not many fans launch
sites about NFL coaches):
</P>
<P>
   George Siefert (home.earthlink.net/(tilde)tomasik/seifert.html):
Posted are high school photos, fishing photos and Seifert's
unforgiving rendition of Bossa Nova.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Parcells (www.geocities.com/Colosseum/Bleachers/4283): A
New York Jets-hater posts a mean-spirited image gallery of
Parcells.
</P>
<P>
   Rich Kotite (members.tripod.com/(tilde)itpa/kotite.html): A Jets
fan with too much time on his hands takes a few shots at Kotite.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Green (www.dennisgreen.com): The official site of the
Minnesota Vikings coach offers live audio streaming ``without media
interpretation.''
</P>
<P>
   AT LEAST IT'S NOT BARBARA WALTERS: In case you miss how the
panelists of ABC-TV's The View will analyze the Jan. 30 Super Bowl,
Star Jones can fill you in. She's the Jan. 24 scheduled guest on
ABC.com's celebrity chat leading up to the Super Bowl. Who's next?
