<HEADLINE>
AYLSWORTH IS CONTENT AT LEHIGH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS COCOLES  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Four years later, everyone Steve Aylsworth bumps
into for the first time asks him the same question.
</P>
<P>
   It usually comes after Aylsworth tells classmates and others he
calls Malibu home.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing everyone always says is, `What are you doing
here?' '' Aylsworth said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here'' is Bethlehem, Pa., and Lehigh University, where
Aylsworth is a senior point guard for the Engineers' men's
basketball team.
</P>
<P>
   Migrating from ``Baywatch'' country to the quiet countryside of
Eastern Pennsylvania hasn't been easy for Aylsworth, a Westlake
High graduate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I'll think, `I can be going to school in San Diego,'
'' Aylsworth said. ``Four years is a long time to be away. I
thought about going to work in New York after I graduate, but I
think I'm going to work in L.A. for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't as if Aylsworth threw a dart at a map of the United
States and it landed on Bethlehem. Attending Lehigh is something of
a family tradition.
</P>
<P>
   Steve's father, John, and older brother, Bob, both played
football for the Engineers, John as a wide receiver in the early
'70s and Bob as a quarterback from 1993 to 1995 after transferring
from Tulane.
</P>
<P>
   Steve, a football and basketball star at Westlake, chose Lehigh
over several Ivy League and other East Coast schools.
</P>
<P>
   As a freshman, Steve played wide receiver on the football team
and quickly switched over to basketball for the season's final 17
games.
</P>
<P>
   But the rigors of playing two sports _ Aylsworth played in a
handful of basketball games with a football-related
separated-shoulder injury _ and Lehigh's competitive academic
standards were too much.
</P>
<P>
   ``I practiced nine months out of the year. I might have taken
two weeks off before the start of spring football. . . . I was just
getting beat up,'' Aylsworth said. ``In high school they encourage
you to play both sports because I really think football gets you
ready for basketball and basketball gets you ready for football.
</P>
<P>
   ``But at the college level, everything is so specialized. When I
started playing basketball, I was so far behind everyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   Aylsworth, a 5-foot-10, 170-pounder, really didn't blossom on
the basketball court until his junior season. Despite starting just
six of 28 games, he led the Patriot League in assists with 107.
</P>
<P>
   As a senior, Aylsworth is again leading the conference in
assists with 76 (5.3 average). He's also averaging almost four
rebounds and six points per game.
</P>
<P>
   Aylsworth, a finance major, was the basketball team's
Scholar-Athlete Award winner the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   And though Lehigh has a composite record of just 22-74 during
his career entering tonight's game at Colgate, Aylsworth won't have
any regrets when he completes his eligibility in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   There have been special moments along the way. Such as last Feb.
27, when the Engineers upset two-time defending champion and 22-5
Navy 53-45 in the opening round of the Patriot League Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``That made a tough year worth it,'' said Aylsworth, who had a
steady game (seven points, six rebounds and five assists). ``I
didn't go to a school that had a winning tradition and in some ways
it's been tough, but in others it's been very rewarding.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there is Aylsworth's history of having his biggest games
against Lafayette, Lehigh's archrival.
</P>
<P>
   His career highs in points (31 last Jan. 20), assists (eight on
Jan. 8, 1997) and rebounds (eight on Jan. 8, 1997) were established
against the Leopards. He also scored 29 points as a freshman
against Lafayette.
</P>
<P>
   Aylsworth had a similar habit in high school. As a Westlake
sophomore, he scored 32 points, including 16 in the fourth quarter,
against rival Thousand Oaks.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was kind of my coming-out game. I always had good games
against Thousand Oaks, too,'' Aylsworth said. ``My brother had a
big game to beat (Lafayette) in double overtime in football one
year. Now everywhere I go I hear `Aylsworth always has big games
against Lafayette.' That's kind of funny.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-18-00 2215EST &QL; 
