<HEADLINE>
TROJANS LOSE FLETCHER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USC freshman point guard Sandy Fletcher has been
pulled from the team by the football program after he encountered
academic problems.
</P>
<P>
   Fletcher, who is a free safety-wide receiver on the football
team, joined the basketball team last month to add depth. But the
day before last week's game against UCLA, the basketball team was
informed he would no longer be allowed to play.
</P>
<P>
   He did not suit up for last Wednesday's victory over UCLA.
Fletcher appeared in four games and averaged 1.0 points and 0.5
rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   With his departure, junior Rashad Jones is the only point guard
left to back up starter Brandon Granville.
</P>
<P>
   __ Record start If USC (10-5, 3-0) defeats Arizona State on
Thursday at the Sports Arena, the Trojans will have their first 4-0
start since the 1978-79 season, when the Pacific-10 Conference
expanded to 10 teams. USC finished 20-9 that season, which was Bob
Boyd's final year as coach, and finished second in the Pac-10.
</P>
<P>
   __ Best team? USC coach Henry Bibby was asked Tuesday if this
was the best team he has coached in his four years?
</P>
<P>
   ``The first year here was probably the best because we had some
fifth-year seniors like (center) David Crouse, but these guys are
learning a lot about each other,'' Bibby said. ``Is this the best
team? It could be. We're one or two pieces away from being a really
good team.''
</P>
<P>
   __ More attention: With a 3-0 start in the Pac-10, the Trojans
are detecting a different attitude surrounding the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``I noticed when we got back from the Washington trip
undefeated, a lot of people didn't think we could start like
this,'' forward Sam Clancy said.``And then we got a win over UCLA
and a lot of people are getting really excited now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since we're 3-0, we feel like we can play with any team in the
country.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Three more steals: USC guard Jeff Trepagnier needs three more
steals to break the school record of 62 set by Derrick Dowell in
1987. Trepagnier is tied for first in the nation in steals per
game(4.3).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
