<HEADLINE>
COMMUNIST KEEPS JOB IN RUSSIAN PARLIAMENTARY SURPRISE
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ The political party most closely associated with Acting
President Vladimir Putin unexpectedly joined forces with the
Communists Tuesday to re-elect the Communist speaker of the Russian
Parliament's lower house.
</P>
<P>
   The unexpected maneuver blocked two former prime ministers,
Yevgeny Primakov and Sergei Stepashin, from a chance to lead the
Duma, the lower house of Parliament, and prompted a furious walkout
by more than 100 deputies in protest against what one described as
a ``a cynical backroom deal,'' and another as a ``political
farce.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot take part in this pigpen,'' declared Sergei Kovalyov,
a former dissident and liberal deputy for the last eight years.
</P>
<P>
   The exact motives of Putin, now the leading candidate in the
March 26 presidential elections, were not immediately evident,
except that the maneuver offered him at least the temporary support
of a party, the Communists, which is most likely to oppose his
policies in the lower house.
</P>
<P>
   The acting president, not a member of Parliament, hinted at the
coalition in a speech to legislators earlier in the day. ``For
normal work, we need the biggest possible base of support in the
state Duma,'' he said. ``This is not a political but a purely
pragmatic position.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal was apparently put together between Unity, a party
closely linked with Putin, and the Communists in an all-day closed
negotiating session from which all other parliamentary factions
were eventually excluded. With 285 of the 450 votes in the lower
house, the current speaker, Gennadi Seleznyov, was assured easy
re-election, and other candidates withdrew. Seleznyov, a moderate
Communist, has been speaker since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Several party leaders called on their supporters to boycott the
vote, including Primakov, Grigory Yavlinsky, who heads the liberal
Yabloko party, and Sergei Kiriyenko, another former prime minister
and leader of the Union of Right Forces.
</P>
<P>
   Primakov and Yavlinsky said they would refuse to accept any
committee assignments allotted them by what Yavlinsky called the
``aggressive, obedient majority.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the allotment drawn up the Communists and the Unity party,
together with their respective allies, the Agrarians and the
People's Deputies, the Communists will head nine committees and
Unity, seven. Primakov's Fatherland party was given one
chairmanship, while Yabloko received none. Stepashin, one of those
who stepped down, is associated with Yabloko.
</P>
<P>
   After the walkout, Seleznyov, a former newspaper editor, who two
weeks ago lost a bid to become governor of a region outside Moscow,
dismissed the protesters as a minority of malcontents.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   And in a telling shift of political tactics, Boris Berezovsky, a
financier and media magnate elected as deputy from a
poverty-stricken region of the North Caucasus, told reporters
Tuesday that he too was ready for a dialogue with the Communists, a
party he once accused of having ruined the country. ``They are a
real political force,'' he said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   As several commentators pointed out, the deal between the
Kremlin and the Communists _ unthinkable before Dec. 31, when Boris
Yeltsin resigned as president _ seemed to fly in the face of the
results of parliamentary elections in December that many thought
had given the Kremlin a freer hand to pursue its agenda of economic
reform.
</P>
<P>
   `'People who voted for Unity did not intend to vote for the
Communist Party,'' said Boris Nemtsov, a leader of the Union of
Right Forces. ``They intended to support the current prime
minister.'' Putin, who became acting president upon Yeltsin's
resignation, will serve as prime minister until the March 26
elections.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the Yeltsin era, the Russian Parliament was dominated
by a Communist-led majority that frequently obstructed reform
legislation. Thanks largely to Putin's personal popularity, two new
pro-government parties soared ahead in the voting on Dec. 19,
opening the way for a Parliament that could, for the first time,
break the Communists' block on legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, with the Unity party now locked in a formal embrace
with the Communists, the lineup in the lower house looked very
different.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing Tuesday night on a television talk show, Kiriyenko and
Yavlinsky talked of joining Primakov in a new anti-government
opposition. But Kiriyenko said his party _ made up of young
free-market economists _ might still back Putin in presidential
elections. Yavlinsky is already a declared candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Since Yeltsin's unexpected resignation, Russia's political elite
has been lining up behind Putin, whose popularity continues to
soar. But other than the Chechen war, which he vowed to see through
to victory, Putin, a former agent of Russia's security agency, has
no political record, and so far no political program that
distinguishes him from several other Russian political leaders.
</P>
<P>
   By forming an alliance with the Communists, Putin seemed to
point at a new kind of political leadership that put pragmatism
ahead of ideology, or, some say, principle. ``It seems as though
with Yeltsin's exit, the Kremlin is looking to the Communists for
allies,'' Yavlinsky said. ``What we have is a bloc of the
Communists and the unprincipled.''
</P>
<P>
   Primakov, who has all but withdrawn from the presidential race,
warned that the uncontested nomination Tuesday for the speaker's
job was a dress rehearsal for an uncontested presidential election.
``There are things happening here which we deeply do not like,''
said Primakov, who six months ago was pegged as a leading contender
to succeed Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   Some commentators Tuesday said the Kremlin, having won popular
backing for its candidate, was trying to provide Russia's next
president with a loyal and predictable Parliament. ``Seleznyov will
be dependent on the Kremlin, and thankful,'' said Masha Lipman,
deputy editor of the news magazine Itogi. ``This makes him a good
figure.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
