<SLUG> BC-NETHERLANDS-AMRO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABN AMRO SET TO TRIM 10 PERCENT OF WORK FORCE  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The Dutch banking giant, ABN Amro Holdings NV, said on
Friday that it would eliminate more than 10 percent of its work
force as part of a sweeping reorganization program aimed at cutting
costs.
</P>
<P>
   The bank, the world's sixth largest, also said that it would
upgrade its online banking operation to replace the branches that
would be closed as a result of the cost-cutting move.
</P>
<P>
   The reorganization plan calls for the company to dismiss 2,500
of the bank's 24,000 workers over the next five years. The bank
also plans to shut 150 of its 900 branches in the same time period.
The company wants to save $161 million annually by 2004.
</P>
<P>
   ``ABN Amro is realizing that they need to be particularly
cautious about increasing costs,'' said Mathew Czepliewicz, a
banking analyst with Salomon Smith Barney in London. ``They aren't
certain what threat the Internet poses, but today's announcement
was a pre-emptive step.''
</P>
<P>
   European banks, which are just now beginning to embrace
electronic banking the way banks have in the United States, are
increasingly looking to cut costs by moving customers from using
full-service branches to using automated teller machines and online
banking operations.
</P>
<P>
   Very few European banks have an online platform, Czepliewicz
said.
</P>
<P>
   ABN Amro said that it would invest several hundred million
dollars in its electronic banking overhaul. The enhancements are
likely to include better telephone banking, more sophisticated
automated teller machines and full-service banking over the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Rijkman Groenink, head of ABN Amro's European division, said
that the impetus for change came from the need to have ``a more
effective organization to offer competitive prices in the European
market.''
</P>
<P>
   One rival, Deutsche Bank, the largest bank in Europe, announced
last month that it would eliminate 1,200 jobs and would bolster its
Internet banking operation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-18-00 2230EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
