<HEADER>
A9678 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-TRUANCY-AZR &LR;      01-18 1049
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRUANCY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOOLS PUT BOUNTY ON TRUANTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KARINA BLAND  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Phoenix) - Robert Simmons is a kid bounty hunter, tracking down
truant students and bringing them back to school or even into
court, if it comes to that.
</P>
<P>
   He picks up kids playing hooky who are as young as 7 and 8.
Girls who are chronically tardy sometimes turn out to have morning
sickness.
</P>
<P>
   Others tell him they don't come to school because they are bored
or bullied, that they don't have any friends or their parents don't
make them.
</P>
<P>
   Long considered a harmless part of growing up, school offi cials
are going after stray stu dents, mostly because kids who aren't in
school don't do well, and Arizona has one of the highest dropout
rates in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, it costs them money. Schools are funded based on
student attendance, typically about $2,500 per child annually.
Simmons' services cost each school less than $2,500 yearly, and
every kid he puts back in class means at least that much.
</P>
<P>
   At Chandler's Andersen Junior High, Simmons meets on this
morning with two eighth-grade girls who cut classes the day before.
They asked a girlfriend to call in an excuse, pretending to be
their mothers.
</P>
<P>
   But Peggy Benes, the attend ance clerk, has been doing this for
18 years, and she knows a fake call when she hears one. &QL; 
GIRLS WENT TO THE MALL &QL; 
The girls, 13 and 14, admit what they did and tell Simmons they
went to a mall with a 17-year-old boy who got arrested there be
cause the car he was driving was stolen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really liked him and possi bly loved him,'' the 13-year-old
said dramatically. She's known him for a week.
</P>
<P>
   And, oh, yeah, they say, the boy hit a car in the school parking
lot when he came to pick them up but told them not to tell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've learned my lesson, be lieve me!'' said the 13-year-old
who is grounded at home and _ as ordered by Simmons _ will have to
go to school on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   In that class, the girls will learn about state truancy laws,
the importance of education and how learning affects income.
</P>
<P>
   John Hittle, 14, already has been.
</P>
<P>
   He missed nine of the first 21 days of school, and his mother
wasn't happy about it. She called Simmons for help. John was
ordered by a judge to have 30 days of perfect attendance or face
fines, community service and possibly time in juvenile detention.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just laziness, I guess,'' John said. ``I didn't want to
get up in the morning.''
</P>
<P>
   This is his first year at Ander sen, transferring from Mesa af
ter his parents split up. It's been hard on him.
</P>
<P>
   But John has had perfect at tendance for three months. He went
from failing to better-than-average grades, including a B in math,
his favorite subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know school is important,'' he said, telling about a friend
who hardly ever goes. ``It just disappoints me that he's so lazy. I
tell him, `You have to go to school.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Simmons has been at Andersen since 1996, and the truancy rate
has dropped from 5 to 3 percent. He works for both the Chandler
Unified and Kyrene Elementary school districts, writing 129 tick
ets for truancy last year. Only 19 were for a second offense.
</P>
<P>
   By Arizona law, kids must go to school from the ages of 6 until
16, an archaic upper age limit left from times when kids regu larly
left school and got jobs to help support their families. Stu dents
are truant if they miss one class or an entire day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, the reality is we don't give truancy the atten
tion it deserves,'' said Judge Ron Johnson, who presides over the
Chandler Justice Court. TRUANCY COURT Every other Wednesday, he
hears truancy cases. Simmons is there, usually with 15 to 20
wayward students.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't keep kids in school today, the future is dim,''
Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   If they can't make it to class in elementary or junior high
school, he said, they are not going to make it in high school,
where there is even less supervision.
</P>
<P>
   Another problem is, when kids are ditching school, they typi
cally are up to no good, he and Simmons agree. They often hang out
with older kids, experiment with alcohol and drugs and van dalize
things.
</P>
<P>
   In his courtroom, the kids often are surprised that they are in
so much trouble. They face fines of $75, community service and
mandated perfect attend ance.
</P>
<P>
   Hard cases end up in juvenile detention. Their parents are
shocked to find out this is their problem, too. Under Arizona law,
they face $150 fines and 30-day jail terms as well as a day in jail
for each day their kid misses school. PARENTS PUT IN JAIL A judge
for 25 years, Johnson has put parents in jail for their kids'
truancy, though not in Chan dler where he has only been on the
bench since March.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it helps some parents realize this isn't just an
opportu nity for children to attend school, it's the law,'' said
Carol Parish, assistant superintendent of the Kyrene district.
</P>
<P>
   In districts without someone like Simmons, the duty most often
falls to assistant principals who deal with discipline. But they
have enough to do with kids on campus, let alone chasing them to
their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Simmons is certified by the Arizona Supreme Court to issue
citations for truancy, something assistant principals can't do. So,
his message carries more weight.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson has volunteer inter preters for parents who do not speak
English because they often rely on their kids to tell them what's
going on, and one student told his parents he was getting an award
for good work.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Johnson's referrals come from Simmons.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are not enough Mr. Simmonses to go around,'' John son
said.
</P>
<P>
   Children who are truant come from all kinds of families, said
Simmons, who traces them from housing projects to fancy houses with
red-tile roofs.
</P>
<P>
   Often, parents leave for work before their kids leave for
school, so they can't be sure they go. Some moms and dads just get
tired of the fight.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes when Simmons knocks on a door, everyone inside _
including Mom _ is still asleep, and it's almost noon. He sees lots
of parents with sub stance-abuse problems.
</P>
<P>
   And sometimes, kids run when they see him. No matter, said the
former police officer from Ev anston, Ill. He always catches up
with them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
