r a BC-TEENBIRTH-AZR &LR;      01-18 0312
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEENBIRTH-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEEN BIRTH RATE DIPS, STATE STILL RANKS HIGH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KERRY FEHR-SNYDER  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fewer teens are having babies, but it's not because more of them
are choosing to have abortions, a Washington, D.C.-based research
center said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Even in Arizona, where the teen pregnancy rate is higher than
the national average, teens reportedly are having sex less often
and using contraceptives more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overall, it's very good news,'' said Jennifer Manlove, senior
research associate for Child Trends, a non-profit research center.
``We see declines among all ages, all races, all states.''
</P>
<P>
   The findings are part of a national downward trend in teen
pregnancy since 1991. Nationally, the rate fell nearly 16 percent
from 1991 through 1997.
</P>
<P>
   That follows a slight increase from 1986, a record low, to 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some groups want to claim it's due to abstinence,'' Manlove
said. ``Others want to say contra ceptive use. It's probably some
combination of both.''
</P>
<P>
   In Arizona, birth rates for women ages 15 to 19 fell 13.6 per
cent during the same period. But the state's rate of 70 per 1,000
births still was higher than the national rate of 52 per 1,000
births.
</P>
<P>
   Manlove said that it is difficult to pinpoint why Arizona's rate
is higher, although the state's larger Hispanic population may
explain it. The largest proportion of teen births occurs among
Hispanics, she said.
</P>
<P>
   By ranking, Arizona is 31st for teen pregnancies. The lowest
rates are in Vermont at 27 per 1,000 births; New Hampshire, 29;
North Dakota, 30; Maine, 32; and New Jersey, 35.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut, at 36 per 1,000 births, tied with Iowa and
Wisconsin for sixth place. Ne braska and Pennsylvania tied for
seventh at 37. Montana, 38, New York, 39, and South Dakota, 40,
rounded out the top 10. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-18-00 2246EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000118.0407 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-18 22:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9682 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-SEPTUPLETS-FUNDS-KAN &LR;      01-18 0460
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEPTUPLETS-FUNDS-KAN </SLUG>
  
 McCAUGHEY SEPTUPLETS AT CENTER OF FUND-RAISING STORM  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT CANON  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa _ The McCaughey septuplets are still 16 years
from voting age, but they're already playing a role in presidential
politics.
</P>
<P>
   The parents of the celebrated seven-at-once siblings, Bobbi and
Kenny McCaughey of Carlisle, are opening their home this week to
raise money for the presidential campaign of Republican hopeful
Gary Bauer.
</P>
<P>
   For $250 a person, supporters of the former head of the American
Family Council can spend time with the candidate and the couple in
the home built specifically to house the family that grew from
three to 10 on Nov. 19, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Later Thursday night, the McCaugheys will sponsor a
$25-per-person fund-raiser for Bauer at a Des Moines hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Bauer has made opposition to abortion a central plank to his
long-shot campaign, which gets its first test in Monday's Iowa
caucuses. When the McCaugheys learned early in Bobbi's pregnancy
that she had seven fetuses in her womb, doctors suggested they
consider selective reduction. That technique would abort some
fetuses so others would have a better chance of living.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe,'' Bobbie told NBC shortly after the births, ``the
life of a baby starts at the moment of conception and that if you
consider reducing that pregnancy, then you're killing a human
life.''
</P>
<P>
   For six months, their church and friends kept the McCaugheys'
secret about the impending births. But when the media horde came to
Carlisle, the family turned to the anti-abortion Iowa Family Policy
Center's Marlys Popma to act as their spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Now Popma is national deputy political director for the Bauer
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``We asked Kenny and Bobbi to be involved in the campaign. I
did,'' Popma said. ``The McCaugheys are pretty big local
celebrities. When you do a house party, you want somebody people
would see something in. ... I never did ask if the children are
going to be there.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, a campaign spokesman said whether the McCaugheys'
septuplets and big sister MiKayla would be home depended on their
schedule. That night a local television station ran a story that
included comments from people describing the event as exploitive.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, columnist Rekha Basu of The Des Moines Register
wrote: ``The McCaugheys, who vowed never to exploit their children,
are allowing the septuplets to be viewed for a $250 donation to
Gary Bauer. Please tell me this is a bad joke.''
</P>
<P>
   Popma said it was not a joke, just a ``misunderstanding by the
media'' that the children were being put on display.
</P>
<P>
   ``I may actually recommend that the children not be there,'' she
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-18-00 2246EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000118.0408 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-18 22:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9683 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a TEENBIRTHRATEDIPS STATESTILLRANKSHIGH &LR;    01-18 0309
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 TEEN BIRTH RATE DIPS, STATE STILL RANKS HIGH  
 (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KERRY FEHR-SNYDER  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
