   Fewer teens are having babies, but it's not because more of them
are choosing to have abortions, a Washington, D.C.-based research
center said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Even in Arizona, where the teen pregnancy rate is higher than
the national average, teens reportedly are having sex less often
and using contraceptives more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overall, it's very good news,'' said Jennifer Manlove, senior
research associate for Child Trends, a non-profit research center.
``We see declines among all ages, all races, all states.''
</P>
<P>
   The findings are part of a national downward trend in teen
pregnancy since 1991. Nationally, the rate fell nearly 16 percent
from 1991 through 1997.
</P>
<P>
   That follows a slight increase from 1986, a record low, to 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some groups want to claim it's due to abstinence,'' Manlove
said. ``Others want to say contra ceptive use. It's probably some
combination of both.''
</P>
<P>
   In Arizona, birth rates for women ages 15 to 19 fell 13.6 per
cent during the same period. But the state's rate of 70 per 1,000
births still was higher than the national rate of 52 per 1,000
births.
</P>
<P>
   Manlove said that it is difficult to pinpoint why Arizona's rate
is higher, although the state's larger Hispanic population may
explain it. The largest proportion of teen births occurs among
Hispanics, she said.
</P>
<P>
   By ranking, Arizona is 31st for teen pregnancies. The lowest
rates are in Vermont at 27 per 1,000 births; New Hampshire, 29;
North Dakota, 30; Maine, 32; and New Jersey, 35.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut, at 36 per 1,000 births, tied with Iowa and
Wisconsin for sixth place. Ne braska and Pennsylvania tied for
seventh at 37. Montana, 38, New York, 39, and South Dakota, 40,
rounded out the top 10. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-18-00 2246EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
