<DOCNO> NYT20000118.0409 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-18 22:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9684 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-RAMS-WARNER-NYT &LR;      01-18 1096
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-RAMS-WARNER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WARNER, A WELL-TRAVELED PASSER, FINDS A COZY SPOT WITH THE RAMS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Iowa)  (rk) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is it for Kurt Warner. This is his comfort zone.
</P>
<P>
   The pressure of being the St. Louis Rams' starting quarterback,
the intense practice and preparation for the National Football
Conference championship game against the Tampa Bay Buccaneers on
Sunday in St. Louis, the quest for Super Bowl XXXIV, no, none of
that makes Warner quiver.
</P>
<P>
   The heat of handling his newfound stardom and filling the role
as the NFL's most valuable player, the leadership required, the
demands now on his time, no problem.
</P>
<P>
   For Kurt Warner, all of this appears amazingly easy. Confronted
with tremendous challenges, tugged from every angle, he firmly
stands. This is not pressure, he insists. This feels so good.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went from being the whipping boy in the Rams' training camp
two seasons ago to these great opportunities,'' Warner said Tuesday
by telephone from St. Louis. ``When I first got with the Rams, I
don't know if all of the coaches and players even knew my name. I
didn't dress for several games my first year. This season in
training camp, I was the backup and the guy that was yelled at,
that couldn't do anything right. It was like I was used as a
go-through to make points to the starting quarterback. Coaches
don't like yelling at the starting quarterback, the leader, all of
the time. It was, `Let's dump it on Kurt, the backup.' I went
through a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Well before then, he went through a football maze.
</P>
<P>
   Warner went from a bright athletic high school career in Cedar
Rapids, Iowa _ he thought he might be better in basketball than
football _ to gaining only interest from Division III schools in
Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   He signed, finally, at a Division I-AA college, Northern Iowa,
and it was for only three-quarters of a scholarship. He spent a
redshirt year and, thus, five total years at Northern Iowa,
becoming the starting quarterback only as a senior.
</P>
<P>
   After that, five pro teams worked him out (Tampa Bay was among
them) but Green Bay offered the best chance and the most money (a
$5,000 bonus to sign) but they promptly cut him in training camp,
using him, Warner said, only as a ``practice dummy, a camp arm,
pretty much somebody to throw the ball in practices so they could
save the other guys' arms.''
</P>
<P>
   Back to Cedar Falls he went in the fall of 1994 and worked at
the local Hy-Vee supermarket, ``stocking shelves at night'' and
``throwing footballs during the day to anyone I could find to catch
them.''
</P>
<P>
   He did that for six months and then took a chance with the Iowa
Barnstormers in the Arena Football League. After three years of
that, he took another chance, in NFL Europe, with the Amsterdam
Admirals with the condition that the Admirals could find an NFL
team that was interested. Only the Rams showed true interest.
</P>
<P>
   So, after Amsterdam, Warner two seasons ago was third in line
behind the Rams' starting quarterback Tony Banks. Then this season,
he was the backup to Trent Green. Green wrecked his knee in the
preseason. Warner entered.
</P>
<P>
   And made history.
</P>
<P>
   This season he set eight Rams records, tied one and tied an NFL
record while becoming the 1999 season's passing whiz across the
league. A fanciful, big-play passer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hardest times in my life have been when I've had to sit
and watch and play behind other quarterbacks,'' Warner said. ``The
hardest was in college waiting for four years to get to play. Here
with the Rams, before Trent was hurt, it was like I was on the
outside looking in. But once I got in, there wasn't one particular
game this season where I thought: `Wow, this is it. I'm comfortable
now.' I played well in college, the Arena League, in NFL Europe,
wherever I got a chance to start. I expected to play well here. I
feel more comfortable being a starter than a backup. That's my
comfort zone. I want to take control and just play football.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this type of atmosphere, I'm more focused, more of a
leader, more in control. All of the great players want the ball in
their hands. It's why I like playing quarterback so much. The
decisions are on me. I don't like leaving my fate in anyone else's
hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Few players in any sport have done more with an opportunity than
Warner did this season. He threw 41 touchdown passes and led the
Rams to a league-high 526 points and to a 13-3 record. He followed
that by throwing five touchdown passes against Minnesota last
Sunday in the Rams' 49-37 playoff victory.
</P>
<P>
   He is fortunate that the Rams feature an array of dynamic,
playmaking pass catchers and a stout offensive line that adeptly
protects him. Warner, however, maximizes those ingredients with his
cunning ability to read defenses quickly, with quick
decision-making, a strong arm, accurate passes and aggressiveness.
</P>
<P>
   How o many NFL teams that could have signed him have
ignored him? Even the Rams left him unprotected in the league's
expansion draft before this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think, even here, my teammates had respect for me as a
person but as a player only the defensive guys on our team really
knew about me,'' Warner said. ``They got the chance to go against
me every day on the scout team. The guys on defense were wondering
why I didn't get more of an opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   But now, everybody knows: Warner is hot. He is humble. Late in
the Vikings game, he strolled up and down the sideline,
congratulating most of his offensive teammates, thanking them,
talking about goals achieved and goals yet realized.
</P>
<P>
   They all know that Warner and his wife, Brenda, have overcome
hardships. Brenda's parents were killed in a tornado in Mountain
View, Ark., in 1996. And one of his sons, Zachary, now 10, suffered
a brain injury when he was four months old. Kurt Warner's teammates
know their quarterback's story _ from supermarket to one step from
the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``My parents taught me respect, honesty and faith in God,''
Warner said. ``I know that family is important and we are teaching
those things to our three children. I've tried to put character at
the forefront of my life. It is how I've prepared myself for what's
happening now.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Super Bowl is one game away, and that is really something.
I still don't think anybody can stop our offense, but if anybody
can, I'd guess it would be Tampa Bay. They match up with us. They
are solid everywhere on defense. They're good. But I believe our
offense would have to stop itself. Right now, we're all just in a
good zone.''
</P>
</TEXT>
