<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-IMAGE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VICE PRESIDENT REVS UP TO DISPEL STOIC IMAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK MONTGOMERY  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WATERLOO, Iowa _ ``Before we begin,'' an energized Al Gore told
a crowd in the middle-school cafeteria, ``if you all have the time,
I'd like to go around and shake hands with each person here.''
</P>
<P>
   Seven hundred people stood up.
</P>
<P>
   It took 40 minutes. People with cameras snapped pictures of the
vice president with his arms around their children. Those with a
gripe, such as the farmer who hated gambling, had face time. A
hipster with a shaggy beard and a ``Porn Star'' stocking cap
stepped up just to say ``hey.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore had eight tables to go when campaign aides, tapping their
watches, nudged him away. ``I'll get to you folks later,'' he said.
``I'm here for a job interview.''
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore in Iowa is a man dressed down and revved up, speaking at
a volume of 10, pumping every hand in the joint, staying late,
slapping backs, lashing out at ``fancy, union-busting law firms,''
saying ``by God'' for effect, flashing his temper and his wit, and
reminding everyone within earshot he's a fighter.
</P>
<P>
   What happened to Al Gore?
</P>
<P>
   What happened to the formal, subdued vice president who met with
Iowa Democratic leaders last spring to plan strategy for these
first-in-the-nation caucuses?
</P>
<P>
   ``Back then he was stiff, programmed, didn't seem to have the
energy,'' said former U.S. Rep. Dave Nagle of Waterloo. ``It was
like seeing your kid in the choir: He didn't do great but you were
proud of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now he's captain of the football team: focused, ready, excited
about the fight.''
</P>
<P>
   So what happened? Gore's supporters say Bill Bradley happened.
</P>
<P>
   After the former basketball star and U.S. senator from New
Jersey mounted a surprisingly strong challenge for the Democratic
nomination, Gore was transformed from the methodical ``heir
apparent,'' in Nagle's words, ``to someone who feels free to
formulate his own administration and wage his own campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's in a race now, and he's liking it.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike his battle in New Hampshire, where opinion polls show
Bradley with a slight edge, the vice president has maintained a
20-point lead over Bradley in Iowa polls.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts credit the Gore campaign's attention to labor and
farm groups _ two elements key to the party base in Iowa. Gore
stresses to small-town crowds that Bradley voted against ethanol
subsidies important to corn growers, and he voted against a bill
providing federal aid to 1993 flood victims. Bradley also has
resisted Gore's proposal for a series of debates on farm policy.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, using his own commercials that say he's ``Fighting for
Us,'' is just now beginning to conquer his image as the stoical,
trusting Tonto to Bill Clinton's Lone Ranger. ``He's been living in
the shadow of the presidency,'' said campaign manager Donna
Brazile, and it's a presidency tarnished by scandal at that.
</P>
<P>
   As such, it's not unusual for Gore to speak 30 minutes without
mentioning Clinton by name, referring instead to ``this
administration.'' For example, ``this administration'' has presided
over the ``longest economic expansion in the nation's history,'' he
notes at nearly every campaign appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Gore's vow to provide every child with health insurance
and preschool, his warnings of urban sprawl, and his $115 billion
plan for ``revolutionary improvements'' in public education subtly
suggest that Clinton, on the really tough fights, wasn't always
tough enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to do more than just play defense'' against a
Republican Congress, says Gore, typically clad these days in a blue
denim shirt and tan slacks. ``I believe the presidency is a
day-by-day fight for Americans facing all different kinds of
problems.''
</P>
<P>
   The fight for now is with Bradley, who has proposed sweeping
health-care reform that includes a program of monthly vouchers to
replace Medicaid. Gore argues that would cut benefits to the
nation's neediest.
</P>
<P>
   Battling for the party's left wing, Gore has emphatically said
the Confederate flag over South Carolina's statehouse should come
down, that Gov. George Bush's tax-cut plan is reckless, and that
affirmative action would stay in place under his leadership.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, he said he would require members of the Joint
Chiefs of Staff to agree to allow gays to serve openly in the
military, then backtracked and said he would not impose such a
litmus test.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has accused Gore of thinking incrementally, of lacking
vision. He notes that Gore has proposed more new spending on the
military than on education, despite the end of the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president's chief nemesis, however, may be Al Gore
himself _ or at least the figure lampooned in the media as the
stiffest supporting character this side of Oz's Tin Man.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have not known me,'' he told reporters last month, but
knowing the true Gore remains a challenge for Iowans.
</P>
<P>
   One morning last month, Gore addressed a Jewish breakfast group
using the precise, measured voice of Albert A. Gore Jr., the
senator's son who attended an exclusive boys' school in Washington.
``We must be a facilitator of a process of peace that leads to
security in the Middle East,'' he told the audience.
</P>
<P>
   By afternoon he was just A Gore _ a summertime farm boy who
calls Carthage, Tenn., his home. At a forum for family-farm
activists in Ames, his dialect was more southern (``That's, what,
'bout twenty-five hunnerd hogs?''), his posture more casual, and
his emotion more direct as he criticized Bradley for refusing to
debate him that day on that stage.
</P>
<P>
   One farmer defiantly asked: ``When are the Washington
politicians and the fat cats at the World Trade Organization going
to start listening to us?'' Gore's jaw tightened. ``Well, I'm here.
I'm listening,'' which drew applause.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I work in Washington, D.C., and, yes, I grew up more
there than on my family's farm,'' barked Gore, now red in the face.
``But I've got a farm today and my heart's in Smith County,
Tennessee...And let me say one other thing...''
</P>
<P>
   But by now, his critic had sat down and hushed up.
</P>
<P>
   An aide whispered to the press, ``Now that's the real Al Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   Some crowds need no convincing. At the United Auto Workers Local
838 in Waterloo, which endorsed Gore last summer, the vice
president recalled the group's struggle in the mid-1980s, and Larry
Goodwin nodded.
</P>
<P>
   Goodwin, 56, was laid off from Deere and Co. for nearly five
years during the Reagan administration, when the farm crisis
reached its depth and organized labor struggled for political
clout.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worked three part-time jobs, from 7 a.m. to midnight at a
golf course, a gas station and tending bar. And I was making half
the money I made at Deere,'' Goodwin said. ``These last seven
years, you know what? I haven't been laid off once.''
</P>
<P>
   So let Gore stomp and shout a little, he said. ``Mr. Bradley's a
nice guy,'' Goodwin explained with a grin. ``But we don't need
nice.''
</P>
<P>
   And before the pumped-up veep left the union hall, Gore made
sure he shook every hand.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-18-00 2248EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
