<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: NEW OWNER IS PLAYING AN OLD GAME
</HEADLINE>
   (With FBN-JETS-OWNER, FBN-JETS-DEAL) 
(rk) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ No news was Wood news Tuesday at the Waldorf-Astoria,
where Robert Wood Johnson IV announced that the New York Jets would
remain in a holding pattern on the subjects of the former and
possibly future coach Bill Parcells (until the weekend) and a new
stadium (presumably not until 2008).
</P>
<P>
   But along with four AA batteries, Mr. Woody (I am not sure if he
prefers his intimate tabloid designation or a more formal
appellation, such as did the late Hess) made it very clear that he
is hoping his $635 million toy comes equipped with each. ``The Jets
have never had their own stadium,'' Mr. Woody said, without
mentioning what he might contribute to help them get one. ``They
have been in the Mets stadium and now this, since 1984. Every game
they played for the last 39-plus years has been an away game. They
have never had the home-field advantage, so to speak.''
</P>
<P>
   Is that right? Then why is it that the new owner, despite
longstanding connections to the Hess family, not to mention the
Johnson &AMP; Johnson family fortune, said that Jets' season tickets
have been ``impossible'' for a longtime fan such as himself to
obtain?
</P>
<P>
   That's because Jets games have been sold out for years, with a
long waiting list of wishful thinkers. These tickets have been
purchased by people presumably rooting for the Jets on the days
Giants Stadium dresses up in green.
</P>
<P>
   Let's make one thing clear, before the mayor of New York begins
his usual act of supplication, and starts whistling in the West
Side wind, bidding taxpayer money against no one. The Jets have not
been without a home-field advantage since Leon Hess moved them
across the Hudson, while continuing to call them the New York Jets.
What they have not had is a home-owner's advantage, the kind of
profit-friendly lease arrangement that Hess never worried about
because his original $250,000 investment had multiplied like an ant
colony over the past three decades.
</P>
<P>
   In a bidding frenzy against Charles Dolan, Mr. Woody emerged as
the so-called winner last week in the Jets sweepstakes, paying
hundreds of millions more than many industry analysts believed the
Jets were worth. ``I think,'' he argued Tuesday, ``it is worth what
I paid for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it was not a very attractive deal, compared to more
recent NFL acquisitions in Washington and Cleveland, which came
with sparkling new stadiums, and all the pricey operational
amenities such as naming rights. Bill Parcells could promise to
coach this team until the Guy in the Glass has a long, white beard,
and the Jets would still require financing and land for a new home
before they would be worth what Mr. Woody paid.
</P>
<P>
   So here we go again, with another case of a very rich guy buying
something terribly inflated and wasting precious little time before
asserting that somewhere doroad, he will need bailing out.
``Eight years from now, they will be playing somewhere else,'' Mr.
Woody said of the Jets, a motion that was hip-hip-hoorayed by Paul
Tagliabue, the NFL commissioner, who rambled on about how a new
facility ``would energize the Jets' fans even more than they are
energized.''
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, most Jets' fans wouldn't care if the team played
on a landfill in Staten Island, as long as Parcells was still the
coach.
</P>
<P>
   Next season is what fans care about, and rightly so. Politicians
should see the big picture. If I were negotiating for New York, I
would tell Mr. Woody to take a number, and a comfortable seat in
the waiting room. If we find a solution to the housing problems
currently posed by the Yankees and the Mets, maybe we'll get around
to you.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Wilpon, the Mets' co-owner, Tuesday threw out the
possibility of Shea Stadium being done over for football, after a
new baseball park rises next door. A fine idea, as long as the Jets
offer to privately finance a healthy portion of the project.
</P>
<P>
   New York shouldn't pay for what it doesn't need. Its economy
seems to have survived quite nicely without a professional football
team and the eight playing dates that come with it. All of Mr.
Woody's Republican donation-making and name-dropping isn't going to
make Christie Whitman or any succeeding New Jersey governor throw
up another football stadium. He has no leverage, so for what
potential benefit other than trophy hunting should the city invest
in a team that deserted it 16 years ago?
</P>
<P>
   That was Hess, of course, but Hess' team is what Mr. Woody has
bought. For $635 million, he gets the track record, the bad stadium
lease and the opportunity to talk Parcells into keeping him company
for another year or two. What a steal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
