<DOCNO> NYT20000118.0417 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-18 22:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9698 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-ARAMARK-BOSS-ART-NYT     01-18 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARAMARK-BOSS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARAMARK CEO: A DEAL MAKER FROM HIS EARLY DAYS
</HEADLINE>
 
(Attn: Pa., Mass., Ill.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(jw) 
 By JOSEPH NEUBAUER with BRENT BOWERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
(Joseph Neubauer is the chief executive of Aramark Corp., a $7
billion managed-services company based in Philadelphia.)
<TEXT>
<P>
   When you come from a family of survivors, you've got to look
around the corner constantly. My father left Germany in 1938; he
had many siblings but was only able to get two sisters out. He
masqueraded them as princesses.
</P>
<P>
   In Israel, he set up an export-import business in cheese and
poultry. During the '48 war, I remember looking out the window at
the British soldiers in their red berets. My mother's sister in the
United States sent us care packages.
</P>
<P>
   I came to this country by boat, alone, when I was 14, to live
with my aunt and uncle. I was in a cabin with several other boys.
Our first port was Halifax; I was wearing short pants when I saw
snow for the first time. I was shocked to be able to make a phone
call without paying for it; it never occurred to me that the people
on the other end had to pay.
</P>
<P>
   I worked for my aunt and uncle in their gift shop in Danvers,
Mass. I was the first foreigner, and the first Jew, that kids in
the high school had seen. I was an outsider and had to work hard to
become an insider. This is a country that takes outsiders and lets
them become insiders.
</P>
<P>
   I learned my English from John Wayne movies and answered
questions with words like ``yup'' and ``nope.'' My English teacher,
Miss Williams, stayed after school to help me improve my speech. At
the end of my freshman year, I was the only kid who didn't get a
report card. The principal, Cornelius Xavier Dunn, told me it
wasn't fair to grade me because I had only been in the country a
few months. But he said: ``I'll make a deal with you. We'll promote
you to the sophomore class, and if you do well, you can stay.''
I've been doing deals ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Like in college, I became the head of food services for my
fraternity. Let me tell you, waiting tables for a fraternity,
you've got to serve fast. If you dawdle, your life is in danger. On
the other hand, Introl of the kitchen and the fridge on
weekends.
</P>
<P>
   My father wanted me to be an engineer _ a real profession, he
said. But I fell in love with economics while at Tufts and accepted
a scholarship to the University of Chicago Business School. I
called Dad _ he was now back in Germany _ and asked for pocket
money. He wanted to know why I had to go to business school.
``You're either born a businessman, or you're not,'' he said. But
he sent the money.
</P>
<P>
   My first full-time job was as a lending officer at the Chase
Manhattan Bank. Then I joined PepsiCo as an assistant treasurer.
When the Nixon administration let exchange rates float, I urged the
brass to liquidate a loan of 80 million German marks. ``Take the
loss now or pay more later,'' I said. I was 29. They followed my
advice, and a year later, I was a big hero. You have got to be
successful early.
</P>
<P>
   Not that I haven't made my share of mistakes. Aramark bought a
trucking company right at the beginning of deregulation. We didn't
understand what we were doing. Later, we said we ``sold'' it, but
in fact, we gave it away, along with a cash prize, like a dowry.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen years ago, my fellow managers and I fought a hostile
takeover attempt. We mortgaged our homes; we mortgaged our
children; we mortgaged anything we could find. Today, Aramark is 93
percent owned by employees, and we've created hundreds of
millionaires. Our people sell hot dogs. They do laundry. This is
not a dot-com company. We have real earnings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-18-00 2252EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
