</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IOC-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARTING WEDNESDAY: A GLOBAL CAMPAIGN TO PROMOTE THE OLYMPICS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif.)   (af)  
 By STUART ELLIOTT 
  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are two ways marketers confront crises that threaten to
tarnish the reputations of their brands. One is to frankly address
the problem in advertising, acknowledge shortcomings and pledge
reforms. The other is to pretend the problem never happened and
introduce a warm and fuzzy campaign that hopes to woo consumers
with emotional rather than rational appeals.
</P>
<P>
   Guess which approach the International Olympic Committee is
taking in its first worldwide campaign promoting the Olympics,
coming months after a vote-buying scandal sullied the squeaky-clean
image of the Games?
</P>
<P>
   Here's a hint: The announcer whose voice you'll hear in the
television commercials, narrating footage of athletes hugging, is
the king of touchy-feely Hollywood filmmaking, Robin Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Still wondering? Well, the TV, radio, print and Internet
campaign, scheduled to begin appearing Wednesday, features choir
music and phrases like ``Your spirit ennobles me.''
</P>
<P>
   One final clue: The theme is ``Celebrate humanity,'' not ``We're
sorry we blew it.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, it's difficult to imagine that the Olympic committee
or the media companies that are spending billions of dollars for
television and sponsorship rights to the games would endorse the
``mea culpa'' strategy.
</P>
<P>
   And the idea for the campaign _ reminiscent of upbeat Olympic
promotional efforts created in-house by television networks like
CBS and NBC or the work of the sports documentarian Bud Greenspan _
predates the scandal, which was centered on shenanigans in the
selection of Salt Lake City as the site of the 2002 Winter Games.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, according to executives of the Olympic committee and
its agency, the TBWA/Chiat/Day unit of TBWA Worldwide, there is no
need for breast-beating because research among consumers around the
world _ and the interest among marketers in becoming Olympic
sponsors after the 2000 Summer Games in Sydney, Australia _
indicate no lasting damage to the reputation of the games.
</P>
<P>
   ``The campaign is not designed as a response to the events of
last year,'' Michael R. Payne, marketing director for the Olympic
committee, said Tuesday at a news conference in midtown Manhattan
where reporters were offered a preview of the ambitious advertising
effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anything,'' he added, ``the crisis served to reinforce the
direction we were already focusing on, the values that make the
games ial,'' among which he listed ``the idealism of the
athletes, respect for one another, the balance between body and
mind and fair play.''
</P>
<P>
   One brand marketing expert said he approved of the decision to
ignore the scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the worst possible thing to do,'' said David Aaker, vice
chairman at Prophet Brand Strategy in San Francisco, ``because all
you're doing is calling attention to it.''
</P>
<P>
   To confirm the wisdom of its course, the Olympic committee had
an independent company, Sponsorship Research International, poll
consumers after the scandal broke to gauge the implications.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were interested to see whether the basic values, the
interest in watching, the interest in the athletes, would be
adversely affected by the crisis,'' said Richard W. Pound, vice
president of the Olympic committee and chairman of its marketing
commission. ``Perversely enough, the interest has increased.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, he added, ``we didn't change the scope or the basic
emotional story line'' of the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The appeal to ``Celebrate humanity'' is illustrated through
archival footage and photographs of triumphant Olympians like Jesse
Owens, Mary Lou Retton, Greg Louganis and Wilma Rudolph.
</P>
<P>
   Aaker gave thumbs-up to that, too, saying: ``The Olympics is all
about prestige and being global, which is why everyone wants to be
associated with it. But it lacks energy and emotion. So by doing
this, they're exactly on the right track.''
</P>
<P>
   But the campaign is not all about the thrill of victory, as ABC
Sports would say; the agony of defeat is also prominent as tales
are retold about athletes like Derek Redmond, whose serious injury
in a race in the 1992 Summer Games forced him to hobble to the
finish line.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stories that touch your heart,'' said Lee Clow, chairman
and chief creative officer at TBWA Worldwide, owned by the Omnicom
Group, ``come from more than looking in the record books to see who
won gold, silver, bronze.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, in one TV spot, Williams declares: ``Just a reminder. At
the Olympic Games, you don't have to come in first to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Another spot tweaks Nike Inc. for a taunt made in a smart-alecky
campaign by Wieden &AMP; Kennedy, which ran during the 1996 Summer
Olympics. As footage shows a Bulgarian athlete celebrating his
silver medal in weightlifting, Williams says: ``Someone once said
you don't win the silver, you lose the gold. Obviously, they never
won the silver.''
</P>
<P>
   The commercial is intended to ``respond with a certain amount of
good humor'' to Nike's paean to winning gold, Pound said, which
``we thought was not appropriate.'' Since 1996, he added, the
Olympic committee has ``built a very strong partnership with
Nike,'' that includes sponsorship ties.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are confident we will do very, very well with renewals''
among sponsors, Pound said, in addition to the two that have
already re-signed, Coca-Cola and Visa International.
</P>
<P>
   First-time advertisers are making Olympic deals, too.
Monster.com, the job search Web site owned by TMP Worldwide, signed
agreements with the Salt Lake City Organizing Committee and the
United States Olympic team to become their initial dot-com sponsor
for 2002 and 2004, in the category of ``online career management
services.''
</P>
<P>
   The Olympic committee's media partners, which include NBC, a
unit of the General Electric Co., and the Time Inc. division of
Time Warner Inc., have agreed to donate commercial time and ad
space to run the campaign, which will continue through the Summer
Games. And plans are already being made for similar campaigns for
2002 and 2004, Payne said.
</P>
<P>
   The executives at the news conference declined to quantify the
value of the time and space. But they described estimates in news
reports of $150 million as possibly low because the campaign will
run in more than 200 countries and appear often in large, expensive
media markets like Europe, Japan and North America.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
