<SLUG> BC-GLF-HOPEADV-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUVAL DOESN'T MIND NUANCES OF PRO-AM STYLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY MORGAN  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERMUDA DUNES, Calif. _ David Duval has played in five Bob Hope
Chrysler Classics and has three top-five finishes, including last
year's memorable victory.
</P>
<P>
   But Duval, otherwise known as ``Mr. 59'' in these parts after
shooting his stunning, 13-under-par score in the final round a year
ago, said there is no great secret to playing well in this five-day
affair.
</P>
<P>
   Learn to live with it, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Embrace it as much as anything,'' Duval said as he prepared
for today's first round of the $3 million event. The first-place
check is worth $540,000. ``I enjoy it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hope tournament, however, isn't for everyone. Some pros stay
away because the first 72 holes are played with four amateur
partners, and that can lead to slow play and occasionally frayed
nerves.
</P>
<P>
   Duval, for example, said he knows an amateur will step in his
line as he gets ready to putt. He knows he will be far down the
fairway waiting for his amateur partners to catch up and sometimes
hit over his head.
</P>
<P>
   He knows they will look for errant shots deep in the trees. He
also is aware there might be problems with overeager galleries
anxious to get a closer look at celebrities.
</P>
<P>
   But all of that is part is playing in the Hope, and Duval said
he has grown to enjoy it. He certainly has been successful at it,
with more than $728,000 in winnings in five previous appearances
and a scoring average of just over 68 strokes a round.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not going to be a normal tournament where there's two or
three pros,'' he said. ``It's going to be slow and we're going to
have to wait. It doesn't bother me or fluster me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoy being out here. I get a kick out of the fact that we
as pros are kind of forgotten for the first few days. When they get
to choose between me and Roger Clemens (his playing partner in
today's first round at PGA West), you know they're going after him
to get an autograph. They're not coming after me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get a kick out of that. I just think it's a neat event.''
</P>
<P>
   Duval is one of 17 former Hope winners in this week's field.
Among them are Fred Couples (1998), John Cook (1992 and '97), Tom
Kite (1993) and 70- year-old Arnold Palmer, a five-time winner.
</P>
<P>
   The field also includes tour rookies Casey Martin and Gary
Nicklaus, John Daly, Davis Love III and Jesper Parnevik. The pro-am
is loaded as well, with celebrities like Rush Limbaugh (who is
paired with Palmer today at PGA West), Bill Murray and Joe Pesci.
</P>
<P>
   The host course is Bermuda Dunes Country Club, which will be the
site of Sunday's final round. Other courses in the rotation are the
Palmer course at PGA West and Indian Wells and La Quinta Country
Clubs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-18-00 2309EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
