r a BC-KANSAS-BOARD-KAN &LR;      01-18 1004
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KANSAS-BOARD-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROUPS PLAN POLITICAL STRATEGIES FOR KANSAS SCHOOL BOARD RACES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATE BEEM  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The statewide election for the Kansas Board
of Education usually doesn't attract much attention, let alone
voters.
</P>
<P>
   But this year shapes up to be different, as incumbents and
challengers focus on the board's vote last August on new science
standards that de-emphasize evolution.
</P>
<P>
   Five board seats are up for grabs this year in the Nov. 7
balloting. Four of them are held by board members who voted for the
new science standards.
</P>
<P>
   The election could be a test of Christian conservatives'
political resilience, said Rob Boston, communications director for
Americans United for Separation of Church and State, based in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's potentially a bellwether race,'' Boston said. ``Already
you're seeing this little spurt of anti-evolutionism around the
country.''
</P>
<P>
   It should be the highest-profile state board race ever in
Kansas, said Mark Tallman of the Kansas Association of School
Boards.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than anything else,'' he said, ``the evolution issue put
the state board in the spotlight.''
</P>
<P>
   The controversy is mobilizing people to get involved in the
races, but whether that will translate into greater turnout at the
polls is another question, Tallman said.
</P>
<P>
   Groups from the moderate Mainstream Coalition to the
conservative Kansas Republican Assembly are forming plans and
committees to try to get their candidates elected.
</P>
<P>
   David Raffel of Shawnee, Kan., is working to make sure Kansans
don't forget what the board did last summer.
</P>
<P>
   A billboard on northbound Interstate 35 at the Cambridge Circle
exit depicts a backlighted Bible and the words, ``Science textbook
in Kansas public schools. No!!! Vote Aug. 1, 2000.'' The billboard,
aimed at Kansans driving into Kansas City, was put up by Save Our
Schools, a group Raffel started last fall.
</P>
<P>
   Raffel said the evolution controversy inspired him to become
involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realized I have to pay closer attention to the people I'm
voting for on a local level,'' Raffel said.
</P>
<P>
   Raffel, who said his group didn't have many members yet, has
spoken at several state board meetings, vowing to oust conservative
Republicans Linda Holloway of Shawnee, Scott Hill of Abilene, Kan.,
Steve Abrams of Arkansas City, Kan., and Mary Douglass Brown of
Wichita, Kan. None of the four has filed for re-election, although
Brown said Tuesday that she intended to.
</P>
<P>
   So far, only two candidates have stepped forward: Sue Gamble, a
Shawnee Mission Board of Education member, has filed for Holloway's
2nd District seat, and Bruce Wyatt of Salina, Kan., has filed for
Hill's 6th District seat.
</P>
<P>
   Holloway has said she'll decide by March whether she'll seek
re-election. Abrams said he'd announce in the spring, too. Hill
hasn't said publicly whether he will run again.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Wagnon, a Topeka, Kan., Democrat who voted in August
against the science standards, said he planned to run for
re-election.
</P>
<P>
   The filing deadline is June 12. The primary is Aug. 1.
</P>
<P>
   The Mainstream Coalition says it wants to form a loose statewide
network of like-minded moderate and liberal organizations so money
isn't wasted on duplicate efforts across Kansas. The coalition's
political action committee, which meets Monday, can endorse and
contribute to candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas Republican Assembly's first fund-raiser for board
candidates _ the ``I Back the Board'' Reception for the six board
members who voted for the science standards _ is set for Jan. 28 in
Topeka.
</P>
<P>
   Both groups say they're ready to recruit candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Nonprofit groups can't take direct political action but are
gearing up for educational campaigns. Kansas Citizens for Science,
formed after the board's August vote, plans to conduct workshops
for science teachers, hold events on Charles Darwin's birthday, and
distribute brochures and fliers detailing the changes made in the
science standards.
</P>
<P>
   The Christian Coalition of Kansas will send questionnaires to
candidates and publish their answers in voter guides, which will be
distributed through churches and other organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Several board members of the Jewish Community Relations
Bureau//American Jewish Committee want to get involved in the
election, and the organization plans to hold candidate forums as
the election nears, Executive Director Marvin Szneler said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can educate people about the choices out there,'' Szneler
said. ``We can encourage people to be pro-active, to be vigilant.''
</P>
<P>
   Few national groups have weighed in.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't surprise University of Kansas political scientist
Burdett Loomis. He doesn't expect national groups to send money and
resources to Kansas for the state school board races. After all,
there's a presidential election and a chance for the composition of
Congress to change this year, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But national groups are watching.
</P>
<P>
   Americans United for Separation of Church and State has followed
situations in other states in which local school board members
tried to inject religion into public schools, Boston said. Voters
traditionally haven't re-elected those members. But the Kansas
state board race will be the first test of this pattern on a
statewide basis, Boston said.
</P>
<P>
   The elections also have caught the attention of People for the
American Way, a liberal watchdog group based in Washington. It's
early in the election cycle for the group to get involved, said
Mary Jean Collins, national field director. But her organization
will be watching to see who the candidates are, Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   There will be some high-caliber challengers, said Craig Grant of
the Kansas National Education Association. His union's members _
most of the state's public-school teachers _ will make sure of
that, Grant predicted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just can't believe that we won't have enough folks running
to make it a pretty darned important race,'' Grant said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
