<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-18 23:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9810 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a PROJECTISSUESRAISEDAGAIN     01-18 0763
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 PROJECT ISSUES RAISED AGAIN  
 (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KERRY FEHR-SNYDER  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's a battle that telescope oppo nents thought they already had
won, and they resent having to fight it again. And they fear that,
in the end, their sweat lodge, prayers and ``talking circles''
won't stand against the mighty Smithsonian Institution.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is a picturesque parcel of Montosa Canyon, at the base
of Mount Hopkins south of Tuc son. The Smithsonian wants the site
for a giant telescope array to study quasars, pulsars and super
novas.
</P>
<P>
   Native Americans say the proj ect would destroy the sanctity of
their sweat lodge.
</P>
<P>
   In the middle is the U.S. Forest Service, which ultimately will
decide who gets the canyon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a popularity contest or who has more money than
someone else,'' John McGee, su pervisor of the Coronado Na tional
Forest, told a group of telescope opponents last week.
</P>
<P>
   McGee, who last August re jected the Smithsonian's original
request to build the array, says that decision is valid, but he had
to consider the second proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Foes fear that the Smithsonian will wield its influence and en
croach on the land they use for purification ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do believe we're incompati ble in that space,'' said Noel
Cree-Taulabee, a board member for the non-profit group To All Our
Relations, which is leading the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can the Smithsonian build elsewhere, or is our ceremonial
place disrupted forever?''
</P>
<P>
   Trevor Weekes, a senior Smith sonian astrophysicist, said the
Smithsonian has proposed an al ternate site, north of its visitor's
center.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's not nearly as pro tected from the light'' of metro
Tucson, Weekes said. ``What we're detecting is lights, so we need
the darkest site possible, and Montosa Canyon is shielded in all
directions.''
</P>
<P>
   The Smithsonian has not pro posed building the telescope out
side the forest because, Weekes said, ``as we go farther and
farther away from the base camp, we lose the advantage of
infrastructure _ the road, the power, all the support that the
observatory needs.''
</P>
<P>
   The government's denial of the Smithsonian's first request re
lieved sweat lodge operator Cayce Boone, a Navajo, who believed it
was final.
</P>
<P>
   But the Forest Service's recon sideration indicates otherwise.
McGee said he has no choice but to evaluate the new request.
</P>
<P>
   ``The decision I made last August stands,'' he said. ``But when
I get a proposal, we have to evaluate it.''
</P>
<P>
   Forest Service spokeswoman Gail Aschenbrenner said the most
recent proposal includes lowering the profiles of each telescope
dish, building individ ual fencing around them, moving an access
road away from the lodge and eliminating an alter nate site to the
south.
</P>
<P>
   But those changes don't amount to much for opponents, who
maintain their quiet, spiri tual getaway will be disturbed by the
telescope's appearance, whir ring motors and vehicle traffic.
</P>
<P>
   ``A win-win to you is a loss to us,'' Ricardo Harding, a member
of To All Our Relations, told McGee.
</P>
<P>
   The Smithsonian, which oper ates an observatory atop Mount
Hopkins, wants to build a $21 mil lion gamma ray telescope 1,000
yards from the sweat lodge. The telescope would have six 34-foot
dishes arranged in a hexagon with a seventh in the middle.
</P>
<P>
   The dishes would be used to detect faint blue flashes of light
known as Cherenkov radiation, which is produced when gamma rays
strike the Earth's atmos phere. The Smithsonian main tains that the
telescope won't be visible to surrounding property.
</P>
<P>
   The Smithsonian has argued that it has operated in the area
longer than the sweat lodge has. The observatory opened in 1968;
the lodge about a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   But Boone, who says his medi cine man grandfather instructed him
to build the lodge, calls that argument spurious. ``We're still
using the ancient religious site of our ancestors,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He finds it ironic that the Smithsonian, which works so hard to
preserve Indian artifacts and history, would ignore the wishes of
living Indians.
</P>
<P>
   Chucki Singer, a member of To All Our Relations, said she fears
Forest Service officials are ig noring nature's laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``The land is here to use, but if you rip up the land to build a
telescope, that's not natural,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Others complained that they should not have to keep fighting the
Smithsonian's application.
</P>
<P>
   ``To our way, it's disrespectful to keep coming back until you
get your way,'' Johnson Jose said. Indian Country Today contrib
uted to this article.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-18-00 2312EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
