<HEADER>
A9812 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKC-UCLA-LADN-(SLANG)     01-18 0548
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA IN MUST-WIN SITUATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ No one is sure how UCLA will play Thursday against
No. 2 Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   As poorly as it did against USC? As well as it did against North
Carolina? Or in some impassioned yet imprecise purgatory?
</P>
<P>
   But there's no denying the stakes: The Bruins (10-4, 1-2) must
win to keep their Pac-10 championship hopes alive.
</P>
<P>
   A loss drops them three games behind Arizona (15-2, 4-0) with a
Feb. 19 date in Tucson looming. What's more, the Wildcats already
swept the Bay Area schools (Cal and Stanford), an accomplishment
the Bruins will have difficulty duplicating.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to win (Thursday) if we're going to stay in the title
picture,'' UCLA senior Sean Farnham said. ``If we drop three back
in the first half (of league play), we'll be digging ourselves a
large hole.''
</P>
<P>
   If past is prologue, the game will be decided in the final
minute. The Bruins won seven of 10 in Pauley in the 1990s, but a
mere 21 points separated the teams. In fact, UCLA has not beaten
Arizona by double digits at home in 13 years.
</P>
<P>
   But the most telling statistic of all is this: The winner of the
UCLA-Arizona game in Pauley has won the conference championship 11
of the last 14 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're going to compete for the Pac-10, then we have to beat
Arizona and we have to defend our homecourt,'' junior Rico Hines
said. ``This is a must-win game.''
</P>
<P>
   UCLA's challenge is avoiding the temptation of tempo. Depleted
by injuries and attrition, the Wildcats have just seven scholarship
players and seem vulnerable to pressure defense, fast breaks and
fatigue.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins, as always, love to run. But they have played best
this season when using tempo-killing defenses like a 3-2 zone or
sagging man-to-man. The closer big men Dan Gadzuric and Jerome
Moiso are to the basket, the better UCLA's chances. It worked
against DePaul, it worked against Purdue and it worked against
North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order to keep our two 7-footers in the game and out of foul
trouble, it makes sense to have them as the last line of defense
protecting the basket,'' Bruins coach Steve Lavin said. ``The
(zone) and the (sagging) man-to-man accomplish the same thing: They
force people to shoot over the top.''
</P>
<P>
   Arizona leads the Pac-10 in 3-point shooting (37.3 percent), but
with speedy freshman guards Jason Gardner and Gilbert Arenas, the
Wildcats prefer fast breaks to half-court grinders. They struggled
against Washington and Washington State last weekend, and both
teams made Arizona play slowly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you can tire Arizona,'' said Stanford coach Mike
Montgomery, who lost to the Wildcats two weeks ago. ``Over the
course of an 18-game (league) season, it's possible they could get
worn down. But in any given game, they're used to playing big
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``UCLA needs to do what it does best.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Rush update: UCLA forwarded the JaRon Rush investigation to
the NCAA last week, but school officials don't expect a decision
until late this week at the earliest.
</P>
<P>
   Once the NCAA rules on the case, the Bruins have the right to _
and are expected to _ appeal. That process could take another week
or two.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-18-00 2322EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000118.0427 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-18 23:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9813 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GIULIANI-MCCAIN-BALLO     01-18 0961
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIULIANI-MCCAIN-BALLOT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 GIULIANI REBUKES GOP FOR BID TO KEEP McCAIN OFF BALLOT   By CLIFFORD J. LEVY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani rebuked New York's Republican
State Committee Tuesday for trying to knock Sen. John McCain off
the presidential primary ballot in roughly half of the state's
Congressional districts, risking a new rift with party leaders he
had otherwise been courting in his expected run for the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani is supporting Gov. George W. Bush of Texas in the
presidential race, as is the state party. But he said he had long
opposed efforts to use the state's famously cumbersome ballot laws
to fend off insurgents, describing what he said was the value of
primaries in battle-hardening the front-runner and showcasing the
party's principles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The primaries should be open, whether you like the people who
are going to be in it or not,'' Giuliani told reporters at City
Hall. ``It gives a chance for the party to really demonstrate what
it's all about. I think it would be a very, very good contest
between Senator McCain and Governor Bush. I think Governor Bush
would ultimately win, and I think it would strengthen him in his
ability to carry the state in November.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani did not specifically refer to Gov. George E. Pataki,
who approved of the petition challenges, or other state Republican
Party leaders. The mayor made his comments as lawyers for the
Republican State Committee filed challenges to McCain's nominating
petitions in 16 of the state's 31 Congressional districts.
</P>
<P>
   In adding his voice to the longstanding criticism of the primary
system in New York, Giuliani is likely to complicate his relations
with the state party, which have been improving in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate race is expected to be close, and Giuliani could face
difficulties if he does not have the spirited backing of party
cadres in Republican strongholds in the suburbs and upstate, which
he has sought to cultivate in the last year. These are the same
officials who have lined up behind Bush, spearheading his petition
drives and running as his delegates to the Republican National
Convention.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the mayor is known for being outspoken, and some party
officials responded to his remarks Tuesday by saying that while
they were not pleased, Giuliani was still their candidate against
the prospective Democratic nominee, Hillary Rodham Clinton. They
also suggested that Giuliani's attack on the system could bolster
his reputation for independence, which could help him with
Democrats and unaffiliated voters, not to mention McCain
supporters.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who is suing in U.S. District court to gain a ballot
spot across the state in the March 7 primary, said once again
Tuesday that the party was using communist tactics to ensure a
victory for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Another Republican contender, Steve Forbes, whom the state party
considers less of a threat to Bush, spent $750,000 on lawyers and
petition gatherers in New York and is expected to be on the ballot
across the state. The party is not challenging his petitions. Three
others _ Gary L. Bauer, Sen. Orrin G. Hatch and Alan Keyes _ have
withdrawn from the New York primary because the rules are too
daunting.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Allen, a spokesman for the state party, declined to comment
on Giuliani's remarks. But the party issued a long statement
calling McCain a hypocrite, pointing out that he twice brought
petition challenges against weaker candidates when he ran for
re-election to the Senate from Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``Senator John McCain did not hesitate to use the ballot access
provisions of Arizona law,'' the party's statement said.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki's press office did not respond to three requests for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, who is a friend of both Bush and McCain, has
repeatedly feuded with the state party since he endorsed the
incumbent, Mario M. Cuomo, a Democrat, for governor in 1994 over
his challenger, Pataki, who won.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly enough, the schism began to heal last summer after Pataki
persuaded Rep. Rick A. Lazio of Long Island to abandon plans to
force a Republican primary against Giuliani in the Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Giuliani said that while he would not have necessarily
wanted a Senate primary, he would not have resorted to using the
ballot laws to clear the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody welcomes a primary,'' the mayor said. ``Even when it's
good for you, you don't realize it at the time. You only find out
later when you won the election that it actually helped you win.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, when he first ran for mayor, Giuliani unsuccessfully
challenged the petitions of Ronald S. Lauder, who entered the
Republican primary, and then, after he lost to Giuliani, ran on the
Conservative Party line in the general election.
</P>
<P>
   After Giuliani lost the general election to the Democratic
nominee, David N. Dinkins, he questioned whether the expensive
primary challenge by Lauder was one factor in his defeat. Giuliani
did not face a primary in 1993, when he won his first term, or in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   Under the complex system, campaign organizations are required to
collect signatures in all 31 districts, with the threshold
depending on the number of registered Republicans in the district.
Candidates can qualify in some districts and not others.
</P>
<P>
   In each district, voters cast ballots for delegates to the
national convention who are pledged to the candidates. The
delegates with the three highest totals win convention spots.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic candidates are also required to collect
petitions, but their system is relatively easier. Both major
contenders this year, Al Gore and former Sen. Bill Bradley, are
expected to be on the ballot statewide.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-18-00 2323EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000118.0428 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-18 23:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9815 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-HKN-RANGERS-HURRICANE     01-18 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-HURRICANES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH A PEEK AT SPRING, RANGERS BEAT HURRICANES
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For the first time in more than two months, the New
York Rangers can call themselves a playoff team.
</P>
<P>
   Not since Nov. 11 had the Rangers been one of the top eight
teams in the Eastern Conference. Not until Tuesday night. Valery
Kamensky had a goal and two assists, and Mike Richter did the rest,
making 24 saves as the Rangers held off the Carolina Hurricanes,
3-2, at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   The victory avenged a 1-0 loss in Carolina last week and moved
the Rangers past the Hurricanes and into a tie with the Pittsburgh
Penguins for seventh in the conference standings with 44 points.
</P>
<P>
   The victory was the Rangers' fifth in their last six games,
third in a row, and it improved their record to 17-20-7-3. Two
months ago, the fans were calling for the firing of coach John
Muckler and Neil Smith, the team president and general manager.
Now, the Rangers are in position to earn their first postseason
berth in three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   The Hurricanes, still without the unsigned center Keith Primeau,
were playing their second game in two nights, and it showed.
Carolina, on a three-game losing streak, was 5-11-1 over their last
17 games. The Rangers, meanwhile, had won four of their last five
games.
</P>
<P>
   This time, the Rangers jumped on the Hurricanes early _ on the
game's first shot.
</P>
<P>
   The goal belonged to Kamensky, who has now scored a goal in each
of the Rangers' last three games. His fourth goal of the season
came two minutes into the contest and was set up by defenseman
Sylvain Lefebvre, who chipped the puck from his own blue line over
Carolina defenseman Marek Malik, just as Kamensky was jumping onto
the ice for a line change.
</P>
<P>
   Lefebvre's heads-up play sent Kamensky in on goaltender Arturs
Irbe for a breakaway. Irbe was no match for Kamensky, who beat the
Hurricanes goaltender from the edge of the left circle.
</P>
<P>
   The one-goal lead lasted until 13:44 of the first period, when
Bates Battaglia tied the score off an assist from Paul Coffey, who
leads all active players in points against the Rangers with 83.
Battaglia took a pass from Coffey, which Radek Dvorak tipped, and
beat Richter with a backhander through the skates.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers also went into the first intermission on the power
play, after Kamensky drew a holding penalty on Curtis Leschyshyn
with 18.2 seconds left in the period. The Rangers have been better
on the power play lately, and Kamensky has been one of the reasons.
</P>
<P>
   This time he assisted on Adam Graves' 16th goal of the season,
at 1:07 of the second period, and the Rangers had a 2-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Graves' goal _ he poked in the rebound of a little Kamensky
wrist shot _ was the 263rd he has scored with the Rangers, moving
the left wing _ and acting captain in the injured Brian Leetch's
place _ past Vic Hadfield and into sole possession of fourth on the
Rangers' career scoring list.
</P>
<P>
   At 13:46, the Rangers took a 3-1 lead, about 3 1-2 minutes after
Richter had preserved the 2-1 lead with a phenomenal kick save with
his right leg to rob Andrei Kovalenko.
</P>
<P>
   John MacLean's 10th goal of the season, his third in two games,
and his seventh goal over the last nine games, made it 3-1.
</P>
<P>
   This one was set up by Kevin Hatcher, who gobbled up a loose
puck at the left point before jumping into the rush. Hatcher, an
offensive-minded defenseman, made a strong play, carrying the puck
beyond the goal line, then dropping a one-handed pass back to
MacLean just off the left post.
</P>
<P>
   The goal was important because the Hurricanes seized the
momentum late in the period. At 17:33 _ seconds after Irbe stoned
Hatcher's backhand attempt on a 2-on-1 break _ Sami Kapanen scored
his 17th goal of the season to cut the lead to 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   Kapanen had originally been trying to pass from the right
circle. Mathieu Schneider blocked the pass, but the puck went right
back to Kapanen. Richter had anticipated the pass and was now
off-balance. As Richter fell backward, Kapanen's shot went off the
goalie's glove and into the net.
</P>
<P>
   It turned out to be the last goal of the game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
