<SLUG> BC-RAYTHEON-OUTLOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAYTHEON TURNS DOWNBEAT ON EARNINGS A 3RD TIME
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., R.I., Va.)   (rk) 
 By ANDREW POLLACK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Raytheon Co. shocked Wall Street again Tuesday by lowering
its profit forecast for the third time since September, the latest
sign that the military contractors created by a wave of mergers in
the 1990s are proving difficult to manage.
</P>
<P>
   The Lexington, Mass., company said it now expected earnings for
the fourth quarter of 1999 to be 20 to 25 cents a share, less than
half the analyst consensus of 59 cents. The company also reduced
its profit expectations for all of 1999 and for 2000 to well below
the levels it had forecast in October, when it had last lowered its
outlook.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon class B stock plummeted 25 percent, closing at $19 a
share, down $6.375. The shares have lost about three-quarters of
their value since July, with the biggest fall _ 44 percent _ coming
on the day of the last profit warning in October. The first warning
came in September.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon acquired several military businesses, notably those of
the Hughes Electronics Corp. and Texas Instruments, as part of a
consolidation encouraged by the Pentagon that was intended to
adjust the industry to the end of the Cold War. But the company,
which makes the Patriot missile and the Tomahawk cruise missile,
has had trouble integrating and managing its new properties.
</P>
<P>
   ``The assessment of markets and competition that they would
normally do continuously probably fell by the wayside in this
consolidation process and they lost track of what was happening in
their business,'' said Paul Nisbet, analyst with JSA Research in
Newport, R.I.
</P>
<P>
   What was especially worrisome to some analysts was that the
latest profit shortfall stems not only from problems in the
military business but from delays in producing and shipping
business aircraft. That operation, known as the Raytheon Aircraft
Co. and built around the Beech Aircraft Co. that Raytheon acquired
in 1980, had appeared to be running smoothly.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is kind of like a one-two punch for Raytheon,'' said
Loren Thompson, military analyst at the Lexington Institute in
Arlington, Va. ``Back in October, most of the problems were in the
defense area. Now it appears they are having additional problems in
the general aviation unit.''
</P>
<P>
   The problems represent a setback to Daniel P. Burnham, who took
over as Raytheon's chief executive in December 1998 after having
had success running the aerospace business of AlliedSignal.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon, which has eliminated thousands of jobs in the last two
years, seems to be following the pattern set by Lockheed Martin
Corp., which suffered setbacks and earnings disappointments as it
sought to digest acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   The Boeing Co., another of the Big Three aerospace companies,
also has had difficulties, but mainly in commercial aircraft
manufacturing. Boeing has suffered fewer problems from its
acquisition of McDonnell Douglas and the aerospace unit of Rockwell
International because those companies did not overlap much with
what Boeing was already doing, Nisbet said.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon said it expected earnings per share for 1999 as a whole
to be $1.15 to $1.20, compared with the $1.40 to $1.50 that the
company had given analysts in October, when it last lowered its
forecast. For 2000 the company expects earnings per share of $1.60
to $1.75, down from the $2.10 to $2.25 forecast in October and less
than half the $4 or more that analysts had estimated before then.
</P>
<P>
   In explaining the latest setback in 1999 results, the company
said that production and shipment of 19 aircraft were delayed and
that it made accounting adjustments to the results of Raytheon
Aircraft. It also cited a delay in signing a $1.3 billion airborne
radar contract with Britain and higher interest expenses and
banking fees because its credit rating was lowered in November.
</P>
<P>
   The reduced profit expectations for 2000, it said, stem from a
three-month delay in Federal Aviation Administration certification
for a new business jet, a lower outlook for shipments of commuter
aircraft and fewer sales prospects overseas for various missiles,
especially the Patriot.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon said it would restate its earnings for 1997, 1998 and
1999 to reflect new accounting standards on recognizing revenue
from aircraft sales. The company said the restatement would change
revenues less than 1 percent each year and earnings less than 6
cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman said executives would have no further comment until
results were released next Tuesday. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
