u a BC-TORRICELLI-INVEST-NYT     01-18 0602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TORRICELLI-INVEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.J. SENATOR PROFITS FROM PRIVATE STOCK INVESTMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DAVID KOCIENIEWSKI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ Sen. Robert Torricelli's $5,000 investment in a
privately held Internet company has grown to a value of $225,000,
even though he promised five years ago to avoid making investments
that are not available to the general public, his aides
acknowledged Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But faced with criticism from campaign finance groups, his aides
defended the action, saying that elected officials should be able
to profit from the surging stock market.
</P>
<P>
   The Asbury Park Press reported Sunday that Torricelli, a
Democrat, stood to make an enormous profit from his 1999 investment
in e.Volve Technology Group, a company that was bought later in the
year by a publicly traded Internet company, eVentures Group, which
is based in Jersey City.
</P>
<P>
   The transaction does not violate the law or the U.S. Senate's
ethics regulations. Torricelli was one of 15 people offered a
chance to buy the stock, but his aides said it did not constitute
any form of preferential treatment.
</P>
<P>
   They also defended a separate transaction in which Torricelli
bought shares in a company that sells diet plans on the Internet
and has announced that it plans later this year to offer stock for
public sale, its initial public offering.
</P>
<P>
   ``He changed his mind about participating in IPOs after
consulting with his financial advisers, because the senator knew
that all his investments would be disclosed to the public,'' said
Richard McGrath, his spokesman. ``But there has never been a
conflict of interest. He completely adheres to the Senate ethics
rules. And if he does eventually make a proft, it's because he's
willing to take a big risk.''
</P>
<P>
   But government watchdog groups say that elected officials raise
troubling ethical questions whenever they take advantage of
investment offers that are not available to the public because they
create the perception of preferential treatment and the potential
for conflict of interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``This kind of transaction creates the potential for the person
doing a big financial favor for an elected official and coming back
later to ask for a payback,'' said Fred Wertheimer, president of
Democracy 21, a nonpartisan public policy group. ``They shouldn't
do it,''
</P>
<P>
   McGrath said the senator felt comfortable in investing in the
companies, and in reversing his policy of avoiding private
investments, because neither company was involved in any business
concerned with his official duties.
</P>
<P>
   McGrath also indicated that Torricelli's profit was only on
paper so far. He is forbidden to sell the stock in eVentures until
Sept. 21, 2001, and its price could fall by then, McGrath said.
</P>
<P>
   During the last decade, several members of Congress have been
harshly criticized for investing in a stock before it was available
to the public. When he was in the Senate, Alfonse M. D'Amato of New
York, and Rep. Tom Foley of Washington state, who was speaker of
the House, both profited from such deals.
</P>
<P>
   Torricelli's two stock purchases last year are the latest in a
series of investments and fund-raising entanglements that have
placed his financial dealings under scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   He made his pledge to avoid participating in such offerings in
1994, after he was heavily criticized for a $144,000 profit from a
private purchase of stock in a New Jersey bank. At the time, he
promised to avoid such offers in the future and to put his entire
portfolio in a blind trust.
</P>
<P>
   ``My integrity is worth more than profits,'' he said at the
time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
