<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS TRAVEL: BRANDING COMPETITION IN MARKET FOR INTERNET
BOOKINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOE SHARKEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the landmark 1967 film ``The Graduate,'' there is a famous
scene at a cocktail party where a helpful older man whispers this
single word of business advice into the ear of the callow,
befuddled young Dustin Hoffman: ``Plastics.'' Remake the movie
today and you'd have to change the line to ``Branding.''
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere is the branding game more intense than in Internet
commerce. And the competition is especially rough in online travel
booking, where about three dozen companies, with Expedia.com and
Travelocity.com far out in front, are competing for a share of the
rapidly expanding Internet travel market. Though the online
domestic travel market is currently a minuscule $5 billion out of
about $550 billion spent on travel annually, it is expected to
reach $38 billion by 2003.
</P>
<P>
   By then, after an inevitable shakeout, only a few major brands
will dominate the consumer part of the business, which now accounts
for about 30 percent of online sales, most of them in leisure
travel.
</P>
<P>
   As the overall online travel market grows, however, projections
indicate that business-to-business sales _ which encompass most
corporate travel spending _ will grow to 80 percent of the online
market from the current 70 percent, while business-to-consumer
sales _ of the sort now dominated by Expedia.com and
Travelocity.com _ will decrease to 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cost of creating brand awareness is staggering,'' said
Gadi Maier, the president and chief executive of GetThere.com, an
online travel company that used to be known as Internet Travel
Network before Maier and other top executives took a hard look last
year at the high-stakes playoffs his company was competing in and
said, in effect, we're outta here.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the company _ which regards its booking engine
technology as superior to the competitors for the complexities of
corporate travel booking _ chose a new game. With financial backing
from United Airlines, American Express Travel Related Services and
others, the company changed its name, went public last November,
and has begun concentrating instead on licensing its technology to
businesses that will in one way or another repackage and resell the
online product, mostly for business travel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've basically outsourced the branding to companies who are
established brand names and have the wherewithal to support those
brands,'' Maier said.
</P>
<P>
   GetThere.com has quietly lined up an impressive roster of
corporate customers, among them American Express, to license its
technology. American Express is about to start offering its clients
a new booking engine from GetThere.com. Since 1998, American
Express, through its American Express Interactive unit, has used
Expedia.com's online booking engine.
</P>
<P>
   An American Express spokeswoman said that it would shortly begin
offering the GetThere.com engine ``side by side'' with the
Expedia.com engine to corporate clients, who can decide whether to
go with the GetThere.com technology.
</P>
<P>
   Maier said that the GetThere.com booking engine and corporate
services, adapted to reflect a specific company's travel policies
and usage, would ultimately become the industry standard for the
complexities of corporate online booking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now,'' he said, ``a lot of business travelers have to
make arrangements with a phone call to the corporate travel
agency.'' That is often frustrating for the employee and
inefficient for the corporation, since most of the booking work is
done, in effect, by hand, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the day, arranging travel is really a computer
problem,'' he said. ``It's really just a linear program.'' That is
especially true for corporate travel, where technology can keep
track not only of individual employee travel portfolios but also of
bulk discounts, upgrades and other intricate variables. Also,
technology never acts like it is being imposed upon, the way a
travel agent at the end of the phone line can, Maier said.
</P>
<P>
   American Express, for its part, said it would welcome the cost
savings represented by a shift of more of its travel business to
online booking rather than using its travel agents.
</P>
<P>
   Expedia.com contends that it is happy with the way things are
working out _ even though American Express is replacing Expedia.com
altogether in favor of GetThere.com as the booking engine for its
own consumer travel Web site. American Express is planning to
rejuvenate the site (www.americanexpress.com/travel) for a bigger
push into the market now dominated by the Expedia.com and
Travelocity.com brands.
</P>
<P>
   Still, with one-time competitors like GetThere.com sublimating
their brands to focus on a new strategy, Expedia.com cannot resist
noting that its own brand is riding high in the online travel
business, whatever American Express does at the corporate end.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really are focused on owning and not renting our
customers,'' said Suzi Levine, the Expedia.com product manager. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
