<HEADLINE>
SAFETY REIGNS AT YEARLY LAS VEGAS GUN SHOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By WILLIAM HERMANN  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Las Vegas, Nev.) - Wilhelm Bub its stood amid thousands of
gleaming revolvers, rifles and other deadly weapons Tuesday and
addressed the hottest topic at the world's biggest gun show:
</P>
<P>
   Safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of the safest pistols in the world,'' Bubits, a
Steyr Pistols engineer, said about his newest creation, the M-9
semiautomatic pistol.
</P>
<P>
   ``I design safety right into the heart of it.''
</P>
<P>
   He showed how the M-9 can be disabled by turning a key in the
base of the magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``See?'' he said triumphantly, noting that he couldn't pull the
trigger or even disassemble the pistol. ``This gun is so safe it's
even approved for sale by Mas sachusetts.''
</P>
<P>
   As usual, the approximately 1,200 booths at the annual Shot Show
displayed many of the most lethal weapons legally available. But at
display after display, this year's main message was safety.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. firearms industry _ having seen what happened to Big
Tobacco _ feels besieged by lawmakers seeking new gun-con trol laws
and public officials threatening to litigate.
</P>
<P>
   In response, the show's safety products seem to be saying more
than just: ``You can no longer shoot this gun.''
</P>
<P>
   They're also pleading: ``Don't sue me!''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-nine U.S. cities and counties are suing gunmakers,
seeking compensation for the costs of police, emergency, court and
jail services related to illegal or irresponsible firearms use.
</P>
<P>
   None is in Arizona. Last year the Legislature prohibited the
state, counties or cities from suing gun manufacturers except for
defective products.
</P>
<P>
   Still, gunmakers have gotten the point.
</P>
<P>
   Remington is showing off its new EtronX rifle system, which
fires a cartridge electronically instead of by having a firing pin
slam into a primer within a brass case.
</P>
<P>
   The safety advantage, Reming ton spokesman Abe Deffenbaugh said,
is that, ``When you turn and withdraw a safety key on this rifle
the whole electronic firing system is shut down.''
</P>
<P>
   Several manufacturers, includ ing Heckler &AMP; Koch Inc., are
offering trigger-blocking devices that, once locked, make it impos
sible to activate the weapon's firing pin.
</P>
<P>
   Another booth touts CCL Secu rity Products gun locks. Spokes man
Jim Stafstrom noted that three years ago there were only three
manufacturers showing gun locks at this big trade show.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year I've counted 25 companies selling locks,'' he said.
``Does that tell you what is important in the business right now?''
</P>
<P>
   In October, several gun manu facturers including Sturm, Ruger _
based in Prescott _ Smith and Wesson, Colt, Glock and Beretta met
in Washington, D.C., with city representatives on how to improve
safety in their products.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to work with the mayors on gun safety,'' said Doug
Painter, director of the National Shooting Sports Foundation, an
industry association and the sponsor of the Shot Show.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened at Columbine High School has put a new spot
light on this industry. We are in a climate of litigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Not far from Painter, Scotts dale businessman Tom Loeff, owner
of Advanced Security Systems, was displaying his locked gun cases.
</P>
<P>
   Loeff designed the small pis tol-sized Gun Vault for people who
want to be able to grab a pistol fast but have it remain
untouchable by anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   The little metal safe has a hand-sized impression on top. By
moving one's fingers in a set sequence within the impression, a
door swings open to reveal the pistol.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got the idea for the vault 10 years ago,'' Loeff said. ``But
only recently has it caught on big. Our sales are up 80 percent in
the last 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``Safety is what the industry has got to start being about,''
Loeff said. ``Manufacturers know it, the states know it, the public
knows it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-18-00 2337EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
