<SLUG> BC-CELEBRITY-MOB-TRIAL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM GRIT TO GLITTER TO GRIT: MURDER CHARGE BRINGS CLUB OWNER
HOME  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla.)   By ALAN FEUER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It is 2,000 miles due south on Interstate 95 from
Staten Island to Miami Beach, which is far, but not far enough for
a man to escape his past.
</P>
<P>
   That is the story of Chris Paciello. In the last 12 years, this
handsome 28-year-old, bundled in muscle and charm, has embarked on
a journey that has taken him from what the government calls the
gritty ranks of a New York Mafia crew to the glittering nucleus of
southern Florida's pink-martini-with-a-supermodel crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, Paciello, who owns a miniature empire of South
Beach night spots, has surrounded himself with starlets, ocean
vistas and a swing-first macho allure. Despite his success, federal
prosecutors say he is nothing but a street tough who fled his
Staten Island neighborhood and never thought that the neighborhood
would yank him back.
</P>
<P>
   Two months ago, Paciello's roots caught up with him. He was
charged in a federal racketeering indictment with killing a Staten
Island woman in 1993 while running with what has been described in
the court papers as a vicious Bonanno crime family robbery crew.
</P>
<P>
   Now, instead of relaxing in his beachfront manor on San Marino
Drive in Miami Beach, he is confined to house arrest at his
mother's home on Staten Island. He no longer hobnobs with
superstars. He appears in court with his co-defendants _ guys with
nicknames like Gonzo, Little Joey and Fabritz.
</P>
<P>
   The trial, which is to begin in September, is so emblematic of
the cross-pollination between celebrity culture and the mob that it
sometimes seems as if the main players are auditioning for their
movie roles.
</P>
<P>
   Paciello appears at court hearings blowing kisses to his
supporters. His former girlfriend, a model, is whisked from the
courthouse in a white limousine. Even the receptionist at the law
firm representing Paciello has a part: she refers all callers to a
publicity agent who has been managing Paciello's image during his
defense.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 18, 1993, prosecutors say, Paciello drove the getaway
car in a robbery that resulted in the death of a Staten Island
woman, Judith Shemtov, 46. Three months earlier, the government
says, Paciello smashed through the window of a bank in the Staten
Island Mall with a sledgehammer and made off with more than
$300,000 in cash.
</P>
<P>
   From 1987 to 1993, according to other court papers, Paciello
robbed numerous stores, pharmacies and video shops. He took part in
nearly a dozen club and bar brawls, prosecutors say. He earned the
name the Binger, prosecutors said, because of his penchant for
bingeing on mayhem.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the government has asserted that Paciello was not ``a
lone player in instances of street thuggery'' but was tied to a
``powerful organized crime syndicate.'' According to the
indictment, he was a member of the Bath Avenue Crew, a group of
young street thugs who grew up along Bath Avenue in Bensonhurst,
Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   The crew reported to Anthony Spero, the former acting boss of
the Bonanno family, and Joseph Benanti, a Bonanno family soldier,
the indictment said. Six crew members as well as Spero and Benanti
are awaiting trial with Paciello.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the most chilling evidence against Paciello comes from a
secretly made tape that was introduced at a detention hearing.
According to a transcript of the tape made in September, two months
before his arrest, he is heard discussing a South Beach nightclub
owner who once worked with him , Gerry Kelly, with an undercover
agent posing as a dishonest cop.
</P>
<P>
   ``He always drives drunk, you can arrest him,'' Paciello tells
the agent. Later, his intentions turn darker: ``We got to get him
beat up. I got to get him whacked.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Kelly, who is under 24-hour police protection, said
he was stunned by the tape. ``All of us thought he was just a young
guy who made it big, who was very handsome, who hooked up with the
right people and made it into the celebrity circle,'' Kelly said.
</P>
<P>
   Paciello has denied the charges against him. His lawyer, Roy
Black, has said that Paciello is a self-created man, a Staten
Island boy reinvented in Miami Beach, who has been accused by the
government because of his fame, not for ties to organized crime.
</P>
<P>
   Many of Paciello's colleagues in Florida agree.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Paciello was adored in South Beach. He has been featured
in publications like People, Details, and The Wall Street Journal.
He has donated to charities. Last year, he was the host of a gala
for Miami Beach's mayor, Neisen Kasdin. In December, 70 friends
turned up in U.S. District Court in Miami for his bail hearing.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Raised in a humble home on a humble street on Staten Island,
Paciello was born Christian Ludwigsen. According to his lawyers, he
has gone by his mother's maiden name since moving to Florida in
1993 because he has ``no meaningful relationship'' with his father,
George Ludwigsen.
</P>
<P>
   Paciello wanted to be a mobster shortly after graduating from
high school, prosecutors said. Around the same time, he appeared on
the fringes of New York City's nightclub scene. He made inroads
into the club world through a man named Michael Caruso, a club
promoter who worked at the Limelight in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, the two men opened a nightclub in Miami Beach on a lot
owned by Carlo Vaccarezza, a former driver for John J. Gotti, the
one-time Gambino family boss, according to testimony by Caruso at
the trial of Peter Gatien, the Limelight's owner, who was acquitted
of drug conspiracy charges in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The club was called Risk. Months after it opened, Risk burned
down under suspicious circumstances, federal prosecutors say,
allowing Paciello to collect a $250,000 insurance claim and open a
new club, Liquid, with the better-connected Ingrid Casares, the
heir to a wealthy Cuban family and a friend of celebrities like
Madonna.
</P>
<P>
   With Ms. Casares as his partner, Paciello's credibility and
income skyrocketed. They opened a restaurant called Joia in 1998,
and soon after, another club, the Bar Room. Gossip columnists
linked Paciello to Jennifer Lopez, the actress; Niki Taylor, a
model; and Sofia Vergara, the co-host of a Spanish-language
television show.
</P>
<P>
   But Paciello felt diminished by his success. During his
conversation with the undercover agent, captured on tape four
months ago, he said he had become a weakling in Miami Beach.
According to the transcripts, he talks about putting on his
``costume'' to go ``out trick or treating'' again _ a phrase the
government says is a euphemism for returning to his days as a
robber.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Ms. Casares has supported Paciello, saying through Ms.
Grubman, the publicity agent, ``I stand behind Chris 100 percent.''
She and Paciello were days from opening their fourth business, the
West Palm Beach Liquid, when he was indicted on Nov. 28. Days
later, he turned himself in.
</P>
<P>
   Paciello openly acknowledges knowing the members of the Bath
Avenue Crew from his days in New York City, although his lawyers
contend that he never committed a crime with them. Back in U.S.
District Court in Brooklyn for a hearing on Jan. 7, he found
himself reunited with the old gang: Charles and Joseph Calco,
Fabrizio DeFrancisci, Joseph Dellatorre, Anthony Gonzalez and
Thomas Reynolds.
</P>
<P>
   He switched between making loose chatter with his buddies and
smiling at Ms. Casares and Ms. Vergara, who had turned up to
support him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
