<HEADER>
A9838 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-GIULIANI-NY-PRIM     01-18 0579
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-GIULIANI-NY-PRIMARY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: GIULIANI DEFENDS VOTING RIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times says in an editorial Wednesday, Jan. 19: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani has broken the shameful silence among top
New York state Republicans about their party's effort to prevent
Sen. John McCain from running statewide against Gov. George W. Bush
in the March 7 presidential primary. As Giuliani noted, a party
that supports open elections ``ends up being a much more active and
growing political party.'' Unfortunately, he does not speak for the
powerful stealth wing of his own party.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George Pataki, the power behind that wing, has sent word
that this primary system works just fine, and asserting that a few
feeble changes in the outrageous qualifying rules amount to real
reform. Meanwhile the state Republican chairman, William Powers,
sits smugly behind the scenes, authorizing legal challenges
intended to keep McCain off the ballot in half of the state's 31
congressional districts. And the supposed beneficiary of this
rigged election, Bush, drifts along obediently, apparently content
to take a tainted victory rather than face a real contest.
</P>
<P>
   The New York mayor's tribute to the advantages of open elections
points up a painful truth for Republican voters in New York state.
If they could have a real primary, the state might be pivotal in
the nominating process. Suppose McCain does handsomely in the New
Hampshire primary on Feb. 1 and then shows staying power in the
next primaries, which include his home state of Arizona. After
those few contests, March 7 arrives like a windstorm with a dozen
primaries including those in Maryland, Ohio, Missouri and
California, as well as New York. Normally, New York would be a big
trophy for any candidate. But since the whole country knows the fix
is in there, a Bush victory will be discounted as a staged event,
producing delegates but no real test of the winner's appeal in the
Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   New York's anachronistic ballot-access rules require candidates
in both parties to gather signatures from registered voters.
Democrats need 5,000 signatures statewide to get on the ballot. The
entire exercise is unnecessary, but at least that number is low
enough that voters will have a chance to vote for their party's
major contenders, Al Gore and Bill Bradley. Because of the
Republicans' more complicated rules, only three of six prominent
candidates tried for a spot on this year's ballots. Bush's
petitions were easily harvested by the state GOP machine. Steve
Forbes had to spend $750,000 to amass the required signatures. To
keep McCain from competing effectively, the state party will
challenge his petitions in 15 to 17 districts.
</P>
<P>
   In the face of Bush's docile endorsement of this flagrant
trickery, McCain has taken his case to federal court. He is
arguing, correctly, that New York voters are being deprived of the
constitutional rights under the First and 14th amendments. The
court should direct that McCain's name appear on the ballots, as it
required the addition of Forbes' name on ballots statewide four
years ago. In years past, the federal courts often stepped in to
prevent the disfranchisement of Southern voters by discriminatory
state laws. Now it is time for the courts to secure the voting
rights of New York Republicans. A simpler solution would be for
Bush to join Giuliani in urging a fair primary with a full ballot
on March 7.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
