<SLUG> BC-EDIT-OBSERVER-CAMPAIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL OBSERVER: LONG DAYS,BEDS ON THE CAMPAIGN TRAIL
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By STEVEN R. WEISMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa _ This is the time of year when presidential
candidates tramp around Iowa and proclaim their yearning for a
better America. For Bill Bradley, that includes better motel beds.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally in his high-minded stump speeches, Bradley pauses
to complain impishly about the ``rubberized pillows'' in Iowa's
far-flung hotels and motels, and the sheets that ``come loose from
the mattress every time you turn over.'' He leaves out that it
can't be any easier to sleep in a small bed for someone who is 6
feet 5 inches.
</P>
<P>
   From Bradley's point of view, the bed that doesn't fit is an apt
reflection of the Procrustean format of the Iowa caucuses next
Monday, where the system so clearly favors Al Gore. Iowans choose
their candidates not in a statewide primary but in 2,100 local
caucuses, throwing the advantage to the entrenched unions,
political clubs and community groups backing the vice president and
long accustomed to getting their supporters out. The Bradley
campaign compares its troubles to running against the Chicago
Democratic machine.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's aides say they have no choice but to mobilize people
who have never shown up at caucuses before _ kids, idealists, labor
dissidents and others inclined toward the former senator's low-key
fervor. Since the beginning of the year, he has spent $1.3 million
in television advertising. He has devoted 10 days to traveling
around the state, slipping into the role of itinerant preacherlike
outsiders going back to Eugene McCarthy and Jimmy Carter, who used
to quote the theologian Reinhold Niebuhr to the effect that ``the
sad duty of politics is to establish justice in a sinful world.''
But while often authentically inspiring, Bradley's appeals can come
across as pious, ethereal and even a little grumpy.
</P>
<P>
   There are of course the standard references to health care,
poverty and economics in Bradley's speeches. But the candidate
seems most distinctive when talking about making Americans feel
``less lonely, less fearful and less isolated'' in a changing
world. ``The untapped potential of the presidency is to unlock in
each of us the capacity for self-fulfillment,'' he told a group
celebrating Martin Luther King's birthday this week. He went on to
promise to work for ``a world of new possibilities guided by
goodness.''
</P>
<P>
   Less artfully, Bradley told a separate group of students that it
was not enough to battle bigotry in others. ``If you haven't had a
conversation about race in a long time with someone of another
race, you are part of the problem,'' he said sternly, and perhaps a
little sanctimoniously as well.
</P>
<P>
   The former senator's style does not get much overt audience
reaction, but that is OK with him. ``I don't want applause,'' he
said in a conversation aboard his bus as it rolled across central
Iowa. ``I want people to listen, and in the process be moved.'' His
style, Bradley said, is ``to lead from idealism and not
interest-group politics'' and ``awaken in people what they believe
politics could be.'' If his approach does not work, he said with a
shrug, ``I'm out, and life goes on.''
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Gore seems to revel in his organized support and
theatrical applause lines. At the Union Baptist Church in Des
Moines, a black congregation in the eastern part of town, Gore
jumped up and down and rolled his head from side to side during a
rollicking refrain of ``Restore it!'' from the choir. At the pulpit
he got cheers when he declared, ``I am a Baptist,'' and cascades of
applause as he growled out a list of African-Americans who have
served in the Clinton administration. When someone shouted, ``Run,
Al, run!'' he threw back his head with a dramatic laugh and shouted
back: ``I will! I will! I will!''
</P>
<P>
   With less than a week to go before the caucuses, Gore remains
the front-runner while Bradley hopes to make a showing respectable
enough to proclaim a moral victory he can ride into New Hampshire
the following week. Both states are getting a close look at two
styles of Democratic presidential politics that have been around
since Adlai Stevenson, the cool egghead, and Hubert Humphrey, the
happy warrior. This year's version is Laconic Bill versus Pumped-Up
Al. In a few days, voters will get to decide which style is more
attractive _ or at least less irritating.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
