<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-SETTLEMENT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSOURI COURT REJECTS EFFORTS TO SHARE IN TOBACCO SETTLEMENT
MONEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIT WAGAR  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   JEFFERSON CITY, Mo. _ The Missouri Court of Appeals on Tuesday
tossed aside one of the last roadblocks to the state's receiving
its tobacco settlement payments, adding a tone of realism to
lawmakers' debates over how to handle an estimated $6.7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The court's Eastern Division ruled 2-1 that Missouri hospitals
and three other groups are not entitled to a share of the state's
settlement with cigarette makers.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Jay Nixon praised the decision, saying that the
more than 50 hospitals involved should press their own lawsuits
against cigarette makers instead of trying to siphon off part of
the state's settlement.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court found that if they want to bring lawsuits, they can
bring them,'' Nixon said. ``But they should not have tried to get
inside our pot of money.''
</P>
<P>
   The money is Missouri's share of the $206 billion that the major
U.S. cigarette makers agreed to pay over 25 years to reimburse
states for the cost of treating smoking-related illness.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon said Missouri is one of just six states still trying to
clear up legal issues surrounding the settlement. Kansas received
the first payment last year on its share of the settlement, which
is expected to total $1.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon called on hospitals, which have now been rebuffed twice,
to drop further appeals and let Missouri receive its first-year
payment of $183 million by April.
</P>
<P>
   But Larry Coleman, a Kansas City attorney representing the
hospitals, promised that he would appeal the ruling to the Missouri
Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   An appeal would delay receipt of the money for months because
the settlement requires the end of litigation before disbursements
begin. The lawsuit already has held up the first payment of $105
million, which sits in an escrow account until all legal action is
finished. Another payment, of $78 million, is scheduled in April.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals panel upheld the St. Louis Circuit Court's ruling
that the hospitals had no right to the proceeds of the state's
lawsuit. It said the hospitals, along with plaintiffs representing
taxpayers, consumers and family members who died of smoking-related
diseases, needed to file their own lawsuits to recover damages.
</P>
<P>
   What hospitals lost in court, however, they are seeking to
obtain from the legislature. The Missouri Hospital Association was
among a long list of health-related industries that on Tuesday
asked a Senate committee for a share of the money.
</P>
<P>
   Hospital groups testified at hearings in November that they
wanted up to $1 billion of the settlement as compensation for
having treated indigent patients.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Sen. Steve Ehlmann of St. Charles was incredulous.
The request, he said, seemed a bit cynical, given the hospitals'
legal action against the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're saying you want to claim a portion of the settlement,
but if you lose, you still want the money from the legislature,''
Ehlmann said. ``After you've caused us to spend money on litigation
and you've delayed the state's access to the tobacco money, then
you come here and want us to give the money to you.''
</P>
<P>
   The hospital association is not a party to the lawsuit, but many
of its members are.
</P>
<P>
   Ehlmann's observation came during a hearing by the Senate
Pensions Committee to take testimony on half a dozen
tobacco-related bills.
</P>
<P>
   Senate President Pro Tem Ed Quick, a Liberty Democrat, proposed
a constitutional amendment that would ask voters for authority to
spend 60 percent of the money on health-related programs, 20
percent on anti-smoking efforts and 20 percent for an emergency
fund for state government. A companion bill would set up a trust
fund to receive the money once it is available.
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. Franc Flotron, a St. Louis County Republican, said such
a plan could leave the money in ``Hancock purgatory.'' If the money
stayed in the trust fund, it would not be subject to the Hancock
Amendment, which sets a limit on total state revenue.
</P>
<P>
   If voters reject the ballot proposal, then the money would build
up in the account, but would not be available for the legislature
to spend or refund, Flotron said.
</P>
<P>
   Quick said that if voters rejected the proposal, the account
would allow the money to accrue until another plan could be
submitted to voters.
</P>
<P>
   Several witnesses testified in support of Quick's plan, urging
senators to use most of the money for health programs. But many of
the programs went far beyond health care. In many cases, the
Pensions Committee heard more about job creation than medical care.
</P>
<P>
   A big push has started to see that the money is used for
life-sciences research, which could boost economic development
efforts in Kansas City and St. Louis, witnesses said. The current
and former chancellors of Washington University talked about how
subsidized research would lead to more high-tech jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The Civic Counsel of Greater Kansas City also suggested using
tobacco money to boost scientific research. But the group also
urged spending money on early childhood care because good programs
could reduce adult smoking.
</P>
<P>
   Associated Industries of Missouri suggested using the money to
fund a tax-credit for small businesses that provide health
insurance for their employees. Increasing the number of workers who
have health insurance would give health-care providers less
incentive to shift costs to patients insured by large companies,
AIM said.
</P>
<P>
   Even a school nurses' group said its members hoped they would be
included in health-care programs funded by tobacco money. And an
anti-abortion lobbyist said anti-smoking programs should be funded
because cigarettes increase the likelihood of a miscarriage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-18-00 2358EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
