<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-DEBT-PLAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE REPUBLICANS TO SEEK PLAN TO PAY OFF U.S. DEBT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., N.M.)   (rk) 
 By DON VAN NATTA Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Speaker Dennis Hastert of Illinois plans to
announce on Wednesday that House Republicans will work to develop
an economic plan to pay off the national debt by 2015, Hastert's
aides said Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The aides said Hastert would ask the House Budget Committee to
begin work on legislation that would use all of the projected
Social Security surplus and part of the projected federal surplus
to eliminate the nation's $5.8 trillion debt within 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   John P. Feehery, Hastert's press secretary, confirmed Tuesday
night that the goal of the Republican plan would be to retire the
nation's debt, but he refused to divulge details.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has been in debt since 1835.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we eliminate this debt, that money can be freed up for use
on other priorities like tax relief, investing in our schools or
fortifying our national defense,'' according to a text of a speech
that Hastert is scheduled to deliver on Wednesday in Albuquerque.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference on Jan. 6, Hastert pledged to reveal
details on a long-term plan to eliminate the national debt. At that
time, he promised that the effort would not affect three tax cuts
that the Republicans, who control Congress, have vowed to pass this
year.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed cuts would eliminate the so-called marriage
penalty, establish tax-free savings accounts for education and
create tax incentives to help revitalize the nation's poorest urban
and rural areas.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans have said they will send the proposed cuts to
the floor as separate spending bills, which would provide a total
of $135 billion in tax cuts over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   As the election year gets under way, Hastert's announcement
would demonstrate that Republicans were trying to establish an
aggressive legislative agenda before President Clinton delivered
his final State of the Union address on Jan. 27.
</P>
<P>
   In another sign that Hastert's announcement was motivated in
large part by election-year politics, an aide said the booming
economy would allow the Republicans to pass their proposed tax cuts
and still be able to accommodate the $483 billion multiyear tax
cuts proposed by Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, the front-runner for
the Republican presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Hastert said he intended to call on the president to
assist Republicans in their effort to retire the debt. Hastert also
intends to ask that the long-term debt retirement plan be presented
to the Republican leadership by April 15.
</P>
</TEXT>
